<HEADLINE>
CABBY IS ACCUSED OF TRYING TO TAKE 2 WOMEN PASSENGERS CAPTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a time when many cabdrivers are worried about
being fined for not picking people up, one driver was arrested
Wednesday and charged with refusing to let his passengers go.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the cabby, Akhtar Bajwa, twice in the past few
weeks tried to kidnap women who hailed his taxi in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, on Nov. 2, the authorities said, Bajwa sped off
to Queens with a 30-year-old woman he had picked up at East 47th
Street and Third Avenue. The woman had asked to be dropped off at
her home on Manhattan's Upper East Side. But the police said Bajwa
refused to stop, ignoring the woman's screams, and drove across the
Queensboro Bridge. Once in Queens, the woman was able to escape
when the cab was forced to stop in traffic, the police said. She
provided the police with the driver's hack license and the police
began to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two weeks later, on Monday, a 26-year-old woman got into
Bajwa's cab at West 47th Street and Sixth Avenue, en route to her
home on the East Side of Manhattan about 10:45 p.m., the police
said. This time he pulled over at Madison Avenue and East 40th
Street. Then, investigators said, he got out of the car and into
the back seat, where he tried to tie the woman's hands with a
scarf. But she broke away, slid across the back seat and ran out
the door.
</P>
<P>
   Neither woman was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The second woman was able to copy down the license plate number
of the cab and she called the Taxi and Limousine Commission on
Tuesday. Investigators said an alert clerk there, Alma Johnson,
remembered that detectives had called in several days earlier
looking for help in identifying the driver in a similar incident.
Ms. Johnson put the woman in touch with Detective Louis Donofrio of
the 17th Precinct, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time investigators arrived at the garage where Bajwa
leased his cab, he was already out driving a 12-hour shift. A
description of the cab was given to patrol units, and at about
12:35 a.m. Wednesday, officers from the Manhattan Street Crime Unit
spotted Bajwa's vehicle in Lower Manhattan and pulled him over.
</P>
<P>
   Bajwa, 45, of Brooklyn, was awaiting arraignment Wednesday night
on one charge of kidnapping and one of attempted kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Bajwa has been a licensed cabdriver for at least five years.
Investigators said he did not have a criminal record, although he
had been cited for driving without a license in March 1998. A
spokesman for the Taxi and Limousine Commission, Allan J. Fromberg,
said Bajwa's taxi license has been suspended, pending the outcome
of the kidnapping cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
