<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS AND DAVENPORT NEED THREE SETS TO GAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (UPDATES thruout with Williams win) 
(rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All systems appeared to be go for a scintillating
Chase Championships debut by Venus Williams. Her college homework
was up to date, there was no threat of another sibling uprising by
her younger sibling, Serena, the injured and absent U.S. Open
champion, and Venus' perforated blue tennis dress harmonized with
Madison Square Garden's interior as if they had been professionally
dyed to match.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that but the father/coach, Richard Williams, was calmly
chomping his toothpick on the sidelines, and Venus' veteran
opponent, Conchita Martinez, was nursing a nagging backache and a
nagging suspicion that Williams' firepower might be more than she
felt like handling at the end of another long year, Martinez's 12th
in tennis harness. Martinez forced Williams to struggle before
falling 6-2, 5-7, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Something about the novelty of her first encounter with
Williams, clearly the people's choice with superior celebrity
drawing power, affected Martinez like a noseful of smelling salts.
She rallied after dropping the first set and struck the final ace
of the seesawing second set. Then, just when it seemed as if
Williams, who apparently had not studied Martinez along with her
schoolwork, was going to ride a 4-2 third set lead directly to the
finish line, Martinez insinuated herself back into the thick of
things by forcing an errant backhand from Williams at break point
of the seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams refused to be flustered by the Spaniard's
persistence, broke straight back for a 5-4 edge and earned a match
point when Martinez slashed a backhand volley just wide of the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was obviously hitting the ball better than she usually
hits it in other matches,'' Williams said about Martinez, whose
down-the-line passes rarely missed their target. The Spaniard's
crafty interplay of topspin line drives and off-pace floaters, the
ingredients that obtained her the 1994 Wimbledon crown at the
expense of Martina Navratilova, yanked Williams around the court
like a fish on a line.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, it was back to basics for Lindsay Davenport and Amelie
Mauresmo, a Chase ingenue thanks to a season that began with a
breakthrough run to the Australian Open final.
</P>
<P>
   They put aside their checkered past, that awkward January moment
when the disgruntled Davenport reacted to her semifinal surrender
to the then 29th-ranked Frenchwoman by accusing Mauresmo of hitting
the ball like a person of the wrong gender to be performing on the
WTA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport made peace by quickly penning a private note of
apology and publicly praised Mauresmo's rippling one-handed
backhand and rippling musculature as a strength and a weapon, not a
curiosity. By the time the hard-hitting duo hit the court Wednesday
night, their rivalry was evenly proportioned at 2-2, and the
second-seeded Davenport made it clear she didn't take this opponent
lightly. But she took awhile to demonstrate it.
</P>
<P>
   After an ineffectual opening set, where Mauresmo surged out to a
3-0 lead, Davenport, hobbled by a sore left thigh incurred in a
finals victory against Hingis on Sunday at Philadelphia, seemed
disinclined to play catch-up until Mauresmo served for the set at
5-1. Then Davenport, the defending Wimbledon champion, inflicted a
3-6, 6-3, 6-2 reversal of fortune on her challenger. ``Oh, it's
sore,'' Davenport said of her leg. ``But what can you do. It's the
end of the year. I'm not dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampered by a recurring wrist injury, Davenport admitted she had
been on the verge of calling it a year two weeks ago. ``But I
didn't want it to end,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The morning match, watched by 2,000 customers, not all of them
paying, produced an upset: 17th-ranked Anke Huber, a 1995 Chase
finalist who barely squeaked into this year's event, ousted her
best friend, ninth-seeded Julie Halard-Decugis, 6-1, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Next for Huber is Davenport. ``Against Lindsay, I lost the last,
I don't know, five, six, seven times,'' Huber said. ``But now it
doesn't matter. I'll try to do my best. I played eight weeks in a
row, but I'm still alive and I'm trying.
</P>
<P>
   Huber reached a career-high fourth in the ranking five years ago
but has battled recurring injuries, and recurring ennui, in the
interim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
