<HEADER>
A3440 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      11-18 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Rockets had just been blown out by the Dallas Mavericks, of all
teams. They had shot worse from the field and the line than they
had all season. They had allowed 37 fast-break points, 18 more than
in any other game. Point guard Steve Francis had been ejected in
the second quarter. They had fallen to 2-7.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich warned, things would get
tough.
</P>
<P>
   He said this to explain the importance of maintaining faith that
things can turn around. But typical of the Rockets' season, no
matter how dark it has been, fate seems to pull down the shade a
little further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys after the game, believe it or not, it's going
to get tougher,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I'm going to stick with this.
I still believe in them, still like them. For the breakthrough to
come, we have to be together.''
</P>
<P>
   After facing the 7-2 Sacramento Kings tonight, the Rockets play
six of their next seven games on the road. The one home game is
against the Mavericks, whose rout stretched their winning streak
against the Rockets to three games, including two straight at
Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   There was good news Wednesday: Francis was fined $5,000 for
Tuesday's takedown of Dirk Nowitzki but escaped a suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after Tomjanovich made his renewed plea for unity in the
face of adversity, the message did seem to have been received.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work together and stay in there,'' Rockets center
Hakeem Olajuwon said. ``When everybody doubts us, we can do it.
When everybody criticizes us, we can do it. But we have to work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that well-intended sentiment, however, is that
it remains only a starting point. Two weeks into the season, the
Rockets remain in the starting blocks.
</P>
<P>
   They have, however, made progress.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich drew up a new play for Tuesday and, without a day to
practice, added it to the repertoire. It worked. He ran plays that
had been all but shelved. They worked. The Rockets looked for open
shooters and found them. They made the extra pass to get the ball
inside.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rockets still suffered their worst defeat of the season
by finding new areas in need of repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even teams that have been together do that,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``Not shooting the ball well is one thing. Then we're making
mistakes, little mental mistakes, that are costly. Right now, our
margin for error is so small, the mistakes are costing us games.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the mistakes that have hurt them, the Rockets have
reduced their chances to fourth-quarter make-or-break moments by
shooting terribly.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets are shooting just 42.2 percent from the field. They
rank 26th in the NBA in scoring, 22nd in field-goal percentage and
26th in 3-point percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is not all about shooting, but we've historically
been a high-percentage shooting team, especially when you factor in
3-pointers,'' Tomjanovich said. ``This year we're not even close.
Our regular shooting percentage is way down. Guys are in the low
40s. Guys are!y~ l!
</P>
</TEXT>
