<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-JAZZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ DEFEAT KNICKS, 98-90
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Since 1992 the New York Knicks have resolved to
leave with a victory. Innumerable players and lineups and three
different coaches have failed.
</P>
<P>
   When the Knicks look cross court at Karl Malone, the mammoth,
6-foot-9-inch, 256-pound power forward, they cringe. He may be 36,
but he still can dip his shoulder and mow them over.
</P>
<P>
   Malone scored 33 points on Wednesday night, making 13 of 15 free
throws and quelling every Knick run with a huge jump shot. His
partner in time, John Stockton, added 17 points, 11 assists and all
the hip checks imaginable as Utah knocked the wind out of New York,
98-90, at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz finally found some consistency in its game after a 3-3
start, parlaying its victory over the San Antonio Spurs on Monday
into another victory over a National Basketball Association
finalist. Utah once led by 20 and never completely let the Knicks
back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jeff Van Gundy's up-and-down team fell to 5-5 with
three games left on their Western Conference swing. They play the
Suns in Phoenix on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz and Knicks, two physical teams presumed to have trouble
adapting to the league's new rules, were whistled for more than 60
fouls. Utah lulled the Knicks into a wrestling match, and New York
took the bait, growing angry and finally disenchanted.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Knicks complained about Malone's receiving his
share of calls. The Knicks were whistled for 31 personal fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs left the game with 7 minutes 5 seconds remaining
when he collided with Stockton while crossing midcourt. He suffered
a laceration over his right eye and retreated to the locker room to
receive four stitches.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe for losing to Utah is time-tested by now for New
York: when the Knicks take their sweet time getting back on defense
and use their hands instead of moving their feet on defense, they
fall off of the map of upper-echelon teams.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell scored from nearly every angle, keeping the
Knicks in the game with 24 points. He made pull-up jump shots and a
monstrous dunk through the middle of the Jazz defense with less
than six minutes left. Yet with Allan Houston in foul trouble and
no one else able to assert himself on offense, it was not going to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks put together a 12-4 run to creep within 6 points to
begin the fourth quarter. Larry Johnson's spinning layup around
Bryon Russell made the score, 77-71, and momentarily hushed the
vociferous crowd of 18,890.
</P>
<P>
   It was not so much that Sprewell found his range _ he did,
scoring 8 points in the fourth after a 4-for-13 start _ or that the
Knicks began to do something on offense other than settle for
20-foot jump shots. In the final minutes, they played defense as if
they cared, with Kurt Thomas and Johnson battling Malone inside and
the backcourt refusing to let the Utah guards beat them backdoor.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the Knicks could accomplish late, though, did
little to make up for how awful they looked in the beginning. Utah
opened with a flurry. With Stockton swiveling heads by whipping the
ball to open teammates, the Jazz made its first 10 shots and did
not miss until the Kentucky rookie Scott Padgett misfired inside
with 5:45 left in the opening quarter. Utah led by 19 in the first
quarter and 20 in the second, getting easy baskets while the Knicks
fell asleep in transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slow starts have been our downfall all season,'' Marcus Camby
said. ``We can't seem to pinpoint it. We've got to come out with
heart and effort. We weren't even getting back on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing that badly that early is an ill-advised thing for an
opposing team to do in the Delta Center. The rowdies start making
noise, the home team catches fire and before you look up, the game
is over.
</P>
<P>
   Houston could hardly help his teammates. He picked up his third
foul with 10:42 into the second period, played only seven minutes
in the half and attempted just three shots.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Knicks tried to get back in the game, they did it
by resorting to one-on-one forays. Sprewell, Marcus Camby and John
Wallace did their best to create scoring opportunities, but there
was little rhythm or symmetry to how the Knicks were playing. They
could never quite come all the way back, having dug themselves a
gaping hole the size of nearby Bryce Canyon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
