<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-RACISM-SUIT-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 SUIT AGAINST BUFFALO-AREA MALL FOR RACISM SETTLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A suit accusing a shopping mall in suburban Buffalo, N.Y., of
causing a teenager's death through racist transportation practices
ended abruptly Wednesday with a settlement of $2.55 million.
</P>
<P>
   The case involved Cynthia N. Wiggins, a 17-year-old black
resident of Buffalo, who had taken a city bus to get to her job at
the mall's food court in December 1995. Because the mall had banned
city buses on some routes from dropping passengers on its property,
Ms. Wiggins had to cross a busy seven-lane highway, where she was
hit and crushed by a dump truck.
</P>
<P>
   After the accident, the Wiggins family and other members of the
African-American community accused the mall, Walden Galleria in
Cheektowaga, of trying to use the highway as a moat to exclude some
city residents from the mall. The high-profile trial, which began
Nov. 8, was expected to build into an emotional affair, brimming
with images of racism.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, lawyers for both sides announced that the mall's
owner, Pyramid Companies of Syracuse, would pay $2 million of the
$2.55 million settlement, over time, to Ms. Wiggins' son, who is
now 4. It did not admit any wrongdoing. The Niagara Frontier
Transportation Authority, which operates the bus line, agreed to
pay $300,000; and the truck driver, John P. Bunch, agreed to pay
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we were winning,'' said Johnnie L. Cochran Jr., who
represented the Wiggins family. ``But in the end, I think everyone
felt that it was time for a healing process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this trial had gone to a verdict, no side would have won,
and it certainly would have gone to an appeal,'' said Albert J.
D'Aquino, a Galleria lawyer. ``The judge felt that it would be a
divisive issue in the community.'' Both sides praised the judge,
Justice Jerome C. Gorski of state Supreme Court, for helping to
forge the settlement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before that happened, Cochran had begun to portray Ms. Wiggins'
story as one of frustration and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   On a dismal December day, with snow drifts of up to eight feet
high, Ms. Wiggins had boarded the Route 6 metro bus for the ride
from Buffalo's predominantly black and low-income east side to the
Galleria. Because the mall excluded Route 6 buses from its
property, Ms. Wiggins got off at an intersection with no crosswalks
or pedestrian signals, seven lanes of highway away from the mall.
</P>
<P>
   She made it past six lanes before she was struck. The truck
driver, Bunch, said that he never saw Ms. Wiggins.
</P>
<P>
   Later, officials from the Transportation Authority revealed that
they had, over several years, repeatedly asked the mall to allow
the bus onto the premises but that the mall had always refused,
fearful of rambunctious youths. Then, Cochran and numerous
organizations in Buffalo began to question why the Route 6 bus was
forbidden while charter buses were not.
</P>
<P>
   In response, defense lawyers said that bus passengers had always
had the option to transfer onto a bus that stopped closer to the
mall. They said that the Galleria, which is private property, was
not required to accommodate public transportation. And they noted
that Ms. Wiggins was jaywalking when she was hit.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Ms. Wiggins' death, the mall changed its bus
policy, following the threat of a boycott by local civil rights
groups and the Buffalo teachers' union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
