<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S MISSION: STOP EL DIABLO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley TRIBUNE  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ Los Angeles Galaxy midfielder Danny Pena
remained quiet during Sunday's lunch at the Staples Center's Fox
Sports Sky Bar, concentrating on watching the wizardry of D.C.
United's Marco Etcheverry on television.
</P>
<P>
   Etcheverry dissected Columbus' defense, which set up three goals
and scored another to lead United to a 4-0 rout of the Crew in the
deciding game of the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorizing MLS defenses is nothing new to the man known as ``El
Diablo'' in his native Bolivia _ a nickname given to him by his
brother-in-law for dribbling as if he's possessed by the devil.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they say, big players make big plays and the money players
play when it really counts,'' said United coach Thomas Rongen of
Etcheverry. ``Not just against Columbus, but throughout the year,
he is a great captain and leader for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As Etcheverry goes, so goes United. His service to front-runners
Roy Lassiter and fellow Bolivian Jaime Moreno is the best in the
business. His 17 assists this year matched the Galaxy's Mauricio
Cienfuegos, but Etcheverry's deadly left foot on free kicks
provides another weapon to his arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   This is why many consider the 1997 MLS Most Valuable Player the
best player in Major League Soccer's four-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Set plays are a reflection of who's serving the ball and you
got one of the best in the game serving the ball in Marco
Etcheverry,'' said the Galaxy's Paul Caligiuri. ``And he's just so
smart. He will pick you apart if you let him.''
</P>
<P>
   Why was Pena observing Etcheverry so closely? Because he's the
one who will be asked to man-mark Etcheverry in Sunday's MLS
championship in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put any more pressure on myself than is
already expected,'' said Pena. ``He's not a player you can stop for
90 minutes. He's a player that, hopefully, I can contain for the
majority of the time and hopefully limit the service he's capable
of giving to his front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big part of their team, there's no doubt about that.
But I feel if I can do my job, 60 or 70 minutes of keeping him
under control, it's going to make the other guys on United have to
work a little bit harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too many have been successful containing Etcheverry, but
Pena is arguably the best man-marker in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one answer we have had for the last three years is Danny
Pena,'' said Caligiuri. ``He has been our one midfield general when
it comes to man-marking other teams' playmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about Danny, he really steps up to the
challenge and down deep I know he's relishing this chance in such a
big game. He really has a blue-collar work ethic and you're not
going to get a better performance out of a different player than
Pena.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we've always said we have the best defense in the
league, plus Danny Pena.''
</P>
<P>
   Etcheverry is a master at dragging man-markers around and
spinning them to the turf. He can split your vision and is
impossible to stop if given space to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to try and make him go backwards,'' said Pena. ``He's
not a player that you're going to swipe the ball away from as often
as you like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to stay by his side and not allow him to face the goal
where he can place those services up top.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have to be careful when I get near him, because he's a
player that get's a lot of fouls called (in his favor) from
referees.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a concern for Schmid. In the 1996 final, United scored
all three of its goals on set plays to beat the Galaxy 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players like him definitely have a bonus in this league,''
said Schmid. ``If he falls over, the chances of the whistle being
blown is much greater than if Clint Mathis falls over in the same
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it is everywhere else in the world with the
league's best players. So with Etcheverry, you just have to do a
good job of standing him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, who was in D.C. when United beat Columbus, said it might
take more than just the work of Pena to slow Etcheverry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbus' defending on Etcheverry was not very good,'' said
Schmid. ``They gave him too much space. We may have to mark him
zonally with Roy (Myers), Ezra (Hendrickson) and Clint (Mathis)
picking him up at times. Marco likes to pop deep and wide into
different places. You always have to be aware of him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
