<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-PISTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PISTONS NIP NETS, 109-107 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ The New Jersey Nets looked across the
basketball court on Wednesday night and saw a vulnerable cast of
underachievers not unlike themselves. A talented yet somewhat
desperate club, the Detroit Pistons provided a grand opportunity
for the Nets to instill life into their dying season.
</P>
<P>
   And with seven seconds remaining, the chance for a small revival
was there. With the Nets trailing by 2 points, Stephon Marbury, the
hottest shooter on the floor, received an inbound pass from Johnny
Newman and began driving to the basket from the right wing. He went
airborne, met with Detroit's Christian Laettner and powered a layup
over Laettner's outstretched arms. The ball caromed off the rim.
Jamie Feick tipped it fruitlessly toward the basket, then Elliot
Perry grabbed the rebound and took a shot that was blocked by Grant
Hill. The buzzer sounded and the chance was lost. The Nets, losers
in their previous three games, fell again, 109-107, at the Palace.
</P>
<P>
   They are 1-7 heading into Friday's game against Boston and will
play five of their next six games on the road. While Coach Don
Casey talked about the positives _ his club's 47 percent shooting
and its ability to stay close throughout _ Feick, the blunt
forward/center who complained on Tuesday about being removed from
the starting lineup, again chose not to mince words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit was in the same position as us,'' said Feick, who was
contrite about his previous outburst, after grabbing a team-high 11
rebounds off the bench. ``They needed a win. We needed a win.
There's no excuse. We had it in our hands. We should have pulled it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to praise the Nets for their offensive fluidity
because Detroit (3-6) has one of the worst defenses in the league.
The Pistons entered allowing 107.3 points a game, second most in
the league, and allowing opponents to shoot 46 percent from the
floor. They were also coming off a tough, hard-fought loss in
Toronto. Pistons Coach Alvin Gentry did not hide what this victory
meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the Super Bowl for us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though, like the Nets, Detroit lacks a legitimate center, it was
hard to tell on Wednesday night. Casey had replaced Feick with the
7-foot-1-inch Jim McIlvaine for added defensive post presence, but
the Nets were destroyed in the paint, being outscored, 70-20.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets received strong performances from Marbury and Van Horn
(season-high 30 points, 9 rebounds). Marbury led all scorers with
35 points, including 24 in the second half and 10 in the fourth
quarter. He made six of eight 3-point attempts, gave out seven
assists and, after the Nets fell behind by 107-101 with 2 minutes
20 seconds remaining, made a 3-pointer to keep his team hopeful.
Van Horn followed with a foul shot.
</P>
<P>
   Laettner, who supported Grant Hill's 32-point performance with
20 points and 10 rebounds, answered with a driving layup and then
Marbury made a nice steal and layup to cut the deficit to 2 points
with 30 seconds left. Marbury was visibly miffed before making his
theft, as he thought he had been fouled on the previous trip
downcourt. The Nets followed with a stop of Jerry Stackhouse, which
set the stage for Marbury's near basket at the end. There was
definitely contact on Marbury's shot over Laettner, and Marbury
wondered after the game where the new no-touch rules had gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand the rules,'' Marbury said. ``It goes in
your favor the first, second and third quarters, but then at the
end of the game it's like, `We're going back to the old style.' I
was trying to score. There was contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, who was visibly despondent before, during and after
Monday's loss to Seattle, entered the Palace with newfound joy.
Instead of focusing on the poor play by him and his team, he looked
at the big picture, smiled and said: ``I feel great. I have a great
life.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this season, Van Horn played the way he is
supposed to. He hit six of his first eight shots in scoring 13
first-quarter points as the Nets took a 35-25 lead. He had 20
points by halftime as the Nets held a 61-57 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn thought the Nets lost the game in the third quarter,
though, when their offensive execution and ball movement reverted
back to one-on-one play, and Detroit outscored them, 32-26, to take
the lead for good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
