<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3452 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-     11-18 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AGREES WITH WHITE HOUSE ON SPENDING CUTS
</HEADLINE>
  (UPDATES thruout with bill being worked out, prospects of bill in
Senate. REPLACES NIRELAND-TALKS as lede in paper) 
(rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and Republican leaders in Congress
agreed in principle Wednesday to an across-the-board spending cut
to seal a deal on the overdue federal budget, then, after grappling
all day over how to make that cut, prepared to shake hands on it.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, Rep. C.W.
Bill Young, R-Fla., said he was ``filing the bill tonight,'' the
minute White House officials finished checking its fine print.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides agreed in principle Wednesday morning on the last
piece of the puzzle: an across-the-board budget cut of 0.38
percent, out of about $610 billion in spending for federal
agencies. Then they argued all day about how to perform that fiscal
microsurgery, which would yield close to $1.3 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Their dispute was ``like when you go to buy a house, and you've
agreed on the price, and all that's left is a disagreement over the
color of the trim on the tool shed,'' said Robert Stevenson, a
senior aide to Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., who is chairman of the
Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   While passage of the final bill by the House is expected to be
routine, another fight threatens it in the Senate. That involved a
battle over federal price controls for dairy farmers, an issue so
crucial to the combatants that they are threatening to shut down
the Senate, block any final budget bill and keep Congress in
session well into December.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., has placed a formal hold on the final
spending package in an effort to protect his state's 23,000 dairy
farmers from legislation favoring Northeastern milk producers.
</P>
<P>
   The budget cannot pass, and Congress cannot adjourn, until he
lifts that hold. That is because the legislation he opposes is in
the final spending package that will be filed in the House, voted
on and most likely passed on Thursday, before going to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to take the dairy out'' of the spending bill, said
the Senate minority leader, Tom Daschle of South Dakota. ``It will
blow it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lew, the White House budget director, said the dairy
dispute was so dire that it ``raises a real risk of a government
shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   This looming problem dismays many members of Congress. When the
House majority leader, Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, began talking
about it on the House floor Wednesday, members began to moo.
</P>
<P>
   The day's war of words began when the House speaker, Dennis
Hastert of Illinois, said President Clinton had agreed in a
telephone call from Turkey to an across-the-board cut of 0.38
percent in the budget, which is now 47 days overdue.
</P>
<P>
   That cut was a political do-or-die issue for the Republicans,
but only part of the financial solution. The final piece was
agreeing on how to impose it.
</P>
<P>
   The senators, representatives and White House aides coming and
going through the Senate's corridors for the negotiations looked
exhausted after 10 nearly nonstop days of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders were pressing them hard to finish their work
without spending more money. ``If I were king, I would have their
heads all cut off,'' the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott of
Mississippi, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was seeking every last new dollar it could
extract from Congress before shaking hands, including $100 million
for a program for disabled workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans needed nearly $7 billion in savings to allow
them to say that their spending bills would not dip into Social
Security surpluses _ a political point they have made daily, since
spring, but still have not formally fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   The money would ``help them fill the hole they created'' with
new programs they wanted, along with new spending the White House
fought for and won, Lew said. So the White House brought nearly $7
billion to the bargaining table Wednesday, enough to cover the
Republicans demands without an across-the-board cut.
</P>
<P>
   Up to $3.5 billion would come from a one-time transfer from the
Federal Reserve's portfolio of government securities _ a strictly
bookkeeping device, since the money belongs to the government to
begin with.
</P>
<P>
   The rest would come from delaying government paychecks for
military personnel and many civilian employees for about 48 hours,
until just after 12:01 a.m. next Oct. 1, the start of the next
fiscal year. This would not actually save any money, but simply
shift more than $3.2 billion in spending into next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals remained in the final package, along with the
across-the-board cut. Both sides agreed to exclude military
personnel from the cut. Then came the stumbling block: how to
impose the $1.3 billion cut.
</P>
<P>
   The argument was over who would control the budget-cutting
scalpel, what programs could be protected and which ones could take
deep cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides described this as an issue of ``flexibility.'' Two
weeks ago, Clinton vetoed a 0.97 percent across-the-board cut that
Congress passed, almost exclusively with Republican votes, calling
it a ``blind'' and ``mindless'' exercise.
</P>
<P>
   To make such a cut seem sensible to Democrats, the White House
insisted on more flexibility to protect some programs from cuts.
</P>
<P>
   An across-the-board cut was a matter of principle for the
party's conservatives in the House, who wore big buttons on their
lapels Wednesday saying they had ``stopped the raid on Social
Security.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Just as important to two Democratic senators are demands for
their home states.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia is threatening to filibuster
the final spending bills to protect his state's coal miners from a
federal court ruling barring them from dumping in valley streams.
Byrd has drafted last-minute legislation that would stop the court
ruling from taking effect for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The White House first supported Byrd's effort on behalf of his
state, then said it would veto any bill containing it. It appeared
to be striking a noncommital stance on the issue Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Kohl and the dairy dispute. It threatens the final
budget bill, containing five of the year's 13 spending measures in
a $390 billion package.
</P>
<P>
   This year the House approved a measure that lets a system
keeping the price of milk in New England artificially high to
remain in place for another two years.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has placed a hold on every piece of legislation pending in
the Senate, including the budget bill, to stop that measure from
becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raw politics _ that's what originated it, and that's what
keeps it going,'' Kohl said in an interview Wednesday. He promised
to ``do everything I can'' to keep the cartel from being extended.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a provision of a 1996 farm bill that allowed the
formation of a cartel, called the Northeast Dairy Compact, which
puts a floor on the price of milk in the six New England states. It
keeps milk from Midwestern dairies out of New England, protecting
hundreds if not thousands of dairy farmers from those states.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl calls it ``diametrically opposed to everything this country
stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Authority for the cartel expired on Sept. 30, though a judge's
order has kept the pricing mechanism in place temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   In September the House voted, 285-140, to extend the system.
Then Hastert and Lott agreed this week to attach a two-year
extension of the cartel to one of the final spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The milk issue is ``all about economic self-interest,''
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said last month. Now it will be
decided in the closing hours of this Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
