<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-BRUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS LOSE THEIR TOP LINE AS THEY TIE WITH BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils let a two-goal
lead slip away Wednesday night, but once again they found a way not
to let a two-game losing streak take hold. They grabbed and
clutched their way to a 2-2 tie with the Boston Bruins in a game
that had little to excite the crowd of 14,219 until overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The tie extended the Devils' undefeated streak at home to nine
games. They have seven victories and two ties in that stretch, and
their loss to Pittsburgh in the home opener remains the only defeat
of the season at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils (9-6-3) earned a point in the standings, but the game
may turn out to be costly because the three players that make up
what is considered their top line were not on the ice at game's
end. Petr Sykora left in the second period with a bruised knee and
did not return. Patrik Elias and Jason Arnott missed most of the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora said afterward that he did not think he would miss any
action, but he was quick to add that it all depended on how his
knee would feel in the morning. Elias said he got hit on top of his
foot with a puck and the foot was still painful. Arnott left
because he got hit in the mouth again; he had returned from a mouth
injury in the loss to Washington in the previous game.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were not happy afterward about squandering a two-goal
lead in the third period. The tying score came with 4 minutes 31
seconds left in regulation when Martin Brodeur allowed a soft goal
to Joe Murphy, who made his debut with the Bruins after walking
away from a tryout with the Rangers last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have buried them earlier and we didn't,'' said
Brodeur, who faced 31 shots, including three in overtime. ``We hit
the post a couple times and missed chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur was lucky when Jason Allison's shot in the overtime hit
the corner of the crossbar and the right post.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik was more critical of the way the Devils collapsed in
the third period. He blamed the Devils' inability to seal matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not having the killer instinct,'' Holik called it, as he stood
in front of his stall in the quiet Devils' dressing room. ``We
played their game, instead of finishing them off. We got a little
lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Gomez and Sergei Brylin scored the goals for the Devils in
the first and second periods, before the Bruins rallied for goals
by Mikko Eloranta and Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Niedermayer, who has gone without a goal even though he
has played every game, assisted on both goals for the Devils. He
made the pass for Gomez's fourth goal of the season that opened the
scoring 5:55 into the game. Niedermayer then took a shot that
Brylin deflected for his fourth of the season with 1:10 left in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur made 29 saves, including one in the overtime, and
Boston's Robbie Dallas made 37 saves, including five in the
overtime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
