<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HIRE SCIOSCIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Former Los Angeles Dodgers catcher Mike
Scioscia will be introduced as the new Angels manager today in a
news conference at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia is believed to have received a three-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement ends general manager Bill Stoneman's search
that lasted 2{ weeks since his hiring and included interviews with
seven candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, who will turn 41 this month, beat out Chris Chambliss,
Joe Maddon, Joel Skinner, Ken Macha, Bob Boone and Hal McRae for
the position.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia's primary task will be to bring together a clubhouse
that became so divided last season that manager Terry Collins
resigned Sept. 3. Stoneman focused on looking for someone he
thought would be able to manage people and gain the respect of the
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I'm looking for) somebody who understands baseball is a team
sport and treats the job as such,'' Stoneman said during the
interview process. ``If somebody buys into that, we'll have a lot
more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month Scioscia resigned as manager of the Albuquerque
Dukes, the Dodgers' Triple-A team. After the Dukes finished the
season with a record of 65-74, Scioscia decided it was time to
pursue other opportunities in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, who caught more games for the Dodgers (1,395) than any
player in team history, played for the Dodgers from 1980-92 and
finished his playing career in 1994. He was the Dodgers'
minor-league catching coordinator in 1995-96, and the major-league
team's bench coach in 1997-98 before taking the post with
Albuquerque last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were the last team in the majors to hire a manager,
which meant they had no competition for candidates. However, the
search delayed other priorities, like trying to re-sign pitcher
Chuck Finley, hiring a scouting director and a major-league
coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process was much more time consuming than I thought,''
Stoneman said. ``But it was time well-spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia becomes the 16th Angels manager (not counting interim
managers) in club history, and the fifth in the 1990s, following
Doug Rader, Buck Rodgers, Marcel Lachemann and Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Only three managers in Angels history _ Norm Sherry, Gene Mauch
and Rader _ have winning records with the club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
