</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-GOMEZ-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS KNOW GOMEZ IS BOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Erica Gomez, a 5-foot-9 UCLA point guard, yells at
6-4 post player Carly Funicello about how to play in the post.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever confuses Gomez for a post player, yet Funicello
listens as Gomez tells her to use her drop step.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the leader,'' Funicello said. ``She's been here five
years. You ask her about a player, she can tell you about their
strengths and weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies a truth about this season's UCLA women's basketball
team: Gomez's influence is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Her demeanor is one of professionalism, not emotion. Same with
her teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erica's not one to talk about her feelings,'' forward Maylana
Martin said. ``We don't want to make a huge deal about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In summer pickup games, Gomez chose the teams. No one questioned
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody,'' Funicello said, ``because Erica knows.''
</P>
<P>
   At the team's media day, everyone talked about Gomez. Ask a
teammate about the team's chances, she doesn't talk about holding
off Oregon or Arizona or beating USC. She talks about Gomez. Even
USC coach Chris Gobrecht, when UCLA is mentioned, invokes Gomez's
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can get the ball to anyone like I've never seen,''
Gobrecht said.
</P>
<P>
   There's great reason for this outpouring of references. Gomez is
sidelined until late December at the earliest as she recovers from
surgery to repair a torn labrum and fractured shoulder. She injured
herself playing on the beach with guys in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dang it,'' she said. ``I'm tired of sitting around. I try and
contribute as much as I can. For the first time, I feel like I can
help somebody. They understand I'm telling them something because I
want them to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. Gomez might be injured, but this is her team _
so much so that she returned for her senior year after considering
skipping it. Her reasons are numerous. First, she's the oldest
player, having turned 23 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm the grandma,'' she said. ``I feel so old. When
(teammates) are dancing and acting loud, I feel old: `Been there,
done that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Second, she's the point guard on a squad that won the Pacific-10
and reached the NCAA Elite Eight last season, returns almost
everyone and is ranked in the top five in just about every national
poll (it started fifth in AP but has moved up to 4th). Many believe
this UCLA team has the best chance since the 1978 national champion
to reach the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Third, she hurt her knee in the NCAA Tournament, and the way
Louisiana Tech bounced the Bruins out of the postseason didn't feel
right to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would've been a hard way to end her career like that,''
Martin said. ``I was hoping that would make a difference in her
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   So bring on the Pac-10 and the NCAA Tournament. Gomez is back _
even if that means being back in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Being the center of attention always has been difficult for
Gomez. She prefers staying to herself and rarely is seen at campus
sporting events. She hears the little girls shouting her name but
has difficulty acknowledging them. But she's working on it. While
she was typing on campus one day, a fan walked up to her and told
her he was sorry about her shoulder and he would pray for her.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez gave a perfunctory ``thanks'' and kept typing, barely
looking up.
</P>
<P>
   As the man walked away, Gomez realized she had been rude, so she
walked over to him and apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing a lot of thinking,'' she said. ``Knowing how
much impact our team has on the kids. I ask myself, `How do I want
to be treated?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's more mature and she's seeing things in a different
way,'' UCLA coach Kathy Olivier said. ``She can do a lot for
women's basketball. She realizes that. I think it's awesome. I love
it. She'll feel that much better if she lets the fans in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
