<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISRESPECT ANGERS MURRAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ You'd think the Los Angeles Kings lost by five
goals in one of the most horrific displays in hockey history.
</P>
<P>
   A day after watching his Kings get outshot 23-1 in the third
period, yet hang on for a 3-2 win against Chicago, coach Andy
Murray said his club needs to respect other clubs before it can be
a serious playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't feel we showed enough respect for our opponent
in the third period,'' Murray said. ``Who are we not to be
respecting our opponent? Who are we? They don't give you the
Stanley Cup for having 28 points in the middle of November.''
</P>
<P>
   The message: Doing it and getting away with it against Chicago
is one thing, but if it against the Phoenix Coyotes tonight at
Staples Center, forget about stealing a win.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reviewing the videotape of the third period debacle
against the Blackhawks, Murray talked with the Kings about why they
stopped working hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about this respect factor,'' Murray said. ``There
was nothing for us to learn (from watching) the third period
because it was so bad. We just didn't show them enough respect. We
can't accept it, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of our players has something to prove, as a team and
as an individual. I have something to prove. The coaches have
something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Remaining loyal: Even though Finnish import Jere Karalahti
may be ready to join the Kings as soon as today, Murray said the
24-year-old won't be his first choice if he makes a change on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Murray met with the team before Wednesday's practice and told
them he would remain loyal to the players who were there throughout
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quality player, but (I told them),`You guys are playing
right now,' '' Murray said. ``If I had a guy who couldn't play, I'd
put (Jaroslav) Modry in the lineup. I think you have to have that
loyalty to your players.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said the situation regarding Mattias Nordstrom was
different than Karalahti because Nordstrom spent the last
three-plus seasons with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   __ Slap shots: Modry, Jason Blake, Karalahti and goalie Marcel
Cousineau were slated to play for the Kings' IHL affiliate in Long
Beach on Wednesday. . . . Though Cousineau hasn't played yet this
season, Murray said he wouldn't hesitate to use him if the Kings
played back-to-back nights. If Stephane Fiset doesn't return for
back-to-back games against Colorado and Dallas next week, that
could happen. . . . Defensemen Garry Galley missed practice because
of a family medical situation, and Sean O'Donnell sat out with a
leg injury. Both should play against the Coyotes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
