A3484 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG     11-18 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHN'S FIRST GOAL ENOUGH FOR DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ When Ladislav Kohn looked to the heavens after
scoring his first goal of the season, it was as though a prayer had
been answered for a Anaheim Mighty Ducks team that had been
suffering through a power outage.
</P>
<P>
   The rare Anaheim power-play goal with 6:49 left in the third
period gave the Ducks a much-needed 2-1 victory over the Calgary
Flames in front of and all-time low crowd of 12,928 at the Pond on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly the most riveting game of the season, but all in
all it was a pretty special night for the Ducks, who also killed
off two penalties as they moved back to the .500 mark (9-9-2-1).
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's power play had managed just one goal in its last 25
chances before Kohn deflected a point shot by Paul Kariya that also
bounced off Steve Rucchin before it got to the Anaheim winger.
</P>
<P>
   Kohn's goal couldn't have been more timely, since it helped the
Ducks avoid overtime with a Flames team that has won all five of
its games in extra time.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary had tied the game at 11:41 on goal by Cory Stillman.
</P>
<P>
   After losing three in a row on the road the Ducks needed a good
start and they got just that _ with a little help from the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Tverdovsky's dump-in took an odd bounce off the end boards
and trapped Calgary goalie Fred Brathwaite out of the net. Marty
McInnis quickly pounced on the loose puck and slipped a pass to
Antti Aalto, who scored his third goal of the season into an open
net at 5:23.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim got a good bounce on the other end as well. With 12:45
left in the period, Stillman's blew a shot past Guy Hebert's glove
only to have it hit the right post.
</P>
<P>
   The second period offered little drama other than to see the
Ducks' woeful special teams at work.
</P>
<P>
   The power play, ranked No. 26 in the league, looked as tentative
as ever. Anaheim was 0 for 2 with the just two shots on goal. One
shot by Kariya that never reached the goal hit McInnis in the head,
but the Ducks winger didn't miss a shift.
</P>
<P>
   But the real buzz came when Pavel Trnka was assessed a very
questionable interference penalty midway through the period. That
meant Anaheim's NHL worst penalty killers would have to protect
their slim one-goal lead. After giving up six power-play goals in
the previous two games it was hardly a good bet. But the Ducks
killed off the penalty easily and seemed to gain momentum from the
rare successful kill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
