<HEADLINE>
SKINS GAME SETTING: FROM PLUSH TO ARID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIO, Calif. _ This year,viewers of the 17th annual Skins Game,
now as much a Thanksgiving weekend tradition as leftovers, will see
something new: dsert.
</P>
<P>
   Honest to God, unyielding, unforgiving, civilization-resistant,
snake-hiding desert.
</P>
<P>
   This may be a shock for those who thought Palm Springs was this
green paradise surrounded by pretty mountains. It can be, but the
desert is never far away.
</P>
<P>
   And now, after 13 years of plush courses tucked away in tony
neighborhoods, the Skins Game is venturing into the badlands north
of Interstate 10.
</P>
<P>
   The new Landmark Golf Club, which just opened, next weekend
starts what its owners hope is a long and profitable association
with the tournament that sired what grew up to be golf's cash-flush
silly season. This is notable on two accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The complex, two 18-hole layouts both more than 7,000 yards
long, was built in about a year. And it is a public, albeit
expensive, facility. It also borders public lands, so it won't have
that cushy country club feel. Landmark officials had to do a little
scrambling to pull it all off.
</P>
<P>
   ``On December 1st (last year), we were building a course for the
public to play. By Dec. 17th, we were building a course for the
Skins Game,'' said Johnny Pott, Landmark's senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the course can be set up tough enough to
challenge the professionals, but high handicappers can have a fun
round.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to overpower the course might not be a good idea. Pott
said there are generous target areas, but hit a crooked shot and
your ball will be long gone.
</P>
<P>
   This year's field consists of defending champion Mark O'Meara,
world No. 2 David Duval, Spanish star Sergio Garcia and Fred
Couples, who was added to the field to replace the late Payne
Stewart. They will play for $1 million, which is how much money
Tiger Woods won in the season-ending World Stroke Play Championship
in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Garcia's first tournament appearance in Southern
California. It's also going to be new experience with an American
holiday tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't really televise the Skins Game in Spain,'' he said
during a conference call with reporters. ``But I did watch a couple
when I was playing in the states. It looks very enjoyable. It will
be nice to play one of these tournaments where you can have a
little bit of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that wasn't fun was dumping his caddie, Jerry
Higgenbotham, formerly employed by O'Meara's.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia fired him last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't happy, it didn't look like he was happy either. I
thought things weren't working, so it's time to move on,'' Garcia
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The Skins Game looks like it will be just one of many stops in
the states for Garcia, who plans to play 16 to 17 events here next
season with several stops possible in California.
</P>
<P>
   That might stimulate golf's next great rivalry, that is Woods
versus Garcia, whose popularity is already approaching Tigermania
proportions, especially in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing. The other day a guy almost broke his head trying
to get an autograph. It was almost scary,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio, wait until you get a load of the desert. Now that is
scary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
