<HEADLINE>
HACKETT EXPECTED TO BE KEY MAN IN 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As D.J. Hackett became stronger and faster, it was
tempting for the Cal State Northridge football coaches to play the
freshman wide receiver. But they held firm, sticking to the plan to
redshirt Hackett, a 6-foot-3, 180-pounder out of San Dimas High.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Hackett to make an impact at CSUN in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really, really hard for us not to play D.J. this
year,'' CSUN interim head coach Jeff Kearin said. ``He has really
worked hard in the weight room. I feel really good about D.J.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin said Hackett could move into a starting role next year,
because of the graduation of wideouts Aaron Arnold and Terrence
Jones. With the season ending this Saturday against Northern
Arizona, it's time to take a look at some Matadors who are being
looked upon, like Hackett, as stepping to the forefront next
season:
</P>
<P>
   __ Joe Gilliam, wide receiver. A freshman, he has been the most
promising offensive newcomer to the program this season. He has 22
catches for 234 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   __ Erik Gardner, defensive lineman. The junior stayed relatively
healthy for a full season for the first time since he came to CSUN
and the coaches are excited about his progress.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner (6-6, 240) has the size and quickness to become a great
pass rusher.
</P>
<P>
   __ Johnny Acosta, offensive lineman. The junior came to
Northridge after being named honorable mention JC All-American at
Chaffey College. But he came to fall camp out of shape and has only
showed hints of being a great tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the season has gone on, (Acosta) has played himself into
better shape,'' offensive line coach Bobby Connelly said. ``He
needs to have a rigorous offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Acosta will be relied upon even more because freshman Nick
Longshore, who started the first half of the season at left tackle,
is going to begin serving his two-year Mormon mission in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hassan Abdul-Malik, defensive back. He earned the starting
free safety job last spring, but a pulled hamstring cut his '99
season to just two series in the opener against Western Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Malik, a sophomore, redshirted. He should form a potent
combination next year with safety Jeremy Golden, who was
academically ineligible this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Evaluations: Several NFL scouts have inquired about Arnold,
the school's all-time leading receiver, over the course of the
season. Here is some input from the scouts Kearin has received:
</P>
<P>
   ``They see a guy who's got tremendous numbers. That, coupled
with good size. His size is what makes the difference. . . . (The
scouts) like the fact that he's graduating; he's a `program' guy.
They see some toughness in him.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Candidates: Some of the names being mentioned for the
head-coaching vacancy at Montana State are: Stanford offensive
coordinator Bill Diedrick, Purdue assistant head coach Scott
Downing and Eastern Washington head coach Mike Kramer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
