<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AGREES WITH WHITE HOUSE ON SPENDING CUTS
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and Republican leaders in Congress
agreed on Wednesday to an across-the-board spending cut to the
long-overdue federal budget, and then, after grappling all day over
how to make that cut, shook hands on it Thursday morning and made a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides agreed on an across-the-board budget cut of 0.38
percent, out of about $610 billion in spending for federal
agencies. Then they argued all day about how to perform that fiscal
surgery, which would yield close to $1.3 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before midnight on Wednesday they agreed to exclude
military personnel from the cut and to give the White House the
flexibility it sought on imposing the cut on the rest of the
government, said Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., who is chairman of the
Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Their daylong dispute was ``like when you go to buy a house, and
you've agreed on the price, and all that's left is a disagreement
over the color of the trim on the tool shed,'' said Robert
Stevenson, a senior aide to Domenici.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before midnight, the chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, Rep. C.W. Bill Young, R-Fla., said he
planned to file the final spending package on the floor of the
House before dawn. The White House said at 1 a.m. on Thursday that
it was still reviewing the bill's fine print.
</P>
<P>
   The House will meet on Thursday morning to debate it. Congress
is operating under a 24-hour continuing resolution, keeping the
government running without a real budget until midnight. Under
expedited rules of procedure that members jokingly call ``martial
law,'' the House is expected to pass the final package, containing
the last five of the year's 13 spending bills, and send it to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Then another battle is likely in the Senate. It involves federal
price controls for dairy farmers, an issue so crucial to the
combatants that they are threatening to shut down the Senate, block
any final budget bill and keep Congress in session well into
December.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., has placed a formal hold on the final
spending package in an effort to protect his state's 23,000 dairy
farmers from legislation favoring Northeastern milk producers.
</P>
<P>
   The budget cannot pass, and Congress cannot adjourn, until he
lifts that hold, because the legislation he opposes is in the final
spending package that will be filed in the House, voted on and most
likely passed on Thursday before going to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lew, the White House budget director, said the dairy
dispute was so dire that it raises a real risk of a government
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   This looming problem dismays many members of Congress. When the
House majority leader, Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, began talking
about it on the House floor Wednesday, members began to moo.
</P>
<P>
   The day's war of words began when the House speaker, Dennis
Hastert of Illinois, said President Clinton had agreed in a
telephone call from Turkey to an across-the-board cut of 0.38
percent in the budget, which is now 47 days overdue. That cut was a
political do-or-die issue for the Republicans, but only part of the
financial solution. The final piece was agreeing on how to impose
it.
</P>
<P>
   The senators, representatives and White House aides coming and
going through the Senate's corridors for the negotiations looked
exhausted after 10 nearly nonstop days of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders were pressing hard to finish without spending
more money. ``If I were king, I would have their heads all cut
off,'' the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was seeking every last new dollar it could
extract from Congress before shaking hands, including $100 million
for a program for disabled workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans needed nearly $7 billion in savings to allow
them to say that their spending bills would not dip into Social
Security surpluses _ a political point they have made daily, since
spring, but still have not formally fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   So the White House brought nearly $7 billion to the bargaining
table on Wednesday, enough to cover the Republicans demands without
an across-the-board cut.
</P>
<P>
   Up to $3.5 billion would come from a one-time transfer from the
Federal Reserve's portfolio of government securities - _ strictly
bookkeeping device, since the money belongs to the government to
begin with.
</P>
<P>
   The rest would come from delaying government paychecks for
military personnel and many civilian employees for about 48 hours,
until just after 12:01 a.m. next Oct. 1, the start of the next
fiscal year. This would not save any money, but simply shift more
than $3.2 billion in spending into next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals remained in the final package, along with the
across-the-board cut. Both sides agreed to exclude military
personnel from the cut. Then came the stumbling block: how to
impose the $1.3 billion cut.
</P>
<P>
   The argument was over who would control the budget-cutting
scalpel, what programs could be protected and which ones could take
deep cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides described this as an ``issue of flexibility.'' Two
weeks ago, Clinton vetoed a 0.97 percent across-the-board cut that
Congress passed, almost exclusively with Republican votes, calling
it a ``blind and mindless'' exercise.
</P>
<P>
   To make such a cut seem sensible to Democrats, the White House
insisted on shielding some programs and cutting others more deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before midnight, they won an agreement. Domenici said
that its terms allowed some programs within federal agencies to be
protected from the cuts; other programs could be cut by up to 15
percent to make up the difference and achieve the savings.
</P>
<P>
   That helps ``make it not really across the board, but driven by
policy,'' Lew said. ``With a little more room to concentrate, it
becomes a tool we can manage.''
</P>
<P>
   An across-the-board cut was a matter of principle for the
party's conservatives in the House, who wore big buttons on their
lapels today saying they had ``stopped the raid on Social
Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as important to two Democratic senators are demands for
their home states.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia is threatening a filibuster to
protect his state's coal miners from a federal court ruling barring
them from dumping in valley streams. His last-minute legislation
that would stop the court ruling from taking effect for two years.
The White House first supported Bryd's effort, then said it would
veto any bill containing it. It appeared to be striking a
noncommital stance on the issue on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Kohl and the dairy dispute.
</P>
<P>
   This year the House approved a measure that lets a system
keeping the price of milk in New England artificially high to
remain in place for another two years.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has placed a hold on every piece of legislation pending in
the Senate, including the budget bill, to stop that measure from
becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raw politics _ that's what originated it, and that's what
keeps it going,'' Kohl said in an interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authority for the cartel expired on Sept. 30, though a judge's
order has kept the pricing mechanism in place temporarily. In
September the House voted, 285 to 140, to extend the system. Then
Hastert and Lott agreed this week to attach a two-year extension of
the cartel to one of the final spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The milk issue is all about economic self-interest,''
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said last month. Now it will be
decided in the closing hours of this Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 0156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
