<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS' SUCCESS HAS KENNEDY WALKING ON AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The new life that has been breathed into the Seahawks
has not gone wasted on Cortez Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   At 31, with a decade in the NFL, seven Pro Bowl appearances and
not a single Seahawks playoff game to relish, Kennedy is so
inspired this season he looks as weightless as a NASA experiment.
</P>
<P>
   It's not often you find a 306-pound defensive tackle
twinkle-toeing across the turf like Fred Astaire.
</P>
<P>
   The way Kennedy's playing, he had better watch out. The Arthur
Murray School of Dance might call him for tips on that feathery
little number he unveiled last Sunday night against the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, a buoyant Kennedy two-stepped over Denver
lineman Mark Schlereth, leveling the veteran as Kennedy went in hot
pursuit of quarterback Chris Miller. It was a gem of a play.
</P>
<P>
   After such moves, people are talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My friend) Richmond Webb from the Dolphins called me after
the game,'' Kennedy said Wednesday. ``He said, `Tez, you're 31.
You're supposed to be on your way out of this league. You're
playing like you're 21 or 22.' But I don't feel it. By body's
aching. I'm nicked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's why I'm so happy. I'm so happy in my 10th year, on
my way out of the league, and we're standing here 7-2. I figure I'm
on the three-year plan. I want to get to the playoffs and to the
Super Bowl and then quit. Maybe we'll do it in two years.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual in the NFL, the way pain often accompanies good
things. Only in Kennedy's case, the scales have at times seemed
tipped too heavily in favor of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Here he is, playing some of his best football on what is the
best Seahawks team he's ever seen and he's thinking about winning
the big one soon so he can call it a career _ a complete career.
</P>
<P>
   But there is good reason for some of Kennedy's world weariness.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the third-year pro from Miami reeled off an atomic
season and was voted the NFL's defensive player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a footnote to this outstanding achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Also in '92, Kennedy's Seahawks bombed in an embarrassing 2-14
campaign and, far worse, Kennedy was stung by the death of Jerome
Brown, his former Hurricanes' teammate, best friend and training
partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tragedy,'' Kennedy said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individually, it's been great. I've done a lot of things on
the football field and playing all these years with the Seahawks.
But I'm starting to feel I've been doing this a long time already.
My body's tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, as the Seahawks stand alone atop the AFC West with a shot
at playing a few important games in January, Kennedy is casting
these marvelous times as his swan song _ an interesting image
considering the source.
</P>
<P>
   But if the loss of Brown in '92 made Kennedy understand how life
is a weird mix of pain and happiness, he has been jarred again this
season by the loss of his agent and friend, Robert Fraley.
</P>
<P>
   Fraley, along with golfer Payne Stewart and four others, died in
a plane crash last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Robert died, that was really tough, especially when it's
someone you look up to,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things Robert said was: `Tez, you're going to make
the Pro Bowl (this season) because you're in great shape. I have to
play at Pebble Beach the week of the Pro Bowl, but after the Pro
Bowl, stay over in Hawaii for a week and we're going to come spend
some time with you,''' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Robert's wife the other day and I told her if I
get to the Pro Bowl, `I'm going to fly you over so we can get
together' and she said, `Tez, I'll fly myself over to see you
because Robert would have been so proud.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, though, has learned how to persevere _ a skill honed by
so many trying seasons in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, in the heart of the 10-year stretch of playoffless
seasons when former owner Ken Behring was attempting to move the
Seahawks to Los Angeles, Kennedy filed a lawsuit with other
teammates. The suit charged that the Hawks deserved to stay in
Seattle because that's what the players' contracts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably wanted to trade me after I filed that lawsuit,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Behring's son, David, ranted against Kennedy by calling
the career Seahawk ``fat, lazy and lacking in leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   After the season, Kennedy was presented with the Steve Largent
Award _ an award to the player who best exemplifies the spirit,
dedication and integrity of the Seahawks. David Behring had to do
the honors.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, the Behrings were gone and so was Dennis
Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kennedy is benefiting from the leadership of Mike Holmgren.
Tez is tasting sweet revenge for all those trying, numbing, losing
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the nine years I've been around, I've never been in a
situation like this. When it gets to be November and it starts
raining around here, it was the time we'd be losing and we'd all be
depressed. Now we're just happy and jolly and the rain doesn't
bother us anymore,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Holmgren comes up to me and says: `Tez, this is what
you've been waiting for,''' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him, `Coach, I will do whatever it takes to win.
I've tried it my way for nine years and it never did any good.' So,
he brought new life to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tez may be feeling like his body's done too many years of hard
labor, but the way he's playing, it's delightfully impossible to
tell.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
