<HEADLINE>
NBC RATES MIGHTY LOW WITH LOYAL NASCAR FANS 
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By John Sturbin 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the height of the Vietnam War, one of the tongue-in-cheek
suggestions offered for resolving the conflict was to televise it
live on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because it would get canceled in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by Sunday's overnight ratings _ and the overnight
rantings and ravings sent to my voice and e-mails _ NBC's debut
coverage of the NASCAR Winston Cup Series had a similar chilling
effect upon television's fastest-growing sport.
</P>
<P>
   Very strange. And if you are Dick Ebersol, the chairman of NBC
Sports, very disconcerting in light of the ``milestone'' $2.4
billion contract signed between the stock-car sanctioning body and
its newest television partners last week.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural Pennzoil 400 drew a sellout crowd of 80,000 to the
Homestead-Miami Speedway in South Florida. But the preliminary, or
overnight, rating of 3.0 and 7 share was the lowest for a Cup race
this year. (Ratings measure the number of U.S. households with
televisions watching the event, and share is the number of
households with their TVs turned on and watching the event.
Overnight ratings measure the top 44 markets).
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR also reported that the rating was the lowest of any race
broadcast on network TV since it began compiling such information
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch! And again, very strange, considering that Winston Cup
points-leader Dale Jarrett _ a popular, second-generation driver _
went into the day poised to clinch his first series championship.
After keeping track of every lug nut and lap for 32 races, how
could any self-respecting NASCAR fan not tune in to watch that bit
of unfinished business?
</P>
<P>
   Well, plenty of loyal NASCAR fans found something better to do
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe the loyal NASCAR fans initially did tune in. And maybe
about halfway through one of the most boring races of the year, and
with Jarrett's position safe and sound, they decided it was time to
channel surf for a football game.
</P>
<P>
   Or wash their socks.
</P>
<P>
   Or otherwise register their displeasure with the quality of
NBC's broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Or demonstrate their disappointment at the impending departure
of their friends at CBS/TNN and ESPN/ABC from the broadcast scene
after 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Choose your rationale. But the numbing numbers were recorded
only three days after NBC, News Corp.'s Fox Sports and Time Warner
Inc. unit TBS agreed to a landmark six-year, $400 million-a-year
contract with NASCAR. NBC, which was scheduled to televise the
Pennzoil 400 before the blockbuster contract was announced, will
team with TBS to show the second half of the schedule in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, NBC cannot be faulted for the fact that the race
was a snoozer. Blame that on the relatively flat, 1.5-mile
Homestead layout and its current one-groove personality. Rookie
sensation Tony Stewart did his best to liven up the afternoon with
a bit of paint-trading against teammate Bobby Labonte while
jockeying for the lead in the latter stages.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart then handed NBC a nice post-race story line with his
rookie-record third victory of the season. And Jarrett deservedly
did hoist the Cup, joining his father, Ned, as the second
father-son championship combination in NASCAR history.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several fans leaving voice and e-mails at the office here
blasted NBC's coverage, labelling it ``pitiful'' and ``sanitized''
and ``god-awful.'' And stuff like that. In other words, they felt
the coverage was not up to the standards they have grown accustomed
to on the current network lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, some of the anger aimed at NBC was of the backlash
variety, directed at the performances of lead announcer Allen
Bestwick, color commentators Joe Gibbs and Mike Wallace, and host
Brian Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Primarily because they are not Bob Jenkins, Benny Parsons,
Ned Jarrett, Dr. Jerry Punch, Bill Weber, John Kernan, Buddy Baker,
Ken Squier, Mike Joy, Dr. Dick Berggren and all the familiar faces
and voices we have welcomed into our living rooms on race weekends
for the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   No fans are more loyal than NASCAR fans, a fact NBC undoubtedly
banked on before it landed the lucrative contract. Judging by
Sunday's overnights, NBC learned that fan loyalty was not included
in the deal.
SPOTLIGHT ON... Team Rahal's Indy run hinges on fiscal sense Now
that he has reigning Indianapolis 500 champion Kenny Brack under
contract, CART team owner Bobby Rahal has an extra incentive to
return to the Indianapolis Motor Speedway next May.
</P>
<P>
   Team Rahal is among a group of prominent CART loyalists
seriously considering the purchase of Indy Racing League chassis
and engines in a one-off bid to compete in the 84th Indianapolis
500. Rahal, the 1986 Indy 500 champion, has joined the majority of
his CART brethren in boycotting the race since 1996 in a
philosophical disagreement with IRL founder Tony George.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's negotiations between George, who also is the
president of the IMS, and leaders of the Championship Auto Racing
Teams series helped thaw some of the lingering ill will. And CART's
2000 schedule neatly has provided an opening for those teams
longing to try to qualify and race at The Brickyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that we are going through the process of due
diligence toward participating at Indy,'' Rahal said. ``I wish it
was as simple as that. It's not as though it's an inexpensive
proposition. Having said that, I think open-wheel racing deserves
our doing everything we can to get back. For us to go back would
bring back the stature of Indy, and \Rcreate\S a halo effect over
open-wheel racing as a whole. Over the next several months, I'll be
talking with our partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to manage Kenny there and \Rteammate\S Max Papis; I
think he'd light the place up. While we're going through due
diligence and it would be nice, it cannot come at any expense of
our CART program. That's our primary goal: to win the CART
championship next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I had my druthers, we'd be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack, the 1998 IRL champion, won last year's race while driving
for four-time Indy 500 winner A.J. Foyt of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indianapolis is the world's biggest race ... if you look at
the attendance and everything,'' Brack said. ``I'm aware from a
driver's standpoint that I will never win a bigger race in my
career. My goal for next year is to win in the CART series. I would
obviously like to go back to Indy and defend the championship, but
I understand there are things that could make that not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahal, who co-owns the team with comedian David Letterman, said
he has approximately 60 days to consider several issues concerning
Indy. Chief among them is budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to go to Indy, you've got to go to win _
meaning multiple cars, engines and crews,'' Rahal said. ``If you
think you're going to stroll in and blow anybody off, it wouldn't
be too smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahal said the cost to cover purchase of IRL equipment would be
approximately $1 million per car _ one that would have to be
dissected and learned almost on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody would feel all you have to do is show
up,'' Rahal said. ``But there are good people out there that can
short-cut a lot of the learning curve on those cars. It's a big
demand on the CART teams to go forward on this. It's not like it's
a cheap or easy deal. In some respects it's a hardship to gear up.
But if in the long term open-wheel racing regains its positiveness,
you do everything you can to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other teams reportedly mulling a return to Indy are Newman/Haas
Racing with Michael Andretti and Christian Fittipaldi; Team Penske
with Gil de Ferran and Helio Castro-Neves; Chip Ganassi Racing with
reigning CART champion Juan Montoya and Jimmy Vasser; Team Kool
Green with Dario Franchitti and Paul Tracy; and the reunited 1992
Indy 500 winning combination of Al Unser Jr. and owner Rick Galles.
QUICK HITS Petty sets Cup debut Adam Petty, NASCAR's first
fourth-generation driver, plans to make his NASCAR Winston Cup
debut at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth in April.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a new three-year sponsorship agreement with Sprint,
Petty will attempt to qualify for the DIRECTV 500 on Friday, March
31. That would set up the possibility of Petty competing against
his father, Kyle, in the same Cup race also featuring the in-house
battle between seven-time series champion Dale Earnhardt and
rookie-of-the-year candidate Dale Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be difficult,'' said Petty, 19, who has charted
a five-race Cup program for 2000. ``I know from watching my dad and
granddad \RRichard\S that the Winston Cup Series is the toughest
competition there is. But we're ready for the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty completed his rookie season in the NASCAR Busch Grand
National Series at Homestead-Miami Speedway on Saturday. In his
most recent appearance on the 1.5-mile TMS quadoval, Petty finished
16th in the O'Reilly 300 NASCAR Craftsman Truck race in a Dodge
fielded by grandfather King Richard. Martin facing surgery Winston
Cup star Mark Martin is scheduled to have surgery on his
chronically ailing back Monday, the day after the season-ending
NAPA 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway. The surgery will fuse two lower
vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dread it,'' said Martin, driver of the No. 6 Valvoline Ford
Taurus. ``I really dread being crippled again and having to rehab
again and fight my way back from being helpless. It takes a lot of
your manhood away when you're handicapped like that. It's just not
worth going on like I am right now if there's a chance I could get
better.'' Atlanta tickets remain Approximately 12,000 reserved
tickets in the East Turn and Weaver Grandstands are available for
Sunday's NASCAR Winston Cup season-ending NAPA 500 at Atlanta Motor
Speedway. Ticket office hours have been expanded from 8 a.m. to 7
p.m. Tickets also are available via Ticketmaster at
www.ticketmaster.com. Ray tests at Kentucky Reigning Indy Racing
League champion Greg Ray logged the first laps over 200 mph at the
new 1.5-mile Kentucky Speedway on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Team Menard were accompanied to Sparta, Ky., by Brian
Barnhart, the director of racing operations for the IRL. Barnhart
said Ray ran between 25 and 30 laps with a top speed of 208 mph in
an effort to get feedback on a surface that was finished last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to find the line on the racetrack,'' Ray said,
``and see if the seams where they patched the lanes together were
even and didn't bother the car. And find the bumps. It's probably
fine the way it is, but we gave them some suggestions, and I think
they agreed to do all those things.''
</P>
<P>
   The $152 million facility initially will seat 65,000. The track
is scheduled to play host to the inaugural The Belterra Resort Indy
300 on Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the track can be two-groove,'' said Ray, of Plano.
``There's probably one line that is faster, but I think you can run
three or four lines, and certainly at least two.'' Ray claims IRL
awards Greg Ray and team owner John Menard collected more than $1
million of the $2.8 million in bonuses and special awards presented
during the IRL's award ceremony in Indianapolis on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest payoff was a $1 million bonus for winning the season
championship. Ray earned $30,000 for leading a league-high 464
laps; $10,000 for winning four pole positions and $10,000 for
leading the most races at halfway.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Harrington earned $50,000 as rookie of the year, and
motorcycle aficionado Scott Goodyear was presented a new
Harley-Davidson for winning the most-popular-driver award. Last
words ``It's important that things work for Fox or NBC or whoever,
because they are going to be the way the bulk of fans see and
perceive our sport.'' _ Kyle Petty, on the prime partners in
NASCAR's new TV deal
INSIDE THE NUMBERS Genuine Ford guys Ned and Dale Jarrett became
the second father-son combination to win NASCAR championships when
Dale clinched the 1999 NASCAR Winston Cup crown at Homestead-Miami
Speedway on Sunday. (Lee and Richard Petty were the first.) The
Jarretts also have played a significant role in the NASCAR
championship history of Ford Motor Co., as two of five drivers to
win titles for the manufacturer: Year Driver Car owner Wins Poles
1965 Ned Jarrett Bondy Long 13 9 1968 David Pearson Holman-Moody 16
12 1969 David Pearson Holman-Moody 11 14 1988 Bill Elliott Harry
Melling 6 6 1992 Alan Kulwicki Alan Kulwicki 2 6 1999 Dale Jarrett
Robert Yates 4 0
</P>
