<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RANGERS GENERAL MANAGER DESERVES PAT ON BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For now, Doug Melvin was right. And to prove it, he almost has a
bruised spine from all the congratulatory slaps on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow baseball executives spent last week toasting Melvin at
the general manager's meetings in California.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Paul Beeston, No. 2 man in the game behind
commissioner Bud Selig, told Rangers owner Tom Hicks, ``Your GM
should be arrested for grand larceny.''
</P>
<P>
   And the phone calls and e-mail at The Ballpark in Arlington ran
90 percent in favor of what Melvin did.
</P>
<P>
   All this over the trade two weeks ago of Juan Gonzalez. Count me
among those who agreed with Melvin on this one, but I darn sure
don't think the deal with Detroit was that cut-and-dried, or that
wonderful. The only dissent, however, over the moving of Juan seems
to have come from segments of the local media, plus a small
minority of fandom. Everywhere else, Melvin is being hailed as bold
and bright for this decision.
</P>
<P>
   But what you won't find is Melvin patting himself on the back.
``There was nothing easy about trading Juan, and with his
credentials, why should there be?'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   And by next August, or the August after that, once we receive a
definitive read on how the cargo from Detroit has performed for the
Rangers, then comes judgment day. Also in the equation is what
Melvin adds to the Rangers with the massive amount of short-term
and long-term payroll saved by trading Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Melvin was right, mainly because he was a jump
ahead on both the financial market and the talent market in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   With a glut of star-quality players becoming free agents after
the 2000 season (including Juan), Melvin correctly predicted six
weeks ago that the winter trade scene would become crowded and
therefore weaker as far as receiving value. Hence, the quick
trigger-finger with Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the bottom-line aspect. ``If there's one crazy
contract by one team, it will blow the lid off,'' Melvin said the
day he dealt Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   There was. It did. Less than a week after the Gonzalez deal, the
dumbo Dodgers traded with Toronto for outfielder Shawn Green, then
signed Green for an astonishing $84 million for six years.
</P>
<P>
   If a Shawn Green is making $14 million a season, then what will
Gonzalez eventually want? Certainly much more than the $15 million
that the Rangers feared would be Juan's number.
</P>
<P>
   So Melvin got the fast break on everyone. His fellow GMs, many
of them facing the same headaches, were not hesitant to applaud him
during the California meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, a lot of clubs seemed to feel we had done the right
thing,'' said Melvin, low-keying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what I really found encouraging, was the amount of
interest in the Detroit players we got,'' he added. ``All those
names came up in trade proposals last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as free-agent-to-be pitcher Andy Ashby, who the San Diego
Padres moved to Philadelphia. What the Padres wanted from the
Rangers was pitcher Francisco Cordero and outfielder Gabe Kapler, a
request Melvin nixed. Both Cordero and Kapler, of course, just
arrived from the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   It will be important, obviously, that the Gonzalez deal delivers
on-the-field value to the Rangers. But just as vital for a general
manager is the juggling of the budget on players' salaries. Melvin
made that kind of call in trading Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there are 15 percent of the players making 75
percent of the money in the major leagues,'' Melvin said. ``I've
never heard of a union intent on satisfying 15 percent of its
members, but the players have that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under that guideline, if our budget is $75 million, $50
million of that would go to four players. You can't put the right
team on the field if four players command 75 percent of your
budget. I didn't want to trade Juan, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin read the market correctly, and acted. And his current
read now centers on the slim pickings among free-agent pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an interest,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   But does he really? Lefty Chuck Finley reportedly has been
offered $27 million for three years by the desperate Indians. And
lefty Darren Oliver, the former Ranger, turned down four years at
$24 million from the Cardinals. Is Oliver nuts, or is this just
baseball?
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's own free-agent pitcher, Aaron Sele, is said to have an
asking price of $36 million for four years. Melvin sounded
confident of still being able to re-sign Sele, but bet this: Melvin
won't go for that asking price.
</P>
<P>
   And Kenny Rogers? Again, the Rangers have interest, and Rogers
has little bargaining power. But his demands could still be
outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin just jumped out of one financial fire with the Gonzalez
trade. But free agency now shoves him right back into the burning
house. Welcome to the financial inferno that is baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
