</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WORKERS (Beijing) _ Workers at an outmoded textile factory
in Beijing say the trade accord comes too late to help them _ their
factory is a likely casualty _ but they welcome it, railing against
their Communist Party-appointed managers. The big question is
whether the government can provide a safety net for them and
millions of others. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-THALIDOMIDE (Washington) _ In a serendipitous discovery that
grew out of the pleas of a lawyer whose young husband was dying of
cancer, scientists will report that thalidomide can slow the course
of a deadly bone cancer. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-LIFESPAN (Undated) _ Yielding a sharp insight into the
genetic reasons for death, a team of Italian scientists has
discovered a gene that controls lifespan in the mouse. In people,
where the gene was first found, the effects are unknown, but the
scientists and other experts in aging say they can envisage drugs
that affect the gene being used as an anti-wrinkle skin cream and
perhaps for less frivolous rejuvenation effects. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JUPITER (Undated) _ Measurements from the Galileo spacecraft
suggest that Jupiter formed farther out in the solar system than
where it now orbits, and that it somehow moved inward, wreaking
havoc on theories of the early years of the solar system. By James
Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-JOURNALISM (Nashville, Tenn.) _ In September 1971, the
latest $95-a-week greenhorn, a shaggy-haired 23-year-old named
Albert A. Gore Jr., joined the Nashville Tennessean. The grizzled,
bourbon-swilling veterans presumed that the son and namesake of
Tennessee's recently deposed U.S. senator was looking to pad his
resume. But to their surprise, Gore stayed for nearly five years
and became a skilled investigative reporter. Many were caught off
guard when he abandoned the trade to run for Congress in 1976. By
Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TECH-WORKERS-SHORTAGE (San Francisco) _ Thanks to the booming
technology-based economy, companies' long-standing scramble for
qualified technical workers has taken on an air of desperation
lately. A severe shortage of engineers who design hardware and
software and create Web pages has led companies and their
recruiters to try all sorts of tricks, like one persistent
entrepreneur who repeatedly called a Web site here looking for
Nevil _ unaware that Nevil is a black Labrador retriever. By Matt
Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IRS-WORKERS (Undated) _ Urged on by Congress to get tough on
abuse of taxpayers, the Treasury Dept. is formulating a plan to
subject IRS employees to more scrutiny than other federal workers.
But IRS managers and union leaders, and even some in the inspector
general's office, say intensified scrutiny will distract many IRS
agents as they defend themselves, making the agency less potent in
pursuing tax cheats. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Chinese stocks have zoomed since
the WTO agreement Monday. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-HYPERMARKETS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ A little over a
year ago, the French food retailer Carrefour set up one of its
sprawling hypermarkets on the edge of Jakarta. If opening a fancy
modern grocery in a shrinking economy seemed risky then, it seemed
foolhardy a month later, when rioting mobs looted the new market.
But in the year that followed, the supermarket has been visited by
a different sort of mob, one bent on buying as much as it can. By
Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHANGES-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Two big advertisers in two big
competitive categories _ energy and telecommunications _ are making
changes on their accounts. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bob Herbert talks about efforts to
