A3519 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SOC-GALNOTE_LADN-(SLA     11-18 0268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALNOTE_LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES GALAXY NOTEBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ Los Angeles Galaxy defender Robin Fraser was
selected as Major League Soccer's Defender of the Year, edging D.C.
United's Jeff Agoos and last season's winner, Lubos Kubik of the
Chicago Fire.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser, 32, who finished third in last year's voting, helped the
Galaxy become the first MLS team to allow less than one goal per
game (29 in 32 games) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The team captain has helped the Galaxy lead the league in least
goals allowed the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy arrived on Wednesday in Foxboro, where the game-day
weather forecast is in the 50's with a slight chance of showers. In
the 1996 final in Foxboro, torrential rains changed the pace of the
game as United won, 3-2, in sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember waking up that morning and seeing a monsoon,'' said
Agoos of MLS Cup '96. ``It became less of a soccer game, more of
how to survive. It should be a different environment this time. The
field looks as good as it's going to get. We should see more
attractive soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Both United and the Galaxy like to spread the field, but Foxboro
has one of the smallest fields in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the smallest field we've played on,'' said Galaxy coach
Sigi Schmid. ``It makes it easier to defend. Both teams have speed
up front. Short fields mean there's not that much space behind the
fence. The last time we played at Foxboro, we scored five goals.
Half that many would be great Sunday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
