<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3520 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-STRONACH-LADN-(SL     11-18 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-STRONACH-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONACH REVERSES STAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Santa Anita Park owner Frank Stronach reversed
his previous stand Wednesday and said his five race tracks will
continue paying dues next year to the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association, but at a reduced rate.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, while attending the Breeders' Cup at
Gulfstream Park in Hallandale, Fla., Stronach threatened to quit
paying dues to the struggling national organization. He has been
openly critical of the group for being ``buddy-buddy'' and
``clubish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stay in, but we will pay a reduced rate,'' Stronach
said in a telephone interview from his home in Vienna, Austria.
``Hopefully, we'll have some positive influence on the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   NTRA spokesman Chip Tuttle confirmed that Stronach indicated he
would like a reduction in dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no agreement on that,'' Tuttle said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Santa Anita, Stronach owns _ or is about to own _ Golden
Gate Fields near Berkeley, Thistledown in Cleveland, Remington Park
in Oklahoma City, Okla., and Gulfstream. In fiscal 1999, those
tracks paid dues totaling approximately $1.2 million to the NTRA.
The association has an annual operating budget of nearly $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   A mathematical formula that determines the dues of member tracks
is based largely on the track's handle _ the amount of money bet on
races run at that track. Santa Anita's contribution in fiscal 1999
was approximately $400,000, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly respect Mr. Stronach's investment in thoroughbred
racing and understand that he has made a significant investment in
the future of the sport,'' Tuttle said. ``We share a lot of common
ground and mutual areas of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Stronach revised his stand on dues after a teleconference with
NTRA commissioner Tim Smith late last week. From Austria, he
renewed his criticism of the organization and called for a
democratic election of the NTRA board. NTRA board members, six in
all, are appointed by Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``(A lengthy) phone conversation with ... Smith was constructive
and cordial,'' Tuttle said. ``He indicated to us he was not going
to withdraw the tracks and we plan to continue discussions over the
next several weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Stronach's core beliefs is that thoroughbred horse racing
should be essentially unregulated in the United States and allowed
to operate unfettered. For example, he would like to see the
elimination of government-approved race calendars, so that tracks
could operate year-round if they wished. Stronach said the NTRA
should lobby federal and state governments for such diminished
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1998, the NTRA was formed to unify the horse
racing industry and develop marketing strategies to revive
struggling tracks. The league office in New York is headed by Smith
and his six hand-picked board members.
</P>
<P>
   One of those holding a chair in the boardroom is Doug Donn,
chairman of the Stronach-owned Gulfstream Park. Stronach may be
using the dues issue as a negotiating tool to get another seat on
the board _ perhaps for himself.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Stronach is not the first race track owner to
threaten a pullout. Several tracks on the East Coast are
considering similar action.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months the association has come under fire for its
fund-raising methods and for its hand in establishing the Los
Angeles-based Television Games Network. Many member tracks,
particularly in New York and Pennsylvania, believe the Oregon
gambling hub used by TVG competes with their own betting systems.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach himself doesn't support TVG and has not entered an
agreement with the network that would allow it to broadcast any
signal from Santa Anita in the Winter-Spring Meet, which begins
Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, his tracks will remain NTRA members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NTRA will be there and will be supported. It's a new
organization so let's reassess it,'' he said. ``The important thing
is we need a national organization that will promote (free
enterprise).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
