<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3521 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      11-18 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE ARRIVES JUST IN TIME FOR SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Perhaps the Sonics were a little too anxious to return
home.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of leaving behind a tie or belt or toothbrush after
their nine-day voyage back east, the Sonics apparently forgot to
pack their defense for the return trip.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the final buzzer drew near did it seem the Sonics had
been express-mailed their defensive schemes. That is when the
Sonics finally cooled the hot-shooting Golden State Warriors enough
to grab a 111-108 victory Wednesday night in KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had lost two of three games this season after giving
up more than 100 points. They avoided keeping with that trend in
spite of their own difficulties and an unusually overbearing
offense from the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State's point total was its season high and the
second-highest by a Sonics opponent. The Warriors (2-6) entered the
game shooting 39 percent, though they bombed the Sonics with a
52-percent outing.
</P>
<P>
   It took a frantic half-court trap with 6.4 seconds left to put
the Warriors away. Mookie Blaylock could have tied the score on the
game's final possession. But the Sonics somehow forced him to heave
a desperation shot as the buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a lucky night,'' Sonics guard Gary Payton said.
``That's what I consider it _ luck. We should play better than we
did. If we played defense a little bit better than what we played
or even half of what we can play, we could have probably beaten
this team by a lot more and everybody could have rested for (the
Thursday's game).''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Sonics (7-2) play at Vancouver in their second set
of back-to-back games this season. They take a two-game winning
streak up north, but you would never know from their reaction over
beating the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those nights when a win was anything but
satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the Sonics were entrenched in a seesaw battle
against the struggling Warriors. Even when the Sonics increased a
80-79 advantage late in the third period and led by 12 points in
the fourth, the game never seemed under control.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 103-93 with 5:55 left, the Sonics buckled as Golden State
smacked them with a 13-4 run. The Sonics later clung to a 109-106
lead when Horace Grant hit a pair of free throws with 37.1 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Cummings quickly responded with a 14-foot jumper. Then Vin
Baker shot an airball with the shot clock running down, and that
gave the Warriors hope until the end.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Antawn Jamison's game-high 27 points made him the
toughest Warrior to control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against guys like San Antonio and the (Los Angeles) Lakers, we
can't rely on playing 24 minutes and play 48 minutes,'' Grant said.
``We've got to play aggressive all the time. A win is a win. But as
a team, we can't go into a place like Vancouver, which is very
talented, and expect to win with the defense we played tonight.
We've got to play like we played in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the Sonics only played stingy defense in spurts. If
not for a huge third quarter that helped the Sonics open a 22-point
lead, the Sonics might not have been able to sustain the Nets' late
rally.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus Wednesday night was the Sonics' on-again,
off-again defensive effort is a nasty trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just concentration,'' said Vin Baker, who led the Sonics
with 23 points on 10 of 19 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Said guard Brent Barry: ``Guys are competitive enough to say
that we won, but we didn't win the way we wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry electrified the crowd and sparked the Sonics late in the
third. He flew baseline and threw down a dunk over Cummings. Barry
drew a foul and made the free throw to complete a three-point play
that put the Sonics ahead, 85-79.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, who had trailed by eight points in the first half,
took an 89-83 advantage into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Person came off the bench an hit two 3-pointers early in
the fourth. His last bomb put the Sonics ahead, 99-87, with 9:14
left in the game. Persons' baskets represented the first time the
Sonics had anyone score off the bench other than Vernon Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   Person (6) and Maxwell (8) combined for 18 points _ all the
Sonics could muster off the bench. The Warriors' reserves countered
with 36. That, plus a rebounding discrepancy, nearly doomed the
Sonics. The Warriors finished with a 40-33 edge on the glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a game I was really worried about because we come
back from a long trip like that and just have one day off,'' Sonics
coach Paul Westphal said. ``Sometimes you take these home games for
granted. We were a little flat defensively, but we still found a
way to pull the win out so it was a really good win for us.''
</P>
<P>
   A win, yes. But `ugly' is probably the better adjective.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
