<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3522 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-LBMEN-LADN-(SLANG     11-18 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LBMEN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME HAS COME FOR MORGAN, 49ERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Wayne Morgan launches his fourth season
Saturday as Long Beach State's men's basketball coach, which may be
surprising to some since it was pretty well understood when he
started out Year 3 that it had best be a winning one.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. The 49ers came in at 13-15, and, looking back,
they're fortunate their record was that good. It took a
buzzer-beating basket by D'Cean Bryant at Loyola Marymount to get
into overtime, where the 49ers prevailed, and another last-second
shot by Charles O'Neal in order to beat UC Santa Barbara at home.
</P>
<P>
   There is no misunderstanding what's expected in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   As Athletic Director Bill Shumard put it, ``It is time for us to
win again.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan doesn't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have a winning season,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And by ``winning season,'' neither of them are talking about
merely getting above .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for us be in postseason play,'' said Shumard,
meaning the NCAA Tournament, or at least the NIT, not just the Big
West Tournament, where the 49ers are 1-3 the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in place. The 49ers return seven players from a year
ago, including all five of their starters two of them All-Big West
second team picks, Ramel ``Rock'' Lloyd and Mate Milisa, and
another, Antrone Lee, who was selected to the Bill West
all-tournament team and has displayed marked improvement already in
two exhibition wins.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, this time Morgan has everyone in place
from opening day. There will be no waiting around this season for a
key player to become eligible at midseason, as was the case three
years ago with Ike Nwankwo, and two years ago with Andy Betts, and
last year with O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the 49ers will start out this season, Morgan said, the
same way they finished last season, playing uptempo basketball,
taking advantage of their athleticism and speed.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings about the obvious question: What took so long?
</P>
<P>
   It's simply the belief, misguided perhaps, that the 49ers
thought they'd be a better rebounding team than they were. Now they
know better. So, the plan is to get the fastbreak rolling the
instant someone has his hands on the ball, whether it's off a
rebound or from out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only change I've made since the day I got here,'' Morgan
said, ``is that we run on makes and
</P>
<P>
   misses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a poor rebounding team,'' he acknowledged, noting the
49ers ranked 10th in rebounding last season in the Big West, ``and
people are playing a zone against us. One of the ways to beat that
is to get down there before they set up the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way is to beat a zone is by making 3-point baskets. The
49ers were 10th in that department, too.
</P>
<P>
   So, Morgan brought in 3-point specialist Brad Smith, who made 73
3-pointers last season at Cypress College, which is more than twice
as many as any 49er made and nearly half what all
</P>
<P>
   the 49ers made.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good shooter,'' Morgan said of the 6-foot-4 Smith, who
was four for 10 shooting 3s in the two exhibitions. ``And he's got
a very quick shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Another newcomer is 6-9 forward James Williams, whom Morgan
describes as ``a very key guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to help us a lot,'' Morgan said of Williams, who
averaged 12.8 points and 7.6 rebounds last season at Dixie (Utah)
Junior College. ``He's very athletic ... and, from what I've seen
so far, he's our best rebounder'' Williams had 13 rebounds in
Tuesday night's exhibition romp ``and the runs the court better
than our other frontcourt players.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest of the cast is familiar:
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd, a preseason pick by no less than six national
publications as the Big West Player of the Year. He averaged 18
points a game last season, the fourth-best single-season scoring
average in Long Beach State history, and, says Morgan, ``On any
given night he's capable to being one of the best 2 guards in
America. What we've got to do is have him do that on a night to
night basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Milisa, the 6-11 center, the team's leading rebounder a year ago
(5.6 average), who, Morgan said, ``is bigger, stronger, more
mature, more comfortable with what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, the 6-7 senior guard and forward, who, Morgan says, ``has
an incredible intellect for the game ... who would be an
all-conference player if he shows the same aggressive he did in the
tournament,'' when he scored 33 points against Idaho (14) and Boise
State (19).
</P>
<P>
   D'Cean Bryant, 6-6 forward from Lynwood, originally a Prop. 48
player who received another season of eligibility by earning his
bachelor's degree over the summer. It is Morgan's hope he'll
display his talents as he did in the 49ers' first exhibition game
when he scored 10 points over a 4{-minute span over a full 40
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Stone, 6-8 junior, playing his third season with the
49ers. ``He's improved a lot, he's playing very well right now,''
Morgan said. ``He knows all five positions on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Johnson, 6-1 sophomore guard. ``He has really improved,''
Morgan said. ``He worked extremely hard over the summer. He's a
very tough kid. And he can really jump.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, 6-3 senior guard, who Morgan says is another of the
49ers' ``keys'' to the season but missed Tuesday night's game
because of illness. ``He's an extremely talented player,'' Morgan
said. ``I'd like to see him have a string of good luck for a
change. No injuries, no sickness, no personnel problems. He's
probably one of the 20 best players in our conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other newcomers are guard Keith Felton ``who's a better
player than we thought,'' Morgan said and freshman Danny Horan, a
walk-on from Villa Park High. Another walk-on is 6-8 junior forward
Rory Clark, who averaged 16 points at Kaiser High in Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the season,'' said Morgan, who's 36-48
in his three years at Long Beach State and hasn't had a winning
season yet. ``It's the first year I've got veterans returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, we need to have a winning season. Learning how
</P>
<P>
   to win is a huge thing. First you have to learn how to compete,
then you have to learn how to win. When you do those two things,
and when you have carryover year to year ... that's what you call a
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hindsight being 20-20, yes, there are some things I would have
done differently, there are some things I should have done better.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know I can coach. Not only do I know I can coach, my
peers know I can coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Shumard, Morgan's boss, has given his coach a firm
timetable by saying it's time to win again. But he insists he
hasn't issued a ``win-X-number-of-games-or-else'' edict,
explaining: ``Basketball coaches put enough pressure on themselves.
There's additional pressure because he's the coach at Long Beach
State. We have a tradition. We expect to win. He doesn't need any
more pressure from me ... or anyone else involved in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable where's he's positioned the program. I think
we're on the threshold of some pretty great things.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's set the table to win. We all expect to win. To what level
... I think we need to be careful. I've heard a few people say that
with this team in this league and with this schedule they ought to
win 20 games. And I'm quick to say, `Whoa, wait a minute.' Let's
take a look at the nonconference schedule, and at how balanced and
how competitive the Big West is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, our goal every year is to be in postseason play ...
and the time is right for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
