<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING AROUND WITH OUR WALLETS ON EMPTY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ I'm not mad at banks because of ATM surcharges. I'm
mad because they got me addicted to ATMs in the first place.
<P>
   As with any drug, the suppliers gave it away until we got
hooked, then they started charging us more and more.
</P>
<P>
   Remember life before ATMs?
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally you'd run out of cash at a bad time and have to
hustle around _ borrow money from your neighbor, sell your hubcaps.
But most of the time, you planned ahead and did just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Now how often are you frantically scrambling and searching for
an ATM, because you haven't been to a cash machine in two hours and
you're running low? I go to baseball and football games and there
are hourlong lines at the ballpark ATM. Didn't these people realize
they were coming to a ballgame?
</P>
<P>
   Some days I think I spend more time staring at ATM screens than
at my own TV screen, and that worries me.
</P>
<P>
   We have become ATM-dependent, ATM junkies. We won't be happy
until they make a personal ATM the size of a Palm Pilot, which will
print out bills, deducting funds from our bank account and the U.S.
Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the bills will have to be much smaller, about the
size of a Frito.
</P>
<P>
   I believe the government is making bills in varying sizes now
anyway, because I saw a sign in a store, ``Sorry, we don't accept
bills bigger than a $20.''
</P>
<P>
   I bet the new $500 bill is so big you can roll it up and use it
as a fungo bat.
</P>
<P>
   THE 49ERS are doomed to years of struggle, but at least the
Raiders have a decent team. In this age of NFL parity, it's
conceivable that they'll make it to Super Bowl, in which case:
</P>
<P>
   -- With the team cash-strapped due to poor ticket sales, the
players will have to hold bake sales to raise money for the trip to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Raiders won't sell their allotment of Super Bowl tickets,
so the game will be blacked out in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Raiders will win the Super Bowl and Los Angeles will
build them a stadium and lure them out of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   I think the Raiders and the 49ers ought to merge.
</P>
<P>
   The new team could play home games at the Giants' new ballpark.
There's no parking there, but everyone can park at the Oakland
Coliseum and ferry 'cross the Bay. With limited seating and a cool
ballpark, the games will all be sellouts even at obscenely inflated
prices, helping ease the financial burden the Raiders have heaped
on the taxpayers of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   There's enough talent on the two teams to make one really good
roster. The 49ers will get a top draft pick due to their crappy
record this season, and the Raiders' people can do the actual
drafting, since the 49ers' front office is currently clueless.
</P>
<P>
   What about a team name? We'll need one that retains the
character of both teams. Something from the Gold Rush era, yet
something that smacks of aggressive invasion of rights and
property.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gate Claim Jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   IT SNOWED at Tahoe, and the newspaper delivery was delayed, and
R.G. Lasson had nothing to read with breakfast, which happened to
be a sack of Pepperidge Farm Tahoe Chocolate Chunk Cookies.
</P>
<P>
   So Lasson did what any avid reader does when there's nothing to
read _ reads anything. In this case, the cookie package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tahoe ... An oasis in the majestic snow-topped Rocky
Mountains. The perfect name for an incredible cookie.''
</P>
<P>
   IF THE FBI takes over the investigation of the EgyptAir crash,
does Richard Jewell become the prime suspect?
</P>
<P>
   DO NOT DISTURB: The front entry to One Second Street, a building
scheduled for demolition, is home to a few homeless guys.
</P>
<P>
   George Seibert noticed that the lads have draped a red, white
and blue tarp over their little encampment. On the tarp is stamped
a corporate logo: ``Hyatt Resorts.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CHAINS are taking over, but the little guys are fighting
back with better business names. Sandy Mac Nab spotted a bakery in
Willits, Calif., called Baked to Differ, and an auto repair shop in
Eureka, Calif., named Honest Engine.
</P>
<P>
   IF OUR POLITICAL leaders are going to attack the ATM surcharge,
how about taking a whack at an even greater rip-off: The candy-bar
surcharge on change.
</P>
<P>
   You find yourself short of change for a parking meter or bus
fare or a Chronicle, you go into the corner market with your dollar
bill, and the reaction ranges from scorn to hostility to derisive
laughter. So you don't even try, you buy a pack of gum or a candy
bar in order to get the change.
</P>
<P>
   It's so humiliating to ask a merchant for change that whenever I
do it, I wear a ski mask.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
