<SLUG> BC-TAXES-R&AMP;DCREDIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH INDUSTRY WINS AGREEMENT ON EXTENDING R&AMP;D TAX CREDIT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The high-tech industry secured a victory on one of
its top legislative priorities Wednesday as Congress and the White
House agreed to a five-year extension of the research and
development tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   The tax write-off, which offsets the cost of developing products
ranging from software to drugs, had become entangled in a much
broader dispute over how to spend the anticipated federal budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans both support the tax credit, which is
worth about $2 billion a year to high-tech companies. But President
Clinton vetoed the tax credit in September when the GOP tied it to
a $792 billion tax cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of negotiations, administration officials and
congressional Republicans agreed on a $15 billion bill to extend
several expiring tax provisions, including the R&AMP;D tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   In order to put off the costs until the budget surplus swells,
the compromise will force high-tech companies to wait a year before
claiming the tax credit. Nevertheless, the agreement was hailed as
a major accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ecstatic,'' said Connie Correll, communications
director for the Information Technology Industry Council, which
represents some of Silicon Valley's largest firms in Washington.
``This is a tremendous boost for our industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Congress has only  &LR; extended the tax credit only one
year at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years is a reasonable amount of time that provides some
predictability,'' said Ed Black, president of the Computer and
Communications Industry Association. ``We want it to be
stimulative, and if you can't put it into your planning for the
future, it doesn't accomplish that.''
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley executives now have their sights on a permanent
extension of the tax write-off, an idea which has been endorsed by
President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the front-runner for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents contend that such tax breaks amount to little more
than corporate welfare and should be redirected toward either tax
breaks for individuals or social programs. But such complaints were
not heard Wednesday on Capitol Hill, where members have been
showered with record contributions from the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``R&AMP;D tax credits are good for all Americans, even though it
might go to companies that are doing research and development,''
said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of fact, as a result of that investment, it does
create more jobs, it helps America compete internationally,
technologically. I think it's a good investment of the people's
money in terms of a growing economy and the creation of more
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had their own words of praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research and development is the engine that drives our
country's economic growth,'' said Rep. Bob Matsui, D-Sacramento.
``This tax credit is a tremendous catalyst for companies who might
otherwise not take the risk of developing or improved &LR;   &LR; improving
technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   High-tech firms have made more than $3.8 million in political
contributions this year _ more than twice the amount during an
equivalent period last year, according to an analysis by the
nonpartisan Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Though no one expected the credit to die after the president's
veto, there was concern that it might be limited to one year.
Several sources said the administration tried to limit the
extension to two years in order to keep costs down but was
ultimately persuaded to accept five years.
</P>
<P>
   The tax relief package is expected to sail through the House and
the Senate later this week. It also includes a provision to protect
more than 1 million families who take advantage of child-care
credits from being bumped into a higher tax bracket, and provides
tax credits for employers who hire welfare recipients and veterans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 0339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
