<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 03:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3534 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CYBERSQUAT-LEGISLATIO     11-18 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSQUAT-LEGISLATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET TRADEMARK ACT CRITICIZED BY LEGAL SCHOLARS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ With both major political parties in a headlong
rush to court the high-tech industry, Congress is about to expand
corporate rights to Internet domain names, at the expense, say many
legal scholars, of small businesses and individuals.
<P>
   Lawmakers and Internet experts alike widely condemn so-called
cybersquatting, a form of extortion that the Trademark Cyberpiracy
Prevention Act is intended to stop.
</P>
<P>
   A cybersquatter is an individual who registers a famous name of
a corporation or person as a Web site address and then offers to
sell the name back to the person or company.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow trademark owners to sue people who register
a domain name that is ``identical to or confusingly similar to'' an
existing trademark or who demonstrate a ``bad faith intent to
profit'' from the trademark. It would also protect the names of
famous people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, all my bill is doing is taking traditional
trademark law _ which has been recognized for almost our entire
nation's history _ and applying it to the Internet,'' said Rep.
James Rogan, R-Glendale, a former judge and law professor.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation sped through the House on October 26 on a voice
vote. A similar bill passed the Senate, and the final version is
expected to pass Congress this week and then be signed by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But other legal experts say the legislation represents a major
expansion of trademark law that sharply tilts the balance in favor
of large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the bill ``massive overkill,'' Michael Froomkin, a law
professor at the University of Miami, said the bill's $100,000 in
statutory penalties will allow large companies to threaten small
businesses and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major things it's going to achieve is that now you
can write these scary demand letters to mom and pop domain
registrants, and say, `Do what we say, or you risk being liable for
up to $100,000,' '' Froomkin said. ``Unless they go to a lawyer to
find out where they stand, they're just going to cave, because
that's a scary, big number for your average small-businessperson.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill was pushed by Hollywood studios, which want more
protection for copyrighted names like Mary Poppins or Daffy Duck,
and by the trademark industry, including the American Intellectual
Property Law Association and the International Trademark
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But Milton Mueller, director of the graduate program in
telecommunications and network management at Syracuse University,
said his research shows that the flip side of cybersquatting,
so-called reverse domain-name hijacking, is just as big a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when you as an individual user have a perfectly
legitimate registered domain name, and somebody with a trademark
sends you a mean note from a lawyer threatening you with a lawsuit
and all kinds of expenses and tries to take the name away from
you,'' Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with these bills is, typically, they are drafted
at the behest of the trademark owners and they don't contain
protections against abuse of the process by the trademark owners.''
</P>
<P>
   In two well-known cases, a 12-year-old boy registered his
nickname, Pokey, and was threatened by the maker of Gumby and Pokey
toys, and Archie Comics pursued a child named Veronica who
registered her name.
</P>
<P>
   The White House initially opposed the bill, saying it takes a
unilateral U.S. approach that interferes with efforts to develop a
worldwide process to resolve domain-name disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The government-sponsored Internet Corporation for Assigned Names
and Numbers has a new international domain-name dispute process, in
coordination with the World Intellectual Property Organization, a
multilateral institution based in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe fundamentally we'd be walking down the wrong road
if we legislated a cybersquatting law and then the 200 or so
Internet countries around the world started legislating their own
rules and laws,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said last
month.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Domestic Trademark Law Pushed
</P>
<P>
   But Rogan said his bill applies only to domestic name
registrations, and that the White House wants to shift control over
Internet trademarks to an international tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Americans have a right, and I think an obligation, to
enforce our laws within the four corners of our nation, and not ask
some international organization not based in the United States to
enforce American trademark law,'' Rogan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why in the world would we want to surrender our sovereign
right to enforce domestic trademark law ... to some foreign entity,
oftentimes made up of members that compete with us in the economic
sphere?''
</P>
<P>
   To skirt White House objections, lawmakers attached the measure
to a satellite bill that the White House said President Clinton is
eager to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say current trademark law is already resolving many
cybersquatting problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts have been dealing with the more egregious cases of
real squatting by people who have no legitimate need or purpose for
getting a domain name other than to extort or extract some payment
from someone else,'' said David G. Post, a Temple University law
professor. ``But if this establishes a rule that in the case of a
conflict, the trademark owner always wins, that's a mistake. That's
bad policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller argued that electronic commerce has been growing by
leaps and bounds with minimal government interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there's some unruliness and a little bit of lawlessness
to the Internet,'' he said. ``But you can't rely on
special-interest industry lobbyists to say what's good for the
Internet economy. You have to take a little more long-term,
balanced approach. You have to make it a safe place for individuals
and small players as well the large companies that can afford to
lobby Congress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 0348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
