<HEADLINE>
SITE'S USE OF DALLAS COWBOYS WEAVES TANGLED WEB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys long have been considered the NFL's sexiest
team, but this isn't what they had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet site is using the Cowboys' name to promote
pornography and gambling online. A fan who accidentally reached the
site Wednesday while seeking the Cowboys' official site called the
NFL office in New York to complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started looking at it, and needless to say, we're taking
the appropriate steps to stop them from using the Cowboys' name,''
said Brian McCarthy, the league's senior corporate communications
manager. ``A lot of people out there try to attach their name to
the NFL. There are two areas that the NFL would never promote, and
that is pornography and gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   The site has a small disclaimer disavowing association with the
``Dallas Cowboys Football Team.'' It offers no information about
the Cowboys or the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The site's goal it says is ``to provide the finest sports
information available while at the same time giving our customers
visual pleasure. Life is short, we try to live it ever \Rsic\S
chance we get. If you are offended by our selections please
leave.'' The site's Webmaster did not immediately respond to an
e-mail request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys spokesman Rich Dalrymple said he was unaware of the site
and referred all questions to the league office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the ones who police that,'' Dalrymple said.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is in the process of evaluating the site to find out
where it originates. McCarthy said NFL Properties, the licensing
arm of all 31 NFL teams, first will send a cease-and-desist letter
that threatens legal action for illegally using a trademarked name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fan who called was under the impression that it was a site
maintained by the Cowboys,'' McCarthy said. ``If you type in the
words Dallas Cowboys, you could easily end up at this site. We can
see how people could be confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-cybersquatting legislation, which seeks to protect
trademarks online, has been attached to the Satellite Television
Home Viewers Act. The controversial bill passed the House last week
and is awaiting a vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It would allow trademark holders to sue cybersquatters in the
nation where the domain name was registered and seek up to $100,000
in damages.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
