<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-FINLEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS INTERESTED IN HAVING FREE-AGENT FINLEY MAKE A VISIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Free-agent pitcher Chuck Finley, unlikely to
re-sign with the Anaheim Angels, is starting to visit other teams
and other cities. The Rangers are hoping The Ballpark in Arlington
will be one of his stops.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin, who met with Finley last week in
California, said yesterday he would like to bring the left-hander
to Texas some time later this month and is planning to discuss that
with his agent, Tim Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But only if he's really interested; you have to be careful,''
Melvin said. ``We brought in a big left-hander \RRandy Johnson\S
last year. ... We want to make sure we're attractive to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley is attractive to a number of teams, partly because right
now he's only looking for a three-year contract. Two other
free-agent left-handed pithers, Darren Oliver and Kenny Rogers,
could each command as much as a five-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Both Oliver and Rogers are former Rangers pitchers, and their
agent, Scott Boras, said both would be interested in returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darren, as you know, still lives there, and Kenny enjoyed
living there,'' Boras said. ``But there are 17 teams looking for
No. 1 and No. 2 starting pitchers, and 14 teams are looking for
left-handed starters.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras worked out a five-year deal for Rogers with the New York
Yankees in 1995, but Melvin is reluctant to go even four years with
a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin has made a four-year offer to Aaron Sele, but it's only
the fourth time in five years as Rangers general manager that he
has offered a four-year contract to a pitcher. He also offered a
four-year deal to Rogers in 1995, John Wetteland in 1996 and
Johnson last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at a lot of four-year contracts on pitchers and a
lot of them are bad deals,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who will be 37 next year, is reportedly looking for a
three-year deal worth $27 million. He and his agent were in Phoenix
yesterday meeting with the Seattle Mariners and were unavailable
for comment. But Finley's asking price is why the Angels have
backed off in their attempts to re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we're not,'' Angels president Tony Tavares told
the ``Los Angeles Times''. ``But at the numbers I'm hearing, I'm
not sure we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels aren't the only team scared by the high cost of
pitching. The St. Louis Cardinals are backing off re-signing Oliver
because of what they've heard it will take.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way beyond where we ever thought it would go,'' Cardinals
GM Walt Jocketty said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said, ``A lot teams are afraid of the cost of pitching. I
think that's why you see so many teams trading for pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Kile, Pat Hentgen and Andy Ashby are among the pitchers
who have been traded since the end of the season. The Rangers have
talked with the Toronto Blue Jays about David Wells and the Dodgers
about Darren Dreifort and Ismael Valdes, but are uneasy about what
it would take to get them.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are especially interested in the Rangers' young relievers
_ Francisco Cordero, Jeff Zimmerman, Tim Crabtree and Mike Venafro
_ but Melvin is extremely reluctant give any of them up.
\Nsubheds:Zeile, McLemore at impasse The Rangers have reached an
impasse with free-agent third baseman Todd Zeile and free-agent
second baseman Mark McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   A source said Zeile is looking for a four-year deal; the Rangers
have offered a two-year contract with an option for a third year.
McLemore also wants a multiyear deal, but the Rangers are offering
only a one-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he is continuing to talk to both players' agents.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
