<HEADLINE>
TRUCKS, SUVS HIT THE TRACK AT 0 TO 60 IN SIX SECONDS, FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is this a truck or a race car? There are times I feel I need a
harness to hold back all its horses. While I haven't timed it, I've
read the Ford Lightning can do 0 to 60 miles per hour in a flat six
seconds. And, I believe it.
</P>
<P>
   This is a truck, of course, a very fast one. It can beat out
most sports cars at the starting gate (or light), maybe even the
ML55 sports utility from Mercedes. Of course, the Lightning is not
as plush as that Mercedes, but it does go for less than half the
price of a ML55.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Lightning is an F150 4 x 2 with a 5.4-liter Triton
Supercharged Intercooled V-8 with a modified 4R100 four-speed
automatic transmission and lots of heavy-duty equipment from its
battery to its cooler. It's nicely equipped with 6-way power
driver's seat, leather interior, power windows and locks, fog lamps
and more. The only options on it are a towing hitch and 6-disc CD
changer bringing the $29,355 price to $30,450 including $640
destination charge.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a truck to haul things to the dump, it's for show.
You don't have to burn rubber at every light, or challenge a
Porsche. It's a truck to be appreciated for all that's hidden under
the hood.
</P>
<P>
   And to employ a loyal cadre of believers, Ford is building these
SVT (Special Vehicle Team) models with four key ``virtues:''
performance, substance, exclusivity, and value. For that, buyers
will find certified SVT dealers, a certificate of authenticity to
owners showing its production sequence number out of the total
produced each year, a magazine (the SVT Enthusiast), and a discount
at the Bob Bondurant School of High Performance.
</P>
<P>
   When I first drove the Mercedes ML320, I thought it was the best
SUV around. Since that time, it has won accolade after accolade as
outstanding. That model came with a V-6 engine that performed
superbly; it had great pickup, who could want anything more. Then
came the ML430, with V-8 power that literally took off.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mercedes is coming out with a 360-horsepower ML55 that will
do 0 to 60 m.p.h. in 6.3 seconds. Believe me, if the 430 challenged
my belief in the difference between a V-6 and V-8, the ML55 is
going to truly put it to the test. The only thing that puts us all
back to reality is the price tag: around $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   While speed is a selling factor for some trucks and SUVs, what
is really growing, especially in the sport utility field is the
outfitting of these vehicles to individual desires.
</P>
<P>
   Land Rover is setting up dealerships that resemble an
outdoorsman's lodge, packed with not only Land Rover models but
also equipment that can be used for hunting, fishing, mountain
biking, you name it. Many of these dealerships also have outdoor
tracks so you can see just how the Discovery will do crossing logs,
or clinging to the side of a hill.
</P>
<P>
   Jeep is promoting a Jeep 101 course that travels from city to
city. They are an opportunity for both owners and prospective
buyers to test a Wrangler, Cherokee, or Grand Cherokee over a run
that includes rocks, log crossings, muddy paths, 30 degree
embankments, as well as some highway driving. If you want to
accessorize the Jeep, there's a whole line of goodies to do so. One
item that intrigued me was a tent that clips to the back of the
Jeep allowing access to the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is offering a full line of SUVs to meet anyone's needs from
the two-door Explorer Sport to the biggest SUV of all, the
Excursion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
