<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-ISLAND-BO     11-18 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-ISLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET SUVS, HOW ABOUT A 1931 ROADSTER/PICKUP? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLESBORO, MAINE _ When the ever-efficient ferry Margaret Chase
Smith dropped us off on this island off the coast of Maine,
Vacation '99 was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the island itself changes little from year to year,
each visit brings greater understanding about how life is lived out
in the middle of Penobscot Bay. Arriving ``on island'' this summer,
I was ready for the annual rummage sale, the Ice Cream race, the
Island Forum programs, the Historical Society's annual meeting and
a few cocktail parties _ in short, your normal not-so-quiet
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   But what I probably enjoyed the most was the island auto show.
This unofficial collection of vehicles clearly reveals what a big
part trucks (and now SUVs) have played in island life over the
years. They deliver, haul, go over roads that aren't really roads,
and do heavy-duty work. And, apparently, it's been that way since
motorized vehicles replaced horses _ a good 20 years later on
island than on the mainland because the original ferries were
barges more suited for carrying four-legged, rather than
four-wheeled, cargo. Indeed, old pickups, Jeeps, and panel trucks
used to dot the seaside landscape before a huge environmental
cleanup a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour after disembarking from the ferry, we drove by
arguably the nicest '40 Ford pickup I've ever seen, parked in front
of Bob Leach's garage. That was quickly followed by a 1928 Ford
Model A station wagon delivery truck.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there was old friend Charlie Pendleton (for whom the
Charlie Pendleton Band is named) roaring by in his aquamarine 1966
Pontiac Catalina convertible that looks as nice as when it rolled
off a GM assembly line. But beecause it's not a truck, we'll talk
about his car another time.
</P>
<P>
   A generalization from 15 years of summer visits: Islanders love
full-size Chevy pickups, most likely because Dutch Chevrolet in
Belfast is the nearest dealership. Summer residents love SUVs, a
trend that started 15 years ago with Suburbans and VW buses and
continues today with an array of Cherokees, Explorers, Rodeos,
4Runners, Pathfinders, Bravadas, and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Being a superstitious sort, I immediately decided to mix
business and pleasure, determining to track down the owners of the
vintage vehicles and do a story. In the process, yet another
interesting antique truck came out of its garage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The '28 Woody
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We found the '28 Woody wagon parked in front of Stan and Nancy
Van Horn's new gift shop, The Islesboro Artisans. The shop was
sensational, but the story behind the car was even more so.
</P>
<P>
   It was sold out from under, so to speak, it's original owner, an
``older woman'' in Blue Hill, Maine, when she was hospitalized. The
car _ and its owner _ had been around.
</P>
<P>
   The gear shift knob is a polo ball, courtesy of Will Rodgers,
and it sports a Virgin Islands inspection sticker from the days
when it was nicknamed ``double trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   On its trip to this island it encountered tire trouble on the
ferry and the aforementioned Bob Leach came to the rescue,
sandblasting a wheel to get a good seal for the tire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The '40s pickup
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All of which brings us back to Leach's garage and the '40 Ford
pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you saw that, huh?'' says Leach, trying his best to
politely ignore this island newcomer (only 20 summers). ``Well it
belongs to one of our summer residents, and I really don't think
he'd want to talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   To make a long story somewhat shorter, it took a few phone calls
_ to (yet more hints) islanders Bud Mitchell, Ralph Gray, and Suki
Love, and the '40 Ford pickup's owner returned a call.
</P>
<P>
   He was more than happy to talk about his car. It had been
lovingly restored by a friend and was a ``hot rod'' for its time _
the flathead was bored out and it had high compression Offenhauser
heads. He graciously invited us to visit and photograph the '40
Ford while begging us not to reveal his identity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another hint: He wasn't John Travolta, even though that was
Travolta's Rolls in Leach's Garage on another day, but that isn't
part of this story and Bob Leach wouldn't confirm that identity,
either.
</P>
<P>
   When our subject said to please identify him only as a West
Coast entertainment executive, my wife asked, ``Couldn't that mean
he makes porn movies?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is no, but the movie ``Potrait of a Lady'' is among
his directing credits and we apologize if this spoils his ``cover''
for he truly is a gentleman, one who says that the island actually
is an ideal place to keep and drive an antique car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roads are such that you wind up driving between 25 and 40
miles an hour _ perfect for these cars.'' And the exhaust tone when
he fired up the Ford to move it for photos . . . well, it was to
die for.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more.
</P>
<P>
   Leach then unveiled a sister to the '40 Ford _ a 1931 Model A
roadster/pickup. It's just what the name suggests. A pickup with a
convertible roof over the cab.
</P>
<P>
   It, too, has been lovingly restored, the winner of every show in
which it has been entered.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing what Ford developed almost 70 years ago, makes me chuckle
when I see the new Ford Explorer Sport-Trac _ an SUV cab with a
pickup bed in back. It shows that today's trend to hybrid
combinations of cars and trucks is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   We're reinventing our wheels all the time.
</P>
<P>
   And making them better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 0952EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
