<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Clinton has paid dues on abortion issue
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abortion-rights advocates are coming ritually unglued over the
compromise the Clinton administration agreed to in order to free up
funds to pay America's U.N. dues. They overreact. If they really
want to scare themselves, the advocates need to check out the Bush
campaign's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, a spokeswoman for George W. Bush suggested, does not
go far enough to harry and penalize foreign family-planning
organizations that support lawful abortion, or support merely
less-harsh anti-abortion laws.
</P>
<P>
   With the House Republican leadership holding U.S. participation
in the United Nations hostage to a rump of anti-abortion zealots,
the Clinton administration had little choice but to take the
compromise that pays our $926 million arrears and finally ends
Washington's embarrassing status as the world's biggest freeloader.
</P>
<P>
   The White House accepted a provision that bars U.S. funds from
family-planning efforts abroad if the agencies also perform
abortions or even support abortion. That cutoff has been the goal
of anti-abortion activists for years. President Clinton vetoed
previous efforts, but with the United States, after years of
domestic deadlock, on the verge of losing its U.N. vote over unpaid
dues, what was a president to do?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, to listen to the abortion-rights groups, go ahead
and lose our U.N. vote and as a result lose our purchase on
international leadership in general. Choice advocates are treating
the agreement as if it were not only a regrettable retreat from
principle on Clinton's part _ as it is _ but as if it presaged the
end of lawful abortion. It does not, at least not by the hand of
this administration.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise is more screwy than dangerous. It includes a
provision for the president to waive the prohibition. The penalty
would be $12.5 million cut from U.S. aid to family planning
overseas, with the money going to aid for children.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to sign the waiver promptly. The loss from
the international family planning budget will be just 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By far the larger danger to free choice resides, not in this
forced and reluctant fudging by a president who has defended choice
stoutly, but by a Republican Party that continues in the thrall of
its plentiful anti-abortion absolutists.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's people promised that the GOP nominee in waiting would
withhold by executive order all U.S. funds from any international
family planning agency that endorses abortion, as President Reagan
did, and as Clinton quickly undid.
</P>
<P>
   And GOP House leadership remains unable or unwilling to stop the
party's anti-abortion hotshots from undermining and outright
menacing major U.S. national interests to score even small but
showy points like this one.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that the issue worked against them in recent
elections, Bush and the GOP are trying to soft-pedal their standing
commitment to end lawful abortion, but the confrontation over U.N.
dues has smoked both out. Their opposition to legal abortion,
however demure it may be when circumstances allow, is intact.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
