<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Wifely three-step lag is baffling
 &HT;    (For release Nov. 21, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a question I often wanted to ask my wife for most of
our 46 years of marriage. Continually having her trailing three
steps behind me while walking in public is a great annoyance
inasmuch as I unceasingly am compelled to turn around to see if she
has stopped to window shop without signaling me or been carried off
by kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   There have been times when I have walked more than 100 yards,
turned around and could not locate her, she having peeled off to
stop into a store. And what about those times when I thought she
was with me and I began talking aloud (and alone, much to the
amusement of passing strangers)?
</P>
<P>
   Our relationship has pretty much been 50-50, except for the
three-step lag. She takes no guff from me and I none from her. We
are independent people who usually like the same things and the
same people.
</P>
<P>
   The three-step lag should not be considered some manner of
subservience; Lord no! While some might think ours is a stormy
relationship, it is not. We understand, enjoy and appreciate each
other. Our marriage is solid.
</P>
<P>
   But to the question: I finally blurted it out the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, when we were standing in front of the rabbi on our wedding
day,'' I began, ``I stopped the proceedings for a moment and said
there was one stipulation that must be met _ and that was you would
have to walk three steps behind me for the next 46 years, what
would you have said?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy,'' she retorted. ``I would have thrown my wedding
bouquet in your face, said nothing and walked away from the
ceremony, you pig!''
</P>
<P>
   I don't doubt it. But the stipulation was not made because I did
not know at the time that she was a three-step lagger. Through the
years, in commiseration with other husbands, I have come to find my
wife's cadence is not unique. It seemingly is epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   (One person also reminded me that there are countries in which
women walk ahead of the men; countries peppered with land mines.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, the first analysis from the female side is that we males
walk too fast. I disproved that with a simple test. Walking at my
usual pace, my wife fell three steps behind me within seconds.
Continuing that pace, she still stayed three steps behind me.
</P>
<P>
   The only time we seemingly walk together is when it is raining
and we have but one umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how fast or slow I walk, she stays three steps behind
me, other than when she stops to window shop or is fighting off
kidnappers. How does she do that? It's like she's achieved some
sort of orbit and stays there. While it frustrates me, I admire her
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   She cannot explain this other than to grumble about having
shorter legs, which, I remind her, are just as short after she
falls three steps behind but stays on pace. Add that to the fact
that I have relatively short legs as well, and consistently am
passed up by swift, short-legged women while doing my daily hike in
the park. (On those rare days when my wife joins me in the park,
she stays three steps behind me. Baffling!)
</P>
<P>
   To compound this confounded situation, there are times when she
dashes past me like a greyhound chasing a rabbit. Those occasions
usually occur when I turn boorish for whatever reason men turn
boorish, and she wants to show her displeasure by whizzing past me
into a kitchen supply store.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, I make an effort to lag myself, slowing my walk
to a near standstill. And I look back. And she still is three steps
behind. ``How do you do that?'' I would demand of her, and she'd
just smile; you know, that sneering smile that tells you she is
woman and that you can't get inside her head.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other husbands, I am resigned to the three-step lag.
Nothing is going to change. I am going to continue looking over my
shoulder to find her.
</P>
<P>
   The good news about it is that she's usually there.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
