<HEADLINE>
BACK IN '78, HE WAS A SUBURBAN PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is one time when I was ahead of the curve.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The day: February 6.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cold Monday, with off-and-on spitting snow. That night
I was at the college hockey Beanpot Tournament as the snow turned
into the Blizzard of '78.
</P>
<P>
   But that morning and early afternoon had been spent at Davy
Chevrolet in Danvers negotiating the trade of my 1976 Plymouth
Volare station wagon for a 1978 Chevy Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, the deal was done. I don't remember the
figures, but it was a very good deal. Of course, the sticker for a
Silverado Suburban (I still have it) was $8,381.70, with the
Silverado package accounting for $635. The 31-gallon fuel tank
cost, of all things, $31. Who says auto makers didn't have a sense
of humor?
</P>
<P>
   Friends thought I'd taken leave of my senses.
</P>
<P>
   But I'd had it with the Volare's drivability problems. (It
stalled most every time it was asked to take a sharp left turn from
a stop because its one-barrel carburetor needed regular replacement
of both accelerator pumps and floats).
</P>
<P>
   The Suburban (I called it a truck at the time, never having
heard of a sport utility vehichle) seemed like the perfect answer.
Here are the things I loved about the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Pollution-control devices? It really didn't have any unless you
consider a PCV (positive crankcase ventilation) valve that sucked
crankcase fumes back through the carburetor. It delivered 15 miles
per gallon as long as the air cleaner was changed regularly, which
it was for 115,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Space? Unbelievable. When the twins (the same ones who were
married last month in a double wedding) couldn't get along with
their younger brother, one got the rear seat, the other the third
seat, and the third in the cargo area. You have to remember,
seatbelts weren't much in use in those days and car seats were just
coming into their own.
</P>
<P>
   Visibility. I didn't realize it when I was sitting in the
showroom, but this may have been the biggest advantage of this
vehicle. You sat way above the crowd when you were in a Suburban.
Trucks and SUVs didn't make up 25 percent of the traffic on the
Expressway as they do today, and you could see way down the road.
That is one thing I envy today whenever I'm stuck behind a truck or
SUV, and that's more often the case than not as they occupy an
increasing share of the roadways.
</P>
<P>
   Hauling capacity. Packing for vacation consisted of throwing
everything and anything we wanted to take in the back, putting five
bicycles on my homemade roof rack, and taking off. We never took
the kitchen sink, but we always brought a barbeque grill.
</P>
<P>
   Image. The Suburban was hardly a status symbol. It was big,
solid black, and menacing. You were accorded respect at
intersections.
</P>
<P>
   Foul weather capability. The best that can be said is that it
sat so high you didn't get stuck in deep snow. But it was two-wheel
drive and was tough to stop on packed snow and impossible on ice.
</P>
<P>
   Size. We felt safe. The hood was huge. The vehicle was heavy.
Fortunately, in eight years, the only accidents were minor: My
backing-up dent in the tailgate and Mrs. G's close encounter with a
parked VW in a local parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Uniqueness. For several years, we were an anomaly. A few folks
had conversion vans, but the truck revolution was still a long way
away.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time to replace the Suburban, the price of a
similarly equipped vehicle had tripled making another one way out
of our price range.
</P>
<P>
   But, even though we were priced out of the new market, back in
1987 we had decided bigger was still better and the next two
Griffith family vehicles came out of the same mold: used Ford
Chateau Vans.
</P>
<P>
   The vans had the same advantages and kept hauling us on
vacations and delivered the aforementioned twins (and enough
paraphernalia for dorm rooms) to college in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, I was selling off part of the used-car lot that
our driveway had become and wound up selling the second Ford van
(still running and looking great with 127,000 miles on it).
</P>
<P>
   Today, I drive a sedan and cuss the SUVs in the passing lane
because I can't see around them.
</P>
<P>
   Davy Chevrolet and my original Suburban no longer exist. Of
course, memories of our Suburban remain. One of the best is from
the Great Blizzard. We'd closed the deal on Monday and were to pick
it up on Tuesday. Wrong. Instead, we sat home and dug out of the
snowy aftermath and finally took delivery 10 days later.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's no longer a unique vehicle except for its size.
</P>
<P>
   And every manufacturer has an entry or three aimed at this share
of the market.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the SUV is here to stay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
