<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-SUVS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION IS FIERCE IN THE SUV MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you thought there could be nothing new under the sun
in sport utility vehicles, along comes BMW with a novel twist _
design an SUV that performs like a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The BMW X5 is officially listed as a truck, but BMW says it will
handle and have the power of a BMW car. It is equipped with a
32-valve, V-8 engine with 282 horsepower, and has a five-speed
automatic Steptronic transmission along with full-time
all-wheel-drive.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's new marketing stragegy took a different tack _ big is
better. The company is calling the Excursion the ``king of the
road,'' even if critics compare it to a huge ship _ Titanic.
Excursion, however, is in no danger of sinking. Ford already has
some 50,000 orders for the huge SUV. Since 1935, General Motors has
commanded this ``big'' field with its Suburban model. The Excursion
now takes the title, running 7.4 inches longer, 5 inches higher,
and 1.2 inches wider than the Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   Size doesn't come without a price. Excursion, which will sell in
the mid $30,000 range, most likely won't fit in the garage. In
fact, it will be tough to park it almost anywhere. It also gets
terrible mileage: around 13 miles per gallon in city driving.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're looking to comfortably cart nine of your friends
and still have cargo space, and a 9,600-pound towing capacity, this
baby is for you. The Excursion is powered by a Triton V-10 engine
with 310 horsepower, the only V-10 in a sports utility.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors isn't sitting by idly. While not matching Ford
size for size, it is offering a new Chevy Suburban, while its twin,
the GMC Suburban now becomes the Yukon. Both vehicles have been
redesigned with new stiffer bodies. The monsters can pull up to
10,500 pounds, come in either four-wheel or two-wheel drive
versions, can carry up to nine passengers, and have lots of comfort
features like optional second-row reclining bucket seats.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's newest entry in the field is the Xterra, designed to
fit the lifestyles of active people. It can be used as an off-road
vehicle and is packed with storage spaces. The Xterra has features
such as a roofrack that can handle 125 pounds, and an optional
removable front basket that can carry up to 30 pounds of wet gear.
</P>
<P>
   This vehicle is also spacious _ bigger than a Jeep Cherokee or
Toyota RAV4 _ and has lots of storage area. The rear seat sits
higher, offering passengers a better view. When the seats are not
needed, the cushions can be removed to provide a flat cargo area
with the seats folded down.
</P>
<P>
   To design the vehicle, Nissan went to trail heads, surfing
spots, campgrounds, etc. to watch people using sport utilities.
What they found were people with sedans and trucks, not SUVs,
outfitted with bungee cords, racks, and compartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discovered a whole generation of young buyers who use their
vehicles like they use a good piece of sports equipment; and most
SUVs today are either too expensive or lacking the basic utility to
meet their needs,'' says Jerry Hirshberg, president of Nissan
Design International in California.
</P>
<P>
   His comments ring a bell with this non-SUV owner. Attending a
recent Jeep 101 program, I put a Grand Cherokee through its paces,
then tried a plain Cherokee. I told a Jeep representative I liked
the Grand Cherokee best. He said he preferred the plain Cherokee _
``it's $18,000 less,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the ultimate sport utility for a hot rodder is the
Mercedes-Benz ML55, a souped-up version of its popular ML sport
utilities. The ML55 can do 0 to 60 miles per hour in less than 6.9
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   While its going to be the fastest on the road, Mercedes doesn't
recommend taking it off the road. (With a $60,000-plus price tag,
almost $21,000 more than a ML430, who wants to cause problems?)
</P>
<P>
   The sport utility category has become a major factor in most
company's total sales figures. Lincoln has outsold Cadillac on the
basis of its Navigator. Lexus has become the top-selling luxury
maker since it added the RX300. Even more companies are about to
jump in: Volkswagen and Porche are working jointly on producing
individual models. Hyundai will offer the Santa Fe next year, and
Ford is coming up with some new models and variations on present
models.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
