<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: WHAT'S THE LINE ON VIRTUAL VEGAS?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Nov. 21.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ A few years ago, an old pal whose name often appears
in the papers got a call from the district attorney's office in
Nassau County, a New York suburb. The cops said, we know you've
phoned a bookie 450 times to bet on sporting events, because the
line was tapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to talk to my lawyer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the prosecutors lost interest in my famous friend. And
he has lost interest in dealing with illegal bookmakers, if not in
gambling on the fortunes of the Giants and the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I place my bets on line through a site in Costa Rica,'' he
said the other day. ``It works like a charm.''
</P>
<P>
   A search engine reveals some 400 Web sites that offer gambling,
often from such Caribbean locales as Antigua and Curacao. All it
takes to get into the action is a credit card. Like Vegas, the
virtual casinos never close. Unlike Vegas, you're not expected to
tip the dealer if you win.
</P>
<P>
   There are no signs yet that the offshore sites pose a threat to
this gambling mecca, which is on track to host a record 34 million
visitors this year.
</P>
<P>
   There's another statistic, however, that the Las Vegas
Convention and Visitors Authority is considerably less eager to
publicize: In 1998, a typical year, players left behind $7 billion
in Las Vegas casinos.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, worldwide online gambling revenue is expected to
total $1.2 billion this year. Like just about everything else to do
with the Internet, people in the know expect business to boom.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as a sop to local sensibilities, the just-ended fall
Comdex computer trade show, which drew 200,000 attendees, didn't
tout online gambling sales booths amid all the Internet fever.
</P>
<P>
   But the most recent issue of Casino Player, to be found in many
Las Vegas hotel rooms, features dozen of ads for online action. And
many of the Web sites are linked to various Vegas gambling
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   By all appearances, today's art-collecting gambling lords, as
the legitimate heirs of the Los Angeles mobsters who founded this
place, are claiming a piece of the cyberaction.
</P>
<P>
   They probably would agree with Tom Bell, of the libertarian Cato
Institute, who believes technology gives the gamblers a free ride.
Says Bell: ``The Internet's inherently open architecture already
hobbles law enforcement officials. Relentless innovation ensures
they they will only fall farther and farther behind.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't kept the feds from trying. In a test case brought in
New York, nine people charged with breaking the nation's wire laws
pleaded guilty. Cases against four others are pending, and seven
more remain fugitives. Two cases were dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Internet Gambling Prohibition Act of 1999 awaits
floor action in the Senate, with 23 current co-sponsors. A similar
House bill is moving forward. An aide to the chief Senate author,
Arizona Republican John Kyl, says it stands a good chance of
passage next year.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, don't bet against the odds that my celebrity
pal will be heavily ``comped'' with all kinds of Vegas-style
freebies as he continues to bet on his favorite teams _ on line or
off.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
