<SLUG> BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-SUVS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION IS FIERCE IN THE SUV MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you thought there could be nothing new under the sun
in sport utility vehicles, along comes BMW with a novel twist _
design an SUV that performs like a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The BMW X5 is officially listed as a truck, but BMW says it will
handle and have the power of a BMW car. It is equipped with a
32-valve, V-8 engine with 282 horsepower, and has a five-speed
automatic Steptronic transmission along with full-time
all-wheel-drive.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's new marketing stragegy took a different tack _ big is
better. The company is calling the Excursion the ``king of the
road,'' even if critics compare it to a huge ship _ Titanic.
Excursion, however, is in no danger of sinking. Ford already has
some 50,000 orders for the huge SUV. Since 1935, General Motors has
commanded this ``big'' field with its Suburban model. The Excursion
now takes the title, running 7.4 inches longer, 5 inches higher,
and 1.2 inches wider than the Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   Size doesn't come without a price. Excursion, which will sell in
the mid $30,000 range, most likely won't fit in the garage. In
fact, it will be tough to park it almost anywhere. It also gets
terrible mileage: around 13 miles per gallon in city driving.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're looking to comfortably cart nine of your friends
and still have cargo space, and a 9,600-pound towing capacity, this
baby is for you. The Excursion is powered by a Triton V-10 engine
with 310 horsepower, the only V-10 in a sports utility.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors isn't sitting by idly. While not matching Ford
size for size, it is offering a new Chevy Suburban, while its twin,
the GMC Suburban now becomes the Yukon. Both vehicles have been
redesigned with new stiffer bodies. The monsters can pull up to
10,500 pounds, come in either four-wheel or two-wheel drive
versions, can carry up to nine passengers, and have lots of comfort
features like optional second-row reclining bucket seats.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's newest entry in the field is the Xterra, designed to
fit the lifestyles of active people. It can be used as an off-road
vehicle and is packed with storage spaces. The Xterra has features
such as a roofrack that can handle 125 pounds, and an optional
removable front basket that can carry up to 30 pounds of wet gear.
</P>
<P>
   This vehicle is also spacious _ bigger than a Jeep Cherokee or
Toyota RAV4 _ and has lots of storage area. The rear seat sits
higher, offering passengers a better view. When the seats are not
needed, the cushions can be removed to provide a flat cargo area
with the seats folded down.
</P>
<P>
   To design the vehicle, Nissan went to trail heads, surfing
spots, campgrounds, etc. to watch people using sport utilities.
What they found were people with sedans and trucks, not SUVs,
outfitted with bungee cords, racks, and compartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discovered a whole generation of young buyers who use their
vehicles like they use a good piece of sports equipment; and most
SUVs today are either too expensive or lacking the basic utility to
meet their needs,'' says Jerry Hirshberg, president of Nissan
Design International in California.
</P>
<P>
   His comments ring a bell with this non-SUV owner. Attending a
recent Jeep 101 program, I put a Grand Cherokee through its paces,
then tried a plain Cherokee. I told a Jeep representative I liked
the Grand Cherokee best. He said he preferred the plain Cherokee _
``it's $18,000 less,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the ultimate sport utility for a hot rodder is the
Mercedes-Benz ML55, a souped-up version of its popular ML sport
utilities. The ML55 can do 0 to 60 miles per hour in less than 6.9
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   While its going to be the fastest on the road, Mercedes doesn't
recommend taking it off the road. (With a $60,000-plus price tag,
almost $21,000 more than a ML430, who wants to cause problems?)
</P>
<P>
   The sport utility category has become a major factor in most
company's total sales figures. Lincoln has outsold Cadillac on the
basis of its Navigator. Lexus has become the top-selling luxury
maker since it added the RX300. Even more companies are about to
jump in: Volkswagen and Porche are working jointly on producing
individual models. Hyundai will offer the Santa Fe next year, and
Ford is coming up with some new models and variations on present
models.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-MARKET-BO     11-18 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-MARKET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSCLE MEETS FINESSE IN THE FAMILY `TRUCK' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You think you know trucks. You're either a Ford Guy, a Chevy
Guy, a Dodge Guy. A solitary kind of guy. Think again.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, there's a good chance you're not even a guy.
There's a good chance your truck _ even a big, four-door V8 _ may
be none of the above. There's a good chance your truck may be
wrapped in the sheetmetal of a sport utility vehicle. And there's a
good chance your truck/SUV will be hauling not only tools and
materials to the job site, but kids to soccer, and dressed-up
parents to a fancy restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   These are times of great change in the truck/SUV market.
</P>
<P>
   You've got trucks, beds intact, that are more like SUVs. You've
got SUVs, looming presence intact, that are more like cars. Even
Cadillac and Lincoln will have pickup trucks in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   If, for the past couple of years, the truck/SUV world has been a
place of TRUCKS, Page G11 &QL; 
niches, auto anufacturers are now creating veritable crannies
within the niches. Consider the Chrysler PT Cruiser. Is it a car or
a replica 1930s panel truck?
</P>
<P>
   Will the Ford Escape Sport Wagon be a truck or an SUV?
</P>
<P>
   And what of those SUVs riding on car platforms: the Lexus RX
300, Toyota RAV4 (it will get even bigger by 2001), and the Honda
CR-V. How far removed are they, really, from station wagons such as
the Volvo Cross Country?
</P>
<P>
   And what of what will likely be this year's ultimate crossover
vehicle, the BMW X5 _ an SUV developed on the race track?
</P>
<P>
   We are buying pickup trucks _ particularly four-door,
many-passenger jobs _ and SUVs _ which are evolving faster than we
can buy them _ in record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The registration of SUVs has about doubled since 1992, tripled
since 1987, according to the US Commerce Department's Census
Bureau. Based on projections from 1997 figures, there are more than
15 million SUVs registered today, up from 7.1 in 1992. There are
nearly 75 million trucks registered, up from 59.2 million in 1992.
That means there is one pickup truck for every five licensed
drivers; one SUV for every 14 licensed drivers.
</P>
<P>
   And in both cases, we are driving myriad vechicles.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive News classifies 2000 small pickup trucks as the
Chevrolet S pickups, Dodge Dakota, Ford Ranger, GMC Sonoma, Isuzu
Hombre, Mazda B series, Nissan Frontier (small, but four doors),
and Toyota Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Its large 2000 trucks are the Chevrolet Silverado, Dodge Ram,
Ford F Series trucks, Ford Super Duty, GMC Sierra, GMC Sierra
Classic, and Toyota Tundra.
</P>
<P>
   Noteable this year is that four doors are available on many of
them, as is seating for six, along with smooth, quiet rides. A
family affair.
</P>
<P>
   Making big news is the Toyota Tundra, a truck Toyota wishes it
had built three years ago. Now, the company has ``gone American''
by giving the Tundra a V-8, 245-horsepower engine, seating for six,
and a sedanlike ride. And, it is being built in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is coming out with an F150 SuperCrew that has four
conventional doors and is a foot longer than the SuperCab.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has seen sales of four-door pickups in its F-Series climb
from 5 percent in the 1996-'97 model years to 70 percent in 1999.
So while Ford has itself not only comfortably ensconced, but
expanded its line in four-door pickups, it is free to roam in more
esoteric fields.
</P>
<P>
   You've got the Roush F-150 _ that's Roush as in NASCAR's Jack
Roush, he of the screaming Mustang. It comes in various levels,
from outside wrapping, through upgraded suspension, wheels and
tires, to full-blown power _ a 5.4 liter, 335-horsepower,
supercharged V-8. Too tame for you? Consider, then, the SVT
Lightning. It's 5.4 liters, 360 supercharged horsepower, 0 to 60 in
about 5.4 seconds. See ya, Mr. Roush.
</P>
<P>
   But even small trucks can have four doors, and leading the way
is the Nissan Frontier Crew Cab. Compact, maneuverable, good to
haul folks and loads. Joining this act will be the Dodge Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet, which lost sales when it missed the four-door pickup
truck boom, is offering the four-door option on several models
including its C/K series.
</P>
<P>
   For Chevy fans, the big news is the new Silverado _ again,
offered with extended cab, four doors. It will be a powerful beast
with a base engine _ V-6, 200-horsepower _ that can be quickly
supplanted by V-8s that deliver 270 and 285 horsepower, a 6.0-liter
that cranks out 300 horsepower, or the 6.5-liter diesel at 215
horsepower, but loaded with torque.
</P>
<P>
   GMC follows its Chevy kin with the Sierra offering an extended
cab, four doors, and more horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodge Dakota four-door has front-hinged rear doors with
full-sized windows. And in the mainstay Ram, look for upgraded
suspension, steering and brakes _ and don't forget that popular
Cummins Turbo Diesel as an option.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of SUVs, the crossovers are even more fierce.
</P>
<P>
   Consider how many there are now on the market.
</P>
<P>
   According to Automotive News, small SUVs include the Chevrolet
Tracker, Honda CR-V, Isuzu Amigo, Isuzu VehiCross, Jeep Wrangler,
Kia Sportage, Nissan Xterra, Suzuki Vitara, Suzuki Grand Vitara,
Toyota RAV4.
</P>
<P>
   At midrange are the BMW X5, Chevrolet Blazer, Dodge Durango,
Ford Explorer, GMC Jimmy and Envoy, Honda Passport, Infiniti QX-4,
Isuzu Rodeo, Isuzu Trooper, Jeep Cherokee, Jeep Grand Cherokee,
Land Rover Discovery, Land Rover Range Rover, Lexus LX 450, Lexus
RX 300, Mercedes M Class, Mercury Mountaineer, Mitsubishi Montero,
Mitsubishi Montero Sport, Nissan Pathfinder, Oldsmobile Bravada,
Toyota 4Runner, and Toyota Land Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   And largest are the AM General Hummer, Cadillac Escalade,
Chevrolet Suburban, Chevrolet Tahoe, Ford Expedition, Ford
Excursion, GMC Yukon XL, GMC Yukon and Denali, and Lincoln
Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting the biggest wake is the new Ford Excursion, perched atop
an F250 platform and easily the largest SUV roaming the roads.
</P>
<P>
   The Chevrolet Suburban, long the leader of the big boats, has
gotten rounder, and its sister, the GMC Suburban, is now known as
the Yukon XL.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the news is big.
</P>
<P>
   BMW is refusing to call its new X5 an SUV. Sport activity
vehicle is the preferred term. And if 0 to 60 mile per hour in 7.2
seconds and a top speed of 130 m.p.h. is your idea of activity in a
rig that looks like an SUV, then the $50,000 X5 may be your cup of
tea.
</P>
<P>
   But diversity being the name of the game in SUVs, there is
excitment farther down the economic scale.
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at Gen-Xers is the Nissan Xterra, a sport ute based on the
Frontier pickup truck. Water resistant seats (kayaking); storage
bins atop the roof (hiking, other activities), it has action
written all over it. And at a base price of $17,500, it's got good
deal written all over it as well.
</P>
<P>
   These are days of rapid evolution in the world of trucks and
SUVs. The models you first meet this year may be radically
different three years from now.
</P>
<P>
   And it will get harder and harder to answer the question: ``Am I
driving a truck, an SUV, or a car?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
