<SLUG> BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-INDUSTRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCKS AND SUVS CONTINUE TO DOMINATE THE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The SUV and truck industry is about people and vehicles. Folks
buy trucks and SUVs to take skiing, haul boats, lug kids and pets.
Manufacturers market them for active lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   But the SUV and truck phenomenon is also about numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, annual sales of SUVs in the United States have grown
from 900,000 to 3.1 million vehicles. Since the Econoline van was
introduced in 1960, Ford has sold more than 6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, trucks continue to account for roughly half of all new
vehicle sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ford soon will have six different SUVs on the market and have
more than 50 variations of its trucks, starting with the
best-selling F-150 and moving up the size scale.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 25 SUVs on the market now with at least
another 20 expected to join in the battle for market share in the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan, being hammered elsewhere, continues to be a strong
player in the Northeast, which accounts for 25 percent of US sales.
</P>
<P>
   The company's hot new Xterra _ Motor Trend's sport/utility of
the year _ has zoomed past Nissan's goal of 52,000 sales with more
than 75,000 units sold. The larger Pathfinder has been a stong
seller and is expected to get a beefed-up V-6 during 2000 to
rectify a notable need.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for niches in the SUV market seems to have no end.
Mercedes is introducing the luxury ML55 AMG. It's got 342
horsepower, goes from 0 to 60 m.p.h. in 6.4 seconds, features
18-inch tires and all the bells and whistles you'd expect for
$64,900.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum will be the sixth SUV in the
Ford lineup _ a challenger to Toyota's RAV4 in the small SUV
market. ``It'll be a little more carlike,'' says J.C. Collins,
Ford's SUV Group brand manager. No surprise, it, too, will have a
name beginning with Ex and carry high Expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has been in the vanguard of truck and SUV sales, and
management intends to keep the company there.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are time-starved,'' says Collins. ``But at the same
time, they're recreation-oriented and participate in the activities
that an SUV is geared to: Lugging skis and skiers into snow
country, mountain biking. The SUV and its capabilities play a big
part in these customers' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Ford's Explorer were 431,000 in 1998 _ higher even than
the best-selling Toyota Camry that year. With Ford introducing a
redesigned Explorer Sport, a new Explorer Sport-Trac, and the new
mini-SUV in the first half of 2000, the company has no plans to
relinquish its position as industry leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Sport-Trac will further close the dividing line between
pickup and SUV, adding a molded cargo area, and optional folding
and lockable tonneau cover, a bed extender, a power rear window and
power outlet in the cargo bed.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also is hitting the market with an new advertising campaign
called ``No Boundaries.'' Each ad is centered around active
lifestyles and features both the Ford brand name and a member of
the SUV lineup.
</P>
<P>
   It's all geared to tie into Ford's already established Ford
Tough and Ford Country campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a line between pickup and SUV.
</P>
<P>
   ``SUV buyers in general look to carry people and cargo inside
their vehicle,'' says Collins, ``whereas a pickup buyer may want
comfort in the cab with a cargo out back.'' The Sport-Trac may
diminish that dividing line a bit. ``Males like this one,'' says
Collins, ``and young and young-thinking females like the Explorer
Sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the big trend in pickup trucks is four-door crew
cabs.
</P>
<P>
   On display at the recent New England Auto Show were Nissan's
Frontier, the first to offer a four-door crew cab in a compact
pickup, and the Dodge Dakota Quad Cab that boasts the most power,
most towing and payload capacity, and seating for six. Soon to come
is Ford's F-150 SuperCrew, the first full-sized four-door pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've positioned ourselves to have the truck that will do the
job you need to get done,'' says Al Giombetti, Ford's truck group
brand manager. ``People still want the capability and versatility
that a pickup offers.''
</P>
<P>
   What's evident is what Collins says: ``It looks like the days of
super-high production runs of individual vehicles are over. We have
to be more responsive to the customer. They speak, we listen, and
the results are all these derivatives of several basic vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Gimobetti sees no end to the demand for trucks, either. ``Trucks
and vans are solid sellers. There's a huge loyalty factor with our
F-series.'' But he also knows things will continue to change.
``Today's innovations become tomorrow's expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which keeps us writing and reading about the industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
