<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-MINIVANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAZDA'S REVAMPED MPV SETS NEW PACE FOR MINIVAN LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, Honda took the accolades for its Odyssey minivan.
It's still a winner, but this year, Mazda's all new MPV has some
innovative features that may just put it in your winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Setting the $20,000 MPV apart is its use of ``theater seating,''
roll-down windows on the sliding doors, Side-by-Slide second-row
seating, and a Tumble-Under rear seat that folds flat on the floor
in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Side-by-Slide seating offers both captain's chairs and a
bench seat by moving fore and aft and side to side, something not
possible in other minivans. The rear seat, which is raised slightly
for ``theater seating,'' can also be flipped to the rear when the
liftgate is open for use at a picnic or tailgate party.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mazda is not the biggest of minivans, it claims its
OptiSpace design provides more foot room and better use of overall
space to create a feeling of roominess.
</P>
<P>
   The Honda Odyssey ($25,800 for the EX), last year's standout, is
still a winner from any angle. It has performance, styling, great
features including dual power sliding doors, and innovative seating
that includes a fold-away rear seat that can also double as a
picnic center.
</P>
<P>
   The General Motors family of minivans _ Chevrolet Venture
($23,195), Pontiac Montana ($23,895), and Oldsmobile Silhouette
($30,605 for the Premier) _ are all similar in ride, seating,
space, and power. There are, however, differences in options. The
Chevy, for example, has a well-designed built-in child's seat,
while the Olds and Pontiac have great on-board video systems
complete with hookups for video games. All the vans have lots of
storage bags, side-air bags, and an on-board air compressor to blow
up all the inflatables you need.
</P>
<P>
   For the most variations in minivans, no one beats
DaimlerChrysler, the company that invented the minivan, and is
still the sales leader. The Chrysler products offer two different
wheelbases and six different drivetrains. The Chrysler Town &AMP;
Country ($26,360) and the Dodge Caravan ($29,405) are the only
minivans with all-wheel drive. Dodge also offers a sport package
that includes AutoStick, an automanual transmission. The Plymouth
Voyager ($18,685) is the lowest-priced member of the family.
</P>
<P>
   If you're comparing minivans and looking for a benchmark, the
Dodge Caravan is the top seller in the country. About the only
thing it doesn't offer is a power sliding door.
</P>
<P>
   The Sienna ($27,700) is everything you'd expect from a Toyota.
It is refined, quiet, and offers good performance. The minivan
comes with V-6 power and is based on the Camry platform. The Sienna
comes with lots of standard safety equipment, and, like the Ford
Windstar and Honda Odyseey, has a five-star crash protection rating
from the National Highway Traffic Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury Villager ($25,015) and Nissan Quest ($22,160) are a
bit smaller than other minivans, but they offer a good, carlike
ride. Video entertainment systems for rear passengers will be an
option for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Windstar ($27,500) is one of the most spacious and best
performing vehicles in this category. It took a while for Ford to
add dual side doors, which are larger than most for easy access.
Power side doors are an option, and the Windstar includes sensors
on the rear to warn if something is in the way when backing up and
a ``conversation mirror'' that can help keep tabs on those in back.
</P>
<P>
   Minvans are great people and cargo haulers, but not all minivans
are created equal. Most claim carlike handling, but only you can
decide if a model feels more like a car than a van.
</P>
<P>
   Other things to consider when shopping for minivans include
engine noise, pickup and stopping time _ even within the same
family of minivans. Be sure to test a vehicle that is equipped the
way you'd like; adding lots of options can change the way the
vehicle handles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
