<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3636 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-MODELS-BO     11-18 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-MODELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ALL-PURPOSE TRUCK GAINS IN COMFORT AND STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It isn't just a truck anymore, or words to that effect, was the
prominent theme in GMC advertising not long ago. But now trucks are
hot, and GMC is putting the emphasis on building trucks. Period.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, anyone shopping for a truck these days will quickly
realize that trucks really aren't just trucks anymore. Although,
there are still some drivers who actually buy trucks to be used as
trucks, more and more people are buying them as a second ``car,''
or, in some cases, as the primary family vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what they say, all manufacturers are building trucks
with carlike handling features, including cab comfort and automatic
transmissions. With trucks capturing some 40 percent of the market,
and holding the two top places in Top 10 vehicle sales each year,
the manufacturers know they have to please a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   Which helps explain why manufacturers are producing more and
more trucks that can serve as the family vehicle. Lincoln is
expected to put into production its Blackwood, which was shown at
the Boston International Auto Show last week. The Blackwood is a
Lincoln Navigator with two rows of seating and a large, covered
pickup bed behind. You can travel in luxury, have the use of a
cargo bed, and have good towing capacity.
</P>
<P>
   More practical for most people might be the new Nissan Frontier
Crew Cab with four real doors and a full-sized backseat. This
compact V-6 truck comes in either two- or four-wheel drive
configurations. While the bed is short, a nice option is a hinged
tubular gate that when sitting on the bed can keep small items at
the cargo gate. Then if you need to carry a longer item, the
tubular gate can be swung out to rest on top of the flat cargo
gate.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing it can't do is carry a 4-by-8-foot sheet of
plywood. But when was the last time you needed to do that? Besides,
if you go to The Home Depot, they'll rent you a truck for that
specific need for less than $20. So, who needs an 8-foot cargo bed?
Very few.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodge Dakota is also featuring a Quad Cab in its compact
line, and like the Frontier, the doors are front hinged and the cab
is a short 5.3 feet vs. the standard 6.5-foot bed. Dodge is
packaging the truck with a new 4.7-liter 235-horsepower V-8 and a
four-speed automatic transmission that selects between one of two
second gear ratios. Dodge also offers the Dakota ($13,200 to
$19,500) in two bed lengths, regular cab, and a choice of engines
from a 120-horsepower four-cylinder up to a 250-horsepower V-8. The
full-sized Dodge Ram pickups are essentially unchanged for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet and GMC completely redid the Silverado and the Sierra
pickups last year ($15,355 to $32,500). The new trucks are more
rigid, have very roomy cabs, are easier to get into than previous
models, have more power, and brakes that will stop in shorter
distances. For 2000, the trucks will have a four-door extended cab
option. Other options include regular or extended cabs, and
Autotrac four-wheel drive that automatically transfers torque to
the front wheels if the rear wheels are slipping.
</P>
<P>
   The Chevy S10 ($12,108 to $20,192) is the only truck in its
class with standard four-wheel antilock brakes. It comes in two-
and four-wheel drive options, and in a variety of configurations,
including the Xtreme, which tells you all you need to know about
this model.
</P>
<P>
   The GMC Sonoma ($12,600 to $20,500), like the S10, comes in a
variety of configurations and with a choice of engines from a
120-horsepower four-cylinder to a V-8 with 190 horsepower. Manual
and automatic transmissions and two- or four-wheel drives are also
available.
</P>
<P>
   The best-selling vehicle in America is the Ford F-series truck
($15,000 to $30,000). The F-series tops not just truck, but car
sales as well. That alone sends a very positive message about this
line. These trucks come with two- or four-wheel drive, three engine
choices from a 205-horsepower V-6 to a 260-horsepower V-8, a short
or long bed, and regular or extended cab options. New for 2000 are
handy rear-access doors on SuperCab models.
</P>
<P>
   The compact Ford Ranger ($11,700 to $19,400) has been given
extensive equipment upgrades for 2000. Four-wheel drive Rangers
allow the system to be engaged on the fly, no stopping the vehicle
to go into four-wheel drive. Also, the Ranger, along with its
stablemate the Mazda B-series is the only compact to offer two
rear-access panels, for a total of four doors. But while these
compacts have space in the back of the cab, it's a tight fit.
</P>
<P>
   The real workhorse of the Ford line is the F-series Super Duty
($19,000 to $31,000). This new-for-'99 model is designed for
work-related jobs. The truck comes with heavy-duty engine choices
for this type of work including a Triton V-10 and the Navistar
7.3-liter turbo-diesel. While these models handle and ride more
like trucks, the cabs are quite civilized with all the goodies
you'd expect in a fine car.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota shook up the American truck market last year with the
introduction of the Tundra ($17,000 to $28,000), the first
full-sized pickup from a foreign maker. And this truck is a real
contender to steal sales from American manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The Tundra rides and handles superbly, comes in bed choices of
eight or 6 1/2 feet, regular or extended cabs, and two engine
choices: a 3.4-liter V-6 or 4.7-liter V-8 (the same one in the
Toyota Land Cruiser). For 2000, Toyota has added four doors to its
extended cab models, all with their own handles.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota also offers the compact Tacoma ($12,600 to $25,600). As
the price range suggests, this model can be had in many
combinations of cabs and beds, and two- or four-wheel drive
versions. Unlike other makes, the Tacoma's four-cylinder engine
gets high marks from enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Also available is the Isuzu Hombre ($11,500 to $21,200).
Basically, it is a Chevy S10 with Isuzu markings.
</P>
<P>
   While all these trucks will do a job, shoppers need to decide
what that job will be. Obviously, if a truck is going to be the
all-around family vehicle, a supercab model would be the first
choice. But then you need to decide how ``super'' the cab should be
in size and comfort. Then you must consider what your ``payload''
is going to be. Chances are you can do with a short bed, rather
than a long one, and you may not need a beefier full-sized pickup
if you are just doing normal hauling.
</P>
<P>
   Decide, too, if you really need four-wheel drive. Only the Chevy
Silverado/GMC Sierra has a system that can be used all the time.
While the V-6 engine is the most popular available on trucks,
buyers have choices that range from small four-cylinder engines to
heavy duty V-10s. For family-type driving, a V-6 or small V-8
should do fine.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks have a lower price tag than most cars, but load it up
with extras and the price can skyrocket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
