<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-TRUCKS-BUYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TEN BASIC STEPS FOR BUYING AN SUV OR TRUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buying an SUV or truck is just like buying any other vehicle.
You've done it before, but let's just do it by the numbers this
time as a countdown to happiness. (We hope.)
</P>
<P>
   10. Decide what you want, then figure out if you can afford it.
This sounds simpler than it is unless you're a high roller. If
that's the case, you can buy anything you want, and are probably
out driving your latest dream car to your vacation home now and not
reading this. For those of us who have to allot a big chunk of our
income to the auto industry, read on.
</P>
<P>
   Hint 1: SUVs come in three basic sizes: Small, regular, and
large (with a subcategory of truly humungous), most with a choice
of two- or four-wheel drive and an increasing number with an
all-wheel drive option.
</P>
<P>
   The small size includes Toyota RAV4, Subaru Forester, KIA
Sportage, Chevrolet Tracker, Honda CR-V, Suzuki Grand Vitara.
</P>
<P>
   The regular (big) size includes the Chevy Blazer/GMC Jimmy, Ford
Explorer, Jeep Grand Cherokee, Lexus RX300, Mercedes-Benz M-Class,
Toyota 4Runner, Isuzu Rodeo, Olds Bravada, and Mitsubishi Montero.
</P>
<P>
   In the large category are Ford Expedition, Dodge Durango, Chevy
Tahoe/GMC Yukon, Toyota Land Cruiser, Range Rover, Lexus LX470, and
biggest of the big, Ford Excursion, Chevy Suburban, and GMC Yukon.
</P>
<P>
   Hint 2: Wagons such as the Audi Quattro, Subaru Legacy, VW
Passat, Volvo 70-series, and Saab 9-5 are an attractive
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   9. If you can't afford what you want, decide what you like and
can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Hint 1: Auto manufacturers make a big profit on SUVs, especially
those loaded with expensive toys. If cost is your main
consideration, make your selection accordingly. Visit dealerships
to get a feel for what's out there, but it's way too early to make
a commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Hint 2: Examine the family trees for the less-expensive version
of the same basic vehicle. (Prices mentioned here are for
lesser-priced four-wheel drive models.)
</P>
<P>
   a. Ford: The Mercury Mountaineer ($29,370) is a posh version of
the Ford Explorer ($23,070); likewise, the Lincoln Navigator
($45,860) is the upgraded Ford Expedition ($32,525).
</P>
<P>
   b. The Lexus LX450 ($59,005) is the fancy Toyota Land Cruiser
($50,828).
</P>
<P>
   c. The Chevy Blazer/GMC Jimmy are the basic car ($21,970 to
$28,470); The Olds Bravada ($31,498) is the gussied-up, all-wheel
drive version.
</P>
<P>
   d. You'll find the same relationship between the Isuzu Trooper
and Honda Passport; between the Nissan Pathfinder and Infiniti QX4.
</P>
<P>
   8. Now you have to decide whether to lease or buy. To figure out
if you're a good candidate to lease, ask yourself if you:
</P>
<P>
   a. Drive 12,000 to 15,000 miles per year.
</P>
<P>
   b. Keep your car in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   c. Like to change cars every three years.
</P>
<P>
   d. Don't mind having a car payment forever.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't answer yes to all of the above, think long and
hard about leasing. You're heading for extra payments.
</P>
<P>
   7. If you decide to buy, talk to your friendly loan officer to
find out what rate you'll be paying and get some approximate
numbers of how much it will cost you a week or month for various
loan lengths. If your employer has a credit union, payroll
deduction loans are a less painfull way to go.
</P>
<P>
   6. Do your research to find out the true cost (dealer's cost) of
the vehicle(s) you would like. Add about 3 percent for dealer
profit (after throwing out the destination charge). That's a
ballpark figure. Not many of us reach it no matter how much we brag
around the coffee machine.
</P>
<P>
   5. Take a deep breath and decide if you want to continue. After
all, it is your money.
</P>
<P>
   4. Now that you have an idea what you want, it's time to talk
dealerships. It's my feeling that they've changed a lot in the last
10 years. They've always wanted to sell you cars; now, they want to
make you a repeat customer and sell vehicles to your spouse,
family, friends, and neighbors. Visit a few and get a feel for the
atmosphere. Most want to be consumer friendly. They know they have
a good product (it's pretty hard to find a truly bad car these
days) and it's impossible to test drive an SUV without an office
visit. Later you can negotiate by phone or e-mail if you're not
comfortable dealing face-to-face and want to take time to think
about what you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   3. Oh, you have a trade-in. Well, that can complicate things.
Get an idea of what it's worth, and how much it would cost to put
it in A-1 shape so it actually is worth that much. Then either fix
it or subtract the cost of the repairs. Make sure it's clean and
has been serviced relatively recently when you have the dealer give
you his estimate of what it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   Hint: Know your bottom line, i.e. new car cost minus trade-in
value, when you negotiate. It sounds simple, but once numbers start
flying around take the time to do this simple math. If a dealer is
willing to meet your number, it really doesn't matter what values
he assigns to the new car and trade-in.
</P>
<P>
   2. Once the deal is struck, don't think you're done. You'll be
faced with a barrage of add-ons: alarms, warranties, insurance
deals, care-car systems, and the like. You may want an extended
warranty if you're planning on keeping the car for a long time.
Also beware of any unexpected dealer ``add ons'' or ``mark ups.''
Fight them.
</P>
<P>
   It is now time to say yes or no. If you have said yes, if you
have made your commitment, go on to No. 1. If not, go back to No.
10 and run the program again. You'll be amazed at what an expert
you've become and how much less threatening the process can be.
</P>
<P>
   1. Forget all the stuff that went on before. Just like a mother
forgets childbirth, you can put the tough parts of the buying
process aside. Goodness knows, you've worked and shopped hard for
this car. Now enjoy. And you don't have to do that by the numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
