A3644 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SLAVERY-COMMENT19-COX     11-18 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVERY-COMMENT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slavery issue at the heart of secession
 &HT;    By James L. Roark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In February 1861, Georgian Alexander Hamilton Stephens called
slavery the Confederacy's ``cornerstone.''
</P>
<P>
   As vice president of the Confederate States of America, he spoke
with some authority. The ``foundations are laid, its cornerstone
rests,'' he said, ``upon the great truth that the negro is not
equal to the white man; that slavery . . . is his natural and
normal condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet today, a significant number of Southerners deny that slavery
had much to do with Southern secession. They point to states'
rights, self-determination, liberty, protection of hearth and home,
everything but slavery. No historical event as vast as the creation
of a Southern nation can be explained in monocausal terms. But
there can be no doubt about the centrality of racial slavery to the
creation of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no slavery, no Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern struggle to preserve slavery was as old as the
United States. In 1787, Southerners embedded slavery in the
Constitution. By the 1820s, Southerners had aggressively built the
largest slave society in the New World. As they raced westward,
they spread cotton, slavery and plantations halfway to the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Slaveless whites joined slaveholders in supporting slavery and
opposing black equality. As the antebellum Georgia legal scholar
Thomas R.R. Cobb observed, every white citizen of the South ``feels
that he belongs to an elevated class. It matters not that he is no
slaveholder; he is not of the inferior race; he is a freeborn
citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1850s witnessed rising sectional consciousness and hardening
sectional suspicion. Increasing numbers of whites in the South came
to believe that an abolitionized North was taking aim at slavery in
the South, despite the protections of the Constitution. Abraham
Lincoln's election without a single Southern electoral vote
convinced many more Southerners that they could no longer remain
Americans and protect slavery. As Catherine Edmonstron of North
Carolina declared, ``Union now means Conquest _ and Conquest,
Confiscation. So we go.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Southerners rejected secessionist logic. ``I consider
slavery much more secure in the Union than out of it if our people
were but wise,'' Stephens countered. White Southerners were united
in their determination to defend slavery but divided about whether
Lincoln's election made it necessary to secede. Only in South
Carolina did the ``fire eaters'' (insistent secessionists) win
easily. In every other state in the lower South, including Georgia,
the vote was close. But secession prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Confederate President Jefferson Davis argued that secession and
the war that followed were about Southern rights and liberties. But
precisely what rights and liberties? The right of Southerners to
own slaves; the liberty of Southerners to take slaves into national
territories; and the freedom of Southerners to quit a union that
jeopardized those rights and liberties.
</P>
<P>
   When the war came, white men across the South marched off to
protect the life they knew. They fought for home, family, freedom,
their land, racial supremacy and more. But the motives that
compelled individuals to fight Yankees from 1861 to 1865 can
obscure the purposes that brought the Confederacy into being. The
new nation owed its political existence to white Southerners'
determination to preserve slavery and the society they had built
upon it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Southerners who reject the argument for slavery's role in
the origins of the Confederacy claim that the Southern cause
enjoyed a ``rainbow coalition'' of supporters. They point to the
thousands of ``black Confederates,'' slaves who worked on the
fortifications, drove rebel wagons and nursed sick soldiers in
Southern hospitals. They also lift up the willingness of the
government in Richmond in the last weeks of the war to free some
slaves for military service.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, voluntary Confederates were almost entirely pale
skinned. After the Emancipation Proclamation of Jan. 1, 1863, put
the Union squarely on the side of freedom, 100,000 black
Southerners donned blue uniforms to fight a war of liberation. And
the Confederate government's desperate experiment with limited
black freedom generated little enthusiasm on the home front.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Edmondston responded that Southerners had ``hitherto
contended that slavery was Cuffee's (African-Americans') normal
condition, the very best position he could occupy, the one of all
others in which he was the happiest and to take him from that and
give him what we think misery in the place of it, is to put
ourselves in the wrong essentially.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No!'' she cried. ``Freedom for whites, slavery for Negroes,
God has so ordained it!''
</P>
<P>
   An assessment of the role of slavery in the making of the
Confederacy does not necessarily answer all the questions that we
face about how we choose to remember the Southern nation, but it is
the starting place for reasonable discussion.
</P>
<P>
   James L. Roark is an Emory University history professor. His
commentary originally appeared in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
