r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN19-COX     11-18 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What we really need to know about candidates
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Just think. We have only 11 1/2 months
until the next presidential election. I can hardly wait. It seems
as if the candidates have been running since the Berlin Wall fell _
and a few have, such as Al Gore and Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   The latest brouhaha came when a cheeky television reporter from
Boston surprised Texas Gov. George W. Bush with a pop quiz, asking
if he could name the leaders of Taiwan, Chechnya, India and
Pakistan. He got one right. That's one more than I would have
gotten right. I could name former leaders of three of those
countries _ the exception being Chechnya, which hasn't been a
country long enough for most of us to have any but the vaguest idea
where it is, let alone who's in charge. It's somewhere near Russia,
if you're wondering.
</P>
<P>
   A vast hue-and-cry arose from Bush backers and even those who
are still skeptical of his ability to run the Greatest Nation on
Earth, concerned that the pop quiz was ``gotcha journalism.'' Well,
yeah, it was a bit tacky, but it's likely Bush will survive this
tempest in a teapot with little trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the notion of making all presidential candidates take a
quiz has some appeal. It could give voters a notion they're voting
for someone who thinks like they do, which is a feeling you just
don't get from warm-and-fuzzy television commercials of Gore
dressed in earth-tone chinos and a golf shirt, or of George Dubbya
riding a horse. In the interests of civic journalism, I have
compiled my own quiz of questions I would like the candidates to
answer before I decide how I'll cast my ballot. My answers are
below each question. Here goes:
</P>
<P>
   1.) Do you eat beans with your chili, and is there such a thing
as chili that's too hot?
</P>
<P>
   My answer to Part A is yes. I am no purist. I like beans in my
chili, and I like Frito corn chips on the bottom of the bowl and
shredded cheese on top. No doubt Frank X Tolbert, the late writer
and chili impresario for the Dallas Morning News, would have me
strung on a cactus in downtown Terlingua, but there you go. And no,
there is no such thing as too-hot chili. It's like the country song
that claims ``There's no such thing as too much fun.'' I've come
close to having too much fun before, and my last batch of chili
came perilously close to being too hot, leaving me drenched with
sweat. I froze the remainder, hoping a few weeks of being turned
into lumpy brown ice will somehow cool it down a tad.
</P>
<P>
   2.) Who's your favorite Beatle?
</P>
<P>
   Any Beatle save Ringo is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   3.) Do you believe the designated hitter rule used in the
American League should be abolished?
</P>
<P>
   This is critical to my deciding who shall run our country. The
designated-hitter rule is an abomination of nature, and any
potential chief executive who promises to issue an order hastening
its demise has my vote.
</P>
<P>
   4.) What did you think of ``The Blair Witch Project?''
</P>
<P>
   There's only one wrong answer here, and that's to say that you
liked the movie. Not having watched it is acceptable, even
preferable. I'm of the opinion that this movie, filmed for a mere
$35,000 if memory serves correctly and overpriced at that, ranks up
there with ``The Legend of Boggy Creek'' as one of the worst movies
of the 20th century. I've seen scarier episodes of ``Sesame
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   5.) Who's the greatest female country singer of all time?
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of great ones, but there was only one Patsy
Cline. I would give partial credit for picking Tammy Wynette and
take off points for naming any of the Mandrell sisters.
</P>
<P>
   6.) Which type of barbecue do you prefer: beef or pork?
</P>
<P>
   The only bad answer is if a candidate actually confesses to not
liking barbecue at all.
</P>
<P>
   7.) Do you believe in extraterrestrial beings?
</P>
<P>
   Answering no implies a lack of imagination, which would bother
me.
</P>
<P>
   8.) Can you recite the theme song to ``The Beverly
Hillbillies''?
</P>
<P>
   Extra credit goes for also knowing the words to the ``Flipper''
theme song.
</P>
<P>
   9.) Do you have any idea who shot the deputy (as in the song,
``I shot the sheriff, but I did not shoot the deputy''), or what
exactly Billy Jo McAllister tossed off the Tallahatchie Bridge?
</P>
<P>
   I've been wondering about those two events for years.
</P>
<P>
   10.) Which of your opponents would have a tough time getting
through the first two rounds of ``So You Want to be a
Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Watch this show some time. You'll feel really smart for at least
the first three or four rounds. Here's an actual question in the
early round, and remember that these are multiple choice: ``On a
car with an automatic transmission, what does the `N' stand for?''
</P>
<P>
   Nitwit?
</P>
<P>
   I realize that my quiz doesn't address the really serious
questions of state, such as free trade, immigration, nuclear
disarmament and such. But as Dubbya said, whoever's elected has
``experts'' to worry about those matters. I just want someone I'd
feel comfortable drinking a beer with _ and who could at least get
through the first three levels with Regis Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
