<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fangs for writing, fangs for reading
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Letters, I get letters ...
</P>
<P>
   A recent column on snakes brought a variety of responses.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lee Windham, of Hemphill, Texas, related a similar
encounter of mistaken identity:
</P>
<P>
   ``Your story about the black snake you mistakenly thought was a
hose brought back memories. I thought someone had left a short rope
on my kitchen floor and I picked it up. I don't know which of us
was the more surprised, but neither of us stayed around to find
out. I dashed to the living room and the snake scooted under the
dishwasher, picking up speed as he wriggled through a weep-hole in
the bricks and onto the side yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the snake was as round on one end as the other, I
think that it wasn't poisonous but we were both glad to part
company.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no lack of opinion on snakes in Hendersonville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Von Hoene, who recently retired to the mountains of western
North Carolina writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised in the city suburbs of the north and have had a
long-standing fear of snakes. I think this began when was I was 12
years old and on a Boy Scout excursion. During the night it seemed
too cold to venture forth to the woods so I went to the bathroom
through a knot hole in the floor of the cabin. The next day an
extremely large and thoroughly angry black snake was pulled from
underneath the structure by some older boys. This experience
initiated years of nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had forgotten all about snakes until retiring last year. I
was lighting our water heater in the crawl space under our house
and on my back with a flashlight and butane torch when two feet
from my nose a beaded glistening reflected the skin of a snake. I
thought it was heart attack time. In short order I realized that it
was just the skin and a local tradesman later told me he had killed
the snake a few months earlier while working for the previous
homeowner and that it was ``large but harmless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I spilled all my renewed fears out to my barber, a kind of
folksy Oracle at Delphi who is native to the region and he replied
something such as, ``Well ... if ya'll are afraid of snakes, ya
didn't study things out good enough as we have more snakes here
than anywhere's else. I've lived in these hills all ma life and
don't know anyone who died from snake bite so the odds are looking
good for ya.''
</P>
<P>
   Reece Mitchell, of Hendersonville, writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately our local paper carried your humorous but not
funny article `Only good snakes are the dead snakes.' Destroying
without reason the living things that make our earth habitable by
humans is a major reason the planet is in trouble. There are
volumes of data supporting the need to maintain biodiversity, but
I'll mention only one example.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know someone who suffers from arthritis, that person
probably takes a medication that was first discovered in the venom
of a viper.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, from The Lamberts of Hendersonville comes this
venomous retort:
</P>
<P>
   ``I found Murray's negative attitude toward all snakes
reprehensible, and I believe his publishing such ignorant attitudes
in a newspaper column was irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is if I ever find myself in the North Carolina
town of Hendersonville, it won't be the snakes I'll be watching out
for.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
