<HEADER>
A3648 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN19-COX     11-18 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats powwow on state strategy
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Less than two months before the 2000 filing
deadline, Democrats have no credible candidate to go against
Republican U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one symptom of the malaise in the Texas Democratic
Party that caused several Democrats, ramrodded by former state Sen.
Carl Parker (D-Port Arthur) to gather last Thursday, Nov. 11, at
the Hill Country ranch of one of their biggest patrons, Beaumont
trial lawyer Walter Umphrey. They hoped to figure out ways to
re-energize the moribund Democratic Party _ but didn't get around
to discussing an opponent for Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   Former Lt. Gov. Ben Barnes confirmed he was among the two dozen
who attended, along with House Speaker Pete Laney, Democratic Sens.
Judith Zaffirini of Laredo, Rodney Ellis of Houston and Gonzalo
Barrientos of Austin, former Comptroller John Sharp and Texas
Democratic Party Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said a major problem is that Democrats no longer stress
passionately enough issues that appeal to lower-income people, such
as education. They stood by while Gov. George W. Bush took credit
for a tax cut in excess of $1 billion, while teachers pleaded for
more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have surpluses and we don't do the responsible thing,
and the Democrats are not standing on the floor of the Legislature
fighting for those things, what is the reason for minorities in
Houston and South Texas to vote for a Democrat rather than a
Republican?'' Barnes asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying the Democrats aren't for that,'' he said. ``I'm
saying they didn't communicate it to voters. And I think that (1998
lieutenant governor nominee) John Sharp and (comptroller nominee)
Paul Hobby didn't communicate themselves particularly to minority
voters on those points.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, only 3.7 million of 11.5 million registered Texas
voters cast ballots in November. Meanwhile, Sharp and Hobby lost to
Republicans _ Sharp by less than 69,000 votes, Hobby less than
21,000. Democrats say that with even 100,000 more minority voters,
both would have won.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Wendler Sr., a longtime progressive Democrat who wasn't
invited to the meeting, said Democratic slippage in recent
elections happened partly because groups that lobby the
Legislature, which are a principal source of election financing,
won't spend money against incumbents of either party.
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans have grown in number _ to a 16-15 majority in the
Senate and a 78-72 deficit in the House _ Democrats' hopes of
recapturing some ground have given way to efforts to keep Democrats
in place in those bodies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The late Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock and current House Speaker Laney
were elected as Democrats. But to preserve their leadership
positions, both included Republicans on their teams in the name of
bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Republican policies of cutting taxes and limiting government
generally please business owners, so, given a choice, they support
Republicans _ unless the Democrats are incumbents. And the groups
that do support Democrats as a rule don't finance challengers to
Republican incumbents, Wendler said.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Democrats fight hard only for incumbents under fire
or for Democrats running for open seats. In areas where there's not
a tough fight, other Democrats on the ballot are hurt _
particularly statewide candidates, said Wendler _ who watched
former law partner Garry Mauro get just 31.2 percent against
Republican Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultants also concentrate on reliable voters and
compete for Republican and independent voters rather than appeal to
people registered to vote who don't, Wendler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``An overwhelming number of Texans old enough to vote are people
who would vote Democratic if they voted _ because they are people
of modest means,'' Wendler said. ``That is because the Democrats
have historically been for things that helped people of modest
means.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the last decade or so ... there's no effort by what we
say, by what we stand for, to emphasize that, and our campaigns
make no effort to move out in that big majority of people of modest
means who are not voting,'' Wendler said. ``They vote in smaller
and smaller percentages all the time _ because they can't see why
it would make a difference for them to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
