<SLUG> BC-COLUMBIA-HIGHART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH ART CAN BE NEWS, COLUMBIA STUDY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is a quintessential big arts story in the late '90s? New
York mayor Rudolph Giuliani's attempt to shut down the Brooklyn
Museum of Art's controversial ``Sensation'' exhibit _ where high
culture mixed with political intrigue _ fits the bill.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the ideas inside ``Reporting the Arts: News
Coverage of Arts and Culture in America,'' the new study by
Columbia University's National Arts Journalism Program. The report
_ which analyzed articles in 15 metro dailies and The New York
Times, USA Today, and The Wall Street Journal during October 1998 _
concluded that ``high art . . . presented . . . in a way that made
it engage a mainstream audience, attracted the most . . . prominent
coverage of all artistic categories.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the report's findings were predictable. Event listings
occupy close to 50 percent of the space devoted to arts and
entertainment; the pop arts of television, movies, and music
generate much more coverage than the visual arts, architecture, and
dance; and institutions ``that have mastered the technique of
blockbuster presentation win prominent coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as newspapers struggle to maintain resources to cope with
the cultural boom of the '90s, the arts journalism program's
associate director Andras Szanto is optimistic, noting that ``as
newspapers increasingly lose their franchise in breaking news, one
forum they can maintain the franchise in is culture.''
</P>
<P>
   And nodding to the Brooklyn Art Museum flap, research analyst
Andrew Tyndall says that ``when high art enters the culture, that
trumps everything.'' Speaking for himself, Tyndall says arts
editors might want to focus on using reporters _ ``arts
generalists'' _ to go ``sniffing out for the combustion'' at that
intersection of the esoteric and mainstream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
