<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3651 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ANIME19-COX     11-18 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIME19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Japanese animator drawn into contradiction
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Japanese animation has exploded into the American
mainstream, most notably with last week's colossal opening of
``Pokemon: The First Movie.'' The heavily promoted children's movie
about battling ``pocket monsters'' grossed $50.8 million, setting a
five-day record for animated features.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese imports such as ``Pokemon'' and ``Dragon Ball Z'' rule
kiddie TV ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's something we should be proud of,'' said
Hiyao Miyazaki, one of Japan's leading animators, as well as one of
the most respected figures in animation in the world. ``Once you
reach critical mass, however good it may be, it becomes toxic.''
</P>
<P>
   Miyazaki is revered by fans of Japanese animation _ or anime _
for such films as ``Kiki's Delivery Service'' and ``My Neighbor
Totoro.'' His latest feature, ``Princess Mononoke,'' topped ``E.T.
_ The Extra-Terrestrial'' as the highest-grossing film in Japan
before it was surpassed by ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through an interpreter at the Toronto International
Film Festival, where ``Princess Mononoke'' made its North American
premiere, the 58-year-old director was critical of anime's booming
popularity at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that Japanese pop culture has gone well beyond
that critical mass, and in a way what we do in the business simply
chews up children and their consciousness,'' Miyazaki said. ``And
the fact that we in Japan cannot control this kind of output, but
it's simply spreading to the Western world is certainly not
something I can hold my head up proudly about.''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of all films produced in Japan are animated,
ranging from children's fairy tales to complex adult epics. That
group is the most profitable segment of the industry. Anime also
accounts for a sizable portion of Japanese television programming,
more than half of which is based on comic books, known as manga.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, annual rental revenue for anime videos is
estimated at $80 million. Anime video sales revenue ranges between
$75 million and $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Anime accounts for 75 percent to 80 percent of the video rentals
at Bookery Fantasy in Fairborn, Ohio, according to manager Steve
Bates. More than half of the store's video stock is anime, from
all-ages to adults-only viewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing real well with all of the Japanese animation,''
Bates said. ``It's not just `Pokemon' and `Dragon Ball Z'.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many schools of anime, from innocuous children's
programming such as ``Pokemon'' to lyrical, yet intense, tales with
historical settings, such as ``Princess Mononoke.'' Other popular
styles include mecha, or robot anime, and hentai, which is sexually
explicit.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. audiences typically equate animation with Disney features
and Saturday-morning cartoons. ``There's no stigma attached to
seeing an animated film in Japan,'' Bates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Princess Mononoke'' is a sophisticated ecological fable, based
loosely on Japanese folklore, about a war between encroaching
civilization and the beast gods of the forest. The lavishly
animated epic won the 1998 Best Picture Award at Japan's equivalent
of the Oscars and drew record ratings earlier this year when it
aired on Japanese television.
</P>
<P>
   The film's record-setting $150 million gross is remarkable given
that Japan has one-half the population of the United States and
less than one-tenth the number of movie screens.
</P>
<P>
   The English-language version was adapted by ``Sandman'' creator
and fantasy novelist Neil Gaiman and features the voices of Claire
Danes, Billy Crudup, Minnie Driver, Billy Bob Thornton, Gillian
Anderson and Jada Pinkett Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Princess Mononoke'' contains mature themes and violent images,
and it lacks straightforward heroes and villains. The title
character, a feral child raised by wolves, confronts the forces of
industry invading the forest paradise that is her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, we've made many films in the past and our goals
with those films has been to send a message of hope and the
possibility of happiness to growing children,'' Miyazaki said.
``But the truth is that all those children ... are confronted with
the terrible dilemmas of modern life and of humanity. The truth is
that they are worried about the direction of humankind. They're
worried about the continuation and the future of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   By continuing to make movies that only taught children about
hope and happiness, the director felt he would be turning a deaf
ear to their urgent needs and pleas.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we made this film knowing that we would need to step
outside the boundaries of what you call entertainment,'' Miyazaki
said. ``We made this film with a sense of mission. The success of
the film was never in our sights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Princess Mononoke'' ``has some very intense moments,'' said
Deborah Brown, president of D-Anime, the Dayton Animation Club.
``It has things in it that make you think.''
</P>
<P>
   The intellectual component of anime such as ``Princess
Mononoke,'' an example of the wabi-sabi school, is a big part of
the appeal for Brown. ``There's also the sheer beauty of the art,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   D-Anime has about 20 regular members who meet the first and
third Saturdays of the month at the Miami Valley Unitarian
Fellowship in Oakwood to watch and discuss Japanese animation. The
wide range of anime styles is reflected by the group's varied
tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all devotees of the art form, but we all have our
particular preference,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese anime blossomed as an industry in the 1950s and '60s.
The first significant works were inexpensively produced for
television by cutting the standard 24-frames-per-second animation
format of Hollywood cartoons to as few as 10- to
five-frames-per-second. ``Astro Boy'' became an international hit,
paving the way for later series such as ``Gigantor,'' ``Kimba the
White Lion'' and ``Speed Racer.''
</P>
<P>
   The theatrical release in the '90s of adult-themed anime films
such as ``Akira'' and ``Ghost in the Shell'' brought the art form
to a larger, more sophisticated audience.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Pokemon,'' a new generation has discovered anime. Warner
Bros. reportedly paid about $5 million for the rights to the
Japanese ``Pokemon'' film, which was dubbed into English, with a
new musical soundtrack. A sequel is being readied for summer
release, although it may hit theaters sooner to capitalize on the
trend.
</P>
<P>
   You can be certain it's not one that pleases Miyazaki.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, our work is filled with many contradictions,'' the
director said. ``When we made `Totoro,' I made it so that I could
encourage little children to walk out into the woods and pick up
acorns. Instead, I get letters from them telling me about the
dozens of times that they've watched the film, which means that
they're sitting in front of their television sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I have an opportunity, I speak out about this. But
it seems that on this question it's very difficult for my voice to
be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
