<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3652 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-NEWYORK-GIRLS19-COX     11-18 1773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYORK-GIRLS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New bed-and-breakfast a pleasant, relaxing getaway
 &HT;    By Jan Tuckwood
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When we plan a family trip, we steal a tip from
Eloise: ``Getting bored is not allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   You know Eloise, the 6-year-old scamp who lives on the top floor
of The Plaza hotel in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She became famous for the first time in 1955, when Kay
Thompson's ``Eloise'' came out, and she's famous again now. She's
scampering to an FA0 Schwarz near you with new toys and re-releases
of all of her books.
</P>
<P>
   So when we decided to take our four daughters _ ages 19 to 9 _
to New York, we consulted Eloise. Nothing gets a girl psyched for
the big city like a (somewhat bratty) role model.
</P>
<P>
   And I wanted them psyched. Not because they were going to their
idea of heaven _ the home of MTV's ``Total Request Live'' _ but
because they were going to mine: The Manhattan of the Gilded Age.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to turn their clocks back to a more refined time, to
educate them in the architecture of Stanford White, the technique
of high tea, the importance of the right hat.
</P>
<P>
   A history lesson? Sounds boooooring, right?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. When I peppered our travels with tales of fabulous gals
like Eloise and Edith Wharton, Evelyn Nesbit and Elsie de Wolfe, we
skittered right back in time, full of fascination all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Who are Eloise, Edith, Evelyn and Elsie, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   A subjective assessment: They're simply the world's luckiest
little girl, the world's best woman writer, the most beautiful
woman of the century and the world's first Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Eloise, who lives only in the heads of fanciful
folks, the other three ladies lived, loved and created at the end
of the last century.
</P>
<P>
   To know them is to know New York of the Gilded Age.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST STOP: Tea at The Plaza
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows about The Plaza, especially kids who have read
the Eloise books or seen ``Home Alone II: Lost in New York.'' I
didn't even need to point out the hotel. When my 9-year-old saw the
doormen and the famous double P sign at the corner of 59th and
Fifth, she bounded up the stairs and into the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Her first question: Where's Eloise?
</P>
<P>
   We took a walk through the magnificent hotel, built in 1907, and
soon found her: Hilary Knight's famous painting of Eloise, star of
Kay Thompson's books, hangs right by the Palm Court, where
civilized ladies love to sip tea.
</P>
<P>
   Civilized we were not. But place a china teacup in front of a
little girl and even the most dedicated tomboy can master a perfect
pinkie lift.
</P>
<P>
   My 12-year-old, Kate, is a high-tea pro, having sipped Earl Grey
at Brown's Hotel in London. But tea at The Plaza was a first for
Tess, 9, who promptly fell in love with cucumber sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   We sipped, nibbled and carried on a dignified conversation for
an hour. It seemed proper to do a little name-dropping.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-crumpet, I dished: Did you know that the Vanderbilts were
just about the richest family that ever lived when this hotel
opened? Did you know that they had a mansion right next door? And
that Albert Vanderbilt, great-grandson of Cornelius, the one who
made all the money in railroads, was the very first guest at The
Plaza? Oh, and did you know that designer Gloria Vanderbilt got
engaged at this very hotel?
</P>
<P>
   The girls sat spellbound, rapt with these society snippets, the
scones and the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Gossip _ even very old gossip _ sticks with a gal, much like a
passion for clotted cream.
</P>
<P>
   For this pleasant memory with my daughters, I happily shelled
out $29 per person.
</P>
<P>
   Like Eloise, we said: ``Charge it, please! And thank you very
much!''
</P>
<P>
   MORE GOSSIP: Who was the real Lady Mendl?
</P>
<P>
   We enjoyed a spot of tea the next day, too, this time in a place
steeped with the memory of real women: Lady Mendl's Tea Salon at
the Inn at Irving Place.
</P>
<P>
   We took a taxi downtown to Gramercy Park _ a park so wonderful
and private that only people who live around it (including Julia
Roberts) have a key to the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Gramercy, I told the girls, attracted some of the most prominent
writers of the 19th century: Edith Wharton, O. Henry, Herman
Melville and Stephen Crane all lived in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   If you were alive 100 years ago, I told them, and if you were
very witty and charming, you might have visited the very spot where
we're going _ 17th Street and Irving Place, a few blocks south of
Gramercy.
</P>
<P>
   Just walking down this street brings back the rush of history.
It looks much as it did when horse-drawn carriages brought fair
ladies to the steep steps of their brownstones.
</P>
<P>
   The Inn at Irving Place, two meticulously restored townhouses
built in 1834, has no sign, just a tiny picture of a teacup by the
door.
</P>
<P>
   We opened the door and gasped: Dark wood. A grand staircase.
Intricate fireplaces. Welcome to the Gilded Age of the 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   A formally dressed fellow ushered us into Lady Mendl's Tea
Salon, just off the entryway.
</P>
<P>
   We took our seats on the Victorian-style couch, poured our tea
from a sterling samovar and thought about the ladies who once lived
like this.
</P>
<P>
   Who was the real Lady Mendl? She was Elsie de Wolfe, a 5-foot-2
dynamo decorator who popularized chintz, vanity tables and cocktail
parties. She _ not Martha Stewart _ was the first marketer of the
gracious lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Elsie was born around 1865. ``I was an ugly child, and I lived
in an ugly age,'' she wrote in her memoirs. ``From the moment I was
conscious of ugliness and its relation to myself and my
surroundings, my one preoccupation was to find my way out of it. In
my escape, I came to the meaning of beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   She got rid of the gloomy Gothic look and brought in cheery
fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Elsie was famous for her pronouncements: ``Plates should be hot,
hot, hot; glasses cold, cold, cold; and table decorations low, low,
low.'' And, ``I believe in optimism and white paint!''
</P>
<P>
   Elsie and her companion, Bessie Marbury, lived directly across
from the townhouses that are now the Inn at Irving Place. Their
famous salons attracted the sharpest wits of the day: Oscar Wilde,
Sarah Bernhardt, Ethel Barrymore.
</P>
<P>
   When Elsie was 61, she married Sir Charles Mendl and became a
real Lady.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Edith Wharton, Elsie's friend, shared her passion for
decor _ and also for purse dogs. Both Edith and Elsie carried
around small dogs.
</P>
<P>
   No dogs or doggie bags allowed at Lady Mendl's Tea Salon,
though.
</P>
<P>
   After five fabulous courses that set us back $30 per person, we
wandered back out onto the streets of this literary neighborhood
and learned about another one of Elsie's pals: architect Stanford
White.
</P>
<P>
   LOVERS' TRIANGLE: Stanford, Evelyn and Harry
</P>
<P>
   The Gramercy Park neighborhood is full of the memory of Stanford
White, who was called ``the greatest designer that this country has
ever produced'' by Vanity Fair magazine.
</P>
<P>
   He lived here and designed many notable buildings here,
particularly a lavish pleasure palace known as Madison Square
Garden. White's Madison Square, opened in 1890, featured a nude
statue of the goddess Diana atop its tower. But a nude Diana wasn't
half as shocking as the life and death of Stanford White. He loved
beautiful women, particularly Evelyn Nesbit, the stunning actress
who became the model for the Gibson Girl.
</P>
<P>
   In 1906, while watching a revue at Madison Square Garden, White
was shot three times by crazy millionaire Harry K. Thaw, Evelyn's
husband.
</P>
<P>
   A headline in Vanity Fair after his death: ``Stanford White,
Voluptuary and Pervert, Dies the Death of a Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   White's Madison Square Garden is long gone _ the New York Life
Insurance Company (with its golden pyramid roof) now stands on the
site _ but many of his buildings live on.
</P>
<P>
   To get a good look at his work, visit the New York Palace Hotel
at 50th and Madison. The hotel rises from the Villard Houses, a
stunning Gilded Age mansion White built in 1882. Inside the Villard
Houses is the famous restaurant Le Cirque _ too fancy and expensive
for my kids, but they did get a chance to ogle the original marble
fireplace in the hotel lobby.
</P>
<P>
   LADY LIBERTY and
</P>
<P>
   New York's most historic block
</P>
<P>
   All American children should climb to the crown of the Statue of
Liberty at least once. We waited two hours just for the chance to
spend 90 minutes climbing up 354 stairs.
</P>
<P>
   The climb itself is dull until you make it past the 11-story
pedestal into the skirt of Miss Liberty. She's made of 310 copper
plates riveted together and held with iron bars, sort of an Eiffel
Tower with a thin copper skin.
</P>
<P>
   It was worth it: My children, each armed with a disposable
camera, used most of their film inside Liberty's crown.
</P>
<P>
   If you visit the statue in the summer or on a holiday weekend,
like we did, you must take the first ferry of the day to guarantee
a chance to climb.
</P>
<P>
   If you visit in the fall or winter, you'll have time after the
statue to walk from the ferry dock to Hanover Square, the most
historic block in New York. This block, full of 18th- and
19th-century buildings, is surrounded by the glass skyscrapers of
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The original Delmonico's restaurant, where high-society dined,
is still here, on Beaver Street, with a big script ``D'' engraved
in the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Owners have changed many times in the past 170 years, but it's
currently open Monday through Friday and serving the Wall Street
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The next best place to have a drink: Harry's at Hanover Square,
which feels like walking into another era.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK DOWN: At old Manhattan
</P>
<P>
   New York grew from the southern tip of the island northward, so
to get a bird's-eye view of the oldest buildings, head to the top
of the tallest, the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   From the 107-floor observation deck, we could see New York's
original City Hall, Trinity Church (designed in 1846) and the
stunning Woolworth Building, built in 1913. And lots more, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   The Empire State Building observatory has a better view of
skyscrapers, but the World Trade Center gives you the best look of
old New York.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know which the kids liked better: The view or the sheer
terror of being up that high. For a truly scary experience, go up
to the open-air deck. It's like being on the wing of an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Cost to go to the top: $12.50 for adults, $9.50 for seniors and
$6.25 for children 12 and under.
</P>
<P>
   Our reward: A stunning sunset over a city the girls had come to
know, thanks to Eloise, Edith, Evelyn and Elsie.
</P>
<P>
   If Eloise had been there, she might agree: It was all rawther
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
