<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MILNER19-COX     11-18 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MILNER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eddie Fisher's book seems to stretch truth
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember a singer named Eddie Fisher?
</P>
<P>
   I do. Vaguely. The main thing I recall about him is that he was
marred to Elizabeth Taylor when she ran off with Richard Burton. It
was in all the papers back then. Oh yeah, he'd left Debbie Reynolds
to run off with Liz before that. That was in all the papers, too.
</P>
<P>
   If you're old enough, you probably remember something about both
those magnificent episodes. Like I said, it was in all the papers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Fisher has recently come out with a book telling the
details behind those and other scandals of bygone days, and nights.
It's titled ``Been There, Done That'' (St. Martin's Press). And boy
hidee! is his story a humdinger! Somehow or another, though, I
can't quite swallow it all as the truth and nothing but the truth.
</P>
<P>
   As some of you know, I don't ordinarily write here about books I
didn't like as I read them. I'm making an exception this time. I'm
not sure why. Maybe because this particular book outraged me so
that I want to make sure you don't bother to read it. It's
certainly not worth the $24.95 price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some may rush right out and buy it because I declare
it unworthy, particularly since its unworthiness has to do with its
vulgarity. There is a lot of ``sex-and-tell'' in it, but the
vulgarity that struck me is in the attitude of the author.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensively, the author is, of course, Fisher, but there is a
ghost writer in the mix. His name also happens to be Fisher, David
Fisher, but apparently he is not kin to Eddie. At least there is no
mention of a kinship in the jacket notes that tell us the ghost
writer has previously ghosted books for Ed McMahon, George Burns
and ``several sports figures.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what is it about this so-called memoir that offends me so?
It's mainly the attitude, which I attribute to Eddie Fisher, the
singer/man-about-town/self-styled woman magnet and greatest singer
to come down the pike.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he says on page one chapter one: ``The gift in my
throat. ... made me a star, one of the most successful singers in
American history ... I had more consecutive hit records than the
Beatles or Elvis ...''
</P>
<P>
   As I said, I remember Eddie Fisher and some of his songs, ``Oh,
My PopPa,'' for example, but I don't recall him causing anything
even nearly equal to the excitement caused by the Beatles or Elvis,
nor any one of several other singing stars of the '40s, '50s and
'60s.
</P>
<P>
   And the women! He has nothing but insults for the women who
supposedly chased him day and night until they caught him, then did
him dirty. He does say a few complimentary things about Taylor, the
one who treated him like a slave and humiliated him publicly
something fierce by having an open affair with Richard Burton
during the filming of ``Cleopatra'' in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he is a dedicated masochist. That would explain a lot in
his book. But nothing can excuse the way he talks about Debbie
Reynolds, his wife when he ran off with Liz, and Ann-Margaret, and
even his male friends, including Robert Wagner and William Holden,
both of whom he describes as sobbing like babies when they
discovered their loved ones were having affairs with other men.
Gee, thanks, Eddie, I'm sure they thought, ``that's just what I
want my public to know about me.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene he describes when Ann-Margaret surprises him in his
dressing room after a show was embarrassing for me and I don't even
know Ann-Margaret. ``She fell immediately to her knees to show me
how much she'd missed me ...''
</P>
<P>
   I've seen a couple of Fisher's former wives and girlfriends
interviewed on TV since his book came out and they were less than
complimentary and called him a liar. I'm inclined to believe them
after skimming through this book-length tabloid trash. Come to
think of it, the publisher is the same one who had to recall that
so-called bio of Texas Gov. George W. Bush after finding out the
author was a convicted felon.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
