<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-HILLARY _ Maybe it's her we should be building a library
for, not her husband. It probably goes without saying that Hillary
Rodham Clinton has broken the mold when it comes to U.S. first
ladies. It's still about 18 months until her husband leaves office,
and yet some 40 books already have been written largely or
completely about her. (Even the relatively controversial Nancy
Reagan barely hit double figures _ well after leaving the White
House.) And apparently, the deluge is just beginning. Last month it
was ``Bill and Hillary _ The Marriage.'' Come November it will be
publication of dueling tomes (including one from ``Passages''
author Gail Sheehy) purporting to take us inside Hillary's head.
And don't even get us started on the writers who've already signed
contracts to produce books about the all-but-declared Hillary
Clinton-Rudy Giuliani Senate race. A look at the phenomenon of
Hillary Literature and speculation on when _ and if _ it will ever
end. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (e) entertainment and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GATES _ Henry Louis Gates Jr. cannot help being disarming
and ingratiating in the same breath. He is that way in public and
in private, a self-confessed ``race'' man who doesn't believe in
race, a man who ``loves everything about African-American culture''
but wears a neatly pressed white shirt every day, a black man who
had a white girlfriend in elementary school, another in high school
and today is married to a white woman. If they are contradictions,
they help to explain why Skip Gates has rapidly become a black man
for all seasons, showing up on PBS, in The New Yorker, on the op-ed
page of the New York Times and, now, on book tours promoting
``Wonders of the African World,'' the companion volume to the PBS
series, and ``Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African
American Experience.'' (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GATES-BIO _ Bio box on Skip Gates. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GATES-LIST _ Recommended reading: Books by Skip Gates.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-DUBNER _ ``Turbulent Souls'' author Stephen Dubner
wrestles free of his parents' adopted Catholicism to reclaim
Judaism. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-CARTER _ Interview with Buddy Carter about his new
biography of his father Billy Carter. Contrary to popular belief,
the First Brother was not just a beer-guzzling service station
owner. He was an avid reader, shrewd businessman and a complex
character. Buddy talks about his differences with his father and
how they reconciled. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ A look at ``Hitchcock Poster Art.'' Weekly
books column by Scott Eyman. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WEASEL _ James Patterson has successfully managed to
transcend the beach books and become a brand name writer. Review of
the book ``Pop Goes the Weasel,'' by James Patterson. (Eyman, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-STORM _ Few can comprehend the power of a big storm like
the one that hit Galveston, Texas, in 1900. Even weather service
employee Isaac Cline had no idea. Review of the book ``Isaac's
Storm'' by Erik Larson. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-APPELFELD _ NEVASSERET ZION, Israel_ Author who survived
Holocaust has new fears for America. ``The book is about escaping
Judaism and how you cannot escape it,'' Appelfield says, ``And this
is a tragedy.'' (Engelhardt, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-CRICHTON _ A conversation with Michael Crichton, the
writer who makes science fun and (for himself) incredibly
lucrative, inspiring such films and TV shows as ``Jurassic Park,''
``E/R'' and ``Disclosure.'' His newest novel, ``Timeline,''
shuttles to parallel universes of different centuries along the
wormholes of quantum physics. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ The latest Stephen King, available only on
audiotape and read by the author, is _ no surprise _ a collection
of horror stories. The twist is, these stories are all about the
horrors of tobacco, and the nightmares smokers go through for
another puff on the noxious weed. ... Also, former Miami Herald
journalist Tannarive Due plans to finish a project Alex Haley
started, a novel about Madam C.J. Walker, the first black
millionaire. ... Amazon.Com users pick their favorite books, etc. .
. What does Don Imus' decision to drop Imus Book Awards mean to
Barnes &AMP; Noble and the publishing world? (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Remember a singer named Eddie Fisher? I do.
Vaguely. The main thing I recall about him is that he was marred to
Elizabeth Taylor when she ran off with Richard Burton. It was in
all the papers back then. (Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
