<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   DOGGIE _ ATLANTA _ As portion sizes in restaurants get bigger
and bigger, more and more folks are getting extra mileage out of
those meals by doggie-bagging it, according to a new survey. We
look at what's driving the trend, who's doing it and why. We also
look at how restaurants are encouraging it by using fancier,
improved packaging. (Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PANDAS _ ATLANTA _ Coverage of press tour of new panda habitat.
(Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-TURNER _ A new book, ``Turner Speaks,'' (from the author
of a rash of business books that take a bunch of quotes from famous
people and put them together to look like a leadership manual)
pulls together some of the more sane things Ted has said. We pull
together some of the ones the author left out - and they're a lot
more insightful, we think. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   BARGAINS _ If your holiday social calendar exceeds your clothing
budget, don't worry. You can still put together a festive wardrobe
that's versatile enough for parties and family gatherings without
spending a small fortune. We show you three different holiday looks
that cost less than $150. All it takes is an eye for style and a
couple of core pieces that you can mix and match. (Hill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS of three outfits: one for an
office party; one for a family gathering and one for dancing the
night away.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the
current week.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 1116 -- Instead of going to work, why not spend
your five-day workweek on a cruise. short cruises are becoming more
popular. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post). Art includes 3-column photo
of men playing on a cruise ship, 2-column color photo of cruise
ships, 2-column color photo of shoppers in port, 2-column color
photo of a theatrical presentation on a cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REMEMBERING BERLIN -- When a man returns to East Berlin,
so do his fears and memoriesof torture.(Blackerby, Palm Beach
Post). Art includes 6-pica color photo of a chunk of the Berlin
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- A new hotel is joining a golf mecca in
Scottsdale, Ariz. (N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-JAMAICA _ ORACABESSA, Jamaica _ We take readers to
Boscobell Beach, one of the top Jamaica all-inclusive resorts for
families (as opposed to the Hedonism, Couples, Sandals resorts for
lovebirds). We talk to other families to determine what they like
(or don't like) about the place and the all-inclusive aspect.
(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) WITH COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-JAMAICATOUR _ ORACABESSA, Jamaica _ Four days of family
fun in the sun at Jamaica's top all-inclusive resort designed with
kids in mind. The fun's up from sun up to well beyond sundown.
Watersports, games, arts and crafts, petting zoo, and lots of fun
food. And best of all, they have a staff of counselors who keep the
little darlings occupied from 9 a.m. to 10 p.m. so mom and dad can
slurp a beverage or two and relax. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) WITH COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   NEWYORK-GIRLS _ NEW YORK _ Time Travel in Manhattan: A Walk with
Miss Wharton. Our riter drags her two young daughters through the
gilded-age world of Caroline Astor, Cornelia Vanderbilt and Edith
Wharton. We have tea at Lady Mendl's (in a fabulously restored old
brownstone in Edith's neighborhood) and The Plaza; we visit lower
Manhattan (the historic Delmonico's, Harry's at Hanover Square and
Fraunces Tavern); peek in the windows of Stanford White's
Metropolitan Club, wish we were rich enough to have dinner at Le
Cirque's (housed in my favorite gilded-age public building, the
Villard Houses) and look down at New York's oldest buildings from
the top of the World Trade Center. (Tuckwood, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BEN-HUR (40 inches) _ Ben Hur: The Musical. A look at Orlando's
latest theater attraction, an $9 million musical that attempts to
re-create that famous chariot race on stage and has an actual wall
of fire. With short comparison chart of Orlando's version against
epic 1959 movie. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   WITH HUR-REVIEW (15 inches) _ Review of the musical; it gets two
stars. Verdict: Lavish but cardboard-thin pageant of Lew Wallace
novel, not helped by generic songs or mechanical spectacle.
(Erstein, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TORREYEA-PARK (36 inches) _ Torreyea State Park is one of the
best views in Florida, simple, solitary, splendid. The eye wings up
over tranquil miles of tufted forests, fading from green to blue in
the distance, to a horizon of rain-washed pure air. Hundreds of
feet below, beyond a steep tumble of trees and shrubs, the
toffee-colored Apalachicola River runs
</P>
<P>
   calmly to the Gulf of Mexico. Celebrate Florida's state park
system's being named the best in the nation by the National
Recreation and Parks Administration and the National Sporting Goods
Association at an Oct. 23 ceremony in Nashville. Florida beat
Missouri, ennessee and Virginia for the gold medal. By Michael
Browning
</P>
<P>
   WITH PARK-BOX (10 inches, with photos) _ Other parks to visit.
(Browning, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Getaway feature from Wednesday paper. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
