<P>
   KCSKUL: Now that the superintendent and the school board once
again control the future of the Kansas City School District, what
specific steps will they take to right the listing ship? Will the
board abandon its fractious ways and coalesce around Demps? Is
anybody working to make sure good candidates are recruited for the
April school board elections. Four seats are up for grabs. Can
Demps provide any specifics about how he'll implement his
accountability plan and the core curriculum and improve teacher
training? Kevin Hoffmann. 20-25.
</P>
<P>
   CHART: Plans are under way for an additional 20 charter schools
in the Kansas City School District. The impact on the district,
already reeling from the loss of accreditation, could be severe.
Thousands of additional students could be diverted to these public
but independently operated schools. Phil O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   STOW: At a press conference Thursday, Stowers Institute
officials introduce the three researchers already hired and give a
preview of the facilities and the research that will take place
there. Stowers is going after rising stars in basic life science
research with the aim of turning Kansas City into a biomedical
research hub. Alan Bavley and Lynn Franey. 25-30. Graphic,
sidebars, including STOWERS _ Stowers Institute introduces its new
scientific director. By Julius A. Karash
</P>
<P>
   BASS: Because of the Bass case, in which two of three triplet
boys died of starvation, the Division of Family Services plans to
add social workers to Kansas City schools and is meeting with
various groups in the city this week to improve relationships and
get community help on identifying child abuse. Donna McGuire. 15.
</P>
<P>
   LENEXA. Lenexa, Kan., apparently has taken a lead among area
cities in putting its business on the Internet. Now residents can
fill out forms online and pay fees using their credit cards.
Brandon Ferguson.
