<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLULMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORCING THE ISSUE IS A MUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no mystery about what happens to the Patriots when they
lose this year.
</P>
<P>
   They lose the battle along the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   They can't run against a good defense. They can't stop the run
against a decent running game.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL season stats get right to the point.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 AFC teams, including the expansion Cleveland Browns,
the Patriots rank 14th in rushing . . . and, surprise, they're 14th
in trying to stop the run.
</P>
<P>
   The fans and reporters can talk all they want about the
Patriots' coaching whenever the team fails, but that is not the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   So they went for a touchdown with a yard to go in the first
quarter Monday night against the Jets, trailing just 7-0, and
didn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   So they threw the ball with one minute left in the first half,
trailing, 14-3, and the Jets intercepted it and cashed in for a
quick touchdown. That's not the reason the Patriots lost to the
Jets, or the Chiefs or Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   In every one of those games, they've been outhit on both sides
of the line of scrimmage. The other teams just played tougher. The
Patriots are just not a physical team. And football is still a game
of blocking and tackling.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy football types want to make more out of it than that,
but when you want to be one of the best in the NFL, sooner or later
you have to match the opposition physically or go home a loser.
</P>
<P>
   Miami and Buffalo are tougher teams. The Patriots have to try to
win in both of those places the next two weeks, and if they decide
to play ``soft'' like they did Monday night, they'll lose both
games.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for the players to take a little inventory and find
out if they have the heart to win the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe is the best quarterback in the game right now. This
is not just the opinion of your humble reporter; every coach who
has faced him this year says the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   When he has time, he just eats up the opposition. Monday night,
he didn't have a chance. The Jets had someone in his face all
night. They knocked him down 12 times. When they backed off after
going ahead, 24-3, Bledsoe got two quick scores. Then the Jets came
charging back, and in the final three possessions, just one
touchdown away from tying the game, the Patriots had a net of minus
1 yard in 11 plays.
</P>
<P>
   The stats show Miami always plays tougher at home. Coach Jimmy
Johnson blistered the team in Buffalo after the Bills embarrassed
his players, 23-3, Sunday. He's been on their backs all week.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be even more difficult for the Patriots to beat
the Bills in Buffalo in two weeks. Their defense is outstanding,
the AFC's most physical.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots lose to both Miami and Buffalo, then chances are
they'll be on the road in the playoffs trying to get to the Super
Bowl as a wild card. That doesn't happen very often. The Patriots
did it in 1985, and that team did it with heart and courage more
than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins assistant head coach Dave Wannstedt said the key to
winning Sunday is to contain the Patriots' passing game. Wannstedt:
``We will play a lot better than we did in Buffalo. That was just
one of those games. Actually, our defense didn't play that bad.
It's just that our offense didn't do much to help us out. Damon
(Huard) was a little nervous in that situation, and we didn't have
a good day on offense. As a team, we are healthy. We know the key
will be to keep Bledsoe and those wide receivers from making big
plays. I watched the Jets game, and I was surprised. The Jets did a
great job on defense. They did a lot of good things. When you can
stop that passing game, you have a good chance at beating the
Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
