<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH `A' GAME, HE WAS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He still stops to clear his throat every few minutes,
reminding you why he woke up Monday morning and told his boss he
couldn't come to work. After Rick Pitino got the news about Paul
Pierce's weak stomach and sore throat, the coach said Pierce was
``doubtful'' for Wednesday's game against the Cavaliers. But Pitino
has been around the 23-year-old man from Los Angeles for two
seasons now. He knows it takes more than that to keep the
6-foot-7-inch guard out of a game. And not just a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce considers himself a sportsman. He has a putter inside his
locker. He has a pool table in his basement (``My game is real
nice,'' he said with a smile). He has the same agent as dynamic
tennis sisters Venus and Serena Williams, so Pierce likes to think
he can play that sport, too. ``Oh, I'm good at tennis,'' he said.
``When you see this 6-7 frame rushing the net, watch out.'' One
thing his sickness confirmed for him is this: He's not a television
watcher. ``I don't watch it that much; it corrupts the mind,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His sports options limited, Pierce showed up at the FleetCenter
and helped the Celtics beat the Cavs, 114-103. He finished with 30
points, 11 rebounds, 4 assists, 4 steals . . . and 7 turnovers. If
you weren't one of the 14,140 people inside the arena, you would
have agreed with Pierce's TV analysis if you watched his first
half. Mind corruption? Certainly. He didn't look good. And he was
cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building was cold or something,'' he said. ``One time, I
was shaking my hand and my fingers were numb. That's how cold it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that ended in the third quarter, when Pierce went for 14
points. The Celtics still trailed by 7 entering the fourth, but
that was a lot better than the 15-point deficit they had faced in
the game's first six minutes. The new-look Cavs _ they even had new
uniforms with ``Cavs'' printed on their backsides _ were framing
themselves a blowout. Pierce talked afterward about the advantage
he had over 6-5 Cleveland guard Bob Sura, but in the first 30
seconds, there was Pierce attempting a shot and Sura blocking it.
Pierce looked around for a whistle and, amazingly on this night (60
personal fouls), there wasn't one.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Pierce had seven points and four turnovers. In the
locker room, Pitino made a few adjustments while Pierce made a deal
with whomever controls the FleetCenter thermostat. Or at least it
seemed that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air wasn't as cold in the second half,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He took 10 shots in the second half and made six of them. One of
his biggest came 2 1/2 minutes into the fourth. He took a pass from
Walter McCarty, lined up in the corner, and sank a 23-foot
3-pointer. That was big because it gave the Celtics a 1-point lead.
The Celtics hadn't led since scoring the first hoop, nine seconds
into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Pierce knows how to play when he is sick. He also
knows how to play shooting guard, which was questioned before the
season began. He said there isn't much difference in what he is
asked to do. The only change is the faces he looks into. He now
sees thin guards who are often his size or smaller. He is excited
about that aspect of the new gig because he often finds he can
dominate the smaller men. How many shooting guards do you see with
11 rebounds?
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' win and Pierce's recovery masked some other
unpleasant storylines. One of them was the play of Cleveland rookie
point guard Andre Miller. He played only 19 minutes and had 13
points and 4 assists, but it is obvious that he is going to be a
very good point guard. People in Cleveland have seen Mark Price,
Kevin Johnson, Terrell Brandon, and Brevin Knight direct Cav
offenses since 1986. Some in the organization believe Miller can be
better than all of them. Why is this unpleasant? Miller was the
player the Cavs took with the gift first-rounder the Celtics handed
to them. (Just in case I haven't been blunt enough, I think Vitaly
Potapenko and a $30-plus million contract for Andrew DeClercq and
Miller was a terrible deal for the Celtics. But we'll revisit that
another time.)
</P>
<P>
   This also wasn't the best night for Antoine Walker. The captain
is in a 3-point shooting rut right now. That is, he is taking too
many of them. His 3-point attempts are dangerously similar to his
free-throw attempts. That should scare Walker, Pitino, and you (if
you care about the Celtics). Consider that Walker is 6-9 and close
to 250 pounds. Now consider that Bennett Salvatore, Ron Olesiak,
and Jason Phillips were virtually calling fouls on players who
exhaled too dramatically. With that in his favor, Walker did not
attempt a free throw.
</P>
<P>
   That's something Pitino and his staff will certainly discuss
during practice. But for now, they can point to the refreshing
story of Adrian Griffin (23 points, 11 rebounds). They can talk
about a game that began as if it would be an awful loss and wound
up as a double-digit win. And even better, they now know what it
takes to heal their sick shooting guard. All they have to do is
challenge him to a game. Any game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
