<SLUG> BC-DENNIS-HAYSBERT-IN-NOW-AND-AGAIN-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DENNIS HAYSBERT, IT'S HAPPENING `NOW' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Dennis
Haysbert in a scene from ``Now and Again.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Now and again, a television show comes out of nowhere that looks
and feels different, that captures the imaginations of viewers and
compels them to think as they're being entertained.
 &HT;    ``Star Trek'' did that, once upon a time. So did ``The
X-Files.'' To that list, you can add this season's freshman hit
``Now and Again.''
 &HT;    ``At the risk of sounding cocky, and I really don't mean to
sound that way, `Now and Again' is a show I would watch,'' actor
Dennis Haysbert says.
 &HT;    Haysbert, who's won critical praise on the big screen in the
``Major League'' movies and opposite Michelle Pfeiffer in 1992's
``Love Field,'' now plays the enigmatic, nattily dressed Dr.
Theodore Morris, a government scientist who keeps a tight rein on
his creation, superhuman Michael Wiseman (Eric Close).
 &HT;    Written by ``Moonlighting'' creator Glenn Gordon Caron, the
series is the story of a superpowered secret agent with a
bioengineered body and the brain of the ``late'' Michael Wiseman _
played by John Goodman in the pilot. Despite his powers, the new
Wiseman can't forget his wife (Margaret Colin) and teen-age
daughter (Heather Matarazzo), even as he faces off against
terrorists and other assorted threats to truth, justice and the
American way.
 &HT;    ```Now and Again' has a little bit of everything,'' Haysbert
says by cellular telephone from a New York taxi on his way to a
costume fitting. ``And it puts everything in there very seamlessly,
at least in my opinion and, apparently, in the opinion of the
people who have embraced it. The show has action, comedy, drama,
sci-fi and romance all rolled into one, and it literally jumps back
and forth from scene to scene.''
 &HT;    It's the first time in a decade that the actor has appeared in a
television series.
 &HT;    ``I was really making a conscious effort to stay away from
television, because I always thought the speed of it undermined the
quality,'' Haysbert says. ``But that's simply not the case here.
The writing by Glenn Gordon Caron and his staff is incredible. The
actors I'm working with are great. We all have very, very unique
characters to play, and somehow we all blend.
 &HT;    ``I think that's all unusual, especially on television today,''
he says. ``Very few shows have so much going for them, but those
few shows seem to be doing great.''
 &HT;    On a personal level, Haysbert sees ``Now and Again'' as a
character study about two men who come to rely on and trust one
another. Morris respects Wiseman, is proud of him and wants to
protect Wiseman's family, but must maintain a certain emotional
distance. After all, he is the boss.
 &HT;    And, while Morris may occasionally break out in song, he's
commanding and formidable without ever raising his voice.
 &HT;    ``That comes from his great confidence and his intelligence,''
Haysbert says. ``There is no need to yell and scream. If he were to
yell and scream, he'd lose some power. It's just not for him to do.
 &HT;    ``He's so much in control,'' the actor says, ``and I think
Michael depends on him. There's a lot of smart-aleck repartee, but
that's just Michael's way of trying to keep up.
 &HT;    ``And I think Theo actually enjoys that,'' he adds. ``He enjoys
that Michael has a mind of his own, that Michael can ruffle him a
little bit, but he's always in control.''
 &HT;    Haysbert is no stranger to science fiction, having appeared in
1999's ``The Thirteenth Floor'' and, earlier, the 1993 cult
favorite ``Suture,'' in which he played the twin brother of a white
man (Michael Harris) who tries to frame him for their father's
murder. Among his other credits are the recent ``Random Hearts''
and 1995's ``Waiting to Exhale.''
 &HT;    Prior to beginning ``Now and Again,'' Haysbert completed two
films, both due out next year: ``Love and Basketball,'' a
relationship drama co-starring Omar Epps and Alfre Woodard, and
``What's Cooking?,'' a slice of life about four Los Angeles
families, one black and the others Korean, Jewish and Hispanic.
 &HT;    Although he's been working steadily on the big screen, Haysbert
says that he saw ``Now and Again'' as the kind of career
opportunity that justified leaving his native Los Angeles and
relocating his family to Manhattan.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to get into something that gave me some
responsibility and that also spoke to my abilities,'' the actor
says. ``I don't think that I was being utilized as well and as
thoroughly as I could or should be in feature films.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to get into a television show that was special, that
would show off my versatility and what I can do,'' he says. ``Films
weren't allowing me to do that.
 &HT;    ``And `Now and Again' does.'' 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Now and Again,'' consult the
CBS Website at www.cbs.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on Inside Trek and Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
