<HEADER>
A3794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-18 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN PEOPLE LIVED LOCALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)Nana, what does this word mean?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Local? Well, it means things that are close to you, in your
neighborhood or in your town.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Why would anyone use a word like that?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Well, a long time ago, people actually concentrated on things
that were local. If you looked in their heads, most of their
thoughts and energy were concentrated on things that were happening
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Like what?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Well, for example, Marblehead once had a local movie theater.
Your grandfather and I used to walk there and home, talking a mile
a minute. The owner, whose dad and granddad had run the theater
before him, picked movies that fit the town, good foreign films and
thoughtful independent movies. But even more important, say you
went to the movies alone. You'd always meet someone you knew and
have someone to sit with. Say you went with your husband. You'd run
into another couple and maybe go out for coffee afterward and it
would be a social occasion, not a solitary one. Life was much less
lonely when there were places where you ran into people without
having to make a formal date.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)My mother says never talk to anyone at the movies. You
didn't talk to strangers, did you?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's the odd thing, hon. The person in front of you in
line might seem to be a stranger, but it would turn out that you
had mutual friends, or a child in the same school, or you'd crossed
paths somewhere before. There really aren't any strangers when you
live locally.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Why did the movie theater go out of business?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Well, people believed it was important to see the very newest
movies the minute they came out, so they went to the malls. Or they
watched videos. I think people just got used to feeling lonely.
There's so much emphasis on getting what you want as an individual
that being part of a community no longer enters our minds as a way
of being happier.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)How did that happen?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Well, before the chains took over, a town newspaper used to be
filled with articles about that town. When your mom was little, I
wrote for our local paper _ about projects teachers were doing in
the schools, about interesting citizens, and one time, even what it
was like to work on a lobster boat. Most people back then read the
paper, knew what was happening, and as a result, had strong
opinions, so it was easy to start conversations. Back then folks
had time to participate in local affairs _ by voting, by joining
groups, by getting to know the people they read about. Now, with
one owner, the suburban papers all look the same. People are too
busy working or using the Internet to get involved in local issues,
so they don't care that the paper's full of articles that could
apply to any town in America. Most of them don't bother to read it
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Was anything else local, besides the movie and the
newspaper?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   You won't believe this, but the people who worked in local shops
knew my name and would ask how my family was. Not only did I run
into friends while I was shopping, but the people behind the
counter were like friends. The waitress at the coffee shop knew how
I took my coffee, and the pharmacist at the drugstore would ask
about my health. Now, of course, everyone patronizes chains because
they're cheaper, but nothing personal ever happens in them.
Faceless employees are more efficient. If you're in a hurry,
conversations slow you down.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Did you like living locally, Nana?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Oh, hon, I don't know if I can even explain the kind of
connection we felt with one another. You called the place you lived
``your hometown'' for a reason. There's nothing in modern life that
compares with walking into a public place and being greeted with a
smile. Even if you were just running errands, you never felt
invisible. You were recognized everywhere you went. You had the
feeling you mattered to the people you met. Your town belonged to
you, and there was a special place for you in it as well. If
something wasn't going the way you liked, you didn't move. You got
together with other people who shared your concerns and actually
changed it. Is that enough information for your history paper?
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Thanks, Nana. You've been a big help.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Any time, sweetie. You know I'm here at the computer whenever
you want to chat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
