<SLUG> BC-VIETNAMESE-UNCLEHO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, A HAUNTING VIEW IN BOSTON HARBOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In parts of this city's Dorchester neighborhood, home
to as many as 20,000 Vietnamese-Americans, trappings of the
homeland are visible in each shop window and on every street
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Stores crowding Dorchester Avenue offer videotapes of cai luong,
traditional Vietnamese folk opera, as well as foods like canned
rambutan, jackfruit chips, and prawn crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Reproductions of the red-striped yellow flag of the former
Saigon government, which fell to communist forces in 1975, are
prominently displayed in homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   And looming over all of this, some believe, is a perceived image
of Ho Chi Minh, the Vietnamese communist leader, painted in the
blue stripe of an abstract rainbow adorning the Boston Gas tank on
Dorchester Bay.
</P>
<P>
   But many Vietnamese immigrants call Ho Chi Minh a pariah in
their neighborhood. It is one of Boston's most curious ironies for
members of this staunchly anticommunist community that in their
midst sits the 73,000-square-foot rainbow in which many discern the
face of Ho.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the Vietnamese in Dorchester left their homeland to
escape the communist regime that imprisoned them, appropriated
their businesses, and shuttered their churches when it occupied
South Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Ho Chi Minh, who founded and led the country's communist
movement until his death in 1969, personifies tyranny in the eyes
of most Vietnamese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ho Chi Minh and me are enemies,'' Phanreil Thach, 46, on his
way to shop at the Vien-Dong Far East Supermarket, said in a
typical comment.
</P>
<P>
   Corita Kent, the late artist, pacifist, and former nun who
designed the prize-winning peace rainbow in 1971, denied that the
image of the man known in Vietnam today as ``Uncle Ho'' is embedded
in the mural.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Vietnamese believe that, in Big Brother fashion,
Uncle Ho is watching.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about the gas tank's hidden face have passed along
Dorchester Avenue as the Vietnamese community has burgeoned in
recent years. The story is repeated over banh mi thit sandwiches
and cups of ca phe sua, Vietnamese coffee served with sweetened
condensed milk.
</P>
<P>
   Some consider the rainbow an insult. Others are indifferent,
uninterested in any reminder of the turbulent past. Many simply do
not believe that Ho's image overlooks the Vietnamese beauty salons
and travel agencies from a mere three blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   The range of reactions represents the conflicting emotions that
pull at the Vietnamese community about whether to continue waging
the ideological battles of the past or to leave politics behind in
pursuit of the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   Dorchester pharmacist Tuan Q. Tran and his 20-year-old daughter,
Mai Khanh, are typical in their feelings. Tran lectures tirelessly
about the evils of communism in a tone reminiscent of his former
life as a high school teacher in Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, born in the United States and now in college, has
no interest in the subject of communism or, by extension, the gas
tank.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Tran joined a group of Vietnam veterans protesting the
silhouette of Ho Chi Minh, whose facial features and long beard
they see outlined on the left side of the blue stripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot bring Hitler into the Jewish community and see how
they respond,'' Tran said. ``It's the same thing to bring Ho Chi
Minh into the Vietnamese community.''
</P>
<P>
   Tran, 55, is a small man with a coarse mustache and tiny stubble
on the chin of his round face. At the pharmacy, he wears a dress
shirt and tie with New Balance sneakers, dispensing prescriptions
amid rows of Asian nonperishable foods.
</P>
<P>
   A middle-class teacher in his youth, Tran was drafted into the
Saigon government's army in 1968. After 1975, because of his
military service, he spent four years in what the communists called
``reeducation camp.'' Tran calls it prison.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was fed a starvation diet, made to clear minefields
with his bare hands, and force-fed Marxist-Leninist ideology. It
was an experience shared by thousands of other South Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Vietnamese immigrants in America, Tran undertook a
perilous escape by boat. He left with his wife, who was eight
months pregnant, and friends. One man's baby died during the 13-day
journey without food or fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   Communism, Tran said, ruined the prosperity of South Vietnam and
brought years of suffering to him and his family.
</P>
<P>
   In South Vietnam, ``we had freedom. We were practicing a
democracy,'' Tran said. ``Suddenly, the communists came in and we
cannot talk; we cannot move; we cannot stand up and raise our
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk, however, means little to Mai Khanh Tran, 20, who
studies finance at Bentley College, or to her three sisters, none
of them born in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know too much about it, and I'm not too interested,''
she said. ``We would rather (our father) didn't impose his beliefs
on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mai Khanh doesn't understand why Boston Gas has to upset
her father and the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put a little blue paint on the beard or something,'' she said.
``I don't see how that would bother anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a move is out of the question, according to Boston Gas,
because Kent's creation is a copyrighted work of art _ the largest
in the world. Kent died in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will read whatever they want into many things,'' said
Kathleen Hearn, director of public and government relations at
Boston Gas. ``We absolutely do not agree that it has anything to do
with Ho Chi Minh at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of Dorchester's Vietnamese take Boston Gas at its word.
Henry Hiep Tran, 46, calls the image a fantasy of agitated Vietnam
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the vets, after the war, they have memories; they
imagine things,'' said Tran, tapping his temple to indicate that Ho
is all in the head. So Tran, a former South Vietnamese helicopter
gunner who escaped in 1975, is not bothered, though he calls Ho Chi
Minh ``a cheat and a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Vietnamese-Americans would rather not talk about the past,
saying that constant recriminations drain energy away from building
a prosperous life in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't remind me of Ho Chi Minh,'' said Martin Khoi Pham, who
spent 14 years in a reeducation camp because he had been a colonel
in Saigon's army. ``I don't want to remember. When the communists
took over, I lost everything. I've already lost too much of my
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
