 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Hi-tech toys designed with girls in mind 
By James Cummings  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At least in the world of toys, there are times
when boys will be boys, and girls will be girls.
</P>
<P>
   Radica Games Limited, a Dallas-based company best-known for its
hand-held games, has a line of products sold under the name Girl
Tech designed to meet the unique desires of preteen girls. The
products add technology to such pursuits as keeping a diary,
hosting pajama parties and paying tribute to whoever is this week's
``best friend forever.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the products is the Password Journal, a plastic box that
opens only for its owner thanks to a voice recognition module.
Password Journal has compartments for trinkets and slots for pens
and paper. It's small enough to carry around and sells for $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   Another Girl Tech gadget that uses voice recognition technology
is the Door Pass. Attach it to a door and it will ask for a
password any time the door is opened. Unless the owner speaks her
password, the Door Pass, which costs $19.99, sounds an alarm. The
Keepsake Box comes with a remote control, and the box will only
open when the owner punches in a secret code. The Keepsake Box is
supposed to show up in stores later this month and will sell for
$19.99.
</P>
<P>
   Also do out this month is Bug 'Em, a listening device. The user
places a ladybug-shaped microphone in the room she wants to monitor
and listens on a receiver from a nearby room. It is to sell for
$19.99.
</P>
<P>
   Girl Tech devices are sold through major retailers, and online
through EToys.com and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
