 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
It's shore to be a hit 
By Gregory Kallenberg  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ How high-tech is Play-Doh? After all, it's just
Play-Doh, right? If you believe this, you haven't seen the new
Play-Doh, the super-duper, high-tech Play-Doh. The kind of Play-Doh
you find in Play-Doh's Seaside Playworld ($30). In this new
Play-Doh set, kids build a 3-D beach scene with a new lineup of the
pliable and reusable clay. Here you'll find a wet-and-sandy-feeling
Play-Doh and two slimy ocean-scented colors (smelling oddly similar
to Body Works' Sea Spray and Sea Weed bubble baths). The scented
and textured Play-Dohs add a bit of realism to the seascape and
help kids develop the senses. The set includes a pail to make sand
castles, a two-piece fish mold and lots of other ocean shapes.
(www.hasbro.com)
</P>
<P>
   `CRASH' WORTH THE CASH
</P>
<P>
   You're sick of the shooter games. You're sick of the sports
games. You want a race game, but the adult racing games can be so
boring. Really, who wants to be in a NASCAR race and go around an
oval 80 times? That's when you find Sony's Crash Bandicoot's Crash
Team Racing ($50) and you think, ``Cool! Finally a racing game for
me!'' In Crash Team Racing, you take on the persona and drive the
car of any of your favorite characters, including Crash, Tiny or
Cortex. In the adventure mode, you try to win races in order to
solve the mystery of Aku-Aku. Tracks can be anywhere from the polar
ice cap to the Amazon rainforest. The game is fun for the whole
family and is especially entertaining in the head-to-head mode.
(www.playstation.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
