<SLUG> BC-CANADA-SPIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPY BLUNDER DRAWS CRITICISM IN CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ Secret-service agents may find themselves sifting
landfills for Canada's lost secrets amid one of the worst spy
scandals in the country's history, one in which indulging the
national passion for hockey led to a spectacular breach of
security.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Intelligence Security Service is now confirming
that a top-secret document _ reportedly containing key operational
plans of the agency for the upcoming year _ was stolen from the
back of a spy official's minivan last month. The culprits are
believed to be smash-and-grab thieves, not secret agents from enemy
powers, but there is still fear that the document might wind up in
the wrong hands, compromising Canada's security.
</P>
<P>
   The incident has triggered a huge political controversy and
damaged the reputation of the Intelligence Security Service,
Canada's CIA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fiasco and national embarrassment,'' said
Conservative parliament member Peter MacKay. ``It's like something
from an Austin Powers episode, not a front-rank intelligence
service.''
</P>
<P>
   It all started early last month when an intelligence analyst
removed the highly-classified material from spy agency
headquarters, apparently to study up on operations in hope of
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The removal of material was a major violation of security rules
made worse when the analyst headed off for Toronto, the material on
the back seat of her minivan.
</P>
<P>
   Her destination was Toronto's Air Canada Center, home of the
Maple Leafs. But as she cheered on the hockey team, thieves were
smashing out a window of the vehicle, left in a public parking lot
outside the arena. And Canada's top secrets vanished into the
night.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has launched an internal investigation of the
analyst, who remains at work. Her name was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Several days after the theft, and apparently at the urgent
behest of the spy agency, Toronto police launched a manhunt in
mid-October, and apprehended a trio of ``druggies.'' According to
the Globe and Mail newspaper, which broke the story, the three
substance abusers admitted stealing the briefcase, but said they'd
been so disappointed with the haul they'd simply tossed the
briefcase _ and its ultra-classified contents _ into a dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, none could remember the exact location of the
dumpster. The thieves led detectives to several bins. All were
found to be empty; and the best hope now for Canada's spymasters is
that the stolen secrets are simply rotting in some landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the material to be irretrievably lost,'' said Dan
Lambert, spokesman for the spy agency.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the agency has come under attack from politicians,
editorialists and other critics for allegedly seeking to conceal
the blunder, or at least not reporting it to the federal
intelligence watchdog committee with much alacrity _ the committee
learned of the loss from press reports.
</P>
<P>
   The material, which the agency describes only as an
``operational planning document,'' is believed to outline
counterintelligence and counterterrorism priorities, including
codenames of targets and informants.
</P>
<P>
   The Intelligence Service conceded in a statement: ``We consider
the loss of this document to be a serious matter of national
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are calling it the most damaging internal security breach
since the Canadian Security Intelligence Service was founded in
1984. It was the country's first fulltime professional spy agency.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence analysts said the worst fallout may be damage done
to the service's reputation among Britain's MI-6 and the CIA, which
shares much sensitive material with its northern ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be noted, and remembered, in Washington and
London. For Canada, that's the real problem,'' said Wesley K. Wark,
professor of history at the University of Toronto and president of
the Canadian Association for Security and Intelligence Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada has always had a `holier-than-thou' attitude about its
ability to protect secrets,'' Wark said. ``In order to share with
important allies it must convince them it remains cautious and
secure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
