<SLUG> BC-CPT-Y2K-MOVIE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K MOVIE NOT REALISTIC, BUT A HEALTHY SCARE, EXPERTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By MARILYN GEEWAX  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Y2K: The Movie'' is an ``irresponsible'' spark
that could light a panic among many Americans. But it also could do
some good if it leads people to take sensible precautions for Jan.
1 computer glitches.
</P>
<P>
   That was the split verdict among a dozen government and industry
officials who gathered with a reporter this week to watch a preview
copy of the NBC suspense-thriller, which airs at 9 p.m. EST Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In two hours, the movie manages to hit virtually every Y2K panic
button, from planes falling from the sky to nuclear reactors
melting down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very irresponsible,'' said Delta Air Lines Captain Bill
Watts, a Y2K expert and pilot who plans to be flying Dec. 31 during
the rollover to 2000. After scribbling two pages of notes on the
technical inaccuracies in the movie, Watts declared the
aviation-related plot twists ``comical.''
</P>
<P>
   John Castagna, a spokesman for the Edison Electric Institute, a
trade group for power companies, said the movie will ``reinforce
beliefs'' among those who think Y2K will be a disaster, even though
the power outages portrayed in the movie are ``very, very
unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Horn, R-Calif., chairman of the House subcommittee
that studies Y2K, agreed that the script contains many implausible
scenarios, but said the movie could be ``very useful'' if it spurs
people to prepare for Y2K now, rather than at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   If too many people ignore Y2K until late December, they might
start a New Year's Eve panic at the grocery store and bank, as they
do in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those things could happen,'' Horn said. His
subcommittee has long urged people to stock up on enough food,
water, batteries, blankets and prescriptions to last through
several days of Y2K-related disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   The movie depicts chaos spreading across the globe as the new
year moves from one time zone to the next. As midnight passes from
Asia to Europe, all sorts of computer-controlled equipment begins
to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Parisians panic as the City of Light goes dark. When 2000
arrives at New York's Times Square, throngs riot as the electric
power grid collapses along the Eastern Seaboard. Grocery stores
start rationing food and ATMs refuse to dispense cash.
</P>
<P>
   Before the long night is over, federal troops shoot and kill an
innocent man protecting his property and millions are ordered to
evacuate their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The movie stars Ken Olin, who plays a systems-failure expert
working for the federal government. The plot revolves around his
efforts to get planes out the air and water into an overheating
nuclear reactor.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the movie, alarms sound, things blow up and people
die, but the trouble-shooter stays calm. Meanwhile, Olin's wife,
children and father must wait for their hero to save the world and
get home.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with big-budget movies, the special effects seem
cheesy. Still, with an explosion of some sort between every set of
commercials, action-movie fans will find something to like.
</P>
<P>
   A disclaimer at the movie's start says it is not based on fact.
But concerns are very real about the Y2K bug, a software flaw that
exists because many older computer programs and chips recognize
only the last two digits of the year. When 2000 arrives on Jan. 1,
those computers may misinterpret ``00'' as 1900 and trigger massive
equipment malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's capital, government and industry representatives
have spent two years monitoring efforts to fix computers, and last
week, President Clinton said the nation's basic infrastructure
would work well throughout the date rollover.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
