<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-AUCTIONS-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: CLICKING ONTO REAL-ESTATE AUCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Real-estate auctions have found their way to the
computer screen in the hands of several auction companies, amid
some skepticism in the industry over the extent to which
computerized auctions are likely to replace traditional auction
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential is gigantic even if just 15 percent of real
estate is sold over the Web,'' said Kevin Hickey, president of
Homebid.com (www.homebid.com), an Internet real-estate auction
company based in Scottsdale, Ariz., that specializes in residential
property.
</P>
<P>
   Homebid.com is not alone. Other Internet real-estate auctioneers
include R-buy.com (www.rbuy.com), a World Wide Web site based in
Denver that offers commercial and residential property. Another is
eProperty (www.eproperty.com), a Web site owned by Kennedy-Wilson
International, a real-estate company in Beverly Hills, Calif., that
offers commercial and residential property.
</P>
<P>
   But the process is less than a year old, and Internet
auctioneers say that so far only about 200 properties _ almost all
of them homes and condominium apartments offered individually
rather than in packages of properties _ have actually been
transferred to new buyers after being auctioned online.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those sales were in January from a single auction of
property around Hartford, Conn., owned by the federal Department of
Housing. In that auction, Homebid.com offered 148 homes and
apartment buildings in individual lots. A nearly even mix of
families and investors eventually closed on 109 of the properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just as exciting as being at a real auction,'' said
Tracy Ogrodnik, an accountant from Durham, Conn., who, with her
husband, Walter, were the top bidders at $30,000 for a federally
owned town house in Meriden, Conn., 30 miles south of Hartford. The
Ogrodniks are investors who took title to the house in January,
upgraded it, and resold for $55,000 in May to a buyer who moved in.
</P>
<P>
   The Ogrodniks have previously bought houses at traditional
ballroom auctions. ``But this was better because you could be sure
what the bids were,'' Mrs. Ogrodnik said. ``There wasn't any noise
and you didn't have to drive far or deal with a room jammed full of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In an online auction, potential buyers bid on property from
their home or office computers. The auction takes place within a
specific time, sometimes as long as a few days, and all the bidders
are electronically informed by the auctioneer about what others'
bids are. The bidders do not see whom they are bidding against.
</P>
<P>
   To become approved as a bidder, the participant must first
register on the Web site by disclosing such information as name,
Social Security number and real estate agent, required for all
bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Payment for the auction service will eventually come from the
agent's commission if there is a sale, and there will be no charge
if there is no sale. The fee can range from .50 percent of a
property's sale price for a simple auction to nearly 6 percent in
cases when the auctioneer also acts as a broker.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of Internet auctions say that they hope to create
greater interest in homes, land and commercial buildings by making
bidding more convenient. But some real-estate consultants question
whether online auctions have a large enough appeal to be successful
and say that in some cases property may be more profitably sold by
traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that you would be hard-pressed to see a deep use of
the Internet for resale homes, because it is such a personal
sale,'' said Richard Gollis, cofounder of Concord Group, a
real-estate consulting company in Newport Beach, Calif. But
compared with traditional real-estate auctions, they may have the
advantage of generating more offers, which can be especially
desirable for sellers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants also say that buyers might fear that some of the
bidding is fraudulent and designed merely to push prices up,
although they note that this would require the cooperation of the
real estate agent and could be punished by law. Participants in the
auction must judge for themselves whether the auction companies
through which they are doing business provide enough safeguards to
ensure that there is no fraud, the consultants say.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several traditional real-estate auctioneers _ among them Ayres
Auction and Real Estate, based in Jacksboro Pike, Tenn., and Hudson
&AMP; Marshall, of Macon, Ga. _ have not started online sales, though
they do not rule out Internet service in the future. ``It's the
next natural step,'' said Monte Marshall, owner of Hudson &AMP;
Marshall. ``The problem is that people are a little leery of it,
and in most cases it would take some time for them to get
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The real-estate auction _ whether online or in a room _ differs
from conventional auctions in that the buyer does not immediately
pay and walk away with the product. The winning bidder and seller
must get in contact through their real estate agents to arrange the
signing of bank, real estate and title documents that are subject
to the usual problems that may ultimately kill a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Homebid.com, the only company to have a substantial number of
sales, said that nearly 80 percent of its winning bidders actually
closed the deal in the end. Those houses sold for an average of 98
percent of their estimated value, Homebid.com said. The company has
auctioned nearly 650 properties on line, most of them detached
homes or town houses, leading to about 150 closings, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two residential auctions held by Homebid.com in Phoenix and Las
Vegas in June and July, mostly for homes in those areas, were
relatively slow. Only 65 out of about 500 properties offered
eventually sold. Hickey, Homebid.com's president, said that this
indicated that buyers of private homes preferred the greater
latitude they have in traditional negotiations with sellers. As a
result, he has adjusted the company's Web site to allow for longer
bidding periods and sealed online bidding, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the property being auctioned, good deals may be
difficult to find, said Matt Shanaberger, vice president for Robert
Charles Lesser &AMP; Co., a real-estate consulting company in Los
Angeles that has no ties to online real-estate auctions. He expects
bids to stay near market levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You aren't going to see a $125,000 house going for $250,000 or
the other way around,'' Shanaberger said. ``There's not going to be
a huge spread in prices. There are far too many experienced
players.'' Shanaberger also said that it remained to be seen
whether there were enough people willing to bid via computer to
keep the industry alive.
</P>
<P>
   Selling property on the Internet is not necessarily new. For
example, property owners have offered land and houses for sale on
eBay.com (www.ebay.com), an all-purpose auction site, for the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
   But real-estate consultants say that Web sites with such a wide
scope are risky to use for such large transactions as real estate
because it is difficult to know whether the buyers or sellers are
just teen-agers having some fun.
</P>
<P>
   While there are no safeguards against this, they said that most
of the Web sites that specialize in real estate at least have the
backing of companies that have been in the real-estate industry for
several years. ``We're not some new cyberspace company,'' said
James Peterson, president of eProperty, the commercial property and
residential estate auction Web site. ``We have years of
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But many real-estate auction companies remain cautious about
launching Internet-only auctions. Steve Good, chief executive
officer of Sheldon Good International, a real-estate auction
company based in Chicago, said some bidders preferred to attend
auctions in person to gauge their competitors by looking at the
``whites of their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   That is partly why Good's company continues to offer auctions
that bidders can attend in person. But in September, his company
for the first time allowed people to bid in those auctions via
computer. ``Where online auctions are going, I don't know,'' Good
said. ``But we haven't had any resistance so far.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-13-99 1809EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
