<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3813 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-REASONS-BOS &LR;      11-18 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REASONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING SENSE OF A BROTHER'S MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A BOOK OF REASONS 
By John Vernon 
Houghton Mifflin, 272 pp., $23 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When elegant prose describes disgusting things, readers are
caught in the middle. The lyricism of the writing compels one to
continue even as the subject matter repels, and the tension becomes
a third element that traps readers in a kind of morbid fascination.
Such is the case with John Vernon's ``A Book of Reasons,'' a
beautiful, horrible book that _ like that tension _ keeps circling
around its subject, unresolved and uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   The subject that has so bewitched Vernon, a novelist, is his
brother's life. A recluse, seemingly incapable of forming lasting
relationships, Paul Vernon lived his final years in a run-down old
house in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   As this memoir opens, after Paul's death, his brother is heading
toward the house to clean it up and sell it _ and, ideally, come to
terms with the strange and lonely man his brother was at life's
end. What he finds confounds his imaginings of what any person,
particularly a once-beloved brother, could become. The house is
unheated, broken down, and filthy beyond belief; its very walls
reeking with the human and animal excrement and animal corpses
within. Although John Vernon allows that he has drifted from his
brother, he cannot get his mind around the idea that the boy he
remembers and the man he used to know could have lived like this.
</P>
<P>
   At first, John Vernon wants to believe the filth has been left
by vandals since his brother's death, but he soon dismisses this
excuse as fantasy: The debris is too deep and too old. But that top
layer of denial, like the first load of trash, is only a start, and
this book is Vernon's intellectual excavation. Unfortunately, in
his search for answers _ the ``reasons'' of the title _ what he
primarily unearths are more questions.
</P>
<P>
   In his four novels, Vernon has used his writing to explore, if
not explain, the lives of historical figures, including Baby Doe
Tabor and the explorer Robert Cavelier de La Salle. In this, his
first nonfiction book, the author seems compelled to do the same.
The result, while frustrating, is often fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   To make sense of his brother's apparent madness, Vernon reaches
out to the great thinkers of the past, evoking the reasons of
history and philosophy to explain his unreasonable relative. A
visit to Wal-Mart becomes a religious experience, for example, as
the search for the perfect thermometer (which, he convinces
himself, will make Paul's wreck of a house appear normal) turns
into a quest for truth. Descartes, Pascal, Cardinal Richelieu, and
Samuel Beckett all end up joining the shopping expedition, though
Vernon has the sense to keep them in perspective with a healthy
disrespect for both his own philosophizing and our much less
intellectual time: ``In the twenty-first century we'll hold up
happy faces to ward off vampires,'' he writes, reflecting on
contemporary iconage.
</P>
<P>
   Recollections of Paul's funeral bring out Goethe, Lincoln, and
Tod Browning's cult film classic ``Freaks,'' which climaxes with
the circus sideshow acts chanting: ``One of us, one of us,
ooga-booga, one of us.'' And when philosophy falls short, the
history of science comes into play: We may not learn why Paul's
house lacked an outdoor thermometer, but we learn of the simple
tool's invention and the religious controversy it caused.
</P>
<P>
   These historical flights, however, do not serve as adequate
escapes, the excavation unearths no explanatory truth, and Vernon
keeps returning _ and returning us _ to his brother's house, where
there is no reason or poetry or science. Veering like his prose
between the reasonable past and the unpalatable present, the author
himself appears to be trapped. Unable to accept the lack of reason
in his brother's life, the sheer randomness of decay or illness, he
worries at it the way he worries at the house, ineptly building
stairs and haphazardly hiring cleaning and disposal crews who steal
as much as they discard.
</P>
<P>
   He seems aware of his dilemma, writing: ``Reasons are not
answers. Reasons are recipes for making sense of the world's
arrangements and accidents.'' However, we are stuck watching the
novelist in thrall to this most futile, and common, endeavor of
healthy relatives of the mentally ill: that of trying to understand
the irrational behavior of his brother in rational terms.
</P>
<P>
   By our nature, we seek to understand that which we do not,
Vernon says over and over in a variety of guises. We have always
sought out the logic behind the natural world's workings. But in
this case, no matter how far back Vernon reaches into history or
scientific theory he can find no causal link, no logic. Which
leaves him, and us, without resolution. When the author drives back
to his wife, his thumb swollen from his inept hammering, he may
have come to terms with the histories of science and religion, but
not with his brother. His acceptance is uneasy at best, and leaves
us as we last see him: sleepless, beguiled, and a little afraid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
