<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-UNIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RE&AMP;C NOT FOR SALE, CHIEF SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some on Wall Street believe a quick fix for Raytheon Co.'s
ongoing cash crunch would be to sell its relatively obscure
engineers &AMP; constructors division.
</P>
<P>
   But Raytheon says it is not seeking a buyer for the heavy
industrial design and construction unit known as RE&AMP;C, which has
been losing money. Instead, Shay Assad, the division's new chief
executive, says RE&AMP;C is in the midst of a turnaround and should
make a profit next year on revenue of around $2.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Assad wouldn't rule out a sale of his
division. But he insists the unit is back on track after red ink
last year and so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to see the fruits of what we set out to do,''
Assad said.
</P>
<P>
   The unit, part of Lexington, Mass.-based Raytheon since the
1960s, specializes in big projects such as power plants,
refineries, and demilitarization facilities for chemical weapons.
Last year its work produced about 10 percent of the beleaguered
defense contractor's revenue of about $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But RE&AMP;C's work seems to offer few synergies with Raytheon's
better-known bomb and missile lines, and many analysts believe a
sale would help Raytheon focus on that core military business.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that if they get the right price, they'll sell
(RE&AMP;C),'' said Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette analyst Joe Nadol.
</P>
<P>
   Into this picture last year marched Assad, a 21-year Raytheon
veteran. Since then Assad says he has made the unit more selective
in bidding on construction contracts.
</P>
<P>
   He's shifted or replaced 28 of the 35 top executives at RE&AMP;C,
and brought in veterans from rivals such as Fluor Corp. to oversee
human resources, procurement, and other functions.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has also scaled back RE&AMP;C's ambitions overseas, where it
once dreamed of making big profits building dams and power plants
that could be floated into harbors on barges.
</P>
<P>
   He calls many such projects too risky, and instead touts work
such as the $1.1 billion, three-year contract RE&AMP;C announced last
week from Sithe Energies Inc. to build power plants in Everett and
Weymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Next year Assad expects RE&AMP;C to earn about 75 percent of its
revenue from domestic work, compared with 60 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sithe vice president John O'Brien won't say whether Raytheon's
bid to build the plants was lower than those from competitors such
as Stone &AMP; Webster Inc., but says he isn't concerned by talk of a
possible sale of RE&AMP;C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are a lot of talented individuals'' at RE&AMP;C who
could complete projects even under a new owner, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to spin off RE&AMP;C have dogged Raytheon ever since it bulked
up the business line early in the 1990s. The division has drawn
special scrutiny as a spinoff candidate lately because of
lower-than-expected profit margins at Raytheon's defense units,
sending shares of the parent company tumbling more than 50 percent
since July.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Raytheon chief executive Daniel Burnham has
authorized companywide layoffs and a broad restructuring in which
he apparently considers everything on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham is cryptic about his intentions for RE&AMP;C. ``The first
priority for Raytheon Engineers &AMP; Constructors is to fix the
business,'' he said through a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But in an industry known for price competition, Assad insists he
can still improve RE&AMP;C's prospects despite losses this year and
last, with better service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got ourselves in trouble when we were building plants and
facilities in parts of the world we weren't familiar with,'' Assad
said. ``It's a lot easier to solve problems when the project team
is in Cambridge and the plant is in Everett, vs. when the plant is
in the middle of India and eight hours away from the nearest
airport.
</P>
<P>
   RE&AMP;C's renewed domestic focus comes amid a boom in building
gas-fired power plants in the United States, helping position the
company to increase revenue 31 percent to about $2.7 billion this
year, from $2.065 billion in 1998. Assad said he expects revenue in
2000 will be within 5 percent of 1999 sales.
</P>
<P>
   RE&AMP;C has promised recoveries before, however, only to fall
short. For the first nine months of this year it lost $65 million,
primarily related to delays at four overseas projects Assad calls
``the bane of my existence.''
</P>
<P>
   These include problems at power projects in Britain, India and
Thailand, and at a metals facility in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Assad wouldn't be more specific, but says the rest of the
company's roughly 40 other big projects are on track. The company
employs about 8,000 people worldwide, down from 9,800 at the start
of 1998 after layoffs, buyouts and divestitures.
</P>
<P>
   A Fall River native, Assad was named to head RE&AMP;C last year to
replace Charles Q. Miller, who quit as the company was disclosing
layoffs last year.
</P>
<P>
   Assad is perhaps best known within Raytheon for negotiating a
$1.3 billion deal with Brazil to build a monitoring system in the
Amazon basin, a contract finalized in 1997. He is familiar with
RE&AMP;C operations as well, having spent 18 months in the unit's
Denver office overseeing work on a rocket launch tower.
</P>
<P>
   RE&AMP;C now has about 840 people in Denver and major offices at
Princeton, N.J. and in Birmingham, Ala. In Cambridge, the company
has about 300 people at a Kendall Square facility known as the
Badger building after a predecessor company, a facility that
employed 1,700 at its peak in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   So is Raytheon shopping RE&AMP;C around? ``There's no truth'' to
that idea, Assad said. Even if the division were to be sold
eventually, a buyer might want to keep RE&AMP;C intact because of its
reputation. ``If it was sold, it's not like it's going to be broken
apart and disintegrate,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
