<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE OF TWO MARKETS AND THEIR WIDENING GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've got two stock markets at the moment: a broader market that
is doing OK and a technology market that is doing spectacularly.
The gap between the two gets bigger every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The polarization is more extreme than anything we have ever
seen,'' says Thomas O'Neill, chief investment officer at
FleetBoston Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence for the gap shows up practically everywhere you look.
Consider: The average mutual fund is up 15 percent this year,
according to Lipper Analytical Services. The average science and
technology fund is up 76 percent. The Nasdaq index, home to all the
big technology stocks, is up 50 percent for the year compared to a
gain of 15 percent for the broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   The story is much the same closer to home. In April, EMC Corp.,
a Hopkinton maker of storage equipment, passed Gillette to become
the Massachusetts company with the greatest market value. It was a
symbolic changing of the guard, the new economy supplanting the
old.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, EMC was worth $85 billion and Gillette was
worth $37 billion _ a spread of better than two to one.
</P>
<P>
   Can the new world really be that much greater than the old one
or is the growing gap in valuation a sign of a market that has gone
bonkers?
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, quite a few money managers and economists say
there is a method to the market's madness. While they concede that
there are plenty of signs of excess in technology investing, they
say there are also fundamental reasons for the triumph of the tech
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Like what? The bulls point to three things. They include:
</P>
<P>
   --The tremendous growth in high-tech earnings. According to Syl
Marquardt, research director at John Hancock Funds, the technology
firms in the S&AMP;P 500 will boost their earnings by 40 percent this
year. Earnings for the 500 companies overall will grow 17 percent.
Although it is true that the tech sector sells at a higher
price-to-earnings ratio than the market overall, that price premium
looks more reasonable when future earnings growth is figured in,
says Marquardt.
</P>
<P>
   --The US economy is hooked on technology. America is in the
midst of a capital spending boom that shows no sign of ending.
Business spending on information equipment and software has been
growing at a 16 percent annual clip since 1991, according to Mark
Zandi, chief economist at RFA Dismal Sciences, a Pennsylvania
forecasting firm. Corporate America is buying computers,
telecommunications gear, and the software and the services that
come along with them.
</P>
<P>
   --The rest of the world is playing catchup. Technology is not a
fad that countries can choose to ignore. It is an imperative.
``Everyone else is going to have to substitute technology for labor
if they want to stay competitive,'' says Allen Sinai, chief
economist for Primark Decision Economics in Waltham. In other
words, other countries will have to hike their spending on
computers, telecommunications gear, and software, and chances are,
much of it will be supplied by American high-tech firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going on is real,'' says Zandi, who in the next breath
adds, ``but some of it is also surreal.'' The surreal parts are the
incredible prices that many technology stocks have reached,
especially the start-ups with no track record. Yet even some of the
established tech companies sell at price-to-earnings ratios that
can cause noosebleeds.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, whose stock seems to go up every day, trades at a
p/e ratio of 101; the comparable number for EMC is 81. The entire
market trades at a ratio of just over 30. The higher the ratio the
greater the expectation of future profits. ``These prices don't
leave much room for a slowdown,'' says Marquardt of Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   A slowdown could come as a result of a weaker US economy, a
distinct possibility in the coming year. It could also come if
technology buyers decide to pause and digest all their old
purchases before buying new stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas O'Neill thinks there could be a technology correction
even without any change in fundamentals. He points out that there
have been other technology booms in the past _ the personal
computer boom of the early 1980s was a famous one _ and that booms
have a way of ending in busts.
</P>
<P>
   The technology doesn't go away, but only a few of the companies
will survive and thrive. ``This thing will end badly for the vast
majority of stocks,'' he warns.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill calls the current infatuation with tech stocks a mania
and describes the current valuations as mindboggling. Says O'Neill,
``I can't remember a time when the pendulum has swung so far to
excess.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he right? Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Goldman Sachs speaks, people listen.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in CMGI, the Andover, Mass. Internet company, climbed 20
percent Wednesday after Goldman Sachs initiated coverage of the
company with a strong recommendation. The stock also got a boost
from a Prudential Securities analyst who raised his price forecast
on CMGI.
</P>
<P>
   The stock climbed 20 7/8 to 124.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI has provided financing for a slew of Internet companies
including Lycos, a portal, and GeoCities, a Web page hosting
service. GeoCities was bought by Yahoo earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's stock price jump made CMGI chief executive David
Wetherell about $300 million richer. Even in the world of the
Internet that qualifies as a good day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
