<SLUG> BC-CPT-IBM-MAINFRAME-Y2K-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K-OK, Y2K-NOT OK: START-UP GETS ATTENTION WITH LAST-MINUTE 
OFFER
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yawns might have seemed the likely response last week when a
small Silicon Valley start-up, Y2K-OK LLC, introduced a new tool
for diagnosing and fixing Year 2000 computer problems on popular
IBM mainframe and midrange computers.
</P>
<P>
   After all, experts have been warning corporate and government
clients for years that there are no silver-bullet solutions to Year
2000 problems. And recently, they have been advising businesses to
concentrate on contingency plans for working around breakdowns
rather than searching for last-minute fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most established players are struggling for attention.
One vendor, CCD Online Systems, recently pledged to donate $50,000
to charity if its software failed to uncover at least 50
significant errors in each million lines of code that the Internal
Revenue Service or other major computer users had already repaired.
There have been no takers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, surprisingly, the fledgling Y2K-OK is causing a stir. The
company, based in Campbell, Calif., said that more than 20,000
visitors showed up at its Web site last week in the first three
days after the product was announced. More than 100 visitors, from
Singapore to the nearby San Jose police department, downloaded a
free version that performs a limited audit of a system's readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our salesmen have a ton of leads,'' said Albert P. McBride,
the company's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Free samples of products often attract a crowd, of course, but
Y2K-OK might still have gone unnoticed were it not for its
pedigree. The tool is the brainchild of Willard H. Wattenburg, a
63-year-old inventor, computer scientist and radio talk show host
with a reputation for iconoclastic brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-OK's story is a severe test of the proverb ``Better late
than never,'' akin to opening a toy store on Christmas Eve.
Successful or not, it will go down as one of the more colorful
tales in Year 2000 product lore.
</P>
<P>
   Wattenburg, often called Dr. Bill or Wild Bill by those who know
him, has spent the bulk of his professional life in computer and
nuclear weapons work. But he particularly enjoys developing simple
solutions to complex problems, as when he persuaded California
highway engineers to use surplus railroad flatcars as temporary
replacements for bridges destroyed in California earthquakes to
quickly restore traffic.
</P>
<P>
   His patents include one of the first home smoke alarms, and he
has played bit roles in two Clint Eastwood movies. One devoted fan
of his radio show tracks his life and exploits at www.drbill.org.
</P>
<P>
   Wattenburg is currently an adjunct professor at Chico State
University in Chico, Calif., but he is more widely known for his
Saturday and Sunday night call-in shows on KGO radio in San
Francisco. He said he had little interest in Year 2000 issues until
late 1998, when he was recruited to help rescue a Defense
Department computer program riddled with date problems that would
hit as soon as 1999 began.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other entrepreneurs in recent years, Wattenburg became
convinced that the world needed a fully automated fix for the
problem. He decided to focus on how computers interpret programs'
instructions rather than on the programs themselves.
</P>
<P>
   He started by developing a method to get an IBM 390, one of the
most widely used mainframes, to treat calculations involving
numbers (including dates) as invalid operations. He envisioned that
the invalid result could be made to trip a program that would
convert the numbers to a different math system for execution _ a
system in which Year 2000 date confusion would be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The math was a numbering system that IBM and Allstate had first
applied to Year 2000 repairs in 1997 but were never able to
popularize.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge with the Year 2000 problem is that for decades,
programmers used only two digits to express years. The century was
always assumed to be 19. Thus, 62 stood for 1962, 96 for 1996. When
2000 arrives, however, the two zeros will be interpreted as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   The Allstate system, known as the A0 system, borrows extra
numerals from the Base 16, or hexadecimal, numbering system, which
uses the letters A through F to represent the numbers 10 through
15, so that 10 in hexadecimal is 16.
</P>
<P>
   A standard hexadecimal system would not work in this case
because, for one thing, years previously entered in a database
would have the wrong values. In Base 16, for example, 99 represents
159, and the next number is A0, which represents 160.
</P>
<P>
   But by borrowing the use of A through F for just the 10's column
and keeping the standard zero through nine in the ones column, the
A0 system can delay a turnover to 00 for 59 years.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate's approach had limitations that led Wattenburg to
develop his own variation on A0 math and new rules for how to
calculate with it. His system can only handle dates until 2049, 10
years fewer than Allstate's approach, but it has extra room for
control sequences that, he says, make it possible to automate more
Year 2000 work.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his early version was not persuasive enough for the
journal Science to agree to publish it. Nor was it ready for
market. For example, it lacked the coding to convert the Wattenburg
math back to decimal numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Wattenburg was ready to give up by February when McBride's wife
heard him mention his Year 2000 work on radio and suggested that
McBride might be able to develop the tool further.
</P>
<P>
   The two men knew each other from McBride's days as a graduate
student at the University of California, when Wattenburg had been
his thesis adviser. McBride was intrigued by the challenge of
fleshing out Wattenburg's vision.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was willing to lend the team computer time at a Bay Area
facility but told Wattenburg it was too late to get computer users
to try anything new. IBM, Microsoft, Intel and others all declined
to finance the project.
</P>
<P>
   But William N. Joy, co-founder and chief scientist of Sun
Microsystems, was impressed and quickly arranged for Sun to provide
an undisclosed development grant on condition that Y2K-OK make a
free version of the product available to small businesses that
might be starting late on their Year 2000 work.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Sun nor IBM has endorsed the tool released this week.
But Steven Carre, an IBM executive who works on Year 2000 solutions
told The San Jose Mercury News, ``I wish all my customers who are
not ready would call Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Carre said he did not expect many to make that call. The history
of other tools suggests that those who do make their way to the
company's site (www.y2k0k-solution.com) may end up discouraged by
the pricing for the full package or by the tool's limitations.
</P>
<P>
   The most important limitation is that computer users may be
exposing themselves to new problems if databases converted to
Wattenburg numbers are sharing information with programs that have
not been converted.
</P>
<P>
   And the Y2K-OK tool currently works only for Cobol programs on
the IBM 390 and its clones, and for Cobol and RPG programs on IBM
AS400 midrange computers and their clones.
</P>
<P>
   Even Wattenburg wonders how many people will be willing to
experiment with his tool with fewer than than 50 days until the
Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al and his team did a great job,'' he said. ``It's just too
bad we couldn't have been ready sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-14-99 1706EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
