<HEADLINE>
BECOMING A `MILLIONAIRE' NEVER SO EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody has an explanation for the runaway popularity of ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' Vicarious greed. The irresistible lure
of gambling. The thrill of rooting for the contestants. The novelty
of the format to viewers too young to remember the quiz show
scandals of the 1950s. The ageless charm of host Regis Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   Its attractions may be debatable, but there's no argument that
the ABC show is huge hit, averaging more than 23 million viewers
every time it's on, outdistancing all competition, even, last
Thursday, the ever-popular ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   My own theory is that people are drawn in droves to the show
because it allows them to feel intellectually superior to the
morons who try and fail to answer the idiotic questions. Many of
the multiple-choice questions on ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire''
are almost unbelievably simple-minded, on a par with Groucho's
favorite, ``Who's buried in Grant's Tomb?'' All in all, the show
makes the average ``Jeopardy'' seem like a Mensa test by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a typical question from a recent show: ``What did the
character Little Bo Peep lose? a) mittens b) pigs c) sheep d)
flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, that one occurred in a lower prize-money range, but the
questions don't get a lot tougher as the stakes soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' has been criticized for not having a better
demographic mix of contestants. Of the first 60, 50 were white
males. The producers blame the lack of diversity on a ``blind''
screening process in which people call a toll-free number and
answer a series of trivia questions. It seems only fair that women
and minorities should have the same opportunity as white guys to
answer stupid questions for big money. They sure couldn't do any
worse than some of the contestants have done to date.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night's show, one contestant flamed out at the
$32,000 level because he couldn't pick the name of the composer of
the ``Blue Danube'' waltz. Another had to call a friend for help _
that's allowed _ answering a $32,000 question about where ``author
Henry David Thoreau lived for two years in a hut.'' Lake George? I
don't think so. Luckily for him his friend was able to give him the
correct answer.
</P>
<P>
   One contestant couldn't identify the famous American primitive
artist who didn't start painting until she was in her 70s. Maybe
Georgia O'Keefe? He asked Regis to poll the audience, another of
the show's innovations. One-third of them also thought it was
O'Keefe. Goodbye $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the questions become more challenging as the prize money
approaches the highest levels. The million-dollar question may be
posed in Sanskrit for all I know. Thus far, no contestant has won
more than $500,000. The highest-level question I can recall,
$125,000, involved the number of arms on a squid. It's not in the
Bo-Peep category, but it's not that difficult. Of course that's
easy for me to say because a) for some strange reason (Miss
Mahoney's biology class?) I happen to know the answer, and b) I'm
not sitting in the hot seat with Philbin boring in, asking, ``Is
that your final answer?'' According to a story in the current
People magazine, the show's producers encourage Philbin to heighten
the tension to make contestants sweat. He does a masterful job of
tormenting his victims, but he's been practicing for years on
Kathie Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Millionaire'' has already inspired one Fox
knock-off titled, with brilliant simplicity, ``Greed.'' According
to a Los Angeles Times story, other networks and syndicators are
considering developing quiz programs, including one called ``Who
Wants to Marry a Millionaire?'' in which women would compete for
the attentions of wealthy men. Just what this competition might
involve is as yet unclear, but I'd guess it won't involve answering
questions about Little Bo-Peep. Although who knows?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
