<HEADLINE>
TICKETMASTER TRIES TO STIR THE PASSIONS OF EVENT-GOERS 
 HAND-HELD WIRELESS DATA GETS A FLAT-RATE TEST 
 A DEBIT CARD FOR STUDENTS, WITH OVERSIGHT FOR PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, people have gone to music stores to buy concert
tickets. Now Ticketmaster Online is putting a music store inside
its ticket shop.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday, Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch features the
``Ticketmaster Store,'' where users can buy more than 150,000
items, including CDs, apparel, videos and memorabilia about their
favorite artists.
</P>
<P>
   The move is the first significant e-commerce expansion for
Ticketmaster (www.ticketmaster.com), which until now has sold only
tickets and goods from local vendors through CitySearch's City
Auction service.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Sullivan, Ticketmaster Online's vice president of
e-commerce, called the store ``an absolutely natural fit for us.
When someone plops down $120 for tickets, they're indicating a
passion that's just about impossible to find in other product
categories.''
</P>
<P>
   The site will try to exploit that passion. First, it will divide
its merchandise into four product categories _ sports, arts,
theater and family. Shoppers can find autographed baseballs or team
jerseys in the sports category, for example, or buy a Monet poster
in the arts section.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, users will be shown various artist-related items as
they buy tickets, and if they register with the site, they can get
information e-mailed to them about performers, like concert
playlists and tour news. They can also pre-order CDs and videos.
</P>
<P>
   Digital music is also in the company's cross hairs. Sullivan
said that the site will soon test different digital music systems,
with an introduction planned for next year. In addition,
Ticketmaster will integrate the store with the CitySearch
offerings, he said, ``so someone can buy tickets, get a CD, book
dinner and make a hotel reservation from one place.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Tedeschi
</P>
<P>
   Hand-held Wireless Data Gets a Flat-Rate Test
</P>
<P>
   A spinoff of 3Com Corp.'s Palm Computing division plans to say
Monday that it will test a flat-rate wireless service offering
nationwide access to the Internet and electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
   OmniSky Corp., which is based in Palo Alto, Calif., will in
partnership with AT&AMP;T offer a small radio modem that attaches to
Palm V hand-held computers. The company said it would begin a test
program in December for 5,000 users of the popular hand-held
digital organizer. At the end of March, it plans to follow with
commercial service for a flat monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   The new service is based on AT&AMP;T Wireless Services' Cellular
Digital Packet Data network, or CDPD, and is intended to offer a
similar range of services now provided by the Palm's wireless Palm
VII hand-held computer and a growing range of pagers and cell
phones connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those plans, though, have been criticized because they
are priced on a usage basis that charges by the amount of data, in
bytes, the user sends or receives. That plan has proved unpopular
with the Palm VII: consumers have had difficulties estimating how
many bytes they consume in any given month, and corporate users
complain that it makes budgeting for wireless use of the Palm VII
almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The new service will be free during the company's four-month
test period after the 5,000 Palm users purchase a $299 modem. The
company said it had not yet determined the monthly price but said
it would be less than $50 and could possibly be as low as $30 for
regional service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about real Internet access,'' said Patrick McVeigh,
chief executive of OmniSky. ``A lot of people have tried this in
the past, but we believe we've hit on the right value
proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobile wireless data devices have long been an object of desire
in the industry, but have been slow to take off. Companies like
Radiomail and Wynd Communications stumbled in the early 1990s, when
broad consumer demand for ``e-mail on the go'' never developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good first step,'' said Andrew Seybold, publisher of
Andrew Seybold's Outlook, an industry newsletter on mobile
computing. ``Flat-rate pricing is the right model.''
</P>
<P>
   OmniSky was formed in June of this year by executives from 3Com
and Infoseek; it has financing from 3Com and Aether Systems, a
maker of wireless Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Markoff
</P>
<P>
   A Debit Card for Students, With Oversight for Parents
</P>
<P>
   A new type of Visa card allows students to shop until their
parents say drop. Called the PocketCard, it carries the Visa label
and is used like any other credit card. But it is technically a
debit card, financed and guaranteed by a ``sponsor,'' like a
parent, through an account set up on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The account must be tied to a checking or savings account, which
allows the card to be almost instantly replenished over the
telephone or with the click of a mouse. Transactions can also be
monitored as soon as they are made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I see as the most unique is the real-time access to
the transaction data,'' said Jeff Green, editor of Bank Network
News.
</P>
<P>
   The cards, which are available through www.pocketcard.com, are
geared toward people like parents or business owners who want to
give others money to work with but still want some control over the
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about a 13-year-old kid having this relationship where
she can have her own card with her name on it and the parents can
give her supervision and support,'' said Bill Scheurer, founder and
chief executive of PocketCard.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors must be at least 18 and card holders at least 13. There
is an annual fee of $15 for a family and $20 for a business. A
charge of 25 cents is levied on each transaction, including
deposits. The company also charges an ATM cash fee of $2 in
addition to whatever the host bank charges.
</P>
<P>
   Yvette Burgen, who lives near Detroit, got one for her
18-year-old son, Jason, after she drove 80 miles round trip to buy
him something he needed quickly at the University of Michigan. She
said the card was attractive because it provided some financial
flexibility without relying on credit, while at the same time
giving her some oversight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Whitaker
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-14-99 2047EST &QL;
</P>
