<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE VENTILATION MAY END MOISTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, November 21, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have condensation in my attic, where there is some
pressed-board flooring. Moisture seems to be coming up through the
pressed board. The insulation in my attic floor, under the pressed
board, is not wet, but there is no vapor barrier under it. I have a
ridge vent, and six soffit vents on each side of the house. What
can I do to get rid of what moisture is there? The bathroom fan
exhausts through one of those soffit vents.
</P>
<P>
   TOM FULGONI, Billerica, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That moisture on the pressed board is not coming up through
the pressed board, but is condensation of moisture already in the
attic. To get rid of it, I suggest adding more soffit vents (vents
on the underside of the roof overhang). To put in a vapor barrier
under the existing insulation is difficult, but this is not
necessary because the ceiling paint in the rooms below may form a
vapor barrier; or you can paint the ceilings with a vapor barrier
paint. BIN, a white-pigmented shellac, is a vapor barrier.
</P>
<P>
   While it's OK to exhaust the bathroom through a soffit vent,
make sure the duct carrying the air fits snugly in the vent; in
other words, you do not want the duct to just lie there in front of
the soffit vent; that would allow excess moisture into the attic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We own a house in Maine with asbestos siding. A company said
it would power-wash the siding to clean it. Is this acceptable?
</P>
<P>
   ELEANOR LAMBERTSON, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No. Power-washing asbestos-cement siding can release asbestos
fibers into the air. I don't think this is a federal or
state-by-state law, but power-washing that kind of siding should
not be done anywhere, any way. Asbestos-cement siding should not be
sanded, scraped, or anything else but washed with detergent and
water. When paint on the siding is peeling, it is particularly
unfortunate because the peeling cannot be safely removed, except by
washing, which is not very effective.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am filling the open stud walls on my house with insulation.
The walls are uneven so I am furring out the studs so the final
wall finish will, indeed, be even. With the new wall furred out a
little, the electric switches and outlet boxes will be indented.
How can I bring them flush with the wall? Incidentally, can I cover
the wires in the walls with insulation?
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD BODURTHA, Plymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can cover wires in the walls with insulation. You are not
supposed to cover exposed wires in the attic floor, but it is done
in thousands of houses throughout the country without serious ill
effects. The danger if you do that is that the wires, covered with
insulation, will overheat and cause a fire.
</P>
<P>
   To correct the mystery of the indented outlet boxes, relocate
them to the proper position, since the wall finish is off anyway.
Or, put spacers behind the bolts that hold the outlet or switch
fixtures to the boxes; this will bring them out even with the wall,
so they can be covered properly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I spend my winters in Florida, summers in Nova Scotia. When
visiting my daughter's house in Framingham recently, I noticed
yellow jackets had gotten into the walls. My daughter and
son-in-law are not doing anything about it. They are coming in
under a 4-foot-wide soffit. Shouldn't they do something? Might they
be boring holes in the studs or something?
</P>
<P>
   M.A., Florida/Nova Scotia
</P>
<P>
   A. Your family doesn't have to do anything because there is
nothing to do, if the critters stay in the walls. The yellow
jackets are wasps, and they will die out in winter after eating all
kinds of bugs all summer long. Your family could seal the soffit to
prevent further invasion and to make you feel better. The wasps are
not drilling holes in the studs because they don't do that sort of
thing. The insect that drills holes in wood is a carpenter bee, and
even she (females drill holes to store their eggs in) would drill
holes in siding or outside trim.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house was built in 1955, with a few towel racks that seem
to have been put up with library paste. One small member of my
family actually pulled it off. How can we reinstall it?
</P>
<P>
   BEVERLY BRULE, Northborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah, yes, the collapsing towel racks. In those halcyon days of
building, anything went, and usually collapsed. Towel racks, toilet
paper holders, and other fixtures were put up with grout, which did
not hold as well as the thin-set mortar of today. It's a wonder
your rack lasted as long as it did.
</P>
<P>
   To reinstall it, scrape the old grout off the brackets as well
as the wall on which the bracket was applied. Apply an adhesive
caulk to the fixture brackets. It comes in a caulking cartridge for
use in a caulking gun, so it is easily applied to the fixture.
</P>
<P>
   Press firmly, and hold onto it for several minutes for it to
set. Left alone, it will sag. You have to be there for five minutes
or so, keeping it in position. Once it sets, though, it will hold
very well. An alternative way: Do the same as above with thin-set
mortar, which you have to mix yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
