<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LANDSLIDE _ YET _ FOR E-VOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a few hours on Tuesday (Nov. 2), Helen Steverson had the
toughest job at the Lexington Street Fire Station in Cambridge,
Mass. She was assisting voters with the newfangled ballot box, a
super-high-tech innovation that left locals scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``They upgraded the system,'' Steverson explained. ``They
replaced the old machine with the crank.''
</P>
<P>
   The machine with the crank? It looks like Cambridge has made it
into the 20th century, with minutes to spare. Actually, the city
got rid of the old crank machines two years ago. But the rest of
the system is a relic of the Paper and Pencil Age. Here's the
drill: You give your address to a volunteer who crosses your name
off a computer printout. No one asks for identification, and the
list almost always includes names of neighbors who have moved or
passed away. You step behind the star-spangled curtain and fill in
little circles, like a standardized test. Easy enough. But what do
you do with the cardboard sleeve that says, ``Insert finger here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what that means,'' says Steverson. ``We confused
them good this year.'' At 79, the Cambridge native has been
volunteering at the polls for 24 years. She works alongside her
friend Ethel Odell, 78, and the two have become Election Day
fixtures at the fire station. ``It's a civic duty,'' says
Steverson. ``It's a community,'' adds Odell. ``I see people I
haven't seen all year.''
</P>
<P>
   So what do the experts think about voting on the Internet? ``It
will be a long time before it gets here,'' says Steverson.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe or maybe not. Voters in eight precincts in Iowa tested
voting on the Internet this week, and more than 85 percent of the
1,253 participants in the volunteer pilot project said they would
vote on line again, according to Iowa Secretary of State Chet
Culver. The program was run by a company called VoteHere.net;
naturally, the software developers will tell you that the future of
democracy (and their companies) depends on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? You can bank on line. You can buy (or learn to fix)
a kitchen sink. You buy a little red sportscar or fulfill other
little red fantasies. ``We need to do everything possible to
encourage participation in the democratic process,'' says Culver,
ticking off the depressing statistics. Voter turnout nationwide was
only 44.9 percent last year. Two million eligible voters between 18
and 24 are not voting. The US ranks 137th out of 167 democracies
when it comes to voter turnout. But if folks were allowed to click
and pick in their pajamas, the numbers might improve.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, security and privacy issues need to be ironed out.
There's also the question of the digital divide. Polling places
will always have to remain an option for people who do not own or
even use computers. But Iowa is testing the system again in
January, when high school students statewide will cast ballots in a
mock presidential caucus, and Culver predicts on-line voting will
be common in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that encourages folks to vote is a good thing. But at
the same time, the pundits and software peddlers should consider
what's lost in the name of progress. ``Voting should be a
quasi-religious experience,'' says Tracy Westen, president of the
California-based Democracy Network (www.dnet.org). ``It should be a
philosophical and ethical commitment, and the ceremonial aspects
are important. You go to the place, you see the flag, you walk into
the booth, you take your kids with you, and you hand in your
ballot. Those things are important.''
</P>
<P>
   And some day, they might disappear. Frankly, I'd choose on-line
voting over going to the polls any day (especially a stormy one).
But I'll miss the familiar walk to the fire station, the dodging
past the sign-holders and the hand-shakers, the fumbling with the
ballot. What are you supposed to do with that stupid ``Insert
finger here'' sleeve anyway? It's for privacy, Steverson says, but
it's OK if you ignore it. ``I'll be 80 soon,'' she adds, ``and this
might be my last year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Here's a new low, as seen on eBay: A greedy little
entrepreneur is auctioning the domain name, egyptair990.com, with
bids starting at $2,500. The seller, who goes by the tag keith786
and claims to be from Atlanta, didn't return e-mail messages. No
wonder. The speculator in other people's misery doesn't even own
the Web address. That privilege goes to Doug Desjardins, a
Washington attorney with the firm R. Jack Clapp and Associates.
Desjardins insists he has no intention of using the address for a
profit, and that he isn't selling it on eBay or anywhere else; he
says he gave the domain name to the families of victims of ValuJet
Flight 592 to set up an informational site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-11-99 1323EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
