<HEADLINE>
TOYS THAT DO _ AND DON'T _ MAKE THE GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the fifth consecutive year, Child Caring is publishing the
holiday toy list prepared by Teachers Resisting Unhealthy
Children's Entertainment (TRUCE).
</P>
<P>
   Many toy lists are published at this time of year. Some focus on
toys that are physically unsafe; others recommend toys based on
popularity. What distinguishes the TRUCE list is that it focuses on
the value of the quality of the play that a toy does or doesn't
promote. Founded in Cambridge, Mass., TRUCE is a national group of
early childhood educators. While the list highlights specific toys,
TRUCE also reminds parents that these toys represent trends to
watch for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOYS TO AVOID
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These toys use electronics in gimmicky ways that limit and
inhibit creativity and/or dictate a script:
</P>
<P>
   Elmo Talking Doll Stroller by Sesame Street/CTW. When you put
the doll in the stroller, it says, ``Whee, let's do it again.''
$20, ages 2+(1).
</P>
<P>
   Amazing Amy Playmates by Playmates. A computerized doll who
talks. $60, ages 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Looney Tunes Talking Cup &AMP; Bowl Sets by Funomenon. The cup and
bowl are computerized so that as a child uses them, they talk back,
saying things like, ``That was delicious!'' $14, ages 3+.
</P>
<P>
   These toys hook kids on the media, giving them the message that
the media is all-important in the world at a time when they benefit
more from first-hand interactions with people and with objects:
</P>
<P>
   Clue Keeping Blue by Fisher-Price/Tyco. A computerized stuffed
animal based on the TV show. $17, ages 1 1/2+.
</P>
<P>
   Tummy Glow Teletubbies by Playskool. All five Teletubbies, with
glowing, noisemaking pictures in their tummies. $13, 12 months+.
</P>
<P>
   Star Wars Episode I Electronic Board Book by Publications,
Int'l. A board book where pressing a button elicits a noise to
accompany the picture of fighting and guns shooting. $7, 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   These toys focus young girls on their bodies and encourage
inappropriate and stereotypical behavior:
</P>
<P>
   Body Art Activity Case by Colorbok Paper Products. A case with
tattoos, bellybutton and nose rings, and other trinkets. $8, 6+.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme Green Teen Skipper by Mattel. Skipper (Barbie's little
sister) colors her hair green to ``cruise the mall.'' $8, 4+.
</P>
<P>
   These toys emphasize violent, grotesque, and sexual images and
undermine lessons that caring adults teach:
</P>
<P>
   Super Soaker Naboo Pistol by Larami. An air-pressure rifle that
looks like an Uzi. $13, 6+.
</P>
<P>
   WWF (World Wrestling Federation) Action Figures by Jakks and WCW
(World Championship Wrestling) Action Figures by Toy Biz. Based on
real-life wrestlers seen on TV, these action figures include the
severed head of a woman and a toilet to smash the opponent. $7 and
up, ages 4+.
</P>
<P>
   WWF Bangers by Jakks Pacific. Wrestlers made of cloth. When
smashed against a hard object, they say angry, fighting phrases.
The female figure says, ``Do you want a piece of me?'' $7, 4.
</P>
<P>
   Impaled Mummy with piercing action by Toy Island/Universal.
Stick a spear in the hole in the bloodied half skeleton, and watch
as his intestines fall out of the chest. Each figure has a
different horror. $9, 4+.
</P>
<P>
   These toys have scripted play and turn play into ads for
products that young children cognitively can't recognize:
</P>
<P>
   Barbie `Toys R Us' Toy Store by Arco Toys/Mattel. A miniature
collection of Mattel brand-name toys to set up as a Toys R Us store
where Barbie then shops. $15, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's Birthday Doll Party Kit by Hasbro. Doll and party
items to act out a birthday party at McDonald's. $10, 3.
</P>
<P>
   These take the creativity out of classic toys:
</P>
<P>
   WCW Mold &AMP; Mash Wrestlers Crash Set by Colorbok. Art set with
four wrestler molds and wrestling ring with the motto: ``Rules &AMP;
bones are meant to be broken.'' $8, 6+.
</P>
<P>
   Night at the Movies, Loving Family Series by Fisher Price.
Miniature props create a living room with TV and VCR with mini
videos to insert into the TV (family figures not included).
</P>
<P>
   Rotten Egg Game by Toy Biz. Electronic game records and plays
back each player's name, then yells insults as children throw the
egg to each other. $20, 5+.
</P>
<P>
   These link play to candy:
</P>
<P>
   Jar Jar Binks Monster Mouth by OddzOn/Lucasfilms. Based on a
``Star Wars'' character, the monster mouth opens and its candy
tongue sticks out. Child's mouth goes in Jar Jar's mouth to lick
the tongue. $4, 4.
</P>
<P>
   Deluxe Breakfast Set by Strombecker. Miniature brand-name cereal
foods. $10, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOYS FOR HEALTHY AND CREATIVE PLAY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These toys offer open-ended play and help children develop
social skills, such as cooperation and sharing; physical skills,
such as small- and large-muscle development and eye-hand
coordination; and thinking skills, such as creativity, imagination,
language development, math concepts, and problem-solving:
</P>
<P>
   Toobers and Zots by Hands-on. Large flexible colored foam pieces
that bend, twist, and connect. $15, 5+.
</P>
<P>
   Play Toys Modular House Structure by Plan Creations. Three
wooden house segments that connect to create structures. Includes a
multicultural collection of toy people. Furniture available
separately. $30, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Flexible Dolls by Fanny's Play House. Small 5-inch cloth dolls
in a variety of skin tones and outfits. $7, 2+.
</P>
<P>
   Plan Toys Unit Blocks by Plan Creations. Hardwood building
blocks in 30- and 50-piece sets. $34 and $50, 2+.
</P>
<P>
   Big Bob's Itty Bitty Blocks by Small World Toys. A set of 28
wooden blocks. $6, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden Chug Along Construction Train by Simplex. Interchangeable
wooden shapes to build your own train and, as child gets older, to
create your own train cars. $27, 2+.
</P>
<P>
   Imagination Transportation by Creative Art Activities. Includes
components of a biplane, car, and tall ship. $25, 6+.
</P>
<P>
   Paint Center by Koosh Creative. Paint set with brush, roller,
etc. $18, 4 to 137.
</P>
<P>
   Multicolor Art Case by Battat. Case with pastels, markers, etc.
$7.50 to $20, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Max Discovers Shapes and Colors by International Playthings.
Noncompetitive beginning matching game. $11, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Color Mosaics by Simplex. Color shapes for use with or without a
frame. $8, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperative strategy games by Family Pastimes. Four games for
ages 4 and 5; $15.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Gel Ball by Play Visions. Shiny, squishy ball. $4, 3+.
Promotes small- and large-muscle motor development, endless play.
</P>
<P>
   Hoppity Ball by Small World Toys. Durable PVC ball large enough
to sit on, with large handles. $17, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Sport Set by R.A.M. Sports. Small replicas of official
basketball, football, and soccer balls. $15, 2+.
</P>
<P>
   Woodkins Dress-up Kids by Pamela Drake. Wood-framed person's
body with interchangeable facial expressions and clothes. $12, 2+.
</P>
<P>
   The Very Busy Baker by ALEX. Play bakeware kit with cooking
equipment, utensils, apron, and chef's hat. $30, 4+.
</P>
<P>
   I Spy Floor Puzzles by Briarpatch. 35 giant pieces. $15, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Bugs Puzzle by Small World Toys. Colorful 35-piece wooden
puzzle. $12, 4+.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderboard by Dowling Magnets. Magnetic pieces. $12, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Wall by Magic Wall. Magnetic panels attach to the wall for
use with magnetic pieces. $25, 3+.
</P>
<P>
   Earl E. Bird by Early Years. Multisensory toy that squeaks and
crinkles. $12, birth+.
</P>
<P>
   Poppa Geppetto's Toys by Manhattan Toys. Wood and soft fabric
rattles to pull and stretch. $12, birth+.
</P>
<P>
   Funland Farm by T.C. Timber. Wooden farm pieces and figures.
$40, 2+.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOTES &QL; 
 &QL; 
(1) Ages are recommended by the manufacturer. TRUCE notes that
manufacturer's ages are sometimes exaggerated on either end to
stretch sales and that a better guide is your personal knowledge of
a child's interests and abilities. &QL; 
 &QL; 
For more information, contact: TRUCE, Box 441261, Somerville, MA
02144, or go to the Web site, http://www.wheelock.edu/TRUCE. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
