<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3840 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-LOBBY-$ADV14     11-18 1468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-LOBBY-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS'S DOORS OPEN TO WELL-HEELED TECH LOBBY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By MARILYN GEEWAX  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With registered lobbyists now outnumbering members
of Congress roughly 40 to one, most of the men and women who get
paid to influence legislation are having a tough time arranging
meetings with powerful lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   But for those lucky lobbyists who represent high-flying
high-tech companies generating enormous fortunes, the doors on
Capitol Hill are swinging open and the phone lines are free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress is absolutely overwhelmingly interested in working
with us,'' said Steve Papermaster, an Austin, Texas, entrepreneur
and member of the executive council of Technology Network
(TechNet), a political action group founded two years ago in the
Silicon Valley. ``They are opening their doors. In fact, they are
calling us.''
</P>
<P>
   With politicians now so enamored, bills favorable to technology
companies have been speeding through an otherwise listless
Congress. In just little more than the past year, the
Republican-led Congress and Democratic White House have agreed to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Impose a three-year moratorium on taxes on electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increase the number of visas issued to highly skilled
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limit lawsuits against companies involved with Y2K-related
software flaws.
</P>
<P>
   _ Extend copyright protections to material published on the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, most members of Congress still thought the Web
was something you took care of by swiping a broom in the corner.
This year, committee hearings lavished attention on the issues of
Internet privacy, encryption, e-mail marketing and more.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists and lawmakers alike say the dramatic change was caused
by one thing: money. Big piles of money on Wall Street. Money back
in the home districts where young people are getting
computer-related jobs. Money in the campaign war chests.
</P>
<P>
   ``More attention is paid to a flourishing industry,'' said Rep.
Steve Horn, R-Calif., a member of the House Internet Caucus. When
an industry has the power to create thousands of jobs in your
state, ``you've got to stay awake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some say legislators are now so responsive that next year,
companies may have the power to mold the laws that will govern the
wired world of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a wonderful window of opportunity where high-tech is
still being seen in a very positive light,'' said Rick White, a
former congressman from Redmond, Wash. Now a lawyer who advises
high-tech companies, including Dell Computer Corp. and Amazon.com,
White said tech titans are so popular today on the Hill that ``they
probably could get Congress to do anything they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Papermaster, who also heads TechNet Texas, the Austin-based
branch of TechNet, said this passion for technology spread through
Washington ``like wildfire over the last 12 to 24 months.''
</P>
<P>
   For millions of Americans who began using the Internet years
ago, Congress may seem a little late to the love affair. But no one
working on Capitol Hill seems surprised that lawmakers were among
the last to appreciate the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has always been slow to come to any new technology,''
said Edward Segal, president of Internetlobby.com, a group
representing users of the Internet. ``Electricity was around for
years before Congress put electric lights in the Capitol.'' Even
now, many lawmakers remain reluctant to send e-mail or update their
Web pages, he said.
</P>
<P>
   White, who was elected to the House in 1994 and served two
terms, said Congress's well-deserved reputation as ``an
old-fashioned institution'' initially turned off the Silicon Valley
entrepreneurs, who tended to be young, politically naive and West
Coast-oriented. ``They were clueless about this process'' of making
laws, White said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Clare Fitzgerald, executive director of the Electronic
Commerce Forum, which lobbies for Internet-based companies, agreed
that the physical and psychological distance between the Hill and
the Valley retarded development of relationships between techies
and legislators. ``It's the nature of the California culture to
ignore Washington if possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1998, the wall of indifference began to erode, especially
on the Washington side. The fantastic growth of America Online Inc.
and Internet-focused companies in Fairfax County, Va., made a
profound impression on the lawmakers and staffers who lived nearby,
and wished they could see such job growth to their own districts.
``The Northern Virginia phenomenon has had a big impact'' on
Congress, Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators suddenly wanted to meet the wizards who created such
wealth. ``I can get a high-tech CEO in anywhere'' to meet with a
member of Congress, Fitzgerald said. ``I certainly never saw
anything like this when I was working for the banking industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Congress was waking up to the New Economy, entrepreneurs
in the high-tech breeding grounds of Texas, California, Washington,
Massachusetts, Georgia, Colorado and elsewhere were starting to
develop a new appreciation for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   They realized they had problems that Congress could help them
solve.
</P>
<P>
   Shortages of engineers and programmers spurred companies to seek
higher immigration ceilings for highly skilled workers. Companies
focused on electronic commerce began worrying that state and local
governments would impose a patchwork of taxes on Internet
transactions. Federal restrictions on exports of certain
technologies were hurting business.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the example of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   When Microsoft started going through a highly publicized
antitrust case brought by the Justice Department, tech executives
realized Washington could reshape an industry with century-old
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other companies would look at Microsoft and think, 'That could
happen to me,'' White said. Suddenly, executives knew ``they had to
do a better job of making their case to the government.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, tech companies have been hiring lobbyists
at a furious pace and organizing political networks to make
themselves heard. In fact, the lobbyist buildup is happening so
fast, numbers are hard to nail down.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics, a non-profit research group,
says public documents show spending on lobbying by computer
equipment and services companies shot from $25 million in 1997 to
$39 million in 1998. The 1999 figures are expected to show another
sharp increase in spending.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this ramping up, the high-tech world doesn't yet have a
clear, coordinated lobbying agenda. Indeed, many big, tech-driven
companies, such as Microsoft, AOL and AT&AMP;T, often want very
different things out of Washington. Still, some legislative goals
seem nearly universally supported.
</P>
<P>
   Companies want Congress to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep Internet transactions from being suffocated by a crazy
quilt of state and local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bolster spending on scientific research and development.
</P>
<P>
   _ Approve electronic signatures to facilitate commerce on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increase funding for education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow more hiring of highly skilled immigrants and boost
exports of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said high-tech companies have an opportunity to push
this agenda in 2000 because most members of Congress are willing to
take advice from entrepreneurs. ``You can count on two hands all of
the people (in Congress) who really understand the high-tech
world,'' she said. ``But you're at a stage that won't last that
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, lawmakers will ``hire the right staffers to close the
information gap,'' she said. Once they feel more confident about
the substance of a debate, legislators may become more argumentive
and less willing to do whatever the high-tech titans tell them to
do. Once that happens, lobbyists may find ``the door will be
closing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ROLE OF TECH LOBBYING GROWING QUICKLY
</P>
<P>
   ....................................................................
 ...1997................1998
</P>
<P>
   Registered federal
lobbyists................................18,590..............20,512
</P>
<P>
   All federal lobbying expenses..............................$1.26
billion......$1.42 billion
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists' spending in the high-tech sector:
</P>
<P>
   Electronics manufacturing and services.................$8.88
million.....$10.6 million
</P>
<P>
   Computer equipment and services........................$24.96
million...$38.99 million
</P>
<P>
   Proportion of lobbying expenses from high-tech......26.9
percent......34.9 percent
</P>
<P>
   Source: Center for Responsive Politics
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
