<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: HITCHING WEB SITES TO A STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember Carl Sagan's singsong declarations about space being
filled with ``billions and billions'' of stars? Cyberspace is now
becoming filled with stars too, as a lengthening list of dot-com
marketers center their advertising on celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Famous faces and voices are peddling Web sites,
electronic-commerce companies, PCs, search engines and e-tailers _
almost anything interactive- or Internet-related. They range from
immediately recognizable (Donald Trump) to nostalgic favorites
(Barry White) to hip semi-celebrities (the singer Seal).
</P>
<P>
   The trend is not unexpected if dot-com advertising is considered
to be mimicking the model established by pitches for traditional
products like packaged goods.
</P>
<P>
   The initial phase is to inculcate the name, usually by
repetition and spelling: ``Remember, that's
w-w-w-dot-beauteesoap-dot-com. And don't forget, `beautee' has
three E's.'' Then comes the phase of differentiating one brand from
another, particularly in categories where the participants are
proliferating.
</P>
<P>
   And what better way to try doing that than renting some star
power, a device known as borrowed interest? If Amos and Andy could
make Americans brush with Pepsodent toothpaste, and Ozzie and
Harriet make them snap pictures with Kodak film, why can't Sophia
Loren make shopping at www.giftcertificates.com chic and Dr. Joyce
Brothers make buying computers at www.cozone.com seem like a
no-brainer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are inundated with dot-com this and dot-com that,''
said Joseph Park, chief executive at Kozmo.com in New York, a
company specializing in so-called urban delivery services. ``One of
the key challenges is to build credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A celebrity subconsciously brings credibility and legitimacy
to whatever claims are being made,'' he added. A humorous
television commercial for Kozmo.com by DiMassimo Brand Advertising
in New York presents Lee Majors as a contemporary version of Steve
Austin, the character he played on ``The Six Million Dollar Man''
in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dot-coms are using celebrities to bring the familiar to the
world of the unknown,'' said Kathy Delaney, partner and executive
creative director at Deutsch Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these dot-com companies are brand-spanking-new,'' she
added. ``The celebrities lend immediate recognizability.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch is introducing a television and print campaign for the
Encyclopedia Britannica Web site (www.britannica.com) that features
Seal, Ms. Taylor, Norman Mailer, Anjelica Huston and Francis Ford
Coppola.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrities are brands, and their brands can drive brands,''
said Richard Kirshenbaum, co-chairman at Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP;
Partners in New York, an agency with many dot-com clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The latest thing is the merging of commerce and entertainment
to create content that consumers remember,'' he added. ``So if
content equals entertainment and celebrities equal entertainment,
therefore content equals celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, the stars have an obvious link to the
dot-coms they promote. For example, a campaign for
Barnesandnoble.com presents authors and entertainers whose books
and compact discs are sold at its Web site (www.bn.com). In
addition to White, the husky-voiced singer, they include the
mystery writer Sue Grafton, the law novelist Scott Turow and the
chef-turned-scribe Emeril Lagasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not using a spokesperson who may or may not like the
product,'' said Carl Rosendorf, senior vice president at
Barnesandnoble.com in New York. ``Our spokespeople are the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relevance of the person is most important here,'' he
added. ``At the same time, we're giving the buying-online process
some personality and style.'' The campaign is created by the New
York office of TBWA/Chiat/Day, part of the TBWA Worldwide unit of
the Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the celebrities are relevant to where we're spending
most of our money,'' said Len Short, executive vice president for
advertising and brand management at Charles Schwab in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Because Schwab ``bought time in some key sports properties,'' he
added, the brokerage firm's commercials include the football
players Jason Sehorn and Shannon Sharpe and the tennis players Mary
Joe Fernandez and Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   ``The celebrities put us in the event,'' Short said, ``but the
point isn't celebrities. It's that we show them to be surprisingly
intelligent about investing'' _ because they are Schwab customers,
natch. The Schwab spots are created by BBDO New York, part of the
BBDO Worldwide unit of Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to get a celebrity for celebrity's sake may bring a bit
of attention to a brand, but it does little or nothing for the
brand in the long term,'' said Ted Sann, co-chief executive and
chief creative officer at BBDO New York, which is known for
star-infused campaigns for Pepsico Inc. brands like Frito-Lay
snacks and Pepsi-Cola soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly the same as for general brand advertising,'' he
added. ``There has to be a brand positioning before you hire a
celebrity, which the celebrity has to fit. That was the case with
Cindy Crawford and Ray Charles and Michael J. Fox for Pepsi and
Diet Pepsi.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   How then does Ms. Loren fit with Giftcertificates.com?
</P>
<P>
   ``In a media environment that's so cluttered, especially this
season, you've got to hit as hard as you can,'' said Mark Paviluk,
vice president and group management supervisor on the company's
account at Grey Advertising in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what could be more impactful than the most beautiful woman
in the world, who appeals to everyone from the housewife in Des
Moines to the Chanel shopper in Manhattan?'' he asked rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   For Cozone.com, a unit of CompUSA, a campaign features Trump,
Dr. Brothers and the basketball star David Robinson, all depicted
as fish out of water: Trump, for example, taking a pottery class,
and Ms. Brothers on a turkey shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrities often get used too much in advertising,'' said
Edward Boches, chief creative officer at the Cozone.com agency,
Mullen Advertising in Wenham, Mass., part of the Lowe Group unit of
Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea here is that just because the celebrity is good at
one thing, it doesn't necessarily mean he or she is good at other
things, like buying computers,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, sometimes stars are part of campaigns because they are
stakeholders in the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Whoopi Goldberg, for instance, is a part owner in a
gift-certificate Web site, Flooz.com, so she appears in the
advertising by Hanft Byrne Raboy &AMP; Partners in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And members of the NFL Quarterback Club _ present and past
players like Bernie Kosar of the Cleveland Browns, Warren Moon of
the Kansas City Chiefs and Ricky Williams of the New Orleans Saints
_ will be featured in a campaign by Organic in New York for Pseudo
Programs, an Internet broadcaster that uses streaming media on a
Web site (www.pseudo.com). Pseudo has scheduled a live show on the
site at 11 a.m. (Eastern time) Tuesday to promote its coming QB
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an endorsement deal,'' said Jeanne Meyer, senior
vice president for marketing at Pseudo in New York. ``The
Quarterback Club is making a cash investment and Bernie Kosar is
joining our board of directors.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. That's another trend, executives who appear in
ads for the companies they own.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-15-99 2335EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
