<HEADER>
A3846 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-18 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOOP LEAVES VERMONT JOURNALIST JOBLESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Oct. 4, Terry Allen, a freelancer and part-timer for a
Vermont newspaper, scored a journalistic coup. A front-page piece
she wrote for that day's Boston Globe revealed that Indonesian
students at Norwich University _ a private military college in
Northfield, Vt. _ had links to the Indonesian Army's feared special
forces.
</P>
<P>
   The story _ which Allen says her newspaper declined to publish
before she took it to the Globe _ made serious waves, coming in the
wake of the bloodshed in East Timor and the White House's decision
to end military cooperation with Indonesia. It brought political
heat down on Norwich, was picked up by everyone from the Associated
Press to CNN, and motivated several senators to express their
concern directly to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks later, Allen says she was suddenly fired
from her part-time job as wire editor and layout person for the
company that publishes the Barre-Montpelier Times Argus, the
Rutland Herald, and a Sunday paper. She says Times Argus managing
editor Scott Fletcher told her that she couldn't be trusted. ``I
don't know why I was let go,'' she says. ``They have no reason, I
know of, to distrust me.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen's departure raises disturbing questions. Was she, with her
well-known liberal politics, seen as too advocacy-oriented by her
editors? Did she pay a price for ruffling the feathers of a local
institution to which her publisher has financial and advisory ties?
Was her real sin breaking a controversial story? Her bosses simply
aren't saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to give you a big fat no comment,'' says Sunday
editor Dirk Van Susteren. ``We just don't comment on this
publicly,'' adds publisher R. John Mitchell. Fletcher, who even
declines to confirm that Allen was fired, characterizes her as a
former part-timer ``we don't use anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that no one from our organization can give
you our version of events,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   One party that didn't remain silent was Norwich, which moved
quickly to counter Allen's story. Even before it was published,
school president Richard Schneider sent a letter to Allen _ with
copies to Fletcher and Van Susteren _ accusing her of
unprofessionalism and expressing concern over ``the potential
appearance of bias on your part.'' (In another strange twist to
this tale, Schneider later wrote to Allen acknowledging that he had
been incorrect in some of his criticisms of her work.)
</P>
<P>
   In the days following the Oct. 4 story, both the Rutland Herald
and Burlington Free Press editorialized on behalf of the school,
arguing that the university could actually exert a positive
influence on the Indonesian students. Schneider said much the same
thing in an Oct. 14 op-ed piece in the Times Argus, and Norwich
also placed ads in the Free Press and Argus, characterizing the
idea of rejecting the Indonesian students as ``discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider was unavailable for comment. But Norwich spokesman Tom
Greene says Allen ``seemed particularly concerned with making a
case against Norwich, which led her to report selectively . . . I
think her passion for the subject should have been a reason for her
to pull off the story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an agenda in that story,'' responds Allen, who accuses
Norwich of spreading ``misinformation about me . . . My agenda is
that it was a great story. There were times I have been very
politically active in my life . . . in this case, I was at least 98
percent a journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen's Oct. 4 story did include two incorrect first names and a
wrong dateline. But when asked about any major accuracy problems in
the piece, Greene said, ``selectively reported, yes. Factually
inaccurate, no . . . The story's fair game, but it's a question of
slant on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gareth Cook, the Globe's New England editor who handled the
story, said Greene complained that it ``was written with an agenda
(but) no one challenged the accuracy.'' After the Oct. 4 piece,
Allen also produced an Oct. 7 Globe follow-up reflecting Capitol
Hill opposition to the Norwich progam. And on Oct. 10, the Sunday
paper that Allen had worked for ran a follow-up piece she wrote on
the controversy _ catching up to a story that Allen says Fletcher
had rejected in the first place because it wasn't news.
</P>
<P>
   Lurking in the background here is Mitchell's connection to
Norwich. He is a member of the school's board of fellows, which
Greene characterizes as ``an advisory group (with) no formal
authority.'' He is also a Norwich donor, although he won't mention
a dollar figure. ``I know we're supposed to be pure,'' says
Mitchell, adding that ``I don't get involved in day-to-day decisons
about how the paper is run.'' Several sources concur, saying
Mitchell is the kind of hands-off publisher who separates his own
interests from the newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   So, why was Terry Allen dismissed right after producing the kind
of story most editors dream about? ``I wasn't let go because I was
unethical,'' she says. ``I was not inaccurate. I was not
insubordinate. I was not unprofessional in my behavior.'' There may
be an answer. But for now, it's very tempting to believe that Terry
Allen didn't deserve her fate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mark Jurkowitz covers media issues for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
