<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVER BUILD A CLOSET IN THE BASEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband built a cedar closet in the basement. He painted
the concrete walls to help keep moisture out, put plastic behind
the wood walls, and lined them with pressed board under a cedar
overlay. The odor of cedar and glue is awful. I can't use our
clothes; they are too smelly. What can we do now?
</P>
<P>
   J.F., Millis, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. For starters, a clothes closet should not be built in the
basement; it is virtually impossible to seal the closet against
moisture, especially the passage of water vapor up through the
concrete floor.
</P>
<P>
   Since it is unlikely that you can seal out all moisture, I
suggest the following, unless you move the closet upstairs: If
there is a window in one of the walls, keep it open for
ventilation, particularly important in summer. Use a dehumidifier
in the dog-day months of July and August, when humidity peaks.
Ventilation is less important in winter. If there are no windows,
make some in the band joist above the foundation wall.
</P>
<P>
   And get rid of that pressed board, since the cedar is
ineffective and the glue is probably formaldehyde, which smells to
high heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Build a regular wall with insulation and plasterboard finish;
then line the walls _ or one or two of them, anyway _ with cedar
liner boards; they should not be overwhelming. Besides, cedar is
only a deterrent to moths; it does not kill them or their larvae.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You wrote recently that when a washing machine is on the
second floor, you need to install a tray underneath to catch any
water in case of a broken hose or an overflowing machine. Where can
I get one of those trays?
</P>
<P>
   PHILIP MANN, Ayer, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think they are made, although you could have one
fabricated by a metal worker. I mentioned a tray because the reader
was concerned about runaway water. And, to be safe, that tray
should have a drain leading to another drain on the first floor or
basement.
</P>
<P>
   All this means is that a tray will allay any concerns about
water damage, but is not necessary. You do take a chance of the
machine overflowing, and that could be critical if it overflows
when it is filling, because it is never likely to stop. But chances
are very low that this will happen. To keep hoses from bursting,
install a one-handle shutoff to them, so you can turn them on when
using the machine and off when not. This saves wear and tear on the
hose and reduces the chance of a burst. Finally, use steel-clad
hoses that are very resistant to bursting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am having some of my rotted exterior windowsills replaced
with new ones. They look pretty good, but some of the sills look a
little far out, sticking out a bit over the wall. The installer
said that is how a sill should be. How far should they stick out?
</P>
<P>
   JULIA BALAS, Dorchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Standard stickout or overhang is 1 1/2 inches; a little more
is OK, but you don't want it much less, because the sill acts as a
drip edge, allowing water to drip beyond the wall. Not enough of an
overhang will result in water running under the sill and down the
wall, and perhaps into it. You'll notice a small groove on the
underside of the sill; that is to prevent water from percolating
under the sill to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel the sill is sticking out too far, you can always cut
1/4 inch from the face of it, but I really don't think this will be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wall-hung Vent Away toilet leaked from a crack. I have to
replace it, but this type is no longer made, and, so far, I have
been unable to find a substitute. I cannot put in a regular
floor-mounted toilet. Where can I find a wall-mounted toilet?
</P>
<P>
   DOROTHY COLBERT, Tuftonboro, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. You may have to go to a big city for such a toilet, but they
do exist. Call Watertown Plumbing &AMP; Heating Supply, 617-924-2840.
They have one of the biggest plumbing inventories this handyman has
ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The mounting box for my ceiling fan is too low for the fan to
fit properly against the ceiling. It would be a big hassle moving
the box farther into the ceiling. How can I make the bell mounting
of the ceiling fan, the part that is supposed to fit snugly against
the ceiling, do so?
</P>
<P>
   SCOT LEHIGH, Charlestown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't bring the box up (it would, indeed, be a hassle), so
bring the ceiling down. Not the entire ceiling, of course, but you
can devise a wood medallion that would sit against the ceiling;
then the bell will fit snugly against it. You might be able to find
a plastic medallion; if not, make a round or square one of wood,
bevel the edges, and create something decorative as well as useful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sorry about that, but an incorrect phone number was given for
the Mirage Rolling Screen Door mentioned in a recent Handyman
column. The manufacturer no longer has a phone listing, and its 800
number has been assigned elsewhere. The handyman tried to track
down the company from the dusty brochure in his files, but without
success.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
