<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3851 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-VIDEO-GAMES-BOS &LR;      11-18 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING FROM GAME BOYS TO MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jason Bilsky was in his early teens and living in Orlando,
he came home from school in the afternoon, plopped a cartridge into
his clunky Atari 2600 video-game console, and hunkered down with
Space Invaders. Now 29, he comes home from work in the evening,
slips a CD into his sleek Sony Playstation and kicks back with
Metal Gear Solid.
</P>
<P>
   The difference? Sixteen years. That's about it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we've gone from paddle games to games that play like
Hollywood movies. But video-game consoles _ those boxes that
connect to your TV, as opposed to games you play on your computer _
are still seen as a bratty nephew within the showbiz family despite
their phenomenal success. Pop quiz: which did more business during
its first 24 hours in the marketplace, Sega's new Dreamcast console
or the movie ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace''?
Surprise answer: Dreamcast, by a score of $97.9 million to $28.5
million. Yet we still tend to consign console games to the
toys-for-teens dustbins of our minds, hauling them out only to flay
them for being too violent, addictive, sexual, and/or mind-numbing.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever you think of these games, don't think of them as
solely child's play. A lot of former game boys, like Bilsky, have
grown up to become game guys. Today, they're surfing a wave of
current and near-future technology as they battle virtual villains,
score digital touchdowns, and spin the tires of code-generated
racing cars. According to the Interactive Digital Software
Association, 54 percent of the primary users of console games are
ages 18 and over. The Yankee Group, a Boston research firm, puts
the figure at a more conservative 40 percent. Either way, teens and
preteens are clearly not the only ones who got game.
</P>
<P>
   For Bilsky, there's only one drawback to being something of a
video game elder. ``It does feel kind of weird to go into a video
store and see that I'm older than anyone except the parents who've
brought their kids,'' muses the computer graphics designer.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, these relative old fogeys tend to have, you know, like
jobs. Families. Responsibilities. Frederick Baker, a 36-year-old
Coast Guard avionicsman who repairs and flies fixed-wing aircraft
at Otis Air National Guard Base on Cape Cod, has a wife and a
3-year-old son. He also has a stash of four consoles, plus a
hand-held model, the better to settle down with the likes of
Wipeout, Roll Cage, and Future Cop: LAPD. Of the last game, Baker
says, sounding a bit sheepish, ``Basically, you're a cop who
controls a vehicle that transforms from a Mack, and you're putting
down bad guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But Baker, a onetime board gamer, can also wax enthusiastic
about the creative graphics of today's games, about the challenge
of mastering them, and about the the sheer thrill of putting, say,
a futuristic if virtual race car through its paces. ``Sometimes he
just plays for hours and hours,'' reports his wife, Jennifer, her
voice sounding as if she is at the midpoint between amazement and
resignation. (Women are outnumbered by men in the console game
universe by a 2-to-1 margin, according to IDSA.)
</P>
<P>
   What those of us who view these games as simply teen
time-fillers don't realize is that their history in the home goes
back more than a generation. It started in 1972 with the Magnavox
Odyssey: paddle hockey, black and white image, no sound. The years
that followed produced a roller coaster of downs (goodbye
Colecovision) and ups (hello Sonic the Hedgehog). They also created
a generation of vidkids who grew up with their hands firmly locked
around a joystick down at the local arcade or in the family den.
These white-knuckle digital pilots ascended from the 8-bit era to
the 16-bit, eventually witnessing the dawn of Sega and Nintendo
during the 1980s. In the '90s, as they've become adults, they've
latched onto Sony's 32-bit Playstation, Nintendo 64, and now Sega's
128-bit Dreamcast.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Laskowski, a 33-year-old administrative director of a
company that owns four McDonald's restaurants, started vidoeogaming
back in the Pong Era. Pong was a simple but semi-addictive arcade
paddle game that burst forth in 1972 and eventually made its way
into homes. ``I played games every day during my teenage years,''
recalls Laskowski, who lives with his wife and two young sons in
Woonsocket, R.I. ``When the excitement waned, a hot new game would
come out and refire my interest. I always wanted something bigger
and I always wanted something better.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawkowski was typical. He moved onward through a series of
gaming gear, from Atari to Mattel to Nintendo. As happened to many
of ancient and honorable gamers, however, the fire cooled while he
tended to the business of becoming an adult. But today he runs two
contemporary machines in his home, a Nintendo 64 and a Dreamcast,
pumping out football, wrestling, and shooter games at will. ``As a
kid,'' he says, ``games were a kind of fantasy. You could find a
piece of your dreams by playing them. But nowadays, I mostly just
sit here and marvel at the ability of the designers to create such
an incredibly eye-catching product that's so enjoyable to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this is a great time to be shopping in the video game
candy store, particularly if you're old enough not to have to ask
Mom and Dad for money to buy the goodies. Dreamcast, launched to
waiting customer lines in September, put Sega Enterprises Ltd. back
at the table with the other members of gaming's Big 3, Nintendo Co.
Ltd., and Sony Computer Entertainment Inc. It has also upped the
ante, creating a new generation of games by introducing a more
powerful, Internet-ready, graphically rich system and backing it
with a $100 million marketing push.
</P>
<P>
   Sony plans to retaliate in March with the Japanese release of
its next-generation Playstation 2 (US release: fall 2000), complete
with its own 128-bit Emotion Engine. Nintendo, meanwhile, is
working on a 256-bit console tentatively known as Dolphin, hoping
to deliver, by the end of 2000, with bells and whistles that will
further knock a gamer's socks off. Nintendo also says it will
introduce a new 32-bit version of its portable Game Boy next fall,
thereby replacing the hottest piece of video game hardware of all
time: 80 million units sold.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional industry wisdom holds that older players tend to
favor sports and racing games rather than fighting and shooting
games. (Sega is marketing a Dreamcast fishing game with a
controller that simulates the lazy cast of a fly rod. Try selling
that to a twitchy kid.) Many game developers believe that these
adults want games they can learn fairly quickly. But for someone
like George Cavros, a 28-year-old emergency medical technician,
figures he spends at least 500 hours a year with a game controller
in his hands, learning time isn't an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I do games where you run around and kill guys,'' Cavros
says. ``But I prefer strategy games and war games that involve
careful thinking and planning. And I like putting myself in
situations that don't happen to people in ordinary life. A good
video game is like being inside a good book and living a
character's life. You're experiencing a world in which you don't
live. But you're in that world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big 3 console makers are obviously aware of the 20- to
40-something crowd. When Sony launched its Playstation in 1995, it
made a concentrated effort to go after what spokesperson Molly
Smith calls ``an older, more sophisticated market.'' The strategy
worked: more than a third of the demographic base of the Sony
console, which has sold more than 60 million units, is 24 years or
older. Smith says the company is aiming lower these days, having
increased its number of titles aimed at young teens. But targeting
kids can be a good way of hitting grown-ups, especially if we're
talking about adults who are trying to recapture their youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really about downward aspiration,'' explains Peter Moore,
senior vice-president for marketing for Sega of America Inc. ``I'm
44. But when I pick up a controller and play a game, I'm suddenly
younger because of that. I'm playing again. We like to say here,
`Everybody's 17 when they get that contoller in their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are it's been in their hands for as long as a quarter of
a century, since the days of ``Pong'' and other artifacts.
``Playing video games is a natural thing for these people because
they've been doing it all their lives,'' says Perrin Kaplan,
director of corporate affairs for Nintendo of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toy industry loses people when they grow older. We
don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
