<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3852 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-18 1755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE IN TOYLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you're standing in a store aisle surrounded by
more toy choices than Santa's elves ever dreamed of, stop a second
before you cart one to the register and ask yourself this question:
What kind of activities can this toy lead to?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the answer this holiday season is too often,
``Nothing good.''
</P>
<P>
   Early childhood educators say they are finding some disturbing
new themes among the toys being marketed for young children this
year, from a growing reliance on electronic technology to an
increase in violent themes and toys that involve candy in play.
</P>
<P>
   For Boston College developmental psychologist Martha Bronson,
the first hint of the troubling trends came after she had spent a
few afternoons visiting toy stores for a research project. Then she
pored through 30 or so holiday toy catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all,'' she says, ``it was very depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Her complaint is that manufacturers are taking the play out of
toys. ``It's through play that young children learn about the
world. A good toy opens doors for a child to how the world works.
It leaves gaps for the child to fill in so that there's room for
imagination and creativity,'' says Bronson. A good toy has
possibilities. It expands play, it doesn't limit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic gadgets, where a baby pushes a button and gets
entertained, are about as limiting as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a toddler's perspective, it's nothing more than a magic
trick,'' says Bronson. ``No matter how many times she pushes the
button, there's nothing a baby or toddler can learn from that
toy.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a toy that gets boring very quickly and is put aside, a
big deal when you consider the time and money you spent choosing it
and the unrewarded energy a child put into it. But there are other
developmental problems with these toys, too, says early childhood
educator Diane Levin of Wheelock College, a specialist in
children's toys and media and the author of ``Remote Control
Childhood?'' (NAEYC Press).
</P>
<P>
   One of a child's earliest developmental tasks is to learn about
cause and effect, where baby does something and sees an immediate
result: She smiles and Daddy smiles back; he shakes a rattle and
there's a noise; she kicks a mobile and it moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electronic toys short-circuit this process,'' says Levin.
``What babies get out of it is that something happens inside the
box. It takes them away from the process of understanding how you
influence the world, how you make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Distracting sound chips
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Electronics are even creeping into some classic toys, say toy
gurus Joanne and Stephanie Oppenheim, authors of the popular
parents' guide ``Oppenheim Toy Portfolio'' (2000 edition).
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, everything has a sound chip, which is a distraction
for little kids, not a plus,'' says Stephanie Oppenheim. ``Taking
your first step with a push toy is a big deal by itself. You don't
need sounds and lights on the toy.''
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheim says they were hard-pressed this year to find a toy
garage that didn't have sound added. ``Kids are better off bringing
their own horn and motor sounds to it,'' she says. Even stuffed
animals, one of the most reliable toys you can give, are
increasingly adulterated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a Magic Kermit Talking Doll we liked because there are
four things you can make him do, and it's huggable,'' she says. But
there is also a Rock and Roll Elmo and Ernie they don't like:
``It's a one-note toy. There's nothing to do but watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, there are too many toys that dictate play or offer
only one way to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a toy kitchen that told kids which color pot to put
on the stove,'' asks Oppenheim. ``That flies in the face of
everything we know about the importance of toys helping children
bring imagination to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, generic props are almost always better than specific
ones. ``Some kitchen toys come equipped down to a plastic fried
egg,'' says Bronson. ``But a plastic fried egg can only be a
plastic fried egg. Better to let them pretend a block or leaf is an
egg.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Violence and grotesquerie
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is it more obvious that a toy can only be what it is
than in the proliferation of toys with violent, grotesque, and
sexual imagery, a trend identified by TRUCE (Teachers Resisting
Unhealthy Children's Entertainment) in its annual toy list. Levin,
a TRUCE spokeswoman, says there is more violence and grotesquerie
this year than ever in toys for young children. The example she
cites is the Impaled Mummy, where you put a spear in the toy's back
and its intestines fall out. Not only does it endorse a violent
action, but this toy also presents a problem developmentally,
because it focuses children on subject matter that would not
normally cross their horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage, they're trying to undertand how the body
functions, and they don't have the cognitive skills to separate out
what's real and what's not,'' she says. ``A toy like this confuses
them on both fronts.'' A 3-year-old who scrapes his knee, for
instance, might overreact, worried that his insides will fall out.
In addition, she says, when children are confused by the message a
toy sends, they work that much harder to figure it out even though
they don't have the cognitive equipment to do so. ``That takes
their energy away from the issues they do need to work on,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Bronson worries about the implied message we send when we give
toys like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you give a child any toy, you are saying, `This is
appropriate, this is for you.' You are sanctioning the activity the
toy generates, including the violence,'' she says. ``I don't think
parents think about that enough.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sending wrong messages
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Bronson asks the all-important question, ``What kind of
activities can this toy lead to?'' the ``nothing good'' answer is
particularly apropos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad enough when a toy is designed to follow a script from
TV or video; that leads to imitative rather than creative play,''
she says. ``When the play the toy promotes is violent _ when the
only play value of an action figure is to beat up another action
figure _ what image of the world does a child construct?''
</P>
<P>
   The grotesqueness of most action figures raises another issue.
Bronson says more and more research shows that young boys think
their bodies have to look like muscle-bound action figure bodies,
much the way little girls think they have to look like Barbie. And
with so many action figures presenting distorted and violent female
body images, boys and girls potentially get equally distorted ideas
about female sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The movies and TV shows these figures come from _ ``Star Wars''
or WWF, for instance _ are rated by their industry as not
appropriate for very young children, yet toys spun off from them
are marketed for toddlers and preschoolers. ``What does `Star Wars'
have to do with an 18-month-old's world?'' Levin asks. She urges
parents to stay away from things like the ``Star Wars'' board book
with sound effects. Not only do the sounds distract from the
reading process and set a child up to need constant stimulation,
but the content also ``hooks them on violence and begins to
desensitize them to it, even at 18 months,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Candy-toy links
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toys with violent themes don't even get considered by the
Oppenheims but Stephanie Oppenheim says they had to sidestep many
more of them this year than ever before. They also stay away from
the candy-toy link, a trend that made it to the TRUCE ``Toys to
Avoid'' list for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was barely visible last year at Christmas,'' says Levin.
This year it's all over the place, from plush 3-inch Pokemon toys
with Wonka TartnTinys candy inside to minitrucks carting mini M&AMP;Ms.
Disney has a Tarzan rainstick candystick: ``The downpour that
sounds delicious.'' And perhaps most offensive of all is Jar Jar
Binks Monster Mouth, where a child sticks her mouth into Jar Jar's
to lick the candy off its tongue. ``The sexual overtones to that
could set up kids to be accepting of an abusive sexual come-on,''
says Levin.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious and more typical trouble with a candy-toy link is
that it promotes poor nutrition. ``Kids learn from their play, so
the message that junk food is OK becomes ingrained,'' says Levin.
</P>
<P>
   So what should we be buying?
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most important is for young children to have a rich
variety of playthings,'' says Oppenheim. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   --Birth to 12 months. ``Babies need responsive people more than
responsive objects,'' says Bronson. Keep toys simple, basic, and
predictable: rattles and mobiles.
</P>
<P>
   --12 to 24 months. They're grappling with cause and effect and
for control. Give them toys that offer opportunities to push, pull,
fill, empty, pile, and climb. Blocks are great; so are simple
stacking toys, board books, and stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   --2 to 3 years. Oppenheim says the best new toy for this age is
the Tomy Ball Party Connecting Bridge by International Playthings.
``It's basically a ball run,'' says Stephanie Oppenheim, ``so they
make it happen. As they get older, you can make a color game out of
it: red balls first, blue second; and you can make it
interactive.'' Also good at this age are toys that involve texture,
shape, size, and color: simple matching games, basic musical
instruments, balls for large motor skills, and familiar objects for
fantasy play.
</P>
<P>
   --3 to 5 years. Play becomes more purposeful as they act out
themes of their lives. Provide items for fantasy play (boys like
this as much as girls); materials for lacing, beading, matching,
and sorting; simple board games of chance or games like dominoes or
lotto; art materials for creating and planning ahead; beginners'
building sets. Oppenheim's advice about construction sets like Lego
is that less is more _ ``Too many pieces overwhelm'' _ except for
train sets: ``If you only have enough track to make a circle, it's
boring.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one more trend the Oppenheims noticed this year: dirty
toys.
</P>
<P>
   Dirty toys?
</P>
<P>
   ``Open the box and many toys have grease, dirt, and human
hair,'' says Stephanie Oppenheim. ``We're telling parents not to
give any toy to a young child without washing it first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz welcomes comments and can be reached via e-mail
at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
