<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AT THE PEOPLE WHO LOOK AT THE CARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since in addition to being personally fascinated with autos, I
also write about them, shows like the New England International
Auto Show are fun in a couple of ways.
</P>
<P>
   In one manner, I approach them just as most of you do: spot
interesting-looking cars, walk around them, and check their lines
from all angles; climb into the drivers' seats and imagine myself
the owner; sit in the back and get the feel for being a passenger.
Grab literature. Check sticker prices. Walk and gawk until my feet
get sore.
</P>
<P>
   But since writing about cars also means having some
understanding of the people who buy them, it's also fun to attend
an auto show and, while moving among the cars, watch you folks
check them out.
</P>
<P>
   This makes it easy to spot trends: which cars are clicking with
which groups of people.
</P>
<P>
   It makes it easy to spot enduring traits: which groups of people
are borne back ceaselessly to the same brands, year after year,
even as those brands may be changing radically.
</P>
<P>
   And it is also inevitable that you run across irony and humor as
you listen to certain folks comment on cars.
</P>
<P>
   Like the guy, wearing a ``Buy American'' button standing before
a Toyota Tundra pickup truck and exhorting that he would never buy
something made in Japan. He was surprised when I told him it was
built by American hands in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Or the yahoo who approached a glistening Saleen Mustang
convertible, set his Pepsi on the polished rear deck and announced
so all could hear: ``I have one of these puppies. It's not a
Saleen, but it's a Mustang.'' Right, and Charlie Parker may have
been OK, but Neil Diamond in ``The Jazz Singer'' was just awesome.
</P>
<P>
   But if you watched carefully, there were serious, interesting
observations to be made about both cars and the people who studied
them:
</P>
<P>
   --Any time you saw a group of young kids (as in too young to
drive) rolling rapidly across the floor, you knew they were headed
to the Volkswagen Beetles.
</P>
<P>
   --It was almost endearing to watch young couples sit in the
front seats of Mercedes and dream of the day any one of these might
be their car.
</P>
<P>
   --Families of four or more, of course, went to the vans and
SUVs, but you spotted them again later circling the four-door,
six-passenger pickup trucks that are in abundance this year.
</P>
<P>
   --And speaking of vans, don't many of them seem to be getting
progressively smaller?
</P>
<P>
   --Older folks formed the steadiest lines to the Lincoln and
Cadillac displays and many had to be surprised at the youthful
sportiness of the Lincoln LS or the Cadillac Catera.
</P>
<P>
   --Watching large groups of people emerge from the gargantuan
Ford Excursion reminded me of a day at the circus. How many clowns
could you fit into one of those beasts?
</P>
<P>
   --In this day and age, why do sellers of automobiles think they
must use tall, thin women in tight clothes to sell us their cars?
</P>
<P>
   --At a show where flash and glitz are at a premium, it is
amazing how those fabulous Porsche automobiles can sit there
looking so benign.
</P>
<P>
   --The bug look is obviously in for the latest generation of SUVs
_ that's bug as in having an exoskeleton in the form of racks,
step-up rails, and various tubes wrapped over and around the autos.
It was most noticeable in the Kia Sportage 4 x 4, the Sportage EX,
the Nissan Xterra, and the Isuzu VehiCross.
</P>
<P>
   --Not buglike at all but out there on the edge where SUV meets
car meets sport vehicle are the BMW X5 and the Mercedes ML55 AMG _
both as comfortable at up to 135-150 m.p.h. as they are off road.
</P>
<P>
   --Seeing this evolution in SUVs made me wonder how long Jeep can
wait before designing something beyond the basic box (rounding off
corners on Cherokees is not a major design statement) that will
appeal to younger drivers.
</P>
<P>
   --You want cars that look fast and sleek just sitting there?
Here are a few that caught my eye: the Saab Aero 9-5, the BMW M5,
the Cadillac Catera, the Chevrolet Monte Carlo, the Subaru Imprezza
RS all-wheel-drive, the Audi TT Quattro, and the CL 500 Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   --Looking futuristic yet retro was the new Ford Thunderbird,
this one a yellow bird, its doors open like wings and exposing a
plush interior as the car spun on its platform.
</P>
<P>
   --Remember the old Dodge Power Wagon: looming, almost toothy up
at the grill. A prototype at the show was definitely modern, but
decidedly evocative of the old beast. If those buglike SUVs ever
marched to war, this Power Wagon could lead them.
</P>
<P>
   --The rush to build the four-door truck that is an SUV that is a
car proceeds headlong with Ford's F-150 Supercab, the Chevrolet
Silverado, the Dakota Sport, the Nissan Frontier, and the Toyota
Tundra.
</P>
<P>
   --Clashing examples of SUVs turned into one of the above: the
Ford Explorer Sport Trac is the SUV with a bed added and it works
superbly. The Lincoln attempt _ turning a Navigator into a
Blackwood _ is just plain ugly. A Lincoln SUV-pickup? Spare us.
</P>
<P>
   --And finally, one thing any good auto show needs is a display
of exotics, those cars most folks don't even get to see up close
and personal, let alone own. I know the intent of the show is to
sell, but a Ferrari or Lamborghini display sprinkled here and there
would add greatly to the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Update:
</P>
<P>
   In a review of the Mercury Sable a few weeks back, I wrote that
the car had an intermittent but troubling wind noise. Credit the
Ford Motor Co. with jumping on the problem. The company sent an
engineer out to test the car and determined that some of the rails
that guide the windows up and down to tight closings had been
incorrectly installed. Since the car was a factory prototype, it's
not a problem you should expect on production models.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3855 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTO-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      11-18 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 JETTA TDI _ A DIESEL THAT'S FUN TO DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The time: A glorious Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The place: Interstate 95 in New Hampshire and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The car: A 2000 VW Jetta TDI. The TDI signifies that a
turbocharged, direct-injection diesel engine is powering us along.
</P>
<P>
   We're zipping along about 70 miles per hour in the middle lanes
as a steady line of SUVs zooms past in the high-speed lane. Most
have one or two people aboard and don't look to be loaded with
anything more than a suitcase or two.
</P>
<P>
   I turn to Mrs. G and say: ``It's a self-righteous feeling to be
driving a vehicle that's getting 49 miles per gallon while all
those cars are getting about a third of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, self-righteousness only counts for so much. The truth
is that this Jetta is flat-out fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My prior experience with diesels was limited.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, a former colleague racked up 100,000 miles on a
diesel VW Rabbit and used to rave about how much he loved the car _
and the great gas mileage it got.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Roy, a mechanic for a fleet of oil trucks, had a diesel
Chevy pickup truck in the late '70s. He had nothing but trouble and
couldn't get rid of it soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   My new son-in-law, Stefano, drives a turbocharged Fiat Punto
around Milan. My few rides in the car have shown it to be a totally
reliable vehicle. It has big rubber bumpers for forcing its way
into parking spaces; it's easy on gas; and it more than holds its
own on the high-speed autostradas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus I was somewhat less than fully prepared when this Jetta TDI
arrived for a test drive.
</P>
<P>
   Did I have to deal with letting glow plugs heat up before it
would start? (No.) Would it give itself away with rocks-in-a-pail
diesel vibration? (No . . . just enough rattling at idle to let you
know it was a diesel.) Would it smoke like an 18-wheeler? (No
again.)
</P>
<P>
   This is a nifty package. On the road, it's hard to believe that
there's only 90 horsepower under the hood emanating from 116 cubic
inches (1.9 liters). The TDI cruises effortlessly at highway speeds
_ moving with the flow of traffic anywhere from 5 to 15 m.p.h. over
the posted limits. From a dead stop, it effortlessly climbs the
mountain road leading to home.
</P>
<P>
   At 60 m.p.h., the tach read 2,000 r.p.m. _ a tried-and-true
benchmark for long engine life.
</P>
<P>
   We'd driven it well over 300 miles and the gas gauge had barely
dropped to midway, leading to a common first reaction: ``That gauge
is broken!''
</P>
<P>
   The Jetta's previous driver had complained because the best
mileage he could get was 49.5. We were hoping to hit 50, but a
frantic call from VW recalled the test car before we reached the
pumps. It seems that someone put out the word (erroneously) that
the car hadn't been cleared to be sold in Massachusetts (it has).
</P>
<P>
   Our abbreviated test was a disappointment, but it didn't prevent
the family from reaching a conclusion: This package is a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certain cars and certain engine-gearing combinations just seem
to click with me. The first time I really appreciated it in a
four-cylinder was in a '94 Honda EX. Later, I came across it in a
Mazda Protege ES. This Jetta hit my personal bull's-eye by putting
its torque just where you want to use it _ on highway on-ramps, in
passing situations, when accelerating from the endless traffic
lights and stop signs we deal with daily. Did you ever notice that
TV commercials rarely place the product in a traffic jam _ unless
the car is going to magically fly over it all?
</P>
<P>
   The reason to write about this Jetta was strictly the diesel
engine. Royal Ford, who regularly reviews autos for the Globe, gave
the top-of-the-line V6 Jetta a solid thumbs-up earlier this fall,
and we found no reason to argue with his review.
</P>
<P>
   The TDI was the basic GL trim level and has an MSRP of $17,995.
</P>
<P>
   As the price of gas marches toward $1.50 a gallon _ up about 40
percent since spring when I actually filled up for 89 cents a
gallon _ you'd think folks might look more closely at diesels, but
VW's Steve Keyes doesn't think that's the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows that gas would have to hit $2 a gallon _
and maybe a lot higher _ before folks would buy for economy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there are diesel fans out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe 5 percent of the market will look at a diesel,'' said
Keyes. ``And those are the folks you can't get out of the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Count me among them. Self-righteous? Not really. Just a guy
savoring a car that's fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The back door shape. You have to make like a matador dodging a
bull to let the chest-high curve of the door past you.
</P>
<P>
   --The center armrest. In the down position, it interferes with
shifting, using the handbrake, and fastening seat belts. In the up
position, you can't get at the stuff stored in the top container _
cell phone, directions, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The red and blue dashboard lights.
</P>
<P>
   --Trunk space. You have to see it to believe it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $17,995 &QL; 
Price as tested: $17,995 &QL; 
Horsepower 90 /Torque: 155 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 98.9 inches / 172.3 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 68.3 inches/ 56.9 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 2873 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
