u v BC-NEW-SCIENTIST-BUDGET-     11-18 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-SCIENTIST-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This budget has been transmitted three times _ into
the ``v'' advisory, ``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news
files.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Thursday, Nov. 18,
1999, and anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New
York Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAST DINOSAURS MAY HAVE ROASTED ALIVE &LR;  _ The dinosaurs may have
perished in a gas-fuelled firestorm, claims a team of American
oceanographers. They believe that huge shock waves generated by the
asteroid or comet colliding with the ocean floor would have freed
vast quantities of methane trapped beneath the Earth's surface,
which set the air ablaze. 600 words. By Michael Day. Slugged:
BC-DINOSAURS-ROASTED-ALIVE-NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL WALKING ROBOT NEEDS HELP WITH BALANCE &LR;  _ Engineers in
Australia are building a two-legged industrial robot inspired by
the robotic ''exoskeleton'' worn by Sigourney Weaver in the movie
''Aliens.'' The Robolift will be able to walk about doing things no
forklift truck ever could. 600 words. By Mark Schrope. Slugged:
BC-INDUSTRIAL-WALING-ROBOT-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF)
