<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-CRASH _ CAIRO _ The latest from Egypt as the investigation
continues into the crash of EgyptAir Flight 990. The anger of
Egyptians and the family of co-pilot Gameel el-Batuouty grows as
accusations of his intentionally crashing the plane to commit
suicide become rampant in U.S. media. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-LENNY _ SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ Hurricane Lenny, an
unusually powerful late-season storm, continued to pound the
eastern Caribbean on Thursday. The storm halted its northeastern
movement and made it difficult for any type of rescue effort to get
to devastated islands. Developing. (Williams, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: Mike Williams is attempting to get a charter flight to St.
Croix and is expected to file from there. He would be one of only
two reporters there.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-OSCE _ ISTANBUL _ The chill of Cold War seemed to be
revived on Thursday as President Clinton and Russian President
Boris Yeltsin faced off at a summit of world leaders over Chechnya.
Developing. (Deans, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OSCE-JOHNSON _ ISTANBUL _ An interview, if possible, with U.S.
Ambassador to the Vienna-based OSCE, David Johnson, a career
diplomat and young father of three from Columbus, Ga. Developing.
(Deans, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-YELTSIN _ ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Sometimes history unfolds
on the fly, even in the most scripted of moments. (Deans, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-FOOD _ WASHINGTON _ Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman and
John Koskinen, chairman of the President's Council on Y2K
Conversion, join food industry officials Thursday for an
announcement on the Y2K readiness of the nation's food supply.
(Geewax, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   FLU _ WASHINGTON _ The National Council on Patient Information
and Education holds an event to discuss new flu drugs, flu
prevention and how to recognize and treat the virus' symptoms.
Participants will also discuss a Gallup poll on American attitudes
regarding the flu virus that is scheduled to be released Thursday.
(Schultz, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CIVICS _ WASHINGTON _ About one-third of students scored above
the ``basic'' level and about one-fourth scored below in civics
test results to be released Thursday by the National Asssessment of
Educational Progress. Experts split over whether that is a good or
bad performance by the 22,000 4th, 8th and 12th graders who took
the test last winter. (Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   With CIVICS-DATA (Eds: No state rankings; national results only)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-AUDIT _ WASHINGTON _ The inspector general of the
Education Department is expected to report to Congress late
Thursday afternoon that the department's financial records for
fiscal 1998 (cq) were so fragmented that they couldn't be audited.
Education Secretary Richard Riley is furious that Republicans
started blaming him for this Wednesday, before he or they had seen
the report. (Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   FEDBUD-MYSTERY - WASHINGTON _ Congress rushed to vote Thursday
on a $490 billion spending bill without giving members an
opportunity to see what they're paying for. The huge ``omnibus''
legislation, was wrapped up behind closed doors the night before.
It will be days or longer before most members and the public find
out what's in it, but many expect key members to ``earmark''
spending projects for their districts. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-AID _ WASHINGTON _ Congress members representing
flood-ravaged parts of North Carolina comment on the disaster aid
contained in the final appropriations package being voted on
Thursday in the House. (Dart, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE _ COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ A 40-foot pyramid of logs
being assembled for Texas A&AMP;M's traditional pregame bonfire
collapsed early today while dozens of students were climbing on it.
At least four students were killed and 25 were injured. Hours after
the collapse, at least one person was trapped live in the rubble.
Officials were performing head counts at the university's residence
halls in an effort to account for everybody who may have been
working on the structure. (Austin American-Statesman) WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-PARENTS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Jupiter-Tequesta
Athletic Association has a novel idea for the 6,000 kids in its
youth leagues. Make good sportsmanship mandatory _ for the parents.
Beginning Jan. 1, the JTAA will be the first youth group in the
nation to require parents to attend an ethics class. (O'Meilia,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: Moving in both (a) national and (s) sports categories.)
</P>
<P>
   HITLER-SILVERWARE _ ATLANTA _ Auction of Hitler tableware, at
Atlanta's Great Gatsby's, winds down. We take stock of the
criticism, noting that this sort of thing is likely to continue,
given that WWII vets are dying and their families will look to sell
their war trophies. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDCLUB _ ATLANTA _ The government's charges of organized crime
involvement against an Atlanta strip club and its owner and
operator sound tough on the surface, but most of those charges are
built on a filament of an association that occurred 15 years ago.
The indictment says the association with the Gambino mob continues,
but it is short on specifics. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-MONEY _ WASHINGTON _ A month after Senate Republicans
killed efforts to ban soft money, Time Warner executives announced
that the company will stop making the unregulated donations from
its corporate treasury to the political parties. The move makes
Time Warner _ the parent of Cable News Network, Time magazine and
Warner Brothers _ the fifth company to stop making donations of
soft money, so named because they are not subject to federal
contribution limits. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-HILLARY _ Maybe it's her we should be building a library
for, not her husband. It probably goes without saying that Hillary
Rodham Clinton has broken the mold when it comes to U.S. first
ladies. It's still about 18 months until her husband leaves office,
and yet some 40 books already have been written largely or
completely about her. (Even the relatively controversial Nancy
Reagan barely hit double figures _ well after leaving the White
House.) And apparently, the deluge is just beginning. Last month it
was ``Bill and Hillary _ The Marriage.'' Come November it will be
publication of dueling tomes (including one from ``Passages''
author Gail Sheehy) purporting to take us inside Hillary's head.
And don't even get us started on the writers who've already signed
contracts to produce books about the all-but-declared Hillary
Clinton-Rudy Giuliani Senate race. A look at the phenomenon of
Hillary Literature and speculation on when _ and if _ it will ever
end. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (e) entertainment and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ At a Washington court hearing Tuesday, a judge will
determine what intimate details Newt Gingrich's lover, Callista
Bisek, will have to reveal under oath about their relationship.
(Stanford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-BROWN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ He's one of a select club in Texas,
a state senator whose imprint is on most of the environmental
legislation passed in the last two decades. He's talked about as a
candidate for lieutenant governor. But Sen. Buster Brown's had a
tough year, defending against charges of sexual harassment in the
workplace. Last week, the Republican Party in his Southeast Texas
district, which has been sending him to Austin since 1981, turned
against him. The Lake Jackson Republican Party said he should
resign because his sexual escapades make the party look bad.
(Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
