<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3915 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-NEW-MUSIC-BOS &LR;      11-18 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-MUSIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST IN MUSIC COMES OF AGE IN LOS ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The suits were a sign.
</P>
<P>
   There weren't many of them, to be sure, and they were in the
requisite black. But the fact that anyone at all was wearing one
drew more attention than did the conference goer with magenta hair.
It was unintended _ and sometimes unwelcome _ evidence that both
they and the on-line music industry are maturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad, isn't it?'' said Sunjay Guleria, clad in a black
blazer over blue jeans and impossibly hip eyewear. ``I remember
when I used to be one of the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Guleria is 29, hardly ancient by any standard. The exhibit hall
at the three-day extravaganza known as webnoize, put on by the
Stoneham-based company of the same name, was packed with people his
age. More than a few industry veterans have already cracked 30, a
pronouncement often accompanied by a wince. Anyone over 40 was an
obvious minority.
</P>
<P>
   But in an industry as young and as demographically specific as
digital music, youth is relative. It also rules. Among the
conference attendees were teenagers available to explain some of
the latest technologies and recent college graduates congratulating
each other on taking their companies public.
</P>
<P>
   Overheard in the Century Plaza Hotel lobby, one early
twentysomething to another, both wearing yellow-tinted sunglasses
indoors, one with a cell phone headset plugged into his ear: ``Hi.
Nice to meet you. Congratulations on those stock options.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the nearly 1,000 people who had registered for the
conference, which sold out at $895 a ticket, they had come to
Southern California as much to see and to be seen, or to find out
who's up to what in the fast-moving world of digital music, as to
attend panel discussions with titles like ``Virtual Skulls &AMP;
Crossbones: Music Piracy and the Internet'' and ``Staffing for the
Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   But upstairs in the lobby bar, and on the patio where spreads of
sushi and fajitas and linguini were set out, the talk was also
about what after-hours concerts and receptions to attend. Microsoft
Corp.'s bowling party was invitation only. Everyone was invited to
hear the group Supreme Beings of Leisure play at Listen.com's West
Hollywood gala. Webnoize may not come close in size or power to
Comdex, the mega-computer conference taking place in Las Vegas this
week, but it was where computer geekiness and cool converged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a level of excitement here; everyone seems pumped,''
said Monty Schmidt, 35, president of Sonic Foundry Media Services.
``You can sense that people know they're on to something.''
</P>
<P>
   That something is the ability to sell music on the Internet,
circumventing the traditional record labels by allowing listeners
to download music directly to their computers and then carry it
with them on portable players. These days, anyone can sell their
music on line, and sometimes it seems everyone is. In the
competitive world of Web sites now aimed at teenage and young adult
listeners, the garage band is god.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh definitely there's going to be a fallout,'' said Matt
Garman, 23, who described himself as Riffage.com's ``e-commerce
wizard,'' then handed over a blue business card with the more
formal title of online commerce manager. ``There aren't enough
bands for all the sites. It's going to be about who can get the
bands, who has enough money to do the marketing, who's the more
artist friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also, according to display after display, about
interaction with the audience. Almost to a web site, each one
claimed a unique feature. Each one claimed that users in effect
control the sites themselves. Still, one claim was indisputable:
the way young people interact with music has less to do with
flipping on the stereo than with becoming a part of the equipment
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Bane, a 33-year-old strategic account executive at STV
Streaming Video Solutions, said: ``Absolutely, convergence is where
it's at. There's a light at the end of the tunnel, but we don't
know how long that tunnel is or if there's another tunnel after it.
But we're all racing to be the one to get there first.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Roli Jr., 29, president and publisher of webnoize, which in
part covers the on-line music industry, added: ``The music idustry
is not just the music industry anymore. It's how do you do videos,
how do you do games, how do you get people involved.''
</P>
<P>
   At the mycaster.com booth, for instance, Jason Kay, vice
president of business development, demonstrated a personal
broadcast system that allows users to become virtual disc jockeys,
creating their own radio stations and even airing their own
thoughts over the Internet. Among the stations operating: ``A
Stoned Guy in Texas'' and a group of Australian college students
who have open-mike discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs in a private suite, the icast.com senior vice
president, Geoffrey Miller, promised to ``give members the tools to
express themselves creatively way past home pages.'' In
non-Webspeak, that means users will be able to edit their own music
and videos, then share them with the rest of the world once the
entertainment portal launches in January.
</P>
<P>
   The only downside to all the digital downloading appeared to be
that with only so many eyeballs and advertising dollars to go
around, no one is making money at it yet.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't dampen the party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
