<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-FOOD19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K EXPECTED TO CAUSE FEW FOOD SUPPLY PROBLEMS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans shopping for their New Year's Eve parties
will find an impressive bounty in the grocery stores, despite any
small problems caused by the Y2K bug, Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in front of mounds of groceries stuffed into carts at a
Giant Food store in suburban Washington, Glickman proclaimed that
``the food system is not at risk'' of failure from the Y2K bug, a
programming flaw that could cause some computerized equipment to
fail on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that grocery stores may be hit with ``some spot
shortages'' of perishable foods in late December as people
stockpile before the date change. In addition, a few older
computers in stores might malfunction. ``But the problems will be
negligible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesalers and retailers carry a 30- to 60-day supply of
nonperishable food, he said, so even if power outages or other
difficulties disrupt normal food production, the nation could
absorb the impact with little effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Grocery Manufacturers of America, a trade association, says
food makers have spent $1.8 billion fixing and testing computers to
avoid any production problems Jan. 1. Stores also are in good
shape, with 96 percent of all checkout scanners now set to properly
process date information.
</P>
<P>
   John Koskinen, chairman of the President's Council on Y2K
Conversion, also participated in the press conference. For months,
he has been urging consumers to have on hand a three-day supply of
food and water as the New Year approaches. But he warned against
waiting until the final days of December to shop.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the period between Christmas and New Year's Eve
will be a ``high-activity time,'' with many people preparing for
millennium parties. If everyone rushes for the cheese balls and
salami at the same time on New Year's Eve, stores could see spot
shortages. ``Don't wait till the last day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
