<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BODY-ART-EXHIBIT (New York) _ ``Body Art: Marks of Identity,''
at the American Museum of Natural History, is a transparent effort
on the part of a family-style institution to heat up its image and
pull in a fresh audience, one that probably couldn't care less
about large, extinct reptiles with tiny brains. The theme is
personal adornment of the most intimate kind, usually applied
directly onto or into the skin. The exhibition _ smart, extremely
entertaining and assembled in record time _ is geared to the
current fashion-as-art vogue. The packed installation offers just
enough bare, multicultural flesh to inspire viewer rubbernecking,
without actually being an adults-only affair. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   GULBENKIAN-COLLECTION (New York) _ What is there to be said
about the Metropolitan Museum of Art's wonderful exhibition of
treasures from the legendary collection that Calouste Gulbenkian
assiduously brought into being in the first half of this century,
and then left to the world in the form a private museum in Lisbon
where he spent the last dozen years of his life? See it, enjoy it,
pore over its every object from beginning to end, that is, from a
17th-century Armenian illuminated Bible to a vitrine of three
Japanese lacquers. In between lie extraordinary examples of Islamic
and Turkish textiles and ceramics, 18th-century silver, European
painting and the Art Nouveau jewelry of Rene Lalique. Glean all you
can about the many forms that visual power can take, and the spells
they cast on generation after generation down through time. By
Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   KATE-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' at the Beck.
Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
