<P>
   &UR; BILL BRADLEY'S NAOMI WOLF &QL; 
 &UR; DICK MORRIS TAKES HIS ACT TO THE INTERNET &QL; 
 &UR; ARE BRADLEY'S JOCK ENDORSERS REALLY HELPING? &QL; 
 &UR; THE DEMISE OF `ULTIMATE FIGHTING' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SLATE, the premier online magazine of politics and culture, is
now available to your readers from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   To purchase these ``separate buy'' articles from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   1. BILL BRADLEY'S NAOMI WOLF, by Jacob Weisberg
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Al Gore isn't the only candidate with a guru.
Bill Bradley has one too, a Harvard professor by the name of Cornel
West. While West is not being paid by the Bradley campaign, as
Naomi Wolf is by Gore's campaign, he plays an analogous role as
affiliated intellectual. Where Wolf advises Gore about how to score
with women voters, West is helping Bradley appeal to blacks. And as
in the Gore-Wolf case, the benefits of the Bradley-West
relationship are clearly reciprocal.
</P>
<P>
   1,200 words: Slugged BC-BRADLEY-GURU-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   2. DICK MORRIS TAKES HIS ACT TO THE INTERNET, by William Saletan
</P>
<P>
   Like his past careers as Bill Clinton's savior, confessor,
accuser, and pundit-translator, Dick Morris' latest incarnation as
Internet democracy-builder is an act. He's not building direct
democracy with his vote.com Web site. He's building a rather
different political system, which might more aptly be called
dickmorrisy.
</P>
<P>
   1,500 words: Slugged BC-DICK-MORRIS-WEBSITE-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   3. ARE BRADLEY'S JOCK ENDORSERS REALLY HELPING? by William
Saletan
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of history's greatest basketball players headlined a
Madison Square Garden fund-raiser for Bill Bradley last Sunday. The
event, complete with cheerleaders, movie stars, and lights and
music reminiscent of an NBA game, enthralled the press. But Bradley
has pitched himself as a man of substance in a world corrupted by
glitz. So it's worth asking whether the jocks' media blitz for
Bradley, punctuated by their full-court press on Sunday's political
talk shows, conveyed anything of substance.
</P>
<P>
   1,200 words: Slugged BC-BRADLEY-JOCK-POLITICS-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   4. THE DEMISE OF `ULTIMATE FIGHTING' by David Plotz
</P>
<P>
   ``Fight Club,'' a movie about a fictional organization of men
who strip down and beat each other to pulp, has provoked more than
its share of media hand-wringing. It has not, however, sparked an
iota of interest in a real organization of men who strip down and
beat each other to pulp: the Ultimate Fighting Championship. UFC's
flameout from national sensation to total irrelevance is a tragedy
of American sports, a cautionary tale of prudishness, heavy-handed
politics, and cultural myopia.
</P>
<P>
   1,900 words: Slugged BC-ULTIMATE-FIGHTING-SLATE
</P>
</TEXT>
