   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-WAGE-LAWS (Los Angeles) _ An increasing number of
employers who do business with government are suddenly finding
themselves required by local ordinances to grant big raises and
benefits to their low-wage workers. Forty-one cities and counties
in 17 states, particularly those with large constituencies of
low-wage workers, have enacted living wage laws since the
movement's birth five years ago. As one follows another _ lately at
the rate of a new ordinance a month _ the living wage movement has
broadened from a simple emphasis on higher wages into a wide range
of requirements involving health insurance, vacations, sick pay,
job security and incentives to unionize. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
