A3972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-TEEN-FILES-BOS &LR;      11-18 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TEEN-FILES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEEN FILES' PROBES YOUTH VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TEEN FILES: THE TRUTH ABOUT TEEN VIOLENCE 
Produced by: Arnold Shapiro 
Hosted by: Leeza Gibbons 
Date: Friday, 8 p.m. 
On: UPN 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rikki, a stout 14-year-old girl, admits she's done things like
bust ``somebody in the face with a skate.'' Her powers of
intimidation make people ``nice'' to her, she believes. Another
city girl, Dee, just missed being shot in a hail of drive-by
bullets because of her gang affiliation. Teenaged Seyha has been a
gang member since the age of 12 and has been incarcerated now and
then for violent misdeeds. Matt, a 14-year-old white suburbanite,
tried to commit suicide three times and, we learn in ``Teen Files:
The Truth About Violence,'' was institutionalized for plotting a
Columbine-like massacre inspired by the Colorado killings.
</P>
<P>
   In all, a diverse group of eight troubled California teens with
a history of violence was assembled for this UPN documentary, which
debuts Friday at 8 p.m. There is much that is wrong with the
two-hour program, especially its disconcertingly peppy music-video
style, but there is a lot more that is right.
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of a month, producer Arnold Shapiro filmed the
kids in a number of provocative settings designed to elicit
understanding of their violent impulses and explore their potential
for positive change. For example, they visit an LA hospital where a
trauma surgeon shows them gruesome and sometimes pitiful outcomes
of street mayhem. The film's most emotionally wrenching moments are
kindled by a visit to Columbine, where the teenagers are asked to
confront the agonies of tearful parents and teachers remembering
individuals killed in the bloodbath there.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, ``The Truth About Violence,'' which also covers the
group's activities at an Outward Bound-like wilderness camp, seems
contrived. At times, it plays like a hybrid of MTV's
quasidocumentary ``Real World'' series and ``Scared Straight,''
Shapiro's late-'70s film about a program to shock juveniles out of
antisocial behavior by taking them into a state prison. It can be,
alternatively, too tidy, too politically correct (despite the
clouds of profanity), and soap-operatic in its melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   But under the artifice _ including tasteless gunfire sound
effects and familiarly choppy MTV-inspired editing _ is an often
powerfully affecting and valuable account of troubled youngsters
with a chance at a better future. By encouraging them to plumb
their own pasts and interact frankly with one another, it digs
beneath swaggering, threatening teen stereotypes to reveal bright
kids struggling with painful histories. As young children, many of
them witnessed horrific violence or were themselves beaten or
sexually abused. No wonder one girl won't permit herself to say,
``I love you'' to anyone, or why, for another, it's such a
challenge to even imagine making friends or being kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truth About Violence'' makes a convincing case that with
committed support and attention, young people such as these can
change and perhaps even flourish. What it fails to emphasize,
however, is the lack of social programs and of the political will
required to make such transformations possible on a national level.
</P>
<P>
   UPN is to be commended for broadcasting ``The Truth About
Violence.'' It's worth noting, though, that the struggling network
has recently improved its fortunes with ``Smackdown,'' a weekly
wrestling spectacle that has earned high ratings and the
condemnation of many critics appalled by its vulgarity and bloodily
violent content.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
