<HEADER>
A3981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-test5-HNS &LR;      11-18 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-test5-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Testing. Please ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- From vessels to valves, doctors are engineering
replacement parts for ailing hearts as well as improving arteries
for bypass surgery. And now -- for the first time -- a complete
heart valve has been grown in the lab using cells from blood vessel
walls in sheep, researchers reported Sunday at the American Heart
Association meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   The sheep cells were seeded into a biodegradable, synthetic
form, or scaffold. As they grew, they were subjected to increasing
flows and pressures to mimic the blood flow patterns in the heart,
which made the growing valve stronger. After 14 days, the cells had
grown into the desired shape -- including flaplike structures that
allow the blood to flow in only one direction.
</P>
<P>
   The valves were surgically implanted into the sheep, where they
worked well for more than five months.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are interested in figuring out how to grow human
valves from a patient's own tissue because the current options are
so limited. The pig valves now used in humans stiffen and stop
working after a time. Patients with mechanical valves have to take
blood-thinning drugs to prevent blood clots. A patient's body
wouldn't reject nted it in the patient. The DNA ``turned off'' the
genes responsible for the growth of an abnormal layer in the wall
of the engrafted vein, which eventually leads to blockage.
</P>
<P>
   In the year following their bypass surgery, the patients who
received gene therapy had fewer than half of the reblockages of the
patients who received surgery alone.
</P>
<P>
   Although the study was small, the results were statistically
significant, Mann said, showing promise for a treatment that is
fast and relatively cheap. ``This procedure could end up having a
major impact,'' Mann said, ``not only on long term success of all
types of bypass surgery, but also on the cost of treating graft
blockages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1517EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FLU19-COX     11-18 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH FLU BUG ON THE MARCH, ELDERLY WARNED TO GET SHOTS
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A health group urged older people Thursday to be
vaccinated against influenza, warning that 90 percent of people who
die from the disease are over age 65.
</P>
<P>
   Flu cases were reported in 30 states during the past week, said
Dr. Rashid Ahmed Chotani of John Hopkins University said at a news
conference held by the National Council on Patient Information and
Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flu is here, and we need to worry about it in a big way,''
Chotani said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Golodner, chairwoman of the council, said that ``flu, most
of which is preventable through vaccination, unfortunately takes a
heavy toll each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Influenza infects nearly 40 million Americans a year, and kills
about 20,000 of them, the council said. Americans spend nearly $4.6
million a year treating the flu.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll released Thursday found that one in five Americans
reported having the flu within the last three months. One-fourth of
those with symptoms said they were treated by a doctor, and more
than half reported missing work.
</P>
<P>
   People with flu symptoms should contact a doctor within two days
and should consult their pharmacist for over-the-counter
medications, Golodner said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccinations reduce the risk of death from influenza by nearly
80 percent. Besides the elderly, patients with chronic illness, and
pregnant women are more susceptible to the flu and should be
vaccinated, Chotani said.
</P>
<P>
   Flu shots are offered at local heath clinics, hospitals, and
shopping malls for about $7 to $10.
</P>
<P>
   The council also announced a national campaign to educate
doctors and patients on how prevent and treat the flu. The
campaign, which includes public service announcements and a flu
awareness Internet site (www.talkaboutrx.org), will end in March
2000. The council also has a toll-free number: 1-877-358-2638.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
