<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORS QUESTION VALUE OF BUSINESS SCHOOL EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, how much did you learn at the last business seminar you
attended?
</P>
<P>
   Was it worth the several hundred, or several thousand, dollars
that you or your company shelled out to fine-tune your skills,
advance your knowledge or propel your career?
</P>
<P>
   Or was it just a break from the office routine, with lunch and a
nice hotel conference room thrown in?
</P>
<P>
   In the growing world of business education, whether it's Harvard
or some two-person computer training team, most companies are
receiving far less value than the billions that they are spending
would suggest, according to two established English business
writers.
</P>
<P>
   Business schools are big business but are not living up to the
standards they preach, Stuart Crainer and Des Dearlove write.
</P>
<P>
   Business writers for publications such as ``The London Times''
and ``The Financial Times'', the authors set their investigative
sights on business schools in their provocative ``Gravy Training:
Inside the Business of Business Schools'' (Jossey-Bass, 315 pages,
$).
</P>
<P>
   Companies spend more than $100 billion annually worldwide on
training, according to a Penn State study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dauntingly, (the study) estimates that over half of this is
wasted as much is carried out with no objective,'' the authors
write.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the $3 billion so-called executive education
industry branch of the business school curriculum. With courses
ranging from $1,395 for a three-day seminar at Vanderbilt
University on effective management techniques to $40,500 for a
nine-week advanced management program at Harvard, it's easy to see
how the authors arrived at their title.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they all have in common is a price tag that reflects the
buying power of business,'' Crainer and Dearlove write.
</P>
<P>
   Price aside, how have business schools measured up in their
effectiveness on American business? Not too well, the authors
argue.
</P>
<P>
   Laden with so-called strategic planning and attention to the
bottom line, business schools have notoriously ignored the human
element, an effect that was felt painfully during the early '80s as
corporate America lost its market share on household names to
foreign competitors, the authors suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only were the business school graduates of the time
ill-equipped for managing real people, their analytical skills also
proved ineffective as companies were outflanked by more nimble
competitors,'' they write. ``The new arrivals _ many of them
upstarts from Silicon Valley and Japan _ broke the mold. They
seemed to be making up strategy as they went along. They had not
been to business school.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect of business schools on wealth creation is also
questionable, Crainer and Dearlove write.
</P>
<P>
   ``If business schools were supposed to turn out entrepreneurs
who would go forth and multiply _ creating jobs and adding to GDP _
then they have not succeeded,'' they write. ``When it comes to
successful business start-ups, with a few notable exceptions such
as Dell Computers, business school graduates are conspicuous by
their absence.''
</P>
<P>
   Crainer and Dearlove suggest that this inability to meet true
market needs is causing business schools to lose to a new
competitor: company universities.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than a thousand corporate universities, with
names such as Walton Institute in Arkansas, Home Depot University
in Atlanta, Target Stores University in Minneapolis and Dell
University in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola University supplies 550,000 student days a year and
costs $170 million to run. But all 139,000 Motorola employees are
expected to train at least 40 hours a year there, and Motorola
calculates that every dollar invested in training reaps $33. The
training facility even has its own international MBA program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference between Motorola U. and a conventional
university is the absence of a football team,'' Crainer and
Dearlove write.
</P>
<P>
   With so much being invested in advanced or continuing education
by business, it might be worth picking up this book before you or
someone under you sign up for that next course.
</P>
<P>
   Finance &AMP; Accounting: How to Keep Your Books and Manage Your
Finances Without an MBA, a CPA, or a Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   By Suzanne Caplan
</P>
<P>
   Adams Media Corp., $17.95
</P>
<P>
   ``What is a general ledger?'' is the name of Chapter 1 in this
back-to-basics book, illustrating how business author, consultant
and former small-business chief executive Suzanne Chapman starts at
the beginning. Many managers of small businesses delegate finances
and accounting to outside sources and rarely look over the monthly
statements. This is a big mistake, Chapman warns. She takes readers
painlessly through the processes for a better understanding of the
numbers game.
</P>
<P>
   User's Guide to the Information Age
</P>
<P>
   By Kenneth M. Morris
</P>
<P>
   Lightbulb Press, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   Smart appliances, cyberlibraries and distance learning are some
of the subjects covered in this slim volume of 160 pages. Filled
with colorful graphics and a hip layout, this book shows users how
to get the most out of the Information Age. From tips on buying a
computer to blocking and filtering information you don't want on
your home screen, this book covers the waterfront in a quick, sassy
style.
</P>
<P>
   Simplify Your Workday: How to Survive _ And Thrive _ From Nine
to Five
</P>
<P>
   By Barbara Hemphill and Pamela Quinn Gibbard
</P>
<P>
   Reader's Digest, $17.95
</P>
<P>
   Every interruption in your workday by a phone call or co-worker
costs you 10 to 15 minutes after you put down the phone or close
your office door. office organization gurus Barbara Hemphill and
Pamela Quinn discuss dealing with the throng, as well as hundreds
of other topics related to business and home life. Not many new
ideas here, but they are organized in one book, which could help
those who haven't read up on time management and related issues.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1529EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
