<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
 
GO TO THE MAIL WITH STONE COLD STEVE AUSTIN (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My wife's cousins are big fans of Stone Cold Steve Austin.
Where can I write to request an autographed picture? _ J.K.M., West
Pittston, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Austin or any other World Wrestling Federation
member in care of Titan Towers, 1241 E. Main St., Box 3857,
Stamford, CT 06905-3857.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, whose real name is Steve Williams, is a 34-year-old
native of Victoria, Texas, who played football for two years at the
University of North Texas. He left school in 1986, 17 hours shy of
a physical education degree.
</P>
<P>
   After attending a Dallas wrestling school run by Chris Adams,
Austin fought his first match in 1989 at the Sportatorium.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Mitchell Ryan in any current TV shows? _ J.S., Midland
Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ryan is a cast member of the ABC sitcom ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,''
portraying Greg's well-heeled father, Edward Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   The 71-year-old actor has more than 100 TV and film credits,
including the recent films ``Grosse Pointe Blank,'' ``Liar Liar''
and ``The Devil's Own.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time Ryan has starred in a series with Susan
Sullivan, his ``Dharma'' spouse and a member of the same theater
group. They were also in the 1978 TV drama ``Having Babies'' and
the 1976 movie ``Midway.''
</P>
<P>
   You can write to Ryan or any member of the show's cast in care
of ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' 20th Century Fox TV, 10201 W. Pico Blvd.,
Trailer 779, Los Angeles, CA 90035.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I redeem blue stamps? _ C.G., Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A: If you're referring to stamps issued by Blue Chip Stamps, you
can get redemption books and a catalog by calling (323) 724-8600.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Chip Stamps was founded by nine grocery and drugstore
companies in 1956. Berkshire Hathaway acquired a controlling
interest in the company and merged with Blue Chip in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   During the '70s, Blue Chip earned more than $120 million each
year because of unredeemed stamp books, enabling Berkshire to
purchase See's Candies and other companies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1535EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
