<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3999 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-CHILDREN'S-BOOKS-HNS &LR;      11-18 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN'S-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S BOOKS: OF TINY ACORNS, GIANT OAKS, AND SNAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KARLA EATON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marsha Danzig has created an inspirational tale in her work
``The
</P>
<P>
   Tiniest Acorn, A Story to Grow By.'' It is reminiscent of the
visual power found in ``The Biggest House in the World,'' a classic
by the late Leo Lionni. Both works deserve a pleasant pause by both
young and old because they teach lessons from which we can all
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig's work follows the best in books for kids, inspiring them
to realize their greatness and see themselves full of all the
goodness that others see.
</P>
<P>
   Lulu is this tiniest of acorns who struggles to recognize her
glory when she grows into a mighty oak.
</P>
<P>
   Only after hearing another's words of praise for her does she
realize that she is not just the acorn she used to be but, instead,
is a magnificent tree. Beyond the strong message of this story,
Danzig's book is extremely appealing to the eye, with text printed
in casual handwritten print, dialogue in different color text, and
colorful illustrations that instantly draw the reader closer.
</P>
<P>
   The tenderness of the text coupled with the tenderness of the
illustrations combine for a compelling lesson for young and old.
This message is even stronger when the reader absorbs the epilogue
where the writer explains her own background as a cancer survivor
and accomplished academic who, like Lulu, struggled to recognize
her own virtues. Danzig is using Lulu to spread words of
encouragement: We are all capable of great things.
</P>
<P>
   Another tiny creature, a snail, searches for greatness in
Lionni's work, ``The Biggest House in the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Danzig's book, this one couples a powerful message with
stunning visuals. The tale from the wise father snail encourages
his child to appreciate what he is for its many benefits, a small
snail in a small house. This allows him to move freely in the
splendor of the world, bringing him immense happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Lionni, known by many as a painter and graphic artist, was also
an accomplished children's book author and winner of four Caldecott
Honors. His fables often focused on animals and the natural world.
``It's Mine,'' ``Swimmy and Alexander'' and the ``Wind-Up Mouse''
are just a few of this prolific author's masterpieces. His
inspiring words and pictures have captured children's imaginations
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Revisiting his works is a glorious way to pay tribute to him.
</P>
<P>
   A great children's book is created in the harmony of words and
pictures. Lionni was a master of his trade, teaching, delighting,
intriguing and transporting his readers to places in his
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   In those footsteps, Marsha Danzig's first publication is an
endearing tale with an inspirational message. Whether it's a big
house or a little acorn, children will be pleased to have these
stories read and adults will be pleased to read. Big and small,
young and old, we all win.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karla Eaton, a college literature instructor, can be reached
mkeaton &LR; erols.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
