<SLUG> BC-LEVI-STRAUSS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE EXECUTIVE CHANGES LIKELY AT LEVI STRAUSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Philip Marineau, the outsider who was hired to
revive Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., has fired top executives of the
struggling San Francisco jeans manufacturer and a company spokesman
said more personnel changes were anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   After just seven weeks on the job, the former Pepsi-Cola
executive has ousted John Ermatinger, 45, president of Levi's
Americas division, and Robert Holloway, 40, vice president of
marketing for people aged 15 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   The news, effective immediately, comes just one week after
Marineau removed Levi's chief marketing officer, Gordon Shank, from
his position. Shank had spent 25 years with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good news for Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. because we are
renewing our company and positioning ourselves to be successful in
the year 2000,'' said Levi spokesman Jeff Beckman, explaining that
the firings were all part of Marineau's plan to turn the company
around. ``Part of that plan is Phil's recognition we must have the
right leadership in place to deliver those plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Marineau, who started in his new position Sept. 27, sent an
internal message to employees late Monday explaining the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``While John and Rob are both highly skilled professionals, it
is my assessment they do not have the level of experience and track
record in their current roles to accomplish what we need to be
successful,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ermatinger nor Holloway returned messages asking for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   To replace Holloway, Marineau promoted James Capon, vice
president of marketing for the U.S. young adult division (target
ages 25 to 34), to the newly created position of president of the
Levi's brand.
</P>
<P>
   Capon is identified in a lawsuit filed against the company by a
former Levi employee claiming retaliation. The employee, Patricia
Ogden, said she was fired after participating in an investigation
of Capon, who was then president of the Dockers brand, and Dockers
executive Vincent Tavani, who has since left the company, for
promoting women with whom they were having affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Beckman called the charges against Capon baseless. ``We
conducted a thorough investigation, and James was completely
exonerated,'' he said of Capon.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbi Silten, marketing director for the Slates brand, was
promoted to the newly created position of president of U.S. Dockers
and Slates brands. Silten has been with the company since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Levi will conduct a search to replace Ermatinger, but Marineau
will lead the Americas region in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   Beckman hinted at staff changes to come. He said, ``We'll be
making a number of other adjustments as we look forward, because we
are looking at other ways of consolidating and removing
redundancies.''
</P>
<P>
   In his lengthy memo, Marineau acknowledged that a number of
``experienced and accomplished'' employees have been leaving the
company, but he assured employees he had been hiring top talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to staff the organization at the appropriate size to
match our level of sales,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although still recording $6 billion in sales, Levi has been
losing its foothold in the market to other manufacturers in recent
years and reported a 13 percent drop in sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   One retail expert said Levi missed the boat on a number of key
fashion trends in the jeans market and allowed its competitors _
everyone from designers to department store brands _ to horn in on
their territory.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Liebmann, of WSL Strategic Retail, a marketing and retail
consulting firm in New York, was encouraged by the fast-moving
efSB0
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1549EST &QL; 
