<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-MICHAEL-YORK-IN-THE-OMEGA-CODE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MICHAEL YORK, `OMEGA' SPELLS SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Michael York in
a scene from ``The Omega Code.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    For more than 20 years actor Michael York has been a mainstay of
Hollywood's British-expatriate community, natural heir to David
Niven and Ronald Colman as a gentleman to the manner born.
 &HT;    He never quite attained the stardom of fellow Brits Michael
Caine or Sean Connery, however. Instead, he earned a reputation as
a reliable professional who could be counted on for a solid
performance, even if he wasn't likely to send a movie through the
box-office roof.
 &HT;    But late in October, to his own and everyone else's surprise,
York awoke to discover that his latest movie, the hardly heralded
``The Omega Code,'' was a hit in theaters across America,
outgrossing rivals starring the likes of Brad Pitt, Bruce Willis
and Michelle Pfeiffer.
 &HT;    Implausibly, the $7 million ``Omega Code,'' produced by the
low-profile, Christian-fundamentalist Trinity Broadcasting Network,
managed to earn more per theater than major-studio entries such as
Pitt's ``Fight Club'' and Willis and Pfeiffer's ``The Story of
Us.'' The Hollywood Reporter called its box-office take
``eye-popping.''
 &HT;    Though he admits to surprise at the actual numbers, York says
that in retrospect there were signs that something was happening.
 &HT;    ``Even before the film opened,'' he recalls, ``I was in Oklahoma
City, and a woman selling me a newspaper said, `I'm going to see
your movie the first day it opens.'''
 &HT;    In a limited release, ``Omega Code'' already has earned more
than $8 million, with a wider release planned in the next few
weeks. In Portland, Ore., the film _ which co-stars Casper Van
Dien, best known for ``Starship Troopers'' (l998), and English
actress Catherine Oxenberg, last seen on television's ``Dynasty'' _
sold more advance tickets than any film ever, save only ``Star
Wars: The Phantom Menace.''
 &HT;    At first, York admits, he was hesitant about doing the film,
fearing that it would come across as fundamentalist propaganda.
 &HT;    ``I first had said I wasn't interested in being in a tract,'' he
says. ``But, while it has moral underpinning, it's a millennial
thriller shot in Rome and Jerusalem.''
 &HT;    York plays Stone Alexander, a Rupert Murdoch-like media kingpin
based in Rome who hungers for the ancient knowledge hidden in a
code within the Bible _ knowledge that conveys awesome power.
 &HT;    ``And, like most power, it corrupts,'' the actor says. ``He
turns into a megalomaniac. Casper plays a guy who once worked for
Stone and then takes it upon himself to stop him.''
 &HT;    In other words, it's a classic good-vs.-evil story, a fact which
York thinks may account for much of the film's success.
 &HT;    ``TBN has grassroots-Christian folks who were complaining that
there was nothing for them to see,'' he says. ``The film took $2
million the first weekend. Now we'll see if it will cross over to
people outside of the Bible Belt.''
 &HT;    His travels across the country in his one-man show have left
York more attuned to America as a whole than is the case with many
Hollywood actors, for whom the area between New York and Los
Angeles might as well be a black hole.
 &HT;    ``What I've been hearing when I take my one-man show on the road
is that a lot of people feel that Hollywood has disenfranchised
them with all the gratuitous sex and violence masquerading as
entertainment,'' he says.
 &HT;    Not that York is much of a square. His previous film this year
had a fair bit of gratuitousness of its own _ a reprise of his role
as Basil Exposition, head of British intelligence in Mike Myers'
raunchy sequel, ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
 &HT;    ``It's hard to believe, I know,'' he says with a laugh. ``I've
been in two humongous hits in one year.''
 &HT;    It's been a while since York had that experience, though there
was a time when his films routinely earned rave reviews and bulging
box-office coffers alike.
 &HT;    His film debut was in Franco Zeffirelli's high-profile
production of ``The Taming of the Shrew'' (l966), opposite Richard
Burton and Elizabeth Taylor. The Italian director _ who had
directed York in ``Much Ado About Nothing'' at England's National
Theatre _ also cast him in ``Romeo and Juliet'' (1967).
 &HT;    The young actor worked with several other critically esteemed
directors, appearing in Joseph Losey's brilliant ``Accident''
(l966), Bob Fosse's ``Cabaret'' (l971) and Richard Lester's ``The
Three Musketeers'' (l973), as well as co-starring with fellow
up-and-comer Farrah Fawcett in the science-fiction smash ``Logan's
Run'' (l975).
 &HT;    As he aged out of his matinee-idol period, York displayed a rare
sense of perspective. Instead of burning out or dying too young
from overindulgence in the Hollywood high life, he forged a new
career for himself as a respected character actor, displaying a
poise and professionalism that are unusual in the movie industry.
 &HT;    Today he lives with his wife, the talented photographer Pat
York, in a magnificent house high in the hills above Sunset
Boulevard. At 57 he looks at least a decade younger _ young enough
to suggest that there's a Dorian Gray-style portrait aging
somewhere in his attic.
 &HT;    As that rarest of rarities, an actor who thinks about his art
and has something to say, York has lectured on the history of
acting, and is following his insightful autobiography
``Accidentally on Purpose'' (1991) with ``A Shakespearean Actor
Prepares,'' an acting treatise co-written with stage director
Adrian Brine.
 &HT;    Fans of books on tape have heard York's extremely well-modulated
tones reading a wide variety of material, from ``The Book of
Psalms'' to Anne Rice's ``The Vampire Lestat.''
 &HT;    Not that he's forsaken the screen: Besides ``The Omega Code,''
he has two other current films _ ``The Haunting of Hell House,'' a
straight-to-video gothic mystery produced by Roger Corman, based on
a Henry James short story and shot in Ireland, and ``Merchants of
Venus,'' an offbeat comedy which co-stars Beverly D'Angelo.
 &HT;    The risque ``Merchant'' was screened at the Moscow Film festival
earlier this year, as part of a Michael York retrospective _ as it
happened, one that coincided with a Kremlin exhibition of his
wife's photos.
 &HT;    It casts York as a Russian who emigrates to southern California
and, anxious not to end up driving a cab like his uncle (English
actor Brian Cox), lands a job in a marital-aids factory.
 &HT;    The classically trained British actress Prunella Gee, who
co-stars in the picture, kept telling York what an enormous switch
the role was for her.
 &HT;    ``But I told her, you don't put a label around your neck saying
`Dramatic Actor,''' York says. ``You do it all. In Britain, that's
the tradition.''
 &HT;    That's his philosophy _ stay around and stay busy.
 &HT;    ``Obviously, working in rubbish is not good for you or anyone,''
York says. ``But you have to recognize that everything is changing.
Some actors can hold off without working for years. But when I'm
not working I'm writing or lecturing, busier than when I'm filming.
 &HT;    ``And you never know what's going to happen,'' he adds.
``Studios can spend $100 million on a picture and it totally goes
bottom-up. Then you can get a `Blair Witch Project,' and it
works.''
 &HT;    Or you can get ``The Omega Code,'' which is making York a star _
all over again.
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Omega Code,'' consult the
official Website at www.theomegacode.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
