<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4029 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-NETWORKS-COMMENT-S     11-18 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NETWORKS-COMMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS MAY BE CATCHING ON _ ORIGINALITY SELLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes a while to get the networks' attention. Twenty years,
in this case, and that's probably about average.
</P>
<P>
   The message, once they are more or less alert and have wiped the
drool from their chins:
</P>
<P>
   HELLO, NETWORKS. GUESS WHAT? PEOPLE ARE TIRED OF YOU AND YOU
HAVE TO GIVE THEM A REASON TO TURN ON THEIR TV SETS!
</P>
<P>
   Or they won't. Or they'll turn on the sets and leave the room.
Or they'll go on a surfing safari _ everybody's learning how _ for
hours at a time, from one channel to the next. Or they'll ignore
the TV and talk to their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   This is a revelation to network TV. One minute, everybody was
perfectly happy watching ``Laverne &AMP; Shirley.'' A minute later, the
networks couldn't get viewers to watch the latest sitcom if you
paid them.
</P>
<P>
   People still seem willing to watch the occasional drama, so long
as it's not exactly like every other drama. Which is a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The same old-same old isn't cutting it anymore. Our voodoo
trance has lifted. Too much of the tiresome has spoiled the medium.
One more ``Friends'' knockoff, one more wacky neighbor, one more
goofy girlfriend, and we're outta there. Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   The audience craves something different. Almost anything
different. Slowly, the networks are learning to give it to them,
though they might still be garbling the message.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone think the phenomenal success of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' is due solely to a pent-up demand for quiz shows?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, yes. The networks probably do, because Fox whipped up
``Greed'' in a jiffy and NBC is supposed to be dickering with a
``Twenty-One'' revival. It better hurry.
</P>
<P>
   (Quick diversion. Speaking of ``Greed,'' it was unpardonable how
the producers milked their million-dollar winners through three
commercial breaks last Thursday. In effect, they cheated viewers
and suspended time to bring the winning contestants back this week,
probably to announce that they'll take their money and not pursue
the $2.2 million jackpot.)
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, the big-money quiz show genre has been dormant so long
that ``Millionaire'' and ``Greed'' seem new, involving and exciting
_ sensations no one would ascribe to ``Shasta McNasty'' or ``Oh
Grow Up.''
</P>
<P>
   After a frenzy of imitation, quiz shows will run their course
and we'll all be yawning again, as with prime-time animated shows
and newsmagazine shows. But the first full flush is fun. TV needs
fun.
</P>
<P>
   There are glimmering signs that the broader message is being
received. The message is that programmers must escape ruts.
</P>
<P>
   The TV universe will collapse if it is dominated by
cookie-cutter series and generic movies. Titillation and
promotional sizzle can't sustain the old forms in the absence of
fresh types of programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie'' was a big hit earlier this month for several reasons.
Those included a production standard that was crisp and wholesome.
It was an old musical done new, and right, and respectfully, all of
which made it a novelty. And its ratings dwarfed those of two
hackneyed miniseries on CBS and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is already drawing criticism for ``Survivor,'' a show being
readied for next summer. Something about stranding 16 contestants
on a Pacific island called Pulau Tiga and letting them vote
periodically to winnow the group to one ``survivor,'' who will win
a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Survivor'' concept has already had a life abroad. A death,
too _ a losing Swedish contestant committed suicide after he
returned home in 1997. But it'll be something different for the
U.S. audience.
</P>
<P>
   Come July, which would you rather see on CBS, '`Survivor'' or a
``Cosby'' rerun? I'd rather Pulau Tiga by the tail.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has every reason to embrace the new, inasmuch as its
existing programming has taken a high-board dive into an empty
pool. Sure enough, it's reportedly considering a neat twist on the
``Millionaire'' phenom.
</P>
<P>
   An inside source said ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire''
is in television's ``primordial ooze right now,'' but may surface
soon with a contestant search.
</P>
<P>
   It's self-explanatory. A multimillionaire, unmarried but not
unwilling. And a national search, or contest, for a ready-made
spouse. It's real. The presumed sequel, a ``Who Wants to Divorce a
Multimillionaire,'' is an altogether different genre.
</P>
<P>
   So we've got greed and lust covered, or at least greed. UPN can
work on gluttony: ``Who Wants to Eat a Cow.''
</P>
<P>
   It's low stuff, more apt to lead to riches than honor. But
whatever else these show are, they aren't just another batch of
sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, that makes them beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
