<SLUG> BC-FBO-NOWLIN-TEX </SLUG>
 
OKLAHOMA HIGH SCHOOL FOOTBALL PLAYER GETS PAST DISABILITY (For use
by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most young defensive backs, Levi Nowlin fantasizes about
big plays. It's an ordinary daydream: Intercept a pass, sprint for
the end zone and start highstepping in for the touchdown, Deion
Sanders-style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practice it all the time,'' said Nowlin, a 5-foot-3,
120-pound strong safety for the Quapaw (Okla.) High School football
team.
</P>
<P>
   But while it might be a common dream for ballplayers, Nowlin
faces anuncommon physical obstacle to make that play happen. A
birth defect left Nowlin with one leg and no hands. Nowlin must use
a prosthesis not only to compete in three sports but get around in
everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the disability, nothing seemed to get in the way of
Nowlin's inspiring performance this season for Quapaw.
</P>
<P>
   Nowlin capped off his first season of varsity football by being
a unanimous selection for newcomer of the year in his team's
district. And in a recent column in the Fort Worth (Texas)
Star-Telegram, Deion Sanders recognized Nowlin, writing: ``I'm here
to tell you that I'm not too old to have heroes. His story is
certainly an inspiration to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Having Sanders acknowledge his efforts ``just blew my mind,''
Nowlin said. ``Here he is, Deion Sanders; and here I am from little
old Quapaw, Oklahoma. It's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowlin also has an apparent fan in Colcord football coach James
Bryant, who nominated Nowlin and confirmed that the selection was
legitimate. ``We didn't know about him until we played 'em,''
Bryant said. ``Watching all the game tapes on Quapaw, we never
noticed his condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it wasn't like he shied away from contact; he played as
hard as anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said his players, at first stunned by Nowlin's effort,
pulled no punches. ``They didn't tear into him, but they tried to
block him when they had to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the honor, Nowlin, who plans to lift weights to improve
his size, said he made a lot of mistakes the past season. ``I
didn't play as good as I could play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Simpson, Nowlin's coach, said football fans in this
northeastern Oklahoma community don't necessarily see a young
athlete overcoming a handicap this season. Instead, they see ``the
situation of a young man aspiring to be a college football
player,'' Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowlin's goals are simple: One, he'd like to play football as
long as he's physically able; two, he'd like to see a Cowboys game
and Sanders play.
</P>
<P>
   Why Sanders, whose flamboyant style differs from Nowlin's humble
persona? ``I've liked him for a long time,'' Nowlin said. ``He gets
the crowd going.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson said he has known for a long time that Sanders is
Nowlin's favorite. ``He's tried (a touchdown dance) a couple of
times in practice,'' he said. ``But in our (winless) situation, we
kind of shy away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   No one deserves to do one more than Nowlin.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1622EST &QL; 
