<TEXT>
<P>
   HOW WELL DO STUDENTS KNOW THEIR COUNTRY?
</P>
<P>
   Correct answers on the national civics test
</P>
<P>
   In fourth grade:
</P>
<P>
   _ 93 percent identified Bill Clinton as president of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   _ 74 percent said that in the United States, laws must be
applied to everyone equally.
</P>
<P>
   _ 41 percent said that the president signs congressional bills
into law.
</P>
<P>
   _ 15 percent named two services that government pays for with
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In eighth grade:
</P>
<P>
   _ 81 percent identified Martin Luther King Jr. as someone who
was concerned about the injustice of segregation laws.
</P>
<P>
   _ 58 percent said that in the United States, the rights of the
people are not limited to those identified in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   _ 26 percent identified two ways that citizens can be involved
in presidential campaigns and elections.
</P>
<P>
   _ 6 percent described two ways that countries benefit from
having a constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In 12th grade:
</P>
<P>
   _ 90 percent said that Social Security is an issue of primary
concern to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   _ 60 percent identified a legitimate way to protest local
government policies.
</P>
<P>
   _ 45 percent said that the president and the State Department
have the greatest authority in foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   _ 30 percent said that the Supreme Court's power of judicial
review helps protect minority rights.
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Assessment of Educational Progress civics tests
administered to 22,000 public and private school students in winter
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
