<HEADLINE>
EGYPT ENRAGED BY AMERICA'S RUSH TO PIN BLAME ON AIR CRASH  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This ``separate buy'' article is from the International Herald
Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS TWO EDITOR-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS, AT 800 (100 WORDS) AND
AT 1,075 (125 WORDS). TOTAL OF UNCUT VERSION IS 1,200.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By BRIAN KNOWLTON  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A second team of Egyptian aviation specialists
arrived here Thursday to join U.S. investigators in an effort to
agree on what was said in the cockpit of the doomed EgyptAir Flight
990 and whether it helps confirm or dispel the theory that a
co-pilot caused the fatal dive.
</P>
<P>
   At the Justice Department, a deputy attorney general, Eric
Holder, cautioned that investigators had reached no conclusions.
``It's simply too early to decide exactly what has happened here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian authorities have angrily protested against what they
say is a rush to blame the co-pilot, Gamil Batouti, and to portray
the crash as a criminal act.
</P>
<P>
   They succeeded in delaying a handover of the investigation to
the FBI, which is regarded by some Egyptians as an intrusive
intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. investigators have moved steadily toward the conviction
that Batouti uttered a prayer, plunged the plane into a sharp
descent, then struggled to keep its nose down as the captain
returned to the cockpit and fought desperately for control. All 217
aboard died in the crash on Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   A snatch of conversation from the audio tapes recovered from the
wreckage, not officially made public but widely disseminated,
apparently has Batouti saying, ``I put my trust in God'' shortly
before the dive.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Nabil Fahmy said Thursday that Egyptians were ``angry
about the way this is being reported.''
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned against leaping to conclusions as, he noted,
happened with the Oklahoma City bombing of a federal building in
1995, when Arabs were at first suspected, or with the bombing at
the Atlanta Olympic Games in 1996, which was wrongly attributed to
a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   Fahmy said he had listened to the tape. He would not comment on
its contents, but said it did not appear to confirm a suicide
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Holder said that Egyptian cooperation had been excellent but
indicated that the investigation would not be guided from Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working in partnership with Egypt,'' he said at a
news briefing. ``But I would not say anything is contingent upon
the approval of the Egyptian government.''
</P>
<P>
   Batouti's family has rejected suggestions that he was suffering
from financial woes or psychological depression. He was not an
Islamic extremist, they say, nor, as a Muslim, would he have
considered suicide, let alone what would amount to mass homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the confusion and sharp dissent over what the tapes reveal,
the next few days of listening, translating and analyzing the data
_ and correlating what was said with the data-recorder information
on when different cockpit controls were activated _ could prove
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board said it would work
through the weekend to provide a ``literal, factual transcript of
all conversations and sounds'' aboard the plane.
</P>
<P>
   A meticulously coordinated time line could provide crucial
information. A prayer by the co-pilot would have a dramatically
different meaning if uttered just before he sent the plane into a
dive, as U.S. investigators now believe, than it would if it came
just after he had discovered some grave mechanical malfunction. Or
if, as some Arabic speakers say, his prayer was simply a
commonplace one.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian officials, and many Arabic and Muslim experts, insist
that such an invocation of God is routine for many Muslims. They
have demanded a more careful study of the tapes and warned against
any rush to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still working to synchronize the timing of the
voice recorder with the 150 data channels on the flight data
recorder.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board has repeatedly said that the EgyptAir data
recorder, one of the most sophisticated available, showed no sign
of any mechanical disability.
</P>
<P>
   But the data analysis will not be an easy task either and it is
not clear whether the American and Egyptian authorities will
ultimately be able to agree on all points.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said it could take at least five days for a
precise transcription of the final minutes of the flight to be
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis now involves safety board experts, Federal Bureau
of Investigation agents, translators, specialists from the Egyptian
aviation authority and EgyptAir.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time Thursday, representatives of Boeing, which
made the plane, and of Pratt &AMP; Whitney, which made its jet engines,
were included in meetings to listen to the tape, along with the
Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of understanding and carefully translating the
Arabic voices heard on the tape has been a thorny one. Different
interpreters have rendered various phrases differently.
</P>
<P>
   The prayer Batouti reportedly uttered is one that Muslim
passengers and crew frequently recite before a flight. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 800) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A report that Batouti had sent money back with a colleague a day
before returning himself was denied by a son, Mohammed, a police
officer, who said he personally had asked his father to send $300
as soon as possible, the Los Angeles Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   A nephew, Sharif Batouti, denied that medical bills for
treatment of one of Batouti's daughter in Los Angeles for lupus had
left the family in financial difficulty. His uncle, he said, was
``filthy rich'' from an inheritance, land holdings, and his
co-pilot's pay. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Egyptian friction has many layers. The countries work
closely on a multitude of issues and do not want to jeopardize the
relationship. Egypt also fears for the possible damage that might
result, particularly to its vitally important tourism industry, if
passengers thought EgyptAir planes or crews were not trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Some Egyptians in turn suspect that U.S. authorities are acting
to protect the interests of Boeing, a major business power.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the question of what could be a huge legal
liability bill.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a $50 million wrongful-death lawsuit was filed by
the estate of a New Jersey chef who died aboard Flight 990.
</P>
<P>
   Ghassan Koujan, 38, of Paterson, N.J., was among the 217 people
aboard the Boeing 767. An attorney, Gerald Baker, said he believed
the suit he filed in U.S. District Court, which named EgyptAir and
Boeing as defendants, was the first to result from the crash.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir, on the other hand, could find itself dispensing tens
of millions of dollars to settle wrongful death claims. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 1,075. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,200) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   The challenges facing salvage crews still at work in the deep
Atlantic waters off Massachusetts where the plane crashed are
particularly daunting, and anything close to full recovery may not
be possible. The U.S. Navy is contracting for a large ship capable
of lifting heavy objects to continue the search.
</P>
<P>
   Married 27 years, Batouti joined EgyptAir in 1987 after he
trained pilots at Egypt's Civil Aviation Authority and in the air
force. The 59-year-old aviator had more than 5,000 flight hours in
a Boeing 767 and was to have retired in March.
</P>
<P>
   In Egypt, his brother-in-law, Essam Dahi, described Batouti as a
man of honor and faith.
</P>
<P>
   The relief co-pilot, Batouti was scheduled to take over late in
the New York-to-Cairo flight, but entered the cockpit shortly after
takeoff and asked to fly. His request was granted. &QL; 
