<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SPENDING (Washington) _ The House wraps up work on a
long-delayed budget bill after protracted, partisan haggling.
Congressional Republicans and the White House are claiming the 2000
spending plan as a triumph for their priorities. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   VIEQUES-BOMBING (Washington) _ The Navy is preparing to abandon
high explosive bombs and shells and shift entirely to inert weapons
for final combat training on the island of Vieques in case the
White House orders the change as part of a compromise to reopen the
Puerto Rican target range. The Navy says it is getting ready for
the unwanted change after encountering problems preparing the
destroyer USS John Hancock for duty in the Persian Gulf without
gunfire training on Vieques. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-ISLAMIC (Washington) _ The Council on American-Islamic
Relations, an advocacy group here, argues that the EgyptAir
co-pilot's phrase about putting his trust in God is not enough to
prove that he committed a criminal act. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-YELTSIN (Istanbul, Turkey) _ President Clinton warns
Russian President Boris Yeltsin against feeding an ``endless cycle
of violence'' in the disputed region of Chechnya. Yeltsin, at first
defying international involvement, later gives ground and agrees to
allow a Norwegian official to visit the war-torn region of Russia,
officials said. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PIPELINE (Istanbul, Turkey) _ In a geopolitical victory
for President Clinton, Turkey, Azerbaijan and Georgia sign a deal
to build a pipeline that would send oil to international markets
without going through Russia or Iran. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush says he
``will resist'' any restriction on free trade, suggesting that free
trade would have priority over human rights violations in other
countries if he is elected president. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a''category)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ An all-white jury finds Shawn
Berry guilty of capital murder in the dragging death of a disabled
black man. The jury now must decide what punishment to recommend to
the court. By PATTY REINERT and RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE-TRAGEDY (College Station, Texas) _ A five-story pyramid
of logs assembled for Texas A&AMP;M University's traditional pregame
bonfire collapses, killing at least nine students and injuring more
than two dozen others. By JIM KIMBERLY and KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE-SAFETY (Undated) _ In 90 years of tradition, there has
never been a bonfire disaster like the one at Texas A&AMP;M University.
We look at safety requirements and who is in charge of the
celebratory bonfire. By TONY FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEVI-STRAUSS (San Francisco) _ Philip Marineau, the outsider who
was hired to revive Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., has fired top executives of
the struggling San Francisco jeans manufacturer and a company
spokesman says more personnel changes are anticipated. By VICTORIA
COLLIVER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-A&AMP;M REAX (College Station, Texas) _ Reaction from Texas A&AMP;M
and Texas football players and coaches to the bonfire accident that
killed at least nine students and left many more hospitalized. By
JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBC-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ Saddled with the worst record in the
Western Conference, the Houston Rockets try to right their ship
tonight when they play host to the Sacramento Kings at Compaq
Center. JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-AL-MVP (Arlington, Texas) _ Texas Rangers catcher Ivan
Rodriguez is the surprise winner of the American League Most
Valuable Player Award, edging Boston pitcher Pedro Martinez, the
23-game winner and Cy Young Award winner who was left off two
ballots completely. By BILL SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-TECH (Lubbock, Texas) _ With Bobby Knight and the Indiana
Hoosiers in town to help open the new basketball arena, a national
TV date for the women's basketball team and a bowl bid at stake for
the football team, this is a big sports weekend for Texas Tech. But
the talk of Lubbock this weekend revolves around the fate of
embattled football coach Spike Dykes, who may be preparing for his
final game with the Red Raiders. By W.H. STICKNEY.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-FLORIDA-FSU (Gainesville, Fla.) _ For the sixth time this
decade, national-championship implications will hang in the balance
as Florida and Florida State met this weekend in their annual
grudge match. This year, Florida State is No. 1 and Florida No. 3
heading into the showdown at the Swamp. By BILL SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ After all these years of crusading
for good causes, Jesse Jackson is now taking up a bad one _
defending violence. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton has
learned that silence is not always golden, a valuable lesson in
running for public office. Silence can generate as much criticism
as exaggerated rhetoric. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
