<HEADER>
A4064 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-2700(2n     11-18 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-2700(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST OF THE COFFEE-TABLE BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UNDATED:this book's covers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Life: Our Century in Pictures'' edited by Richard B. Stolley
(Bulfinch, $60 _ The ``Life'' in the title refers to the magazine,
and everything here is culled from the best of that publication,
which means it's all very good indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Art
</P>
<P>
   ``American Characters: Selections from the National Portrait
Gallery'' by R.W.B. Lewis and Nancy Lewis (Yale University Press,
$45) _ The art is stunning, the notations are enlightening, the
overall effect is outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of Craft: Contemporary Works from the Saxe
Collection'' (Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco, $50) _ The Saxes
collected works in glass, fiber, ceramics, wood and metal; these
photos will help you understand why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eastman Johnson Painting America'' by Teresa A. Carbone and
Patricia Hills (Rizzoli, $65) _ Compiled via the auspices of the
Brooklyn Museum of Art, this stunning book chronicles the career of
19th-century artist Eastman Johnson; accompanying text is
especially distinguished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holding Ground: The Art of Gary Ernest Smith'' by Donald J.
Hagerty (Northland, $40) _ The author notes, ``The art of Gary
Ernest Smith speaks for landscapes and cultures rarely, if ever,
spoken of in contemporary American art.'' He's right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norman Rockwell: Pictures for the American People'' by Maureen
Hart Hennessey and Anne Knutson (Abrams, $35) _ Of course there's a
Rockwell book to mark the end of the century, even if it isn't
designated as a millennium title. And, of course, it's delightful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Dog Man'' by George Rodrigue (Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang,
$50) _ You love ``Blue Dog'' art, or you don't. But if you do,
you'll want to own this book, particularly for the artist's
insightful comments on what affects his work and why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victorian Painting'' by Lionel Lambourne (Phaidon, $59.95) _
This massive tome is a throwback to the '80s, when every
coffee-table art book weighed 20 pounds. This volume is as much
text as art, and is recommended specifically for those who really,
really want to learn more about its subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visions of the West'' edited by Melissa Baldridge (Gibbs
Smith, $60) _ The photos and artifacts represented here are drawn
from several private collections, most notably those of J.P. Bryan.
Everything's interesting, and reading this gives a sense of why
some people will expend millions of dollars and years of their
lives gathering things for other people to see.
</P>
<P>
   Sports
</P>
<P>
   ``And the Crowd Goes Wild'' by Joe Garner (Sourcebooks Inc.,
$49.95) _ It had to come to this: Text plus photos plus two CDs of
event broadcasts so we can hear Bobby Thomson's playoff homer in
1951 and other great sports moments while we're reading about them
and looking at the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best Shots: The Greatest NFL Photography of the Century'' (DK
Publishing, $30) _ The title explains it all. You love pro
football, you'll love these photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``ESPN Sports Century'' edited by Michael MacCambridge (ESPN
Books, $40) _ From Dick Schaap to David Halberstam, some of the
finest living American writers take turns telling about great
sports moments of the 1900s. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Photography
</P>
<P>
   ``Chihuly'' by Dale Chihuly (Abrams, $75) _ This eponymously
titled collection of photos displays the awesome beauty of the
glassblower's art. It would adorn any coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living Planet: Preserving Edens of the Earth'' by Frans
Lanting, Galen Rowell and David Doubilet (Crown, $40) _ It is not
insulting to say this book, whose royalties benefit the World
Wildlife Fund, is exactly what you'd expect _ gorgeous photos of
animals and plants and oceans.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Plains'' by Peter Brown (Doubletake Books, $39.95) _
There really is beauty in sparse landscape, and Brown's photos
prove it. Residents of West Texas and Kansas in particular will
rejoice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other Worlds: Images of the Cosmos From Earth and Space'' by
James Trefil (National Geographic, $35'' _ To quote H. Rider
Haggard, ``In skye ... strange thinges there be.'' Beautiful
things, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secret Worlds: Photographs by Stephen Dalton'' (Firefly, $35)
_ From bees to bats, Dalton allows us to discover unexpected color
and drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tazio Secchiaroli: Greatest of the Paparazzi'' by Diego
Mormorio (Abrams, $49.50) _ Sean Penn and Madonna probably wish
Secchiaroli had never spawned his legion of imitators, but the
``shoot-'em-if-they're famous'' pioneer is still best as well as
first.
</P>
<P>
   Literature
</P>
<P>
   ``The A-Z of Great Writers'' by Tom Payne (Carlton, $35) _ This
collection of short biographies includes 389 novelists, historians,
playwrights, poets and other distinguished men and women of
letters. It's a fine reference work and intriguing reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gardens of the Imagination'' edited by Sophie Biriotti and
illustrated by Peter Malone (Chronicle Books, $24.95) _ Excerpts
from famous books and poems are colorfully illustrated. This theme
sounds simple but the premise is wonderfully realized.
</P>
<P>
   Architecture
</P>
<P>
   ``Building the Book: Cathedral'' by David Macaulay (HM Company,
$29.95) _ The difficulty in describing this book _ it's sort of a
primer on how a Gothic cathedral was designed and constructed _
shouldn't be taken as any indication that it's less than
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If This House Could Talk: Historic Homes, Extraordinary
Americans'' by Elizabeth Smith Brownstein (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $35) _
Yes, we get more about Lincoln's home in Springfield and Robert
Frost's New Hampshire Farm, but we also visit Booker T.
Washington's residence in Tuskegee, Ala.; Edward Gorey's digs in
Yarmouth Port, Mass.; and other unexpectedly interesting dwelling
places.
</P>
<P>
   Texas
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Friends: Great Texas Courthouses'' by Bill Morgan
(Landmark Publishing, $55) _ The price is a bit steep, but the
quality is unquestionable. From Mason to Mount Vernon, Morgan takes
readers on an engaging tour of those ubiquitous small-town squares
and their courthouse centerpieces that we all recognize and love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Cattle Barons: Their Families, Land and Legacy'' by
Elmer Kelton, photography by Kathleen Jo Ryan (Ten Speed Press,
$49.95) _ Kelton's essays are, as always, great fun and
informative, too. Ryan's accompanying photos help maintain a
friendly tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Houses Built by the Book: The Use of Published Designs,
1850-1925'' by Margaret Culbertson (Texas A&AMP;M, $39.95) _ It is
undoubtedly true only dedicated state historians would be initially
drawn by this book. But it's not as limited as it sounds;
Culbertson gives readers a sense of why houses were built in
certain ways, and it's enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDUL/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
