<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4065 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-2700(2T     11-18 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-2700(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST OF THE COFFEE-TABLE BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
and LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems that each year, a dominant theme emerges among the
hundreds of oversize or ``coffee-table'' books. Animals in the Wild
was the subject in 1995; Art was the rage in '96 and '97; and Home
Decorating dominated in 1998. In 1999 _ you guessed it _ there is a
plethora of coffee-table books that claim to encapsulate the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   We have 1900-99 represented in more ways than Hillary Rodham
Clinton has had hairstyles. Want to understand these 100 years via
art or photographs or athletic achievements or architecture? You
can take your pick. Other, less dominant trends include more
coffee-table books devoted to sports and literature. There are
still plenty of art books, and tomes about all things Texan are
more numerous than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are so many oversized books to choose among this
year, we have selected 42 books from almost 700 for a ``best-of''
listing. The 10 we believe are the best are ranked in order. The
other 32 are grouped by category and listed alphabetically.
</P>
<P>
   THE 10 bEST:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Century'' (Phaidon, $49.95) _ It is almost inconceivable
that this fabulous collection of photos and brief essays is priced
so low. ``Century'' is the clear-cut best oversize book of 1999
because it is concise, yet completely captures each year. The art
is superb, the printed words crackling and appropriate. Even if you
don't otherwise collect coffee-table books, you ought to have this
one. Placed in a time capsule or blasted into outer space, it would
serve well as evidence of who and what we were circa 1900-99.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Earth From Above'' by Yann Arthus-Bertrand (Abrams, $65) _
Arthus-Bertrand spent five years circumnavigating the globe to work
his magic as an aerial photographer. The results are masterful;
you'll have the sensation of viewing our beautiful planet from a
hovering spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Brassai: The Eye of Paris'' by Anne Wilkes Tucker with
Richard Howard and Avis Berman (Abrams, $60) _ Published in
conjunction with a recent exhibition at The Museum of Fine Arts in
Houston, this collection of the French photographer's genius is
outstanding. It isn't just for francophiles.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``The American Art Book'' (Phaidon, $39.95) _ From Berenice
Abbott to William Zorich, with Donald Judd and Sister Gertrude
Morgan and Nancy Spero in between, this richly illustrated tome
presents samples of the work of 500 great American artists. A
glossary and listing of museums where featured works are displayed
sums up an outstanding collection.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``American Chronicle: Year by Year Through the Twentieth
Century'' by Lois Gordon and Alan Gordon (Yale University Press,
$49.95) _ The title is self-explanatory. What's special (and
endearing) about this book is that it doesn't pretend to have only
lofty information. Yes, we learn which symphonic works were
composed in certain years, which historic events occurred when and
which great books were written. But there's an annual listing of
hit TV shows, too.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``The Holy Bible'' illustrated by Barry Moser (Viking Studio,
$65) _ This is not a new work but is the century's only published
Bible illustrated by a single artist. He is Barry Moser, the gifted
designer/illustrator whose other works adorn such sanctified spots
as New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art and the National Gallery
of Art in Washington, D.C. This book is huge, weighing in at easily
5 pounds, but it is so, so beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   7. ``Diego Rivera'' by Pete Hamill (Abrams, $49.50) _ Most books
representing works by an artist are heavy on the art and light on
the printed commentary. This is almost the reverse. Hamill, in a
chatty rather than professorial style, tells us all about events in
Rivera's life that influenced his art. If you just want pretty
pictures, choose another book. But if you want to learn about a
great artist, ``Diego Rivera'' is a perfect choice.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Glory: Photographs of Athletes'' by Richard Corman (Morrow,
$45) _ Muhammad Ali's visage peers forth on the cover, but this
isn't another of those find-'em-everywhere coffee-table books with
huge black-and-white portraits of familiar faces such as Michael
Jordan, Nancy Kerrigan and Ken Griffey Jr. Instead, Corman
intersperses the expected snaps of George Foreman and Michael
Johnson with breathtaking photos of cyclists and college wrestling
coaches and just plain folks out for a little exercise.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Great African-American Women'' by Darryl Lyman (Jonathan
David Publishers, $29.95) _ Oprah is included here, and Rosa Parks
and Barbara Jordan and others who made their historic mark and have
received deserved acclaim. But Lyman also singles out great women
whom most of us might never have heard about, such as Juanita Kidd
Stout, the first black woman to serve on a state supreme court, and
Elizabeth Ross Haynes, who fought the YWCA's color barrier until
full integration was achieved in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Peanuts: A Golden Celebration'' by Charles Schulz
(HarperCollins, $45) _ Good grief, Charlie Brown! Are you really
50? It's true, and creator Charles Schulz takes us on an engaging
romp through the cartoon past. It's regrettable, though, that
nowhere is it pointed out that, without ``Peanuts' '' gentle social
proddings, the world might not have accepted ``Doonesbury'' or
``Bloom County'' a couple of decades later.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the rest
</P>
<P>
   The 20th century (any titles with a millennium theme):
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Century: Art &AMP; Culture 1900-1950'' by Barbara
Haskell (Whitney Museum/Norton, $60) _ It's only half a century,
but why quibble? Haskell, the Whitney curator of painting and
sculpture, gives us 50 years' worth of eye- and mind-candy.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Photography: A Century of Images'' by Vicki Goldberg
and Robert Silberman (Chronicle Books, $40) _ An adjunct to the PBS
TV series, this book will conjure many memories, including some
that are uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Century of Country: An Illustrated History of Country
Music'' by Robert K. Oermann (TV Books, $39.95) _ The 1900s country
scene kicked off with Powder River Jack and Kitty Lee, and ends
with the Dixie Chicks and Tim McGraw. This book tells you how and
why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children's History of the 20th Century'' (DK Publishing,
$29.95) _ As with all DK's titles for younger readers, this one is
colorful, concise and entertaining. It ought to be a study staple
for every child in junior high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine: The Spirit of 20th-Century American Heroes'' edited
by Gina Misiroglu (New World Library, $29.95) _ A hallmark of
20th-century history was the opportunity to record the thoughts and
acts of great men and women in their own words. JFK, Amelia
Earhart, Paul Robeson and many more speak to us between this book's
covers. MORE: .MDUL/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
