<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Stewart In Miller's `Ride'
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Stewart, whose last appearance on Broadway was in the
acclaimed 1995 revival of ``The Tempest,'' will return in March as
the charismatic bigamist and businessman at the center of Arthur
Miller's ``Ride Down Mount Morgan.'' Stewart said his return was a
testament to his inordinate love for the play and its central
character, Lyman Felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur has created a wonderful and complex leading
character,'' Stewart said. ``It's musical and emotional and
expressive, and very, very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shubert Organization has committed a theater, as yet
undetermined, for the play, to begin performances for a limited run
on March 20.
</P>
<P>
   The story of a man whose two wives _ and two lives _ converge
after a nearly deadly accident, ``Ride'' had its world premiere in
1991 in London. The play had its United States debut in 1996 at the
Williamstown Theater Festival, with F. Murray Abraham playing
Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the play arrived in New York, at the Public Theater,
where Stewart took over the role of Lyman, and fell in love with
it.
</P>
<P>
   While critical reaction to ``Ride'' has been uneven, Miller said
last year's sold-out run at the Public had inspired him. ``The
enthusiasm is so high,'' he said. ``We're all a little nutty about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The brevity of last year's run _ a month _ had also inspired
Stewart to push for a longer opportunity to perform the show on
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain pieces of work that simply don't leave you
alone,'' he said. ``Certain characters and plays that continue to
haunt you. I think actors need to pay attention to that.''
</P>
<P>
   More From Miller
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on Broadway, David Richenthal, producer of ``The
Price,'' also by Miller, said he was confident _ nay, sure! _ that
the revival of the 1968 play would be a hit on Broadway, despite
early ticket sales that were ``not abysmal but not where I'd like
them to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Richenthal's strategy? Advertising, and lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll spend any amount of money to advertise this play to help
find it an audience,'' Richenthal said. ``Whatever it takes.
Because audiences love it, and I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, Richenthal said he had doubled his
advertising budget, paying about $125,000 for new spots emphasizing
a bundle of positive reviews the play has received. The play opened
on Monday night at the Royale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in for a big fight,'' Richenthal said. ``But anybody
who's writing an epitaph on this show is premature.''
</P>
<P>
   A Busy Roger Rees
</P>
<P>
   Roger Rees is going to be a busy man next spring if the
Roundabout Theater Company has its way. A week after signing on to
appear in an April production of ``Uncle Vanya,'' at the
refurbished Selwyn Theater, Rees spent this week talking to actors
about a proposed production of ``Arms and the Man,'' by George
Bernard Shaw that Rees would direct.
</P>
<P>
   The show would appear at the company's temporary home at
Gramercy Theater in February.
</P>
<P>
   But if Rees and the Roundabout can't get the cast they want
another as-yet-undetermined show will take its place.
</P>
<P>
   Health Watch
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few health updates:
</P>
<P>
   Carol Burnett, the heart and soul of ``Putting It Together,''
was back onstage Tuesday night after missing all weekend because of
the flu. Ms. Burnett informed the audience at the Saturday matinee
of her illness _ ``Something icky has invaded my body'' _ but
apparently was in good voice by Monday, the show's dark day.
``Putting It Together,'' a revue of the songs of Stephen Sondheim,
will open as scheduled on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile at the New York Theater Workshop Nathan Lane was
suffering a cold on Wednesday, resulting in the cancellation of
that evening's presentation of ``Wise Guys,'' the new Sondheim
musical. He was to be back Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   And in Chicago, the stars of Disney's ``Aida'' were also to be
back onstage Thursday night, after an accident that brought
Saturday night's performance screeching to a halt. Near the end of
the musical, the actors Heather Headley and Adam Pascal were inside
the play's central set element, an elevated stone tomb, when a
cable failure caused the set piece to fall about 10 feet to the
stage. The two actors rolled out and lay silent for several moments
before the action was stopped and a doctor was called to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pascal and Ms. Headley were shaken up and suffered bruises.
Two scheduled performances on Sunday were canceled, and
understudies appeared on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida,'' with a score by Elton John and Tim Rice, is on a
tryout run at the Cadillac Palace in Chicago before its move to the
Palace Theater on Broadway on Feb. 25. Officials said the accident
would have no effect on the show's run in Chicago or New York,
though there will be one change: from now on the tomb will no
longer elevate, said Chris Boneau, a spokesman for the musical. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Two new plays, one a transfer, one a delay: As expected,
``James Joyce's `The Dead''' will move to Broadway to the Belasco
from Playwrights Horizons. Performances begin on Dec. 14, for a
limited run of 10 weeks. And ``Wrong Mountain,'' by David Hirson,
has delayed its opening from Dec. 14 until Jan. 13 to avoid what
producer Michael David called ``a historically distracting
holiday,'' not to mention the six other Broadway shows to open in
December.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Wooster Group's latest effort, ``North Atlantic,'' closes
on Sunday but will reopen on Jan. 11 for an open-ended run. The
play, about a surreal set of Navy types adrift in the, well, North
Atlantic, stars Willem Dafoe and Kate Valk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Talk about Take Your Daughters to Work Day. Off Off Broadway
has two prominently pedigreed young women in residence: Keira
Naughton, the daughter of the director and actor James Naughton,
who is appearing in ``Uncle Jack,'' at the TriBeCa Playhouse, and
Emma Zaks, daughter of the director Jerry Zaks, who will appear in
``Out of the Blue,'' a new musical at the Miranda Theater, which
began rehearsals this week. Performances will start on Dec. 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
