<SLUG> BC-LOLA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TURKISH TRANSVESTITE JUST WANTS HAPPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Osman, a proudly macho Turkish taxi driver living in Berlin,
wants Murat, his gorgeous, baby-faced younger brother, to lose his
virginity. Osman wants it so much that he drags Murat out of the
taxi and over to a prostitute who has just agreed to a fee of 100
marks (about $50) for the assignment. Murat (Baki Davrak), however,
runs away. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Murat is young, but he knows he's gay, and in ``Lola and Billy
the Kid,'' a well-meaning German-Turkish drama with a message, he
learns just how difficult coming out can be. If Kutlug Ataman, the
film's writer and director, is on target, some Turkish families
living in Germany are so homophobic that they make Newt Gingrich
look like the president of Act Up.
</P>
<P>
   Lola (Gandi Mukli), a transvestite who works at a Berlin club,
turns out to be a relative of Murat's; Lola's family did not react
well to the discovery that he was gay. Now Lola is in love with a
black-leather-jacket guy who calls himself Billy the Kid (Erdal
Yildiz), spelled Bilidikid in German, and things would be fine if
it weren't for Billy's attitude.
</P>
<P>
   He's so horrified about being gay that he wants Lola to have
sex-change surgery so they can marry and live normally like
everybody else (his words). Lola wonders, ``Why can't we just be
happy like we are?'' The film is Murat's search for his own
identity, which involves getting to know Lola.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sometimes amusing subplot about Friedrich (Michael
Gerber), an older gay German man who drives a fabulous Daimler
convertible and falls for Iskender (Murat Yilmaz), a hirsute
Turkish prostitute with attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The finest moments in the film involve Iskender; Friedrich's
white-haired little-dog-toting mother, Ute (Inge Keller), and an
extremely valuable brooch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lola and Billy the Kid'' has an important social message, but
it's delivered in a much too heavy-handed and simplistic fashion to
have the impact it should. The film is not rated, but it includes
strong profanity (the film is in German and Turkish with English
subtitles), a number of discreet sex scenes and one extended scene
of disturbing violence.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `LOLA AND BILLY THE KID'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Kutlug Ataman; in Turkish and German,
with English subtitles; director of photography, Chris Squires;
edited by Ewa J. Lind; production designer, John Di Minico;
produced by Martin Hagemann; released by Picture This
Entertainment. Running time: 94 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Gandi Mukli (Lola), Erdal Yildiz (Bili), Baki Davrak
(Murat), Masut Ozdemir (Kalipso), Celal Perk (Shehrazade), Hasan
Ali Mete (Osman), Michael Gerber (Friedrich), Murat Yilmaz
(Iskender) and Inge Keller (Ute).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1644EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CIVICS19-COX     11-18 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVICS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOST U.S. KIDS SHOW BASIC KNOWLEDGE OF CIVICS
 &HT;    WITH CIVICSDATA19-COX
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two-thirds of American students have at least a
basic knowledge of civics, according to national test results
released Thursday by the Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   That may be better than most grown-ups could do; one national
poll showed that 63 percent of adults couldn't name all three of
the federal government's branches: executive, legislative and
judicial.
</P>
<P>
   Most fourth-graders could name the president and knew that all
people, including the police, are supposed to obey the laws.
</P>
<P>
   Most eighth-graders knew that Martin Luther King Jr. opposed
racial segregation, and most could identify concepts from the
Declaration of Independence, the Constitution and Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Most twelfth-graders knew that Social Security concerned the
elderly and that the rights of the majority are limited by
protections in the Constitution for the rights of individuals and
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But about one-third of the 22,000 students in 4th, 8th and 12th
grades who took the tests last winter were scored ``below basic''
in their knowledge of the government and of the skills, rights and
responsibilities of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, only one-fourth soared above the ``basic'' level to
earn grades of ``proficient'' or ``advanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley praised the upper one-fourth
for showing ``a grasp of civics above grade level.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he plans to work with educators and civic leaders
``to find new ways to engage the (bottom) one-third of our students
who need to learn much, much more about our ddemocrtic way of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While deeply troubling, the ... findings in civics are not
surprising,'' said Charles N. Quigley, one of the people invited by
Riley to speak at the ceremony releasing the results of the test
conducted as part of the National Assessment of Educational
Progress.
</P>
<P>
   Blaming schools for failing to adopt high-standard curriculums,
Quigley said: ``Failure of students to do well on the NAEP study is
a direct consequence of the widespread lack of adequate curricular
requirements, teacher preparation and instruction in civics and
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley, executive director of the California-based Center for
Civic Education, said a study done for his center by the Lyndon B.
Johnson School of Public Affairs in the University of Texas at
Austin showed that there isn't a single state or school district
with a satisfactory program for teaching civics and government.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Ravitch, a New York University professor, noted that all
the seniors will be old enough to vote in next year's presidential
and congressional elections. ``Yet, about 35 percent of the seniors
lacked even a basic understanding of our system of constitutional
government,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ravitch served on the National Assessment Governing Board, a
panel of educators and citizens who decided how high scores had to
be for the various achievement levels. ``It was a judgment call,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the achievement levels announced Thursday :
</P>
<P>
   -- The top rating of ``advanced'' for ``superior'' performance
went to 2 percent of the test-takers in grades four and eight and
to 4 percent in twelfth grade.
</P>
<P>
   -- A rating of ``proficient'' for showing ``full mastery'' of
the knowledge and skills went to 21 percent in grades four and
eight and to 22 percent in twelfth grade.
</P>
<P>
   -- A rating of ``basic'' for ``partial mastery'' was awarded to
46 percent in fourth grade, 48 percent in eighth grade and 39
percent in twelfth grade.
</P>
<P>
   -- Failing ratings of ``below basic'' went to 31 percent in
foruth grade, 30 percent in eighth grade and 35 percent in twelfth
grade.
</P>
<P>
   In some grades, totals didn't total 100 percent because the
numbers were rounded.
</P>
<P>
   A summary and a full report on the civics test scores are posted
on the Internet at http://nces.ed.gov/nationsreportcard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
