<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BATTLE AND THE WAR AROUND THE DECATUR SIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most people, being handcuffed and hustled into a police van
would be a frightening and humiliating experience. But for some
people, being arrested and braceleted constitutes a photo
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson knew what he was letting himself in for
when he led a small group of parents and ministers onto the campus
of Eisenhower High School in Decatur, Ill., to protest the
expulsion of six students from the school.
</P>
<P>
   He invited arrest to attract more attention to the campaign he
was leading to persuade the Decatur school board to change its
punishment of the students. And it was a smart, effective move.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's mission in Decatur should not be disparaged just
because of his reputation for enjoying publicity and the sound of
his own voice raised in reverberating, alliterative protest against
some small, large or middling injustice.
</P>
<P>
   The Decatur Six were expelled for two years by the school board
because of their participation in a brawl in the stands at a Sept.
17 football game at Eisenhower. Originally they were seven, but one
of the students withdrew from the school during the expulsion
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Under the glare of national publicity and prodded by Jackson,
Illinois Gov. George Ryan and state school Superintendent Glenn
``Max'' McGee, the school board reduced the expulsions to one year
and permitted the students to continue to earn credits by attending
alternative programs.
</P>
<P>
   Not good enough, said Jackson. He and McGee worked out a plan to
allow the students to return to regular classes provided they keep
their noses clean and maintain ``C'' averages while in the
alternative programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the school board just said ``no.'' And that set the stage
for Jackson's protest and arrest at Eisenhower and the
intensification of national attention on Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has threatened to file a federal lawsuit against the
school district, which he should win, if it comes to that. The
board's blanket punishment does appear too excessive.
</P>
<P>
   The board should relent and judge the expelled students
individually because there almost certainly are differing degrees
of guilt. And there also are the differing attendance, academic
performance and conduct records to take into account.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the students are scheduled to graduate this year. They
would have a strong incentive to work hard and behave themselves in
the alternative program proposed by McGee to graduate with their
class. Another is an honor student and captain of his varsity
basketball team. He also would have a strong motivation to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Because of failures and frequent absences, three of the students
are repeating freshman year for the third time. They might not be
able to qualify for early reinstatement, but if they did, everyone
would be better for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Decatur school board made its point. But it can only come
off looking shortsighted and mean-spirited if it insists on
sticking to what amounts to an academic death sentence for all or
some of the Decatur Six.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson is championing a just cause, a victory for him
would not necessarily be good for public education. It could send
the message to school districts across the nation that they risk
political retaliation and humiliation if they make determined
efforts to bolster discipline at public school campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur's zero-tolerance-for-violence policy is not unique. Many
school districts nationwide have adopted such policies, based on
the reasonable assumption that a safe and secure learning
environment is indispensable to high academic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   If they cannot provide a safe setting for learning, increasingly
the public schools will lose students to private schools, and the
movement to undermine the public schools with voucher programs to
pay for private schooling will continue to gain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about the voucher movement _ it has as much, if
not more, to do with deteriorating discipline and violence in the
public schools as it does with comparative instruction and student
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest advantage of private schools is that they have the
power to expel any student who misbehaves and detracts from the
learning environment, with no responsibility for that student after
expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   Public schools can't do that. But they do need the authority to
deal with violent and disruptive students. And the best way to do
that in many instances may be to expel them for long periods in
order to get their parents' attention and make them live up to
their disciplinary responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Decatur school board has erred on the side of excess in this
matter. But in doing so, it focused national attention on the
school discipline problem. Having made its point, it should show
some flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   There is right on both sides of this issue. A creative
compromise is needed. Otherwise, either the school board or Jackson
will win a battle and contribute to losing a war against the forces
that are attempting to dismantle public education.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
