<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To watch the video title shuffle, try updating a mail order
catalog. ``What's interesting this year is how many movies that
have been gone for years are now coming back,'' said Irv Slifkin,
an editor of the 2000 catalog from Movies Unlimited, a company in
Philadelphia that, along with Facets International of Chicago, is
one of the most versatile mail order operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Beatles film ``Yellow Submarine,'' long kept out of
circulation by a rights dispute, is now back from MGM. So are
``Dances With Wolves'' and ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' both of
which were owned by Orion, now defunct, but have also been picked
up by MGM. ``People may not have realized it, but you couldn't have
gotten them for a couple of years,'' Slifkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples include ``The Onion Field,'' Joseph Wambaugh's
police drama; ``Where Eagles Dare,'' Brian G. Hutton's World War II
thriller and one of Movies Unlimited's most requested titles;
``Stop Making Sense,'' Jonathan Demme's Talking Heads concert film,
and ``Labyrinth'' and ``Dark Crystal,'' two Jim Henson films that
have large followings and are now available from Columbia Tri-Star.
``People have been paying hundreds of dollars for used copies of
those two,'' Slifkin said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he added, there has also been a large increase in
wide-screen letter-boxed editions of big films like ``Chinatown''
and Carl Theodor Dreyer's silent classic ``The Passion of Joan of
Arc.'' But with a total of 40,000 titles, the catalog doesn't limit
itself to movies. Occupying 63 pages, old television shows have
always been best sellers, and this year, Slifkin said, the demand
is for boxed sets of series like ``That Girl,'' with Marlo Thomas,
and ``The Avengers,'' the '60s show with Diana Rigg and Patrick
Macnee, which has quickly grown to 23 volumes, and ``Monty Python's
Flying Circus.''
</P>
<P>
   Growth in other areas is somewhat surprising. ``There's more
interest in silent films, with more coming out and more being
restored,'' Slifkin said. Among hundreds of titles is Herbert
Brenon's ``Peter Pan'' (1924), adapted from James M. Barrie's play
and incorporating his and others' ideas about expanding the story
to the screen. The video will be available from Kino on Nov. 30,
but Slifkin said there have been many pre-orders. ``It's a very
different version,'' he added. ``People who saw `Hook' should take
a look.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten Clara Bow films, released by Milestone and others, are also
among the most requested of the silent films. ``Who knows Clara Bow
today except older people?'' he said. ``But it seems younger people
are interested, too. The orders we're getting point to a pretty big
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight actors _ Gwyneth Paltrow, Drew Barrymore, Sandra Bullock,
Leonardo DiCaprio, Ronald Colman, Johnny Depp, Tony Curtis and the
erotic thriller star Shannon Tweed _ have been added to the
featured stars list. All get specially tinted sections of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog is $9.95, and a DVD catalog can be ordered at no
extra charge. Information: (800) 523-0823. Everything is also
available on the &QL; 
Web:www.moviesunlimited.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Entrapment
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like bungee-jumping off the top of a skyscraper and
being yanked taut exactly at the floor one needs to purloin a
valuable painting. Young and lithe, Gin (Catherine Zeta-Jones)
works stunts like this while posing as an insurance investigator, a
job that introduces her to an old master thief named Mac (Sean
Connery). Soon they are planning crimes together, culminating in
the rigging of a computer to help steal billions. Naturally, all
the training and planning inspire a May-December attraction between
the two, which, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``works
because it isn't forced, and because both actors are so
mischievously game.''
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Fox. $108.09; DVD, $34.98. 112 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13. Release date: Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Iron Giant
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the red scare of the 1950s, Brad Bird's movie (loosely
based on a children's fable by Ted Hughes) lets the villagers of
Rockwell, Maine., make what they will of a huge iron man who wades
ashore one night. In the resulting panic, the Army is summoned
along with a nasty g agent whose paranoia leaves no opening for a
rational reaction. Only a young boy named Hogarth has the tolerance
and fortitude to try to establish contact in a story that has
lessons for children and memories for adults wrapped up in a
``smooth, skilled example of animated filmmaking'' (Lawrence Van
Gelder). _ 1999. Warner. $24.98; DVD, $24.98. 86 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG. Release date: Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Haunting
</P>
<P>
   Recruited to participate in what they think is a study of sleep
disorders, three participants (Lili Taylor, Catherine Zeta-Jones
and Owen Wilson) report to Hill House, a hulking pile with walls
that come alive with the spirits of children murdered there in the
last century. Actually, the participants have been brought together
by Dr. David Marrow (Liam Neeson) to serve as guinea pigs in his
research on fear and hysteria, and soon there is plenty to go
around as the house itself erupts in a lavish and at times scary
movie ``firmly committed to the notion that more is more''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. DreamWorks. $107.37; DVD, $29.98. 113 minutes. Closed
captioned. Release date: Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut
</P>
<P>
   When Stan, Kyle and little Kenny emerge talking very dirtily
from a movie by the obscenity-spewing Canadian filmmakers Terrance
and Phillip, it sets off a ruckus in the white-bread town of South
Park. Rallied by Kyle's mother, Sheila Broflovski, the nation
spares no personal freedom to crack down on potty mouths.
Eventually, violence being more acceptable than naughty words,
there is warfare with Canada in a very funny film that ``cannily
zeroes in on some essential contradictions of American popular
culture'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Paramount. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 90 minutes. Closed
captioned. Release date: Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INHERIT THE WIND.  &LR; In a Showtime incarnation of the famous
faceoff, Jack Lemmon represents science as Henry Drummond and
George C. Scott upholds fundamentalism as Matthew C. Brady. The
case, of course, is the so-called monkey trial in Hillsboro, Tenn.,
in 1925, which pitted Clarence Darrow against William Jennings
Bryan. Right up there with Fredric March and Spencer Tracy in
Stanley Kramer's 1960 film, Scott and Lemmon, Walter Goodman wrote
in The New York Times, ``invest their roles with a humanity that
cuts deeper than ideology.'' 1999. MGM. $49.95. 133 minutes. PG.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; XIU XIU: THE SENT DOWN GIRL.  &LR; In a film directed by the Chinese
actress Joan Chen, a tailor's teenage daughter (nicknamed Xiu Xiu)
is sent to the Tibetan plains to learn horse herding preparatory to
joining the Iron Girls Cavalry. There she bonds with a nomad and is
stranded when the cavalry is disbanded and only the politically
well-connected are allowed to return home. Seduced by a handsome
peddler and taken advantage of by soldiers, she finally joins with
the nomad in a final, courageous act of violence in a film that
maintains a poetic distance from its brutal physical facts. 1998.
A-Pix. $80.13. 99 minutes. Mandarin with English subtitles. R.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEROES AND VILLAINS.  &LR; Rowan Atkinson (`` Bean''), Jennifer
Saunders (``Absolutely Fabulous'') and Jim Broadbent (``The
Avengers'') star in three tales of British eccentrics: a race car
driver, a 19th-century socialite and an uptight military hero.
1999. BFS. Three cassettes, $19.98 each, $59.98 for the set. 55
minutes each. Information: (800) 268-3891.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
