<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RKO 281': LACKLUSTER DRAMATIZATION OF INTRIGUE SURROUNDING
`CITIZEN KANE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a film is trying to latch onto someone else's glory, it helps
to jump in at the right end of the career. ``RKO 281'' depicts
Orson Welles' making of ``Citizen Kane'' and William Randolph
Hearst's efforts to thwart the release of the film, whose
megalomaniacal newspaper tycoon was so clearly modeled on him. But
while ``RKO'' portrays Welles in his first and most complete flash
of genius, it has the glamour and artistry of those stiff,
self-important commercials for cheap wine he made near the end of
his life. Like so many other disappointing HBO biographical movies,
including ``Dorothy Dandridge'' and ``The Rat Pack,'' this one
takes a juicy idea, lines up a seductive cast, then hands them a
banal script that lets everyone down.
</P>
<P>
   ``RKO 281,'' whose title refers to the number the studio gave to
the project, begins with an echo of ``Citizen Kane'': a deathbed
scene and a newsreel setting up the hero's life. Instead of Kane's
own death and life, here we see little Orson at his mother's
deathbed and the headline ``Boy Wonder Wows Hollywood'' when the
24-year-old Welles arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Those borrowings work well enough, but the film quickly falls
into a trap; showing the creation of a masterpiece is usually a
terrible idea. The film also tries to improve on real life,
inventing one of the lavish dinners Hearst and his mistress, the
actress Marion Davies, gave at his castle, San Simeon. The
screenwriter Herman Mankiewicz had been a frequent guest, but this
fictional version also includes Welles (who never was). The
invention is not a problem in itself, but the hokey way in which it
is used as the genesis for ``Kane'' is. After the dinner, Welles
comes up with the idea for the story of a media baron and asks
Mankiewicz to collaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Mankiewicz pulls out his unpublished novel about
Hearst. ``Great minds think alike,'' he says. But the film swerves
away from one of the most contentious, bitter and probably
unsolvable issues in film history: How much writing credit did each
man deserve?
</P>
<P>
   As the shooting of ``Kane'' begins, ``RKO'' nudges viewers with
visual reminders. When he meets the cinematographer Gregg Toland,
Welles is holding the famous snow globe that falls out of the dead
Kane's hands. Viewers who know ``Kane'' will feel constantly poked
in the ribs, while those who don't will wonder what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   Liev Schreiber moves in and out of Welles' voice in a
distracting way, occasionally capturing its timbre. Without a solid
script, he can't give Welles an inner life, so he offers a broad
outline of the legend: brilliant, charming, self-absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   John Malkovich is terrific as the hard-drinking Mankiewicz, who
would never subsequently equal his work on ``Kane.'' When
Mankiewicz argues that Hearst is too powerful to take on, Welles
pompously tells him, ``I expected more from you, Mank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, me too, but I got used to it,'' Mankiewicz says
casually, sipping his drink. Malkovich creates a deft, understated
sketch of what Hollywood can do to talent.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Griffith is sympathetic as the hapless Davies, doing
jigsaw puzzles on the floor of the castle. And James Cromwell makes
a surprisingly powerful case for Hearst as a human being when, as
Hearst, he insists that his privacy has been violated. When it is
time to depict Hearst's evil side, though, the script clumsily
shows him making blunt anti-Semitic remarks to Louis B. Mayer
(David Suchet).
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's effort to suppress the film is a tale of media power
that resonates today. But it takes half of ``RKO 281'' to get
there, and when it does it is flat-footed in its depiction of
Hollywood intrigue. Brenda Blethyn and Fiona Shaw prance around as
Louella Parsons and Hedda Hopper. Instead of creating the texture
of 1940s Hollywood, like most of ``RKO 281'' they seem as flimsy as
paper dolls.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RKO 281'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Saturday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Ridley Scott and Tony Scott, executive producers; Diane Minter
Lewis and Chris Zarpas, co-executive producers; Su Armstrong,
producer; Benjamin Ross, director; script by John Logan, based
partly on the documentary ``The Battle Over Citizen Kane'' from the
PBS series ``The American Experience.'' A Scott Free Production.
</P>
<P>
   With: Liev Schreiber (Orson Welles), James Cromwell (William
Randolph Hearst), Melanie Griffith (Marion Davies), John Malkovich
(Herman Mankiewicz), Brenda Blethyn (Louella Parsons), Roy Scheider
(George Schaefer), Fiona Shaw (Hedda Hopper) and David Suchet
(Louis B. Mayer).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
