<HEADER>
A4074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-BRADLEY-$ADV21-C     11-18 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE, BRADLEY VOTING RECORDS SHOW POLITICALLY POTENT SPLIT
 &HT;    980&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories
for release Sunday, Nov. 21.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore and Bill Bradley rarely disagreed as
senators, but when they did it was usually about guns and butter _
and sometimes honey.
</P>
<P>
   Those differences could be important in the presidential race,
especially when the two Democratic presidential candidates face off
in the South, where military and farm programs are fighting words
in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man is easy to pigeonhole based on a comparison of the
yeas and nays they cast during the nearly eight years they spent
together in the U.S. Senate, from 1985 through 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The record shows both could be political mavericks and
intellectual loners, sometimes moving to their own rhythms rather
than those of their constituencies or their party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And they could defy political labels.
</P>
<P>
   In the debate over a 1988 federal antidrug laws in the 1980s,
for example, the ``Southern conservative'' Gore voted against the
death penalty for drug kingpins, while Bradley, a ``Northeastern
liberal,'' voted in favor of it.
</P>
<P>
   But on matters of defense and agriculture, two of the defining
political issues of the South in this century, Gore's votes in the
Senate reflect traditional political attitudes much more often than
Bradley's.
</P>
<P>
   Gore represented Tennessee in the Senate from 1985 until his
election as vice president in 1992. Bradley was elected three times
to the Senate from New Jersey and retired in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   From 1985 through 1992, the Senate recorded 2,722 votes. Of the
2,137 votes cast by both Gore and Bradley during that time, they
agreed 1,604 times _ more than 75 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   But on Jan. 12, 1991, they had their most dramatic disagreement,
and one that is as reflective of their differences as any.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was one of only 10 Democrats to vote to authorize U.S.
military force to expel Iraqi troops who had invaded Kuwait the
previous summer. Bradley voted with the losing Democratic majority
in opposition to President Bush's war effort.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time Gore and Bradley had crossed swords on
defense-related issues. Gore supported production of the MX
multiple-warhead missile, the B-2 bomber, the Seawolf nuclear
submarine and the space-based Strategic Defense Initiative, all of
which Bradley opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's anti-military efforts in the Senate culminated in an
unsuccessful proposal in 1992 to cut $18 billion from the
Pentagon's budget over five years to finance education, health care
and environmental programs. Gore voted against Bradley's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did, however, endorse the Reagan administration's
support of the Nicaraguan rebel army in 1986, though he eventually
withdrew his backing after disclosures of the Iran-contra affair
the following year, in which some proceeds of arms sales to Iran
were diverted to benefit the rebels. Gore opposed the CIA-backed
contras.
</P>
<P>
   Equally striking is the way in which Gore and Bradley
consistently lined up on opposite sides on virtually every vote
taken between 1985 and 1992 on the federal government's various
farm price support programs.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it involved peanuts, tobacco, wheat, dairy products or
honey, Bradley routinely voted against farm subsidies, while Gore,
just as routinely, supported them. In 1990, Bradley even voted
against natural disaster relief for farmers. Gore supported the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the only farm-related vote that has caused Bradley any
political heartburn on the presidential trail has been his vote
against subsidies for ethanol, a fuel additive made from corn. Such
subsidies are popular in Iowa, which hosts the first presidential
preference voting next year, and Bradley now supports ethanol
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Gore's farm support votes are also causing the vice
president problems. In 1985, Gore voted to subsidize the tobacco
industry, while Bradley opposed the measure. But Gore and the
Clinton administration have led the attack on tobacco in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Gore voted the opposite of Bradley to support a 1988
bill that was designed to protect the largely Southern-based
textile industry from imports. As vice president, Gore has
championed the administration's free trade policies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's record on most of these issues may be popular in his home
region, but it might work against him elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not always a good thing in Democratic presidential
primaries,'' said Merle Black, a political science professor at
Emory University in Atlanta and co-author of ``The Vital South,'' a
1992 book about the pivotal role the South plays in presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic primaries, especially in the Northeast, attract more
liberal voters. And as Bradley has effectively positioned himself
to the left of the vice president, his Senate voting record is part
of his campaign's appeal to liberals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard assumption _ that they are nearly identical _
misses the detail,'' Eric Howser, Bradley's press secretary, said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   To counter, Gore emphasizes one big difference between his and
Bradley's Senate voting records _ Bradley's support for school
voucher ``experiments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never supported vouchers,'' Gore repeatedly notes in an
appeal aimed at teacher organizations, which are active in
Democratic primaries and which regard vouchers as a threat to
public education funding.
</P>
<P>
   But when the presidential campaign moves to the South next
March, Gore's emphasis is likely to shift to other differences in
his and Bradley's voting records, specifically, his own
pro-military votes and Bradley's consistent opposition to farm
price support programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there are issues that resonate in the South,'' said
Gore press secretary Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In their Senate days, Gore and Bradley also split company on
several key votes in the Senate's effort to stop the record growth
of the federal budget deficit during the Reagan and Bush
presidencies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore voted for a proposed constitutional amendment requiring a
balanced federal budget, and Bradley opposed it. Gore also
supported the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings law in 1985 that tried to set
spending caps, but Bradley rejected it as a gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also was a bit more partisan than Bradley in voting to
confirm presidential appointees, rejecting more nominees than
Bradley. But Bradley voted against the Supreme Court nomination of
David Souter, while Gore supported it. And Bradley opposed the
nomination of Alan Greenspan to head the Federal Reserve, while
Gore voted in favor of it.
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
