<SLUG> BC-FORCE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FORCE MORE POWERFUL': WINNING A CAUSE BY REFUSING TO FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most stunning images from Richard Attenborough's 1982
film, ``Gandhi,'' is the line upon line upon line of protesters
standing up to British oppression by lying down, or allowing
themselves to be knocked down.
</P>
<P>
   What Gandhi did was undeniably momentous. He invented and taught
passive resistance based on the Hindu concept of satyagraha, the
assertion of truth through firmness and patience, and as a result
won India its independence. Luckily, early-20th-century movie
cameras were around to record much of it.
</P>
<P>
   The cinematic possibilities in Gandhi's accomplishment make it
all the sadder that ``A Force More Powerful,'' a documentary about
nonviolent protest written, directed and produced by Steve York,
has taken such a formal approach.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which opens Friday, conveys valuable information, but
with the imagination and liveliness of a high school history
lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Moviegoers will learn dates and the names of some true unsung
heroes, but in unmemorable ways. Even the screen titles are
academic: ``I. India,'' ``II. Nashville, Tenn.'' and ``III. South
Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nashville,'' the best-told story, introduces the Rev. James
Lawson Jr., a young Methodist minister who worked with the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. Lawson taught the principles of passive
resistance to young black people in Tennessee in preparation for
the lunch counter sit-ins of 1960. The film of their rehearsals and
of the sit-ins is fascinating, as is a brief early appearance by
King on ``Meet the Press'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively unknown hero of South Africa's victory over
apartheid is Mkhuseli Jack, who led consumer boycotts beginning in
1985. Gandhi's story began in Africa too, where he lived from the
early 1890s to 1914. When he staged peaceful protests there, Jan
Smuts, then the country's interior minister, told him: ``You reduce
me to helplessness. How can we lay hands on you without looking
like villains?''
</P>
<P>
   That was the point, of course, and the method continues to work
miracles.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `A FORCE MORE POWERFUL'
</P>
<P>
   Written, produced and directed by Steve York; director of
photography, Giulio Biccari, Peter Pearce and Dilip Varma; edited
by Joseph Wiedenmayer and Anny Lowery Meza; music by John D.
Keltonic; released by Santa Monica Pictures. Running time: 110
minutes. This film is not rated .
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Mkhuseli Jack and the Rev. James Lawson Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1703EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
