A4084 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      11-18 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SACKLER GETS ASIAN ART; ARMANI AT GUGGENHEIM; GIFT AT CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Passage From India
</P>
<P>
   Cary Welch, a Harvard alumnus and scholar, has given the Arthur
M. Sackler Museum in Cambridge, Mass., more than 300 works of
Indian and Islamic art.
</P>
<P>
   Welch, a leading collector of Turko-Indo-Iranian art for the
last 40 years, was a teacher and curator at Harvard until his
retirement in the mid-1970s. He gave the Sackler, part of the
university art museums, his works from India, Iran and Turkey
dating from the 15th to 19th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's collection includes more than 250 works from India,
among them 190 drawings and paintings from Rajasthan. Combined with
his 1995 gift to the Sackler of more than 70 Indian paintings, plus
earlier donations from John Kenneth Galbraith and John Goelt, the
Harvard University Art Museums now have the most important
collection of Indian drawings and paintings in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The Fogg Art Museum, the Sackler's sister institution, has a
world-class collection of Western drawings. ``It adds strength to
strength,'' said James Cuno, the director of the Harvard museums.
</P>
<P>
   He said an exhibition of Welch's drawing collection, with a
catalog, would be held at the Sackler in about three years. ``It
makes us a stop for anyone studying Persian, Turkish and Indian
art,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to Fashion
</P>
<P>
   Since its blockbuster 1998 exhibition ``The Art of the
Motorcycle'' which drew record-breaking crowds of more than 500,000
visitors, the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum in New York has been
casting about for another offbeat subject from 20th-century
culture. This week it announced that its big fall show in 2000
would be a Giorgio Armani retrospective.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the museum choose the Italian fashion designer to fill
its entire rotunda at one of the busiest times on the art world
calendar?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking about doing a big fashion show for about
five years now,'' said Lisa Dennison, the Guggenheim's chief
curator. ``We debated and debated about who the great fashion
designers are that haven't been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dennison added that the museum did not have seasons and
that, contrary to what most people thought, the summer was its most
popular time of year because of tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armani comes right after `1900: Art at the Crossroads,' a
survey show of the year 1900, which is very classical,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The Armani show, to run from Oct. 13 through Jan. 10, will
feature more than 200 garments plus sketches, photographs and a
video presentation. The exhibition's curators are to be Germano
Celant and Harold Koda. Koda was a curator at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art, where he helped organize exhibitions for its Costume
Institute. Celant, a senior curator of contemporary art at the
Guggenheim, has organized exhibitions that included a fashion
component, like ``The Italian Metamorphosis, 1943-1968'' in 1994.
He also helped organize the first Biennial in Florence, ``Looking
at Fashion,'' three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The motorcycle exhibition had an unusual installation: the
California architect Frank O. Gehry wrapped the rotunda in shiny
stainless-steel panels. Now the Guggenheim has asked the French
architect Jean Nouvel to design the Armani installation. Robert
Wilson, the stage director, is to work with Nouvel on the lighting.
</P>
<P>
   But the big question is whether the Armani company will help pay
for the exhibition. ``We do not have a sponsor yet,'' Ms. Dennison
said. The museum hasn't asked Armani to be a sponsor, she added,
and is seeking other corporate support.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim has received financial help from fashion
companies in the past. Its five-year arrangement with Hugo Boss,
the German menswear company, ends this year. Boss sponsored two to
three exhibitions a year and provided educational support to the
museum along with funds for the annual $50,000 Hugo Boss Prize,
awarded to a young artist. Although Boss decided to concentrate its
energies on sports events, officials at the Guggenheim said the
museum hoped to continue some ties with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Gift
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Art Institute has also received a gift of drawings
this week. Jean and Steven Goldman, patrons of the museum, gave it
$5 million toward renovating its department of prints and drawings
and announced their intention to donate their collection of about
80 old master drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goldman, a scholar in Italian 16th-century drawings, has
been a lecturer and an adjunct professor at the institute's school.
``Precisely because she is a scholar, the collection has
intellectual integrity,'' said Suzanne Folds McCullagh, the curator
of early drawings at the institute. ``As collectors, the Goldmans
were not afraid to take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goldman said she began collecting drawings 33 years ago with
a Madonna and Child by Carlo Maratta. Her works date from 1450 to
about 1650, and include drawings by masters like Titian, Guercino,
Parmigianino and Romano.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of things we didn't have before,'' Ms.
McCullagh said. ``What is important is that this gift isn't just
bricks and mortar but a collection, too. And we're hoping it will
instill more philanthropy from other collectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Appointment
</P>
<P>
   Ned Rifkin, director of the High Museum of Art in Atlanta since
1991, has been named director of the Menil Collection in Houston.
He succeeds Paul Winkler, who resigned in February. Rifkin begins
his post Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Resignation
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Stebbins, who for 22 years has been a curator at the
Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and was most recently chairman of the
art of the Americas department, has resigned effective Jan. 17. He
is the third senior curator to resign or be asked to leave the
museum in the last five months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
