<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4093 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-EGOYAN-PROFILE-H     11-18 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EGOYAN-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOURNEY' INTO ARTISTRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vast majority of movies are meant simply to entertain.
</P>
<P>
   So Atom Egoyan, 1997 best-director and best-writer Oscar nominee
for ``The Sweet Hereafter,'' has trouble understanding why some
people seem so put out when, now and then, a film strives to be
more. Like painting, writing or music, some movies, Egoyan
believes, can and should strive for artistry.
</P>
<P>
   This came up because I told Egoyan that a novelist who had seen
his newest film, ``Felicia's Journey,'' had asked why anyone would
want to make a movie that was disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that laughable,'' Egoyan said, looking not at all like
he was about to laugh. ``Some of the artists that I most respect, a
lot of them writers, have this view that movies are somehow an
escape from it all. (They say) `Movies should be entertaining.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand that. A movie can be disturbing and
entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be the short definition of Egoyan's work: disturbing
and entertaining. Take the exquisitely elusive ``Exotica,'' a film
about several troubled characters built around a high-class men's
club. Or the deliciously sad puzzle film ``The Sweet Hereafter,''
in which a small town is turned inside out by a bus accident that
has killed several children.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those films, in which the ``plot'' is almost impossible
to summarize, ``Felicia's Journey'' could be given a short ``genre
film'' description. But not only would that give away a few things
best not known before seeing it, but it also would be highly
misleading.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say this: It is a highly unconventional thriller,
set in England, in which a naive, lost Irish girl (Elaine Cassidy)
is given shelter by a likable but disturbed man (Bob Hoskins).
</P>
<P>
   Egoyan is uncomfortable talking about the artistry in his work,
but he won't pretend it's unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit coy when you make a film like this to say you just
want people to see it as a movie,'' he said. ``You've designed it
and expressed it in a way that invites further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If `Felicia's Journey' was made just as a movie, it would
provide more visceral and immediate jolts. But there is space in
this movie _ and time _ which allows a viewer to contemplate other
issues: What is the nature of consciousness? What is the nature of
personality? When are we really being ourselves?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like (being considered artistic) in the sense that it
marginalizes the work, but artistic in the sense I would use the
possibilities of cinema in an exploratory way. Using it as an art
form, as opposed to an industrial means of communicating narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an attempt to operate at a different level and
combine elements of music and cinematography and drama in a really
textured way _ to find a form, which elevates the material into
something a bit more mythic.''
</P>
<P>
   Egoyan, 39, was born in Cairo and raised in Victoria, British
Columbia. Since ``The Sweet Hereafter,'' he has been regarded
almost as a Canadian national treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a book by William Trevor, ``Felicia's Journey'' is much
more about what is beneath the surface of his characters than what
is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Films are about the seduction and pleasure (of the
audience),'' Egoyan said. ``To get the full pleasure you have to be
looking for other levels of meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, though, to be too obscure, too subtle. Egoyan
says he was guilty of that in his early films, but he believes that
what we, as viewers, don't see is revealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `The Sweet Hereafter,' I tried to deal with the notion of
incest, but from the point of view of what a victim would think is
going on as it is unfolding. So that is subtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can see that movie, and they may not even get that
that's what's going on. Because they are in as much denial as (the
girl victim) is.''
</P>
<P>
   That film has a key scene in which a man we thought of as a good
father is seen quietly, tenderly but clearly molesting his
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `What was happening in that scene?''' Egoyan said.
He believes those viewers have done the same thing the victim has
done _ denied the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've had the information; you've seen the empirical evidence
on screen. But you have effectively denied that scene,'' Egoyan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, to me, is very interesting as a phenomenon. Those people
might say, `That is very subtle.' Well, it's not, really. You don't
want to believe that's what is happening. You don't want to believe
who this man is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1712EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GULBENKIAN-COLLECTION     11-18 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULBENKIAN-COLLECTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: CALOUSTE GULBENKIAN'S LIFELONG PASSION FOR THE BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT3) has beent sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What is there to be said about the Metropolitan
Museum of Art's wonderful exhibition of treasures from the
legeollection that Calouste Gulbenkian assembled in the
first half of this century and then left to the world in a museum
in Lisbon, where he spent his last dozen years? See it, enjoy it,
pore over its every object from beginning to end: that is, from a
17th-century Armenian illuminated Bible to a vitrine of three
Japanese lacquers.
</P>
<P>
   In between lie extraordinary examples of Islamic and Turkish
textiles and ceramics, 18th-century silver, European painting and
the Art Nouveau jewelry of Rene Lalique. Glean all you can about
the many forms that visual power can take and the spells they cast
on generation after generation.
</P>
<P>
   See this show also for proof that great collectors are as driven
as artists and have as little choice in their calling, even though
the evidence here won't exactly prove that natural collectors will
pursue their quest regardless of their financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Gulbenkian was born into a family of prosperous
Armenian merchants and bankers in Istanbul in 1869.
</P>
<P>
   For another, his skill and tenacity as an organizer of oil
companies and a broker of trade agreements eventually made him one
of the world's wealthiest men, and also one of the shrewdest and
most determined of art buyers. Still, the urge to collect seems to
have asserted itself before all else.
</P>
<P>
   Gulbenkian made his first acquisition at age 14 when his father
gave him a small amount of money as a reward for academic
excellence; he went directly to a market and purchased an ancient
coin. It was not for another seven or eight years, after returning
to Turkey from schooling in France and England, that he grasped the
importance that oil would soon have and began to explore the Middle
Eastern oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   The 80 objects in this exhibition are diverse enough that they
nearly form a mini-Met. Every gallery presents a different facet of
Gulbenkian's collection and his demanding sensibility; sometimes
there is a change in culture, century or medium every few yards.
Within 30 feet of the entrance, for example, you will move from a
Roman medal bearing Alexander the Great's likeness, to a finely
detailed Late Dynasty head of an old man to a Yuan porcelain stem
cup to Ghirlandaio's gossamer portrait of a Florentine noblewoman
in the bloom of youth, her neck encircled by coal beads.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it all hangs together in a whole in a virtual self-portrait
of a man of passionate connoisseurship, a man of complex cultural
background and princely lifestyle who had a penchant for objects of
lavish material and superb craftsmanship. Gulbenkian was not
interested in being comprehensive in any way; he bought only what
captured and held his attention.
</P>
<P>
   He continually weeded and refined his holdings, giving away,
trading or selling objects that did not measure up. He was famously
picky, taking things home on approval for days or even weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And he frequently beat dealers at their own game. In the late
1920s, when the financially shaky Soviet Union was selling off some
of the Russian Empress Elizabeth I's silver _ a 21-pound dish cover
in the form of frolicking fish by the great French silversmith
Antoine-Sebastien Durand, for example _ Gulbenkian's business
connections enabled him to close a deal ahead of Joseph Duveen, and
at a lower price.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition, then, is a distillation of a collection that
had been rigorously distilled by the time of its owner's death in
1955. (The foundation that he established in his will created the
museum, which opened in its permanent home in 1969.) The show
traces Gulbenkian's taste in big transcultural arcs, alternating
paintings and sculpture with the decorative in ways that create
telling visual echoes.
</P>
<P>
   The fascination with portraiture that asserts itself early in
the show carries on throughout. Near the Ghirlandaio, for example,
there is a remarkable Florentine medal of Filippo Strozzi at an
advanced age, seen in profile, his wrinkles and sags as visible as
his proud unyielding character. Skip a gallery and you'll be face
to face with Rubens' magnificent full-length portrait of Helena
Fourment, his young second wife, arrayed in black satin, queenly
yet beguiling.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is a Watteau study of a woman's head shown in three
graceful positions that seems to capture a single, cinematic
movement. And beyond there is Gainsborough's portrait of Elizabeth
Lowndes-Stone, also full length, her silks and the surrounding
landscape rendered in loose, windswept strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's penultimate gallery holds two great portraits
from 19th-century France. Degas' tiny full-length portrait of the
painter Henri Michel-Levy _ elegant, lost in thought, with a
life-size female mannequin lying at his feet in an awkward heap _
is as pictorially complex and emotionally charged as this enigmatic
artist gets.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite wall hangs Manet's ``Boy Blowing Bubbles'' of
1867, as arresting for its image of youthful focus as for its
luscious shades of gray and gray-white, especially palpable in the
subject's humble jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Gulbenkian's passion for lavish decorative objects finds
expression in a room devoted to Iranian and Turkish ceramics,
glass, tiles and textiles. On one wall a carpet and three hangings
in silk or velvet, most with silver thread, form an isolated
exegesis on motifs derived from nature and the many possibilities
of figure-ground, positive-negative relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The growth cycle itself seems to be enacted in a 17th-century
velvet panel in which patterns of red, white and blue on a cream
background feature flowers in schematic bud form, at half bloom and
full bloom.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A later gallery displays a sampling of the Gulbenkian's
18th-century French decorative arts. Included here are the silver
dish cover and Elizabeth I's three-piece silver centerpiece
featuring impeccably coiffed toddlers, ornately floral silk panels
that once belonged to the French royal family, and a medal cabinet
by Charles Cressant whose inlaid rosewood is all but obliterated by
its engraved gilt bronze mounts.
</P>
<P>
   In the final gallery Gulbenkian's taste for the decoration based
on nature reaches the turn of the century with Lalique's jewelry.
This includes a gold-and-enamel brooch depicting nine serpents that
is the size of a small breastplate and a choker in rock crystal
whose tiny squares depict cats crouched on tree limbs. Best of all
is an amber glass sugar bowl snared in an elaborate silver setting
of writhing, hissing serpents likely to curtail most cravings for
sweets.
</P>
<P>
   At the show's beginning one might take in three illuminated
books of hours, including one from 16th-century France open to a
particularly emotional image of Jesus carrying the Cross. From
14th-century France there's an ivory diptych that recounts the life
of Jesus and in a subsequent gallery a 15th-century Iranian
manuscript illumination in which a young prince surveys seven
princesses installed in a separate pavilions that form a single,
apselike space.
</P>
<P>
   Farther along Fragonard's ``Fete at Rambouillet,'' shows a
boating party moving toward a picturesque garden in a scene that
changes from tame to wild and from frivolous to disquieting before
your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the last painting gallery, ``Wreck of a Transport
Ship,'' an early work by J.M.W. Turner, depicts a futile rescue
attempt in towering seas. The lifeboats and struggling figures are
rendered in exquisite detail, the churning waves in broader strokes
that convey not only the indefatigable power of nature but also the
growing imagination that would be fully unleashed in Turner's later
works.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Only the Best': Masterpieces of the Calouste Gulbenkian
Museum, Lisbon,'' remains at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, 82nd
Street at Fifth Avenue, Manhattan, (212) 879-5500, through Feb. 27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
