<HEADLINE>
MYERS SHOWS HIS `POWERS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `AUSTIN POWERS: THE SPY WHO SHAGGED ME'
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, New Line, CC, VHS $22.98, DVD $24.98. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Most sequels are less entertaining and make less money than
their predecessors. This one did the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spy'' is funnier than 1997's Austin Powers: International Man
of Mystery, and it also made more money on its opening weekend ($55
million) than the first film did in its entire domestic run ($54
million).
</P>
<P>
   Chalk it up to Mike Myers hitting his stride _ and while you're
at it, give the guy bonus points.
</P>
<P>
   Myers plays three roles here (not counting time-displaced copies
of '60s spy Austin Powers himself), so he's in almost every scene.
</P>
<P>
   He's a stitch _ but not without a hitch. ``Spy'' is stupidly
plotted and riddled with holes.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers brush off this laziness as deliberate, with
characters making fun of the nonsense in asides to the audience.
Not making sense is deemed part of the joke.
</P>
<P>
   The plot has Dr. Evil (Myers) in the '90s using time travel to
steal Austin's ``mojo,'' or life force, from the '60s, thus
rendering Austin ineffective in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   To retrieve his ``mojo,'' Austin teams with American spy
Felicity Shagwell (Heather Graham). Meanwhile, Dr. Evil adopts a
tiny clone of himself in Mini-Me (Verne Troyer).
</P>
<P>
   Plopping down in the middle is an obese Scottish mercenary
(Myers again), whose gross-out gags may make you gag.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there's something to offend everyone here. Yet Myers'
crazed performance is more gleefully impudent than mean-spirited,
making this return romp an encore well worth making _ and having.
</P>
<P>
   As with the first film _ 1998's top tape on Billboard's charts _
this one is geared to sales, with the added bonus of DVD.
</P>
<P>
   The latter has scads of added material, including 19 minutes of
unused scenes and a half-hour documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Also featured are three music videos (including Madonna's
``Beautiful Stranger''), three theatrical trailers, feature-length
audio commentary by Myers and director Jay Roach, and a wide-screen
presentation of the film _ not to mention DVD-ROM features. Groovy.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BARTOK THE MAGNIFICENT'
</P>
<P>
   1999, G, Fox, CC, VHS $19.98, DVD $29.98.
</P>
<P>
   Like Disney's ``The Lion King,'' ``Pocahontas'' and ``Beauty and
the Beast'' and Universal's ``The Land Before Time,'' Fox's
``Anastasia'' is spinning off a sequel just for video.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no Princess Anastasia in sight. There's only Bartok,
the wisecracking little bat from the first film.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he and his bear pal, a hammy actor named Zozi (voiced by
Kelsey Grammer), must find a kidnapped Russian prince.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Azaria returns as the voice of Bartok, with Tim Curry as a
monstrous creature too close to his role in ``The Enchanted
Christmas,'' Disney's video sequel to ``Beauty and the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   French Stewart, Jennifer Tilly, Catherine O'Hara and Diedrich
Bader also lend voices to this tale of magic, music and mirth.
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Anastasia,'' the quality of the animation is
remarkably high. Directing were Don Bluth and Gary Goldman, who
also helmed ``Anastasia'' and collaborated on ``The Land Before
Time,'' ``All Dogs Go to Heaven'' and ``An American Tail.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bartok, he's more fun on his own than you'd expect.
</P>
<P>
   Wryly complaining, his voice breaking, he's an amusingly impish
hero, and his mite size makes the fanciful vistas and giant
creatures seem even more imposing.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `TEA WITH MUSSOLINI' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG, MGM, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98.
</P>
<P>
   Italian writer-director Franco Zeffirelli creates a strong sense
of time and place for this semi-autobiographical look at his
childhood, yet the story seems detached.
</P>
<P>
   His surrogate is a homeless boy who's taken in by expatriate
Englishwomen _ and two ``vulgar'' Americans _ in Italy on the eve
of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   As war erupts, the women must cope with the hostilities, even
though one woman did, in fact, have tea with the Italian dictator,
who assured them they'd be safe.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is superb, with Joan Plowright, Maggie Smith and Judi
Dench as the Englishwomen and Cher and Lily Tomlin as the
Americans. They don't always gel well, but they're full of life and
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the boy's presence seems incidental, and the
historical plot has a plodding inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VIDEO RATINGS &QL; 
4 stars _ excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ good &QL; 
2 stars _ fair &QL; 
1 star _ poor &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
