<HEADLINE>
CAYMAN GOVERNMENT TELLS CRUISERS: NEVER ON A SUNDAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGE TOWN, Grand Cayman _ The Cayman Islands made a bold
statement this year about tourism and community values by closing
its ports to cruise ships on Sundays and religious holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson, Cayman minister of tourism, said the decision
followed two years of discussion by the government's Executive
Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we be role models if we openly condone business on
Sundays and religious holidays?'' Jefferson said. ``This sends a
contradictory message to our young people. We cannot tell our
children to respect and live by such values while ignoring them
ourselves. Restoring the sanctity of observing Sundays, Christmas
and Good Friday sends a strong message about the importance of
Christian values in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the first time the Cayman Islands have cited
religious values in closing a port. Two years ago, Grand Cayman
made headlines when it turned away a Norwegian Cruise Line ship
chartered for gay passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from restaurants, there is little commercial activity on
Sundays in the Caymans. Bars close at midnight on Saturdays and
cannot reopen until 1 p.m. on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   The country's deeply held religious beliefs also mean that
public nudity is not tolerated. Laws prohibit topless sunbathing.
And local custom calls on tourists to cover up once they are off
the beach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
