<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING THE TRAIL OF FOLK ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now in its 21st year, Sanford Smith's Fall Antiques
Show is still the premier show in the country for folk art.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Wallach, one of 64 exhibitors at the show, which runs
through Sunday at the Armory at Park Avenue in Manhattan, praised
the show for its antique and period folk art, ``in terms of quality
of dealers, merchandise and the amount of participation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallach is expecting clients from Detroit, Chicago, Cincinnati,
Philadelphia and, yes, Alaska. Among his exhibits is a poignant
shadow-box diorama dated April 5, 1900. It was made by a sailor for
his captain after he survived a shipwreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painted on canvas rescued from the wrecked ship,''
Wallach said.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a six-foot-tall grandfather clock covered with
wooden clothespins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely homemade,'' he said. ``The Shakers invented
the clothespin in about 1850. Here someone in the Adirondacks has
reinvented it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallach said he drove across northern New York State in search
of folk art, but often came home emptyhanded.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Judith Milne, another dealer at the show, said, ``It's tough,
really tough, to find great things now.'' She added that really
good items sold very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Some dealers find stock in novel ways. Amy Finkel of M. Finkel &AMP;
Daughter, a Philadelphia dealer in American needlepoint, created a
Web site, www.samplings.com, and found that it became a source of
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much to our surprise, we find people approach us to sell
things after they see our site,'' Ms. Finkel said. ``We had no idea
it would be such a successful business tool.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At the show, Ms. Finkel is selling a New England needlework
picture signed ``Elizabeth Newsam, Feb. 16, 1753.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a glorious rendition of a couple standing on a hillock _
very much in the mid-18th-century tradition of sophisticated
needlework one finds in Massachusetts,'' Ms. Finkel said. ``To have
made this, you would have had to come from a family who cared
enough to send you to school to learn needlework.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen and Carol Huber of Old Saybrook, Conn., are showing silk
embroideries of classical scenes from the Moravian School in
Bethlehem, Pa., one of the oldest girls' schools in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is so strong now that people are willing to part
with things,'' Ms. Huber said.
</P>
<P>
   She also has a pair of samplers marked ``1807 Holmes Hole,'' the
name of a town on Martha's Vineyard. She found out that the pair
was the work of two classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``One married the other's brother,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Each sampler is priced at $4,500.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate the millennium, Laura Fisher said, she is showing
``textbook examples of museum-quality quilts from every single
decade of the century _ the 19th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Gecker, a Manhattan dealer, has two 19th-century Fiske
weather vanes. One is a rare gilded copper dragon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only other one I've ever seen sold for $95,000 at the
Winter Antiques Show 15 years ago,'' Gecker said.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Milne has a 1930s Adirondacks sideboard that is eight
feet long and has drawer fronts decorated with fish, deer and
horses carved in relief. It costs $12,500.
</P>
<P>
   She also has a striking woodcarving of a man playing pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like an Elie Nadelman sculpture,'' she said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fantasies in Silver &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is extraordinary 18th-century French silver in ``Only the
Best: Masterpieces of the Calouste Gulbenkian Museum, Lisbon,''
which opened at the Metropolitan Museum of Art on Tuesday (review,
Page x). Most of the silver was designed for the dinner table, but
utilitarian functions are strictly secondary. These are Rococo
pieces designed to dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there is a pair of silver mustard barrels made
about 1751 for Madame de Pompadour by Antoine-Sebastien Durand. Two
tiny men, quivers of arrows thrown over their shoulders, are
trundling the barrels along in tiny wheelbarrows, which roll on
silver wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of thing that just screams Gulbenkian,'' said
James David Draper, the Met's curator of European sculpture and
decorative arts. ``He liked things that were the summation of a
civilization. He wanted the perfect representational object.''
</P>
<P>
   An Armenian born in Istanbul, Gulbenkian (1869-1955) became one
of the world's richest men, founding the Turkish Petroleum Co.
before World War I and then using his fortune to amass a fine art
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Another item in the show is a Rococo silver gilt tureen and
stand made for Empress Elizabeth I of Russia in 1758-61. It is one
of eight commissioned from Francois-Thomas Germain, widely
considered the best Rococo silversmith of France.
</P>
<P>
   The lid of the tureen is adorned with two small children at
play. A small boy is tugging on the leash of his dog, trying to
stop it from approaching a nest of eggs in which baby birds are
hatching. A little girl protects one bird by holding it in her
hand. Fruits and flowers are scattered about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel a certain taste for sensuality in such pieces,''
said Joao Castel-Branco Pereira, director of the Gulbenkian Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable piece by Durand is an enormous dish cover
called a cloche. Designed to serve fish, it is festooned with
exuberant sea creatures. A conger eel cranes its mouth to catch a
sardine in midair. Around it, a sole, a red mullet and a dogfish
fall out of a creel. Oysters, clams and shellfish rest on a bed of
algae. On the base, a boy is supported by two dolphins. Waving sea
grasses are etched on the sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fish are so realistic they look like life casts,'' Draper
said.
</P>
<P>
   Few such spectacular silver services survive; most were melted
down by the French kings when they needed money to go to war.
</P>
<P>
   Silver services cost a fortune to make in the 18th century, and
because of their rarity cost a fortune to buy 200 years later. But
Gulbenkian's friends say he used his silver.
</P>
<P>
   One friend, Robert Arnold, recalled: ``Gulbenkian was an
intensely private person, but he entertained lavishly. That silver
was out and around the dining room.''
</P>
<P>
   Sao Schlumberger, a Paris society woman who received an art
scholarship from Gulbenkian when she was 18, said: ``He bought
whatever he liked. He was interested in everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Essayan, Gulbenkian's grandson, said: ``My grandfather
always told me, `I've taken advice, but in the end I always bought
what I liked.'''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold added, ``Rather like the Rockefellers after World War I,
he just bought everything that was the best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
