<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-SON-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAGAN'S SON MIKE TALKS OF CHILDHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TOM SCHULTZ   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ Mike Reagan, the son of former President
Ronald Reagan, says he shares ``Kodak moments'' with his ill
father, who has Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hug him hello and hug him goodbye,'' Reagan said during a
speech here. ``He hasn't said my name in two years, but he knows
I'm the guy who hugs him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sitting down now. It's not easy for him to stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan's ailment has been well documented in recent
years, and public interest in the former president is still high
and particularly persistent in Santa Barbara, where the younger
Reagan was invited to speak Wednesday to the Channel City Club. The
former president and first lady, Ronald and Nancy Reagan, owned a
ranch here, which was their vacation home.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Reagan, 55, is the adopted son of Reagan and his first
wife, the actress Jane Wyman. He is now a syndicated talk show
host.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Reagan largely ignored hot-button issues like
abortion and gun control that he normally tackles on his
conservative radio show. Instead, he offered brief glimpses of his
childhood, and talked about the difficulties of being raised by
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   The experience was not all positive, Reagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Boarding school filled many of his early years, which were spent
largely away from his parents: ``I never really did see them that
much.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Reagan frustrated his father with shallow
academic performances. And like so many sons or daughters, he
sparred with Ronald Reagan over musical taste: ``I was listening to
the Beach Boys, and he was listening to some guy named Glenn
Miller.''
</P>
<P>
   But if his relationship with his parents was at times distant,
it was not without value, Reagan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jane Wyman and Ronald Reagan have the same defects _ yeah,
they were born with a work ethic,'' Reagan said.
</P>
<P>
   While his father was governor of California, Reagan loaded
freight at a Los Angeles trucking dock, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had guys on the dock coming up to me asking, `Do your
parents just not like you?'''
</P>
<P>
   For much of his adult life, Reagan raced and sold speed boats.
</P>
<P>
   His current radio program went national in 1992, and it is now
heard on stations across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan said he has no plans to abandon his latest line of work,
and will not be seeking public office any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   If you get elected,'' he said, ``you've got to say goodbye to
your family. I'm not willing to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
