 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Friday, November 19, 1999,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX _ LAS VEGAS _ Cable and DSL technologies continue their
push for high-speed Internet access, but complex installations and
a critical lack of availability hamper wiper usage. In the
meantime, new wireless technologies such as ``Bluetooth'' hold the
promise of briding the gap between speed and efficiency. An
overview of what's new and hot, plus a look at the problems.
(Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   DELLHOUSE _ In Dell's vision, the typical American household
will have a sleek descendant of the venerable PC as the command
center for numerous Internet-connected devices. The family room
will be a multi-media playground tying TV, PC and music systems
together, while family members who want to surf the web from
somewhere quiet will use wireless connections to the Internet from
other rooms. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   HOMEDEPOT _ATLANTA _Home Depot announced a 3-for-2 stock split
and a 50 percent increase in the quarterly cash dividend.
Stockholders of record on Dec. 2 will be issued 1.5 shares for each
share held. The additional stocks will be distributed Dec. 30.
After the split, the number of shares outstanding will increase to
about 2.22 billion from about 1.48 billion. It's the company's 13th
split since it sold shares to the public in 1981. (BOnd, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RETOOL _ KENNESAW, Ga. _ ReTool, a new chain that sells used
tools, just opened in this suburban Atlanta town. It's the first of
as many as 500 stores across the country, according to its parent
company, GrowBiz. ReTool sells tools at half price and buys them
from the public. Most of the tools originally come from Home Depot
or Lowe's, says owner Ben Boston of Marietta, Ga. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
