<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS MOVES TOWARD RESTORING MEDICARE FUNDSBy LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress appeared ready Thursday to restore $16
billion to Medicare over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The action came as the House voted 296-135 for a massive
spending bill to finance much of the federal government through
September 2000. Senate action could come by this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare provisions ease cuts imposed primarily on hospitals
and health maintenance organizations as part of the 1997 Balanced
Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care providers who have been struggling under the
burden of money-saving regulations imposed in 1997 will now be
getting some much-needed relief,'' said Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr.,
R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years, the bill increases payments to
hospitals by $7.2 billion, to managed care groups by $4.8 billion,
and to nursing homes, home health and hospice services by $3.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also increases the amount spent for Medicare Part B _
doctors and related services _ by $2.8 billion over five years.
One-fourth of the cost of Medicare Part B is paid by beneficiary
premiums. Medicare Part B is expected to spend roughly $100 billion
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional staffers said Thursday they did not know how much
premiums would have to increase to cover the additional Part B
expenses. The monthly premium is now $45.50 and will remain at that
amount in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare provisions are intended to fix a problem caused by
the 1997 law. Because of the law, payments to hospitals for
outpatient services were cut in many areas below payment levels in
effect before the law was passed. The bill includes revisions to
add $3.9 billion for outpatient services, plus another $3.3 billion
for hospitals over all over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also extends from 36 months to 44 months the coverage
for people taking immunosuppressive drugs used in organ
transplants. It also suspends until 2003 proposed caps on payments
for physical theraphy and occupational therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
