<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV25-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYING WITH EGYPTAIR ON OUR MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Nov. 25)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day we flew east, front page newspaper photos showed the
shocked and tortured faces of relatives. A week later when we flew
home the photos were of mourners gathered for a large memorial.
</P>
<P>
   You can sit on a plane and read about another plane plunging
into the ocean, on its way to Egypt from New York, 30 minutes after
takeoff, but it doesn't stop you from flying. Your friend says the
odds are with you. It's usually a long time between bad air
crashes. Besides, you see car wrecks all the time and that doesn't
keep you from driving.
</P>
<P>
   So, you pack up early in the morning and get on a plane that you
trust will get you where you're wanting to go, even though you know
there are no guarantees you'll get there.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still unsure of the cause, but you squeeze
into your seat and go through your own personal boarding ritual.
Check to see what the movie will be, locate the nearest bathroom.
Stick the water bottle in the seat pocket in front of you, see if
there's anything in the reading rack but golf magazines and settle
back, trusting someone to get you there.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't entirely settle back. Even though you go ahead and
fly, you do it a little differently this time. You check exit
signs. You listen for appropriate and inappropriate noises. You
realize you have absolutely no control over this plane and send up
a little prayer as it starts down the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes flying is like a day off from work with the flu.
You've got a Vanity Fair that will last a few hours, music if you
want, a movie, someone to bring you food and drinks, make sure you
have a blanket. But those are the flying days when your head is not
caught up in front page photos.
</P>
<P>
   This time it doesn't matter if they've run out of pillows. It
doesn't even matter that you're so far in the back that all the
pasta is taken and only beef is left.
</P>
<P>
   So what that the guy in front of you has tall hair which will
probably block the movie screen. The flight attendant commiserates
and gives you a free headset.
</P>
<P>
   You don't even mind that the connecting flight from Chicago is
delayed because of mechanical problems and they're waiting for
another plane. Take all the time you need. They have a plane just
in from London that will do nicely but it needs to be serviced.
We'll wait.
</P>
<P>
   The guy in the camel coat with the sunglasses grousing at the
ticket agent behind the counter is not happy about waiting. He's
playing the role of very important and personally inconvenienced, a
type commonly seen at boarding gates. But on this day he grumbles
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm imagining it but I think we're being mannerly out of
respect. Another time we will be the impatient throng, complaining
about time lost, sighing heavily, critically noting the bulging
sides of another's carry-on.
</P>
<P>
   Why are we so lucky and 217 people on EgyptAir Flight 990 were
not? They had people who loved them, important jobs to do, friends
to meet, adventures to have. They didn't imagine their plane diving
into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   They were thinking miles and hours ahead, of the food they would
eat, the souvenirs they'd buy, the love they would make. But until
then maybe they'd have something to drink and hope the person next
to them didn't snore.
</P>
<P>
   They were like everyone in my plane, breathing each other's air,
rubbing elbows, touching thighs, anticipating one another's
bathrooms habits. Readers, watchers, eaters, sleepers, mostly
strangers who just happened to decide to go to the same place on
the same day on the same plane.
</P>
<P>
   It gets bumpy during the last 45 minutes. The college student
next to me, who's been under headphones the whole way, now has her
face to the window and I ask if she sees any lights yet. I tell her
that I always feel better when I see lights. She says it's raining
and there's nothing but black out there.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot has been pretty chirpy. A flight attendant was
offering free wine earlier and one walked down the aisle whistling.
</P>
<P>
   Now the captain tells the flight attendants to sit down. We
passengers will have to make sure our own tray tables are locked up
and our seat belts are securely fastened. He apologizes for the
turbulence but says we'll soon be landing, and then we are.
</P>
<P>
   The student points outside to where a city suddenly appears and
we smile at each other. We bump. We touch down. We stop.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 people are delivered this night safe and sound,
like some sort of miracle. We find the people we belong to and go
our separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
