<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-TV-DEAL-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV DEAL POWERFUL FOR NASCAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASCAR's announcement last week that it has agreed to a new
television deal worth a reported $2.8 billion marks a major step
forward for stock car racing.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the money being paid out by NBC Sports and Turner
Sports, NBC's cable partner, and Fox and its FX cable network
indicates that the networks now view NASCAR as comparable to pro
football, baseball and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   NBC/Turner and Fox/FX will combine to pay NASCAR $400 million a
year for six years, with Fox/FX signed for an additional two years
at a reported $200 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   The NBC/Turner contract begins in 2001 and expires in 2006, with
the Fox/FX deal extending through 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The total being paid to NASCAR is more than the networks are now
paying major-league baseball and the National Hockey League, and
close to what they are paying the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   Only the National Football League contract, which got a $17.6
billion, eight-year deal in 1998, is significantly more than what
NASCAR will make. Dick Ebersol, chairman of NBC Sports, called that
a ``ridiculous deal.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC/Turner will televise the final 18 races of the season, while
Fox/FX, which also has the NFL, will televise the first 18.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's all-star race, The Winston and the Bud Shootout, a race
featuring all the pole winners from the previous year, are also
part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   The Daytona 500 and the Pepsi 400, also run at Daytona, will
alternate between the two networks. In odd years, Fox will have the
Daytona 500 and NBC the Pepsi 400, and the coverage will be
reversed in even years.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR is the healthiest of any sport right now,'' Ebersol
said, pointing to Nielsen ratings which show that while other
sports are either losing viewers or have leveled off, NASCAR's
numbers are increasing yearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox walked away from hockey, and we walked away from
football,'' Ebersol said. ``It's going to take some education on
our part to learn the wheres and whys of racing, but we're excited
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Winston Cup, the contract calls for the networks
to televise Busch races.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the networks involved was key for NASCAR, according to
Bray Cary, NASCAR's vice president for broadcasting and technology.
Cary assisted Brian France, NASCAR's senior vice president in
charge of marketing, in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we've only had about 20 percent of our races on
network TV,'' Cary said. ``Now, 70 to 75 percent will be on the
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Fox is committed to doing a one-hour pre-race show
prior to each event. NBC will do 30 minute pre-race and 30 minute
post-race shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the pre-race shows are good lead-ins to the event and
will help draw new viewers,'' Cary said.
</P>
<P>
   The networks will also market NASCAR heavily, according to
Ebersol. ``I think you can expect to see references to NASCAR in
our other programming,'' he commented.
</P>
<P>
   According to France, the networks will retain ``full control of
the editorial content. They will also be in charge of production,''
although they are expected to work with NASCAR on new technology to
improve racing telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The exact method for distributing the television money has not
been worked out in detail. Generally, NASCAR will get 10 percent,
the tracks 65 percent and the drivers 25 percent. But the 65
percent going to the tracks will not be shared equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Daytona 500, which is our Super Bowl, will get more than
the others, and we're working on a formula which will include TV
ratings, purse size, attendance and about 30 other things that will
determine how much each race gets,'' Cary said.
</P>
<P>
   Cary said that all races will be carried in their entirety
regardless of rain delays or other problems. ``In most cases, the
networks will carry the race from start to finish,'' Cary
commented. ``In some instances, a particular race might be switched
to the network's cable partner for the conclusion, but the complete
race will be shown.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
