<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Nov. 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Showers and a few thunderstorms will develop across the
Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys on Friday as moisture from the
Gulf of Mexico streams northward and intercepts a cold front.
Showers will produce brief downpours in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, lighter rains will dampen parts of the lower Ohio
Valley and central Great Lakes as the availability of moisture
decreases along the northern flank of the front. Meanwhile, showers
of rain or snow will fall across parts of the upper Mississippi
River Valley as cold, moist air wraps west-southwestward around a
low pressure system centered over Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Very mild air will surge into the upper Ohio River Valley ahead
of the cold front as increasing winds from the south build to
speeds averaging 15 to 25 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle or light rain will speckle parts of the Southeast as
moist winds from the Atlantic press inland across parts of
northeast Florida, Georgia and South Carolina. Farther south, moist
ocean winds will fuel isolated showers and thundershowers near the
east-central and southeast coasts of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will douse parts of the Pacific Northwest as moist ocean
winds persist in the wake of a cool front. Rainfalls will be
enhanced in places, particularly in northern California, where a
jet stream disturbance trailing the front works in tandem with the
lay of the land to lift arriving Pacific air. Rainfalls will be
also augmented along west-facing slopes of the Washington and
Oregon Cascades as Pacific air is forced to ascend the sloping
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Lenny's Lessening
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Hurricane Lenny, armed with winds sustained at 135
mph, drifted toward St. Maarten in the British Virgin Islands. Near
the top of the ring of powerful thunderstorms that encircled the
eye, air flowed efficiently outward away from the center of the
storm, preventing any weighty build-up of air that might cause the
system to weaken. Yet Hurricane Lenny weakened anyway. Lenny's
lessening was caused by the hurricane itself, whose fierce winds
stirred Atlantic seas, allowing slightly cooler water to rise to
the sea surface. Cooler water, in turn, caused the storm to weaken.
</P>
</TEXT>
