<HEADER>
A4145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BODY-ART-EXHIBIT-2TAK     11-18 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BODY-ART-EXHIBIT-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BODY ART': WHEN THE BODY IS AN ART GALLERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Body art: Marks of Identity,'' which opens Saturday
at the American Museum of Natural History, is a transparent effort
on the part of a family-style institution to heat up its image and
pull in a fresh audience, one that probably couldn't care less
about large, extinct reptiles with tiny brains.
</P>
<P>
   The theme is personal adornment of the most intimate kind,
usually applied directly onto or into the skin. The exhibition _
smart, extremely entertaining and assembled in record time _ is
geared to the current fashion-as-art vogue. The packed installation
offers just enough bare, multicultural flesh to inspire viewer
rubbernecking, without actually being an adults-only affair.
</P>
<P>
   Most interesting, though, is the way the show, organized by Enid
Schildkraut, brings art and anthropology seamlessly together. Not
so long ago, one would have been hard put to find a major museum
exhibition in which Greek vases and African sculptures, ethnic
postcards and Indian miniatures, Victorian corsets and Amazonian
nose-plugs got equal time. But they get it here, no problem, and
all in the interest of looking at what people do to their bodies,
and why.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The ``why'' is important. Critical, questioning histories of
fashion are few, but ``Body Art,'' with its cultural breadth and
anthropological bias, at least suggests directions they might take.
</P>
<P>
   The show acknowledges fashion's universal feel-good appeal, but
also its tendency to reinforce hierarchies of superiority and
inferiority along lines of class, wealth and power. It celebrates
fashion's formal inventiveness, but also sees it as a language of
ideas and ideals, in which attitudes _ toward life, sex, age, death
_ as well as cosmological speculations are expressed. Fortunately,
the exhibition approaches such abstract concepts entirely through
concrete things.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And specific techniques for bodily alteration are the subject of
its opening section.
</P>
<P>
   Certain methods, like the use of makeup or shaping through
pressure, are more or less superficial. Effects of the latter are
documented in a 19th-century painting of a Northwest Indian woman
with a flattened forehead, and again, further on, in an early
20th-century field photograph of an African chief with a bound and
dramatically elongated skull topped by a stylish woven hat.
</P>
<P>
   Tattooing introduces invasive procedures and pain, though a 1913
painting by the British artist George Burchett of his flamboyantly
ornamented wife, Edith, could hardly be cheerier. Burchett was
known in his day as the ``King of Tattooists.'' (He was also
tattooist to kings: George V of England was a client). He made his
wife his masterpiece, and she appears here, all smiles, and
covered, indelibly, with butterflies, Crucifixion scenes and
patriotic flags.
</P>
<P>
   Piercing comes next, seen in the figure of a ceramic warrior
from ancient Ecuador who wears spool earrings and a big nose ring.
The ensemble looks impressive, but it's actually fairly
conservative. Other elite males in his culture routinely pierced
their lips, chests, foreheads and chins, and embedded gemstones in
their cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's scarification, produced by cutting into the
skin and applying or inserting substances that raised permanent
welts. A male figure on a ceremonial stool from Papua, New Guinea
offers the first illustration of the technique in the show, but
there are many others, including an exquisite African Luba
sculpture of a seated woman holding a divination bowl, her arms
delicately incised.
</P>
<P>
   After this introductory material comes an overview of body art's
ancient history, sketched out in cosmetic pots from Dynastic Egypt,
dainty gold tweezers from Peru and a pair of clay female figurines
from Costa Rica marked with tattoo-like patterns. With their
kewpie-doll faces, they might be taken for toys. In fact, they are
thought to represent shamans of immense power.
</P>
<P>
   The whole question of the perception and misperception of
cultural values, beauty among them, is, naturally, at the center of
this globe-spanning exhibition. And it is tackled head-on in the
jumble of prints, paintings and postcards that make up the thematic
section called ``Representation.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The earliest book in English on body art, ``Man Transformed or,
the Artificial Changeling'' (1650), by the London doctor John
Bulwer, is here; it treats the phenomenon as morally repugnant.
Later accounts of European voyages to Africa and the Americas are
often less censorious; they tend to see their ornamented subjects
as both freakish and fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   And there are stories of travelers who were body art devotees. A
19th-century Englishman, John Rutherford, apparently became a kind
of Charles Saatchi of the South Pacific. He avidly collected Maori
and Polynesian tattoos and displayed his acquisitions on his
person.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The marked, pierced or otherwise self-altered human form has
always evoked an attraction-repulsion response in the
body-conflicted West. It has often been cited as scientific
``proof'' of racial inferiority and used as an ingredient in ethnic
stereotypes. But body art has also been viewed as exotically
amusing, alluring, even sexy, and has been responsible for some
lucrative, if marginal, show business careers, as this exhibition
points out.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for example, Major Horace Ridler, a circus performer
known to his fans in the 1930s as ``The Great Omi.'' He had
zebra-stripe tattoos, could lift anvils by his nose-ring and, when
not on the road, took up residence at Ripley's ``Believe it or
Not'' Odditorium in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Broadbent, according to an exhibition label, was the most
photographed ``tattooed lady'' of the 20th century. A Ringling
Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey trooper, she provided wholesome
entertainment. (She had a Madonna and Child emblazoned on her
back.) And her political tastes were ecumenical; she wore a tattoo
of Charles Lindbergh astutely placed on her right leg, and one of
Pancho Villa on her left.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition branches off in several directions after this
point, each exploring and elaborating various themes. The notion of
body art as a socio-economic indicator comes across in contemporary
photographs by Sandi Fellman of body-suit-style Japanese tattoos.
The gorgeous floral and figurative designs look sumptuously regal,
but were once worn only by lower class men, who were forbidden by
law to own decorative clothing.
</P>
<P>
   In many cultures, transitional stages of life are visually
advertised; scars made during initiations in Africa and auspicious
patterns painted in henna on the hands of an Indian bride are
examples included here. And occasionally the body is given a new,
different, transcendant identity through art, as in the case of men
in Tierra del Fuego, seen in haunting turn-of-the-century
photographs, who transformed themselves into spirits with all-over
body paint.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, while body art has died out under Western
influence in many non-Western cultures, it has recently taken on
highly inventive forms in the West itself, as one sees in a series
of recent studio photographs by Bettina Witteveen. One of Ms.
Witteveen's sitters, identified as Jon of Manhattan, displays
pierced and elongated earlobes, eyebrow rings, extensive tattoos
and a cylinder passed through the nose, in a super-eclectic,
postmodern style known as ``neo-tribal.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The results certainly look avant garde. But such things change
fast. Two decades ago, if a man wore an earring, no matter how
inconspicuous, he had to watch where he walked. Now piercings of
every description can be spotted in any suburban high school. Could
ornamental scarification be the next Western frontier, cosmetically
speaking? Maybe, but it could also be yesterday's news five years
from now.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever form it takes, body art is here to stay, so the
American Museum of Natural History is on to something. And although
there are dozens of other exhibitions inside this one screaming to
get out _ one for each of the cultures represented, in fact _ the
museum has broken important ground, done so with aplomb, and made
itself look sexy in the process. And that's pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Body Art: Marks of Identity'' opens Saturday at the American
Museum of Natural History, Central Park West at 79th Street, and
remains on view through May 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
