<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTON-MARTIN-LEGACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEGACY OF PRIDE MORE THAN PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with ASTON-MARTIN)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD FEAST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aston Martin's origins date to 1913, when Lionel Martin began
racing souped-up Singer sports cars in amateur competitions.
Success in events at Aston Hill, Hertfordshire, led to the
selection of the company name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lagonda side is even older. Its founder, Thomas Gunn,
produced a power bicycle in 1898 before moving on to motorcycles
and grand touring cars. The name is derived from a stream in
Springfield, Ohio, that Gunn recalled from time he spent in Ohio in
his childhood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aston Martin and Lagonda enjoyed enviable reputations among
Britain's fast set between the wars, but neither was a commercial
success. Both had fallen on hard times by 1947, when they were
snapped up by David Brown, an industrialist who had made enough
money out of tractors to indulge his passion for fast cars and auto
racing. (Brown's initials are the ``DB'' in the model names of many
Aston Martin cars.) Brown's investment paid off in 1959 when Aston
Martin's DBR1/300 won the World Sports Car Championship.
</P>
<P>
   But racing success did not put Aston Martin on a sound financial
footing. After years of selling cars below what they cost to make,
Brown gave up and sold the company in 1971. A series of hopeful or
hopeless owners passed through before Ford took its initial 75
percent share in 1987. That was increased to 100 percent seven
years later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lagonda brand is dormant, and is likely to remain so. It
will be enough of a challenge to sell Aston Martin as a credible
alternative to Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
