</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-BISHOPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC BISHOPS URGE MEMBERS TO CHERISH ELDERLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's Roman Catholic bishops urged their 61
million members Thursday to see the nation's growing elderly
population as valuable and active participants in church life.
</P>
<P>
   Closing their four-day national session at the Capitol Hill
Hyatt Regency Hotel, the bishops said the United States is a
graying nation. It must revere its elders and ``grapple with the
social, economic and spiritual implications'' of an aging populace,
the bishops said in the pastoral letter ``Blessings of Age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the 20th century, one in every 25 people
in the United States was 65 or older,'' the bishops said. ``Today
one in eight _ a total of 33.2 million Americans _ is at least 65.
A person who reaches 65 can expect to live for 17 more years; many
live well beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2030, 20 percent of Americans will be over 65, according to
the letter. ``Society still values youth over age, doing over
being, individualism over the common good, and independence over
interdependence,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   Because stereotypes about aging persist, new responses are
needed, the letter adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope through this pastoral message that we will be able to
energize the people in our own parishes throughout the country to
become very much interested in the plight of old people and the
great resource that they are to us today,'' said Bishop Joseph A.
Fiorenza, head of the Diocese of Galveston-Houston and president of
the bishops' conference.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by a bishops' committee on laity in collaboration with
the conference's Committee on Women in the Church and Society, the
letter speaks to older persons, to their offspring and to their
caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   It urges younger people and caregivers to the elderly to provide
repsectful care, but seek assistance and not bear that burden
alone. It suggests the elderly accept that aging may mean being
more dependent. It notes that many older people to turn to faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of you now have the time and the space to reflect more
deeply and to act with greater moral grounding and vision,'' the
letter states, adding that ``facing one's own mortality means
recognizing that death is part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishops function as top policy-makers for the American
church. The bishops issued the letter at this session because the
United Nations has designated 1999 as ``The International Year of
Older Persons.'' Pope John Paul II, 79, recently issued a letter
directed to the elderly. And the Vatican has urged Catholics to
``make a new commitment not only to care for older persons but to
learn from them,'' the bishops said.
</P>
<P>
   Closing the national session, the bishops also adopted a
pastoral message on charity, calling for a partnership between
government and private sectors to meet human need. That letter
notes that 13.3 percent of Americans live below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
