<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ASTON-MARTIN-ART-NYT &LR;      11-18 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTON-MARTIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTON MARTIN'S MISSION: TO BE FORD'S FERRARI 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(also see sidebar, ASTON-MARTIN-LEGACY) 
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD FEAST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOXHAM, England _ What speck in Ferrari's rear-view mirror _
could it be a fancy Ford?
</P>
<P>
   After decades on the side roads, Aston Martin Lagonda, the
high-performance automaker owned by Ford, is back on track and
bearing down fast. Over four years, it plans to bring out two new
models, build them with advanced materials and new techniques, open
another factory, recruit a lot more dealers and quadruple in size.
</P>
<P>
   The dowdy company will surely be gasping for breath; it has
experienced no changes so sweeping in its 86-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the mindset of Aston Martin was, until recently, firmly
stuck in 1959 _ the one year it beat Ferrari to win the World
Sports Car Championship. Then, like many an English aristocrat, it
settled into an existence of genteel poverty and happy memories. It
had class, but no cash.
</P>
<P>
   That is changing. Ford's strategy is to turn Aston Martin into a
globally recognized British alternative to Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking is this: As an automotive benchmark for technology,
performance, prestige and exclusivity, Ferrari has had a halo
effect on Fiat, its parent, and on Italy as a whole. In theory,
Aston Martin could likewise buff the image of both Ford and the
faded British auto industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari has had few serious rivals for most of its existence,
and Ford executives say it is time to change that. So do
Volkswagen, which has acquired Bugatti, another high-end name built
on earlier triumphs; Audi, with its new Lamborghini subsidiary, and
Mercedes-Benz, which is bringing out a very sophisticated roadster,
the SLR, that is likely to be priced around $275,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy automobile aficionados will have a lot of places to put
their money in the next few years. ``All this is brilliant news for
the customer,'' said Aston Martin chairman Bob Dover in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Aston Martin was slow to pick up the pace after Ford bought
control in 1987. Within two years, Ford also acquired Jaguar, which
was soon losing $1.5 million a day. Overnight, the needs of little
Aston Martin were insignificant in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, five years after Ford took charge, Aston Martin made
only 42 cars. Two years later, it introduced its first all-new
model in 27 years, the supercharged six-cylinder DB7. Since 1995,
it has regularly made about 700 cars a year _ a lot by its own
standards, but only a fifth of Ferrari's output.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Reitzle, group vice president of Ford's Premier
Automotive Group and the man who is now ultimately responsible for
Aston Martin, said the brand is ``a little too exclusive.'' He sees
Aston Martin as a laboratory on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look for high-tech solutions, but will always combine
that with understatement, style and bespoke individual
craftsmanship,'' he said. The latest DB7 Vantage is an indication
of what Reitzle has in mind. It is a svelte coupe ($140,000) or
convertible ($150,000) with undeniably firm muscle tone, thanks to
a mighty 6-liter V12 engine that pumps out 420 horsepower. The
DB7's six-cylinder engine _ adapted from a Jaguar design _ is still
available, but Aston Martin's future revolves around the new V12
and its future derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   The DB7 is just the beginning. In a year, the company will
introduce a production version of a show car, the Project Vantage,
which will replace the V-cars _ large, dated, V8-powered
gas-guzzlers that are no longer sold in North America, though their
replacements will be. While Project Vantage looks like a DB7 after
a steroid overdose, the real difference is its construction, a
combination of carbon fiber, other composite materials and aluminum
in sheet and honeycomb form. It will weigh 2,200 pounds less than
the V-cars, a hefty 40 percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a third model, probably ready for introduction in
2002. Right now, its looks, layout and performance are being
defined, but it is likely to be the model that brings the big
increase in sales volume that Ford expects, thanks to a
comparatively low sticker price. Limited production capacity at
Aston Martin's twin factories northwest of London, near its
headquarters at Newport Pagnell and here in Oxfordshire make a
third plant almost inevitable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dover's strategy calls for 3,000 annual sales, a level at which
he says Aston Martin can be financially self-sufficient, and it
will need to be after Ford has underwritten its ambitious expansion
plan. Ford paid a pittance for Aston Martin _ believed to be about
$30 million _ but it has invested an estimated $800 million in the
company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aston Martin is being given the sort of top-to-toe makeover that
revived Jaguar. Money went into the acquisition of the factory
here, where DB7s are made, and into the modernization of Newport
Pagnell, where the next new model will be built.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul goes deeper than cars and plants. Aston Martin is
introducing Japanese methods of continuous improvement, called
kaizen, throughout the company. Teams of employees videotape and
time production tasks and later discuss ways to improve them _ a
process that would have been unimaginable a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, though, Aston Martin has to find a lot
more customers. Ford reckons there are enough wealthy buffs who
recall Aston Martin's heritage _ and its starring role in early
James Bond movies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While an Aston Martin is still an obscure and expensive object
of desire, Jaguar's turnaround shows what Ford can achieve. And
Aston Martin's supporters have no doubt that the marque has strong
appeal. Alan Baker, manager of an Aston Martin dealership in the
Mayfair district of London, says his customers buy DB7s because of
the way they perform and the way they look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there's the image,'' he said. ``You're immediately
considered to be a gentleman if you drive an Aston Martin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1752EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
