<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COMDEX19-COX     11-18 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMDEX19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMDEX REPORT: INTERNET DOMINATES ALL, BUT SLOW LINKS PERSIST
 &HT;    Moving in (a) national and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The Comdex computer trade show offers plenty of
evidence that the industry's future depends largely on high-speed
access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But for many ordinary home users and mobile phone customers, the
wondrous services promised by these fast links to cyberspace may
prove slow in coming.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, virtually unknown a decade ago, dominated nearly
every public forum and many private talks at the Comdex show.
Visitors stood patiently in long queues to go on line for free at
hundreds of computer kiosks provided by Novell Inc., a networking
software firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every company in every industry is in a state of transition,''
Cisco Systems president John Chambers told a packed house. ``In the
past 24 months, people have really gotten into it, and during the
past 12 months, it's been like somebody switched on a light,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Internet evangelists, including Scott McNealy,
chairman of Sun Microsystems, forecast that simple devices will
replace personal computers in performing a host of online
activities. McNealy has long been fiercely opposed to Microsoft,
the industry revenue leader, and its dominant Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``My one-and-a-half-year-old can operate a set-top box,''
McNealy said in a convention keynote speech. ``He still hasn't
mastered Windows NT.''
</P>
<P>
   After the laughter and applause died down, McNealy added:
``These new devices are so easy that you won't have to worry
whether your kid is computer literate, unless he's sitting in front
of a PC. There will be sensors on everything. And cameras
everywhere. And that's a good thing, unless you're doing something
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ZuluTV, a small company based in Portsmouth, N.H., that made its
first appearance at Comdex this year, reflects the trends that
Chambers and McNealy cited. Beginning early next year, the firm
plans to market a simple device linked to its Internet service
portal that allows anyone to become an instant daily TV
broadcaster. For example, a ``videographer'' could film a wedding
ceremony that could be watched on the Internet in real time by
distant relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The book-sized $2,500 ZuluTV device attaches to any camcorder. A
computer isn't required. Batteries and a fast wireless link to the
Internet make the system fully portable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not about technology,'' said Joseph Smith, the
company's president and founder. ``It's all about content. People
with fast Internet links will be able to watch videos of the same
quality now offered by cable outlets and the networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ZuluTV, other Internet devices shown at Comdex need a
high-speed connection, known as ``broadband,'' to perform
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadband is the hottest topic by far at Comdex,'' Smith said.
But, he warned, it's ``going to be a lot slower in its rollout to
mass users than a lot of people here are hoping or.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is not alone in sensing a ``digital divide,'' as he put
it, that still makes it uneconomical for Internet service providers
to roll out broadband to the home. ``It's also too complex for some
users to install and too expensive for others,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take a look at where we'll be in three or four years,
perhaps a billion people will be connected to the Internet
globally. But perhaps 900 million of them still will be dialing up.
The penetration is just not going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   While such key industry figures as Eric Benhamou, chairman of
3Com Corp., the world's leading modem maker, tout the potential
benefits of high bandwidths that offer rich video services, the
company's Comdex flier takes a more sober approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of computer users in home and home offices rely on
56K analog modems as their primary connection to the Internet _ 96
percent more than any other other Internet access technology,''
3Com reports.
</P>
<P>
   It was to address the slow emergence of broadband that the
Federal Communications Commission on Thursday required local
telephone companies to share their lines with businesses that want
to offer high-speed Internet connections to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
