<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4158 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-RABBI-CHANUKAH-NYTSF &LR;      11-18 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-CHANUKAH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A VIOLENT TIME, A LITTLE LIGHT DISPELS MUCH DARKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By RABBI ELI HECHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A friend commented on some of the recent highly publicized
shootings: ``There is really nothing we can do. My kids go to
school and are exposed to random searches for weapons. The Post
Office is not a safe place. Shootings occur in the work areas. Even
the churches, synagogues and day care centers are subject to
shootings.''
 &HT;    His remarks made me wonder. What is happening to our great
country? What can I do about the situation? How depressing this is.
 &HT;    Then I thought of the good things that may take place because of
the bad things. Let me quote the famous psychiatrist, Viktor
Frankl:
 &HT;    ``I can see beyond the misery of the situation to the potential
for discovering a meaning behind it, and thus to turn an apparently
meaningless suffering into a genuine human achievement.
 &HT;    ``I am convinced that, in the final analysis, there is no
situation that does not contain within it the seed of a meaning.''
 &HT;    My family is no stranger to acts of senseless violence. When my
cousin's son was shot dead in a drugstore some years ago I was
devastated.
 &HT;    Soon after, in 1994, another relative, 16-year-old Ari
Halberstam, was shot dead as he traveled in a van with other young
divinity students.
 &HT;    His assailant, a Lebanese immigrant, claimed to have suffered
war trauma while being attacked in a Lebanese refugee camp. He had
purchased a gun through the mail. His act of savage violence and
mayhem on the Jewish students earned him a sentence of 141 years in
prison.
 &HT;    Recently, Mrs. Devorah Halberstam introduced a bill, nicknamed
``Ari's Bill,'' into the Assembly of the State of New York. The
bill states that no gun kit can be sold through the mail and it
would put teeth into gun-trafficking laws between states.
 &HT;    Devorah is my first cousin and the mother of Ari, who was killed
in that senseless attack.
 &HT;    She took her tragedy, a real meaningless suffering, to try to
accomplish something for the rest of our citizens. How much misery
could be averted if guns were not so readily available?
 &HT;    Devorah has now embarked on a second venture, a new museum for
Jewish children. It will promote harmony, cultural awareness and
tolerance. Ari's life will continue through the children visiting
the museum. His memory will be celebrated through other living
children.
 &HT;    There are others who have risen above misery to find ways to
celebrate the good. For example, take my take good friend Yaakov, a
veteran of wars between the Israelis and Arabs.
 &HT;    He is proud that all through his military duty he was always
able to find the bright side of things. Once, he and his company
were grounded for a long period at the Suez Canal. Almost every day
the Egyptians launched howitzer attacks. The Israeli soldiers,
situated on the Israeli side, either fired back or retreated into
their bunkers for safety.
 &HT;    After a few months of this give and take, the soldiers were at
their wits' end. The holiday of Chanukah was approaching and the
men missed their families.
 &HT;    At Chanukah a candelabra -- menorah -- was needed but none of
the men had one. Not one menorah could be found. It was a very
depressing evening. Suddenly Yaakov came up with a brilliant idea.
Why not take the spent shells and set them up as menorahs for the
holiday. The men passed their novel ideal around.
 &HT;    Menorahs of shell casings were filled with gasoline and rag
wicks were soon burning brightly throughout the military area.
Menorahs everywhere! Imagine turning objects of destruction into
symbols of peace.
 &HT;    None of us look for suffering. However, if we are exposed to it,
then, we need to turn suffering into human achievement.
 &HT;    Our response to the shootings should be to make this world a
safer and better place.
 &HT;    Chanukah celebrates the miracle of the Jewish revolution against
the Greek occupation and religious persecution. This took place in
Israel 165 B.C.E.
 &HT;    A handful of Jewish freedom fighters, called Maccabees, waged a
successful war for religious freedom. When the temple was
reclaimed, services were reinstituted. The main menorah, a seven
stick candelabra, was kindled. Miraculously, the flames burned for
eight days without being replenished with oil, hence the festival
became known as the Festival of Lights.
 &HT;    During Chanukah we give thanks to God for the miraculous time.
This year the first night of Chanukah will be Friday, December 3.
 &HT;    Remember the message of Chanukah and the Chanukah lights turning
misery into miraculous times. A little light dispels much darkness.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.1999 Rabbi Eli Hecht
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif. and
writes a monthly Op-Ed column for the Long Beach Press-Telegeam.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
