<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OSCE-1119-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, YELTSIN CLASH AT EUROPEAN SECURITY SUMMIT OVER CHECHNYA
 &HT;    With CLINTON-YELTSIN-1119.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ President Clinton and Russian leader Boris
Yeltsin clashed Thursday over Moscow's bloody military campaign in
Chechnya, where two months of air strikes have left thousands dead.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by Clinton to allow Western mediators to try to broker
peace in Chechnya, Yeltsin resisted, agreeing only to permit a
fact-finding mission into the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin warned, though, that he would not negotiate with
separatist rebels he regards as terrorists. He challenged his
critics to identify negotiating parties he considers legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Yeltsin vowed, he would press forward with air
strikes that have killed an estimated 4,000 Chechen civilians and
driven 200,000 more from their homes since August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should be under any illusions on this score. There will
be no negotiations with bandits and murderers,'' Yeltsin said. ``We
need to eliminate the bandit formations and to eliminate the
terrorists, or bring them to court.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin addressed his remarks to Clinton and four dozen other
heads of state attending a meeting of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe. The OSCE summit was dominated by
discussion of how the group might help to end the conflict in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels there are fighting for independence from the Russian
Federation that Yeltsin governs. He regards them as a terrorist
organization that has exploded bombs in Russian cities _ killing
hundreds _ and kidnapped Russian civilians and visiting executives
to bring pressure on Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a wave of criticism from OSCE members, Yeltsin lashed
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no right to criticize Russia for Chechnya,'' Yeltsin
fumed. ``Russia, as well as the other members of the OSCE, today
particularly needs a respectful dialogue, not mutual reproaches or
sermonizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sharp rhetoric, Yeltsin agreed to a minimalist
measure, saying he would invite the current OSCE chairman, Knut
Vollebaek, to visit Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Vollebaek's
visit, as yet unscheduled, would give the United States and its
allies ``a foot in the door'' toward peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   There was no disguising U.S. frustration, though, over the
OSCE's inability to halt, or even to slow, the onslaught Moscow has
unleashed on the people of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to oversell this,'' Albright told reporters
Thursday. ``I think that we accomplished a lot. But this is a
longer-term problem, and I think that we need to keep pushing it
along.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step, she said, is for the OSCE to try to put together
a credible group of Chechens who have influence among rebel groups
yet can been regarded as legitimate negotiating partners for
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not easy to identify them,'' Albright conceded. ``But I
think there has to be an effort made to do so. And that, I think,
is what has been missing, is really looking for people that can
legitimately negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   The 54-member OSCE groups the United States and its Western
allies with former Soviet republics and satellite states.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the speeches, Clinton and Yeltsin held a
private 45-minute meeting, much of which centered on Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very vigorous and so was I,'' Clinton told reporters
after the meeting. ``We have a very good personal chemistry, but it
didn't stop us from our clear disagreement here.''
</P>
<P>
   Chechen officials claim that several thousand civilians have
been either killed or wounded in bombing Clinton has assailed as
``indiscriminate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours after Clinton and Yeltsin met, the Russian flew back to
Moscow, leaving behind his Foreign Minister Igor Ivanoff to
represent Russia at the summit. It concludes here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, though, signed as a witness to a pair of agreements in
support of two pipelines that, if built, will be able to carry huge
volumes of crude oil and natural gas from the Caspian Sea to the
Mediterranean via Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The pipelines would strip Russia of its monopoly control over
transporting Caspian oil to U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This enhances our energy security,'' said U.S. Secretary of
Energy Bill Richardson. ``It ensures that the West has secure and
stable pipelines.''
</P>
<P>
   All existing pipelines leading from the Caspian flow either
through Russia or to Iran, which is forbidden from selling oil to
the United States under sanctions stretching back 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton leaves Istanbul Friday afternoon for a one-day visit to
Greece, where he hopes to advance planning for peace talks in New
York next month between ethnic Greek and Turkish leaders on the
divided island republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton goes to Florence, Italy, on Saturday on the next leg of
a swing through southeast Europe that will take him to Bulgaria and
then Kosovo before he returns to Washington next Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
