<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WINTER-$ADV20 _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The international
relief community is significantly behind schedule in preparing for
the Balkan winter. With frost covering the hills, nearly 20,000
families still haven't received basic materials they need to secure
their burned-out houses from the bitter cold. Food supplies also
are problematic as the narrow transportation corridor _ a two-lane
bridge between Macedonia and Kosovo _ into the battered province
has become hopelessly gridlocked. Additionally, aid organizations
are running far behind schedule in getting their own structures for
providing relief in place. (Roughton, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Thurs., Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MUSLIMS-$ADV20 _KASHGAR, China _ A look at the smoldering
resentment among China's Muslims in the country's far western
frontier, a third-world backwater culturally and physically remote
from China's political center. Mostly members of a Turkic minority
called Uighers, they protest Beijing's grasp on their resources and
autocratic rule in mostly quiet ways _ setting their clocks back
two hours to ``real'' time instead of Beijing time, as the Chinese
nearly 2,000 miles away have dictated, or by boycotting Chinese
restaurants. The radical fringes of the 8 million Uighurs continue
waging a hit-and-run campaign of violence from the base of an
underground Islamic party, which is Beijing's number one priority
to destroy. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS and
LOCATOR MAP
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Wed., Nov. 17.
</P>
<P>
   BARAK _ ATLANTA _ Ehud Barak, prime minister of Israel, speaks
Friday to delegates attending the 68th General Assembly. (Graham,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: The following package accompanies the fourth and final
installment, scheduled for Christmas publication, of Christianity
at 2000, an Atlanta Journal-Constitution series that's been running
this year. This is the Washington Bureau contribution if someone
wants them early; the AJC stories will be available in December;
these stories will move again with the AJC package.)
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANITY-ASIA _ SEOUL, South Korea _ This region of the
world has been one of the more painful ones for Christians and
their beliefs. They face persecution everywhere. Vietnamese police
have raided a number of Christian gatherings across the country in
recent months, detaining and harassing scores of worshippers.
Vietnam's Christian population is unclear, although the country of
79 million people has 8 million Catholics, the largest community in
Southeast Asia outside the Philippines. But in secular South Korea,
the number is growing and becoming one of the most active churches
in East Asia. Developing. (Kirk, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANITY-LATAM _ MEXICO CITY _ In this fervently Catholic
country, they build shrines by the thousands and crawl on their
knees to honor the Virgin Mary at her own special basilica. The
main purpose of the pope's trip to Mexico earlier this year _ his
fourth trip to this country _ was to address challenges to the
Catholic Church in the Americas, the most Catholic region in the
world. Mexico is considered a geographic powerhouse for the Vatican
because it is a bridge between South America and North America,
where the church is concerned about the spread of materialism and
secularism. And Mexico, whose Catholic population is second only to
Brazil in number, is home to the Basilica of the Virgin of
Guadalupe, the second-most visited Catholic sanctuary in the world
after St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANITY-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ Across Moscow and the rest of
Russia, sparkling new onion-domed churches are rising from the
rubble of Communism. The Russian Orthodox Church is back, though in
Soviet times it never really went away. The church was a survivor,
and some say collaborator, that has now emerged as a powerful
political and economic force in the new Russia. (Holmes, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Fri., Nov. 19, in both International/Lifestyle
categories for COX PAPERS ONLY.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ ATLANTA _ John McCain comes to Atlanta Nov. 19 to hawk
his book, raise money for his campaign and appear on as many TV and
radio programs as he can. First visit since the spring for a
campaign that is banking heavily on winning neighboring South
Carolina, but has spent little time or money in Georgia. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   MARS _ NASA has Mars in its sights again, and officials are
hoping next week's long-awaited arrival of the Mars Polar Lander
will not be a replay of the embarrassing glitches that turned the
space agency's last mission to the Red Planet a total loss. If all
goes as planned, the NASA's robot lander will touch down shortly
after 3 p.m. Dec. 3, setting the stage for a week of sights _ and
sounds _ unlike anything since spacecraft began visiting the fourth
rock from the sun 39 years ago. Anticipation is already building.
Visitors to the main web site for the mission have been growing
since mid-year, with more than 8 million hits recorded last month.
(Toner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   PANDAS _ ATLANTA _ The two new pandas that Zoo Atlanta landed
from China a couple weeks ago go on display for the first time to
the public. We'll tell how to get tickets, where to see them on the
web, etc. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
