<HEADER>
A4166 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-18 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSE JACKSON IS WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson is having trouble drumming
up support for his crusade to make martyrs out of six black
students expelled from a Decatur, Ill., high school for leading a
violent brawl at a football game that terrified hundreds of others
in the stands. Good.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has a long history of leading noble causes and breaking
down racial barriers. It is painful to criticize him. But this time
he's got it all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He is leading demonstrations in defense of the six teenagers
with the argument that their punishment was excessive. He insists
he does not see this as a racial issue, but of course he does.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is that the facts do not fit his rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of the fight has been shown repeatedly on
television. It is clear that this was not an ordinary fist fight,
as Jackson claims, but, as the school board insists, an action in
which several teen-agers pursued others, beating up on fleeing and
cringing figures until police moved in. The fury of the scene was
horrifying, even from the comfort of my living room.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also claims that the brutal six are victims of a general
``national intolerance of our kids'' born of the Columbine High
School killings and other recent episodes of school violence. He
constantly falls back on racial inferences, although of 1,700
students disciplined in the past two years by the Decatur school,
Eisenhower High, 700 were white.
</P>
<P>
   The school had recently instituted a zero-tolerance policy
similar to those now found in four out of five high schools across
the country. It imposes penalties on students who fight or
intimidate teachers and other students. It may be tough, but it
also seems to be generally working to restore order to the chaos of
undisciplined schools.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Jackson demonstrates no similar concern for the
safety and security of the peaceful majority of students who
deserve a right to attend school events without fear. Or that he
has shown no concern for the fact that his demonstrations forced
the school to close, disrupting the education of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   He really lost it, however, when he compared Eisenhower's
strict-discipline policy to the official racial segregation that
spawned the civil rights movement. ``Decatur is not so far from
Selma (Ala.)'' Jackson thundered. ``The schools are 48 percent
black and brown. The teachers and the school board are 90 percent
white.''
</P>
<P>
   This is pure demagoguery, unworthy of Jackson's stature as a
genuine civil rights leader. The Selma march was in a noble cause.
Going easy on six teenage thugs who beat up on defenseless
acquaintances is not a noble cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. led the march in Selma to bring
down the legal state barriers that kept blacks from voting and
gaining equal access to jobs, education, public places and economic
opportunities. He transformed American society and saved its soul.
</P>
<P>
   Niger Innis, a spokesman for the Congress of Racial Equality,
was right when he protested Jackson's ``drawing racial lines in the
sand ... There are two winners here: Jesse Jackson for the media
coverage and attention he gets, and the local KKK. Everybody else
loses, including those kids.''
</P>
<P>
   By demanding a slap on the wrist instead of serious penalties
for the brawlers, Jackson is giving their fate more importance than
he gives school discipline and the rights of the other students.
``Work with them, not just eliminate them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Troubled kids deserve our help, but not if it endangers
untroubled kids.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson refused to let up after the school board reduced the six
students' punishment from a two-year expulsion, which did seem
usually harsh, to one year with permission to attend an alternative
school. He escalated his demands, insisting the students be
promptly returned to Eisenhower High.
</P>
<P>
   And he filed a lawsuit seeking $5 million for each student,
alleging that their privacy was violated because officials revealed
that the group had collectively missed 350 days of school in recent
years and that some had repeated grades.
</P>
<P>
   They were, in fact, chronic truants whose sudden desire for a
serious, uninterrupted education represents a jarring personality
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is ridiculous, but it will be costly to the
taxpayers and the school system, which will have to hire lawyers to
defend its decisions. Officials retaliated by filing their own
lawsuit seeking an injunction barring Jackson and his supporters
from protesting near the school. The suit claims that he was
causing an unreasonable disruption of school functions.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has vowed to return to the schoolyard this weekend with
another demonstration. He was hauled off to jail earlier this week,
as he had planned, after a prior demonstration for which his
Rainbow Coalition and Operation Push bused in out-of-town
sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   He has inevitably raised racial tensions in Decatur and stirred
up local resentment against non-residents by trying to tell the
schools how to operate. If he is out to discredit the popular
zero-tolerance policy, he is going about it the wrong way with the
wrong so-called victims. If he is merely out to help six students
in trouble, he is overdoing it. Enough already.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
