<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4167 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-SCENE     11-18 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-SCENE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(EDS: WRITETHRU TO CLARIFY THAT GAME IS NOT ALWAYS ON
THANKSGIVING) 
SHOCK AND HORROR PERMEATE A&AMP;M CAMPUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M University students and
faculty watched in horror all day Thursday as one of their proudest
traditions descended into tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is just walking around with their heads hanging
down,'' said freshman Michelle Evans of Corpus Christi. ``It's real
somber. It's completely different from what it is supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans and her boyfriend, sophomore Randy Sullivan, watched as
rescue crews meticulously unstaked a 35-foot edifice of logs
erected for the bonfire before the annual Thanksgiving week
football game against the University of Texas-Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 3 a.m. Thursday, the log pile shifted as dozens
of students worked all-night shifts atop stacks of wood on the A&AMP;M
polo fields. The top logs crashed to the ground, killing at least
nine students and injuring 28 others.
</P>
<P>
   Although classes were not officially canceled, the tragedy
gripped the 43,000-student campus and dominated an otherwise
pleasant Thursday morning. The sprawling polo fields, a giant
meadow normally used for pickup ball games and other gatherings,
was filled with clusters of onlookers, media trucks, emergency
vehicles and construction cranes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to both of my classes, but we didn't do anything but _
well, we started with a prayer,'' said Sullivan, who pinned a white
ribbon on his shirt in honor of the victims. ``Then the profs just
told us to go home and try to deal with it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Students Tommy Balez of San Antonio and David Conner of Houston
dealt with it by continuing to man a shack where bonfire-building
volunteers take charge of the chain saws and axes used to cut the
thousands of logs that the bonfire requires. Balez and Conner were
at the station early Thuursday morning when the pile collapsed
about 100 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear people yelling for help, and we all started
running out there, trying to do anything we could,'' said Balez, an
electrical engineering major.
</P>
<P>
   Balez and Conner said the bonfire, a tradition started to
demonstrate the Aggies' ``burning desire'' to beat Texas, has long
been a unifying activity for Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the things that makes A&AMP;M what it is,'' Conner
said. ``We honor our traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   On the polo fields and throughout the university that dominates
the Brazos Valley region, students huddled in small groups,
exchanging hugs and using cell phones to contact their folks at
home.
</P>
<P>
   At a campus snack bar called Pie Are Squared, students huddled
around a TV set to catch around-the-clock coverage by local
stations. Although notebooks and textbooks were open on many
tables, few students were paying them much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother called me up at 5 o'clock this morning, asking
me if I was all right,'' said Shawn Sams, a freshman biology major.
``I didn't know what she was talking about. When she told me, it
blew me away.''
</P>
<P>
   University switchboards were flooded with such calls, prompting
officials to establish a toll-free hot line for parents and other
family members to check on students.
</P>
<P>
   University President Ray Bowen called the accident ``probably
the single worst thing that has ever happened on our campus.''
</P>
<P>
   He said scores of counselors, both from the university and from
as far away as the Metroplex, were on hand to help students deal
with events.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on the grounds by 4:30 this morning, helping however
they could,'' Bowen said. ``I'm no psychologist, but I think the
kids now don't recognize that they need counseling. But when you
see kids just sitting staring at the wall or doing nothing, they'll
(counselors) move in. Right now, I think they are out there
trolling for students who need help.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
