<HEADLINE>
BUSH WOULD CONTINUE ECONOMIC EMBARGO AGAINST CUBA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush
said Thursday that he would continue economic pressure on Cuba to
end its totalitarian regime. But he suggested that he would not
make human rights a priority in most foreign trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, in a national television interview on CNN,
said he would avidly pursue ``free trade'' around the world, except
for Cuba, if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of his first major foreign policy address, Bush drew
a distinction between trade with Cuba and with China, which he has
endorsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade with China will be trade between companies and
businesses, both large and small, on both sides,'' he said. ``I
know it's in our best interest to trade with the entrepreneurial
class in China. It will help spread freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade with Cuba is different, he added, because capital sent to
that island nation ``must go through the hands of the Fidel Castro
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to support the totalitarian regime of Fidel
Castro,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message to Mr. Castro is: `Sure, we'll end the embargo, but
you must end political repression, you must have free elections,
you must free the prisoners and you must give democracy a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of human rights was broached by the CNN interviewer,
who asked the governor if special provisions should be included in
trade agreements to hold offending countries ``accountable'' for
employing ``slave labor'' or allowing poor environmental practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what the working people (in the United States) ought
to understand is that free trade will yield higher paying, higher
quality jobs in America,'' Bush responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the important lesson of free trade. In terms of whether
or not there ought to be agreements that burden the ability for our
world to trade freely, it depends on what's in them. But if these
are agreements that really try to undermine free trade, I'll resist
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush later added that the United States rejected slave labor ``a
long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it's important to distinguish between what could
be reasonable discussions and laws or amendments that would tend to
undermine trade, which I will resist.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans generally oppose raising labor and
environmental issues in trade negotiations unless those matters
have some immediate bearing on trade.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the sharpest criticism of U.S. trade policy with
China has come from religious conservatives in the GOP's right
wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the human rights situation deteriorates in China, the last
thing the United States should support is China's admittance to the
World Trade Organization,'' said Bill Saunders, a senior fellow
with the Family Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council used to be headed by Gary Bauer, one of Bush's
right-wing opponents for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer opposes trade with China, while Bush praised an agreement
signed earlier this week to help pave the way for China's entry
into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese government is increasingly guilty of religious
persecution, forced abortions and victimization of political
dissidents and ethnic minorities,'' Saunders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would we reward the government with economic security and
open trade? If we give China membership into the WTO, we lose
future leverage in fighting injustice in China, and we effectively
undermine the cause of democracy and freedom around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who plans to outline his foreign policy objectives in a
speech Friday in California, said it wasn't true that he was
``completely inexperienced'' in foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of experience with the country of Mexico,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the North American Free Trade Agreement had benefited
Mexico as well as the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helped Mexico to grow, particularly the northern part of
Mexico, a vibrant, strong economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
