<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TALKS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL ASKS DISSIDENTS NOT TO BLOCK NORTHERN IRELAND PEACE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Former Sen. George Mitchell ended
his mediation effort Thursday with a plea to dissident politicians
not to block the plan it produced to end the deadlock stalling
progress in the Northern Ireland peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither side will get all it wanted and both will endure
severe political pain,'' he said. ``But there is no other way
forward. Prolonging the stalemate will leave this society uncertain
and vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   After 11 weeks of hard bargaining, the Mitchell mission this
week has put in place a series of incremental steps that hold the
promise of ending an impasse over paramilitary disarmament and
starting up the new Northern Ireland government envisioned in the
April 1998 peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan must be endorsed by the Ulster Unionists, and their
leader, David Trimble, faces the challenge of persuading a sizable
number of disaffected members to overcome their objections to
entering government with Sinn Fein, the political representatives
of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   In the most important development of the week, the IRA issued a
statement on Wednesday saying it would be willing for the first
time to discuss dismantling the arsenal of guns and bombs assembled
during its 30-year fight against British rule, a notion it had
previously dismissed as tantamount to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   But the dramatic gesture did not satisfy many Ulster Unionists
who have been demanding the beginning of the actual turnover of
weapons before they will sit in government with Sinn Fein. They
consider Trimble's retreat from that position a betrayal of their
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble is expected to convene a meeting of the 850-strong party
council in 10 days to seek approval for proceeding with the
Mitchell plan, and the lobbying is already intense.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Reg Empey, the Ulster Unionists' chief negotiator, urged
colleagues to ponder the various conciliatory statements that
emerged this week ``so that the true significance and meaning of
them may be forthcoming.'' He said a close reading would produce
the conclusion that ``there is no other way forward.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to combat Ulster Unionist critics' suspicion that
Trimble had not been tenacious enough, Peter Mandelson, Britain's
secretary for Northern Ireland, depicted him as someone who had
fought aggressively for unionist interests.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting after a cabinet meeting at 10 Downing St. at which
the Mitchell plan came in for praise from Prime Minister Tony
Blair, Mandelson said Trimble ``has at times been frustrating,
almost painful, in what he has held out for, but I must say it has
shown a remarkable reward and dividend for unionists in Northern
Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   The peace agreement set up a new Northern Ireland Assembly and a
number of governmental bodies linking Belfast with Dublin, and with
the new legislatures in Scotland and Wales and the British
Parliament in London in an effort to balance the interests of
unionists and republicans. All these institutions could be up and
running next month if the Mitchell plan is accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists, most of whom are Protestants, favor keeping Northern
Ireland British while republicans, who tend to be Catholic, favor
eventual unity with the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   When the disarmament impasse put the agreement in danger of
unraveling, Blair and Prime Minister Bertie Ahern of Ireland held
marathon rescue talks in April and again in July. Those efforts
failed, and they sent for Mitchell, who over a 26-month period
brokered the original agreement.
</P>
<P>
   As Mitchell made his farewell remarks Thursday afternoon before
departing for the United States, political leaders who have lived
in deep distrust of one another for decades lined the walls of the
conference room and then strode one by one to the podium to pay
tribute to his achievement.
</P>
<P>
   One notable success of the Mitchell mission was to create a
spirit of cooperation among sworn enemies, and Mitchell praised
them Thursday for ``having set aside their hostility for the good
of their society.''
</P>
<P>
   Summing up his two extended stays in the province, Mitchell
said: ``I have been involved in this effort for nearly five years.
I cannot say that I have enjoyed every minute of it. But while on
occasion it has been difficult, it also has been one of the most
meaningful times of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
