<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-BOMBING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY WOULD END LIVE FIRE TO KEEP TARGET RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By STEWART M. POWELL   
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Navy would stop using high explosive bombs and
shells and shift to inert weapons at the target range on the island
of Vieques as part of a White House compromise offer aimed at
reopening the bombing range in Puerto Rico, Navy officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's willingness to use duds is part of a White House
effort to persuade Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello and protesters
encamped on the range to allow a Persian Gulf-bound battle group
led by the aircraft carrier USS Dwight D. Eisenhower to train on
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been consulting with Rossello by telephone during
the president's 10-day trip to Turkey and Europe. Alfonso Aguilar,
Rossello's spokesman in San Juan, said Puerto Rico's leaders are
expecting a new proposal from the president at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Atlantic Fleet was planning for the Eisenhower battle group to
train at Vieques without using the high explosive weapons that have
antagonized many of the 9,300 civilian residents on Vieques and
stirred concerns that toxic chemicals in the shells contribute to
the island's higher incidence of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy owns two-thirds of the 22-mile island, located east of
Puerto Rico. Sixty percent of the 396,222 munitions dropped or
fired on the island target range in the 16 years ending in 1998
were explosive; 40 percent were non-explosive. The range was used
an average of 187 days a year over the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using inert weapons is better than not training at Vieques,''
said a Navy official at the Pentagon. ``If the only way we get this
training is by using inert weapons, we're willing to do that. The
Navy is the `can-do service.'''
</P>
<P>
   A Navy official at Atlantic Fleet headquarters in Norfolk, Va.,
said Navy aircraft and warships have access to ready-made
non-explosive munitions that are routinely used in training. ``We
are working very hard to insure that inert training would qualify
our forces according to Navy guidelines,'' said the official, who
also spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's willingness to substitute inert weaponry represents a
turnabout and shows that the Navy is expecting a White House order
to shift to non-explosive weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Navy Vice Adm. William J. Fallon, commander
of the Atlantic Fleet, repeatedly insisted during testimony before
the Senate Armed Services Committee and a Pentagon review panel
that live-fire training on Vieques was essential to prepare
Atlantic-based forces for operations in the Mediterranean and the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Adm. Harold W. Gehman Jr., commander of the U.S. Atlantic
Command, told Defense Secretary William Cohen in an Aug. 27 letter
that live fire training on Vieques is ``part of a complex training
regime that allows us to send our men and women into harms way with
a clear conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vieques range, including an 899-acre live fire impact zone
and an adjacent 11,000-acre buffer and maneuver zone, has been
closed since April 19 after a Marine aviator mistakenly bombed a
hilltop observation post on the range. A Navy contract security
guard, David Sanes Rodriguez, 35, was killed in the accident and
four civilian range employees were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy prompted demands by Puerto Rico's political leaders,
backed by allies in Congress, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
Democratic presidential candidates in 2000 to urge permanent
cessation to the 58 years of live-fire training on the 33,000-acre
island.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello has already rejected Navy bombardment of Vieques with
either explosive or non-explosive weapons. The Democratic governor
has threatened to seek a federal court order to block any
resumption of bombing, by either live ordnance or inert ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar said Thursday that Rossello ``will have to see the
president's proposal and see whether it takes into consideration
Puerto Rico's proposals to end the bombing'' before deciding
whether to fulfill his threat to seek federal court action.
</P>
<P>
   The target range has been used chiefly by carrier-based aircraft
for bombing, strafing and rocket fire, and by surface warships to
practice firing the 5-inch naval guns that fire up to 20 shells a
minute up to 15 miles to support Marines staging amphibious
landings.
</P>
<P>
   Warplanes assigned to the Eisenhower battle group, scheduled to
the sail to the Persian Gulf on Feb. 18, have carried out live-fire
training at ranges in Nevada and northern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But Navy officials have warned that many of the six surface
warships scheduled to accompany the Eisenhower may not qualify for
one of their principal combat missions without first rehearsing at
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE - OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Navy Lt. Cdr. Joe Navratil, a spokesman for the Atlantic Fleet,
said that the moratorium on training on Vieques had already forced
the destroyer USS John Hancock to complete training for operations
in the Persian Gulf after leaving the United States as part of the
battle group led by the aircraft carrier USS John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The 563-foot warship and its crew of 376 left Mayport, Fla., on
Sept. 17 with what Navy officials described as a ``significant
degradation'' of combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
   The warship stopped en route to the Persian Gulf and practiced
shooting at a target range on the Italian island of Sardinia _ the
first time that a U.S. warship had relied solely on a foreign
target range to qualify for a primary combat mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy hallmark is 'ready on arrival,''' Navratil said. ``It
was disconcerting for us to sail without complete combat
readiness.''
</P>
<P>
   The USS John Hancock was on patrol Thursday in the Persian Gulf
assigned to intercept Iraqi smuggler vessels trying to get by a
weapons and oil embargo imposed on Iraq by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of interdiction is being able to fire a warning shot,''
Navratil said. ``Accuracy with naval guns is critically important
for the mission that the Hancock is doing in the Gulf.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
