<HEADLINE>
DO ANIMALS GET BORED? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Do animals get bored?
</P>
<P>
   K.M., Haydenville, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, according to Dr. Nicholas Dodman of the Tufts University
School of Veterinary Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists may not like to give it the human word ``boredom.''
But it is. The animals are finding something else to do when they
aren't stimulated or can't do what they are programmed
instinctively to do.
</P>
<P>
   Dodman cites several examples. ``Horses have what are called
`stall vices,' things they do when they're stuck in their stall for
hours with nothing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He says 25-35 percent of horses do something called cribbing,
grasping a solid surface like their hay bucket or stall door in
their teeth and pulling backwards on it. It causes air to move
around in their throats making a gulping noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some do it 600 times an hour,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Others pace circles into their stall floor. Some dig with their
hooves, sometimes holes up to their chests.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs will chase their tails, chase shadows, leap into the air at
imaginary insects, gnaw on furniture. Many dogs with nothing to do
for hours will lick their paws excessively, causing sores called
licking granuloma. Some dogs gulp at the air ``until they look
inflated, like they ate a basketball,'' Dodman says. ``The air
eventually comes out both ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Bored cats will eat, as in chew AND swallow, non-food items,
like plastic shower curtains, running shoes, woolen objects. Bored
Siamese cats are particularly known for a condition called ``wool
sucking.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodman says monkeys in research facilities sometimes
self-mutilate, picking at their own skin until it bleeds. Bored
Macaque monkeys are known to do rectal probing. A gorilla at a
local zoo was pulling out his hair and eating it, making himself
vomit, behavior Dr. Dodman attributed to boredom. Polar bears in
zoos pace. One at the Bronx Zoo did the backstroke excessively in
its pool. A Russian bear at the San Diego zoo started drinking
water out of its paw, something those animals don't normally do.
</P>
<P>
   Common anti-depressant drugs like Prozac, also used to treat
humans with Obsessive Compulsive Disorder (OCD), are sometimes
given to bored animals that have OCD-like behavior. It cured those
bears, Dr. Dodman said, and the gorilla, and prescribed properly
can also help house pets that have adopted compulsive behaviors
because of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of elementary corrections. A few weeks ago in a column
we labeled Uranium ``Ur.'' The symbol is ``U.'' And we said the
derivation of the name Hydrogen is from the Latin hudor, for water.
Hudor is Greek. Aqua is Latin. Mea culpa is oops, we messed up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4181 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-GIFTS-CHILDREN-TOYS-L     11-18 2058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTS-CHILDREN-TOYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT CHILDREN'S TOYS FOR THE HOLIDAY SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Not for use before Sunday, Nov. 21) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Those charming metal pedal-powered kiddie cars are back, now
manufactured by Sacramento-based Glide Ride. They offer a fire
truck ($249), Checker cab ($229), dump truck and a police car (both
$259). They closely resemble the Murray kiddie cars of the '50s,
but these are meant to be played with, not merely collected.
</P>
<P>
   Glide Rides are made of 18-gauge steel and coated with a
lead-free powdered paint that makes them rust-resistant (another
big improvement over their predecessors). Suited for ages 2-6, the
pedal system has five easily adjustable positions for growing
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Kids may not have the good judgment to ask for one but they are
sure to love them, and the cars are incredibly appealing to parents
with happy motoring memories. Sold fully assembled at Cherish'd,
Woodland Hills; Kae &AMP; Shelly's Hallmark, Thousand Oaks; Coppa
Automotive, San Pedro; and G&AMP;L Collectibles, Covina.
</P>
<P>
   Bop It Extreme is a five-way version of Parker Bros.' already
popular Bop It coordination and reflex game. The hand-held gadget
sets a rhythm and cues the player to bop it, pull it, twist it,
flick it, spin it and pass it in time to the beat or he's out.
</P>
<P>
   Improved coordination is rewarded with faster tempos. Bop It
Extreme was a big hit among Daily News staffers who tried it. The
suggested retail price is $24.99, but we've seen it around town for
$20-$30. Available at most toy and mass merchandise stores.
</P>
<P>
   Music Blocks, made by Neurosmith, is a guaranteed painless way
to introduce children to classical music and orchestra sounds. The
electronic toy comes with a cartridge to play Mozart's Night Music,
but exactly how it is played is up to the user.
</P>
<P>
   Each of five blocks plays a certain phrase from the well-known
piece, allowing users to rearrange the measures by moving the
blocks. And each of a block's six sides, marked by a shape,
represents a different performance of that phrase _ say, woodwinds,
strings or vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Neurosmith says there are a million different ways to play one
work. For even more variety, there are Rhythms of the World and
Sounds of the Symphony cartridges sold separately.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer says it's suited to ages 2 and older, but don't
let that starting age and the primary colors fool you. This is
stimulating and fun for all ages. About $70 at specialty toy stores
such as Zany Brainy and Store of Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   If wrestling-themed stuff is a must-have, WCW Tuff Talkin'
Wrestlers from Toy Biz can be a lot of fun. Goldberg and Kevin
Nash, sold as a pair, have the technology to recognize each other
and personalize their banter as their mouths move. Each figure also
makes grunting or ``oof'' noises on contact. When pinned on their
backs, an announcer three-counts them out.
</P>
<P>
   Although we didn't push them to the limit, they appear sturdy
enough to withstand a lot of punishment. The series also includes
Sting and Diamond Dallas Page pairing. Each pair costs about $40.
They're available at mass merchandise and toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   Riding skateboards is not just a boy thing, as Skateboard
Shannen knows. With Shannen, Mattel gives young kids a simple, fun
introduction to radio-controlled toys. With manipulation of two
easy-to-use joysticks, she goes forward, backward and spins
wheelies. She can get up pretty good speed for jumps, and has a
helmet and elbow pads for rough landings. About $40 at toy and mass
merchandise stores.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Marshall collectible dolls are 15{ inches of high-quality
glamour _ what Barbie aspired to be in her early years before
Mattel cut a great deal on hot pink fabrics. Gene is a Hollywood
star of the '40s and '50s whose elegant wardrobe is part haute
couture, part studio costume department.
</P>
<P>
   Now in her fourth season through the Ashton-Drake Galleries mail
order and specialty doll stores, this is the first year the company
offers Simply Gene, a bathing-suit clad doll _ blond, brunet or
redhead _ for $49.95, including a hairstyling guide.
</P>
<P>
   As in past years, there are completely outfitted dolls with just
the right hairstyle and accessories, such as the Champagne Supper
copper satin and fur ensemble, for $79.95. Available at the Doll
Shoppe, Sherman Oaks; Gallery Decor/Carlin's, Glendale; Thru
Children's Eyes, Thousand Oaks; Dolls on Broadway, Long Beach; and
Bea's House of Dolls, Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARGINS &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   The end is near for Beanie Babies, or so says manufacturer Ty
Inc., which announced a couple of months ago it will quit
production of all Beanie Babies on Dec. 31. The ultimate
collectible Beanie, a black bear with The End and a fireworks burst
embroidered on its chest, has a suggested retail price around $6,
but some sellers are seizing the opportunity to scalp. You can pay
as little as $5.99 at Play Co. Toys and $6.50 at Amy's Hallmark,
both in Woodland Hills, but blink and you'll miss them. Or you can
pay $49.95 on eToys or $59.95 at the Beanie Baby stall at Woodland
Hills Promenade where they are readily available.
</P>
<P>
   Matchbox CAT Power Machines from Mattel are scaled similar to
Tonka trucks and have no-battery motor actions. For example, a
lever on the side of the dump truck raises and lowers the truck
bed. But unlike Tonkas, they are made of sturdy plastic that won't
rust. Just grab them from the sandbox, douse them in the kiddie
pool or turn the hose on them and they're ready for inside play.
About $15 at toy stores and mass merchandise stores.
</P>
<P>
   For little biker wanna-bes, Power Wheels has a piglet version of
a hog. The Harley-Davidson sports ``outrigger wheels'' on the back
to provide tricycle stability, concealed under exaggerated running
boards and exhaust pipes. About $200 at Toys `R' Us, including a
battery pack and charger.
</P>
<P>
   Most kids love to get dizzy, and Dizzy Disc Jr. from Quantum
Toys offers a pretty safe but challenging way to do it. They can
sit, kneel or stand on the round swiveling platform, which can be
set level or cocked at an angle to make it even more fun. It has a
stabilizing base and a built-in handle for portability, and can
hold up to 150 pounds. Parents will like the idea that Dizzy Disc
improves balance and coordination for sports and dance, but kids
will just like to spin and fall down. About $50 at specialty toy
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Cloth-body Singing Steve and Blue from Nick Jr.'s popular
preschool series ``Blue's Clues'' sing songs from the show, and
come packaged in a box with a red Thinking Chair that can be cut
out. That makes it easy for young fans to make up their own Blue's
Clues games at home. About $35 at most toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   Excalibur Electronics Talking Electronic Dart Board is aimed at
ages 9 and older, but comes with less-than-lethal plastic-tipped
darts. At about $100, it's a bit pricey, but it costs a lot less
than hiring a referee. This board knows the rules to five different
games and keeps score. As with other safety-dart games, some
bounce-outs do occur, but since the board is pressure-sensitive it
counts the contact anyway unless players choose to disqualify
bounce-outs. The package comes with replacement tips and six
American flag and Union Jack flights. Available online through
eToys.
</P>
<P>
   Does someone on your gift list have a hankering to try pottery?
No need to rewire the house for a kiln. Imagine Nation has come out
with a Deluxe Pottery Wheel equipped with air-dry clay requiring no
baking. The kit includes paints and mosaics, and extra clay can be
purchased at art supply stores. The wheel runs on four D batteries
or with an adapter sold separately. About $30 at Store of
Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   In board games, everything old is new again. Tried-and-true
Monopoly has a Star Wars Episode I edition that begins at the
low-rent Naboo Swamps and ends at Coruscant, headquarters of the
Jedi Council, deemed equivalent to Boardwalk. The currency is
Republic credits instead of dollars, but there still are familiar
elements, such as the look of the dreaded jail corner. About $60 at
toy stores, mass merchandise stores and specialty stores.
Monopoly's manufacturer, USAoply, also has a new Scrabble Jr. game
with a Madeline theme. The words already are printed on the board,
so players just have to draw the right letters to fill in the board
and score points. Or play it in French on the reverse side. Mais
oui. About $20 at toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   The bad girl of TV's ``Rugrats'' and her African-American friend
have been all dolled up by Mattel as Make-Up Pretty Angelica and
Make-Up Pretty Susie, widely predicted to be hot sellers this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Both soft-bodied dolls have pink tutus, crowns and long skirts
that can be added under the tutu. Angelica comes with her blond
hair in pigtails, but with some work it can be restyled into an
updo, unusual for a vinyl doll. Unfortunately, the main attraction
_ the lipstick, rouge and eyeshadow that emerge or wash off with a
little water _ seems to be their biggest flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Three dolls we've seen did not react as promised on the package,
although Mattel reports it has not received complaints. A very
frank 5-year-old girl said she wasn't interested in playing with
Angelica if she couldn't do her makeup. About $20 at toy and mass
merchandise stores.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie has a desk job and she can't stop talking about it. Press
a button in Working Woman Barbie's back and she says, ``It's
payday. Earning money is fun,'' ``Let's have a meeting'' and other
things we all say at the office, as well as Barbie-isms like ``I
can't wait to go dancing with Ken tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Her accessories include a laptop computer, cellular phone,
coffee mug and file folders. She can shed her blazer and turn her
gray skirt inside out, transforming it into a sparkly red chiffon
number fit for a night on the town.
</P>
<P>
   The enclosed CD-Rom allows players to make their own stationery,
design a cover of Working Woman magazine and do other activities.
Mattel has included replaceable batteries. About $30 at most toy
and mass merchandise stores. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
LITTLE STUFF, LITTLE PRICES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you are desperately seeking Pikachu, Pokemon trading card
sets are hard to come by at Toys `R' Us because of the high demand,
but they are in stock at smaller toy stores such as Play Co., KB
Toys, Gamekeeper and Target, all of which sell starter packs for
about $4.
</P>
<P>
   Tangle Pen is a snaky looking ballpoint that comes in four
interchangeable segments, each with a different color and texture
on the outside and a different color ink. There also is a mini roll
of paper in the end, great for slipping smaller-than-cookie-fortune
notes to friends. About $9 at Store of Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   For babies and older kids who still like to play in the tub,
check out Shakin' Bath Toys, made by Kids II. They are crinkly,
colorful frogs, fish and turtles that start vibrating across the
water when a string is pulled. They sell for $2.99 each exclusively
at Wal-Mart's infants departments.
</P>
<P>
   Bendos from Kid Galaxy are 45 quirky and very pliable characters
that could be the next collectible craze. Bendos are a good
diversion in cars, restaurants, doctors' waiting rooms and anyplace
else kids get fidgety. About $5 at toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   To stash the goods, Zany Brainy has stockings and dreidl bags
that are roomy, nice-looking and well-made for a few years' use _
and they're only $5 each. At that price they make a clever
gift-wrap idea.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEB TOYS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Experts are predicting that more toys will be purchased online
this holiday season than ever. There are several options on the
Web, including eToys.com, ToysRUs.com, SmarterKids.com, KBkids.com,
Toysmart.com, eHobbies.com and ZanyBrainy.com.
</P>
<P>
   Online might be the best way to go for the stuff in highest
demand; eToys advises you while shopping if an item is out of stock
and will notify you by e-mail when it's available. Some, such as
SmarterKids and Toysmart, are offering shipping bargains for early
shoppers, and ToysRUs and KBkids will accept returns or exchanges
of online purchases in their stores. If the item is shipped from
out of state, you can save on the sales tax, which defrays the
shipping charges. Many sites also will giftwrap for an additional
charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
