<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-BEN-HUR19-COX     11-18 1559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEN-HUR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Ben-Hur' musical hits Florida theme-park circuit
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ After three years in the making, at a cost of $9
million and counting, a new tourist attraction has arrived in this
theme-park city. Once you've trekked up Space Mountain, plummeted
down the Tower of Terror and survived the jostling of The Hulk
coaster, how about relaxing in front of ``Ben-Hur: The Musical''?
</P>
<P>
   A new production company bullishly named Global Impact Concepts
is betting it can attract a half-million people annually to sit for
an on-stage chariot race, a fiery sea battle, the crucifixion of
Christ and two dozen songs. Implied in that multimillion-dollar
wager is that ``Ben-Hur'' can generate a sizable theater-going
habit that Orlando has never had. Global Impact managed to build
the show, as last weekend's premiere performances proved, but still
to be determined is whether audiences in sufficient numbers will
come.
</P>
<P>
   Global Impact President Bob Reeder has a history as a family
entertainment Pied Piper, launching the Fort Lauderdale Christmas
Pageant in 1983. That large-cast show featuring live animals and
flying angels now attracts some 50,000 people each holiday season.
So Reeder figured it was time to move to Orlando and create a
year-round spectacle and spirituality event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it to be of epic proportion,'' says Reeder, who
began to sketch out a pageant with a plot that he called ``The
Spectacular Light.'' ``And the more we started writing, we found we
really wanted to do something similar to `Ben-Hur.' Because it has
a little bit of everything in it. The more we thought about it, the
more we decided, well, why don't we just do `Ben-Hur'?''
</P>
<P>
   After all, there's no point in reinventing the chariot wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Civil War General Lew Wallace wrote ``Ben-Hur'' in 1880, pitting
privileged Judah Ben-Hur against his childhood friend Messala, who
grows up to be a tribune in the Roman army that occupies Judea.
Their friendship sours when Messala condemns Ben-Hur to life as a
galley slave, an animosity that culminates in an action-adventure
chariot race between them.
</P>
<P>
   The book became a best-seller, and the story soon moved to other
media. It arrived on Broadway in 1899 _ not as a musical _ and
played there and on tour for the next 20 years. A 1926 silent movie
version set new standards for film spectacle and the remake,
released exactly 40 years ago, copped a then-record 11 Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   In part, because of that movie's action sequences, the chariot
race has overshadowed the story's religious themes for many people.
But, as Reeder is quick to point out, ``The name of the book is
`Ben-Hur: A Tale of the Christ.' It parallels Judah Ben-Hur's life
with the Christ's, how they interacted and how his life was changed
at the cross. It really takes on a whole dimension after that
chariot race.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, what people want to know is how do they stage the race?
Set designer Peter Wolf was taken aback by early creative meetings
where live horses were contemplated. ``And I said, `So we're going
to have on the stage some moving sidewalk or treadmill? Once you've
got those on the stage, where am I going to put my scenery? We have
one chariot race for six minutes, but what do we do the rest of the
time?'''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, relief of Wolf _ and the cleanup crew _
mechanical horses were decided upon, eight computerized stallions
that reach full gallop with animatronic technology similar to that
used across town at Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very complicated show technically,'' says director
Amick Byram, who refereed the battle between ``what is going to
fulfill people's expectations and what is physically possible on a
stage.'' He likened the task to being a theatrical George Patton.
``Sometimes you have to be as firm as Patton was, and sometimes
delicate.''
</P>
<P>
   The creative team wondered how they could possibly compete with
theme-park thrill rides. ``We had these discussions early on _ OK,
it's the Orlando marketplace, people come here to see all this
`wow' stuff,'' says Byram. ``But this is the only thing that
tourists are probably going to see in this city that is not only
going to wow them, but also affect them emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, says Reeder, Disney executives have been encouraging.
``We're really not competing with any of those big boys, because we
can't. We only want (audiences) for two-and-a-half hours. They can
go over there and stand in line and do their thing, and then they
come to the theater and sit in an air-conditioned room, hear a
beautiful orchestra and be entertained.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the gnawing thought remains that if ``Ben-Hur'' does
catch on with Orlando tourists, it won't be long before the Magic
Kingdom unveils a nighttime ``Hercules'' chariot-race show. ``You
know what? That could happen,'' agrees Reeder. ``A lot of people
have said to us since we first came into town that as soon as
Disney or Universal figures out how to do it, they're going to want
to do it. We think that will only complement what we're doing. A
good place to build a restaurant is right next to a successful
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando has plenty of restaurants but few theaters. Luckily,
Reeder found the underutilized, oversized, 2,657-seat auditorium in
the Orlando/Orange County Convention Center. But when he told the
center's management what he wanted, they treated him like a leper.
``We said we wanted at least a three-year lease, and they said,
`Maybe three days or three weeks,''' recalls Reeder. He prevailed
but adds that ``it took 18 months to negotiate that contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeder was also persuasive enough to attract investors to
``Ben-Hur: The Musical'' long before the show was ever written.
``We just shared the vision,'' he says, amassing the $9 million
budget from just a handful of individuals, including major-league
pitcher Orel Hershiser. Reeder's pitch included a plea for faith,
plus an upbeat business plan. ``In our projections, we believe that
within two years, we'll have all of our investors paid back. That's
on a conservative basis of 60 to 65 percent capacity,'' he
explains. Conservative, perhaps, but at Sunday evening's
performance _ the fourth before a paid audience _ the turnout was
already far below that level.
</P>
<P>
   Advance ticket sales are projected to be $2 million by the end
of the month. That's puny by Broadway standards, but nothing seems
to dampen Reeder's spirits. His marketing staff is targeting church
groups from across the country, and he expects general tourist
business to be last-minute impulse buys. ``Seventy-five percent of
the people that are going to come to our show haven't even heard
about it yet,'' he insists.
</P>
<P>
   Reeder also likes to point out parallels between ``Ben-Hur'' and
``Les Miserables,'' predicting financial returns on par with that
literary mega-hit musical. ``It's basically the same thing,'' he
says of the shows. ``It's basically all about forgiveness. We're
trusting that we're going to have some of that same success that
`Les Miz' has had.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``Ben-Hur'' conquers Orlando, that's when the global
impact kicks in. Reeder mentions the possibility of future
productions in New York and even Las Vegas, cities not previously
known for their interest in spiritual entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Once Wolf catches his breath, he will begin thinking about a
redesign for touring. ``If we don't have a theater of this size,
we'll have to change things and come up with effects that are just
as powerful but done in another way,'' he says. ``This isn't really
geared to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Reeder, theater producers as far away as Japan are
already inquiring about licensing his ``Ben-Hur.'' ``This city,
this world, the timing of the millennium, are ready for this story
to be told again, and to be told in the greatest way it could be
told, in music. We think this is just the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just a matter of faith, hope and chariots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben-Hur'' the movie vs. ``Ben-Hur'' the musical:
</P>
<P>
   THE CHARIOT RACE
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE: An 11-minute, 7-lap tour de force, with 9 racers, 36
horses and a big crowd in a coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL : A six-minute spectacle, with no laps because the eight
animatronic horses (price: $600,000) are not programmed to turn,
just to bump each other with a sideways motion.
</P>
<P>
   THE SEA BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE: Flaming arrows and fiery catapults.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL: A cool 1,000-degree wall of butane fire.
</P>
<P>
   THE ACTING
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE: Charlton Heston flashes snarling white teeth and shapely
legs, seething to get revenge from Messala.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL: Robert Patteri's blown-dry mane of hair and
machine-pumped pecs are a little '90s, and he would rather sing to
Messala than harm him.
</P>
<P>
   FATE OF MESSALA
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE: Dies from chariot-race injuries, including being trampled
by horses.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL: Crippled from chariot-race injuries but lives on to
attend Ben-Hur's wedding to Esther.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE: 3 hours, 32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL: 2 hours, 35 minutes (excluding intermission).
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION COST
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE: $14.5 million (earned $70 million domestically)
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL: $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   AWARDS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE: 11 Oscars, including Best Picture.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL: 1 Hapster (if I'm feeling generous).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
