<HEADER>
A4199 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-TORREYA-PARK19-COX     11-18 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORREYA-PARK19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's little-known Garden of Eden
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORREYA STATE PARK, Fla. _ Here is one of the best views in
Florida, simple, solitary, splendid. The eye wings up over tranquil
miles of tufted forests, fading from green to blue in the distance,
to a horizon of rain-washed pure air. Hundreds of feet below,
beyond a steep tumble of trees and shrubs, the toffee-colored
Apalachicola River runs calmly to the Gulf of Mexico, past
Confederate cannon-emplacements dating back to the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Beholding this panorama is like flying with your two feet still
on the ground: It all looks elemental, enormous, like the first day
of creation. But there is a fascinating tangle of history and loss
behind this place, involving a shipwreck, an abandoned mansion, a
mysterious tree on the brink of extinction, and mythical
recollections of Noah's Ark and the biblical Garden of Eden.
</P>
<P>
   Here would be a good place to spend Saturday, when every state
park in Florida will be open free of charge, all 151 of them, to
celebrate Florida's state park system's being named the best in the
nation by the National Recreation and Parks Administration and the
National Sporting Goods Association at an Oct. 23 ceremony in
Nashville, Tenn. Florida beat Missouri, Tennessee and Virginia for
the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, as on most days, you will likely have this
2,495-acre place largely to yourself. Torreya is the second
least-visited state park in Florida, after Lignum Vitae Key State
Park, which you can only get to by boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valleys and ravines filled with massive, ancient trees,
rock-strewn trails and creeks, waterfalls, a thousand species of
plants (some existing nowhere else), hundreds of species of birds
and animals ... this is the magic of Torreya State Park. There is
no other place like it in Florida ... perhaps no place like it in
the world,'' writes Scott Stursa of Wild Florida Online.
</P>
<P>
   Torreya can be reached by car and hiked on foot, but it is so
out of the way, so lost in the leafy wilderness of Liberty County,
that few people are tempted to make the effort. Of the 14,645,202
people who visited Florida's state parks this past year, only
20,469 made their way here.
</P>
<P>
   There are days when, in all of teeming Florida, nobody at all
comes here except park personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other area on earth, when one considers Eden in
Florida, of like size, better blessed with a water supply of pure
water. There is no other area on earth of like size having a better
twelve-month climate,'' declared Elvy E. Callaway, in his 1971
book, ``In the Beginning,'' written to prove that the Paradise of
Adam and Eve _ the Garden of Eden itself _ had been located in
these parts.
</P>
<P>
   To prove his point, Callaway argued that 27 of the 28 species of
tree mentioned in the Bible are to be found here. He identified the
``Four Rivers'' flowing into the Garden of Eden as modern
Chattahoochee, the Flint/Apalachicola, Fish Pond Creek and Spring
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Some people took Callaway seriously. There is a Garden of Eden
Drive in the western part of Liberty County. In 1967, a law was
actually passed by the state legislature, Florida Statute 67-960,
authorizing the planning and establishment of a replica of Noah's
Ark here.
</P>
<P>
   The ark was never built. Money was lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the aura of Eden lingers still, in the memory of a nearly
lost tree: Torreya taxifolia, discovered here and named in the
early 19th century by Bryan Hardy Croom, a planter and botanist who
perished with his wife Frances and their children in the October
1837 wreck of the steamship Home, off Cape Hatteras.
</P>
<P>
   The imaginative Callaway theorized that the ``gopherwood'' of
the Bible, the wood Noah used to build his ark, was actually
Torreya taxifolia. The tree does in fact yield a light, strong,
durable, fine-grained wood, very resistant to water and insects.
Fenceposts made from it 60 years ago are still standing, still
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Torreya taxifolia is one of the rarest trees in America,
related to the yew-tree that produces the cancer-remedy Taxol. A
mysterious blight, similar to the American chestnut blight, attacks
mature trees with a fungus that can move in any direction, from tip
to roots, from branch-tips to trunk, or backwards, and slay mature
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Then, from the dead tree's seeds, little saplings spring up,
fewer and fewer as years go by, to be attacked in their turn by the
fungus. Nobody knows how to save the tree from extinction. Three
years ago, two little Torreya pines stood near the parking lot of
the state park. Today both are dead, and there is only one specimen
left growing in the whole place. Park personnel can show you
embalmed branches in jars of alcohol, pale emerald in color, kept
in a drawer inside the park office. Preservation in fluid has faded
them: The live trees are a deep green, almost black.
</P>
<P>
   Why this tree is disappearing is a mystery. ``When I was a boy,
they were so abundant on the riverbanks we cut them for Christmas
trees,'' said Angus Kemp Gholson, a retired forester and amateur
botanist who lives in Chattahoochee and who is one of the most
respected authorities on North Florida's flora.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory is, when St. Joe Paper cut down the hardwoods in
Gulf, Franklin and Liberty County, and replanted them with pines,
they somehow changed the ecosystem. I may be wrong, but I know that
Torreya has died out within my lifetime. Something happened to kill
it.'' Seven miles of hiking trails are open at the park, and now,
in fall and in winter, is the best time to pace them. June, July
and August are months when insects rule the riverbank, and only the
strongest, hardiest, most bug-defiant visitors dare confront them.
</P>
<P>
   One last reward: There is a magnificent old house on the bluff
overlooking the park today, the Gregory House, built in the 1840s,
on the opposite side of the river. In the 1930s, the place was
falling to pieces, and Civilian Conservation Corps workers
disassembled it and toted it up to this bluff, where it is now open
for tours. In an ever more crowded state, this empty, handsome
house, overlooking a broad arc of faraway forestland, in a park few
people even know about, makes for a spell of magical quiet and
solitude.
</P>
<P>
   Here, less is more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Torreya is one of our hidden jewels,'' said Carrie Canfield, a
spokeswoman for the Florida Department of Environmental
Protection's division of recreation and parks. ``Not many people
know about it, but it is a very beautiful place.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
