<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 11 
</HEADLINE>
  (A graphic of these matchups has been sent electronically to NYT
graphics clients. Call 888-603-1036 for information.) 
(jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   New England (6-3) at Miami (7-2)
</P>
<P>
   Both quarterbacks are coming off tough losses and poor play.
Drew Bledsoe is still seeing Jets defensive backs in his sleep, and
Damon Huard looked terrible against Buffalo. The player who will
bounce back is Bledsoe. No way he has back-to-back horrible games
with so much on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots, 14-12
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (2-7) at Tampa Bay (5-4)
</P>
<P>
   If Tampa Bay had any kind of offense, it would be in the Super
Bowl this year. Last week the Buccaneers held Kansas City to 5
first-half passing yards. Tampa Bay wishes it could throw for that
many. But things are looking up for the Buccaneers. Quarterback
Trent Dilfer is showing a pulse, completing 32-of-47 passes for
five touchdowns in the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers, 9-3
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (7-3) at Jets (3-6)
</P>
<P>
   One day the handsome mug of Bill Parcells will adorn the Hall of
Fame, but moments from this season won't make it into the
acceptance speech. He blew not getting a solid backup quarterback,
and with talent like Keyshawn Johnson and Curtis Martin the Jets
should still be .500 even with the loss of Vinny Testaverde. Ray
Lucas played a great game against New England, but the Bills will
have a few surprises for Lucas as Parcells had for the Patriots.
Lucas' Christmas gift from the Bills is a speedy linebacker who
will ``spy'' on him.
</P>
<P>
   Bills, 24-18
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (3-6) at Cleveland (2-8)
</P>
<P>
   The development of quarterback Tim Couch has been one of the few
positives for the Browns this year. He needs only 162 passing yards
to break the club's season rookie record set by Bernie Kosar in
1985. He has shown poise and a nice touch on the ball, and he has a
stronger arm than most scouts believed. This time Cleveland wins a
game when the clock isn't on zero.
</P>
<P>
   Browns, 12-10
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (6-3) at Green Bay (4-5)
</P>
<P>
   Do not ask Bret Favre about his injured thumb. Please. He gets
irate. He says it has nothing to do with his team's 4-5 record, but
when Favre ails, the Packers feel the pain. Green Bay is desperate,
and that is probably why it will win. It also helps the Packers
that the home team in this matchup has won 11 of the past 12,
including one playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Packers 24-21
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis (7-2) at Philadelphia (3-7)
</P>
<P>
   What the Colts lacked last season was the maturity to win close
games. Well, mission accomplished. But their game against
Philadelphia will be closer than expected. The last three meetings
between these two teams have been decided by a total of 11 points.
The Eagles are a feisty bunch that play well at home and will shut
down Edgerrin James but not Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Colts, 22-21
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (5-4) at Tennessee (7-2)
</P>
<P>
   Steelers coach Bill Cowher this week denied he has lost his
passion, and when meeting with the media, he expressed that
sentiment very, very loudly. Cowher may still have the best vocal
cords in coaching but there is no question he is not as hard on his
players as he used to be. He gives them incredible leeway,
especially quarterback Kordell Stewart, who is more erratic than a
seismograph. Meanwhile, the Titans' Eddie George is just beginning
to pick up steam. He gets double-figure rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Titans, 24-18
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (7-2) at Kansas City (5-4)
</P>
<P>
   If any coach can break Kansas City's stranglehold on opponents
at home, it is Seattle Coach Mike Holmgren. He seeks to open the
season 8-2 for the third time of his professional head-coaching
career. This is significant because the first two times he did that
the Packers won Super Bowls. Holmgren is great in this situation.
He does well at preparing his teams for hostile environments, and
the Seahawks make few mistakes on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks, 19-17
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore (3-6) at Cincinnati (1-9)
</P>
<P>
   Rod Woodson loves the Bengals. He has seven career interceptions
against them, his most against any team, and two were returned for
touchdowns. Not to mention Woodson has picked off Cincinnati
quarterback Jeff Blake three times. Woodson is part of a pretty
good Ravens defense that has not allowed a 100-yard rusher or
receiver this season. The Bengals won't be much of a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens, 21-7
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (4-6) at San Diego (4-5)
</P>
<P>
   One of the best coaching jobs this season comes not from
Holmgren, Jim Mora or Dick Vermeil, but Dick Jauron of the Bears.
That this sorry Chicago team has won four games is one of the great
stories of the season. In fact, five of the Bears' six losses have
been by seven points or less, so the team could easily have two
more wins. The Chargers are still reeling from their 28-9 loss to
Oakland on Sunday, and during the game there was a facemask to
facemask shouting match between quarterback Jim Harbaugh and safety
Michael Dumas. Even without the suspended Ryan Leaf, things still
ugly in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Bears, 28-16
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (5-4) at Arizona (3-6)
</P>
<P>
   Jason Garrett was surprising last week in leading the Dallas
offense past Green Bay. In fact, Garrett is 6-2 in his career as a
starter. He's not great, just solid, and all Garrett needs to do is
keep the Cowboys afloat until Troy Aikman and Emmitt Smith return.
Arizona will present a few problems, namely Simeon Rice, whom no
team has been able to slow this season, but Garrett gets the job
done again.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys, 20-17
</P>
<P>
   Giants (5-4) at Washington (5-4)
</P>
<P>
   New York plans to open up the offense more this week, and that
is a good thing. One player who has taken the brunt of the blame
but shouldn't is quarterback Kent Graham. He has played solidly
despite the poor play of the offensive line and the lack of a
running game. Look for the Giants to throw the ball downfield early
and attack one of the worst defenses this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Giants, 21-20
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis (7-2) at San Francisco (3-6)
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had a nice win last week against Carolina and should
have an equally pleasant time this week against the 49ers. San
Francisco is an organization in disarray. Historically, the 49ers
have dominated the Rams, but the situation has now reversed itself.
St. Louis averages 381.7 yards of offense a game. This is the kind
of number the 49ers used to put on the board a long time ago in a
galaxy far, far away.
</P>
<P>
   Rams, 40-20
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (2-7) at Jacksonville (8-1)
</P>
<P>
   Running back Fred Taylor is questionable with a hamstring pull.
They could use him, and that must sound insane, since
Jacksonville's six-game winning streak is the longest this season
and the Jaguars do have eight victories. But last week Jacksonville
scored only six points against Baltimore, and there is definitely
friction between quarterback Mark Brunell and Coach Tom Coughlin,
who is calling the plays this year. Brunell and Coughlin should get
through this one easily.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars, 30-12
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Oakland (5-4) at Denver (3-7)
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders have one of the more brutal schedules in the league,
but still the team plods along. The Broncos have dominated the AFC
West in recent years, winning 12 straight division games at home.
But that was with John Elway and Terrell Davis. Now, Elway is on
the banquet circuit, and Davis is rehabilitating his knee. So the
Broncos will see lots of Wheatley, who is playing like Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders, 17-14
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
