<HEADER>
A4202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-DUBNER19-COX     11-18 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-DUBNER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dubner goes home again, recounts journey in `Turbulent Souls'
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Stephen Dubner has had a hard time
attending synagogue lately.
</P>
<P>
   It's not because the 36-year-old is having second thoughts about
his reconnection to Judaism after a devout Catholic upbringing. Or
because his struggle with faith has left him alienated from the
service, or even the culture.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing that ethereal. It's just that Dubner is
occasionally put off by the steady parade of people who want to say
hello and shake his hand. It's the price the young author is paying
for writing a best-selling memoir about his 10-year wrestling match
with God.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Turbulent Souls,'' Dubner exposes the fractures he endured
in that match. By opening himself up, he has tacitly invited
thousands of others who have struggled with their own spiritual
dilemmas to compare scars and celebrate the triumph of his choice _
and theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of fun, but it's also a bit of a distraction,''
Dubner says by cell phone from a taxi in New York City. ``People
were really affected by this book.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Turbulent Souls,'' Dubner retraces with poetic elegance his
parents' separate journeys from their Jewish homes, through periods
of religious uncertainty and finally, after they married, into
their rich Catholic faiths.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion would define not only their lives but the lives
of their children. In accepting Jesus, Dubner's parents divorced
their families, their communities and their histories. Immediately
after World War II, when they met each other and married, they
began their journey of reinvention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of a little Yiddish and gefilte fish,'' Dubner writes,
his parents, two Jews from Brooklyn, created a perfect Roman
Catholic family. ``We, the children, were a separate slice of time
like one prehistoric era laid over the last.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubner grew up knowing that his parents had once been Jewish,
but he didn't know what the word meant. What he knew was the bloody
drama of Jesus. The feel of rosary beads in his fingers. The way
the light looked seeping through the stained-glass window of Our
Lady of Fatima Church, where he was an altar boy and his father a
sometimes orator. What he knew was playing checkers across from a
2-foot-tall statue of the Infant of Prague when none of his seven
older brothers and sisters had time for him.
</P>
<P>
   But even in this house filled with crosses _ and a convert's
fervor for Jesus _ faith never quite lodged in Dubner's heart or
the hearts of many of his siblings. When he was 10 years old, his
father died, leaving even more room for doubt.
</P>
<P>
   After earning an academic scholarship to Appalachian State
University and playing in The Right Profile, a band that knocked on
fame's door, Dubner married an Episcopalian woman and began
pursuing a graduate degree in writing at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   But in the most vibrant Jewish city in the Western Hemisphere,
it was only a matter of time before Dubner collided with his
family's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was really this kind of resonance that would make itself
felt to me in various ways,'' Dubner said. ``Obviously, I can't
prove it, but yes, I think there was some sort of Jewish soul lying
dormant in me.''
</P>
<P>
   What Dubner loved about Judaism was its acceptance of the
imperfections of man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm personally not someone who has great thirst for
certainty,'' Dubner said. ``To me, Judaism is a religion that not
only tolerates but actually encourages questioning and examining
things from different angles.'' Dubner devotes a good portion of
``Turbulent Souls'' to his attempts to make sense of his parents'
choices. In the end, he is able to understand that his father,
distraught by the death of his own mother, found solace in the
Virgin Mary. It is a realization that enables the son to make peace
with the father.
</P>
<P>
   What took a little more time was reaching a detente with his
mother, who was not happy that her youngest had so publicly turned
his back on the faith that she had worked so hard to embody. While
Dubner's mother was living in Lake Worth, Fla., a few years ago,
Dubner spoke with Cardinal John O'Connor of New York. His words,
legitimizing Judaism, helped to bridge the chasm between mother and
son.
</P>
<P>
   The book, which illuminates this bridge, has made Dubner
something of a spokesman for Christian-Jewish relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are obvious differences between the two religions,''
Dubner says. ``But at the root, the differences are not as great as
we often play them up to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
