<HEADER>
A4203 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-HUR-REVIEW19-COX     11-18 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUR-REVIEW19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Ben-Hur' music scores, but rest is off key
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The creators of the new $9 million ``Ben-Hur:
The Musical'' intend it to be a spiritual experience, and for me it
was. For most of the evening, I found myself praying. Praying that
the show would somehow get better.
</P>
<P>
   At least you can see where the money went. The numerous
painterly landscapes by set designer Peter Wolf are visually
appealing, even if they and the huge scenery pieces tend to dwarf
the performers. And while the animatronic horses of the climactic
chariot race cannot do much more than kick their legs furiously and
move sideways, that couldn't have come cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Like the animated ``Prince of Egypt,'' this ``Ben-Hur'' spends
time establishing the childhood friendship of the two men who will
grow into enemies _ Jewish Judean prince Judah Ben-Hur and the
future Roman tribune, Messala. Ben-Hur's romantic interest, Esther,
is also introduced as a youngster, with a stroll through the
marketplace song, ``Brand New Day,'' that could have been Belle's
in ``Beauty and the Beast'' with minor adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the adapters want to make sure that tots in
attendance are sufficiently drawn into the story. Could that
explain the laughable close-order march of the Roman soldiers or
the broadly comic depiction of Arab Sheik Ilderim, complete with
idiotic nephew sidekick?
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the musical score by Paul Johnson and Ronald
Owen is tunefully pleasant. If only the lyrics were more tailored
to the story, so they did not sound like generic songs of yearning
(``Where Do I Go From Here?''), generic love songs (``It's Always
Been You'') and generic songs of reunion (``Do You Remember Me?'').
In contrast, a driving, multipart tune about bygones (``Forgive &AMP;
Forget'') stands out as a model of what the rest might have
emulated.
</P>
<P>
   Once the main characters grow up, the show follows the Lew
Wallace novel and the 1959 William Wyler-directed movie version
fairly closely, until after the chariot race. Early on, a rooftop
accident spells bad news for the Hurs, as Messala sends Judah off
to be a galley slave and imprisons his mother and sister. The
stage-wide ship gets attacked in a wimpy sea battle, complete with
a wall of fire that looks like a row of maladjusted butane
lighters.
</P>
<P>
   Judah saves commander Quintus Arrius, who adopts him. Soon our
hero is challenging Messala to a no-holds-barred chariot race.
Well, no holds might be barred if the computerized horses were
programmed to move on a few more axes. As is, the race is a long,
uninvolving six minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a break with Wallace's tale, Messala survives the brutal
matchup, so that scripter Chip Hand can give the show a moral about
forgiveness and reconciliation. Meanwhile, Judah seeks out a
certain carpenter from Nazareth who once did him a kindness, hoping
the silent, robed stranger can cure his mother and sister of
prison-contracted leprosy. Jesus's crucifixion upstages the chariot
race and proves more theatrically effective.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Patteri, sporting Fabio hair, is Ben-Hur as matinee idol,
with a rich, creamy baritone singing voice to boot. The same goes
for the lovely trained soprano of Cassie LaRocca (Esther) and the
malevolence of Stephen Jones' Messala, though all three roles as
written are cardboard thin. Most of the rest of the 47-member cast
is there to be human scenery, an assignment they handle well
enough.
</P>
<P>
   For all I know, ``Ben-Hur: The Musical'' may achieve its
intended spiritual uplift for its target audience. Those more in
search of dramatic values would do well to wait for the next
chariot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
