<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Other state parks worth visiting
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you can't drive nearly 400 miles
northwest this Saturday to get into Torreya State Park for free,
there are other state parks within 100 miles of West Palm Beach,
just as open, just as free on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE INLET STATE RECREATION AREA
</P>
<P>
   It has 340 acres of beach, dunes and coastal hammock, located on
the north shore of Fort Pierce Inlet. Birdwatchers can get an
eyeful on Jack Island. Picnicking and hiking encouraged. Contact
Fort Pierce Inlet State Recreation Area, 905 Shorewinds Drive, Fort
Pierce, FL 34949; (561) 468-3985.
</P>
<P>
   HUGH TAYLOR BIRCH STATE RECREATION AREA
</P>
<P>
   In 1893, Chicago attorney Hugh T. Birch bought three miles of
beachfront in Fort Lauderdale for next to nothing and carved out a
180-acre estate named ``Terramar'' on the property. He donated his
land to the state in 1940, and it has been open to the public since
1949. Nature trails, lagoons and hardwood hammocks show what Fort
Lauderdale used to look like. There is also a bike trail and an
exercise course. Canoe rentals are available. Camping and cabins
are rentable for overnight stays. For more information, contact:
Hugh Taylor Birch State Recreation Area, 3109 East Sunrise
Boulevard, Fort Lauderdale, FL 33304; (954) 564-4521
</P>
<P>
   JOHN D. MACARTHUR BEACH
</P>
<P>
   STATE PARK
</P>
<P>
   It encompasses 225 acres of uplands and another 535 acres of
submerged lands. Visitors can explore both maritime hammock
(seaside hardwood forest) and mangrove communities. A 1,600-foot
boardwalk spans Lake Worth Cove. Herons, ibises, roseate spoonbills
and ospreys haunt the wetlands, and at the beach end of the
boardwalk on the west side of the dunes lies a coastal hammock. A
trail winds through mixed temperate and subtropical trees,
including cabbage palms, mastic trees, gumbo limbos and strangler
figs. The park is named after the previous property owner, John D.
MacArthur, who donated it to the state in the 1970s. For more
information: John D. MacArthur Beach State Park, 10900 S.R. 703
(A1A), North Palm Beach, FL 33408; (561) 624-6950.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN U. LLOYD BEACH STATE RECREATION AREA
</P>
<P>
   Near Port Everglades in Broward County, this park covers 251
acres of green buffer between the Atlantic Ocean and the
Intracoastal Waterway. Named after Broward County's attorney, John
U. Lloyd, who was instrumental in acquiring the property, the park
boasts a wide, flat beach, shaded picnic areas and canoeing. For
more information: John U. Lloyd Beach State Recreation Area, 6503
N. Ocean Drive, Dania, FL 33004; (954) 923-2833.
</P>
<P>
   JONATHAN DICKINSON STATE PARK
</P>
<P>
   An enormous green firewall between rapidly developing Palm Beach
County and more sedate Martin County, it covers 11,500 acres and
offers camping, canoeing and bicycling, picnicking, fresh and
saltwater fishing and guided tours of the Loxahatchee River. The
44-passenger Loxahatchee Queen II takes visitors up the Loxahatchee
River to the pioneer homesite of Trapper Nelson, who came to the
area in the 1930s and lived off the land by trapping and selling
furs, becoming famous as the ``Wildman of the Loxahatchee.'' After
his death in 1968, the state acquired his land. Four scenic nature
trails and a bicycle trail wind through the park. Contact Jonathan
Dickinson State Park, 16450 S.E. Federal Highway, Hobe Sound, FL
33455; (561) 546-2771.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LUCIE INLET STATE PRESERVE
</P>
<P>
   It occupies the northern 928 acres of Jupiter Island and boasts
a 2.5-mile stretch of beach and mangrove-lined creeks. It is
accessible by boat. A 3,300-foot boardwalk meanders from the dock
to the beach. Along the way, you will traverse two coastal
hammocks. A protected reef runs south from the inlet for 4.7 miles.
More than 150 different species of fish can be seen, as well as
countless sponges, crabs and other marine life. Boating, canoeing,
diving and snorkeling are among the attractions. For more
information: St. Lucie Inlet State Preserve, c/o Jonathan Dickinson
State Park, 16450 S.E. Federal Highway, Hobe Sound, FL 33455; (561)
744-7603.
</P>
<P>
   SEBASTIAN INLET STATE PARK
</P>
<P>
   It covers over 600 acres and spans both sides of the inlet. Its
powerful tides and big waves can be dangerous, but surfers come
from far and wide to enjoy the big swells on the north side of the
inlet, or at ``Monster Hole'' on the southeast side. Swimmers can
enjoy the beach and a tranquil tidal pool. Snorkeling and camping
are popular, the fishing legendary. For more information: 9700
South A1A, Melbourne Beach, FL 32951; (407) 984-4852.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
