<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4207 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-HURRICANE-LENNY-1119-     11-18 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-LENNY-1119-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LENNY MAKES ABRUPT HALT, CONITNUES TO POUND EASTERN CARIBBEAN
 &HT;    (725&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ Hurricane Lenny stopped dead in its
tracks and pounded the eastern Caribbean all day Thursday, spinning
out powerful winds and waves that smashed piers, tossed boats about
like toys and demolished beachfront homes.
</P>
<P>
   At least four people were confirmed dead from the storm, which
confounded forecasters by forming so late in the season and then
taking an unusual west-to-east track.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. EST, Lenny was nearly stationary at latitude 18.1
north, longitude 63.2 west, just offshore of tiny St. Maarten.
Winds had dropped to 120 mph after peaking at 150 mph Wednesday.
Forecasters hoped the storm would resume a northeast track and
quickly clear the islands. There was no threat to the mainland U.S.
except for high surf, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean residents were just hoping the late-season menace
would finally go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty bad,'' said Paul Pyles, a 12-year resident of
Frederiksted on St. Croix's western tip, reached by telephone. ``We
don't have power and the cruise ship pier was damaged. I haven't
been out because there's a curfew, but ... I'd say overall we were
pretty fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland Redfield, an announcer for a St. Croix radio station
that broadcast non-stop reports, toured the island and found
relatively little damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did extraordinarily well,'' he said, citing building codes
that were toughened after several powerful storms over the past
decade. ``The roads are clear of debris, although we've been under
a curfew. We should be up to snuff and back to operation by
Thanksgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Redfield said there were no fatalities on St. Croix, contrary to
some media reports. Electric power had already been restored in
Christiansted, the island's largest town, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The news was likely to be much worse from islands further east,
which were punished as Lenny spun in place Thursday. Islands under
the bulls-eye included Anguilla, St. Barthelemy, Saba, St.
Eustatius, Nevis, St. Kitts, Montserrat and an island that is
divided between France and the Netherlands, called St. Maarten on
the Dutch side and St. Martin on the French side. The Dutch portion
faces the Caribbean and the capital, Philipsburg, was inundated by
Lenny's waves. Officials worried that heavy rains would cause the
Great Salt Pond in the middle of the town to overflow, worsening
the flooding. There were reports of smashed boats and one fatality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a very dangerous situation,'' St. Maarten's Lt. Gov.
Dennis Richardson said Thursday. ``We expect conditions to get a
lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined population of both sides of St. Maarten is about
62,000. About 1,200 permanent residents live on Saba; 2,100 on St.
Eustatius; 3,400 on Montserrat; 5,000 on St. Barthelemy; 9,000 on
Anguilla and 42,000 combined on St. Kitts and Nevis.
</P>
<P>
   According to one news report, 100 tourists were evacuated from a
flooded beachfront hotel on Anguilla, a British territory, as
12-foot waves blasted the island's normally placid beaches.
</P>
<P>
   But Lenny's impact was felt as far away as Colombia, where two
fishermen drowned and hundreds of people were left homeless by
flooding and powerful waves.
</P>
<P>
   There was also damage from flooding and pounding waves along
Puerto Rico's south and east coasts, as well as on the nearby
islands of Culebra and Vieques. One Puerto Rican man died when he
fell while boarding up his windows, and a Russian freighter ran
aground near the entrance to San Juan Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny's massive waves raked islands across the Caribbean,
swamping boats against pilings and ripping some free from their
moorings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Huge surf destroyed four homes, chewed up roads and flooded
streets in the business district on Grenada, about 400 miles south
of the storm's center.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On St. Lucia, several people were left homeless when giant
waves destroyed their houses, while a gas station caught fire after
a short-circuit, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Three people were rescued from a harbor in Montserrat after
waves swamped their sailboats.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On St. Barthelemy, weather officials reported a wind gust to
124 mph at mid-day, while on nearby St. Maarten, gusts reached 108
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Airports on most islands remained closed, with dozens of
commercial flights cancelled. Some emergency medical officials flew
into St. Croix before the storm, but relief flights were unable to
reach the hardest-hit islands Thursday as airports could not
re-open because of high winds.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, Lenny was another blow for a region that has been
ravaged by hurricanes over the past decade, including powerful
Hurricane Hugo in 1989, Marilyn in 1995, Georges in 1998 and a
weak-but-pesky Jose earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny was the eighth hurricane of 1999 and the fifth major
storm. Weather experts rate hurricanes as major when they reach
Category 3, meaning winds of at least 111 mph. Such storms are
capable of extensive damage.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny caught many normally storm-wary islanders off-guard. With
hurricane season winding down toward its Nov. 30 close and the
winter tourist season gearing up, many believed the storm _ which
formed out of a blob of disturbed weather near Jamaica early in the
week _ wouldn't amount to much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It snuck up on us so fast,'' said John Stout, who teaches at
the University of the Virgin Islands on St. Croix. ``We prepared
for a (Category) One or Two.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix was battered terribly by Hugo in 1989, with some 90
percent of the island's buildings damaged. If there was any luck
with Lenny for the 55,000 residents, it was that the storm struck
the island's south coast, which is less populated than the central,
hilly spine and the north coast.
</P>
<P>
   A giant oil refinery on the south shore run by Hovensa LLC was
shut down Tuesday as the storm approached but reportedly suffered
only minor damage.
</P>
<P>
   On the north coast in Christiansted, there were reports of
flooding and damage to the roof of one hotel. But some telephones
were working, and many residents felt things could've been much
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, they just wished Lenny would finally move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're okay at the hotel, but it was very bad on the south
shore,'' said a clerk at the Buccaneer Hotel near Christiansted,
reached by telephone. ``It's still blowing. The hurricane is still
just sitting there.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
