<HEADER>
A4216 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-FELICIA'S-JOURNE     11-18 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FELICIA'S-JOURNEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FELICIA'S JOURNEY' LEADS AWAY FROM INNOCENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Felicia's Journey'' suggests a depth of directing skill that
one might not have expected from Atom Egoyan (''The Sweet
Hereafter, Exotica''). Sure, he's used a splintered storytelling
style to layer the events that bring together his protagonists, a
tortured leading man (Bob Hoskins this time) and a suffering young
woman, Felicia (Elaine Cassidy). It's another story of innocence
lost, as embodied by a young girl. But Egoyan's fascination with
that theme plays here as much less of a downer. It's as if getting
out of Canada _ his native land, where he's made his previous films
_ has done him some good.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Hilditch (Hoskins) lives his life as a poseur. He runs a
food-processing factory in Birmingham, England, tasting all the
dishes that the plant sends into the marketplace. ``Food is love,''
he says, with a forced twinkle, and his full jowls and stocky frame
indicate that he's had a lot of love. As we learn in flashbacks,
too much love. His mother (Arsinee Khanjian) was a famous TV
cooking-show host and was stuffing him like a Christmas goose,
insulating Hilditch in a world that seemed to be made of tomato
aspic and pink icing _ a world he still inhabits. Every night, he
goes home and prepares a meal that could feed all of London,
following the directions of his late mother _ he watches her on
video _ to the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine _ she's the archetypal Irish slip of a lass _ can't
enforce innocence in her life. The young man who seduces her _
offering her the affection she can't get from her stern father _
disappears, telling her he's leaving Ireland for England to seek
work. But the boy's family _ and the entire countryside _ disown
him; he's gone off to join the British army. Her dogged search for
her lost lover leads Felicia to an area near Hilditch's factory.
Hilditch takes the forlorn young woman in, beginning the
cat-and-mouse game that Hilditch is addicted to playing with
desperate, lost runaway girls.
</P>
<P>
   By toying with irony, instead of clinging to the spiritual
desolation that marks all of his other work, Egoyan has made a much
more compelling film. Hilditch and Felicia need to be saved more
than anything, but mordant humor gives ``Felicia's Journey'' a
resonance his work hasn't had before. Generally, Egoyan's films are
easy to shake off _ the misery is too meticulously coordinated. But
there are a few offbeat moments that aren't as laboriously worked
out, a sign that he's developing as a writer and director. (He
adapted the film from a novel by William Trevor and fleshed it out
in a way Russell Banks' ``Hereafter'' apparently didn't allow for.)
Hoskins is remarkably subtle; he's not an actor who works totally
from the head, and his full-bodied investment in the role gives
presence and weight to the film. Let's hope Egoyan uses him again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicia's Journey'' is rated PG-13 for adult language, adult
situations and violence.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
