<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COX-SPORTS-PARENTS19     11-18 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-SPORTS-PARENTS19 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fla. soccer league requires parents to be good sports
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A local athletic association has a novel
idea for the 6,000 kids in its youth leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Make good sportsmanship mandatory _ for the parents.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Jan. 1, parents who want their children to play in one
of Jupiter-Tequesta Athletic Association's six sports must take a
half-hour course in how to behave at a youth league game and must
sign a code of parental ethics.
</P>
<P>
   If a parent doesn't attend the class (and pay the $5 fee), his
or her child doesn't play.
</P>
<P>
   The JTAA is the first youth group in the nation to require
parents to attend an ethics class, although 23 other leagues from
Minnesota to Texas will encourage parents to attend volunteer
sessions offered by the Parents Association for Youth Sports, based
in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea because a lot of parents open their
mouths a little too much with their opinions,'' said 14-year-old
Nicole Balogh, who plays softball, basketball and soccer in JTAA
leagues. ``In some cases they hurt the players' feelings. They put
other players down.''
</P>
<P>
   She's talking not only of parents of other teams' players, but
also of parents of her teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to try to de-escalate the intensity that's being
shown by the parents at these games,'' said Jeff Leslie, JTAA
president and father of four. ``Parents are losing their
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my knowledge, we've never had a parent physical
confrontation, but we've had parent shouting matches,'' he said.
The JTAA's action highlights the growing national problem of
violence in youth sports, often among coaches and parents, but even
between players.
</P>
<P>
   Many youth leagues require their coaches to attend four- or
six-hour certification courses that show coaches how to work with
children. The courses emphasize player health, safety, the role of
a coach and the skills involved in their particular sport. To
complete certification, coaches must also sign an ethics pledge to
avoid confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Engh, who pioneered coaching certification in 1981, said
the parental ethics class is merely the next step. ``It's finally
come to this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stories of parents screaming at coaches, other parents and
players are legion and more frequent in recent years, said Engh,
who is president and founder of the National Youth Sports Alliance,
the parent of PAYS.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hat's off to Jupiter. Ultimately this will benefit millions
of children in this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He blames parents prompting kids to specialize in one sport too
early after those parents read about major league pitchers with $84
million contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a kid's bat costs $250, a parent expects that kid to hit
the ball,'' said Jupiter Recreation Director Russ Ruskay, who
supports the parental ethics plan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Jupiter-Tequesta plan, at least one parent per family
must watch a 19-minute video, go over a parents' handbook and sign
the Parents Code of Ethics. For their $5, parents will receive a
PAYS newsletter quarterly and get a coupon for a medium pizza at a
Jupiter Pizza Hut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to create peer pressure among the parents,'' Leslie
said. Organizers anticipate some opposition from parents who use
youth sports as a baby-sitting service and who might be reluctant
to attend the classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many parents might think they don't need it, but you can see
yourself in this video,'' said Nicole's mother, Cindy Balogh, who
heads the JTAA softball league and has three sports-playing
children.
</P>
<P>
   Other leagues have taken a less drastic approach. The Soccer
Association of Boca Raton compels parents and coaches to sign a
code of conduct designed to protect children from overbearing,
hyper-competitive adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they act up, we just show them the form and say, `Is that
your signature?''' said Andy Goddard, head of the association for
3,000 kids. ``I tell everyone that we put the kids first and the
parents and coaches are second. That kind of puts everything in
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Trebor Banstetter, Joe Brogan, Shannon
Colavecchio, Sarah Eisenhauer, Angie Francalancia, Molly
Hennessy-Fiske, Howie Paul Hartnett and Clay Lambert contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
