<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4223 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-Y2K-FRAUD-HNS &LR;      11-18 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-FRAUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT WARNS CONSUMERS ABOUT Y2K SCAMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Con artists, relying on public fears of potential
Y2K-related computer glitches, might call consumers with tales of
financial doom this holiday season in an effort to get their
credit-card and account information, the Justice Department warned
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr. said the agency has
received an undisclosed number of reports of telephone calls from
people purporting to be from banks, credit-card companies and even
the Internal Revenue Service. The schemers say they need the
consumer's personal information due to so-called Y2K computer
problems that might erase financial data on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem refers to the threat of Jan. 1 malfunctions by
computers and other high-tech consumer goods created in the late
1900s that have not been programmed to read 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Federal, state and local governments as well as companies have
spent great time and expense to ensure that their high-tech
equipment continues to operate after the new year. But many
household goods also have date-dependent programs that might be
affected, such as television sets and central heating and
air-conditioning systems.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the public's concern with this potential difficulty next
year, con artists posing as bankers have called to say, ``We've got
Y2K problems here at the bank and we need your account number so we
can move your money into a special account or bond fund to protect
it while we fix the problem,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, false credit-card agents have told customers that
their cards' magnetic stripes are not ``Y2K compliant'' and that
the ``agents'' need the card numbers so they can send replacement
stripes to be put over the old ones, Holder added.
</P>
<P>
   Callers have also said, ``I'm with the IRS, and we're conducting
a computer test because of Y2K problems. We need your Social
Security number to confirm your identification,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once armed with this personal information, con artists can tap
into the victims' bank and credit-card accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Holder said he suspects the problem of Y2K telemarketing fraud
will increase as the new year approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not seen a major upswing in the number of complaints
about Y2K fraud, but we are anticipating that as we get closer to
the end of this year more criminals will try to con consumers, and
(we) want consumers to know what to look for and how to respond to
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holder added that old people and individuals who have already
fallen for telephone scams might be especially vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen clear evidence yet that they are targeting
just the elderly,'' Holder said of the con artists. ``But
certainly, some telemarketing outfits will have ... lists that are
heavily focused on the older population and people who have been
scammed before and that may give them more of a vehicle to target
the elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the Justice Department has a history of prosecuting
telephone fraud, Holder said the agency is well-prepared to handle
the Y2K cons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we may be entering the 21st century, but these schemes are
just dressed up old-fashioned telemarketing fraud in high-tech
clothing,'' he said. ``But old-fashioned or high-tech telemarketing
fraud is a federal crime with very stiff penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   To combat the fraud, the department instructs visitors to its
Internet site at www.usdoj.gov to be wary of unknown callers
seeking information related to money. The agency tells people who
suspect potential telemarketing fraud to call the National Fraud
Information Center at 800-876-7060 or the Federal Trade Commission
Consumer Response Center at 202-382-4357 or 202-326-3128.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a general proposition, consumers should always take the
time to investigate carefully any request or demand for money that
any telemarketer makes, and should never be rushed or forced into
making a hasty decision,'' the department states.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
