<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Nov. 21,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COPELAND-2000 (Undated) _ Aaron Copland, born in a tenement flat
two floors above the dry goods store his Jewish Lithuanian father
ran in Brooklyn, N.Y., would have been 100 on November 14 next
year. And the country Copland loved, the only country he ever felt
comfortable in, with the possible exception of Mexico, has already
started the party. Some 200 events, presented by institutions
ranging from the Philadelphia Orchestra, to Martha Graham Dance
Company, to the U.S. Army Field Band, to the Etowah Youth Orchestra
in Gasden, Alabama will be part of an international commemoration
called ``Copland 2000,'' spearheaded by the composer's ever
vigilant and eternally grateful publishing house, Boosey &AMP; Hawkes.
By Anthony Tommasini. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MODERN-MUSEUM-ART (New York) _ ``Modern Starts: People, Places
and Things,'' is the first of three enormous shows with which the
Museum of Modern Art is fanning the siecle, as it were, while also
examining its unparalleled collection and the way it has
historically been shaped and presented. (``Places'' and ``Things''
are on view through March 14, ``People'' through Feb. 1.) With some
additions fore and aft, ``Modern Starts,'' concentrates on
1880-1920 (the second part, opening in March, looks at 1920-1960;
the third, which arrives next fall, at 1960-2000.) Its organizing
team, headed by John Elderfield, chief curator-at-large, and Peter
Reed, the curator of the department of design and architecture,
decided to abandon the familiar narrative, or any narrative at all,
and let art history take the hindmost. By Roberta Smith. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOFFMAN-FILMS (Undated) _ Philip Seymour Hoffman, 32, the stocky
blond character actor from the suburbs of Rochester, N.Y., who at
the moment seems a candidate to become the last hot actor of the
20th century. OK, OK, that's sort of a trick; the clock is ticking
fast, and there's no new Skeet Ulrich with a film about to pop out
of the pipeline, and being the last anything of the century is
quite a matter of chance. But it is true that Hoffman is going to
end the year in sensational style, appearing in three
buzz-generating movies _ along with ``Flawless,'' in which he
appears opposite Robert De Niro, he is in Paul Thomas Anderson's
``Magnolia'' and Anthony Minghella's ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.''
Hoffman is not likely to cop a People magazine cover in the next
couple of weeks, but by January, an awful lot of people are going
to know who he is. By Jamie Malanowski. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-VIDEO-DISC (Undated) _ It's odd about DVD. With three
million players in use, the digital video disc has emerged as the
fastest growing format ever, and that includes the audio CD and the
videocassette. Yet, according to one industry study, 40 percent of
the American public doesn't know what DVD is. By Peter M. Nichols.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRICE-THEATER (New York) _ Though I saw the original production
of Arthur Miller's ``The Price'' with Pat Hingle and Arthur Kennedy
as the brothers, I have no memory of being as moved and as
peculiarly cheered by it as I was by the current production. As
staged at the Royal Theater by James Naughton (a Tony winner for
his grand performance as Billy Flynn in ``Chicago'', this
``Price,'' like Michael Mayer's recent production of ``A View From
the Bridge,'' realizes all of the text's dangerous tensile
strength. It is both immensely satisfying and, in a way that
straight plays are not often cited for, entertaining. By Vincent
Canby. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   LION-KING-THEATER (London) _ Of all the current theater plays in
London, what has left even The Sunday Times's intellectually
rigorous John Peter crying ``wonderful, wonderful'' is Julie
Taymor's restaging of her Broadway production of Disney's ``Lion
King'' at the Lyceum Theater: a judgment confirmed by reports that
the show is booking until next September and that some Londoners
are mortgaging their mothers to meet the prices the scalpers are
asking for seats. By Benedict Nightingale. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TOGETHER-THEATER (New York) _ Bob Morris talks with Carol
Burnett and Ruthie Henshall, who are appearing together in the
revue ``Putting It Together,'' which opens Sunday at the Ethel
Barrymore Theater in a new production of the Stephen Sondheim song
collection. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BALLET-HISPANICO (New York) _ When Tina Ramirez established the
Ballet Hispanico school and company in 1970, it was a revolutionary
act. Hispanics not only had few dance schools, they also had
trouble getting into dance companies, an almost unimaginable
situation now with the dazzling Hispanic dancers in mainstream
ballet and modern companies. This fall Ms. Ramirez and her
groundbreaking enterprise won two major honors. In September, she
received the Hispanic Heritage Award for Education at the Kennedy
Center in Washington. Since its founding, almost 10,000 children
have studied at the Ballet Hispanico School, which now enrolls 600
students yearly for classes in Spanish, modern and jazz dance and
ballet. By Valerie Gladstone. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-DANCE (Undated) _ There could be little argument that
``A Celebration of 100 Years of American Dance on Film'' was one of
the most wildly improbable dance events of 1999. But the program
also suggested profound changes in the nature of dance in America,
and in the relationship between dance and the electronic media. By
Jennifer Dunning. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FELDMAN-MUSIC (Undated) _ After the Flux Quartet's recent
premiere performance of Morton Feldman's String Quartet No. 2 in
its complete six-hour version, the three orchestral works on a new
Feldman disc seem like Webernian essays in atomistic compression.
Feldman wrote few works for orchestra, yet in the three works here
_ ``Coptic Light,'' ``Piano and Orchestra'' and ``Cello and
Orchestra'' (Argo 448 513-2; CD) _ the more varied palette provides
an ideal entry point into his unique sound world, less daunting and
ascetic than the composer's chamber music. By Lawrence A. Johnson.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDNITE-VULTURES-ALBUM (Undated) _ Laughter is the immediate
response to most of the songs on Beck Hansen's fifth album,
``Midnite Vultures'' _ so much so that it could be called a comedy
record. But it's a comedy record in the sense that intelligent
directors make comedy films: it's one big aesthetic disposition,
rather than the series of bulletlike jokes on what are commonly
called comedy records by the likes of Adam Sandler and Chris Rock.
``Midnite Vultures'' is funny without making actual jokes. By Ben
Ratliff. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIAL-ART (Undated) _ Millennial thinking resonates through
American politics, from Manifest Destiny to the ``vision thing''
any presidential hopeful is still required to spin out. It has
always been there in high art: in the nationalist allegories of
Hudson River School landscape painting, in Social Realism with its
demand for a new order, in Abstract Expressionism with its
commitment to the sublime. And nowhere is millennialism more
consistently explored than in vernacular culture. This fact makes
``Millennial Dreams: Vision and Prophecy in American Folk Art,''
organized by Gerald C. Wertkin at the Museum of American Folk Art
through May 14, one of the few genuinely timely museum offerings of
the season. By Holland Cotter. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MUFFLER-MEN-ART (Los Angeles) _ Produced by mechanics in the
shops where they work, muffler men are being made as advertising
art, proliferating as roadside attractions outside the shops
throughout the Los Angeles metropolitan area. Their makers _ most
are Hispanic _ repaint them frequently to keep them looking shiny
new. But they weather fast, lasting for no more than a couple of
years. So far, very few figures appear to have survived long enough
to show up in flea markets and art shows, and that may explain why
most people have no idea what muffler men are. Now muffler men are
moving into the world of art. In an exhibition at the Fowler Museum
of Cultural History at the University of California at Los Angeles,
``Muffler Men, Munecos and Other Welded Wonders,'' is the first
museum exhibition devoted entirely to these figures. On display
through April 28 are 34 metal images of people, space creatures and
animals. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MARY-AND-RHODA (New York) _ From 1970 to 1977, as Mary
Richards and Rhoda Morgenstern, Mary Tyler Moore and Valerie Harper
made ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' one of the most successful
series in television history. Now they are back together making
``Mary and Rhoda,'' an ABC television movie that began as an idea
for a series and may yet lead to one. In the film, Mary and Rhoda
reconnect in New York, where they both have daughters in college.
By Peter M. Nichols. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-RADIO (New York) _ As the WNYC radio station celebrates its
75th anniversary, it faces not only continued high payments for its
broadcasting license but a backbreaking 200 percent hike in charges
from National Public Radio for syndication of several programs,
including the acclaimed news and feature series ``Morning Edition''
and ``All Things Considered.'' The miracle is that they seem to be
pulling it off. By Valerie Gladstone. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
