<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4237 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-HOMEDEPOT19-COX     11-18 0237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot splits stock, raises dividend 50%
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot shareholders can stop biting their nails.
</P>
<P>
   After months of anticipation, the Atlanta-based retailer
announced a 3-for-2 stock split on Thursday. Home Depot also
increased its quarterly dividend 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company said stockholders of record on Dec. 2 will be issued
1.5 shares for each share held. Those additional stocks will be
distributed Dec. 30. After the split, the number of shares
outstanding will increase to about 2.22 billion from about 1.48
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Following the news, Home Depot stock closed at a 52-week high of
$83.50, up $3.56 1/4. The stock has risen 36 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Stock splits do not affect the value of investors' holdings;
they are akin to slicing the same pie into more pieces. But
historically, companies that split their stock see a greater price
gain over time than those that don't.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming split will be the 13th for Home Depot since it sold
shares to the public in 1981. The last, a 2-for-1 split, came on
May 27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly cash dividend was raised to 6 cents per pre-split
share from 4 cents, payable Dec. 16 to stockholders of record on
Dec. 2. The dividend is equal to 4 cents per share after the split.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
