<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETOOL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Second chance for specialty tools
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do-it-yourselfers, you know the drill all too well.
</P>
<P>
   The remodeled kitchen looks great. The new bathroom is gorgeous.
But the garage is a bulging graveyard of specialty tools you'll
never use again.
</P>
<P>
   There's a second chance for those tile cutters and wet saws at
ReTool in Kennesaw, on Cobb Parkway. ReTool, which opened its first
store in metro Atlanta this week, aims to put a recycled spin on
the growing home improvement market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to sell a tool that you don't need, instead of
just letting it gather dust in the basement or the garage,'' said
ReTool owner Ben Boston
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that philosophy is the soul of ReTool, where
do-it-yourselfers can buy, sell and trade anything from jig saws to
jumper cables. The store, set up to look like a chock-full
workshop, sells hand tools, power tools and shop tools. There's
plenty of goods for mechanics and contractors, too.
</P>
<P>
   ReTool is a new franchise from Minneapolis-based Grow Biz
International, which calls itself the largest resale company in the
country. Its other concepts include Play It Again Sports, Music Go
Round and Computer Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of ReTool is the price, said Boston, who owns and
operates the shop with his wife, Cindy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tools sell for a fraction of their original cost, he
said. For example, a used Craftsman belt sander may sell for $35,
about half the original price tag. Hammers go for less than five
bucks, and $1 can get a used screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 percent of ReTool's merchandise is bought from
individuals. The rest comes from factory overruns or closeouts.
Some tools are reconditioned.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other Grow Biz chains, ReTool is designed for a
national rollout. The franchise will end the year with a dozen
stores in the East and Midwest. Ultimately, there's room for 500
stores or more across the country, said Ted Manley, president and
chief operating officer of Grow Biz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard in the franchising business to predict (growth),
because you have to find the right owners to operate the stores
first,'' Manley said. The cost to open a ReTool is between $110,000
and $161,000. Grow Biz gets 4 percent of the store's gross sales.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, an avid woodworker, gave up a long-time job at Columbian
Chemicals in Marietta to run the ReTool shop. Tired of nonstop
traveling, Boston spotted an ad for the franchise in a woodworking
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this spring, the couple combed hundreds of garage
sales, sometimes as many as 30 in a day, to gather enough inventory
to open the store. Now most of the merchandise will come from
individuals, the Bostons said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ReTool will certainly get some of the same customers
that Home Depot, Lowe's and Sears does, Boston does not see the
giant chains as competition. If anything, they're good for
business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at some of the brands in here,'' Boston said, pointing to
a wall of used power drills, mostly found at garage sales. ``Most
of this stuff originally came from Home Depot or Lowe's. ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
