<HEADER>
A4241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FEDBUD-MYSTERY-1119-C     11-18 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDBUD-MYSTERY-1119-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VOTING IN THE DARK TO SPEND $390 BILLION: NO ONE IS SURE WHAT'S
INCLUDED
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Strewn around an office just off the floor of the
House of Representatives Thursday were bits and pieces of a $390
billion budget to run much of the U.S. civilian government.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists, congressional aides and reporters stood
elbow-to-elbow, poring over a single copy of the 11-inch high
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   With voting on the measure just hours away, even the lawmakers
could not say for sure what lurked in its thousands of pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I defy you to tell me what's in it,'' declared Rep. David
Obey, D-Wisc. on the House floor. As ranking Democrat on the
appropriations committee that wrote the bill, he was in a better
position to know than most.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he told his colleagues, ``Long after this bill is done,
we will be trying to find out what's in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainty about the contents, the bill passed the
House 296-135 and headed for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   More than a month behind schedule, negotiators for the House,
Senate and White House had struck the concluding deals in the early
hours of Thursday morning. The bill wrapped five of the 13 annual
appropriations bills that remained to be enacted into one
``omnibus'' piece of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   If many of the final details were still not yet evident, the
general character of the giant spending bill was plain: It included
something for every state and, most particularly, for the districts
of the key congressional members of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   By a preliminary count, the Labor and Health and Human Services
part of the legislation had 152 items that lawmakers had
``earmarked'' for their home districts. That's more than double the
62 counted last year by the office of Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a
self-assigned watchdog for such ``pork-barrelling'' by his
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Notations on the spending bill showed pages of typed add-ons and
dollar amounts crossed out and, in most cases, replaced by bigger
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   For conservatives who had hoped that the Republican-controlled
Congress would trim back government, the bill is the latest
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans did pretty well in the first few years they took
over Congress,'' said Marshall Wittmann (cq), congressional analyst
at the conservative Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, they've now lapsed into the old ways of doing
business in Washington, which is, spend for your district, protect
your seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the the spending bill, Wittmann said, ``It's easier
to find Pokemon cards than spending cuts in this bill.'' He
ridiculed the 0.38 percent spending rollback for most government
program _ less than a half penny per dollar.
</P>
<P>
   However, Coburn said what bothered him was that Congress did not
roll back its own $4,600 raise. As of Jan. 1, members will make
$141,300 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to change that,'' the Oklahoma lawmaker said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted it would take days before he and other budget
watchers can grasp all that's in the spending legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In one margin of the drafted agreement was typed, without
elaboration: ``$2 million for the University of Mississippi
phytomedical project; $500,000 for Alaska aviation safety
initiative.'' Mississippi is represented by Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, a Republican. And Alaska's senior senator is Ted
Stevens, a Republican who chairs the Senate Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Another item, listed on an added page, was ``$2 million for
Lawton Chiles Foundation,'' honoring the late Florida governor and
U.S. senator, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
