<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4246 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-ROCKETTES-LOS-ANGELES     11-18 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKETTES-LOS-ANGELES-PERFORMANCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETTES KICK IT IN LOS ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Not for use before Sunday, Nov. 21) 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the holiday season, and that means the No. 1 live show in
America comes to Los Angeles. Is it ``Cats''? No. ``The Lion
King''? Think again. The real high-steppin' kings... er, queens...
of the stage are the Radio City Rockettes, whose Radio City
Christmas Spectacular has become a multicity record breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an amazing total of 2 million people in New York, Los
Angeles, Chicago, Detroit, Branson (Mo.) and Myrtle Beach (S.C.)
attended the show, bringing its gross to $83 million. At the
Universal Amphitheatre, the show broke all records for such past
top shows as ``Jesus Christ, Superstar'' and ``Tommy.''
</P>
<P>
   In its second year in L.A., the Radio City extravaganza _ with
more than 50 on-stage performers _ is making a few changes. The
most important one may be that, in addition to live animals, the
show now features live musicians rather than canned music. The use
of tape instead of an orchestra last year caused an uproar among
the musicians' union.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Espinosa, president of Professional Musicians Local 47, says
this year's show will be better for everyone now that musicians are
included. ``When you hear a live orchestra, you don't just hear the
difference, you feel the difference,'' he said. ``I think Los
Angeles audiences are becoming more savvy about what they're
getting. ... When they pay $60 for a show, they expect to get the
works, including a live orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for kids, it's especially great. They get to see musicians
playing on instruments. It really is educational.''
</P>
<P>
   Other new twists include presenting three Los Angeles shows in
Spanish, giving Santa a larger role in the show, spiffing up the
costumes and making it ``snow'' inside the theater. Howard Kolins,
executive producer of the Christmas Spectacular, says it's these
kinds of updates and tweaks that he hopes will make the show a hit
with L.A. audiences for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles is considered to be a place where tradition
doesn't stick,'' said New York-based Kolins, ``But I'd like to
think we can get into the heart of every (Angeleno).''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Los Angeles will never catch up with New York in terms of
the longevity of the show: There, it has run every year since 1933.
Kolins attributes the show's popularity to its cross-generational
appeal and its status as a New York legend. ``It's truly a family
show. No one feels put out that they've had to tolerate the show to
make someone else happy,'' Kolins said. ``Plus, it becomes a
tradition among families who may have seen it in New York, or just
heard about it and now can see it in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Hodges, senior vice president of House of Blues Concerts
(formerly Universal Concerts), agrees that the show's broad
demographics are the secret of its blockbuster appeal. ``It's
certainly been record-breaking for us,'' Hodges said. ``We've
gotten a mixture of people _ some who've been here before, and some
who haven't, both locals and tourists. And from what we've heard
from the retailers and the studio tour people,'' Hodges said,
``They've done great because of the show, too.''
</P>
<P>
   With 53 performances this year, the Christmas Spectacular at
Universal will be hard to miss. But if you're looking to make it a
tradition among your own family, it's best to buy early: Strong
group sales and the reduced number of seats for these shows (3,300
rather than the Amphitheatre's usual 6,000) due to the lavish
nature of the production means that tickets for the most popular
nights do go fast.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Radio City Christmas Spectacular runs Dec. 1-28 at the
Universal Amphitheatre, 100 Universal City Plaza, Universal City.
Performances will be presented in Spanish Dec. 12, 20 (matinee) and
26. Tickets ($22.50 to $63.50) available through the Universal
Amphitheatre Main and CityWalk box offices, online at
www.jobconcerts.com, at all Ticketmaster outlets or by calling
Ticketmaster at (213) 252-(8497).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
