<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-EDUCATION-AUDIT-1stLE     11-18 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-AUDIT-1st </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 LEDE19-COX &HT;    EDUCATION DEPARTMENT MESSES UP ITS ACCOUNTING
 &HT;    FIXES GRAF 2 subbing ``financial statements'' for ``financial
systems''
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard Riley admitted Thursday
that his department had flunked its audit for the 1998 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The department ``lacked adequate financial management systems,
reports and oversight to prepare timely and accurate financial
statements,'' concluded Ernst &AMP; Young LLP, the big accounting firm
hired by the department's inspector general to audit the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working hard on the (fiscal year) 1999 audit to be
released in March 2000, and we're hoping it will show clear
progress,'' Riley told reporters. The department oversees more than
$70 billion a year in spending on operating costs and on loans and
grants to students, schools, school districts, contractors and
states.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said the biggest problem was that the department purchased
a new computerized general ledger system that doesn't work right.
He said that contributed to two other problems: the department's
failure to meet deadlines for supplying reliable information to the
auditors, and its inability to comply with new accounting
requirements that went into effect for the first time in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat wistfully, he noted that the clean audit report
received by the department the previous year had been the first in
its three decades of existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 12 years of the Reagan-Bush administration, the department
had never received an unqualified (clean) audit opinion,'' recalled
Riley, who came into office alongside President Clinton in 1993.
``We undertook a comprehensive effort to improve financial
management and last year ended up with the first unqualified audit
opinion in the department's history, covering 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   That accomplishment was ballyhooed at the time. But this year
the department disclosed little despite constant complaints by Rep.
Peter Hoekstra, R-Mich., about delays in releasing the audit, which
was supposed to be finished in March.
</P>
<P>
   The audit report was sent to Congress Thursday by the
department's office of inspector general. From the report, it
appears that department officials repeatedly convinced the auditors
to give them more time to reduce the number of conflicts between
various sets of books.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a half-billion-dollar transaction had been recorded
backwards, with the result that the books were off by more than $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are troubling, and Mr. Hoekstra and other members
of his subcommittee will no doubt be looking at it when Congress
returns in January,'' said Dan Lara, spokesman for the House
Committee on Education and the Workforce.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, the president's domestic adviser, Bruce
Reed, said he knew the audit report had been delayed, but did not
know that the auditors had refused to certify that the books were
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Secretary Riley's done an excellent job of making the
department work,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
