<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-ISLAMIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSLIMS DISPUTE INTERPRETATION OF CO-PILOT'S PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Islamic scholars cautioned Thursday that the phrase
``I put my trust in God'' that was spoken by the co-pilot on
EgyptAir's fatal Flight 990 does not prove he intentionally caused
the plane to crash into the Atlantic Ocean on Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``This phrase is incredibly common and shows nothing about the
intent of the pilot,'' said Ibrahim Hooper, the national
communications director of the Council on American-Islamic
Relations, an advocacy group here.
</P>
<P>
   Revelations that the prayer was uttered by Egyptian pilot Gameel
al-Batouti just before the plane began a steep dive have prompted
some investigators to suspect that he intentionally caused the
Boeing 767 jetliner to crash.
</P>
<P>
   All 217 people on board died when the plane plunged into the
ocean off the coast of Massachusetts. Cockpit voice recorders
recovered after the crash revealed that Batouti said the Arabic
prayer ``Tawakaltu ala Allah,'' which has been translated into ``I
put my trust in God.''
</P>
<P>
   But Islamic scholars argue that Arabic speakers in Egypt and
other countries often use such prayers and phrases before doing
many everyday tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Imam Mohammed al-Hanooti, former Imam of Dar al-Hijrah Mosque in
Falls Church, Va., said that for religious Muslims, God is involved
in almost every single decision and action in life, which leads
them to say prayers throughout the day for guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said the same thing as the pilot this morning before I
started my car and before I came into this room to speak with
you,'' Hanooti said, adding that ``if the pilot was a typical
Muslim, it wouldn't be at all surprising that he said this prayer
while in the cockpit where there are many tasks to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the prayer, which can be translated into
several English versions, was a key reason that the National
Transportation Safety Board, the federal agency that investigates
airline crashes, considered turning the investigation over to the
FBI. But Egyptian officials, fearing that the Americans may be
misinterpreting the meaning of the prayer, asked U.S. investigators
to step back and let the Egyptians interpret the phrase.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hooper, the many interpretations offered by
American newspapers and television networks of the phrase and its
meaning have confused the debate _ and angered many Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
   In USA Today and on several television networks, the phrase was
translated as ``I made my decision now. I put my faith in God's
hands.'' Other newspapers interpreted the meaning as ``There is no
God but Allah and Mohammed is Allah's messenger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These interpretations simply aren't correct, and they make the
phrase appear sinister when in reality it's not,'' Hooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Yousri Hani, a professor of Islamic studies at Al Azhar
University in Cairo, said the fact that Batouti said a prayer while
in the cockpit actually argues against his attempting suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a religious Muslim would utter this phrase, and since
suicide is one of the worst things a Muslim can do, it doesn't make
sense that this religious man would do something so blasphemous,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hani said a Muslim who was about to commit an act of destruction
would have far stronger phrases to use. ``This prayer is for doing
constructive, everyday things, not a final prayer before death,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hooper admitted that Batouti could have been responsible for
the plane's crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to say what happened on that plane,'' he
said. ``We just want to clear up a cultural misunderstanding so
that this misunderstanding doesn't fill in for fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanooti said the possibility that Batouti was mentally unsound
existed but that the Islamic religion should not be blamed for the
actions of ``one man who no longer knew right from wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
