<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4273 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-DSL-RULING-BOS &LR;      11-18 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DSL-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES HAIL FEDERAL RULING ON HIGH-SPEED INTERNET LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Companies that compete with Bell Atlantic to sell the intensely
popular digital subscriber line high-speed Internet access service
hailed a federal ruling Thursday they said will help them move even
faster to roll out DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   DSL offers Net connections with download speeds 50 to 125 times
faster than dial-up modems by enhancing the carrying capacity of
the standard copper telephone wires that serve the vast majority of
homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, companies such as HarvardNet, Covad Communications,
NorthPoint and Rhythms must pay to have Bell Atlantic install a
second standard phone line for customers, which is then outfitted
for DSL. Bell Atlantic, however, can add the DSL service to current
customers' existing voice lines, giving it a big head start and
cost advantage over rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC announced Thursday that beginning in six to nine months,
it will order local phone incumbents such as Bell Atlantic to share
their home and business lines with rivals, with the price to be
worked out by state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Washburn, president and CEO of HarvardNet of Charlestown,
Mass., the leading non-Bell DSL provider in New England, called the
FCC ruling ``a watershed event. This ruling will establish a level
playing field on price, letting us compete for new customers on the
basis of our superior service alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn predicted the move will cut DSL installation and
monthly fees, now $150 to $300 for typical business customers, by
probably 20 percent each of the next two years and allow his
company to begin moving into the residential market, which has been
prohibitively expensive to crack so far. HarvardNet serves about
one-quarter of New England and is moving into New York.
</P>
<P>
   Annabel Z. Dodd, a Northeastern University instructor and author
of ``The Essential Guide to Telecommunications,'' said the FCC
ruling ``opens up the residential DSL market to competition. Up
until now, Bell Atlantic has pretty much had the field to itself
and competed with cable modems.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, about 200,000 DSL lines are estimated to be in
service, compared to about 1 million cable modems such as
MediaOne's RoadRunner service. An FCC board member, Susan Ness,
said that ``prices should decline (and) services should improve''
as a result of the agency's line-sharing order.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell Atlantic and some industry officials fear the FCC
ruling could lead to customer-service nightmares as people face
endless blame-shifting by two rival companies when their DSL lines
experience problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Wake, chief executive officer of Integral Access, a
Chelmsford-based start-up that provides equipment and systems for
delivering voice and data services over a single line, cautioned
that ``service providers will now need sophisticated management
systems to monitor phone line performance and identify the source
of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have two service providers sharing the same line, they
will need to know where the problem is and who is responsible for
fixing it, in order to avoid finger pointing and quickly re-connect
the service,'' Wake said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's vice president for regulatory affairs, Don Evans, said,
``We have concerns with regard to the impacts on consumers. We
didn't see that there was a need for making this kind of policy
judgment. If this is not implemented properly, consumers are going
to run into complications that will give them a bad experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC proposal calls for heavy fines against incumbent
companies such as Bell Atlantic that fail to live up to promises to
cooperate with rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But Dhruv Khanna, a co-founded and executive vice president of
Covad, based in Santa Clara, Calif., called the FCC ruling ``a
winning scenario for both consumers and the phone companies''
because it will help companies like Bell Atlantic increase local
competition, a key step towards re-entering the long distance
calling market.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling heat from RoadRunner, Bell plans to roll out DSL service
throughout Greater Boston by year's end, although it has faced
scattered complaints about delays and bureacratic headaches
installing service.
</P>
<P>
   One limitation to DSL is that it currently can reach only people
who live about 3 miles from a phone company ``central office.'' But
it has the benefit compared to cable modems that each DSL customer
gets a dedicated line instead of sharing capacity with neighbors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
