<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DIGITAL-FILM-ART-2TAK     11-18 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-FILM-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL VIDEO, IF WIDELY ACCEPTED, MAY TRANSFORM MOVIE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT24,25 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ A digital video camera was perched like a bazooka on
the shoulder of director Mike Figgis as he carved a path through
the oblivious pedestrians on Sunset Strip, following actor Stellan
Skarsgard into a swanky glass-faced office. At the same moment, not
far away, three other digital cameras were following other actors
as they made their way down the sidewalk, chatted on cell phones or
bickered at curbside, the real world swirling all around them.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever this film in progress might add up to artistically,
Figgis, the British director best known for the Oscar-winning
``Leaving Las Vegas,'' is at the very least extraordinarily
ambitious, some might say audacious, about exploiting the digital
technologies that are beginning to seep into the Hollywood
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   His film, ``Time Code 2000,'' is being shot in real time; that
is, as one continuous take, without editing, that lasts a
predetermined 93 minutes. The four cameras dance across a half
dozen sets and down city streets with a breathtaking seamlessness,
following the film's characters in and out of meetings,
assignations and confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis thought of doing the film just a few months ago, and he
said the digital technology would require only four to six weeks of
postproduction work instead of the typical several months, time
spent mostly fussing with the sound mix. The film potentially could
be available for theatrical release before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When it appears in theaters, he said, the images from all four
cameras will be shown simultaneously, either in horizontal strips
with four images shown from left to right or stacked two-atop-two,
allowing audiences to edit the film in their own heads as they
switch attention from one image to another and try to follow the
plot.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For years, digital moviemaking has been a grass-roots movement
among aspiring filmmakers who resented the dominance of the
Hollywood aesthetic. ``Time Code 2000'' brings the new technology
inside the walls of the major studios _ in this case, those of Sony
Pictures, which, not coincidentally, is owned by a company that
also manufactures digital equipment. Once inside the walls, many
believe, digital moviemaking will have a major impact on the way
movies are made and how people view them.
</P>
<P>
   Despite many predictions that digital technology will transform
the industry, its potential influence is still far from certain.
For one thing, many filmmakers are extremely resistant to using
digital video because of the flat, bland image that videotape often
produces, particularly in comparison with the richer images
recorded by film.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of converting to digital projection systems is also
formidable _ $100,000 per projector multiplied by the more than
34,000 screens in the United States alone _ and theater owners and
studios have very different ideas about who should pay the tab.
Meanwhile, even the adventurous Figgis must transfer his digital
tape to old-fashioned film so it can be projected by the machines
now in place.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, digital proponents remain exultant. ``It's a
revolution,'' said Rodger Raderman, chairman of iFilm, a San
Francisco-based company that distributes digital films on the
Internet. ``And I believe it's coming faster than most people
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Documentary filmmakers, in particular, have been at the
forefront, driven by economic necessity and a lack of interest from
the entertainment industry in financing their projects.
</P>
<P>
   Such respected directors as Penelope Spheeris and Spike Jonze
have done work in digital video, and earlier this month New Line
Cinema announced that it had signed a deal with Spike Lee to make
``Bamboozled,'' a movie entirely on digital video.
</P>
<P>
   When digital filmmaking's full potential is reached, a growing
number of people in the industry believe, it might even threaten a
studio power structure that has held firm since the advent of sound
and has absorbed such technological challenges as television and
VCRs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is beyond imagination what this is going to do to
filmmaking,'' said Figgis, whose roots are in music, theater and
experimental film. ``What has been an exclusive medium of high
finance, banking and financial exclusivity is now going to become
something that is within the reach of everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that even the most modestly financed filmmaker
could afford to shoot a movie and transmit it to theaters digitally
at little expense.
</P>
<P>
   This revolution, if that's what it is, is being driven by the
convergence of several technologies: relatively inexpensive digital
video cameras, only now becoming widely available; digital
projectors that eliminate the need for film; and the growing
ability of the Internet and other information pipelines to transmit
digital sounds and images to multiplexes, living rooms and computer
screens without reliance on a studio's expensive production and
distribution services.
</P>
<P>
   It may even become possible to distribute and market those films
effectively on the Internet if the example of this summer's ``Blair
Witch Project'' is a guidepost to the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole economics of the business are basically turned
upside down by digital technology,'' said Bruce Apar, editor in
chief of Video Business, a magazine published by Variety. ``It will
change the movie industry, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging technologies may push change even further. Some will
allow filmmakers to bypass not only film, but digital tape, making
it possible to shoot onto digital sticks, which resemble credit
cards, and computer disks, both of which break down images into
binary code. The images can be downloaded to a computer and
transmitted the same way that any other computer file is
transmitted. They can be edited on the computer screen,
extraordinary effects can be added and the resulting movie can be
sent by modem or satellite to any place in the world. Then theater
owners can download the movies and project them onto a screen with
the new generation of digital projectors.
</P>
<P>
   The financial savings can be considerable, even with available
digital equipment. Digital cameras cost a small fraction of what
film cameras cost, and prices are plummeting. New software allows
anyone to edit film on a home computer. There are no costs for
developing film, no need for reels of celluloid. Instead of paying
hundreds of thousands of dollars to make copies of a movie,
producers could make as many copies as necessary at the click of a
mouse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Figgis illustrated, picking up a small, hand-held camera that
was resting on a nearby chair. ``See this? It's a new,
state-of-the-art digital camera. Costs about $3,000,'' he said.
``I'd be using it on this movie except the tapes are only an hour
long and I need two hours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Code 2000'' is being made on a budget ``in the low
millions,'' Figgis said, about 5 percent of the $60 million that is
spent on the average major studio production. Most of his budget,
though, is going to pay the union wages of those working on the
film and for the handful of sets he is using.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were some young filmmaker in Ohio or someplace,'' Figgis
said, ``and I could use friends and shoot on found locations
instead of on sets, this movie, this very same movie, could be made
for about $100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgis' film looks little like the slick, visually sumptuous
films that Hollywood studios regularly produce. It is rapid, jerky
and definitely ragged around the edges, but Figgis believes that
moviegoers who accepted ``Blair Witch,'' which had many of the same
qualities, will accept his film, too.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of the new technology is most visible on the
proliferation of Internet sites devoted to digital films (even the
major studios have begun to get involved in this) and in the growth
of the microcinema movement, in which digital filmmakers exhibit
their work in cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction to filmmakers is only partly economic. It is also
artistic. Digital video makes filmmakers more mobile, better able
to shoot scenes without cocooning themselves in studios or at
on-site locations, freer to move through the bustle of real city
streets, even interacting with real people they encounter. For most
of the century, filmmakers have been restricted to shots of no
longer than 10 minutes, a length limited by the size of film
magazines. (A 20-minute magazine has recently become available.)
Digital cameras, however, can shoot and shoot and shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Studio executives, who acknowledge that the technology will
change their business, are not so sure that it will make them as
irrelevant as some filmmakers might hope. Studios, they argue, will
still be the marketplace where creative ferment produces the best
stories. And it will still be the studios _ and the surrounding
world of agents and producers _ that will retain control of the
copyrighted characters (think ``Batman'') and the top-name actors
who will be needed to make a movie, even a digital movie, rise
above the expected glut.
</P>
<P>
   By the time that production on ``Time Code 2000'' ends,
scheduled for Nov. 19, Figgis will have shot the film more than
seven times. Then he will choose the version he considers best.
</P>
<P>
   If his project feels a bit like a stunt, Figgis does not
disagree, though he prefers the term ``performance art.'' His movie
is intended, in part, to draw attention to the possibilities
created by digital technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is to have the film released, at least in a couple of
theaters, before the end of the year,'' he said. Columbia Pictures
has not decided whether it will release the film late this year or
early next year. What is telling, though, is that it is possible to
release a film so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be nice to have this look at the cinema of
the next century come out in the last week of this century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
