<HEADER>
A4279 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SUMMIT-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      11-18 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES YELTSIN TO HALT CHECHNYA BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ President Clinton publicly scolded his friend and
counterpart, Russian President Boris Yeltsin, in front of nearly 50
heads of state Thursday, saying the bombing of Chechnya threatens
``an endless cycle of violence'' that could hinder Russia's
post-Cold War integration into the world community.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin was defiant, saying Clinton and others ``have no right
to criticize Russia for Chechnya,'' and refusing to back down
during a private meeting with Clinton later. The Russian president
then walked out of the summit early, saying he had to get back to
Moscow to deal with the Chechnya situation.
</P>
<P>
   Other world leaders at the session of the Organization on
Security and Cooperation in Europe were more blunt than Clinton;
United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan, for example, called
Russia's behavior ``immoral and contradictory to humanitarian
international law.''
</P>
<P>
   But the American president got personal with the man Clinton has
described as his good friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Yeltsin, one of the most thrilling experiences of my
life as a citizen of the world before I became president was when
you stood up on that tank in Moscow, when they tried to take the
freedom of the Russian people away, and your standing there on that
tank said to those people, `You can do this, but you'll have to
kill me first,' '' Clinton said, wagging his finger at Yeltsin, who
was seated across the room in the ornate Ciragan Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had put you in jail instead of electing you president,
I would hope that every leader of every country around this table
would have stood up for you and for freedom in Russia and not said,
`Well, that is an internal Russian affair that we cannot be a part
of,' '' Clinton continued.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton's comments offended Yeltsin, he didn't show it
publicly. He gave Clinton a big bear hug before they entered their
private meeting, although the hour-long session produced no
agreement on Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very vigorous and so was I,'' Clinton told reporters
after the meeting. ``We have a very good personal chemistry, but it
didn't stop us from our clear disagreement here.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia took another hit later in the day when Clinton presided
over the signing of a deal to build an oil pipeline from Baku,
Azerbaijan, through Georgia to Ceyhan, Turkey. The pipeline would
take away some of Russia's control of the transport and sale of oil
from the Caspian Sea region.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin left a few hours ahead of schedule, leaving his
delegation behind to participate in the remainder of the summit.
The White House downplayed Yeltsin's early departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not him stomping out of the room,'' said National
Security Adviser Sandy Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Russia did agree to allow an observer mission from OSCE, formed
to keep disputes in the region from becoming armed conflicts, to go
to Chechnya, a concession the White House hopes could pave the way
for a later mediation by the organization between Moscow and
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also offered Yeltsin a a conciliatory gesture, saying
Russia ``has not only the right, but the obligation, to defend its
territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have often asked myself, as I hope all of you have, what I
would do if I were in President Yeltsin's place,'' Clinton
continued. ``I think before any of us sit in judgment, we should be
able to answer that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton warned, if Russia continues with its strategy in
Chechnya, ``the global integration Russia has rightly sought to
advance, with our strong support, will be hindered.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's condemnation of Yeltsin, along with his unwavering
defiance, underscores the difficulty the OSCE faces in dealing with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole hope of this thing was that it would bring everyone
inside the tent, so we don't have to worry about anyone making rips
from the outside,'' said Marshall Goldman, associate director of
the Davis Center for Russian Studies at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``But inside the tent, you've got this bear that hasn't been
housebroken. The hope, of course, is to co-opt them,'' Goldman
said. But Russia _ anxious to be considered a player in the
post-Cold War world _ isn't about to toady to the West, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin made that point abundantly clear Thursday, arguing that
the OSCE has no business telling Russia how to handle an internal
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin also accuses the United States of hypocrisy, noting that
NATO bombed a sovereign nation, Yugoslavia, when it sought to
combat Serbian attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, which is
Yugoslav territory.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton directly addressed that critique, saying the world
community had made a ``grievous error'' in waiting so long to act
during the ethnic conflict in Bosnia, but ``did the right thing''
in moving more quickly in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe there will ever be a time in human affairs
when we will ever be able to say (that) we simply cannot criticize
this or that . . . because it happened within the territorial
borders of a single nation,'' Clinton told the European leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The President meant to justify US action in Kosovo, but he was
also sending a subtle message that he did not want Chechnya to
become another Kosovo, said National Security Council spokesman
Mike Hammer later.
</P>
<P>
   The conundrum in both regions in similar. In both cases, the
presidents of Yugoslavia and Russia have insisted that they have
every right to bring down violent insurgents inside their borders.
The international community has struggled to balance its commitment
to the integrity of international borders with its desire to limit
rulers who crack down on their own people in the name of domestic
security.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels in Chechnya are generally perceived to be more
aggressive than the Albanian insurgents in Kosovo, and several
Western leaders qualified their condemnations of Russia by noting
that Russia has the right to fight terrorists _ a point Yeltsin
underscored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term peace in the Chechnya republic and so-called
peaceful negotiations with bandits are not one and the same
thing,'' Yeltsin said. ``There will be no negotiations between
bandits and murderers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
