<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4282 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     11-18 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALREADY THE MVP OF RANGERS FANS, PUDGE NOW HAS REAL AWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ They will be forever linked in Rangers lore.
Pudge and Juan. Juan and Pudge. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both arrived in Arlington as full-time players in 1991. Both
were considered young superstars in the making. Both were proud
sons of the Puerto Rico baseball machine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During nine seasons of thick and thin _ but mostly thick _ both
also defied the odds. Together, they reached an elite status in the
major leagues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, however, there was some serious irony to consider.
Within two weeks of Juan Gonzalez's departure from the Rangers _
traded to the Tigers _ Pudge Rodriguez succeeded him as American
League MVP, the league's highest honor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even in making his exit from Arlington, Juan was again
overshadowed by Pudge. Locally, it has always been that way. And
those league MVP awards Juan won in '96 and '98 couldn't change
that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pudge is and was the people's choice, be it in performance on
the field or in all the important intangibles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To the fans, Pudge shows personality and charisma. Juan was
different. That wasn't him. The translation to the fans, fair or
not, was the contrast between warmth and, well, a chill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The language barrier was another factor. And not a small one.
Pudge started early in his career and worked hard at improving his
English. For many seasons, Juan didn't seem to care, although later
he did make an attempt. But Pudge reached many more fans than Juan
just by being able to speak better English. Should that be a
factor? No. Is it? Certainly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was two years ago, however, when Pudge cemented his position
as maybe the most popular player ever in Arlington. Against the
advice of his agent and his union, he cut his own contractual deal
with the Rangers, taking less money to continue his career here
long-term. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Juan could have done that three weeks ago. He didn't. He's now
gone. But as of Thursday, the American League MVP still plays in
Arlington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On-the-field comparisons between the two are apples and oranges,
but again, Pudge has that one thing that separates him from all
others: the big arm behind the plate that changes the way the game
is played by the opposition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Juan, Pudge has had his critics _ mainly local baseball
writers, me included _ who often wondered why the complete player
didn't surface. But to Pudge's credit, he has advanced his game
beyond just the arm and the bat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the scouts whispered that Rodriguez was a ``body
risk,'' meaning a weight problem would limit his major-league
career. Instead, Pudge has become the most durable catcher the game
has ever known, mainly because of an intensive daily workout
program. Fitness training became his obsession, and it shows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another long-standing knock on Pudge was he concentrated more on
offensive numbers than refining the key points of catching: calling
a game, working with pitchers, having sound technique behind the
plate, etc. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of that criticism lingers today, but Rodriguez is now
giving these areas more effort. No longer is it necessarily valid
to say he carries a bad at-bat with him to his position, meaning a
lack of concentration behind the plate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But under the guidance of hitting instructor Rudy Jaramillo, the
offensive numbers for Rodriguez reached career-high levels in 1999.
For a free swinger who rarely walks, having 64 strikeouts in 600
at-bats is an incredible tribute to the art of making contact. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which is also what happened in the very wide-open MVP balloting:
Pudge made contact with each of the 28 voters, which breaks down to
two baseball writers from each league city. He had only seven
first-place votes (pitcher Pedro Martinez of Boston led with
eight), but Pudge was in the top three on 20 ballots and the top
five on 25. Plus, he won despite splitting votes with teammate
Rafael Palmeiro, who had four first-place votes and finished fifth
overall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To some, Pudge's MVP win was a surprise. It shouldn't have been.
He had an MVP season in all areas. More important to the Rangers,
he seems to be getting better in all areas, despite a workload of
144 or more games caught in four consecutive seasons. Rodriguez
will be 28 in two weeks, and, thanks to fitness dedication, the
physical wear-and-tear question is no longer an issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a joyful Rodriguez properly singled out Jaramillo for
special praise. And he thanked Palmeiro for his guidance. And he
also mentioned a call earlier in the afternoon from a former
teammate who wanted to offer congratulations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, Juan and Pudge were linked again by telephone. But, of
course, it's no longer the same. Then again, it never was. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
