<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SPEECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ADDRESS TO FOCUS ON FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PEGGY FIKAC  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ After a series of slips that raised the
stakes for him to show his vision of the America's role in the
world, Gov. George W. Bush is scheduled on Friday to deliver what
is being billed as a major foreign policy speech at the
presidential library of Republican icon Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, I will have a foreign policy with a touch of
iron, driven by American interests and American values,'' Bush, who
is seeking the Republican presidential nomination, said in a recent
television commercial addressing foreign affairs and the military.
</P>
<P>
   The speech and advertising come after gaffes including Bush's
inability to name of leaders of three world hot spots. Such lapses
have been dismissed by his campaign, which says people care instead
about the candidate's ideas for America's leadership role in the
world _ the subject of the Friday speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will describe the importance of keeping the peace for
generations to come and for Americans to seize the moment to lay
the groundwork for a new American internationalism,'' said Bush
spokesman Scott McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientist Bruce Buchanan of the University of Texas at
Austin said Bush's biggest vulnerability is that ``he has not been
in the kind of government circles that lead him to have a
familiarity with foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   That focuses attention on the speech at the Reagan library,
Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be watching to see whether his schooling is
starting to take root,'' he said. ``They will look to speeches like
that to see how far he's come.''
</P>
<P>
   The setting _ the presidential library of the man Bush's father
served as vice president and succeeded as president _ is itself a
powerful symbol for the Republican Party, said Dennis Goldford,
chairman of the Drake University Department of Politics and
International Relations in Des Moines, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Republicans try to be the next Ronald Reagan,'' Goldford
said. ``Republicans are looking for a return of a Reagan
internationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   The core of Reagan's foreign policy was the fight against
communist expansion. The underpinning of this policy was peace
through strength, increasing defense spending, but also negotiating
with the then-Soviet Union on arms control.
</P>
<P>
   The public to this point does not have a definitive picture of
Bush's foreign policy, analysts said. For example, Bush has said he
wants the United States to be able to develop a national missile
defense system. He told the Associated Press he would be willing to
share technology to help Russia develop its own an anti-ballistic
missile system, if Russia promised to reduce its stockpile of
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Goldford likened such statements to a connect-the-dots picture
in which ``there are no lines connecting the dots yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he is heartened by indications that Bush is
leaning toward a view of America taking a world leadership role in
alliances rather than one of unilateral action. Buchanan said he
believes that is the rational view because the world is
interdependent.
</P>
<P>
   Attention has been focused on foreign policy after Bush earlier
this month could not name the leaders of India, Pakistan or the
restive Russian republic of Chechnya in a pop quiz posed by a
television reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said that the pop quiz may have been perceived as
unfair. Even so, he said, ``It's a reminder of the underlying and
more legitimate concern of whether this fellow is up to speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also is scheduled to attend two fund-raisings Saturday
where he is expected to raises $1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
