<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-EGYPT-CRASH-1119-COX     11-18 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-CRASH-1119-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DID EGYPTIAN PILOT COMMIT THE ULTIMATE TABOO?
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   10TH OF RAMADAN CITY, Egypt _ In life, pilot Gameel El-Batouty
appeared to be the model of Egyptian gentility. In death, he is
suspected of a cardinal Egyptian sin _ suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Near the villa where Batouty planned to spend his retirement,
people remember that he would not retreat to his enclosed garden,
but rather sit on his small driveway to chat with neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   He smoked the water pipe with his servant and went to the mosque
on Fridays. On holidays, Batouty transcended the structured
Egyptian class hierarchy and had a butcher slaughter a lamb for
curbside neighborhood feasts.
</P>
<P>
   But Western officials, in so-far unsupported leaks to the press,
believe Batouty may have intentionally plunged EgyptAir Flight 990
to dive into the Atlantic Ocean, killing himself and 216 passengers
and crew.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane crashed Oct. 31, less than an hour after it left
John F. Kennedy Airport in New York for Cairo. A flight voice
recorder, officials say, appears to capture Batouty in the cockpit
and muttering a short prayer before the plane dove.
</P>
<P>
   The murder of hundreds of people would be one of the most
heinous crimes in Egypt's modern history. Moreover, suicide is such
an uncommon and detested act that many Egyptians cannot believe it
could be committed by the consummate family man.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide is a sin in Islam. The Koran, Islam's central text,
stresses that only God can give or take life. Muslims commonly
believe that people who commit suicide go to Hell.
</P>
<P>
   But, Egyptian psychoanalyst Ahmed Fayek said, even more
important than religion, the country's emphasis on family
reputation precludes suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suicide and other socially unacceptable behavior would shame
the family. It would not bring sympathy,'' Fayek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of suicide in the United States and Canada is
common,'' said Fayek, who practiced in Canada. ``(In Egypt),
society does not permit you to commit suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   After decades practicing in Cairo, Fayek said he has only heard
of two suicides.
</P>
<P>
   The family of a man who commits suicide, he said, will be
scorned; his daughters will have trouble finding husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the third day since investigators singled out Batouty,
Egyptians were closing ranks as one big family. Namely, they
rejected any suggestion that Batouty, whose wealth and status
represent Egyptian success, could have committed the shameful act.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers slammed the credibility of the American
investigation. Fellow pilots called a press conference to defend
Batouty. Street corners were alive with conspiracy theories and
people urged those being interviewed to reject the suicide
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the crime means that Batouty would not likely have
let anyone know his plans beforehand. Also, anyone with evidence of
a suicide would be unlikely to come forward with the information
for fear of hurting Batouty's family and national prestige.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be scandalized, I'm sure,'' Fayek said.
``People are going to say Egypt is a backward country, a corrupt
country.''
</P>
<P>
   He distinguished Batouty's case and speculation the pilot faced
personal problems from a terror attack, in which fundamentalists
may ``martyr'' themselves as part of a holy war.
</P>
<P>
   Fayek, however, is one of a minority of Egyptians who will not
rule out that Batouty may have taken the Boeing 767 into its crash.
Without evidence of terrorism or mechanical failure, he said, it
must be considered possible that Batouty had a ``severe psychotic
breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said that just a few commonly spoken words of prayer on
the flight recorder are not enough evidence to show that Batouty
committed the mass murder-suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Other evidence appeared to counter the idea of an intentional
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from Batouty's three-bedroom villa, a house
about an hour outside Cairo that served as a family getaway from a
downtown apartment, neighbors say he had plans.
</P>
<P>
   Retired banker Mahmoud Khairy, 63, said he visited with Batouty
a month ago. At the time, he said, Batouty said he would soon take
his 10-year-old daughter, Aya, to Los Angeles to treat her Lupus.
They said she was improving and this was to be a treatment just to
assure her progress.
</P>
<P>
   That matched family statements Wednesday. While some have
speculated that Aya's uninsured treatments were breaking Batouty
financially, it seems illogical he would kill himself just before
his daughter's treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very special to him. She was his youngest child,''
Khairy said.
</P>
<P>
   Khairy, who knew Batouty 10 years, said the seasoned pilot gave
no indication of financial problems. Not only was Batouty the son
of a wealthy landowner, his wife is from a wealthy family.
</P>
<P>
   Others questioned speculation that Batouty was frustrated
because, at 59 years old and just months away from mandatory
retirement, he was still just a co-pilot rather than a full
captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, he was not frustrated,'' said Roushdie Zakaria,
EgyptAir's deputy chief for the 767 crews. He and others said
Batouty returned to civil aviation from the Egyptian Air Force too
late in life _ in his mid-40s _ to expect to be captain.
</P>
<P>
   Zakaria said EgyptAir policy forbids promotions after age 55, so
Batouty would have been frustrated for years, not just recently.
</P>
<P>
   According to family members, Batouty was early on recognized as
a skilled piloting prospect and obligated to serve as an air force
flight instructor. They said he was at least once a co-pilot to
President Hosni Mubarak, a former bomber pilot.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with family members over two days, there have been
gaps. For example, while one cousin said Batouty had lined up
post-retirement job with another airline, he would not say which
airline.
</P>
<P>
   But, the evidence of Batouty's affable personality and family
devotion seemed to outweigh the few, possibly, incriminating words
on a flight recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Clouding the issue is the unofficial nature of the reports about
the recording; reports that first said there was no problem in the
cockpit and later gave two different versions of Batouty's words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fueling the conspiracy theories,'' said American
University of Cairo political sociologist Saad Eddin Ibrahim. Those
theories include a Boeing Co. cover up of mechanical problems to
suspicions that the CIA altered the voice recorders.
</P>
<P>
   In one of Ibrahim's classes, only one of 45 students said they
considered suicide a possibility in the airplane crash.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
