<HEADER>
A4301 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BONFIRE-AGS-COX     11-18 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-AGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas A&AMP;M alumni mourn loss
 &HT;    By Rebecca Thatcher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As word of the fatal collapse of the bonfire at
Texas A&AMP;M spread through Austin, members of the tightly-knit alumni
club here called each other, fretted over news of the rescue
efforts, and made plans to donate blood.
</P>
<P>
   Attending Texas A&AMP;M is often a family tradition, with an
unbroken line of graduates running from grandparents to
grandchildren. Lou Obdyke, the president of the Capital City A&AMP;M
Club and an Austin lawyer, said many members of the club have
called to ask what they can do to help.
</P>
<P>
   It's a ``pretty rough situation over there in College Station,''
said Obdyke. ``I think the tragedy is what everybody's focused
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, former yell leader, said he was ``deeply
saddened'' by the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to closely monitor this situation,'' Perry
said in a press release. ``I encourage all Texans to pray for those
impacted by this accident, their families, friends, and the entire
student body and faculty of Texas A&AMP;M University.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Immenhauser, a consultant broker in insurance and
investments who graduated in 1994, said she could not understand
how the bonfire could have collapsed or how so many could have been
injured. She recalled only two people being allowed to climb the
structure, and many other safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't see how that could happen,'' Immenhauser said.
``Safety has always been a big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Immenhauser said she feels Texas A &AMP; M should cancel future
Bonfires. ``Out of respect to the students who were killed, I can't
imagine celebrating Bonfire again,'' she said. ``I just think it's
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Haws, an Austin veterinarian who graduated in 1948,
was concerned about his granddaughter, who is a student at A&AMP;M. He
said heard from his daughter that the granddaughter had helped with
the early stages of the rescue effort and was okay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just real sad,'' Haws said.
</P>
<P>
   Dannielle Cantrell, a real estate agent and the president elect
of the Capital City A&AMP;M Club, said she spent almost all Thursday
morning talking to friends and club members about the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just praying for the ones who are still in surgery and
critical,'' she said. ``We're just worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Cantrell and Obdyke said it was too early to speculate about the
future of the bonfire. Obdyke, who cut logs for the bonfire as a
corps member in the 1960s, said he trusted the A&AMP;M administration
to decide what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure President Ray Bowen and the college will take serious
consideration,'' Obdyke said. ``I have faith that he and his staff
will make the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
