<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COX-TEX-BROWN19     11-18 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TEX-BROWN19 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas GOP divided over senator's fate
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGLETON, Texas _ On a sunny morning in September, state Sen.
Buster Brown stood in a public park facing a young woman who used
to work for him. It couldn't have been easy.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks earlier, Brazosport College student Tiffany Black,
then 20, told police that the Southeast Texas senator touched her
breasts and buttocks and tried to kiss her during an impromptu golf
lesson in his Lake Jackson office. Brown, 58, met Black in the park
to read a short letter apologizing for his ``unwanted sexual
advances'' _ as his wife of 32 years, Black's fiancee, Black's
mother and the local district attorney looked on.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the Senate's ranking Republican, hoped the apology would
put the golf lesson to rest: Black agreed to drop her criminal
complaint in exchange for the apology, although she can still file
a civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident may have far-reaching political fallout. The
Republican leadership in Brazoria County, which includes Brown's
hometown of Lake Jackson, demanded last week that he give up the
seat he has held since 1981. Capitol observers say the powerful
senator, who wants to replace Lt. Gov. Rick Perry if Gov. George W.
Bush is elected president and Perry takes his place, may have
knocked himself out of the race for Perry's post.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the incident has widened an existing rift in the
Brazoria County GOP. And in a community where the Republican
chairwoman is married to the city attorney, the district attorney
is married to the city manager and virtually everybody knows
everybody else, it is giving rise to some interesting conspiracy
theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't handled properly from the very first,'' said Ross
Ahlstrom, president of the Brazoria County Republican Men's Club
and a fierce rival of GOP Chairwoman Yvonne Dewey, who had led the
call for Brown's resignation. ``It appears it was done so the
senator could receive the maximum amount of embarrassment without
ever being able to defend himself in a court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who isn't up for re-election until 2002, says that he
won't step down and that he still plans to pursue Perry's job if it
becomes open. In a written statement, Brown criticized the Brazoria
County GOP's executive committee for not giving him a chance to
speak before it voted 19-2 to demand his resignation. He declined
to be interviewed for this story.
</P>
<P>
   A former high school history teacher, Brown earned a law degree
from the University of Texas and went on to become an assistant
district attorney for Brazoria County before entering private
practice and the Senate. He is conservative, and as chairman of the
Natural Resources Committee he has been a friend to business
interests.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown, who ran unsuccessfully for attorney general in 1990,
is more pragmatic than ideological, and he's often praised as a
lawmaker who can work with both sides to get things done. That
quality, coupled with his seniority, has fueled talk of him as a
potential lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   During his 18 years in the Senate, Brown has sponsored 456 bills
that have become law. He was surrounded by dozens of photographs,
plaques, a silver shovel and other emblems of that success as he
gave Black the fateful golf lesson in his Lake Jackson office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why a man would throw away the opportunity he had
for such a thing as that,'' said Harmon Hoot, an Angleton
upholstery store owner who used to head the Brazoria County
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   People in Brazoria County tend to smile and roll their eyes when
asked about the now infamous golf lesson. Grace Cook, who owns
Royal Hair Fashions in downtown Lake Jackson, said many of her
customers have been talking about the senator. For her part, Cook
can't decide whether Brown should resign, because ``we really don't
know the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Thode, chairman of the Fort Bend County Republicans, is
also reluctant to pass judgment. In addition to Brazoria County,
Brown represents residents in Fort Bend and Harris counties, but
Republicans there haven't asked him to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer in three sides to every story: your side,
my side and the right side,'' Thode said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown's critics say his apology makes it clear what
happened. Some also note that an Alvin woman recently told police
that the senator grabbed her and tried to kiss her as she was
leaving his Lake Jackson office more than two years ago. The woman
said she came forward to support Black but didn't want to pursue
criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   His critics say that any Republican who called on President
Clinton to resign for his affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky would be hypocritical not to demand the same from
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He openly admitted it, so there's no question about what he
did,'' said Jorene Aycock, a committee member who voted to demand
his resignation. ``If it's enough for her, that's fine. But once
it's public and he admits to something like that and everyone knows
it's in his character and his behavior _ it's just different
then.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator's supporters say he deserves more credit for an
honorable _ and fairly speedy _ apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to do the Christian thing, to put this thing to bed
and move on down the road,'' said Ahlstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Ahlstrom argues that family ties between public officials and
county GOP leaders influenced the way the Brown flap unfolded. He
also connects it to a Republican rift dating from a 1996 incident
at the Brazoria County Jail. A videotape of guards using dogs to
subdue prisoners there attracted national attention and split the
party into pro- and anti-sheriff factions. Dewey, the GOP
chairwoman, is angry at Brown for staying out of the fight instead
of supporting the sheriff, Ahlstrom claims.
</P>
<P>
   But Dewey, who notes that Ahlstrom ran against her for party
chair, says she was a Brown supporter until the September incident.
And District Attorney Jeri Yenne insists the Brown case was handled
like any other Class C assault, which is punishable by a $500 fine.
In many of those cases, Yenne said, she asks the victim whether an
apology would suffice. She said the ensuing publicity was
inevitable in such a tight-knit community.
</P>
<P>
   John Toth, the publisher of a local weekly newspaper who opposed
Dewey in the jail fight, backs her on the Brown issue. Toth said
the vote was notable because it united members of both Republican
factions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this reflects the feeling of the people around here,''
Toth said. ``When you have all but two members of the executive
committee going against the most powerful senator in the state of
Texas, that tells you something.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
