<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Nov. 19. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TALKS (Istanbul, Turkey) _ President Boris Yeltsin and
the West square off over Chechnya, as the Russian leader tells a
European summit meeting that the West has no right to criticize
Russia for its campaign against ``bandits and murderers.'' But
President Clinton insists that the West is only trying to do for
Chechnya's civilians what it would have done for Yeltsin himself
when he was on the barricades: defend their rights against abusive
authorities. Seldom since the end of the cold war has Russia
appeared so isolated on the world stage. By Michael R. Gordon. (We
plan to move the story by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,400
words.
</P>
<P>
   The story runs with a 4-column photo layout.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to RUSSIA-U.S.-AID.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Lede all on the spending bills,
including the vote by the House and expectations for the Senate. By
Tim Weiner. (Story will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds.: Story is developing.
</P>
<P>
   reefer: SATELLITE-TV (Washington) _ Bowing to an objection by
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, the House passes a hard-fought bill that
would give satellite television companies the right to air local
television channels, assuring that cable companies will soon have a
dose of competition. By Lizette Alvarez. (Scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) Story inside Business.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-OIL (Istanbul, Turkey) _ The energy-rich nations around
the Caspian Sea take a giant step toward embracing one of President
Clinton's most cherished foreign policy projects, a pipeline that
would assure Western control over the region's vast oil and natural
gas reserves. By Stephen Kinzer. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET
in ``i'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   BROKER-DEATHS (New York) _ The Oct. 25 killing in New Jersey of
two stock promoters exposes a seamier side of Wall Street, a world
of low-priced stocks and high-priced dreams, of grimy offices and
sham companies, of swindlers and touts who prey on average people
trying to grab the brass ring in the greatest bull market in
American history. A primer on how the deals are done. By Leslie
Eaton. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Special Report: 3,000 words. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE-COLLAPSE (College Station, Texas) _ A 40-foot pyramid of
logs being assembled for Texas A&AMP;M's annual bonfire collapses while
dozens of students are working on it. By Jim Yardley. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 3-column photo.
</P>
