<HEADER>
A4308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-MITCHELL-BOS &LR;      11-18 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-MITCHELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUIET FAREWELL FOR MEDIATOR MITCHELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Nineteen months ago, the last time
George Mitchell thought his role as mediator in Northern Ireland's
longrunning Troubles was about to end, he was elated,
sleep-deprived and running on adrenalin.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Mitchell, the 66-year-old former US Senate majority
leader from Maine, sat calmly in his spartan office here,
clear-eyed and well-rested, ready to leave Belfast again, five
years after he signed up as President Clinton's adviser on Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good,'' said Mitchell, who, like many a
Downeaster, is a master of understatement.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, at his insistence, there were no deadlines, no
all-night bargaining sessions. In the cold light of day, Mitchell
got lifelong enemies to share the same space, to take meals
together, to talk about fishing, to look deep into each other's
eyes and decide whether they really want to go back to the days
when murder was a form of political discourse.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Mitchell packed his bags for home, convinced that his
work here really is done, that those lifelong enemies have
concluded that while they didn't necessarily like each other, that
while they probably never would be friends, they could nonetheless
do business with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more I can do,'' Mitchell said, glancing at
his watch to make sure he was on schedule to catch the first leg of
his return to his wife, Heather, and their son, Andrew, who turned
2 last month. ``It is up to the parties here to make it work, and I
believe they can.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, in what students of politics consider a masterful
piece of diplomacy, Mitchell got most of the parties here to sign
the Good Friday Agreement, which was meant to transform the debate
over whether Northern Ireland would remain part of the United
Kingdom or merge with the Republic of Ireland from a violent
conflict to one decided by democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   But the two parties most crucial to the deal _ the Ulster
Unionists who represent most Protestants, and Sinn Fein, the
political allies of the Irish Republican Army _ signed up to the
agreement without so much as exchanging a word with each other.
Neither side trusted the other.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists refused to form a power-sharing government with Sinn
Fein, called for under the agreement, until the IRA turned in its
weapons. Sinn Fein said the unionists were using the issue as a
smokescreen because they could not stomach treating Catholic
nationalists as equals. The peace process stalled, and the threat
of a return to widespread violence loomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an agreement, but there was no trust,'' Mitchell
said.
</P>
<P>
   And so, with great reluctance, Mitchell ditched his family and
his Washington law practice 11 weeks ago to try to rescue it.
</P>
<P>
   It was July 16, a glorious, sunny day in London. Mitchell was
knighted by Queen Elizabeth II for his work in Northern Ireland.
Heather beamed as they walked in Buckingham Palace. At the very
moment Mitchell was being honored, however, the Northern Ireland
Assembly that was the cornerstone of the Good Friday Agreement was
collapsing in a sea of recrimination and farce, as unionists and
republicans refused to budge on their positions.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Mitchell got a call from Mo Mowlam, then the British
official in charge of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need you, George,'' Mowlam said.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart,
Bertie Ahern, had spent all their political capital earlier that
month, setting deadlines that passed without agreement or sanction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need you,'' Mowlam repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell wasn't flattered. He did not want to go back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was,'' he recalled, ``the last thing I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, a former professional tennis player, took charge of
the situation. She told him he had to do it. He had invested too
much of his life. Sounding like Humphrey Bogart insisting that
Ingrid Bergman get on the plane in ``Casablanca,'' Heather Mitchell
told her husband he would regret it, maybe not today, maybe not
tomorrow, but someday, if he didn't go back to Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' George Mitchell sighed, ``she was right.''
</P>
<P>
   He told Heather it would be two weeks, three at the most. But
time has a way of dragging on this island. And Mitchell had decided
time could not be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell had set a deadline last year, convinced that the
parties would not reach an agreement without one. But having seen
the hard feelings on both sides after the prime ministers had put
pressure on them to make a deal, Mitchell said he ``discarded any
notion of a deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was about building trust. I had to let them talk it
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of meetings in the drab Castle Buildings office
complex at Stormont here, where the Good Friday Agreement was
negotiated in a series of segregated corners that mirror this
segregated society, Mitchell asked the US ambassador to Britain,
Philip Lader, if he could borrow Lader's mansion in London's
Regents Park.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell says it was a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something happened there, people connected with each other,''
he said. ``I arranged for meals to be served at this table that sat
18, 19 people. There were no seating arrangements, so people mixed.
My only order was that, during meals, we talked about anything but
politics. We talked about fishing, sports, families, the weather.
They became better aware of each other as persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin McGuinness, the former IRA chief of staff and Sinn Fein's
chief negotiator, agrees that the atmosphere changed inside Lader's
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to each other, not at each other,'' McGuinness said.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, there was a more intimate gathering in
Mitchell's suite at the Belfast Hilton. Ulster Unionist leader
David Trimble, his chief negotiator Reg Empey, Sinn Fein leader
Gerry Adams and McGuinness joined Mitchell for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lasted three or four hours,'' Mitchell said. ``A lot got
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Trimble told Mitchell that if the IRA was willing to
appoint a representative to discuss turning in weapons, his party
was willing to form a power-sharing government that will include
two Sinn Fein cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell choreographed a series of confidence-building
statements, first by Trimble, then by Adams, who said that the
``decommissioning'' of IRA weapons ``is an essential part of the
peace process.'' On Wednesday, the IRA, which had previously ruled
out even talking about disarming, said it would appoint a
representative to discuss decommissioning after the power-sharing
government is formed.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Mitchell said the creation of the power-sharing
government and appointment of paramilitary representatives to the
arms decommissioning authority should take place on the same day.
That can happen only if Trimble convinces his party council to back
him next week.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is not Mitchell's business. Thursday, he looked
forward to getting back to his life. His law practice has suffered,
with countless meetings cancelled. He regrets having missed the
noble pennant race of his beloved Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to get a little more depth in their rotation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Mitchell was stuck in Belfast, trying to resolve
a petty dispute over procedure, when his brother died. He barely
made it back in time to deliver the eulogy. This time around, the
personal toll was even higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't around much the first seven months after my son was
born,'' he said, ``but now he is old enough to know when I'm gone,
and it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mitchell says the sacrifices have been worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound corny,'' he says, ``but when you believe
in something, when you believe that what you do can make a
difference for the better in people's lives, your life is never
more meaningful.''
</P>
<P>
   George Mitchell looked down at the plum wall-to-wall carpeting
and then out the window that offers a view of bare trees and little
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he said, ``has been one of the most meaningful times
of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
