<HEADER>
A4309 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-SLEEPYHOLLOW-TEX     11-18 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SLEEPYHOLLOW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISUALLY STUNNING BUT HORRORLESS, `HOLLOW' IS JUST THAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnny Depp faints more often than a Tennessee Williams heroine
in Tim Burton's ``Sleepy Hollow,'' a dizzying retelling of
Washington Irving's story of the Headless Horseman. Ichabod Crane
(Depp) is a New York constable sent to investigate a series of
murders in which the corpses have been decapitated. Crane is a man
of science _ as much as a modern man of 1799 can be _ and his
embrace of technology has separated him from the natural world.
Obsessed with his case of vials, solutions, special lenses and
devices, Crane uses them to make sense of the world. But his
struggle to view the world as a man of reason is shattered when
science fails him. When he discovers it is indeed a Headless
Horseman (Christopher Walken) terrorizing the countryside, Crane,
as jittery and fearful as Nancy Drew, has to relax his grip on
logic so he can solve the case.
</P>
<P>
   In this supernatural detective story, Crane is the hero as
ingenue. It turns out that Crane has a horrible secret, which we
learn about in flashbacks. His mother (Lisa Marie) was a witch, but
a good-hearted one: ``a child of nature'' whom his father murdered
because of her unnatural powers. ``Sleepy Hollow'' has mood and
atmosphere, exquisitely detailed set design and ... well, just
about everything but a story. As a filmmaker, Burton enjoys
conjuring explosive and juicy camp; here, he's made a polished gem
of a tribute to Hammer horror films. Most sets are shrouded in fog,
with more tones of muted grays and blacks than you thought ever
existed. (The gorgeous look comes from production designer Rick
Heinrichs, who has also worked with the Coen brothers, and from
cinematographer Emmanuel Lubezki. It's so crisp and otherworldly,
it looks as if it's set in an Eastern European snow globe _
especially in the stunning last shot.)
</P>
<P>
   As a director, Burton isn't strong on shaping a story. Nothing
much seems to matter except the endless beheadings. Burton also
plunders much of ``Beetlejuice.'' With its spires and covered
bridges, the tiny town could be the ancestor of the little village
``Beetlejuice'' was set in, and the good-luck book that Crane is
given _ a compendium of spells and devices from the spirit world _
is like the ``handbook from beyond'' in that previous film.
Although he's better at presenting action than he was in the past;
the ``Batman'' movies were so badly staged they made no sense.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the luscious joke is casting Walken as the Horseman;
he's a demon with ``a love of carnage'' even before he's
reincarnated as one. Before being captured and beheaded, he's had
his teeth filed to razor points and is clad in form-fitting black
togs, galloping about on a horse as dark as his heart; at one
point, there's a stunning image of him sitting on his bloodstained
mount. Crane's also a joke, clutching his instruments of reason and
fleeing scenes of violence. Eventually, he gathers the nerve in a
climax that's like Burton's 18th-century restaging of ``Terminator
2.'' The Horseman stalks a carriage and jumps aboard to get the
lovely Katrina (Christina Ricci, who, with her long blond wavy
hair, looks _ and acts _ like a voluptuous Glinda the Good Witch
from ``The Wizard of Oz.'')
</P>
<P>
   In look and tone, ``Hollow'' is so masterful _ and well-acted,
with Depp's comic talents well-used _ that it takes a while before
you learn Burton's awful secret. His movies lack subtext. There's
nothing going on inside. It's why ``Hollow'' is never really scary,
despite the violence and endless scenes of beheading: It's a horror
comedy with a shortage of horror. And it's why Burton's ``Ed Wood''
seemed likable but flat. There was no sexual charge beneath the
surface there, or here, despite Depp's constant fainting and the
attempt to depict the Horseman as unleashed id. (Irving's crudeness
served him better in the story.) Crane's observation that ``Truth
is not always appearance'' is peculiarly ironic with a director who
seems to believe exactly the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleepy Hollow'' is rated R for violence, gore and repeated
scenes of beheadings.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
