<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-EMT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEER EMT SAYS SCENE WAS SURREAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By YVETTE CRAIG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tricia E. Jost dug through the collapsed logs at Texas A&AMP;M to
reach a student buried underneath and screaming for help.
</P>
<P>
   As Jost lowered an oxygen mask to his face, the trapped student
repeatedly asked her about the condition of his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 45 minutes I stayed with him and kept him talking so he
would stay conscious. I didn't want him to know that (his friend)
below me was already dead,'' said Jost, the daughter of Fort Worth
acting Police Chief Ralph Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   Jost, 20, an emergency medical technician who volunteers with
the Texas A&AMP;M University Care Team, said Thursday that the
unfolding tragedy was surreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the situation was serious, but I couldn't even fathom
how horrible it actually is,'' Jost said by telephone from the
scene. ``I'm on autopilot. I'm not feeling anything. I'm not
feeling sad. I'm not crying. I have work I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jost stayed with the student, whose name she did not know, until
more help arrived. She said that his arms and legs were pinned by a
pile of logs, but that he was pulled out alive.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, Jost was working as coordinator for rescue
volunteers at the bonfire site. She and seven other crew members
had been there since midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Everything appeared to be going routinely.
</P>
<P>
   The EMT volunteers sat in the back of a rented moving truck,
some watching videos, others studying. Jost was reading her biology
textbook.
</P>
<P>
   Then, about 2:30 a.m., one volunteer shouted that ``the stack''
was falling. Sixty to 70 students were on top of the logs when the
accident happened in a field on the northeast corner of the campus.
A maximum of 70 students are allowed on the stack at one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were screaming and running everywhere,'' Jost said. ``I
put a hard hat on and pretty much ran right into the middle of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next few hours, Jost helped pull victims away from the
collapsed log stack and tended to students with fractured arms,
injured legs and cuts. All the while, she and other rescue workers
strained to locate students crying for help inside the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   By 5 a.m., Jost called her parents to tell them what had
happened.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to assure them that she and her sister, Mandi Jost,
an 18-year-old freshman, were not injured.
</P>
<P>
   Cindi Mendoza, a registered nurse with North Texas Affiliated
Medical Group, said she cried for an hour after her daughter
called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about all of the other parents whose children didn't
make it or were injured,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she also worries about how those who witnessed the
accident, including her daughter, will cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, there seems to be an overabundance of tragedy, and it
seems to be happening to kids,'' she said. ``Those young people out
there today will be left with images most of us will never have to
experience in our whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Mendoza agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit I'm kind of worried about Tricia. We need to make
sure she is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
