<SLUG> BC-GUN-DEATHS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDC: Gun violence declining
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fewer U.S. residents are being killed or injured by
guns, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said Thursday.
But gunshot wounds are still a serious public health concern: More
than 96,000 Americans receive gunshot wounds each year and
one-third of them die.
</P>
<P>
   According to numbers released by the agency, gun violence has
declined since 1993's peak of 39,595 deaths. But guns remain one of
the greatest causes of deaths due to injury, second only to cars,
the CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the most recent year for which national surveys have
been done, 32,436 Americans died from gunshot wounds, and an
additional 64,207 were injured seriously enough to seek emergency
medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers represent a drop of 21 percent in death rates and
almost 41 percent in rates of nonfatal injury since the high-water
mark of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The declines were consistent for most groups within the U.S.
population, the CDC added. Deaths and injuries dropped by similar
amounts among men and women, and among Hispanics and
African-Americans. In fact, the reductions in death and injury were
greater among nonwhites than among whites.
</P>
<P>
   Other surveys taken recently have recorded a nationwide decrease
of 21 percent in the rate of violent crime. The analysis of death
and injury rates bears that out, the CDC said, with one troubling
exception. Though rates of homicide and of accidental death due to
guns have been dropping sharply, the rate of suicide by gun remains
high.
</P>
<P>
   Harsher gun laws, a better economy, an aging population and a
declining market for drugs may have contributed to the declines in
death and injury, the CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
