<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-RECONCILE-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY'S HIDDEN SCARS EMERGE FROM A GERMANY UNITED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Israel)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOTENSLEBEN, Germany _ This is a country of scars. Some are
evident, some lie deeply hidden, as the story of this village on
the former border between East and West Germany shows.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with the evident scars, stroll into the fields beyond
the village, where the quiet quickly gives way to the disquieting:
a wall, a watchtower and coils of barbed wire rise from the
undulating countryside and mark the Cold War's old frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The Berlin Wall fell on Nov. 9, 1989, but elsewhere on the
930-mile border between East and West Germany the end of Europe's
division came more slowly. At Hotensleben, it was only on Nov. 19
that the heavily fortified wall was breached after repeated
protests by local people.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we watched what happened in Berlin, we thought it was a
one-day mistake,'' said Dieter Buchwald, the mayor of this formerly
East German town. ``We were certain the Russians would never
tolerate it. But then we gained courage, and about 300 of us went
every day to press for the opening of our wall.''
</P>
<P>
   After 10 days that opening came. Euphoria and emotional family
reunions followed. Then, as elsewhere, came the difficulties: a
sugar factory closed, a mine shut down, hundreds of jobs were lost.
Widespread unemployment was hard, but a deeper pain emerged when
the hidden scar of Hotensleben at last emerged.
</P>
<P>
   That scar stemmed from the story of Alfred and Eva Jaeckel, the
one Jewish family in the village. Owners of the Hotensleben textile
store, German patriots until Hitler decreed otherwise, they were
banished from history between 1945 and 1989.
</P>
<P>
   East German history was a science in the service of the
Communist regime. Hitler, seen through this prism, was the last
spasm of reactionary capitalism, a man thrust to power by the
German bourgeoisie and resisted by the socialist worker-heroes of
the future East German state. In this vision, the Holocaust had no
place.
</P>
<P>
   So in communist, postwar Hotensleben, on the front line between
the Soviet and British sectors, the story of the Jaeckels simply
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The end of Europe's division also marked the release of buried
history. Sometimes this has proved explosive, as in the Balkans,
where the past has been manipulated again to serve
communists-turned-nationalists. Sometimes, as in this German
village, a result has been a belated push for truth and
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   The push began in 1990 with a property claim from Israel that
arrived at the town and amazed Buchwald.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had grown up in this village, but nobody ever mentioned a
Jewish family,'' said the mayor, an engineer who took office in
1989. ``We heard about Hitler's fascist atrocities, but not about
the Jews, here or anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   The claim came from Alfred's son, Reinhold Jaeckel. Intrigued,
the mayor decided to make use of a government-subsidized make-work
program to give an unemployed person the task of researching
whether a Jewish family called Jaeckel had ever lived in
Hotensleben.
</P>
<P>
   Responses from the town's 2,400 inhabitants were initially
evasive. People old enough to remember the war years seemed
reluctant to talk about the Nazi period; above all, they did not
want their own names linked with any testimony. But gradually the
lost story of the Jaeckels was pieced together.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Jaeckel opened his store in 1907 and fought for Germany
in World War I, earning an Iron Cross for bravery. After the war,
he returned to Hotensleben, where business was good until Hitler
came to power in 1933. Then banners began to appear saying:
``Anyone who buys from the Jews not wanted here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaeckel, like many patriotic German Jews, refused to believe the
worst. He tried to ignore the taunts of the Nazis gathering in the
Knopf hotel next to the store.
</P>
<P>
   But his Zionist son, Reinhold, who was born in 1908, left
Germany for Palestine in 1933, as soon as Hitler gained power.
Having worked most of his life as a teacher, Reinhold Jaeckel died
in Israel in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was always obsessed with what happened in
Hotensleben,'' said Reinhold's son Joram Jaeckel, who lives in
Ramat Gan near Tel Aviv. ``He wanted to know exactly what happened
to his family and he wanted to recover the property. He wrote
countless letters. But until the Cold War ended, we could not do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Cold War hid was the way German barbarism had destroyed
the Jaeckel family. On the night of Nov. 9, 1938 _ the same date in
November that the Berlin Wall would fall 51 years later _ their
store was smashed and ransacked in the Kristallnacht rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred and his wife, Eva, were arrested, taken initially to
Berlin, and then deported to Auschwitz in 1942, where they were
killed. Their son Albert was also arrested and killed by the Nazis
in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost a half-century after these crimes, in 1990, that
Reinhold Jaeckel returned to Hotensleben for the first time,
accompanied by his son. ``We felt a terrible ambivalence,'' Joram
Jaeckel said.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, people were nice, helpful, overwhelmingly
polite. ``On the other,'' he continued, ``I knew that these were
the sons and daughters of my family's murderers, and that the older
people may even have participated in Kristallnacht.''
</P>
<P>
   The only trace of the family in the town was the grave of
Reinhold's grandmother Ernestine Lippmann. An 80-year-old woman in
1938, she was beaten by the Nazis during the Kristallnacht attack
and died 10 days later, on Nov. 19, 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Joram Jaeckel, 53, recalled meeting a woman old enough to have
witnessed these events, asking her about his great-grandmother's
death, and seeing a shadow of unease fall across her face. ``She
did not want to tell the truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchwald, a devout Christian, is now deeply concerned with
historical truth, which he sees as the only basis for ending
Europe's 20th-century convulsions. His own family was uprooted from
Silesia after 1945 when the area became part of Poland, so he knows
the anguish of displacement.
</P>
<P>
   He played an important role in ensuring the restitution of the
Jaeckel home _ then a ruin _ in 1994. The preservation of the wall
outside the village as a memorial to Germany's division has also
been the mayor's work.
</P>
<P>
   In the hall outside his office, Buchwald has organized a
permanent exhibition of the Jaeckel family story made up of
photographs, letters from Reinhold Jaeckel and unsigned testimony
from local people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old people alive at Kristallnacht are still too embarrassed to
sign their name,'' Buchwald said. ``Germans continue to complicate
their history. Some now say it was not really so bad for the Jews
under the Nazis, and so I exhibit these photos. Others say it was
not really so bad in communist East Germany, and so I want the wall
there as a reminder of what that state was.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even with history made so evident, its scars are not quickly
overcome. For four decades, East Germans learned they were the good
Germans, the anti-fascists during Hitler's rule. In this way,
honest confrontation with Nazi crimes was avoided.
</P>
<P>
   One result of this has been the much greater success of neo-Nazi
groups in the former East Germany than in the West. In the last
election in Saxony-Anhalt, the state in which Hotensleben is
situated, the extreme right took 12.9 percent of the vote. This
prominence of rightist groups, in turn, hinders east-west
integration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I note that my children, who are in their 20s, are not
interested in the east,'' said Willi Heidemann, the top
administrative official in the nearby village of Jerxheim, which
was on the western side of the border. ``In part that's because
they are apolitical members of what I call a just-for-fun
generation. But they are also put off by right-wing violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Joram Jaeckel, who is now trying to rent out his recovered and
restored property, puts the neo-Nazism of skinheads down to the
follies of youth. Once, staying at an inn in the nearby town of
Schoeningen, he overhead chants of ``Heil Hitler!'' and shuddered.
But he is more deeply disturbed by meetings with older Germans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I always ask myself,'' he said, ``is `What are they
thinking? What is behind the faces?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1944EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
