<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAGE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOME PAGE': NO REVOLUTION AT HAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid the hue and cry about how the Internet is destroying
personal privacy, few have pointed out that for certain
cyberfanatics that erosion is cause for rejoicing.
</P>
<P>
   Computer gurus like Justin Hall, the bratty, motor-mouthed
exhibitionist who is the focus of Doug Block's intriguing but
disorganized documentary, ``Home Page,'' see no need for personal
privacy once the utopian electronic community of their dreams is
established. The world Hall imagines is a kind of virtual commune
that recalls the headiest collective fantasies of the hippie
counterculture but is situated in cyberspace instead of the real
world.
</P>
<P>
   When first glimpsed, Hall is an undergraduate at Swarthmore
College in 1996, where he is a cybercelebrity who operates a home
page visited daily by 7,000 people. Dressed in psychedelic finery,
his blond hair teased into a pointed tower, he is the very model of
latter-day hippie proselytizer. On his page, which consists of a
daily journal and photographs of him and his friends, Hall
literally lets it all hang out, revealing himself in nude
photographs (he is a soft-featured, girlish-looking boy with an
impish grin) and disclosing the most intimate details of his
personal history and his relationships with a series of women. Hall
is only too eager to confide to the camera that his father was
alcoholic and committed suicide, that he was brought up by a
succession of nannies and that he has had nine years of
psychotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows Hall from Swarthmore to San Francisco, where he
teams up with his mentor, Howard Rheingold, the author and World
Wide Web visionary, to help begin a Web site called Electric Minds
whose goal is the establishment of a virtual community. Their
relationship is far from harmonious, and Hall tests it by sneakily
revealing his mentor's background as a writer of purple-prosed
cyberporn.
</P>
<P>
   Hall is the most vivid and messianic figure in this movie's
portrait of a loosely knit band of computer fanatics who use the
Internet to explore the boundaries of communication and human
relationships. In the film's halfhearted subplot, Block establishes
his own home page, in which he writes a confessional journal, talks
his elderly parents into going online and interviews his wife,
Marjorie Silver, and young daughter, Lucy, about the effects of
computers on their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The more people Block interviews, the more the film seems to
reinforce cliched images of computer nerds as brainy neurotics who
resort to sophisticated high-tech mind games to try to surmount
discomfort in their own bodies. The relationship of Julie Petersen,
her husband, Jim, and her boyfriend, Patrick Farley, is offered as
a utopian paradigm for cybersexual liberation. While Julie traveled
across the country with Patrick, they related running accounts of
their affair on their personal home pages. Jim insists that he was
grateful for their accounts because it was ``better than living in
the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Carl Steadman, one of the movie's few voices of reason,
observes, endless communication doesn't change human nature.
``People disagree,'' he admits. ``And you very well might not like
your neighbor's opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in front of a giant teddy bear, Steadman, the boyish
founder of his own satirical Webzine, continues: ``We've gone from
this state where the Web was going to offer the perfect
communications medium where everyone could talk to everyone else
and their differences would be erased to this fallout where it's
not as we planned, and the Net is not going to provide what we
wanted it to provide, and it's not going to make us rich. There's
no revolution at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `HOME PAGE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Doug Block; director of photography,
Block; edited by Deborah Rosenberg; music by Elephant Ears;
produced by Block, Jane Weiner and Esther Robinson; released by
Copacetic Pictures, Home Box Office and ZDF Arte.
</P>
<P>
   With: Justin Hall, Lucy Block, Doug Block, Patrick Farley, Julie
Petersen, Jim Petersen, Howard Rheingold, Judi Rose, John Seabrook,
Marjorie Silver, Josh Silver, Carl Steadman and J. Carew Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 102 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
