<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-PILOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US AGENTS CONTINUE PROBE OF CO-PILOT IN PLANE'S FATAL DIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Crash-Cairo; i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS AND ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Egyptian officials arrived here to examine and
help interpreting the final remarks made by two of that country's
most veteran pilots, FBI agents continued to gather information on
co-pilot Gamil El Batouty, the man suspected of putting EgyptAir
Flight 990 into a dive from which it could not recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything indicates it was him, but there has to by a why, a
motive, and nothing jumps out,'' said a source familiar with the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Agents were believed to be interviewing everyone who knew
Batouty. He spent much time in Southern California, where his
10-year-old daughter was undergoing medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Egyptian officials who arrived here Thursday _
included senior security staff and technical experts _ began
preparing what the National Transportation Safety Board described
as a ``literal, factual transcript'' of the cockpit voice recorder.
That task was expected to take several days.
</P>
<P>
   The Cairo-bound Boeing 767-300ER had taken off from New York's
John F. Kennedy International Airport on Oct. 31 and was 30 minutes
into the 11-hour flight when it suddenly began a steep, controlled
descent from 33,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the harrowing roller-coaster ride came to an end
when the jet broke apart and smashed into the Atlantic Ocean about
60 miles south of Nantucket, killing all 217 people on board.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty, a veteran pilot who was not scheduled to fly the
airplane for several more hours, had received permission to do so
and was alone in the cockpit when the dive began.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the cockpit voice recorder captures in Arabic what
apparently is a prayer: ``I made my decision now. I put my faith in
God's hands.'' The voice is believed to be Batouty's.
</P>
<P>
   The jet's flight data recorder shows the autopilot was
disconnected, and eight seconds later the plane went into its death
dive.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence gathered from the flight data and cockpit voice
plane's recorders _ the two ``black boxes'' _ points to a cockpit
struggle for control of the doomed jet.
</P>
<P>
   One voice, believed to be that of Captain Ahmed El Habashi, the
pilot is heard exclaiming, ``What's going on?'' Within seconds, he
urged the co-pilot to ``Pull with me! Help me! Pull with me!''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe that remark refers to Habashi's attempt to
bring the plane out of the dive by pulling back on one of the twin
yokes in the cockpit. The theory is bolstered by the unusual
position of the plane's elevators, flaps on the rear section of the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   The left one, on the pilot's side, was pointed up _ something
that would give the plane lift. But the right one, on the
co-pilot's side, was pointed down, the position for a dive.
</P>
<P>
   Further troubling is data indicating the speed brake _ flaps on
the wing which increase the rate of descent and make it harder for
the plane to climb _ had been deployed. The speed brake handle is
located on the pilot's side of the aisle console, but could be
reached easily by either pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Within 35 seconds of the auto-pilot's disconnection, as the
plane hurtled earthward at speeds that exceeded its design, data
shows the twin engines were both shut down. About 14 seconds later,
the plane's transponder stopped working and its two black boxes
shut off.
</P>
<P>
   While some have speculated the engine shutdown may have been a
gross error, or a preparation for an emergency water landing, one
aviation source familiar with the investigation discounted that.
The source also noted that cutting engine power is a deliberate,
two-step action that could have put the jet in more peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the those speeds, it would have been impossible to relight
the engines and the only reason to shut them down is to crash the
airplane,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Other sources said it is likely the other members of the flight
crew, seated in First Class, could not have gotten to the cockpit
to assist because the dive was so steep it caused a sense of
weightlessness inside the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   While investigators have not ruled out mechanical failure as the
cause of the crash, there have been no indications of that yet. If
the theory that Batouty was responsible holds, then the FBI will
take over the criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said Thursday he expected a
decision within days on whether the bureau will assume full control
of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any decisions are going to take an extended
period of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While US officials were cooperating with Egyptian officials,
Holder said, they were not allowing them to block progress of the
inquiry. ``The investigation has not in any way been put at risk,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will seek to work with the Egyptian government and try to
maintain this partnership that we have formed,'' he said. But if
the crash was an act of terrorism, ``our law would cover that
sitation and give the United States government jurisdiction in that
matter, and the FBI would likely be the investigative agency,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, agents would face the daunting task of
trying to determine the motives of the veteran military and
civilian pilot. Friends and relatives have described as a contented
man with five children, including 10-year-old Aya who was being
treated for lupus in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might make sense if the daughter's condition was worsening,
but she was getting better,'' said Vince Cannistraro, former head
of counter terrorism at the CIA. ``Secondly, if the medical bills
were overwhelming that could be a reason, but he comes from a
fairly well-to-do family and the bills were not that onerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he'd spent years at the airline, Batouty, 59, and facing
retirement in March, could have been disappointed that his company,
state-run EgyptAir, had never promoting him to Captain. Family
members have said Batouty was not unhappy with his airline career.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happened in the US, we wouldn't think twice about it,
we'd just say the guy went postal,'' said Cannistraro.
</P>
<P>
   But because suicide is so unusual in Egypt, the act of
deliberately downing the jet would seem even more baffling.
</P>
<P>
   Both Holder and State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin warned
against a ``rush to judgment'' about the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said ``wild conspiracy theories'' by the Arab media and
``speculative conclusions'' in the American press would only
heighten tensions on both sides of the Atlantic. Though he insisted
relations between the two countries remain stable, he issued a plea
for calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have confidence that Egypt and the United States will
work together on this investigation,'' Rubin said. ``Our long and
close friendship will not be harmed because we have confidence that
the Egyptian government, like the United States government, wants
to get to the bottom of this crash and find out what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   As the diplomatic efforts continued, the search for human
remains, and efforts to locate the jet's cockpit, continued in the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The salvage ship Carolyn Chouest Thursday resumed the search
that had been postponed earlier in the week because of rough seas.
It is expected to be joined by a 520-foot ship used to install oil
rigs, is expected to arrive on scene early next month. The Smit
Pioneer, working under contract with the US Navy, will lead the
salvage effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
