<HEADLINE>
`SECRET DEFENSE': MOURNING, SELF-INDUCED, CERTAINLY BECOMES
ELECTRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly three hours, Sandrine Bonnaire grimly mopes through
``Secret Defense,'' French director Jacques Rivette's dreary
contemporary retelling of the Electra myth. Ms. Bonnaire is Sylvie,
a dour cancer researcher who is interrupted one day in her
laboratory by her emotionally distraught younger brother Paul
(Gregoire Colin), who arrives toting a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting he has evidence that their father, who ran a
guided-missile factory, was murdered by his right-hand man, Walser
(Jerzy Radziwilowicz), Paul announces that he intends to avenge the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Paul is certain that their father, instead of accidentally
falling from a moving train, was pushed. As proof, he produces a
snapshot found among his father's belongings showing Walser, who
claimed to be elsewhere, standing several feet from their father at
the station platform shortly before his death.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, written by the director with Pascal Bonitzer and
Emmanuelle Cuau, doesn't begin to make the details of the story
credible. Yet the movie is reasonably well acted ( Radziwilowicz's
porcine Walser is a weirdly ambiguous semi-villain) and sustains an
atmosphere of glum mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvie, deciding that her brother is too unstable to carry out
the murder, decides to do it herself. And the scenes of the taut,
nervous scientist determinedly boarding a series of trains on her
way to kill Walser have a hypnotic suspense. Confronting Walser at
his lavish country estate with its glowing red interiors, Sylvie
draws a gun but is intercepted by his secretary and girlfriend
Veronique (Laure Marsac). As the two women wrestle over the weapon,
it goes off, accidentally killing Veronique. For the rest of the
film _ and it has a long way to go _ Sylvie is so stricken with
guilt and fear that she can barely speak.
</P>
<P>
   Walser, to Sylvie's amazement, disposes of Veronique's body and
enlists her as an ally in covering up the death. Complicating
matters is the arrival of Sylvie's younger sister Ludivine (Ms.
Marsac). Walser's bizarre strategy for allaying Ludivine's possible
suspicions is to promptly seduce her. It also develops that
Sylvie's mother, Genevieve (Francoise Fabian) might somehow be in
cahoots with Walser. But why? Might it have something to do with
the death years many earlier of Sylvie's teen-age sister Elizabeth?
And why are the technicians at a top-secret project in Walser's
company walking around in rubber space suits?
</P>
<P>
   As the glacially paced film inches forward with its halting
conversations and accusatory glances, it tests your patience. And
when the truth ultimately tumbles out and more violence erupts,
don't expect a catharsis.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SECRET DEFENSE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jacques Rivette; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Pascal Bonitzer, Emmanuelle Cuau and Rivette;
director of photography, William Lubtchansky; edited by Nicole
Lubtchansky; music by Jordi Savall; produced by Martine Marignac
and Maurice Tinchant; released by Artificial Eye. With: Sandrine
Bonnaire (Sylvie), Jerzy Radziwilowicz (Walser), Laure Marsac
(Veronique/Ludivine), Gregoire Colin (Paul) and Francoise Fabian
(Genevieve).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 170 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
