s f BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$A     11-18 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bolstering Your Career, Off the Time Clock &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Volunteering _ whether to help children, the elderly, the
homeless or the hungry _ translates into improved performance on
the job and, sometimes, better jobs.
</P>
<P>
   That is the conclusion of John Raynolds, the author of
``Volunteering: How Service Enriches Your Life _ and How Its
Unexpected Halo Effect Boosts Your Career'' (Golden Books, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Raynolds is chief executive of the National Peace Garden
Foundation, having come to that post through some pro bono
consulting work he did for the National Executive Service Corps.
While putting a dollar value on volunteer work is impossible, he
said, it helps people become better workers _ improving their
confidence and cheerfulness _ and can open career doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unexpected results are beneficial,'' he said. ``If you're
demonstrating some sort of skill in the volunteer arena, the people
you meet think of you when an opportunity comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer work is also an indicator of character, he added. In
his work as an executive with the Ward Howell search firm, when
faced with choosing between two candidates of similar strengths, he
said he often picked the one whose resume included volunteer work.
</P>
<P>
   Raynolds estimated that about 50 percent of all adults
participate in some form of volunteer work _ and not just during
the holidays. The work ranges from the hands-on (think soccer coach
or soup-kitchen helper) to the clerical (stuffing envelopes for a
political campaign).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this has come about because our society is so
fragmented, and people are looking for ways to connect to their
communities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers may be connecting, but they are doing it in fewer
hours. Independent Sector, a Washington research group, found that
the average volunteer last year cut back on time by nearly an hour
a week, to 3.5 hours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Constance L. Hays &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giving Parents a Helping Hand &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Help with parenting is sprouting from an unexpected source:
employers.
</P>
<P>
   C.R. Laurence, a hardware manufacturer and distributor in Los
Angeles, gave its 675 employees nationwide and in Canada a copy of
``How to Raise Emotionally Healthy Children'' (NMI Publishers,
1999), a 150-page book by Dr. Gerald Newmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in family values, and giving the book to our
employees is a way to enhance these values among our staff,'' said
Michael Sedano, the company's human resources director.
</P>
<P>
   On the same wavelength, Tommy Hilfiger U.S.A. in Manhattan
sponsored a voluntary two-day off-site parenting workshop for its
area executive staff members and their significant others.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Shapiro, vice president of human resources, said the
company ``believes in the well-being of children and wanted to make
available for our employees the tools necessary for understanding
and living with today's children.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Pronk, a principal with William M. Mercer, the human
resources consulting firm, said that in the last few years
companies have been providing more educational information on
topics important to employees' lives. ``They are doing these
things,'' Ms. Pronk said, ``for very positive reasons.'' _Alisa
Tang
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
