<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CLUTTER IN THE CAR STOPS HERE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, Minn. _ On most days, Don Storholm, an
unpretentious 60-year-old who wears a Mickey Mouse watch, does
business out of his car. For 27 years, he has made a comfortable
living estimating costs for construction projects in the
Minneapolis-St. Paul area, using his mobile office as a base.
</P>
<P>
   But working out of a car can mean chaos: Papers, pens and files
can roll off seats or tumble from the dashboard into under-the-seat
oblivion. To solve the problem, Storholm tried flimsy plastic car
organizers that rest between the seats, but they, too, jumped
around.
</P>
<P>
   So Storholm, in true entrepreneurial fashion, has turned his
need for mobile order into a business, and has been so successful
in turning out a decidedly low-tech solution _ the Executive Auto
Desk _ that he may soon quit his day job.
</P>
<P>
   Storholm is part of a growing legion of people who spend their
days in mobile caves. (italics)``Working(end italics) in their
cars?'' said Faith Popcorn, the trend forecaster. ``People are
(italics)living(end italics) in their cars _ running businesses,
eating, sleeping, studying, giving birth, talking on the phone,
changing their clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   About six years ago, when Storholm got ink on the red velour
interior of a new car, his wife, Sharon, 56, a secretary at a land
development company, didn't just put her foot down _ she picked up
her hammer and nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``She marched out to the garage and just started pounding boards
together,'' her husband recalled. A congenial guy, handy with
tools, he took over and created a portable desk that provided a
flat work surface, a nonskid pad so pens and pencils couldn't roll
away and slots for files, cell phone, laptop computer and fax
machine. There are also compartments for maps, tape measures and an
adding machine. Mrs. Storholm added a detachable wastebasket.
</P>
<P>
   Storholm's work became so much more orderly that he found
himself entering nine bids a day, not the usual seven. And when
clients stuck their heads into his four-wheeled haven, they were
impressed. ``Wow, you're really organized!''' he recalled them
saying.
</P>
<P>
   End of story? Not quite. Other people in the construction trades
told him they could use such desks in their cars and trucks. So he
started making desks for them, too. Then he started receiving
orders from meter readers, real estate brokers, home health care
workers and street pavers.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Storholms had created a sideline that threatened
to overwhelm them. After they set up a Web site (which is now being
reconfigured), orders arrived from as far away as Japan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Mrs. Storholm realized the need for a patent. ``I said
to Don, `When we're in the nursing home we'll be able to say we at
least tried,''' she said. On a car trip to the East Coast, they
went to Washington to turn in their patent application in person.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, two years and one rejection later, their Executive Auto
Desk was officially protected. Of the initial rejection, Storholm
said, ``They didn't like my drawings, so I had to hire an
architecture student to do them on a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Storholms received a plaque from the Minnesota
Inventors Congress proclaiming their prototype work the best
combination of aesthetics, oral presentation and working model.
Asked about the award, which he had to dig out of a closet,
Storholm shook his head with the modesty befitting a Midwesterner
coming face to face with personal achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to be an inventor,'' he said. ``This one is the
first and the last.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand quickly outstripped the couple's ability to build the
desks themselves, so they found a cabinetmaker in St. Paul to
produce them in cherry and mahogany. They now come in three sizes _
for compact cars, full-size cars and trucks. The price is $110 to
$339, depending on the size and whether the desk is assembled
before sale.
</P>
<P>
   The desk, which sits on the passenger seat, looks functional but
elegant. Secured by a seat belt and a cinch strap, it can be easily
removed and stored in the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who like talking on the cell phone and applying mascara
using the rear-view mirror, take note: to work at the Auto Desk,
pull over first. Storholm, father of five, grandfather of seven and
a safety-first kind of guy, slaps a big warning label on every unit
saying exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to control people,'' he conceded, throwing up his
hands. ``But you'd have to be loony to use this while driving. If
this is a problem, they'll have to put warning labels on McDonald's
hamburgers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Storholms are on the brink of going from proprietors of a
mom-and-pop shop to being co-chief executives. The next step is to
find distributors and retailers, then perhaps license the product
to a manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The Storholms seem to be traveling the right road.
DaimlerChrysler recently began offering buyers of its Mercedes-Benz
vans in Europe a backseat office option (the Storholms' patent is
for a front-seat desk), with a bevy of high-tech goodies, for
$12,000.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Bloomington, the Storholms find that most buyers are
men, given that many orders come from the construction industry.
But some women can't help but notice that the Auto Desk can easily
double as a vanity, to store nail polish, perfume and earrings.
``It's the perfect place to put on makeup,'' Mrs. Storholm
whispered, ``but I'd never say that in front of Don.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4327 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-CLINTON-PIPELINE-HNS &LR;      11-18 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PIPELINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S SECURES `HISTORIC' PIPELINE DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ The old Silk Road may soon carry oil and gas
_ and give the United States unprecedented influence over the
energy-rich former Soviet republics in the Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton watched as the presidents of Azerbaijan,
Georgia, Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan joined U.S. ally Turkey to
sign separate deals for multibillion-dollar oil and gas pipelines
that may be as important for geopolitics as for energy
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The pipelines would lessen Russia's influence over the former
Soviet empire and bypass Iran, a key U.S. goal. The pipelines also
would enhance the international standing of Turkey, the most
reliable U.S. friend in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``These agreements we just signed are truly historic. They will
advance the prosperity and security of the region critical to the
future of the entire world,'' Clinton said after the signing
ceremony at Ciragan Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``These pipelines will be an insurance policy for the entire
world, helping to ensure that our energy resources pass through
multiple routes, not a single choke point,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials accused the United States of using undo
pressure to secure the agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. administration brought political pressure to bear on
the companies involved in the construction,'' said Ivan Ivanov, a
deputy Russian Foreign Minister quoted by Interfax News Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said Caspian Basin oil should be transported across
Russian territory. ``The infrastructure is already in place,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson hailed the agreements as a
major foreign policy victory for the United States, which worked
for five years to secure approval for the routes that will link the
East to the West just as the Silk Road through the Caucasus region
once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just another oil and gas deal and this is not just
another pipeline,'' Richardson said. ``It is a strategic framework
that advances America's national security interests. It is a
strategic vision for the future of the Caspian region. These
agreements will help fulfill our commitment to the continued
prosperity and independence of the Caspian state.''
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan, Georgia, Kazakhstan and Turkey signed documents for
a $2.4 billion, 1,200-mile oil pipeline that would travel from the
Azeri capital of Baku through Georgia to the Turkish Mediterranean
port of Ceyhan. Kazakhstan oil will be transported on the
Baku-Ceyhan pipeline once its completed, hopefully in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The four nations and Turkmenistan approved another document for
a $2.7 billion, 1,200-mile natural gas pipeline across the Caspian
Sea to Turkey expected to open in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Turkmen President Sapamurat Niyazov said the Trans-Caspian gas
line will help nurture the region's independence. ``Today, with the
support of the United States, this project has gotten off the
ground,'' Niyazov said. He also asked Clinton to give his nation
``a helping and supportive hand'' in their efforts to build a
pipeline toward Asia to supply China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey and the former Soviet republics, all emerging democracies
with their own internal rivalries, moved forward with the
Baku-Ceyhan oil pipeline despite some skepticism within the energy
industry over its viability.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson defended the Baku-Ceyhan project as ``commercially
viable'' and predicted its feasibility will be proven once a
financing package goes to the market.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton again pledged to work with those nations to put together
a commercial financing package through the Export-Import Bank, the
Overseas Private Investment Corporation, and the Trade and
Development Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, as part of the agreement, guaranteed it would pay for
any cost overruns above $1.4 billion, the cost of the pipeline
going through its territory. The United States has not committed
any funds.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the oil consortium Azerbaijan International Operating
Co. produces 115,000 barrels per day. Much of its oil is
transported on a 100,000-barrel-per day pipeline from Baku to
Supsa, a Black Sea port in Georgia. The Baku-Ceyhan capacity will
be 1 million barrels a day, far in excess of what's being produced
now.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco, the lead firm in the Azeri consortium, has embraced
the pipeline, but several U.S. companies are reluctant. The Caspian
Basin reserves are projected to be on par with the North Sea but a
major find is still elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North Sea, when that was developed, first brought 100 dry
holes before any substantial resources were found. We are confident
that this has enormous resources,'' Richardson told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian-controlled pipeline from Baku traverses Chechnya, a
rebellious province being pounded by the Russian military. Russia
plans to build a pipeline around that troubled area.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also has plans for a gas pipeline called Blue Stream
under the Black Sea. It strongly objected to both the Baku-Ceyhan
oil pipeline and the Trans-Caspian gas pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-backed routes to the Mediterranean also are being
promoted as more environmentally safe than Russia's Black Sea plan
or Baku-Supsa route that requires tanker traffic to pass through
the narrow Bosphorus, the historic waterway out of the Black Sea
that flows through Istanbul and serves as the dividing line between
Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
