<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON LEARNS SILENCE IS NOT ALWAYS GOLDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the perilous political cauldron of the Middle
East, Hillary Rodham Clinton has learned a valuable lesson about
running for public office: Sometimes silence about a crucial issue
can generate as much criticism as exaggerated and ill-informed
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   For the first lady, who would like to become the junior senator
from New York, the incident occurred in the West Bank city of
Ramallah on Nov. 11 when she listened quietly to a blistering
denunciation of Israel by Suha Arafat, wife of the Palestinian
leader.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton sitting near her on a platform, Arafat charged
Israel with using toxic gas to put down Palestinian riots and of
contaminating the water supply. Although Clinton might have
responded publicly with an attack on Arafat's credibility, she said
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   From the point of view of good manners, she did the right thing.
Suha Arafat was her hostess, and the two had embraced warmly when
they met.
</P>
<P>
   From the point of view of a candidate for the public office in
New York, she did the wrong thing. The state has a large Jewish
population that is dedicated to the preservation of Israel and
defensive against critics of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Clinton's anticipated Republican
opponent, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, to castigate her for not
immediately rejecting Arafat's assault on Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He told City Hall reporters that, had he been there, he would
have objected to Arafat's attack. ``I would have made my position
clear,'' said the mayor, ``and I wouldn't have embraced the person
who said it ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton waited a day _ after clearing her remarks with the White
House _ to criticize Suha Arafat's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, who still has not announced her decision to seek
the Senate seat, will find as she moves into a full-fledged
campaign that many Republican brickbats will be flying her way.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the political furor over the Arafat incident is
that Clinton has been a loyal friend of Israel. She drew
unfavorable comments from some Jewish leaders for declaring a few
months ago that a free and independent Palestine nation should be
established. But her proposal is one that, according to public
opinion polls, is favored by a majority of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Her explanation that she remained silent because she did not
want to do anything to interfere with the peace process did not
deter critics from attacking her.
</P>
<P>
   There probably will be times when Clinton wishes she had adhered
to the policy adopted by her role model, Eleanor Roosevelt, after
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Some months after Franklin D. Roosevelt's death in April 1945,
Interior Secretary Harold Ickes and a group of New York Democrats
urged her to run for the Senate in 1946. Their plan called for
Democratic Sen. James Mead to run for governor against Thomas E.
Dewey and for the former first lady to become Mead's successor in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   With Roosevelt on the ticket, they explained, Mead could
probably defeat Dewey, who had run unsuccessfully for president
against her husband in 1944. They even proposed that the party
draft her _ a move that would have proved immensely popular with
New York Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But Roosevelt was adamant in her refusal to seek elective
office.
</P>
<P>
   Her biographer, Joseph P. Lash, explained that she ``wanted to
be free to speak out, a freedom she would have to surrender in
taking public office.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article written for Look Magazine in the summer of 1946,
Roosevelt said: ``If I do not run for office, I am not beholden to
my party. What I give, I give freely and I am too old (at age 62)
to want to be curtailed in any way in the expression of my own
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The former first lady explained that she preferred her work at
the United Nations, where she was a member of the U.S. delegation.
</P>
<P>
   In that bygone era, 53 years ago, Eleanor Roosevelt noted that
``no woman has, as yet, has been able to build up and hold
sufficient leadership to carry through a program.'' What is the
purpose of holding elective office, she asked, if you could not put
through a program.
</P>
<P>
   With the passing years, women have moved up in the government
hierarchy. Today we have four women in the Cabinet, 58 in the House
of Representatives and nine in the Senate. In 1946 there were 10 in
the House and none in the Cabinet or Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But as Hillary Clinton has learned, the road to elective office
remains strewn with hazards and with political partisans who are
anxious to see her stumble over them. If she is to win the Senate
race, she must shield herself to repulse attacks on her knowledge,
her courage, her husband and her ability to know when to speak and
when to remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if she were to have a conversation with Roosevelt, as she
claims to have done in the past, she might decide that she can live
without being a senator.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson can be reached at 202-298-6920.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
