<HEADER>
A4332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GOLDCLUB19-COX     11-18 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDCLUB19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broad charges against club typical of attempts to nab organized
crime
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The sweeping federal charges against an Atlanta strip
club range from violent mob-related crime to prostitution. It is
the type of loaded indictment that prosecutors have used to attack
organized crime since Al Capone was convicted of tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Other prosecutorial tools _ such as the broad Rackeeteering
Corrupt-Influenced Organization law, or RICO, and property
confiscation rule _ have been added over the years. But the goal is
the same: shutting down organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the very expansion of these tools brings an inherent set of
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among them is helping a jury follow the complex and
often interrelated charges that have allegedly piled up over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   One criminal defense attorney, Jerry Froelich, questioned the
wisdom of the government bringing such a complicated indictment
against the club, with charges dating back more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be a very large mistake,'' Froelich said. ``I've
always felt the toughest cases to defend against are the shortest
and tightest ... Lengthy cases can lose jurors. They become tired
and weary. The government can put up so many people who have been
given deals, it can boomerang against them big time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Art Leach, who is no stranger to
lengthy trials, said this case has enough interesting details to
keep a jury's attention. And the case does not have to be long if
many of the defendants plead guilty, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept behind RICO is to bring together before one
jury the totality of what has occurred in the enterprise,'' he
said. ``There are things that we as lawyers can do to try and make
the case move quickly and stay interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach was the federal prosecutor in one of the longest federal
racketeering cases in Atlanta this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The three-month trial of 10 members of the ``Loc Lam gang''
included six weeks of jury deliberations on 209 charges. Seven gang
members were convicted. Mistrials were declared against the three
others because the jury deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
   The Gold Club indictment, unsealed Wednesday, lodges charges
against club owner Steven Kaplan and 15 others, including four who
were not club employees. According to the indictment, the nude
dance club overbilled customers, provided free sex to celebrities
and prostitution to patrons. Club officials are accused of bribing
Atlanta police officers, loansharking, obstructing justice and
skimming cash from the club to evade taxes and buy Gambino family
protection.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the club and Kaplan strongly denied the charges
and predicted they will be completely vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   Leach said he hopes at least some of the defendants, once they
have digested the 97-page indictment, will decide not to fight the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they sit there in their homes and offices and realize what
we know, they will make decisions as to what they need to do and
what's best for them,'' Leach said. ``We would welcome their pleas
of guilty and assistance in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the goal of the FBI and IRS investigation goes beyond
convicting the nude dance club and Kaplan. Federal prosecutors want
this case to lead them deeper into the club's alleged ties with the
Gambino crime family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a continuing investigation and it's broader than this
case,'' Leach said Thursday. ``The investigation clearly includes
people within the organized crime family.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that some of those involved in the criminal
enterprise _ either those indicted who elect to plead guilty or
sources who already have come forward _ will become prosecution
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You typically need insider witnesses to prove a case like
this,'' Atlanta criminal defense attorney Jack Martin said. ``I
suspect they have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jim Deichert, a former federal prosecutor who once headed
the organized crime strike force in Atlanta: ``When you prosecute
organized crime, you use whatever you've got, whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of Atlanta, meanwhile, was considering its own response
to the charges against the club. Mayor Bill Campbell said he will
decide by noon Monday whether to revoke the club's liquor license.
</P>
<P>
   The city's code allows the mayor to suspend a liquor license if
he finds an establishment endangers the health, safety and welfare
of the public.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor may issue an emergency suspension, which would stay in
effect at least until the next meeting of the Liquor License Review
Board on Dec. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Jay Croft contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
