<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4341 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ENEMY-THEATER-REVIEW-     11-18 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENEMY-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CONTACT WITH THE ENEMY': A WARTIME MEMORY THAT RIVALS THE
HOLOCAUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even in a great movie like ``The Best Years of Our
Lives'' (1946), World War II didn't look like such a traumatizing
experience. True, Dana Andrews' character couldn't get his old job
at the drugstore back, and he learned that his superficial wife
loved him only when he was looking handsome in uniform. But Fredric
March just went back to his cushy job at the bank and into the
bosom of his beautiful family. And even Harold Russell, who had
lost his hands in the war, was all right once he realized that his
understanding girl-next-door fiancee loved him enough to deal with
that.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't hear these guys talk about being permanently damaged
psychologically because of the horrors they couldn't put behind
them. As Tom Brokaw said outright in his recent book ``The Greatest
Generation,'' ``They were proud of what they accomplished, but they
rarely discussed their experiences, even with each other.'' Vietnam
veterans, on the other hand, talked, and Francis Ford Coppola made
``Apocalypse Now,'' and some people got the idea that dealing with
the horror of war was something new.
</P>
<P>
   The two World War II veterans in Frank D. Gilroy's affecting new
one-act play, ``Contact With the Enemy,'' belong to the old school.
When these old Army buddies meet by chance at the entrance of the
Holocaust Museum in Washington, they're the picture of
well-adjusted all-Americans. Hank Naylor (Nesbitt Blaisdell) seems
the more repressed of the two. Bill Duffy (Christopher Murney) is
open enough to say, even before the museum doors open, that this
visit is ``like going back to a bad dream.'' But soon enough Hank,
asked to describe the day their outfit saw a concentration camp, is
remembering ``the bodies stacked five high like cordwood.''
</P>
<P>
   We have met Duffy before, in ``Getting In,'' Gilroy's 1997
one-act play about a young Army veteran who is determined to go to
Dartmouth. Like Gilroy, still best known for his Pulitzer
Prize-winning 1964 play, ``The Subject Was Roses,'' Bill was born
in 1926, grew up in the Bronx, went to Dartmouth on the GI Bill,
became a writer and at one point saw Ohrdruf, a concentration camp
in what became East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of the play is that the men's firsthand view of the
Holocaust is not what has been haunting them all these years. An
even more terrible memory drives one of them to drink that day,
after years of sobriety, and to propose an unlikely toast to Boris
Becker. It was something that happened right after Ohrdruf _ or was
it right before? That is the crucial question, both men admit, as
they try to deal with what it says about them personally and about
the shakiness of human morality overall.
</P>
<P>
   Murney seems a bit young for his role, and when the script calls
for catharsis, the two men don't always rise to the occasion, but
Gilroy's play makes its point quietly and thoughtfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contact With the Enemy,'' directed by Chris Smith, continues
at Ensemble Studio Theater through Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CONTACT WITH THE ENEMY'
</P>
<P>
   By Frank D. Gilroy; directed by Chris Smith; set by Kert
Lundell; lighting by Michael Lincoln; costumes by Julie Doyle;
sound by Beatrice Terry; production stage manager, Jim Ring;
associate producer, Edward Miller. Presented by the Ensemble Studio
Theater, Curt Dempster, artistic director; M. Edgar Rosenblum,
executive director; Jamie Richards, executive producer. At 549 W.
52nd St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Nesbitt Blaisdell (Hank Naylor), Christopher Murney (Bill
Duffy), Kathryn Gayner (Guide), Cynthia Hayden (Mrs. Grayson) and
Paul Bartholomew (Bartender).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4342 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BALCONY-THEATER-REVIE     11-18 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALCONY-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BALCONY': UNTANGLING GENET'S PUZZLE OF POWER, LOST AND FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Irma, the madam who has been queen for a day,
dismisses all her prostitutes and customers at the end of the Jean
Cocteau Repertory's production of ``The Balcony'' and stands alone
in her house as the lights go down, a wave of sadness sweeps the
theater. That is exactly the right feeling: the world has been
emptied, for her and for us.
</P>
<P>
   Given the usually comic scenes preceding, that realization is a
jolt. But this Jean Genet play _ about men who pretend in a brothel
to be powerful figures in society and who, after an upheaval, are
thrust into the positions they dreamed of _ is peculiarly
malleable. It is as though Genet, in his many revisions of the
play, stripped it of all authorial intention to force the director
to give it meaning. It can be a political tract, a social satire, a
farce, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   In this production, the director, Eve Adamson, has made it a
psychological puzzle, handing on to the audience much of the task
of supplying meaning, and that twist at the end makes one rethink
the entire piece. As a result some viewers may think Ms. Adamson
might have imagined a few earlier scenes very differently, but none
can deny that the whole performance, every breath and motion, is
hers.
</P>
<P>
   This repertory company is an excellent vehicle for such an
exercise. The actors can pile role on role, like Russian dolls, and
keep us keenly aware of the separate personalities and different
emotional tugs of war and mental games entangling each of them.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Jason Crowl, as a royal emissary, turns up after the
revolution, here called the intermission, to persuade Irma to be
queen and her loutish clients to become bishops, judges and
generals even while he seems to be arguing that there was no
revolution and never had been a social hierarchy at all. And you
wish he'd been given enough lines to spin this out for another
hour, since he seems to believe several versions of his story.
</P>
<P>
   Irma (Elise Stone) has the proverbial heart of gold and really
loves her favorite visitor, the chief of police (Craig Smith). But
he doubts his authenticity, since none of her clients, who get
sexual thrills from fantasies of power, want to be him. Then, when
Irma becomes queen, a failed revolutionary appears at the royal
brothel, or palace of prostitution if you will, claiming to be the
chief, and the chief fairly flies away, exulting: ``I've done it! I
belong to the ages!''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Irma, with a wave of the hand, banishes everyone
else to the shadows and cries as her world dissolves in darkness:
``But what about me? I'm still alive.'' She speaks, alas, for us.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BALCONY'
</P>
<P>
   By Jean Genet; translated by Bernard Frechtman; direction and
lighting by Eve Adamson; sets by Robert Klingelhoffer; costumes by
Margaret McKowen; production manager, Jonathan R. Polgar; sound by
Christopher Martin. Presented by the Jean Cocteau Repertory, David
Fuller, artistic director. At the Bouwerie Lane Theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Elise Stone (Madame Irma), Harris Berlinsky (the Bishop),
Christopher Black (the judge), Tim Deak (the General), Angela
Madden (the penitent), Craig Smith (Chief of Police) and Jason
Crowl (the Queen's Envoy).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
