<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN AND WESTERN LEADERS EXCHANGE CRITICISM OVER CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ President Boris Yeltsin and the West squared
off over Chechnya on Thursday, as the Russian leader told a
European summit meeting that the West had no right to criticize
Russia for its campaign against ``bandits and murderers.''
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton insisted that the West was only trying to
do for Chechnya's civilians what it would have done for Yeltsin
himself when he was on the barricades: defend their rights against
the abusive authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom since the end of the Cold War has Russia appeared so
isolated on the world stage as one by one, Western leaders at the
meeting of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
declared that Russia's indiscriminate bombardment of Chechnya was
needlessly killing and wounding its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, looking unusually hale and combative, mocked the idea
that the plight of civilians justified Western meddling in Russian
affairs. He branded the calls for peace talks as hopelessly naive.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the sharp human rights debates of Soviet times, the
criticism of Moscow on Thursday was more in sorrow than in anger,
as Western officials lectured Russia that its treatment of
civilians in Chechnya fell below civilized norms.
</P>
<P>
   In surprisingly personal remarks, Clinton sought to justify the
West's intercession over Chechnya by recalling how Yeltsin
clambered onto a tank to prevent an assault on his government
headquarters by hard-line Communists during the final days of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Yeltsin, one of the most thrilling experiences of my
life as a citizen of the world before I become president was when
you stood up on that tank in Moscow when they tried to take the
freedom of the Russian people away,'' Clinton said. ``If they had
put you in jail instead of electing you president, I would have
hoped that every leader of every country around this table would
have stood up for you, and not said, well, that is an internal
Russian affair that we cannot be part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin listened attentively to Clinton and later gave him a
bear hug. Still, there was no sign that the Russian leader had been
persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton and other leaders argued that moral considerations
sometimes justified intervention in another nation's affairs _
military action in the case of Kosovo and public criticism in case
of Chechnya _ Yeltsin ridiculed the notion as ``humanitarian
interference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no right to criticize Russia for Chechnya,'' Yeltsin
said at the 54-nation meeting. ``There will be no negotiations with
bandits and murderers.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the public fireworks, the Russians also pressed privately
to deflect the West's criticism of their Chechnya policy.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov gave American officials a
diplomatic paper that hinted Russia would drop some of its
objections to American policy toward Iraq if Washington offered a
private assurance that the issue of Chechnya would not be brought
before the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   A small measure of agreement was reached when Russia agreed to
allow a representative of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe to visit Chechnya. That was less then the
role in mediating the dispute that some Western governments had
sought for the organization.
</P>
<P>
   But Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said, ``I think we got
a good foot in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   With parliamentary elections only a month away in Russia,
domestic politics appeared to be a significant factor in the firey
tone of Yeltsin's speech. The president and other Russian
politicians have discovered that a hard-nosed policy toward
Chechnya and open defiance of the West has become very popular with
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Grigori Yavlinksy, the leader of the liberal Yabloko party, is
one of the few major Russian politicians who have even broached the
idea of negotiating with the Chechens, and for that he has branded
a virtual traitor by some capitalist reformers, including Anatoly
Chubais.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even though the fighting has created more than 200,000 refugees,
many of them ethnic Russians, many Russians seem to think this is
an acceptable price to hunt down the Islamic militants who invaded
Dagestan last summer and who are generally blamed for a spate of
terror bombings in Moscow and other cities. The Chechen guerrilla
leaders accused of the attacks deny the charge.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The antipathy many Russians harbor toward people from the
Caucasus has further tempered their sympathy for the Chechen
refugees. Sergei Shoigu, Russia's minister for emergency
situations, has also sought to defuse the talk of a humanitarian
crisis in Chechnya by asserting that the main fighting would be
over by Feb. 1, and the approximately 200,000 refugees could then
return. Then there is the determination of the Russian military to
avenge its defeat in the 1994-1996 Chechen war, and not only to
subdue Chechnya, but to send a message to the region that Russia is
still a power to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Russian annoyance with the West has been further fanned by a
host of other disputes, including the Clinton administration's
interest in pressing ahead with an anti-missile defense and its
position on oil pipelines in former Soviet areas.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, for example, Clinton watched approvingly as Turkey,
Azerbaijan and Georgia signed an agreement to build a pipeline that
would channel oil from the Caspian Sea to international markets
without passing through Russian or Iranian territory, dealing
another blow to Russian influence in the Caucasus and Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over Chechnya delayed the signing of a new Charter
on European Security, which was to have been concluded on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In criticizing the Russian policy, Western officials sought to
make clear that they agreed that they were not challenging the
Kremlin's right to use military force to put an end to terrorism
and to prevent the nation from fracturing.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, they said, lay in the way Russia was pursuing that
goal _ indiscriminate rocket attacks and bombings that have taken a
heavy civilian toll and have fostered a new generation of
embittered and revenge-minded Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all determined to fight terrorism,'' said Kofi Annan,
the U.N. secretary general. ``But the force we use to fight it
should always be proportional, and focused on the actual
terrorists. We cannot and must not fight them by using their own
methods _ by inflicting indiscriminate violence and terror on
innocent civilians, including children.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerhard Schroeder, the German chancellor, added, ``War is no way
to eliminate terrorism.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As much as such comments irritated the Russians, they fell short
of what some Western critics, such as Zbigniew Brezinski, the
national security adviser under President Jimmy Carter, have urged:
the cut-off or Western credits and assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and other Western leaders were slow to criticize Russia
during the first Chechen war. Clinton, in fact, even likened
Yeltsin then to President Abraham Lincoln during the American Civil
War, while Vice President Al Gore initially insisted that Chechnya
was an internal Russian affair, echoing Moscow's current position.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Thursday's comments by Western officials appeared
designed to persuade their own publics that they are not ignoring
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments were viewed by many observers here as some of
the persuasive. White House officials said that the president
rewrote the remarks as the summit began to include the reference to
Yeltsin standing on the tank. ``The point I was trying to make,''
Clinton told reporters later, ``is there are times in the world we
live in today when we are forced to make judgments about things
that happen within the borders of other countries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
