<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4352 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH19-COX     11-18 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush campaign heads west to California
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ After months of gubernatorial home
schooling, George W. Bush heads to California today for his first
major speech on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   He said he intends to draw a ``stark contrast'' between his
views and those of his GOP presidential rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``America must not retreat within our borders,'' he said in Iowa
Thursday. ``One way to make sure the world is peaceful, as far as
I'm concerned, is to not retreat within our borders.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is elected, Bush said, his administration would
concentrate on four areas: America's ``neighborhood'' of North and
South America, the Middle East, China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   He also brushed aside criticism that as a governor, he is
inexperienced in foreign policy. He noted that three of the
country's last four presidents have been governors and that as
Texas' chief executive, he has had extensive dealings with Mexico.
He also has received intensive tutoring on foreign policy issues
from a team of advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to lead the country,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the policies themselves, the speech offers Bush a
chance to show he has the stuff that presidents are made of. Some
critics, as well as some late-night comedians, have questioned that
as a result of Bush missteps, including his inability pass a
reporter's pop quiz about leaders in world trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some Bush advisers are worried about the image of the
candidate as less-than-smart guy. Throughout this week, they talked
about using today's speech to help counter that by taking questions
afterward, something he did not do at previous policy speeches on
defense, education and faith-based initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has got to give a good speech,'' said Josh Bolten, who has
coordinated the Bush policy team. ``And then he has got to be able
to defend the ideas because he will be questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, as he prepped for his big speech, Bush talked about
the hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people, those are the people who are going to
have the ultimate decision in this campaign. They want somebody
who, who they trust to lead the world to peace,'' he said. ``And
I'm going to make the case that it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not, said Democratic National Committee Chair Joe
Andrew, who branded Bush as a ``cue-card candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is a dangerous world and we need a commander in chief who
can grasp the basic concepts necessary to make our foreign policy
and defense decisions,'' Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of media interviews this week, Bush has been trying
to make his case. And in his autobiography released this week,
Bush, like many Americans, said his view of foreign policy is
colored by what he called the ``the lesson of Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation should be slow to engage troops. But when we do so,
we must do so with ferocity. We must not go into a conflict unless
we go in committed to win,'' he wrote. ``We can never again ask the
military to fight a political war. If America's strategic interests
are at stake, if diplomacy fails, if no other option will
accomplish the objective, the commander in chief must define the
mission and allow the military to achieve it.''
</P>
<P>
   As with all of Bush's major policy speeches, the site for this
one _ the Reagan Presidential Library _ was selected for its
significance: the library is a monument to a chief executive who
had a profound effect on world alignment. But Reagan also struggled
through the Iran-Contra controversy that exposed the secret
underbelly of foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
