<HEADLINE>
A&AMP;M TRAGEDY PUTS TEXAS CABLE NEWS ON THE MAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After playing the role of eager bystander in the reporting of
the Wedgwood Baptist Church shooting, Texas Cable News (TXCN) found
itself a front-runner on a major breaking story Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   From the time the call came in from the ``Bryan-College Station
Eagle'' newspaper around 4:30 a.m., TXCN was up and running with
reports of a freak bonfire log accident at Texas A&AMP;M. As the death
toll grew, so did the aggressiveness of TXCN, a news operation
looking for an opportunity to show why it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   On the air since January, TXCN has quietly built an unwanted
reputation as an ongoing experiment more than as a statewide CNN
wannabe. But Thursday, the station managed to prove to its critics,
at least for the time being, that a 24-hour news channel devoted to
Texas events might not be such a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Although local stations, CNN and MSNBC offered updates and went
live during news conferences, TXCN found itself the news station of
record at intervals, scrolling useful information at the bottom of
the screen, such as where to donate blood and how to contact Texas
A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the cable channel relied heavily on reporting and
footage from sister-station KHOU in Houston (both news operations
are owned by Dallas-based Belo, as is the ``Bryan-College Station
Eagle'' and WFAA/Channel 8), TXCN turned in a rather effective
performance as news-report traffic cop.
</P>
<P>
   But with reporter Brian Giesenschlag, on the scene in College
Station and various anchors in the newsroom, TXCN also established
an identity of its own. And with another big news event the same
day _ the guilty verdict and life sentence handed down in the third
Jasper dragging-death trial _ the little channel that could didn't
do such a bad job. It even managed to provide viewers with Ivan
``Pudge'' Rodriguez's news conference announcing his American
League MVP honor.
</P>
<P>
   Was this the defining moment signaling the arrival of a new news
player in town? ``An opportunity'' is how TXCN general manager Skip
Cass described it. ``We're designed to provide viewers with news
and information during the day. When people come in and show up at
3, they can turn us on, get caught up. Or 4. We're there. This is
why we're here. This is what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
