<HEADER>
A4355 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-UT-TE     11-18 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-UT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.T. STUDENTS SHARE RIVALS' GRIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By THOMAS TERRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _Setting aside their traditional rivalry, shocked
students and officials at the University of Texas offered prayers
and condolences Thursday after a stack of bonfire logs collapsed at
Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of the students, faculty, staff and administration
of the University of Texas at Austin, I extend our deepest sympathy
to the Texas A&AMP;M community as it copes with today's tragic events.
We offer our full support to Texas A&AMP;M as the university confronts
this unfortunate accident,'' UT President Larry Faulkner said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove to the office with a tear in my eye this morning,''
football coach Mack Brown said. ``It makes you want to cry. I can
promise you, nobody here is thinking about football. Our thoughts
and prayers are with those kids and their families, and all of the
people at Texas A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's tragedy occurred as logs from a 40-foot stack came
tumbling while on 60 to 70 students were atop the pile. A bonfire
was to be ignited to ``fire up'' A&AMP;M students for the annual
football game against archrival Texas.
</P>
<P>
   U.T. Student Government President Parisa Fatehi said she and 20
other student government members planned to attend a memorial
service Thursday night in College Station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider them (A&AMP;M students) our friends, our peers, and
just fellow students of Texas,'' Fatehi said. ``We want to share in
this as much as possible, to help them get through this, because it
definitely is a very difficult time.''
</P>
<P>
   Many U.T. students called friends at A&AMP;M to determine whether
any were involved in the accident. Others said they prayed for
friends at the rival university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a few students in the corps (of cadets) and I know the
prayers of the student body here will go out to them. I hope to get
into contact with them as soon as possible. I know they have been
working on the (log stack), and they have been highly involved,''
said Brad Nadal, a corporate communications senior. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a tragedy that will put a damper on one of A&AMP;M's
fondest traditions _ the bonfire _ (and) I don't think it will ever
be the same,'' said Jessica Patterson, a U.T. junior.
</P>
<P>
   In memory of the victims, the flags in front of the Main
Building were flown at half-staff yesterday and the U.T. Tower will
be darkened Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
