<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     11-18 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BREAKING THE BONDS OF INNOCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was simply a deal about basketball and business, Don Nelson
said. The Dallas Mavericks made a trade with the San Antonio Spurs
on draft day last June. The Mavericks received the Spurs'
first-round pick, the 29th and last of the first round, 19-year-old
Leon Smith out of Martin Luther King High School in Chicago. There
had been a conditional arrangement to have the 6-foot-11-inch Smith
play one season in a developmental league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed like a logical thing for everyone,'' Nelson
said wearily the other day from his hotel room in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   He had just been interrupted from an afternoon nap, recovering
from a wee-hours arrival and the latest news media attack he was
enduring. No stranger to condemnation for his hard-line dealings
with New Age stars, the onetime reputed ``players' coach'' now had
to explain why Smith was in a Dallas psychiatric hospital after the
police said he had ingested approximately 250 aspirin tablets in
what may have been a suicide attempt.
</P>
<P>
   How could this have happened, and could Nelson and the Mavericks
have prevented it? Those were the questions demanding more than
knee-jerk responses.
</P>
<P>
   One conclusion being jumped to was how this was a classic
example _ the more common antithesis of the happily-ever-after
Kevin Garnett story _ of what occurs when a high school player
demonstrates his vertical skills by leaping right to the National
Basketball Association. Another conclusion was that the Mavericks,
once they had involved themselves with a fragile young man who was
raised in various group homes as a ward of the state, were
responsible for his emotional well-being.
</P>
<P>
   And while there is merit in each of those arguments, they are
not necessarily solutions. Convincing a Leon Smith that he
shouldn't turn pro is infinitely harder than telling him not to.
Once he has, who can say that Nelson's proposal wasn't the best way
for Smith to pursue long-term success, while forgoing immediate
gratification at the end of the Dallas bench?
</P>
<P>
   David Stern, the NBA commissioner, has correctly argued that the
quickening pace of teenagers' entry into his league is a business
problem, not a moral issue. Tennis players, Stern argues, have been
quitting college and even high school for years. The difference is
that Lindsay Davenport and Justin Gimelstob don't have to fit into
a team's competitive fabric.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is no social service agency, but Stern's commitment to
creating a healthier working environment for his youngest players
was never as clear as his logic. All these years, his league has
reaped the benefits of a free collegiate farm system. A significant
training league _ the kind Isiah Thomas was talking about after his
recent purchase of the Continental Basketball Association _ would
cost plenty. To Nelson's credit, he at least was willing to pay
Smith a season's salary based on the three-year, $1.4 million
contract set by the guidelines of the NBA's rookie scale.
</P>
<P>
   With his own standing shaky at the controls of a wobbly team,
Nelson said he had arranged through a collective bargaining
``loophole'' for Smith to play for St. Louis of the new
International Basketball League under his longtime friend, Bernie
Bickerstaff. ``It was about experience, not a money thing,'' Nelson
said. ``What these kids need is to play. In what league, it doesn't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith agreed to the plan, his former agent, Dan Fegan, said
Thursday from his office in Los Angeles. ``But then he backed off,
and I told him, `You made a deal,''' Fegan said. Soon Smith had a
new agent, Matt Muehlebach, who said no deal. A stalemate ensued,
until this week, when the Dallas police, responding to a call,
found a groggy Smith, his face smeared with green paint, mumbling
about being an Indian who was ``fighting Columbus.''
</P>
<P>
   Associates of Smith's say the team should have anticipated how a
young man who was separated from his siblings at age 5, who had
become one more statistic in the urban bureaucracy, might have
reacted to becoming another basketball transaction. Nelson said he
was merely trying to do ``what everyone in the league knows we have
to start doing for these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In this unfortunate case, the coach is neither saint nor sinner.
His recent history of bizarre player feuds would suggest he lacked
the sensitivity for a case so extreme. That said, if Smith is the
opposite of Garnett, then between them is a more typical kid who
would benefit from what Nelson had in mind for Smith. That is the
more pragmatic path from high school to pro. Leon Smith was
apparently just the wrong player to walk it alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
