<SLUG> BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-PARENTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF TRAGEDY SENDS PARENTS SCRAMBLIMG FOR INFORMATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE STEIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Collette Andreani's day began at 5:30 a.m. with a phone call
from her youngest son's roommate at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   There had been a terrible accident, she was told. The logs being
stacked for the traditional Thanksgiving week bonfire had
collapsed, and her 18-year-old son, Lino, was helping firefighters
pull logs off the injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just sick; it was just an empty feeling,'' said
Andreani, of Grapevine, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly gathered her wits and called her older son, Nic, 20,
also a student at A&AMP;M. He knew nothing about the accident but said
he would gather his friends, go to the bonfire site and lend
support.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the morning, Andreani was able to talk to Lino, who had
been outside
</P>
<P>
   about 3 a.m. hoping to spot the Leonid meteor shower when he and
his friends heard sirens racing toward the bonfire site.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very shaken when we spoke,'' Andreani said. ``He was
right there when they began to pull bodies from the pile.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreani was fortunate in being able to contact her children at
A&AMP;M, in College Station, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Many panic-stricken parents resorted to calling university
numbers in their desperate attempt for information, said Tim
Sweeney, associate director of student activities at Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell they were just holding on as best they could,''
Sweeney said. ``There was a lot of frustration by parents who could
not find a loved one.''
</P>
<P>
   An information hot line was established, but so many people
called the toll-free number that the system overloaded Thursday
morning, Sweeney said. The phone line was down about 10 to 15
minutes, rolling calls over to the University Police Department,
Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the calls were from parents who knew their students
were working on the bonfire. The majority were from people who just
didn't know, though,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Newton, whose 20-year-old son Nathan attends Texas A&AMP;M,
said he went through an agonizing morning. Because of Nathan's
early-morning job in College Station, it is hard to reach him
before 9 a.m. The Newtons finally connected about 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Newton had difficulties grasping the extent of the tragedy and
how it must be affecting the friends and families of the dead and
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I immediately prayed for all of them,'' said Newton, a former
mayor of Colleyville, Texas. ``It's such a tragedy. You wish there
was something you could do for them, but all you can do is pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Ritter, who teaches at Colleyville-Heritage High School,
received a welcome call about 6:30 a.m. from her 21-year-old son,
Zachary, an A&AMP;M senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you so much for calling,'' she told her son. ``Thank
goodness you've learned we need to hear your voice when something
like this happens.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff writer Bechetta Jackson contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
