<HEADLINE>
DRUG NEEDS MORE TESTING; GENZYME, BIOMARTIN SHARES DROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of both Genzyme Corp. and BioMarin Pharmaceuticals Inc.
fell Thursday after the companies said government regulators want
more testing of a jointly developed drug to treat a rare disease.
</P>
<P>
   A new pivotal clinical trial, which will take six months to
administer and require more than 20 particiants, will delay
Genzyme's marketing plans for the drug by at least a year and
postpone BioMarin's anticipated profitability, which was expected
in mid-2001. BioMarin had been testing the drug in 10 patients.
</P>
<P>
   The additional testing required by the US Food and Drug
Administration prompted shares of Genzyme to close Thursday at 37,
down 1 7/8, while BioMarin stock ended at 12 3/16, down 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously expected approval from the FDA,'' said Alison
Lauton, Genzyme's senior vice president of regulatory affairs.
``But the FDA did not not legally tell BioMarin that it absolutely
agreed with the design of their clinical trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies specialize in developing enzyme replacement
therapies for life-threatening diseases. Fourteen months ago,
Genzyme, of Cambridge, Mass., signed a joint development agreement
with BioMarin, based in Novato, Calif., which had developed a drug
to treat mucopolysaccharidosis, known as MPS-1, a genetic disorder
that affects 2,000 to 3,000 children worldwide, some of whom die by
age 10.
</P>
<P>
   When Genzyme agreed to fund the development and
commercialization of the drug, known as alpha-L iduronidase,
BioMarin had an understanding with the FDA about the clinical
testing needed to measure the drug's safety and effectiveness in
MPS-1 patients. The measurements included a shrinking of the liver
and a urine test. All 10 patients, according to Genzymne, showed
various signs that the drug was effective.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme officials Thursday said the FDA, after reviewing the
BioMarin clinical trial data, felt the results were insufficient to
grant formal approval and have asked for another clinical trial to
show additional results.
</P>
<P>
   ``This delay is not good news for BioMarin, but it's not
terrible either, as there are no real firm FDA rules on approving
drugs for rare diseases, especially when only 10 patients are
involved,'' said Jim McCamant, editor of Medical Technology Stock
Letter in Berkeley, Calif. ``But now that there are a growing
number of companies developing drugs for rare illnesses, and the
ones that get approved command high prices, the FDA and the firms
involved will probably develop better guidelines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
