<HEADLINE>
IN SENSITIVE INQUIRY, EGYPT AND U.S. BOTH HAVE MUCH AT STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With AIRCRASH-RDP) 
(bl) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ As the inquiry into the crash of EgyptAir Flight
990 moves into a delicate new phase, Egyptian and U.S. officials
face high stakes in trying to find conclusive and satisfactory
answers to questions about what brought the plane crashing into the
ocean Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   For the Egyptian government, the results of the investigation
could affect everything from national pride to the fortunes of the
country's tourism industry, one of its economic lifelines. In a
sign of how volatile the issue of the inquiry has become,
conspiracy theories are now circulating wildly in Egypt, troubling
both U.S. and and Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Some have blamed Israel's intelligence service for the crash;
others have suggested that the U.S. investigators are covering up
for Boeing, the plane's manufacturer. And as unlikely as the
theories may seem, they have been embraced in Egypt more easily
than the very different hypothesis now being advanced by U.S.
investigators: that the aircraft and all 217 people aboard might
have been brought down by a suicidal Egyptian pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the response by the Egyptian public and the government
to that U.S. suggestion has been so bitter that, to some, it
appears unclear whether the Egyptian government might ever
cooperate fully with the kind of exhaustive criminal probe that is
the next step favored by many U.S. investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they are persuaded that there is reason to suspect
this pilot, I wonder whether Egypt will feel comfortable allowing
an FBI team to come to Egypt and begin asking questions at will,''
said a Western diplomat here who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Egypt are close allies, and both have good
reason for wanting to defuse any possible dispute or tensions.
Egypt receives more than $2 billion a year in assistance from the
United States, making it the second-largest recipient of U.S. aid,
behind Israel. The United States relies heavily on Egypt as a
mediator in Middle East peace talks and as a potential staging area
for U.S. troops in the event of renewed conflict in the region.
</P>
<P>
   An Egyptian challenge to the working U.S. theory has already
delayed any decision to shift responsibility for the case to the
FBI. U.S. and Egyptian officials in Washington are now reviewing
the evidence that has been gathered to date by accident
investigators from the National Transportation Board in hopes of
reaching a joint decision on how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian experts are expected to help interpret voice recordings
from the cockpit, while diplomats from the United States and Egypt
will try hard to present a picture of partnership. Only with the
permission of the Egyptian government could U.S. investigators
begin any kind of criminal inquiry here into the background of
Gameel el-Batouty, 59, the reserve pilot whom the Americans think
may have been responsible for the crash.
</P>
<P>
   But along with its own reservations about such a course, the
Egyptian government is likely also to listen closely to the public
anger being voiced by ordinary Egyptians who say they see in the
pilot sabotage scenario little more than the product of an
overactive American imagination.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans are trying to harm Egypt's reputation by any
means,'' said Mohammed Sami, 62, a retired executive of the
Egyptian railway authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just want to take every small thing and turn it into a
very big complicated thing that backfires against Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman James Rubin went out
of his way at a briefing Thursday to insist that, to date, the
United States and Egypt had been `working very, very closely
together at all levels in the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our long and close friendship will not be harmed because we
have confidence that the Egyptian government, like the United
States government, wants to get to the bottom of this,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Turkey on Thursday, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
amplified his government's reluctance to accept the U.S. theory
that the plane was brought down by pilot sabotage. So far, the
foreign minister said, it was too early to label the crash anything
but a ``technical failure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't jump to conclusions from someone quoting the Koran
and say that this was more than an accident,'' Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
   Moussa's reference was to the cryptic Islamic phrase that
Batouty, then sitting at the controls of the aircraft, was heard to
have uttered at the start of a sequence of events that preceded the
crash. In conjunction with other evidence, the U.S. investigators
at least initially thought Batouty's use of the phrase as an
indication that he might have been preparing for death.
</P>
<P>
   But Egyptian officials have scoffed at that notion, saying that,
if anything, Batouty's language might be a sign that he had
encountered some kind of emergency in the cabin. In a new response
to the U.S. theory, EgyptAir on Thursday dispatched a new team of
medical and technical experts to the United States, and officials
said they would seek to address what Batouty's former colleagues
have called the unfounded allegations against him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Over the 19 days since the crash, Egypt has allowed the United
States to assume primary responsibility for the investigation into
the cause of the incident. But under international agreements that
spell out which country should take charge of such an
investigation, it could reassert its own authority at any time,
according to experts in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no indication that Egypt might take such a step,
but in an implicit warning, the semi-official Egyptian daily Al
Akhbar newspaper complained in an editorial Thursday that the
publicity given in the United States to the theory of pilot
sabotage developed by the U.S.-led team ``indicates that there is
an intention to rule out any American responsibility for this
tragic accident.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh said Wednesday that if Egypt did assert
primacy in the case, the United States would carry out its own
investigation, but he acknowledged that the scope of such an
inquiry could not extend to Egypt without permission from the
Egyptian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Along with its stated aversion to any rush to judgment, the
Egyptian government has solid practical reasons for at least
wishing that the line of U.S. inquiry would shift away from any
finding of pilot misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Any conclusion that an EgyptAir crew member was responsible for
the crash could subject the state-run airline to heavy liability
claims. And an adverse ruling would also almost certainly rebound
against Egypt's tourism industry, the country's main source of
foreign currency, which has only now recovered from the setback
caused by the 1997 killings of 58 foreign tourists during an attack
by militants in the southern city of Luxor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the suspicion and bitterness with which many
Egyptians have responded to the U.S. theory reflects a view that
runs deep in Egypt: a suspicion that the United States and other
Western powers, for all their claims of partnership, do not have
Egypt's best interests at heart.
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments could be heard in conversations around Cairo on
Thursday, as Egyptians from all walks of life spoke with
near-unanimity in rejecting the U.S. theory of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for a scapegoat,'' said Issam Abdel Moneim,
58, an accountant ``They want to escape responsibility,'' said Amr
Abdel Kalik, 21, a student. ``They are not neutral,'' said Manal
Ali, 30, a secretary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
