<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HITLER-SILVERWARE19-C     11-18 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITLER-SILVERWARE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sale of Hitler silverware leaves bad taste in mouths of
Holocaust survivors
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Over the objections of Holocaust survivors and others,
one of metro Atlanta's poshest antiques shops is turning
swastika-embossed silver into gold. Great Gatsby's Auction Gallery
is raising thousands of dollars for a local family by selling Adolf
Hitler's tableware.
</P>
<P>
   The 125-piece set is a mere drop in a torrent of World War II
material coming onto the market as families of aging or deceased
veterans seek to unload the artifacts. Put on sale by a Woodstock,
Ga., family, the silverware is being sold in 52 separate lots via
the Internet. Bidding concludes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday, more than $87,502 had been offered. Gatsby's
will get 10 percent to 15 percent of the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Kowalik, president of Gatsby's, which is based in
Chamblee, seemed puzzled that the auction had sparked controversy.
``This is what we do. We're not condoning Hitler, for gosh sake.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics contend the auction humanizes _ even glorifies _ one
of the monsters of world history, and that it could fuel the fervor
of Hitler buffs.
</P>
<P>
   Erna Martino, 53, head of the Atlanta Organization of Holocaust
Survivors, said the auction ``brings out people who think this kind
of thing is wonderful, and there are a lot of them in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   Martino's brother and sister, 11 and 13, were murdered by Nazis.
She was born in Germany after her parents' liberation from
concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   Martino said selling Hitler's personal belongings is ``morbid,
like someone saying, `I'd like to buy Charles Manson's T-shirt.'
It's very morose and perverse for people to want to own that kind
of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Kaiman, southeast director of the Anti-Defamation League, a
Jewish group that fights bigotry, maintained that thousands of
Americans are gung-ho followers of Nazi ideology. The sale might
create more Hitler fans, he contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It elevates Hitler to celebrity status in pop culture, similar
to, say, Elvis Presley,'' Kaiman said. ``This idea that we
mass-merchandise things that were owned by Hitler _ and that people
would buy them because they would want a part of him _ is
disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   With such concerns in mind, some auction houses have steered
clear of Hitler items.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not sell Hitler memorabilia in any way, shape or
form,'' said Diana Phillips of Sotheby's. ``It is completely
inappropriate. Sotheby's would not want to be associated in any way
with the man responsible for the most shameful period in living
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hitler tableware being auctioned had been shipped home from
Germany by a decorated American soldier from the Atlanta area.
Kowalik said the GI ``liberated'' the Hitler items with a group of
other soldiers who in 1945 stormed the dictator's headquarters in
Munich.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran died recently, and his family, whom Kowalik declined
to identify, decided they needed money more than the World War II
artifacts. They felt they could get more by selling the collection
on the open market than by seeking out museum buyers, Kowalik said.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Cocks, a history professor at Albion College in
Michigan and one of America's foremost scholars on Hitler, said ``a
huge amount'' of captured German material, including some of
Hitler's personal effects, is beginning to show up because American
World War II veterans are dying at a rate of 1,100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Other auctions have sold things such as Hitler's eight-wheeled
Mercedes Benz and paintings. This week, a San Francisco auction
house sold a ledger said to have been Hitler's personal phone book
_ Eva Braun's number is marked ``secret'' _ for $17,000 to an
anonymous buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Most materials going up for sale aren't controversial, Cocks
said _ items like flags and German Lugers. But Hitler's personal
tableware is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an unsavory quality about this stuff,'' he said of the
tableware. ``Most museums wouldn't be interested in honoring such a
person by having it. And they wouldn't want to set up a place of
pilgrimage for neo-Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Laid out inside Gatsby's plush galleries, near four Picasso
masterpieces also up for sale, the silver gleamed, and the initials
``AH'' screamed out from the Nazi eagle-and-swastika emblem.
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes a set of small lobster forks, coffeepots
and teapots, sandwich plates, a martini shaker, a humidor, a
toothpick cannister, a cigarette box and a matchbox cover complete
with a paper-and-pine match box inside. The set includes sundry
containers and dozens of forks, spoons, and knives.
</P>
<P>
   Kit Wellman, director of the Center for Ethics at Georgia State
University, said he could understand a family's need to sell such
artifacts. ``Who are we to say you can't capitalize on something
that's going to make a real difference in your life?''
</P>
<P>
   But he maintained the impact of the auction on Jews and others
should have been taken into consideration. ``We can't just say,
`It's my right, and it doesn't matter if you get upset about it,'''
Wellman said.
</P>
<P>
   And many are upset. Herbert Kohn, 73, lost many relatives to
Hitler's death camps. He escaped Germany, joined the Army and
returned to his native land to fight the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even stand to look at a Mercedes Benz,'' said Kohn.
``This should have been smelted and the silver used for some good
purpose. It bothers me that his initials are on it. That makes it
personal. Makes me remember when I was 6, in 1933, and they kicked
me out of school. They arrested my father, who had been decorated
as a hero in World War I fighting for Germany. History needs to be
known, but not glorified, and this auction glorifies Hitler.'' The
folks at Great Gatsby's say they don't see why selling Hitler's
personal items is so controversial.
</P>
<P>
   The same online auction also offers a Rolls Royce owned by Barry
Gibbs of the rock group Bee Gees and a 16 mm master print of the
Beatles movie ``Let It Be.'' Kowalik would prefer that people do
that about the controversy _ let it be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
