   WOLF-UNDERSTANDING _ (Los Angeles) Wolves N Wildlife ranch
manager Robert Smith led a leashed white wolf Tatonka toward the
students sitting in the bleachers at Van Nuys High School _ home of
the Wolves. The big, bad wolf came snout to nose with the students,
sniffing around for a little fear. ``Oh how cute,'' a girl said,
breaking the tension among the students who didn't know what to
expect from a real wolf. Smith, who takes care of nine wolves, a
Siberian tiger and a black bear at the ranch in Fillmore, brought
the 1 1/2-year-old gray wolf to school Thursday to teach students
about the world's most misunderstood animal. By Troy Anderson (Will
move on the ``n'' California and the ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
