<P>
   BOWLING-SENIOR _ (Los Angeles) Flo Scorpio walks into a bowling
alley the way Frank Sinatra used to walk onto a stage or Babe Ruth
a baseball field. Like she owns the place. She picks up her bowling
ball, shakes her arms a little to get loose, lines up her shot, and
takes a three-step approach to the foul line, letting the ball go.
All the pins go flying except one. The ten pin. If looks could
kill, the ten pin would be dead. ``Should'a been a strike,''
97-year-old Flo Scorpio says to the bowling gods. ``I look at Flo
and think to myself, heck, I've got another 25 years of bowling
left,'' laughs Liz Rogers, president of the 4,000 member San
Fernando Valley Women's Bowling Association. Rogers says she's
checked with the association's state office to confirm her
suspicions. Flo Scorpio of Van Nuys is the oldest woman league
bowler in the state. By Dennis McCarthy (Will move on the ``n''
California and the ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
