brought them to their highest level since the Persian Gulf War on
Thursday, a fact that could soon hit consumers hard with much
steeper gasoline prices, surcharges on plane tickets and higher
costs on a wide range of products. The impact is ``going to be
shocking for people,'' one analyst says. By Greg Wilcox (Will move
on the ``n'' California, ``a'' national and ``f'' financial news
wires.)
