<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4401 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-SATELLITE-TV-ART-NYT &LR;      11-18 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLITE-TV-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL TO LET SATELLITE COMPANIES BROADCAST LOCAL
CHANNELS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Vt., N.Y., Calif., Va., Miss., Ariz.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 26 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After bowing to an objection by Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, the House passed a hard-fought bill Thursday that would
give satellite television companies the right to broadcast local
channels, assuring that cable companies will soon have competition.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, part of a huge spending package, is now before the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill cuts through much of the current static that has so
confused and frustrated millions of home satellite viewers,'' said
Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., who helped push the legislation. ``For
the first time ever, it will usher in an era of head-to-head
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is expected to be signed by President Clinton,
preparing the way for viewers in New York and Los Angeles to begin
receiving local programs on their dishes almost immediately. Once
the legislation is approved, satellite dish owners in other cities
should be able to tune into NBC, CBS, ABC and Fox within six
months. In all, 10 million households own satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Christmas this year, consumers across the nation will have
a real choice,'' said Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va., who heads the
Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of tinkering and compromise, the
legislation nearly lost its footing in the Senate over one
provision.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, who is known for his parliamentary savvy, threatened a
filibuster when he discovered that his colleagues had inserted a
provision to extend loan guarantees of $1.25 billion to satellite
companies as an incentive to serve rural viewers. The companies say
it is too expensive to launch satellites to reach sparsely
populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise was struck Thursday morning, and the final bill was
resubmitted to the House without the contentious measure.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, agreed that the
Senate would take up the issue again no later than April 1, which
appeased lawmakers from largely rural states.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would give satellite companies a six-month grace period
to work out agreements with the networks, and would legally allow
them to broadcast local channels to all viewers. After six months,
deals must be in hand for satellite companies to continue carrying
the channels. The legislation also requires that by 2002 those
satellite companies that carry some local stations must carry all
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Armand Musey, an analyst at Banc of America Securities,
estimated that local stations would charge satellite broadcasters
several times as much as they do cable stations, because satellite
systems have a lower market share. ``A local broadcaster has to be
on the local cable system, or they don't have any audience,'' he
said. Still, he said, because the satellite companies will offer
only a handful of local stations in each city, they will be able to
charge an additional $5 a month and still make a good profit.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kaimowitz, an analyst at ING Barings, said the satellite
companies would want to offer local stations inexpensively because
it is a service intended to attract new customers. And
broadcasters, he said, will want their channels carried on
satellite because satellite subscribers tend to be the young and
well-off viewers that advertisers seek.
</P>
<P>
   He said that about 30 percent to 40 percent of satellite
subscribers also subscribed to cable television, mainly to get
local channels. Some will now drop cable, saving about $15 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The small but growing satellite dish industry has spent three
years lobbying lawmakers to change a law that prevents them from
offering subscribers local programming. The law, company executives
argued, was seriously undercutting their ability to compete with
cable, which serves 70 million households, mostly because
subscribers did not want to give up local programs or settle for
fuzzy reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an impediment for people to subscribe to satellite
channels,'' said Bob Marsocci, a spokesman for DirecTV, the
dominant satellite company. ``They walk into a store and find out
they can't get local TV, and they walk out.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill was ultimately supported by the cable industry
and broadcasters, officials for one satellite company, Echostar
Communications, objected, saying the bill favored DirecTV, which is
owned by General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Watson, a lobbyist for Echostar, said the bill did not
give smaller companies the leverage to secure reasonable
retransmission contracts from the networks. This, she argued, could
discourage start-up companies from getting into the business and
would dilute competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to pay more than cable pays, we are going to have
to pass that on to the consumer,'' Ms. Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   It is an argument backed by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the
chairman of the Commerce Committee. McCain called the bill
anti-competitive for failing to protect satellite companies from
lopsided agreements that he said could still benefit cable
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But executives for the National Broadcast Association and
senators from both parties discounted that theory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
