<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     11-18 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD CALL? JUST ASK WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Note language in 5th graf)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedro was robbed. For our Spanish-speaking readers, Pedro fue
robado.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dominating American League batters like no pitcher in
the last half-century, Red Sox righty Pedro Martinez Thursday
finished second to Texas catcher Pudge Rodriguez in voting for the
American League's Most Valuable Player award.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is a worthy choice, as were Roberto Alomar, Manny
Ramirez, Rafael Palmeiro, Derek Jeter, and Nomar Garciaparra, but
it appears Pedro failed to finish first because of irrational bias
some voters have against pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the 28 voters (George King of the New York Post and
LaVelle Neal of the Minneapolis Star-Tribune) failed to list Pedro
among the top 10 on their ballots. If both writers had picked him
as high as fourth, Pedro would have won the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's horseshit,'' said Ted Williams when he heard
the news that Pedro's name was omitted from two ballots. ``What
game were those guys watching? You're always disappointed when that
happens. I know. I went through it as much as any player.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an understatement. For Ted, every MVP vote was a
nail-biting, smoke-filled-room, Cook County experience. Williams
was a two-time American League MVP, but he failed to win the award
when he hit .406 in 1941, and in both seasons in which he won the
triple crown. He also failed to win when he hit .388 at the age of
39 in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always other things to consider,'' said Ted. ``In a
few years, I thought I should have won. In '41, I hit .400 and I
thought that was pretty good, but DiMaggio hit in 56 straight
games, so I never felt bad about that one. But there were others.''
</P>
<P>
   When Williams lost to DiMaggio by a count of 202-201 in 1947 (a
Triple Crown year for Ted), Williams failed to appear on the top
ten of one ballot. Boston baseball folklore holds that Ted got
jobbed by an ancient nemesis, the late Mel Webb of the Globe.
Research by historian Glenn Stout contradicts the charge. According
to Stout, who dug deep into the files of the late Harold Kaese of
the Globe, all three Boston voters placed Williams first in '47 and
Webb did not vote. Kaese contended it was a Midwestern scribe _
perhaps the grandfather of Minneapolis's clueless LaVelle Neal _
who omitted Ted.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette spoke with Pedro via
conference call after the voting results were released. The Duke
cited the snubs of Williams from a half century ago, telling
Martinez, ``You're in good company with great Red Sox players.''
</P>
<P>
   Elections like Thursday's assure that the sportswriting
fraternity forever will be tarnished by petty nitwits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Max Nichols of the Minneapolis Star (what is it with
the Twin Cities, anyway?) voted for Cesar Tovar as American League
MVP _ just to make sure Carl Yastrzemski would not be unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Several baseball writers failed to vote for Willie Mays when he
first become eligible for the Hall of Fame in 1979. To a lesser
degree, this happens every year. You can't get two dozen writers to
unanimously agree that today is Friday. Many Hall voters believe no
player is worthy of ``first-ballot'' induction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' said Ted, the voice of experience. ``You get
writers that don't see one guy play as much. Somebody's got a
favorite, but maybe they got a grudge. There was that guy who
wouldn't vote for me and I felt badly about it. I know the kid from
Texas is a helluva player, but boy, I think our pitcher was
absolutely phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro added: ``What the reporters do is not my business. I don't
understand that area. The system was there before I got to the big
leagues. I don't think I'll be the one to switch it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no disgrace in naming Rodriguez, although it's
interesting that both Texas voters had Rafael Palmeiro first and
picked Pudge no better than fifth. But it's crazy to believe Pedro
doesn't belong in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   And please, you head-in-sand purists, let's not have any
rhetoric about pitchers having their own award and not being
eligible. There are awards for pitchers, fielders, hitters, and
other specific baseball functions. MVP is for everybody. A Rookie
of the Year has his own award, but can still be MVP. A goalie who
wins the Vezina Trophy in the NHL can be MVP. If Miss Ohio cops the
congeniality award, that doesn't prohibit her from becoming Miss
America. All players are eligible for MVP, and if voters are going
to invoke their own rules and exclude part of the baseball
population from consideration, those voters should send their
ballots to people who are more open-minded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there should be discrimination,'' said Martinez.
``Otherwise, change the name of the MVP to `Regular Player Award.'
We're all players. We qualify as players. What would they do
without pitching?''
</P>
<P>
   Discrimination, one form or another, has cost the Sox another
MVP Award. In 1947, personal pettiness was used against Williams
because he was not a helpful interview. Now Pedro is punished
because he doesn't play every day.
</P>
<P>
   Two writers decided they would not consider Martinez no matter
what he did on the field. The worthy catcher from Texas did not
have to overcome the same obstacle. Pedro fue robado.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
