<SLUG> BC-KOHL-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERB KOHL: SHY SENATOR UNCHARACTERISTICALLY STANDS ON THE
BARRICADES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)  (With SPEND-CONGRESS) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Herb Kohl hardly resembles the prototypical
senator.
</P>
<P>
   He displays not a smidge of pomposity, pretension or bombast. He
is rather shy and shuns the spotlight, and on the few occasions
when he speaks out, he talks softly and tends to look at his feet.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the wealthiest members of Congress. But he lives
simply, has never married and prefers old blazers to designer
suits.
</P>
<P>
   A short, thin, 64-year-old bald man, he is rarely recognized by
tourists here. He usually eats lunch alone in the public restaurant
in the Capitol rather than in the senators' private dining room
where backs are slapped and deals are cut.
</P>
<P>
   In his 11 years in the Senate as a Democrat from Wisconsin, he
has hardly ever made news.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday night, Kohl, objecting to a milk-price feature
of the final spending bill of the year, announced that he would do
everything in his power to obstruct and delay the adjournment of
the Senate for as long as possible unless he received concessions
on the dairy issue. This could keep the Senate in session through
the weekend, if not longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody uses whatever leverage they have, and part of the
leverage I have is the discomfort I can bring to bear,'' Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
   He realizes this is out of character. ``This is very much unlike
me,'' he said in an interview on Thursday afternoon. He went on:
``I hate it. I don't like to be a pain. I've never been an
obstructionist before. But if this is what it takes, this is what
I'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Kohl was born in Milwaukee on Feb. 7, 1935, the child of
Jews who immigrated from Eastern Europe in the 1920s. His father
opened a grocery store in Milwaukee that grew into a supermarket
chain and eventually expanded into department stores. As an adult,
Herb Kohl ran the business, which bore the family name, and by the
time he sold out in 1979, Kohl's dominated the market in the
Milwaukee area.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, when the Milwaukee Bucks basketball team was
threatening to move to another city, Kohl bought the franchise and
kept it in Milwaukee. He still owns the team.
</P>
<P>
   With a fortune estimated at more than $250 million, Kohl
financed almost entirely out of his own pocket his race for the
Senate in 1988, his first foray into politics, and his re-election
campaign in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Each campaign cost him about $7 million. He made it sound
virtuous that he was not raising money from others, using the
slogan, ``Nobody's senator but yours.'' So far, he has no serious
opposition for re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl presents his case for tying up the Senate as a matter of
principle. Under pressure from lawmakers from the East,
congressional leaders stuck a section in the final spending bill
that would prevent the Agriculture Department from putting a new
milk pricing system into effect and would allow the New England
states to maintain a cartel that keeps the price of milk there
artificially high and keeps out milk from other states. This would
work to the disadvantage of dairy farmers in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl complains that no vote was allowed on the dairy matter. He
maintains it is wrong to effectively bar the product from one state
from being sold in another. And he says one of his obligations is
to defend the more than 20,000 dairy farmers in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not just a national senator,'' he said. ``I am a senator
from Wisconsin.''
</P>
<P>
   But in talking with Kohl, it is clear that there is another
reason he is being obstreperous. He may not know the vernacular,
but he obviously feels he has been dissed.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he said, a Democratic leader berated him for
inconveniencing other senators. ``I didn't like the fact he was
upset with me,'' Kohl said. ``But then I decided the hell with him.
He's got a different interest. He just wants to keep the train on
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Then on Thursday morning, he said, he met with Sen. Trent Lott
of Mississippi, the Republican leader, and Sen. Phil Gramm of
Texas, an especially aggressive Republican combatant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was particularly upset,'' Kohl said. He continued: ``They
didn't offer me anything. They made it clear they just wanted to
get this thing over as quickly as possible so senators would know
when they were going to have a vote and when they could get a plane
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohl understands that he hardly brings to mind Horatius, the
legendary Roman hero who stood at the bridge over the Tiber and
almost single-handedly defended his city from an Etruscan invasion.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that the issue he is taking his stand on is not
one of war and peace or life and death. On those matters, he said,
``you have other senators who are out front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's an issue,'' he said, ``where I'm out front or no one
else will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
