<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENNY-DAMAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW-MOVING LENNY WREAKS HAVOC ON ISLANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ Hurricane Lenny stubbornly hovered between St.
Maarten and St. Croix for most of Thursday, battering both islands
with 130-mph winds, sending rooftops flying, washing out roads, and
knocking out power and telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   While the storm lashed at the region, the extent of the damage
remained unclear as emergency and rescue officials could not get to
either island because of dangerous flying conditions. Instead, they
relied on reports from islanders who surveyed the damage once the
worst of the storm had passed.
</P>
<P>
   From those initial reports, Lenny did not appear to cause major
destruction. One man died on St. Maarten when his car flipped over,
and another was missing on St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a reported death on St. Croix, but a Federal
Emergency Management Agency official said the agency could not
confirm if the death was storm-related.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, in St. Lucia's tourism capital of Soufriere,
20-foot waves washed away 40 homes, leaving the families that lived
in them homeless.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, officials said it could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, people were prepared,'' said Carol
Hector-Harris, spokeswoman for FEMA Region 2, which includes the
Virgin Islands. ``That's why you don't have lots of deaths. People
are used to storms here. They know the drill.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenny struck just near the end of the hurricane season, which
officially concludes in 11 days. Though meteorologists tracked its
path and were not surprised by it, ``the intensification came
rather quickly,'' said Ed Tirado of the National Weather Service in
San Juan. At 1 p.m. Thursday, winds whipped at 135 miles an hour.
By the end of the day, they had calmed slightly to 120 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Tirado said the storm was drifting East-Northeast, and by
Saturday should be well north of the Caribbean Island chains.
</P>
<P>
   Friday FEMA officials plan to tour St. Croix to assess the
damage and begin the processes of offering aid for those who might
have lost their homes. They will also coordinate with other
agencies to make sure that families that don't have running water
get bottled water, and utilities are working to restore power on
the island.
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix Governor Charles Turnbull has asked President Clinton
to declare the island a disaster area, making it eligible for
federal disaster aid. The hurricane is a major blow to the
territory, which has a $1 billion debt and still owes $8 million
for federal disaster loans from Hurricane Marilyn and Hurricane
Hugo in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, tropical storms move in a westerly direction, but Lenny
defied that pattern. Wednesday, it seemed to be heading toward
Puerto Rico, but then it shifted away, heading east. That prompted
Puerto Ricans to call Lenny ``zurdo,'' Spanish for southpaw, or
``lefty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were saved,'' said Izzy Jimenez, wearing a Yankees cap as
he strutted through Luis Munoz Marin Airport.
</P>
<P>
   But heavy rains caused several rivers near the pueblos of
Arecibo, Barcelonetta, and Vega Alta to overflow. Residents worried
that continued rains might cause mudslides. In San Juan, one man
who was storm-proofing his house died when he fell off a ladder.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Croix, an island of 50,000 residents, Lenny ripped part
of the Ann Abraham Pier in Frederiksted, a cruise ship dock that
was rebuilt after 1989's Hurricane Hugo turned it into shreds.
Lenny ripped planks off a fish pier, partially destroyed the roof
of the King Christian Hotel and the headquarters of the National
Guard, and smashed more than 50 small sailboats near Christiansted.
</P>
<P>
   It broke windows and caused ceilings to collapse in the Paradise
Mills housing project. Heavy rains caused several roads _ including
Queens Cross Street _ to buckle. Several roads were washed out near
Frederiksted.
</P>
<P>
   More than 420 people stayed in shelters overnight in St. Croix,
Hector-Harris said. By the end of the day, a curfew had been lifted
and most had returned home.
</P>
<P>
   On the island shared by St. Martin, a French territory, and St.
Maarten, which is Dutch, the storm caused similar damage. But
details were sketchy. The US State Department's Caribbean division
had not been in contact with officials on the island, and Thursday
phone lines on the island were down.
</P>
<P>
   On St. Thomas, another of the US Virgin Islands, about 115
people stayed in shelters Thursday, Hector-Harris said, but there
were no reports of destroyed homes.
</P>
<P>
   Hector-Harris said Thursday morning that as she walked around
her hotel on the eastern end of St. Thomas, she could feel Lenny's
effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hellacious,'' she said. ``I was in a huge concrete
building and I felt it shaking. And you could hear the storm at sea
... it's like a whole bunch of trains in a freight yard going at
once.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
