<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL ANNOUNCES SENATE BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vowing to limit the role of the federal government,
Rep. Tom Campbell announced Thursday night that he would challenge
incumbent Dianne Feinstein next year for the U.S. Senate seat from
California.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a Republican representing San Jose, said in a
statement that if elected, he would fight to send power and money
to state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the federal government to constrict our freedom less,
in our personal lives, our work, and our schools, so that we can
realize that opportunity to the fullest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken, tenured law professor at Stanford University
also promised to reduce overall federal spending and to ensure that
money earmarked for Social Security is not spent on other federal
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I oppose federal spending because the federal government does
not pay for what it spends _ as you and I have to,'' he said.
``Instead, it just borrows from the Social Security surplus. This
is irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security surplus became a focal point of the budget
debate this year in Congress, with Republicans advocating budget
cuts to avoid spending the money on federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who has spent four terms in the House, is known for
occasionally breaking with his party, including on the important
issues of gun control and abortion _ both of which he supports.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Campbell said he is convinced California
voters want a Senate candidate who votes conservatively on fiscal
issues and moderately on social issues, and that is how he
describes himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government should help those who need it, and help the rest of
us by getting out of the way,'' said Campbell, who holds a
doctorate in economics from the University of Chicago and a law
degree from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, 47, will contend for the nomination with at least four
other conservative Republicans: Silicon Valley entrepreneur Ron
Unz, state Senate Minority Whip Ray Haynes, San Diego County
Supervisor Bill Horn and businessman J.P. Gough.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein spokesman Kam Kuwata said the senator welcomed
Campbell's entrance into the race, adding that it will make for a
``spirited'' primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope all the Republicans have fun beating each other up and
exposing each candidate's weaknesses,'' he said laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein, a graduate of Stanford University who was mayor of
San Francisco from 1978 to 1989, was elected to the Senate in 1992.
As a senator, Feinstein has focused heavily on crime and the
banning of assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell could face a steep financial challenge in raising the
estimated $5 million needed for the primary and $20 million needed
for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a statewide Field Poll showed Feinstein with a huge
lead over Campbell and other potential GOP nominees. Among all
voters in a hypothetical general election, Feinstein won 55 percent
of the vote, compared with 30 percent for Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Campbell had only a tiny lead among other
possible Republican nominees in the poll's matchups against
Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell will formally announce his Senate bid at a press
conference on Friday in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   (Reporter Name can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
