A4412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-MVP-RODRIGUEZ-NYT     11-18 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MVP-RODRIGUEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ WINS AL'S MVP AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez failed to win the Most Valuable Player Award for
his own team, but was named MVP of the American League Thursday.
Pedro Martinez received the most first-place votes for Most
Valuable Player, but he finished second, in part because two
writers left him off their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre nature of this year's voting, then, assures that the
selection of Rodriguez will go down as one of the most
controversial in baseball history. ``I'm not going to start crying
about it,'' said Martinez, the Boston pitcher who was picked
unanimously for the AL Cy Young Award earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, 28, batted .332 with 113 runs batted in, 199 hits and
25 stolen bases, but his most significant impact was on defense: A
perennial Gold Glove winner, Rodriguez threw out 53 percent of
runners attempting to steal, and because of his presence, opponents
tried stealing only 99 times this year, the fewest in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's special to get this award, because that's the dream of
every player to get this kind of award,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, too, had an incredible season, one of the greatest
ever by a pitcher. He went 23-4 _ the Red Sox were 24-5 in games he
started, while compiling a .507 winning percentage in games he
didn't start _ and his earned run average of 2.07 was 2.79 runs
lower than the league ERA of 4.86.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the Baseball Writers Association of America from
each of the American League's 14 cities vote for the Most Valuable
Player Award, slotting players first through 10th. Among the 28
writers, Martinez received eight first-place votes, while the Texas
catcher had seven, Cleveland's Roberto Alomar, Manny Ramirez and
Rafael Palmeiro had four apiece, Boston's Nomar Garciaparra had two
and the Yankees' Derek Jeter had one first place vote. But
Rodriguez finished with 252 points, ahead of Martinez (239), Alomar
(226), Ramirez (226), Palmeiro (193), Jeter (177) and Garciaparra
(137).
</P>
<P>
   La Velle Neal, who covers the Minnesota Twins for the
Minneapolis Star Tribune, and George King, the Yankees' beat writer
for the New York Post, did not list Martinez in any of the 10 slots
on their ballots. If Neal and King had each placed Martinez as high
as fourth, he would have won the MVP Award. Neal and King could not
be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that because pitchers are given their own honor,
the Cy Young Award, they should not be considered for the MVP
Award. But according to the criterion disseminated to the writers
who vote, pitchers are eligible for selection, and there have been
18 instances when a pitcher was picked as the MVP _ most recently
in 1992, when closer Dennis Eckersley of the Oakland Athletics won
the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens was the last starting pitcher to win the MVP, for
Boston in 1986. In the letter that accompanied the ballots this
year, voters were encouraged to ``keep in mind that all players are
eligible for MVP and that includes pitchers and designated
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The second listed criterion for MVP consideration is the number
of games played, and writers who don't pick pitchers sometimes base
their decision on that reasoning. But Jack Lang, former secretary
treasurer of the writers' association, said that in the past, he
told prospective voters that if they felt they could not consider a
pitcher for the MVP Award, he would reassign the ballot to another
writer. New York Times reporters do not vote in the selection of
postseason awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try everything to convince writers that this prejudice
against pitchers should not exist,'' said Jack O'Connell, the
current secretary-treasurer for the BBWAA.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several controversial votes in past years. In
1947, Boston's Ted Williams won the league's Triple Crown, leading
the league in batting average, home runs and RBIs. But because a
writer who personally disliked Williams failed to vote him among
the top 10 players in the AL, the Yankees' Joe DiMaggio won the MVP
Award.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell, of the Hartford Courant, filled in the other MVP
ballot for the New York area papers this year. He selected Ramirez
for first place and Martinez for seventh. King voted for Jeter for
first place. Both members of the Dallas-Fort Worth chapter selected
Palmeiro for first place and had Martinez listed higher than
Rodriguez. Palmeiro, in fact, was picked as the Rangers' Most
Valuable Player for 1999 by the Dallas-Fort Worth chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed at all,'' Martinez said. ``I don't hold
anything against anybody. There's nothing I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who he would have voted for, Rodriguez replied, ``For me,
Pedro can be second, and Robbie can be third.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez became the ninth catcher to win the award, and of
those, six are in the Hall of Fame, including Johnny Bench and Yogi
Berra. He was on vacation with his family in Florida when he
received word he had won the voting, which was received generally
with surprise around baseball. Many thought that Ramirez or Alomar
would win, but the Cleveland teammates may have split the voting to
the point that neither Indian had enough votes to win.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who finished second in the AL batting race to
Garciaparra, was considered a front-runner early in the season, but
he did not have as many extra-base hits in the second half of the
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
