<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CATHOLICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PASTORAL DISASTER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US Catholic bishops, already burdened with many
responsibilities, will cause more work for themselves and greater
friction in the church by demanding the allegiance of theologians
in Catholic universities. They can mitigate the damage of their
decision by using the new power with discretion. The real danger
facing the church is not abstruse theological writings but the
increasing secularization of American society, which Catholic
universities are ideally situated to combat.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops approved the ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae'' in response to a
call from the Vatican to get tough with Catholic universities in
the United States. These schools have had an occasional teacher who
strayed from church orthodoxy, but that is a small price to pay for
the maturation of the Catholic university system. Because the
universities stress Catholic values and reach out to all segments
of society, they enhance the mission of the church in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the church's universities these days is how to
promote Catholic values in a secular world. The universities should
focus on integrating their instruction in theology and philosophy
classes with student conduct outside the classroom. Instead, if the
new edict is enforced, they will have to worry about whether a
theology professor has obtained a ``mandatum'' from his local
bishop certifying that he is fit to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Roger Mahony of Los Angeles said Wednesday that ``this
is a new moment of collaboration'' between bishops and
universities. Rather than collaboration, universities require
autonomy from authorities to advance knowledge. Tension between
established teachings and new ways of thinking is more an
opportunity than a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop Rembert Weakland of Milwaukee said: ``Passing this
document now will create a great pastoral disaster. . . . It will
only lead to a lot of public bickering, public disputes, where the
church can only be harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishops' document, which now goes to the Vatican for
approval, will not be implemented for months. Once the bishops get
their new powers confirmed, they will need to consult with
university presidents and show keen sensitivity for the many roles
a university plays lest they diminish the great institutions they
are trying to protect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
