<HEADLINE>
BACK ON STAR TRACK  
 ANDERSON DOMINANT IN FALL LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, ARIZ. - It doesn't take a psychic to know which Peoria
Javelinas player a reporter wants to talk to.
</P>
<P>
   ``You looking for Needle?'' Philadelphia Phillies prospect Pat
Burrell asks.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Anderson, at 6-feet-11 and supposedly still growing, is
stretched out in the training room, a day after yielding one run in
six innings to lower his Arizona Fall League ERA to 2.91.
</P>
<P>
   Burrell yells for ``Needle'' to come out.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Ricky Magdalena says: ``I can answer the questions for
him: `I just blew it by them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It is what the Seattle Mariners have been banking on ever since
they made Anderson the 19th pick out of Divine Child High School in
Dearborn, Mich., two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And it is what Anderson has done frequently this fall _ blow the
ball by guys who are on the verge of being in the majors. He is 1-0
in 34 innings, striking out 29 and walking nine. Opposing teams hit
.228 against him.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, however, no longer makes remarks about becoming the
best pitcher in the history of the game, something he said after
being drafted.
</P>
<P>
   Two years in professional baseball have humbled him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when he hears the Randy Johnson comparisons, Anderson,
although flattered by it, simply says, ``I want to be myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners would like Anderson to be another Randy Johnson,
but they know if they move him into the rotation now, it could
backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I'll be next season,'' Anderson said.
``They don't tell me. I just try to work on what I need to do
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is built like Johnson without the facial hair and long
locks. His delivery is frighteningly similar. Anderson throws 96
mph with a three-quarters, sling-shot motion. What he doesn't have
is the command.
</P>
<P>
   That will come. Right now, Anderson is working on all phases:
mechanics, command of his fastball, intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He competes, but he's learning what that means, how to attack
hitters, how to really finish a hitter off,'' said Dean Treanor,
the Javelinas' pitching coach who works in the Los Angeles Dodgers'
organization. ``It all goes with experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel he's made some strides down here, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who was given a team-record $2.18 million signing
bonus out of high school, was 6-5 with a 3.23 ERA his first year in
Class A ball in Wisconsin. He struck out 152 and walked 67 in 111
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 season, however, was an awakening. He started the
season 5-10 with a 5.11 ERA at Double-A New Haven, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   He said he changed his mechanics three times before Team USA
made him a late addition to the Pan American Games roster. It was
then that he seemed to change.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson started the final round-robin game of the tournament
against Brazil, striking out nine in six innings in Team USA's 3-2
victory. He went on to win four of his last seven decisions in the
minors and lowered his ERA to 4.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back, I just went out there and threw the ball,''
Anderson said. ``That helped me a lot. Before, when I messed up, I
would step back and think about what I had to adjust to.'' &QL; 
Notes
</P>
<P>
   Peoria saw its playoffs hopes dashed Wednesday, losing to the
Phoenix Desert Dogs, 5-4. The Grand Canyon Rafters can clinch the
Western Division title with a win over Maryvale today. The Mesa
Solar Sox are the Eastern Division champs and will host the first
game of the best-of-three championship series at 1 p.m. Friday at
Mesa's HoHoKam Park.
</P>
<P>
   The series moves to Scottsdale Stadium at 1 on Saturday.
Baseballs signed by Randy Johnson will be given to 100 fans. If
there is a third game, it will be played at Scottsdale at 1 p.m.
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Solar Sox have two outstanding pitchers: Doug Davis (Texas
Rangers), who is 5-2 with a 2.25 ERA, and 22-year-old Korean Sun
Woo Kim (Boston Red Sox), who is 5-1 with a 2.27 ERA. The team is
led at the plate by 20-year-old outfielder Corey Patterson (Chicago
Cubs), who is hitting .366, fourth-best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Maryvale's George Lombard (Atlanta Braves) has 11 home runs,
which tied a Fall League record held by Ryan Klesko, J.R. Phillips
and Ron Wright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
