<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-JERRYSELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A&AMP;M STUDENT REMEMBERED AS SELFLESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF PRINCE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _There is irony in the name, because friends
and former teachers recall Jerry Don Self as being genuinely
selfless.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably volunteered the most of any student we've ever
had,'' said Gayle Nelson, who was a Lamar High School teacher and
student council sponsor when Self attended the school from
1995-1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got in there and did things, which is probably what he
was doing'' Thursday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Self, 20, was among several students who died Thursday when a
40-foot stack of logs being erected for a traditional Thanksgiving
week bonfire collapsed at Texas A&AMP;M University in College Station.
</P>
<P>
   Many Lamar High graduates enroll at Texas A&AMP;M, Principal Jimmy
Jones said, and he worried that some might be involved in the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   He was saddened but hardly surprised when he learned that Self
was one of the students working on the log stack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very dependable kid, very involved, always one of the
first ones to step up and volunteer,'' Jones said. ``If something
was going on, he was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Self took average talents and pushed himself to above-average
levels, friends said. He was tall, well over 6 feet, but not an
exceptional athlete. Still, he was disciplined and dependable and
worked his way into a starting position on the offensive line by
the end of his senior year, a former coach recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He studied with zeal, pushing himself to reach his goal of
attending Texas A&AMP;M, joining the corps of cadets and studying
toward an engineering degree. He was the first in his family to
attend college.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a fairly decent student,'' Jones said. ``Not too many
kids who choose to go to A&AMP;M are weak in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Self tutored elementary students, served on the student council
and was a Spanish Club member at Lamar. He was spiritual and
attended church often, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar High School assistant coach Bill Riley broke down when he
learned of Self's death. Self and Riley's son, Beau Riley, were
longtime friends and played on the Lamar football team together.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Riley and his son drove to College Station when they heard
the news.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar High School head coach Eddy Peach described Self as ``a
model young man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to find a finer young man than what he was,''
Peach said. ``It's been a tough day for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Self selected Texas A&AMP;M because of its respected engineering
program. He embraced ``the whole Aggie culture,'' said Jeremy Erb,
his former pastor who was serving as a family spokesman Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Self's parents believe that their oldest son died doing
something he cared about, and Erb said they do not blame the
university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any animosity,'' Erb said. ``Jerry died
doing what he loved. There's no anger toward the bonfire. He was
proud and loved the A&AMP;M tradition, and I think the family stands
with him on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Self's parents drove to College Station on Thursday not knowing
whether their son was badly injured. They were told about the
accident during an early morning phone call from A&AMP;M officials.
</P>
<P>
   Before driving to College Station, Michael Roy Self recorded a
new message on his telephone answering machine, asking callers to
phone him on his cellular phone and let him know if they had any
news about his son.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after arriving in College Station, he learned that his
son was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Self's younger brother, Michael Self, 18, just completed Army
basic training. Contacted by phone, he said he was too distraught
to talk about his brother's death.
</P>
<P>
   At A&AMP;M, Self enjoyed playing volleyball and golf and liked
dancing and listening to country music. A member of the Corps of
Cadets Squadron 17, he had helped construct the bonfire last year
as well, Erb said.
</P>
<P>
   Self was torn between working as an engineer or becoming a
minister, Erb said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really involved in local church ministries and was
considering going into the ministry,'' he said. ``He loved God, and
that was a big part of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Working late into the night to erect the logs for the bonfire
typifies Self's life, Jones said. The young man worked in
anonymity, more concerned with the results of his labors than the
commendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Jerry Don as being one of those kids who didn't get
a lot of recognition, but was one of the ones doing most of the
work,'' Jones said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff writer Robert Tharp contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
