<HEADLINE>
AMID HYPE, PINCAY STEERS CLEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Adds info box) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A billboard labeled ``Countdown to History''
looms over the Hollywood Park winner's circle these days, bearing
the career victory totals for Bill Shoemaker (8,833) and Laffit
Pincay (8,818 and counting).
</P>
<P>
   Each time Pincay wins a race, he strides to the board and hangs
a new number beside his name as a track photographer snaps his
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park and Santa Anita are having contests promising an
$8,834 prize to a fan who predicts the day and race when Pincay
passes Shoemaker. Further promotions revolving around Pincay's
record pursuit are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting exciting, especially on days like Wednesday, when
it seemed like old times, with the Panamanian riding in seven races
and winning three, the last by a neck in classic Pincay Power Play
style.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for ``the great man,'' as track announcer Michael
Wrona referred to Pincay in a plug for the contest between races
Thursday, it's as close to business as usual as he and his agent
can make it.
</P>
<P>
   So far, with Pincay 15 wins from tying Shoemaker, trainers and
owners aren't lining up to book his services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't changed at all,'' said agent Bob Meldahl, who has
booked Pincay's mounts since 1991. ``Nobody's expressed, `I'm going
to put you on all these 8-5 shots.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it'll change when he gets to seven or eight (from the
record).''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, people might be angling to have Pincay ride
!ital!their!off! horse to the record.
</P>
<P>
   But if it doesn't happen that way _ if his winning opportunities
don't increase in the next few weeks _ it appears that will be all
right with Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope I don't ride seven, eight horses a day. It's too
demanding,'' Pincay said after his triple on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The only luxury in riding a full card is that Pincay could eat
100 more calories at dinner that night.
</P>
<P>
   At 52, living on 750 calories a day to maintain his 117-pound
riding weight, Pincay feels stronger riding four or five a day.
</P>
<P>
   Often, he rides fewer than that because fields at Hollywood Park
are typically small, and competition for mounts is as keen as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep it to three or four (a day),'' Meldahl said
in the Hollywood Park racing office Thursday morning. ``He's
fresher.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without extra chances, Pincay is riding as well as he has
in years. He has passed the 140-win mark in 1999, already his best
season since '95.
</P>
<P>
   If he kept winning at the rate that put him third in the jockey
standings at the Oak Tree meet, the countdown to history would end
Wednesday, Dec. 29, at Santa Anita. That happens to be Pincay's
birthday _ the day he has said he'd like to do it.
</P>
<P>
   If he kept winning at his 1999 pace, he'd get the record on
Friday, Dec. 31, the fifth day of the Santa Anita season. Then
Pincay might have to allow himself half a glass of champagne that
night.
</P>
<P>
   If he kept winning at his recent pace _ 15 victories in the past
12 racing days, including one Thursday _ he would blow past
Shoemaker on Sunday, Dec. 5. That's practically impossible, though,
because Pincay is scheduled to be in Panama Dec. 2-5 to be honored
at a Latin American jockeys' competition.
</P>
<P>
   Meldahl said a couple of out-of-town stakes assignments later in
December are possible as well. Although a win is a win wherever it
happens, such trips could slow him down simply by reducing his
number of mounts.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Pincay might be helped along if, as usual,
other veteran riders take vacations in December.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's asking for help. Business as usual has always been
good enough for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest with you, I don't think Laffit would
want it any other way,'' Meldahl said. ``He wants trainers to give
him good horses. But he's never in his life asked for anything
special, and he doesn't expect it now.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend: Trainer Bob Baffert, going for his fourth
Hollywood Prevue Stakes victory in a row, will have Cameron Pass
(David Flores riding) and Magical Dragon (Chris McCarron) in the
7-furlong race for 2-year-olds on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert won the race with In Excessive Bull, Commitisize and
Premier Property.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Cenicola-trained Joopy Doopy (Victor Espinoza) is the
likely favorite after going 6 furlongs in 1:08 4/5 to win the Sunny
Slope Stakes at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   The Grade III Prevue, a prep for the Dec. 18 Hollywood Futurity,
is the first of 14 graded stakes on the Hollywood Park schedule.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
Hollywood Park leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Isaias
Enriquez and Pat Valenzuela, 7 wins; Laffit Pincay, 6; Corey
Nakatani and Alex Solis, 5. Trainers: Ian Jory, 4; Mike Mitchell,
3; six tied with 2. &QL; 
Handicapper helper: Until Wednesday, when horses led from gate to
wire in two of the five sprints, front-runners were only 3 for 25
in races up to 7{ furlongs on Hollywood Park's tiring main track. &QL; 
On the stakes schedule: At Hollywood Park: Saturday, $100,000
Hollywood Prevue, 2-year-olds, 7 furlongs; Sunday, $70,000 Matiara,
3-year-old fillies, 1 1/8 miles on turf. At Aqueduct: Saturday,
$150,000 Red Smith Handicap, 3-year-olds and up, 1 3/8 miles on
turf; Thursday, $100,000 Fall Highweight Handicap, 3-year-olds and
up, 6 furlongs. &QL; 
Mileposts: Bob Baffert said Gary Stevens will replace David Flores
aboard beaten Breeders' Cup Juvenile favorite Forest Camp in the
Dec. 18 Hollywood Futurity _ assuming Stevens isn't riding a horse
for the Thoroughbred Corp. in that race. Baffert has blamed Forest
Camp's back-to-back defeats on going too fast too early....
Breeders' Cup Classic winner Cat Thief will resume racing in the
7-furlong Malibu Stakes for 3-year-olds on the Dec. 26 opening card
at Santa Anita, trainer D. Wayne Lukas said.... Golden Gate Fields
opened Wednesday for a 44-day season that includes the Jan. 15
Golden Gate Derby. Frank Stronach's purchase of the San Francisco
Bay Area racetrack is expected to be official in mid-December....
French Group 1 winner Cerulean Sky is coming to Hollywood Park for
the Nov. 28 Matriarch, in which Breeders' Cup Mile runner-up
bold!Tuzla is expected to run and Spanish Fern is a possibility....
Ron McAnally is two away from becoming the second trainer to win
100 stakes at Hollywood Park. Charlie Whittingham had 222.... Dubai
World Cup winner Almutawakel, fifth in the Breeders' Cup Classic,
will stay in the United States for his 5-year-old season with
trainer Mark Hennig.... Retired: Banshee Breeze, the champion
3-year-old filly of 1998 and the runner-up in the past two
Breeders' Cup Distaffs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
