<HEADER>
A4423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS     11-18 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW OBSTACLE ARISES TO PROPOSED OVERHAUL OF ORGAN DISTRIBUTION
SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Ill., N.J., Pa.)  (th) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bitter fight over the nation's system for
distributing donated human organs has erupted in Congress, and a
deal struck last week that would have cleared the way for the
Clinton administration's long-planned overhaul was on the verge of
falling apart Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement reached last week between Donna Shalala,
secretary of health and human services, and a bipartisan group of
congressional members, new federal rules governing organ allocation
would take effect by late December or early January. The agreement
was attached to a spending bill that is due to be considered by
Congress soon.
</P>
<P>
   But in a move late Wednesday, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
and House Speaker Dennis Hastert inserted a countermeasure into a
package that includes two popular bills, one that would help
disabled people get back to work and another that would extend
certain tax credits. That measure would delay the effective date of
the federal rules by three months, giving Congress enough time to
return from its winter break and overturn them.
</P>
<P>
   The package containing the tax credits and work incentives
passed the House on Thursday night. So now there are two major
pieces of legislation working their way through the House and
Senate, each with minor amendments governing organ allocation that
are diametrically opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Because the differing provisions cannot be stripped out of the
bills, it is possible that both could be approved. In that case,
Senate staff members on both sides of the issue said, the bill
signed last would take precedence. But on Thursday, no one was
quite certain how it would turn out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who
supports the Republican leadership and is pressing to delay the
federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli is not the only member crossing party lines. As
chairman of the Senate subcommittee that governs health spending,
Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., worked with Shalala to reach last week's
agreement. On Thursday, a very angry Specter predicted that the
matter might wind up in court, and he threatened to filibuster the
tax-credit legislation to block the actions of his fellow
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the action of the Republican leaders placed
the Clinton administration in a ticklish position. The
administration strongly supports both the tax credit and workplace
bills, and Clinton is not likely to veto them to keep the organ
allocation deal intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have a very serious problem,'' said Dan
Mendelson, associate director for health at the Office of
Management and Budget. ``At this point, it is unclear what is going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute stems from a bitter political and economic feud over
which patients should have priority in receiving human organs, the
nation's scarcest medical resources.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 62,000 Americans are now waiting for a heart, lung,
liver, kidney or pancreas; last year alone, 4,000 people died
waiting. But waiting times vary greatly from region to region, and
in February 1998, Shalala declared the current system unfair and
said she intended to change it.
</P>
<P>
   The country is now divided into 62 local areas, which range in
size from a few counties to several states, and in population from
1 million to 12 million; those areas are subsets of 11 regions.
When an organ becomes available, it is offered locally first, then
regionally, and, in rare cases, nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala's proposal, twice delayed by Congress, would force
organs to be shared across bigger regions, with the sickest
patients getting first priority. The proposal would also greatly
increase the secretary's authority over the United Network for
Organ Sharing, the private agency that contracts with the
government to distribute donated organs. The network has opposed
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has also touched off a fight between large and
small transplant centers, with small centers insisting that
Shalala's rule would put them out of business by steering organs to
big-city hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   This is a major reason why the issue does not divide along party
lines. Members of Congress who represent states that have big
transplant centers tend to support the administration, while those
who represent states with smaller centers want the current system
to remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are extremely high,'' Torricelli said. ``In New
Jersey, a 26-day waiting period for a liver transplant could be
transformed into a 250-day waiting period. Hospitals will close,
donations of organs will be altered. This is an issue that deeply
divides the Congress, and it is something that should be debated
and voted upon in the Congress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
