u r BC-CAR-BISHER-COLUMN19-C     11-18 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BISHER-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart arrives as future of racing
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Look into the face of Tony Stewart and catch the glint
of the unwavering eyes, the even teeth, and you're seeing the new
image of the stock-car racer. The features are those of a young
executive, feet on the ground, head tuned into business. Pleasant,
easy nature, although he does have a temper, which apparently goes
with left-handers, and accommodating. A rookie at the top of his
game.
</P>
<P>
   Then you flash back to the weathered faces of Fireball Roberts,
Cale Yarborough, on down to Darrell Waltrip and Dick Trickle. The
crow's feet gathered at the eyes, the hard lines around the mouth,
all etched there by thousands of hard miles inhaling fumes, and in
earlier times, dust. They laid the foundation for what a major
television network invested millions in the other day. Indianapolis
was once the big dog, the top of the heap, the major leagues.
That's what you drove NASCAR for, to get there. Bobby and Donnie
Allison, Cale Yarborough, Leroy Yarbrough were some who made the
conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart represents the reversal in trend. He worked the
Indianapolis gig to get to NASCAR. He has driven everything from
go-karts to the Indianapolis 500, which he won't be running next
year. That doesn't mean he's restricting himself to stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm driving in a midget race next week,'' he said. ``After
three years of the Indianapolis cars, I lost interest. I didn't
want to run street courses, really didn't want to run road courses.
The midgets I really missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when he ran Indianapolis and Charlotte the same day
and into the night, he drove himself into exhaustion. After
finishing ninth at Indianapolis, he was flown to Charlotte, on a
liquid diet, without eating, and finished fourth, after which he
was rushed to the track infirmary and treated for exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had driven 1,090 miles in one day. I raced 500 miles at
Charlotte, then just tried to hang on for another 100. I won't try
that again, until I forget how bad I felt. I do want to drive Indy
again. I want to win it before I die.''
</P>
<P>
   From the time he was 8 years old, Stewart has had nothing but
racing on his mind. He has worked his way up, as latter-day
wunderkinder have done. He was laid up in his mother's home in
Columbus, Ind., three years ago, recovering from a broken pelvis,
broken collarbone and other calamities, Las Vegas crash mementos,
when the phone rang. His mother said Joe Gibbs was calling.
</P>
<P>
   ```Yeah, right,' I said. But it was. How he got the number I'll
never know. Awhile later, I'd just checked into a hotel in Phoenix
when the phone rang. It was Joe Gibbs calling. He kept calling, and
I guess it was his persistence, but we got together.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Bobby Labonte became teammates, and last week, after
bumping Labonte's car, Stewart went ahead to win at Homestead,
Fla., his third of the season. ``It was an accident, and I
apologized to Bobby. We're OK.''
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us dreamed he'd win a race,'' Joe Gibbs has said.
``We'd thought he'd be up close. None of us dreamed he'd be in the
top 10, much less top five.''
</P>
<P>
   Both he and his affiliate, Home Depot, are NASCAR rookies. Gibbs
by this time is a seasoned veteran of the stocks, a guy who quit
pro football at the top and switched to horses of another nature.
Nobody has ever won a Super Bowl and a Winston Cup, and for that
matter, nobody else has ever worked both jobs before, but with
Stewart on his team, Joe Gibbs is looking good down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the easiest car owner I ever worked for,'' Stewart said.
``He doesn't give you X's and O's like a coach. He doesn't try to
tell you how to drive a race. You see him with a headset on during
the race, but he never says a word.''
</P>
<P>
   Being more than just a driver, Tony understands. He owns cars
himself on about three different levels. One of his drivers in
midgets next year will be another Stewart _ his father, age 62.
</P>
<P>
   Tony is out of the Winston Cup race. Dale Jarrett has that sewed
up. But nobody ever had a rookie season like his, and, win the NAPA
500 at Hampton Sunday, that's like serving notice that here comes
Tony Stewart in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
