A4435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-DRIESELL-TARKANIA     11-18 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DRIESELL-TARKANIAN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Driesell, Tarkanian still coaching after all these years
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia State coach Lefty Driesell is not sure when he
and Fresno State coach Jerry Tarkanian became close friends.
Driesell remembers only the place and the circumstances _ and that
both he and Tarkanian were beginning to go bald.
</P>
<P>
   The place was Hawaii, the circumstances a summer junket
sponsored by a shoe company. The time perhaps was the late 1960s or
early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of coaches were there, but they either spent their time
playing golf or were somewhere shopping with their wives,''
Driesell recalled. ``Tark and I didn't play golf, so we got
together on the beach to swim a little and talk a lot of
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   That scenario was repeated at least five years in a row,
Tarkanian, 69, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd joke about going out and getting our bald heads tanned,''
Tarkanian said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   They are now coaching old-timers. They have a combined total of
1,425 victories in Division I and have outlasted most of their
peers.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, they face off for the eighth time, when Georgia State
opens its season against Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, when I started coaching (at Davidson in 1960), Adolph
Rupp was still going strong,'' said Driesell, who turns 68 on
Christmas Day. ``Now, Dean (Smith) is gone, Norm Stewart, Don
Haskins.... Bobby Knight is still coaching, but he's younger than
Tark and me. We're probably the oldest guys around now.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Smith of North Carolina, the late Adolph Rupp of Kentucky,
Missouri's Norm Stewart, UTEP's Don Haskins and Knight of Indiana _
are among 12 Division I coaches with more than 700 career wins.
Driesell and Tarkanian are on that list with 716 and 709,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we still coaching? I asked my wife that same thing the
other morning, and she said it was probably because I never
considered it a job,'' Driesell said. ``It's always been something
I've enjoyed doing. I know it's not the money, because I've got
plenty of that. You ask Tark and he'll probably tell you the same
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarkanian coached at California junior colleges for seven years
before stints at Long Beach State and UNLV. He returned to his alma
mater in 1995 with the intent of fashioning Fresno State into a
national power before riding off into the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back here because I want to win and win big here before
it's over. That hasn't happened yet, because every year we've had
some kind of problem. We thought this would be the year, but
something has come up already,'' said Tarkanian, who in 28 years in
Division I has won 20 or more games 27 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something'' is the stress fracture sustained by All-America
candidate Courtney Alexander in his left foot and the fractured
tibia that will sideline center Melvin Ely for at least two games.
</P>
<P>
   Driesell was at Maryland and Tarkanian at UNLV when they first
coached against each other. Tarkanian has won six of seven
meetings, including UNLV's victory over Maryland in the '86 NCAA
Tournament at Long Beach State. Fresno State last season beat
Georgia State 83-62.
</P>
<P>
   The battles on the court, however, have not affected their
friendship. They relish the time they have spent together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out in Las Vegas visiting Tark one New Year's Eve and he
took me to one of those parties,'' Driesell said. ``We sat at the
table with Frank Sinatra (who had been a close friend of Tarkanian)
and Elizabeth Taylor. It was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarkanian was with Driesell the night before each of UNLV's four
Final Four appearances in Tarkanian's 19 seasons with the Running
Rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Before UNLV's '87 tournament game against Indiana, the two got
together after Tarkanian broke a dinner date with Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Tark not go out with Bobby, because what (Knight) was
going to do was try to mess up his head,'' Driesell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lefty gave me (grief),'' Tarkanian said. ``I called Bobby and
canceled. But his team beat us anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite having a choice of basketball powers clamoring to play
Fresno State, Tarkanian responded in the affirmative when his old
friend approached him in the spring of '98 about playing
home-and-home dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of Lefty,'' Tarkanian said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
