<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-U.S.-650&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROATIAN GOVERNMENT HARASSING AMERICANS, U.S. OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government of Croatia, an occasional U.S. ally
in peace efforts in the Balkans, is behind a campaign of harassment
against U.S. diplomats and others promoting democracy in Croatia,
according to senior administration officials. Among the actions
were break-ins last month at the homes of a diplomat and a U.S.
government contractor, they added.
</P>
<P>
   The officials say U.S. intelligence agencies have evidence tying
the government of President Franjo Tudjman to the break-ins, which
appear to be an effort to intimidate U.S. diplomats into cutting
off their contacts with opposition political parties in the final
weeks before a parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official has said a listening
device was found in the home of the government contractor _ a U.S.
representative of the National Democratic Institute, which works
closely with the U.S. Embassy in ``democracy building'' projects _
after the break-in at her home.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt in the break-ins, although U.S. officials say
they now fear that government-controlled newspapers and magazines
are trying to incite violence against Americans in Croatia by
portraying them as spies determined to overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary elections are due by late January, and opinion
polls suggest that Tudjman's ruling party may lose. The country
also may soon face presidential elections because Tudjman, who has
run the country with nearly dictatorial powers since it won
independence in 1992, is extremely sick with stomach cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has not formally accused the Croatian
government of ordering the break-ins, but it has demanded that the
culprits be identified and brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two members of the embassy community in Croatia have
experienced break-ins,'' said James P. Rubin, the State
Department's chief spokesman. ``We have referred these cases to
local authorities and are awaiting results of their
investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. diplomat whose home was ransacked was so alarmed that
she left her post weeks ahead of schedule _ her tour ended this
year _ and returned to the United States with her young children,
State Department officials said. She had overseen projects of the
Agency for International Development that were intended to bolster
the organizational skills of opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A department official said the woman's house, in a relatively
isolated neighborhood of Zagreb, had been ``turned upside down''
while she and her children were away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bedroom and an office area were ransacked,'' the official
said. ``Nothing was taken. Nothing was really damaged. It was
outrageous. This was a clear political message to us.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the break-in at the home of the woman
representing the National Democratic Institute was similar in that
no valuables were taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody just rummaged through it,'' said Robert D. Benjamin,
the institute's deputy director for Central Europe. He refused to
speculate on the identity of the intruders, but said, ``We share
the concerns of others who have experienced harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Zagreb office of the institute's Republican
counterpart, the International Republican Institute, recently
installed steel doors in her home to prevent a similar intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the harassment is tied to U.S. government
efforts to assist the opposition parties in mounting a credible
electoral challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Through state-controlled newspapers and magazines, Tudjman's
ruling party, the Croatian Democratic Union, has denounced the U.S.
efforts as interference. U.S. officials said it was unclear what
role, if any, the Croatian leader might have taken in organizing
the harassment of Americans, but they said there is no doubt that
senior officials in his political party are directing the campaign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tudjman, 77, who has had stomach cancer for years, has been
hospitalized, and Western diplomats and Croatian news organizations
have reported that he may be close to death.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven years since Croatia won independence from
Yugoslavia, Tudjman has been alternately condemned and praised by
the United States. He has been criticized for his human rights
record and his brutal treatment of Croatia's Serb population. But
his military assault against Serbian forces in August 1995 in the
Krajina region of Croatia helped force the Serbs to the bargaining
table and prevent a larger war in the Balkans. He also pleased
Washington in 1994 when he persuaded his Bosnian Croat allies to
form a federation with Bosnia's Muslim-led government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
