<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4438 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-COLLAPSE-ART-     11-18 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-COLLAPSE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9 KNOWN DEAD, 28 HURT IN TOWER COLLAPSE AT TEXAS A&AMP;M 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:15 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT29, 30 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ As scores of students were busily
constructing a wooden tower for Texas A&AMP;M University's traditional
football bonfire, the massive 40-foot structure collapsed early
Thursday morning, killing at least nine students beneath a deadly
rubble of logs, some as large as telephone poles.
</P>
<P>
   Even as rescuers continued working into the night, the death
toll seemed likely to rise as officials conceded that the bodies of
two missing students were probably buried beneath the
pyramid-shaped wreckage. Throughout the day, more than a hundred
students wearing hard hats and local firefighters carefully picked
through the rubble, rescuing several students who had been trapped
for hours. At least 28 people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, where football is often described as a secular
religion, the news prompted immediate and widespread grieving as
many television and radio stations interrupted regular programming
to broadcast the rescue efforts. The bonfire is a 90-year-old Texas
A&AMP;M tradition held on the eve of the school's Thanksgiving weekend
game against its archrival, the University of Texas, and this year
it had been scheduled for Thanksgiving night.
</P>
<P>
   The early-morning construction might seem unusual, but
traditionally students work round-the-clock on the tower during the
week leading up to the game. Dr. Ray Bowen, the university
president, said investigators had not yet determined the cause of
the accident, and officials refused to confirm reports that a
55-foot center pole had snapped, saying that experts would work
into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great tragedy,'' said Bowen, noting that the bonfire
will now be canceled. ``Everyone is brokenhearted.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most universities enjoy the allegiance and loyalty of
their students and alumni, few schools elicit the sort of lifelong
passion common at Texas A&AMP;M. Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, a Texas A&AMP;M
alumnus who worked on the construction crews as a student, said the
bonfire was a symbol of the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extraordinary coming together of the student body
to build this bonfire,'' Perry said, in explaining the sentiment
many Aggies, as students and alumni are known, hold for the
bonfire. ``It is very much a part of Aggie lore and traditions and
values. It represents great teamwork. It represents friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Students at the scene described a horrible collapse in the
early-morning hours when much of the campus was sleeping. Tommy
Balez, 20, an electrical engineering student who started working on
the pyramid around midnight, had taken a break about 50 yards away
when he heard a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a loud crack, then another loud crash when it went
over,'' Balez said. He spent more than 12 hours as part of a rescue
team. ``I'm staying until I know everybody is out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Lawson, an acting university spokeswoman, denied any
speculation that carousing by students might have contributed to
the collapse. ``There was no horsing around,'' she said. ``This is
very serious business. They were working, not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Thompson, a Texas A&AMP;M staff member assigned as a student
adviser on the bonfire project, who visited the site at about 10:30
Wednesday night, said he saw no indications at that time of any
problems. At a press conference Thursday afternoon, he said,
``There was no indication of anything unusual. It apparently
collapsed without warning.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students apparently told rescue officials that the center
log snapped at the beginning of the collapse. Thompson said the
center pole is actually two poles bolted together and wrapped in
about 600 feet of steel cable.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
