<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLA-FSU19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gators await humbled Warrick
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Humility, particularly for someone young and
extremely talented, is never easy. But Florida State wide receiver
Peter Warrick says he has had a truckload of it dumped on him since
October.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, once the leading candidate for the Heisman Trophy, saw
that dream disappear with his Oct. 7 arrest on felony theft
charges. A cashier at a Dillard's department store in Tallahassee
sold him and fellow receiver Laveraneus Coles about $400 worth of
merchandise for about $21.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after he was charged, Warrick pleaded guilty to a
misdemeanor, and he avoided jail time in his sentence. After a
two-game suspension, he returned for Florida State's game at
Clemson on Oct. 23. Then he went into a shell, on and off the
field, for several weeks. This week, he broke his silence with the
media and once again apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that a real man admits his mistakes, apologizes
and moves on,'' said Warrick, a senior from Bradenton, Fla.
``That's what I've tried to do. But it hasn't been easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick said he knew that public reaction to his behavior would
be negative. However, he never imagined that on talk shows across
the nation he would become the latest poster child for all that is
wrong with college athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think those people can judge me until they've walked
in my shoes,'' Warrick said. ``I know what I did was wrong. I know
now that I'm a role model to young kids who look up to me. All I
can do is say I'm sorry and promise that I will never do anything
like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick's return to the team after his suspension was in body
but not in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell that he was basically going through the motions
because he was hurting,'' offensive coordinator Mark Richt said.
``Pete has always set the tempo of our practices, because he was
the hardest-working guy out there. But he'd be the first one to
tell you that he wasn't all there.''
</P>
<P>
   After road games at Clemson and Virginia, during which Warrick
received less-than-warm receptions, Florida State returned home for
last week's game against Maryland. It was the final home game for
the Florida State seniors, and Warrick received the loudest ovation
when he was introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick responded with nine catches for 134 yards in the
Seminoles' 49-10 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in a long time, the old Pete was back,''
quarterback Chris Weinke said. ``Just in time, too. Because now we
really neeed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick knows that the always-vociferous Florida fans will be
waiting for him Saturday at The Swamp. The Dillard's in Gainesville
is giving out shopping bags this week in honor of Warrick's
arrival. One entrepreneur has printed T-shirts with the words
``1999 Heistman'' on the front, with a picture of Warrick holding a
Dillard's bag. The shirts flew off the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to stay focused,'' Warrick said. ``This team can
still win the national championship. I've lost the Heisman, but I
can do something about (winning a national title).''
</P>
<P>
   In last year's Florida game, Warrick was the difference. He
caught eight passes for 119 yards and a touchdown, and he threw for
a touchdown in Florida State's 23-12 win.
</P>
<P>
   If the Seminoles win Satuday, they will play in the Sugar Bowl
for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I came back to school _ to play (against Florida)
and to help us win a national championship,'' Warrick said. ``With
everything that's happened, I know this is the game that people
will remember me for.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
