<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scent of terror wafts through King audiobook
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephen King has a new work out, but you won't be able to read
it. Like Tom Wolfe's ``Ambush at Fort Bragg'' in 1997, King's
``Blood and Smoke'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23.50) is available only as
an audiobook.
</P>
<P>
   King says the stories pick up where ``Quitters Inc.'' and ``The
10 O'Clock People'' leave off and focus on ``the horror of the evil
weed, tobacco. There are stories here that scared even me _
psychopathic killers, torture chambers, haunted hotel rooms ... and
wafting through each story, the deadly, seductive scent of
tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories, read by King himself, include ``1408,'' in which an
author accepts a challenge to spend a night in New York City's most
haunted hotel room _ without being able to smoke; ``In the
Deathroom,'' about a man held captive in a South American hideout;
and ``Lunch at the Gotham Cafe,'' a tale of a man going through
withdrawal symptoms from cigarettes and from his soon-to-be
ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the works: Former Miami Herald columnist Tannarive Due has
agreed to write a fictionalized narrative of the legendary Madam
C.J. Walker, the first black millionaire. ``The Black Rose,'' which
will be published by One World/Ballantine in June, was acquired as
part of a two-book deal. The second work, ``The Wisdom of Madam
C.J.,'' set for release in December 2000, will be a collection of
inspirational nonfiction. Due will continue the project begun by
``Roots'' author Alex Haley, who died in 1992. Walker, the daughter
of former Louisiana slaves, was orphaned at 7, worked as a domestic
until she was nearly 40, and then built a hair-care empire that
made her a millionaire by the time of her death at 51.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orchids and Rose: Director Spike Jonze (``Being John
Malkovich'') has agreed to direct the film version of Susan
Orlean's book, ``The Orchid Thief.'' Originally a New Yorker
article, ``The Orchid Thief'' is an account of John LaRoche, a
legendary exotic plant poacher in Florida. Jonathan Demme's Clinica
Estetico productions bought film rights. ... Pete Rose wouldn't
tell NBC reporter Jim Gray, but he promises to reveal all in a
memoir that agent Frank Weiman is shopping to several publishers.
However, Steve Ross of Crown Publishers told the New York Daily
News that Rose does not address the gambling issue and, as far as
he could tell, there was nothing new in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
