<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4443 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-CARTER21-COX     11-18 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CARTER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Billy Carter's son wants to set the record straight
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 21.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKLIN, Tenn. _ Most Americans who were around during Jimmy
Carter's presidency remember first brother Billy Carter as a
wisecracking, beer-guzzling good ol' boy.
</P>
<P>
   That was one image, but it wasn't the complete picture. At least
not to William ``Buddy'' Carter, who wants to set the record
straight about his father in his biography, ``Billy Carter: A
Journey Through the Shadows'' (Longstreet, $22).
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to know he wasn't a joke, which is how the media
portrayed him,'' says Carter, 38, a landscaping foreman for the
city of Franklin. ``Most of the time he was photographed with a
beer in his hand. But he also was a shrewd businessman and a good
father. He read four newspapers a day and six or seven books a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a well-worn vinyl booth in Dotson's Cafe in downtown
Franklin, the slender, sunburned Carter munches on the meatloaf
special of the day and talks about what happened to his father when
a media circus descended on Plains as Jimmy Carter campaigned for
the presidency in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters discovered Billy Carter immediately. They hovered
around his service station, bought him beers and coaxed outrageous
comments out of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he was quotable,'' the younger Carter acknowledges.
``Sometimes embarrassingly so. But in the beginning this was OK; it
was harmless. Then it wasn't long before pictures of him with a
Pabst Blue Ribbon in front of his face began appearing in
newspapers all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jimmy Carter was elected president, the media attention
escalated. And so did Billy Carter's drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the book, I talk about how he was an alcoholic,'' Carter
says. ``He always had been, but it was accelerated by the fame.
When somebody calls you up and says they'll pay you $10,000 a day
and fly you out to California and all you have to do is drink all
day and just talk off the top of your head, most people are gonna
agree to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Carter was having his own problems at the time. He admits
that he was rebellious and aimless. He worked hard at the family
peanut warehouse, but there were no father-and-son chats. Usually
his father would come home to read or sit silently in his favorite
chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody could figure him out,'' Carter says. ``Not even my
mother, who knew him better than anybody. And not the doctors in
the rehabilitation clinic at Long Beach when he went there for his
alcoholism. They tried to get inside his head, and they couldn't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Billy Carter died of
</P>
<P>
   cancer in 1988, any problems between father and son had been
resolved, the son says, but he still didn't understand his father
or the demons that had tormented him.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he could find answers by writing a biography of his
father. Initially it was going to be a traditional biography,
complete with historical details. But after digging through
newspaper clippings and TV tapes, he realized that all the research
was unnecessary. What he really wanted to do was write about how he
felt about his father. And he wanted to set the record straight
about who his father really was.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, says the son, Billy Carter was not a redneck
buffoon. He never hunted, cared little for wrestling or auto racing
and spent most of his free time reading.
</P>
<P>
   And, Buddy Carter adds, contrary to published reports, his
father was not an inept businessman who ran the family peanut
business into the ground. After Jimmy Carter became president,
Carter's Warehouse was placed in a blind trust, which left
management of the company in the hands of lawyers who knew nothing
about farming. Unable to influence the decisions of the management
team, Billy Carter quit the business and quietly accepted the
criticism when the company ended up $1 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no response to the book from the former
president, but reaction from the rest of the family has been
positive. Sybil Carter praises her son for portraying her husband
honestly, even though some of the memories are painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it took a lot for him to write the book,'' she says.
``But if you're going to present a true picture of someone, you
have to show warts and all. Billy was a very complex person, very
smart, but he had an illness. The book shows him in another light,
through his son's eyes in a way they may not have seen through the
media.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter will return to Plains this month for book signings and to
visit his father's grave. And, as usual, he will take a beer with
him to the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' he says, staring into the distance, ``it's my way
of talking to him.''
</P>
<P>
   BOOK SIGNING
</P>
<P>
   William ``Buddy'' Carter will sign books Friday from 10 a.m. to
</P>
<P>
   1 p.m. at Carter's Flower and Gifts, 105 W. Main St., Plains
(912-824-5306) and from 4 to
</P>
<P>
   6 p.m. at Americus Bookstore,
</P>
<P>
   122 W. Forsyth St., Americus (912-928-2849).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
