</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORK-CONGRESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING BILLS IN CONGRESS SEND TONS OF PORK MONEY TO REMOTE
ALASKA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT35 _ is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a throw-away line on NBC's ``West Wing,''
biting in its indictment of an inventive, sometimes outlandish bid
by Congress to spend taxpayer money. There, amid a list of
appropriations requests recited by a fictional White House aide,
was a gem: $2 million to monitor Alaskan skies for volcanic ash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are volcanos in Alaska?'' a ``West Wing'' aide asked,
smirking.
</P>
<P>
   Cue laughter and eye-rolling.
</P>
<P>
   But in the chandelier-studded offices of Sen. Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, who as chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee
controls billions of dollars, the joke was not funny. That is
because the item was not a made-up bit of drama, something writers
of the series knew when they used it. It was a genuine Stevens
request and a sparkling example of the senator's mastery at
steering copious amounts of money to his home state.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Stevens has gotten so good at sending taxpayers' money
Alaska's way that he is threatening to outdo even the legendary
Sen. Robert Byrd in that department, a man whose name adorns many a
highway and building in his home state, West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They laughed hysterically about that: $2 million to track
volcanic ash in Alaska,'' said Connie Godwin, Stevens' press
secretary. ``They would be lucky about the $2 million if they were
on that KLM plane 10 years ago that dropped thousands of feet
because of the ash it sucked in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by a fat economy and a budget surplus, this year
promises to set new records in Congress when it comes to funneling
taxpayer money to projects like counting walruses and fixing YMCA
swimming pools. Detractors call it pork, but those who benefit call
it filet mignon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest pork barbecue of all time, and
unfortunately, at this barbecue, it's the taxpayers who are getting
cooked,'' said Jim Campi, a spokesman for Citizens Against
Government Waste, an organization dedicated to eliminating
``pork,'' or the billions of dollars routed to projects back home
that among other things are not requested by the White House or
reviewed by a congressional committee. The organization's pork
busters will be busy tallying all the special projects in all the
final spending bills over the weeks to come, but right now,
Congress is primed to surpass last year's numbers easily, Campi
said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the pork estimate in 7 of the 13 spending bills for the
fiscal year 2000 is $14.65 billion, Campi said, while the record
for pet projects, set in 1997, was a total of $14.5 billion. And
this under a Republican regime devoted to less government.
</P>
<P>
   For Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is seeking the presidential
nomination and has made pork-busting a mission, this increase in
pet projects, under Republican watch, ranks among his greatest
disappointments. He calls it an evil linked to special interest
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't judge the projects on their merits,'' McCain said. ``I
can judge the fact that the entire legislative process has been
turned on its head.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tussle for pet-project money, known as earmarks, few
lawmakers hold greater sway than the chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, the panel that divides billions of
dollars to keep the military churning, farmers afloat, research
institutions financed and highways built.
</P>
<P>
   For Stevens, the 76-year-old veteran of three decades in the
Senate, what is remarkable is not so much that he carves out
millions of dollars for projects in his home state, with the help
of the other two members of the Alaskan delegation, Sen. Frank
Murkowski and Rep. Don Young, who are also Republicans. It is that
he manages to do so despite the fact that his home state has about
the same number of people as Milwaukee, 614,000.
</P>
<P>
   In some places in rural southeast Alaska, townspeople are so
appreciative that they have dubbed the dollars ``Stevens money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been able to master the art of putting his state first
in line, even though it was the last to join the union,'' said
Marshall Wittmann, director of congressional relations for the
conservative research group, the Heritage Foundation. ``This was
the art of Byrd: take an underpopulated rural state and just pour
in millions upon millions of federal money.''
</P>
<P>
   Wittmann added, ``The joke was that the federal government was
going to move to Martinsburg, West Virginia, and now there is a
danger it will move to Anchorage.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Alaska received more money through earmarks per
person _ $273 _ than any other state, according to Citizens Against
Government Waste. Hawaii came in second, at $155. The national
average was $19. Mississippi led in earmarked money in 1998, thanks
to the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   This coming year could be a tossup between the two states,
considering the $375 million that Lott wrangled to begin building a
$1.5 billion Navy ship that the Pentagon never requested.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Stevens was gung-ho about pet projects ``because he
feels that Alaska has never been given the equal consideration that
other states have been given.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As for Alaska, it will find itself with a bevy of new projects
in the new year, with some already signed into law, and others
waiting in the wings pending Senate approval. Stevens regularly
secures millions for projects in and around Alaska's military
bases, as well as for its fishing, oil and timber industries, and
millions more to create jobs, build highways and finance smaller
projects in communities.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, $900,000 for an airport on St. George's
Island, a speck of a place off Alaska's coast. There is $2.5
million to train Russian and other foreign workers in oil field
management in Alaska, $7.9 million to build the Alaska Maritime
National Wildlife Refuge and visitor center in Homer, $2.2 million
for a senior citizens center in Anchorage and $15 million for the
University of Alaska to study the aurora borealis, a perennial pet
projetevens.
</P>
<P>
   Military bases in Alaska also benefit. There is $9.5 million to
fix a highway at the Elmendorf Air Force Base, $12 million to
refurbish the barracks at Fort Richardson and another $13 million
to build a parking ramp for a C-130 there.
</P>
<P>
   Sea life, too, would be well tended. There is $100,000 to
conduct a census of Pacific walruses, $4 million to help stranded
sea lions and $5 million to monitor fish.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting fish and its fishermen ranks high on the list, with
millions of dollars earmarked for salmon related projects,
including $900,000 to the Bering Sea Fisherman's Association, which
is so well cared for by Stevens that it does not even have to
demand money for its struggling fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Stevens, God bless him,'' said Jude Henzler, the
executive director of the association, based in Anchorage. ``He's
been a godsend to the fisherman in general. You can't lard it on
too thick.''
</P>
<P>
   One amazing feat of Stevens this year is a request for $22
million in emergency financing over a three-year period for four
tiny towns in southeast Alaska that were hard hit by restrictions
on tree cutting.
</P>
<P>
   But in the spirit of ``one person's pork being another's prime
cut,'' as Wittmann, of the Heritage Foundation, put it, the money
has gone, and will go, a long way to helping these communities stay
alive. And this, Stevens' press secretary said, is the unspoken
value of pork, which the senator believes is categorized much too
broadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for Senator Stevens, we'd be in a lot of trouble
for sure,'' said Stan Filler, the mayor of Sitka, a southeastern
Alaska town of 8,000 people that suffered from the timber
industry's decline. Sitka would receive $4 million over three years
to set up new businesses and repair roads and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of years, we didn't get anything, flat nothing,''
Filler said. ``It wasn't like we were even here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
