</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4447 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-GATES21-COX     11-18 2748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GATES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Henry Gates set on putting Africa on the cultural map
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 21.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ In the haze of memory, the night's marination
is clearer than any meal set before them or how the idea took
shape. It was at an Indian restaurant in London, sometime in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Louis Gates Jr. recalls that it was Wole Soyinka's order
of protocol that the number of bottles of wine brought to the table
be in direct proportion to the number of diners. Three sat down to
eat that evening 26 years ago, and ``we got drunk as skunks,''
Gates says.
</P>
<P>
   Indiscretion is more easily admitted to here when the passage of
years bathes it in the glow of youthful abandon. It helps, of
course, to have achieved something in the interim, and a Nobel
Prize for literature, in Soyinka's case, will do. Henry Louis Gates
at the time was a mere graduate student, and a lonely one at that.
He'd arrived at a place _ Cambridge University _ where African
literature wasn't recognized as a real course of study. Ask around
in the anthropology department, someone told him. Isn't that where
they study Africa?
</P>
<P>
   Gates, speaking recently to an hors d'oeuvre-nibbling,
wine-sipping audience at a Boston public television station, was
saying _ in so many words _ that it was a time in a young man's
life when he thinks grand thoughts, wants to do what hasn't been
done.
</P>
<P>
   And now he had done them, fulfillment of not only the quixotic
idea three black men drank to a quarter-century ago but also the
dream W.E.B. Du Bois had in 1909. Soyinka, the only one remotely
well-known at the time, noted that there was an Encyclopaedia
Britannica and an Encyclopedia Americana, but no Encyclopedia
Africana. It had been Du Bois' dream to validate Africa's cultural
worth to the world in just such a way.
</P>
<P>
   Because Du Bois did not live to see it realized, Soyinka said
that night, the obligation for seeing it through was left to others
_ to Africans like himself and Anthony Appiah, the third member of
their party that night, and to African-Americans like Henry Louis
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasms run high when the wine flows, and many a dreamy idea
is put forward, embraced with hearty approval and forgotten by the
time the tab comes around. But Henry Louis Gates swims ceaselessly
in ideas and projects, and now one had taken permanent possession
of him. They would produce the Black Britannica.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, Sir Kenneth Clark's television series
``Civilization,'' along with a book of the same title, captured a
huge popular audience. ``I wanted to do for Africa,'' Gates says,
``what it never would have occurred to Kenneth Clark to do.'' To
Clark no less than to Hume, Hegel and other Western thinkers
through the centuries, Africa had not yet seen civilization. It had
produced no Newton, no Shakespeare, no Dante, no Michelangelo, no
Leonardo, no Goethe. ...
</P>
<P>
   But Gates knew that it had had its glories, too, and that they
were a legitimate part of the human fabric. Ever since he was a boy
growing up in Piedmont, W.Va., a town of 2,000 in the panhandle of
that oddly picturesque state of mountain hollows and exhausted coal
fields, Skippy Gates' imagination was fired by romantic images of
ancient Nubian kings and queens in Africa, regal and beautiful,
powerful and mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   He was recounting all this to a very hoity-toity crowd of
perhaps 300 at WGBH, a good half of whom were black. They were
there for a preview of Gates' PBS series ``The Wonders of the
African World,'' as well as for a talk about the newly published
``Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American
Experience,'' edited by Gates and Appiah.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Gates had called to suggest I drop by for the
preview. My plane from Atlanta was scheduled to land in Boston half
an hour before it started, and I hadn't planned to travel in coat
and tie. ``How dressy is it?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeans are cool, man,'' Gates said. And then, as if further
assurance would seal it, he said, ``Hey, we all a bunch of
Negroes.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was silk tie all the way, but Gates cannot help
being disarming and ingratiating in the same breath. He is that way
in public and in private, a self-confessed ``race'' man who doesn't
believe in race as a biological condition, a man who ``loves
everything about African-American culture'' but wears a neatly
pressed white shirt every day, a black man who had a white
girlfriend in elementary school, another in high school and today
is married to a white woman.
</P>
<P>
   If they are contradictions, they help to explain why Henry Louis
Gates has rapidly become a black man for all seasons, showing up on
PBS, in The New Yorker, on the op-ed page of The New York Times
and, now, on book tours promoting ``Wonders of the African World,''
the companion volume to the PBS series, and ``Africana.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year he was elected to the American Academy of Arts
and Letters, and last year he was chosen as a member of the
Pulitzer Prize committee.
</P>
<P>
   He is everywhere. Plop him down in Ethiopia and who does he run
into in the hotel lobby but Louis Farrakhan, clearly surprised and,
a viewer gathers, not enormously pleased. ``I knew he didn't like
the piece I wrote about him in The New Yorker,'' Gates says in his
Harvard office, ``but I asked one of his bodyguards if I could get
a few minutes with him. He's looking at me through those dark
glasses and says with absolutely no expression in his voice, `If
you think he's going to let your jive-ass interview him, you're
crazy.'''
</P>
<P>
   But of course he did, and the strained exchange on camera _
suspicion and dislike transparent through the icy civility _ is one
of the humorous moments in ``Wonders of the African World.'' It is
also, in its way, typical of Gates _ open to everyone, black or
white. Not only does he bump into the minister of the Nation of
Islam, but on the same trip he buttonholes the archbishop of
Canterbury and the patriarch of the Eastern Orthodox Church. All
are in Ethiopia because of reports that the ark of the covenant _
housed in the temple built by King Solomon, lost after the temple
was destroyed by the Babylonians in 581 B.C. _ is buried in the
ancient Ethiopian town of Axum. Whether the claims are true or not,
they reaffirm for Gates the centrality of Africa in the human
family and in the march of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of Africa itself means more to him than the sanctity of
the blood. ``My ethnicity is not the most important thing about
me,'' he says. ``In my classes, I ask my students: `When you're on
your deathbed, do you think you're going to be thinking about what
race you were?'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had a hip replaced last year, the last thing on my mind
was my blackness. I was wondering if I was going to wake up from
anesthesia. What do you think about when you're in love? You want
to know if she loves you, not if she loves your black self.''
</P>
<P>
   They are questions _ Love &AMP; Death _ closer to the bone than to
skin pigment.
</P>
<P>
   The man saying these things is the same man who, when he was
applying for admission to Yale University, wrote in his Personal
Statement: ``My grandfather was a colored man, my father is a Negro
and I am black.'' (``If that doesn't get their attention, nothing
will,'' he thought.)
</P>
<P>
   But aren't we, someone asks him, greater than the sum of our
demographic parts _ our race, our sex, our ethnicity? He pauses.
``That's a good way of putting it,'' he says. ``You would like to
think so. Race shouldn't matter, but it does. It does because of
slavery and segregation.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 49, Gates is a caramel-colored man for whom race is
essential, perhaps even primary, but not all-defining. His
sentences are often punctuated by an infectious sotto voce chuckle.
``Skip is the happiest, most joyful, optimistic person I've ever
met,'' Sharon Adams, his wife of 20 years, says. They met in 1972
when both were campaigning for former West Virginia Gov. Jay
Rockefeller. ``He loves people. It comes from having had fantastic
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   In his gold wire-rimmed glasses, he can convey a teasing
impishness but more often a sense of being comfortable in his own
skin. He calls himself an African-American, but says, ``I don't
believe liberation lies in what we call ourselves.'' Race, for
Gates, is more a question of historical and cultural heritage than
blood pride. ``If you're counting heads,'' he says, ``I got as many
white ancestors as black,'' and he reaches for a picture on a
credenza behind his desk. ``Look at my father,'' he says. In the
picture, Henry Louis Gates Sr., 86, a paper mill worker who worked
nights as a janitor to send his two sons to school, is shown
alongside Skip and Paul Gates and their late mother. They are all
light and yet black at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard University, barely 10 years after becoming prominent
in the small and remote galaxy of literary criticism, Henry Louis
Gates is almost an industry unto himself _ W.E.B. Du Bois professor
of the Humanities, chairman of the department of Afro-American
Studies, recruiter of faculty members, speakers, benefactors. In an
atmosphere that takes eminence for granted, Henry Louis Gates is
something more. He is a bona fide star, known not just within the
academy but in the larger world.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Fish, the former chairman of Duke University's
much-publicized English department, is as responsible as anyone for
launching Gates' career. Gates was teaching English at Cornell
University in the late '80s when Fish, now dean of the College of
Liberal Arts and Sciences at the University of Illinois-Chicago,
spotted him at a meeting of the Modern Language Association. ``My
first impression of him was that this is an incredibly energetic
person,'' Fish says. ``He tossed out ideas and projects faster than
anyone I've known. I told him I wanted him to come to Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   Fish's livery came to include a number of high-profile
academics, and their salaries created considerable sticker shock
elsewhere in the university. Gates may have been the least
well-known at the time; he may be the only one whose name still
rings a bell.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not a happy experience, at least for Gates. ``I don't
think Duke was prepared for him in any sense,'' Fish says. ``When
you hire Skip Gates, in a sense you're hiring Skip Gates
Enterprises.''
</P>
<P>
   If Duke wasn't sure that's what it wanted, Harvard was. ``One
day the phone rang,'' Gates says, ``and it was Harvard. Listen,
getting out of Duke was like getting out of hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he left, he became the larger cultural figure he is today.
The speed of his ascent has led some to see in him a streak of
self-promotion. Ali Mazrui, a professor of political science and
African studies at the State University of New York at Binghamton,
calls himself a friend of Gates' although he is no fan of his PBS
special. ``There's a striking and gifted entrepreneur in him,'' he
says. ``The fact that he moved from Cornell to Duke to Harvard so
fast should be evidence of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others view him more generously. ``He's very strong on
African-American achievements,'' Fish says, ``but he took care from
the beginning to distance himself from the stronger forms of
Afrocentrism and from those forms that are tied to anti-Semitism.
Skip would be comfortable in a conversation with the
poststructuralists, the feminists, the deconstructionists and all
the other `ists,' but he also gets along with conservatives _
except perhaps for people on the far right like Thomas Sowell and
Shelby Steele.''
</P>
<P>
   His flexibility and independence have made him what Fish calls
``a national social critic.'' ``His pieces in The New Yorker are
chock-full of information and just brimming with intelligence
without knocking you over the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates' book ``The Signifying Monkey,'' an exercise in literary
criticism, won an American Book Award in 1989, but you sense that
he is happier bestriding several worlds. Late on an October
afternoon he hangs up the phone in his office and says, ``That was
The New York Times. They're going to run my op-ed piece.'' The
piece is an argument for bringing more black content _ more color,
you could say _ to the Internet as a means of attracting
African-Americans. As the Internet becomes more a part of American
life, Gates is troubled by what he calls a digital divide _ whites
online, blacks largely not online.
</P>
<P>
   The same week, in New York, he will be speaking alongside the
other Gates _ Bill _ at a symposium addressing the issue. ``It's
going to be the Gates Brothers,'' he says. ``You should come up and
catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Five o'clock has come and gone, and Gates is getting ready to
leave for the day. In a few hours the first episode of ``The
Wonders of the African World'' will air. He ducks his head into the
next-door office of Cornel West, the African-American philosopher
and social critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What're you doing tonight?'' Gates asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to watch the show,'' West says.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon over and watch it at our house,'' Gates says.
</P>
<P>
   Stars hang out with stars.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gates is the best-known African-American intellectual in
the country, he is not every black intellectual's cup of tea. For
some, he has played to a white gallery, and succeeded all too well.
A few days after ``The Wonders of the African World'' aired,
postings on the Internet gave voice to a resentment that would not
have been heard five or six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been receiving a lot of e-mail from colleagues _
specialists in Africa on one level or another,'' says
SUNY-Binghamton professor Mazrui. ``They were overwhelmingly
critical, many of them angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Few could have been more critical than Mazrui's own posting,
which says in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the TV series is more divisive than the book. The
first TV episode sings the glories of ancient Nubia
(understandably) but at the expense of dis-Africanizing ancient
Egypt. On the evidence of a European guide, Gates allows ancient
Egyptians to become racist whites trampling underfoot Blacks from
Upper Nile. Are ancient Egyptians no longer Africans?''
</P>
<P>
   Gates has heard the criticism. ``That's fine. I'm sure not
everyone agrees with everything I write,'' he says. ``But there's a
group of people who don't believe in airing dirty laundry in
public.'' He means, in particular, his interview with Akosua Perbi,
a historian at the University of Ghana at Legon. Africans, Perbi
told Gates, had engaged in slavery long before the Europeans
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It is a delicate question, seldom discussed with candor. ``It's
easier to blame the Europeans,'' Gates says. Perbi also explains
how the system of slavery that existed in Africa was not based on
race, and why it was not always a permanent condition of life or
the fate of the slave's children. Then came the Europeans, and they
brought to it real brutality. But there could have been no
trans-Atlantic slave trade without the complicity of West Africans
rulers and merchants who profited from the sale of human beings to
the Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a scholar,'' Gates says. ``I welcome debate. But if these
people have a problem with what Akosua Perbi said, they need to
take it up with her.''
</P>
<P>
   He is sitting in his Harvard office, on a campus where, a
quarter-century ago, the history and cultural heritage of Africa
meant little more than it did at Cambridge. ``I'm a `race' man, as
they used to say, but I get paid to teach courses in
African-American literature,'' Gates says. ``And I love it. It's
got a double charge. It excites me intellectually, and it enables
me to make a political statement.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's more important to know what people thought and did than
what they looked like, then Africa has its own repository of
achievement _ and cruelty _ like Europe and every other continent.
If not all of it is heroic, ``why should we expect history in
Africa to be less messy than it is anywhere else.'' For Henry Louis
Gates, what matters more is that it is not a curiosity or an
aberration but a part of the human story _ and thus a story in
which we mutually share.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK SIGNING
</P>
<P>
   Henry Louis Gates Jr. will talk about ``Africana: The
Encyclopedia of the African Experience'' and ``The Wonders of the
African World'' at the Auburn Avenue Research Library at 6 p.m.
Monday. 101 Auburn Ave. N.E. Atlanta .770-469-0343.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
