r e BC-BOOKS-GATESBIO21-COX     11-18 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GATESBIO21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Gates file
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 21.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: Sept. 16, 1950, in Piedmont, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: Yale University,
</P>
<P>
   bachelor's in history, 1973 (summa cum laude).
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge University, master's and doctorate in English language
and literature, 1974 and 1979, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Academic posts:
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University, 1991-present.
</P>
<P>
   Duke University, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell University, 1985-89.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University, 1976-85.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Awards and honors:
</P>
<P>
   American Academy of Arts and
</P>
<P>
   Letters, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   National Humanities Medal, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   One of Time magazine's ``25 Most Influential Americans,'' 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Smith Book Award, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   George Polk Award for Social
</P>
<P>
   Commentary, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   American Book Award, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur Foundation ``genius grant,'' 1981.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family: Married for 20 years to Sharon Adams. They have two
teenage daughters.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Wonders of the African World'' (Knopf, $40, 275 pages): In
this lavish companion volume to the PBS television series, Gates
provides a highly personal narrative for Lynn Davis' striking
photos taken throughout their 12-nation trek. Numerous historical
photographs and illustrations are included as well.
</P>
<P>
   OPENING LINES: ``So, Daddy, what in the world am I supposed to
have in common with them?'' my younger daughter, Liza, shouted at
me within the confines of our suffocating train cabin, furnished by
the BBC and Zambia National Railways. It was more a cry of
frustration than anger. In 1994, we were on a 3,000-mile train
trip, filming an episode of ``Great Railway Journeys'' for the BBC
and PBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing!'' her older sister, Maggie, responded on my behalf.
... ``They live in mud huts,'' she continued, ``they are covered
with dust, their clothes are ragged ... they don't even wear
shoes!''
</P>
<P>
   What do we have in common? I allowed myself to wonder in
silence, seeking to avoid the smug intensity of my daughters' gaze
as they dared me to try to think of a convincing response, even
while some part of them might have been desperately hoping that I
could.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African
American Experience,'' co-edited with Kwame Anthony Appiah (Perseus
Books, $100). This massive, 2,095-page volume purports to tell the
history of the African diaspora. Inspired by W.E.B. Du Bois and
assisted by an advisory board led by Nigerian Nobel Laureate Wole
Soyinka, its 3,000 chapters cover topics ranging from ``affirmative
action'' to ``zydeco,'' featuring hundreds of maps, charts and
photographs. Also included are interpretive essays on the Harlem
Renaissance by David Levering Lewis, Du Bois by Cornel West, women
and the black Baptist church by Evelyn Brooks Higginbotham, and
others.
</P>
<P>
   The six-hour PBS series ``Wonders of the African World'' will
air again on WGTV in February. Meanwhile, it is available on home
video for $59.98 through a special Web site, www.pbs.org/wonders.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELA ROWLINGS
</P>
<P>
   Boldword Harvard professor Henry Louis Gates, Jr. head of the
Afro American studies program at Harvard. Harvard professor Henry
Louis Gates, Jr. head of the Afro American studies program at
Harvard. Harvard professor Henry Louis Gates, Jr. head of the Afro
American studies
</P>
