<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4452 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIE-WORLD19-COX     11-18 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WORLD19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bond's `World' is not enough
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pierce Brosnan is so likable as James Bond because he believes
in James Bond. Timothy Dalton didn't believe; he almost sneered.
Roger Moore made Bond a joke. And Sean Connery ... well, he doesn't
need to believe. He was, is and will forever be Bond, whether he
likes it or not.
</P>
<P>
   But Brosnan, despite rumors that he was tired of the role,
clearly still buys into the whole Agent 007 bit _ from the
outrageous stunts to the outlandish double entendres.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, even Brosnan isn't enough to rescue ``The World Is Not
Enough.'' Though it boasts some of the classiest credentials ever
attached to the series _ director Michael Apted (``Coal Miner's
Daughter,'' ``28 Up'') and actors Judi Dench (``Shakespeare in
Love''), Sophie Marceau and Robert Carlyle _ the movie seems dated
and confused. As if everyone involved knew how to make a Bond
movie, but they were thinking about something else at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The picture opens with the usual bang. It's a thrilling set
piece that sends speedboats racing through the middle of London.
Then it settles into the expected groove. Agent 007 sparring with M
(Dench), Q's gadgets, beautiful women and lots of opportunities for
the stuntmen and second unit to strut their stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The plot, if it matters, has to do with rival pipelines being
built to send oil westward from Central Asia. After Marceau's
father, an old chum of M's, is murdered by a nut-case terrorist
(Carlyle), Bond is assigned to protect her and her pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   He does both without much help from either Apted or the
by-the-numbers script. Brosnan is game, but you have to think that,
after the success of ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' he may want to
switch to a different 1960s sex-symbol franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the best thing in the movie is Denise Richards
(``Starship Troopers,'' ``Wild Things'') as a nuclear scientist
wearing tight tank tops and short shorts. Not only does she have a
nostalgia-perfect sex-kitten pout, but she delivers her lines in a
flat centerfold-wannabe monotone. Because she showed that she can
act in last summer's ``Drop Dead Gorgeous,'' you can't help but
wonder whether the cardboard characterization is intentional. If
so, it's absolutely brainy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Is Not Enough''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Pierce Brosnan, Sophie Marceau and Robert Carlyle.
Directed by Michael Apted. Rated PG-13
</P>
<P>
   for intense sequences of action violence, some sexuality and
innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 8 min-
</P>
<P>
   utes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The same old same old.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar
</P>
<P>
   pros-
</P>
<P>
   pects:
</P>
<P>
   Never say
</P>
<P>
   never when
</P>
<P>
   it comes to James Bond and special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
