<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4453 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-HOLIDAY21-COX     11-18 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HOLIDAY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hollywood rolls out the big guns, from an encore of those
quirky, comic toys to heavy-hitting dramas
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 21.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ollywood is planning on ushering in the new year with a Y2 KO.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best family films in years kicks off the holiday
season. Disney's ``Toy Story 2,'' opening Wednesday, is a nonstop
visual joy ride punctuated with plenty of laughs to last through
infinity and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   As the '90s close, film biographies are also coming on strong.
Jim Carrey dons the impish, cunningly wacko veneer of stand-up
enigma Andy Kaufman for December's ``Man on the Moon,'' laced with
new songs from R.E.M. Denzel Washington makes a potent case for a
best actor Oscar nomination for his blistering portrayal of boxer
Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter in ``The Hurricane.'' And three young
unknowns play writer Frank McCourt in ``Angela's Ashes,'' director
Alan Parker's moving and sometimes devastating version of the
author's immensely popular memoirs of his impoverished childhood in
1930s-'40s Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz is building for Tom Hanks' ``The Green Mile,'' another
prison drama from the makers of ``The Shawshank Redemption.'' And
you'll be seeing massive Oscar campaigns for Jodie Foster's lavish
remake of ``Anna and the King,'' Matt Damon and Gwyneth Paltrow's
unsettling character thriller ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' and
Oliver Stone's pro football drama ``Any Given Sunday,'' fronted by
Al Pacino in his tour de force follow-up to ``The Insider.''
</P>
<P>
   We've snagged several early peeks at the more than 30 films
coming to metro Atlanta between now and early January. Here's a
rundown (as always, opening dates are subject to change):
</P>
<P>
   `RIDE WITH THE DEVIL'
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 17.
</P>
<P>
   You expect detail from director Ang Lee. The resonating crunch
of frozen water under a young boy's footsteps as ``The Ice Storm''
nears its painful conclusion. Hugh Grant's perfect-pitch, bumbling
discourse in ``Sense and Sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lee has turned a perceptive ear and lens toward the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ride With the Devil,'' Lee's third English-language film,
stars Tobey Maguire (center), Jeffrey Wright (left), pop's
neo-folky Jewel (right) and Skeet Ulrich in a finely tuned
remembrance of the Union-Confederate struggle in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The characters' diction twists on the gentle formality of the
period. ``Our horses' backs remain our only residences,'' one
character says in relating how teen and twentysomething boys and
men band to fight on the conflict's frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Gripping fight scenes contain the same sort of audible zing-ping
bullet trajectories moviegoers heard in ``Saving Private Ryan.''
And off the battlefield, ``Devil'' is unhurried in its intricate
depiction of a young man's coming of age under extreme
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   `ANGELA'S ASHES'
</P>
<P>
   Opens in December in Los Angeles and New York; Jan. 7 in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Frank McCourt's popular memoirs about growing up in impoverished
Ireland arrives on the big screen as bleak and beautiful as fans
might hope for.
</P>
<P>
   Three talented young actors portray McCourt through more than a
decade of his ``miserable Irish childhood,'' brimming with death,
the sting of regional hatred and adult alcoholism. And following
Oscar nominations for last year's ``Hilary and Jackie'' and her
1996 breakout film ``Breaking the Waves,'' Emily Watson (from left,
with Ciaran Owens and Robert Carlyle) could well find herself in
the running again for her authoritative performance as McCourt's
mom.
</P>
<P>
   At times nearly as heartbreaking as Francois Truffaut's ``The
400 Blows,'' ``Ashes'' is also infused with sweet humor (McCourt
prays to ``the Father, the Son and the holy toast'') and the warm
glow in a boy's eyes as he watches a bigger-than-life James Cagney
in ``Public Enemy'' at a ramshackle Limerick moviehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Director Alan Parker (``The Commitments,'' ``Mississippi
Burning'') says he was determined to make the film after reading
McCourt's book. ``It was the beauty of Frank's writing. I thought
it was incredibly engaging and had incredible heart. In Frank's
very Irish way he also made it very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   And Parker was committed to making it authentic, right down to
Limerick's foggy, watery weather that contributed so much to the
period's health problems. ``We did have rain machines in pretty
much every scene,'' he says. ``There were a lot of damp, soggy
feet. For three months I didn't talk to the crew without somebody
blowing their nose at me.''
</P>
<P>
   `THE HURRICANE'
</P>
<P>
   Opens in December in Los Angeles and New York; Jan. 14 in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington is on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   This month, his new serial killer thriller ``The Bone
Collector'' opened as the No. 1 movie at the box office. He's in
metro Atlanta filming the Disney football flick ``Remember the
Titans'' for producer Jerry Bruckheimer. ``60 Minutes'' plans to
profile him in January.
</P>
<P>
   And in the middle of it all, he'll unveil ``The Hurricane.'' He
plays Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, the talented boxer unjustly
imprisoned for decades for a crime he didn't commit. Directed by
Norman Jewison (``In the Heat of the Night''), it's easily
Washington's best performance since he won an Oscar as the ex-slave
soldier Trip in 1989's ``Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington added muscle mass and a 10-ton attitude to play the
sometimes hot-tempered, often gentle, spiritual Carter.
</P>
<P>
   He's backed by a solid supporting cast, including Rod Steiger,
David Paymer, Dan Hedaya and, especially, Vicellous Reon Shannon as
the teen who corresponds with Carter in prison and believes in his
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
