<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4454 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-HOLIDAY-LIST21     11-18 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HOLIDAY-LIST21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holiday movies first look
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are more early looks and updates on select holiday movies.
As always, opening dates are subject to change. Unless otherwise
noted, material is written by movie critic Bob Longino.
</P>
<P>
   ``TOY STORY 2''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Who would ever think Tim Allen could upstage Tom Hanks? Allen's
Buzz Lightyear may get second billing to Hanks' Woody, but he
steals the sequel. This boisterous, fun, computer-animated frolic
moves at light speed as Woody is captured by a toy rustler, and a
commando team of little Andy's playthings, led by Buzz, goes to the
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``LAST NIGHT''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   David Cronenberg (``eXistenZ,'' ``Dead Ringers'') joins an
ensemble cast in Canadian filmmaker Don McKellar's oddly funny,
certainly peculiar vision of what people might say, think and feel
in the final hours leading up to the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``TUMBLEWEEDS''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The mother-daughter films just keep coming. Janet McTeer and
young newcomer Kimberly J. Brown turn in fine performances as a
family duo heading west after yet another of mom's failed
relationships. McTeer's portrayal _ a combination of sultry
seductress and staunch protector in full Southern drawl _ is
especially effective. The English-born actress won a Tony for the
Broadway revival of ``A Doll's House'' in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GREEN MILE''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment Weekly already seems to be handing the Oscar to
Tom Hanks' Depression-era prison drama, directed by Frank Darabont
(``The Shawshank Redemption''). Hanks plays a death row guard
mesmerized by a hulking convicted killer (Michael Clarke Duncan)
with apparent mystical powers. Audience test responses reportedly
have been through the roof. And that's with an unsettling scene
involving a botched electric chair execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``ANNA AND THE KING''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 17.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 53 years since Irene Dunne and Rex Harrison filmed the
story of a 19th-century governess in the Siamese court, based on
Margaret Landon's memoirs. It was followed by two musicals _ an
unforgettable one (1956) starring Oscar winner Yul Brynner and an
animated version (1999) best described as forgettable. Now, Jodie
Foster and Chow Yun-Fat take the lead roles in a showy production
with an estimated budget of $65 million. With a PG-13 rating,
expect a big family push.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE CIDER HOUSE RULES''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Purists may miss the hunks of plot that don't make it onscreen
in this streamlined version of the novel, adapted by author John
Irving himself. But director Lasse Hallstrom (``My Life as a Dog'')
delivers a well-crafted tale that visually makes the most of its
New England setting. The ubiquitous Tobey Maguire plays the orphan
Homer, who's taught by the orphanage's Dr. Larch (Michael Caine)
how to deliver babies, and also, illegally, perform abortions.
Charlize Theron plays the daughter of a fisherman, and the
instrument of Homer's sentimental (and sexual) education. The
movie's standout: Caine's tender, surprisingly modulated
performance. (Steve Murray)
</P>
<P>
   ``MAN ON THE MOON''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the only comedian more bizarre than Jim Carrey was Andy
Kaufman, who died in 1984 at age 35. Carrey and what seems like the
whole team from ``The People vs. Larry Flynt'' _ director Milos
Forman, co-star Courtney Love and screenwriters Scott Alexander and
Larry Karaszewski _ have made this cryptic movie bio. Among the
film's potential Oscar nominations: R.E.M.'s music. Many from the
cast of ``Taxi,'' the TV series in which Kaufman co-starred, play
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``ANY GIVEN SUNDAY''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Stone's pro football film about the fictitious Miami
Sharks has had many player cuts. Like Tom Arnold and Sean ``Puffy''
Combs. And David Duchovny and Ving Rhames (both for reported
scheduling conflicts). The cast is still a heady list: Al Pacino,
Dennis Quaid, Lauren Holly, Cameron Diaz, James Woods, Jamie Foxx,
Lawrence Taylor, LL Cool J, Mickey Rourke, Ann-Margret and Charlton
Heston. Among the touchstones:
</P>
<P>
   racism and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``MAGNOLIA''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Director Paul Thomas Anderson's follow-up to ``Boogie Nights''
has been a hush-hush project from the get-go. The film's Web site
details the story line in the same manner as the trailer: It just
doesn't give much away. Basically, it's a family and friends story
where relationships need mending. And, apparently, frogs fall from
the sky. The big ensemble cast (Julianne Moore, William H. Macy and
Jason Robards among them) includes Tom Cruise playing a sleazy
late-night infomercial sex-advice guy. Originally Cruise was cast
in a bit part, but it mushroomed to a reported 45
</P>
<P>
   minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``MANSFIELD PARK''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Jane Austen's novel, it's another love story among the
English upper class. Frances O'Conner portrays Fanny Price, a poor
relation sent to live with rich relatives in Northamptonshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``LIBERTY HEIGHTS''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Levinson's latest take on Baltimore involves a Jewish
family in the era of school desegregation and the birth of rock
music. Among those in the ensemble cast: Joseph Mantegna and Bebe
Neuwirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE TALENTED MR. RIPLEY''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Dec. 25.
</P>
<P>
   A touch of evil with all the right players. And filmed in Italy
to boot. Matt Damon (Oscar-winning screenwriter for ``Good Will
Hunting''), Gwyneth Paltrow (``Shakespeare in Love'' best actress
Oscar) and Anthony Minghella (``The English Patient'' best director
Oscar) star. Plus, there's Jude Law and Cate Blanchett. It's the
existential tale of a young, ambitious American (that would be
Damon) who schemes and kills his way into a privileged lifestyle.
Based on the book by Patricia Highsmith, who also wrote ``Strangers
on a Train.''
</P>
<P>
   ``FANTASIA 2000''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Jan. 1
</P>
<P>
   It's out with much of the old (but not, of course, Mickey
Mouse's ``The Sorcerer's Apprentice'') as Disney's 1940 classical
music masterpiece gets an overhaul with many new scenes. And it
plays on the big, big screen _ Imax. James Levine conducts the
Chicago Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``SNOW FALLING
</P>
<P>
   ON CEDARS''
</P>
<P>
   Opens Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Director Scott Hicks' anticipated follow-up to ``Shine'' stars
Ethan Hawke, Max von Sydow and Youki Kudo in a visually stunning if
emotionally underwhelming adaptation of the best-selling novel.
Hicks creates a fluid, moody mosaic that shifts back and forth in
time in its look at small-town racism toward Japanese-Americans in
the 1940s. (Steve Murray)
</P>
<P>
   ``TOPSY-TURVY''
</P>
<P>
   Opens in December in Los Angeles and New York; maybe in January
in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the holidays' most opulent film, ``Topsy-Turvy'' is, at
first, an intricate look at the oddball teaming of England's
Gilbert and Sullivan and how their relationship began to unravel.
Then, with great precision, it becomes a blow-by-blow accounting of
the staging of ``The Mikado.'' Theater purists will likely eat it
up. At times, director Mike Leigh (``Secrets &AMP; Lies,'' ``Naked''),
has created a movie as beautiful to look at as Ingmar Bergman's
``Fanny and Alexander.'' And just as long.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE END OF THE AFFAIR''
</P>
<P>
   Opens in Los Angeles and New York in December; likely in January
in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Fiennes plays a writer and Julianne Moore a married woman
who kindle passion in a remake of the barely tepid 1955 version
with Deborah Kerr and Van Johnson. It's based on Graham Greene's
novel and directed by Neil Jordan (``The Crying Game'').
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
