<HEADER>
A4456 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-MOORE-COLUMN19-CO     11-18 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MOORE-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Already, signs point to 4th Holyfield reign
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The loser continues to receive the accolades normally
reserved for the winner. That's because everybody at the Thomas &AMP;
Mack Center last Saturday night in Las Vegas saw Evander Holyfield
ease by Lennox Lewis for the undisputed heavyweight championship.
</P>
<P>
   Well, everybody, except the judges and those wearing blinders or
stuff featuring the Union Jack of Lewis' home of England.
</P>
<P>
   So Holyfield chatted with David Letterman on Thursday night.
Showtime threw a party for the guy in New York. With more
high-profile stops on the way for Holyfield, he will tell the world
sooner than later that he just isn't ready to stop throwing punches
for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he'll tell us now.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not yet,'' Holyfield said Thursday, chuckling from his
hotel room in Manhattan. ``I'll wait until the end of the year
before I decide whether or not to retire. The more I think about
it, I want to fight, of course. But that's ego. That's getting
caught up in emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Translated: Holyfield is coming back. They always come back in a
sport that is among the leaders in guys hooked on adrenaline. Not
only that, Holyfield is 37 only on his birth certificate. He was so
energetic after his 12 rounds with Lewis that he spent the early
morning dancing before catching a flight back to Atlanta. Holyfield
said, ``I keep proving that age ain't nothing but a number.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Holyfield will return, because he is so close to
becoming greater than Muhammad Ali. They are the only three-time
champions among heavyweights, but Holyfield is an easy scenario
away from snatching a fourth title and doing even more to advance
his legend.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is required to fight Henry Akinwande within the next 90
days or lose the World Boxing Association portion of his
three-headed crown, which includes the International Boxing
Federation and the World Boxing Council. The thing is, Lewis and
his handlers say they won't deal with Akinwande. They still fume
over a 1997 fight that ended in the fifth round after Akinwande was
disqualified for hugging Lewis most of the night.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've forgotten, Holyfield's bout with Akinwande was
canceled last year because of Akinwande's health problems. If
Lewis' camp continues its stance against Akinwande, look for
Holyfield and Akinwande to battle early next year for that vacant
WBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Take Holyfield against Akinwande, and then consider the rest of
our scenario: Boxing is about styles. ``If Lewis wants Mike Tyson,
like he says he does, he's going to put Mike Tyson back on the
map,'' Holyfield said. ``Tyson likes fighters like Lewis who keep
moving backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Lewis' heart remains a mystery. If Tyson becomes his
snarling self again by pounding a couple of patsies before facing
Lewis by the end of next year, then Tyson definitely is destined to
grab Lewis' championship belts in the aftermath. That would leave
Tyson as king of the IBF and WBC, with Holyfield on the throne of
the WBA.
</P>
<P>
   That also would push boxing toward one of its biggest moments
ever with Tyson-Holyfield III, and Holyfield's style would baffle
Tyson a third time. You know, if Holyfield doesn't retire.
</P>
<P>
   And he won't.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
