<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4457 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MAHER19-COX     11-18 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAHER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta to feel the punch of Maher's cynicism
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In an era known for its sweeping cynicism, Bill Maher
is here to tell us that we've still got a ways to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say we're too cynical, but I say we're stupid, we're
not smart enough,'' says the comic, political commentator and host
of ABC's ``Politically Incorrect.'' That's why he's titling his
next HBO special, which tapes soon for airing next year, ``Be More
Cynical.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred Atlantans will get a taste of Maher's latest jabs
tonight at the Punch Line (both shows are sold out), and a few more
will get a chance to joust with him Saturday when he holds
auditions for ``citizen panelists'' for his talk show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect'' (12:05 a.m. on ABC) is Maher's round
table of celebrities, politicians and professional talkers,
matching the likes of, say, Internet gossip Matt Drudge, singer
Debbie Gibson, the Rev. Jerry Falwell and comedian Jon Stewart for
a half-hour of duking it out. The ``citizen panelists'' are viewers
chosen for their outspokenness who sit in on one show.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are so thoroughly vetted by the audition
process,'' says Maher, ``that you almost never get somebody who's
bad at the skill of arguing on a talk show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike our regular panel,'' he cracks.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 auditioners will be whittled down to a few finalists at
WSB's headquarters Saturday; the 50 have already been selected
after sending in postcards to ``PI.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta weed out the crazies,'' Maher says of the
auditioning process during a telephone interview. ``We had a lady
on, we think she didn't take her Prozac that day. She came on in
pyjamas and a boa and sat next to Joe Piscopo, who doesn't need
these problems at this point in his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Maher's new stand-up routine, which he says is fully formed but
still being tweaked, is as up-to-date as the bizarre death of
golfer Payne Stewart (he obsesses over why President Clinton had to
be informed of the progress of Stewart's doomed flight), and as
dated as the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal, which he swears is not last
year's news.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just like the monologues last year, with Monica
(oral sex) jokes. This is more about the culture war that went on.
People kept saying, why can't we get this behind us and get on with
the business of the country? My contention is this was the business
of the country. What was the greater sin: a middle-aged man
cheating on his wife, or was the greater sin to democracy letting
Mary Bono vote on that?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
