<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4458 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIE-SMITH19-COX     11-18 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SMITH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An undogmatic director tackles a very touchy issue
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Some people think that if you believe in religion, you're
stupid,'' says writer-director Kevin Smith. He describes his
Catholic-tenet fantasy ``Dogma'' as a defense and celebration of
faith _ one that includes a giant poop monster, homicidal angels
and the sort of raunchy, sexually explicit chatter that blistered
his films ``Clerks,'' ``Mallrats'' and ``Chasing Amy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pre-emptive strike, its original distributor, Miramax, sold
the movie to Lions Gate to keep the heat off Miramax's parent
company, Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Raised a Catholic in New Jersey and still attending Mass
regularly, Smith, 29, seems surprised by the controversy that
``Dogma'' sparked long before it ever reached screens. It was
denounced, sight unseen, by the Catholic League, based on a reading
of an early version of the script that appeared on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the things that they objected to never made it to the
shooting draft, let alone the finished film,'' Smith says.
``Three-quarters of the things they had hard-core objections to
aren't even in the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Those bits were scrapped strictly to keep the film's running
time down, he says, not because he was censoring himself. Among the
more wounding accusations made against Smith was that he is a
``self-hating'' churchgoer, trying to bash his own religious faith.
``I'm a practicing (expletive) Catholic,'' he says, exasperated.
``Why would I make a movie that bashes myself?''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker talked about ``Dogma'' during a recent stop in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard you say that you wrote this film as a response to
your own struggles with faith. Is that right?
</P>
<P>
   A: Once you become a certain age, it gets harder and harder to
hold on to your faith, because the world throws so much at you.
Also, you start to learn a lot more. And with education comes the
danger of replacing God with science or knowledge or something like
that. Some people fall out of faith just because they don't like
their priest. Some people come to the conclusion there is no God,
it's all hokey nonsense we believed as kids. But I was one of those
people that really wanted to stay with it, because it was so much a
part of who I was when I was younger. But there are times in life
when it is hard to reconcile your faith with the world around you.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in church sometimes doesn't make it any easier, when you
hear a priest rail on again about abortion or the gay community or
something as stupid as ``Don't park in my spot out in the lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: But the movie is ultimately an endorsement of belief.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, I wanted to do something to celebrate the faith, and
also make it kind of cool to be a Christian or a Catholic or just
think about God without being looked at as hokey or boring or
stupid. I wanted to take a vested interest in some form of theology
without seeming like I believe in the Tooth Fairy as well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's really pretty rare for anyone to address religion at all
in movies.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Song of Bernadette'' is a lovely little movie, but it
doesn't play now. We don't live in such an innocent time anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And religion often seems to be so compartmentalized in
mainstream society, something that's kept separate from people's
day-to-day routine.
</P>
<P>
   A: I think that's how the mainstream looks at it. But for the
hard-core people, they live it and breathe it every moment of their
day. I think I fall somewhere between the two. It's not something I
treat like a Sunday-only kind of behavior. But it's also not
something that, every moment of the day, I'm trying to think about
how I'm probably disappointing God or how I could be a better
Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did you think about ``Stigmata?''
</P>
<P>
   A: First, I thought it was overdirected. Second, I'm sitting
watching that movie, and I think, ``I'm the bad guy?'' We made a
movie with a rubber poop monster in it. This guy makes a movie
about a huge Vatican conspiracy to hide a hidden Gospel in which
Christ supposedly speaks about how he doesn't want a church. It's
such a conspiracy that a cardinal will try to kill a woman to keep
it secret. I sat there and thought, ``Why am I on trial here?'' . .
. That movie went on to open for 18 million bucks, and there was no
press conference or an ad in The New York Times. The Catholic
League wasn't going after it. That solidified the suspicion I've
had all along that it was never about me or the movie; it was about
Disney. The Catholic League loves to go after Disney. They've done
it before; believe me, they'll do it again in the future. Going
after Disney gets you covered in the papers or on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So have you had to deal with pickets protesting your movie?
</P>
<P>
   A: We had them outside Lincoln Center for the screening at the
New York Film Festival. I don't really fault any of them, because
they believe the movie they're picketing is this horrible movie
that attacks their faith and mocks them. That's not the movie at
all.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a lot of harsh language in this movie, and by virtue
of that, most of the church people aren't gonna like it anyway.
They didn't like our other three flicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogma''
</P>
<P>
   Grade C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Affleck, Matt Damon and Linda Fiorentino. Written
and directed by Kevin Smith. Rated R for profanity, sex-related
dialogue, violence and drug content. 2 hours,
</P>
<P>
   5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mini-review: While the film pulls no punches in roasting
organized religion, it does so with such minimal spunk and spare
inventiveness that you have to wonder what all the fuss by
Catholics has been about. (Bob Longino)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
