<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4459 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PANDAS19-COX     11-18 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANDAS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unfazed by media to-do at zoo, two bear cubs hang out happily
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lun Lun and Yang Yang were exposed to their first big
Atlanta crowd Thursday, and from all appearances, they weren't
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   As dozens of media types oohed and aahed during a Zoo Atlanta
press tour, the giant panda cubs slept soundly, without flinching
or even bothering to take a glimpse at the scribbling reporters or
furiously clicking photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Yang, the male, curled in a cubbyhole chiseled out of a
gray rock wall. Lun Lun, the female, snoozed nearby atop a wooden
climbing structure.
</P>
<P>
   But if the cubs weren't excited, Zoo Atlanta officials were. And
so were a handful of dignitaries, including Wo Zurong,
Houston-based consul general of the People's Republic of China, and
Dr. Kurt Benirschke, president of the San Diego Zoological Society.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo Atlanta Director Terry Maple, speaking to reporters in
advance of the exhibit's public opening Saturday, declared that the
bears were ``doing great,'' acclimating to their new home ``much
faster than anybody expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other giant panda pair in the United States is at San
Diego. There, Bar Yun, the female, and Shi Shi, the male, don't
appear to like each other much, Benirschke said. Bar Yun required
artificial insemination to produce a baby, now 3 months old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The male is just not interested,'' Benirschke said. The last
time Bar Yun made a pass at Shi Shi, he slapped her in the snout.
</P>
<P>
   But Maple said he doesn't think Lun Lun and Yang Yang will have
that problem. Since their arrival Nov. 5, they've played together a
lot and seem to enjoy each other's company, which means the rare
animals might be more likely to naturally mate _ which is a goal of
the zoo's panda project.
</P>
<P>
   Maple predicted record attendance Saturday _ between 10,000 and
15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo-goers will be issued a stub at the gate, reserving a time
for a five-minute tour of the panda habitat. The stubs are
first-come, first-served and are not expected to last all day.
</P>
<P>
   Mammal curator Rich Sartor said visitors will be urged to stay
calm when viewing the pandas. The inside viewing areas are
soundproof, but he won't abide anyone pounding on the thick glass
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Though the bears appeared oblivious to the throng of reporters
Thursday, Sartor's worried that too much noise might upset the
emotionally sensitive animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should keep in mind, `You're visiting someone's home.'
Enjoy them, but be respectful. We don't want to cause them
stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials cautioned that the small parking lots near the zoo
in Grant Park might not be adequate for the crowd. A special
shuttle will run continuously to the zoo from Turner Field's gold
lot, where parking will be free, from 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. Saturday and
Sunday. Also, MARTA buses will run from the West End station every
20 minutes instead of the normal 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Police have a plan for the expected flood of traffic, but
zoo-goers should expect jams, said zoo marketing director Gail
Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo's gates will be open from 9:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.,
regular hours. Zoo members can enter a half-hour sooner, at 9 a.m.
Admission is $12 adults; $10 senior citizens; $8 ages 3-11; free
ages 2 and under. More information: www.zooatlanta.org or
404-624-5600.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect a lot of people to come early,'' she warned. ``There
will be long lines before the zoo opens.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
