<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4460 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-JAMAICATOUR21-     11-18 1833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-JAMAICATOUR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Activities, amenities reeled us in
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 21.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORACABESSA, Jamaica _ You may have seen the families and couples
swaggering through the Atlanta airport. Sunburned. Sandaled. Hair
in tiny braids with clattering beads. Toting boxes of duty-free rum
and sporting brand-new ``We Be Jammin''' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been to Jamaica, mon,'' is the message their carefree
stride and I-know-something-you-don't-know expression suggests. Too
cool for words.
</P>
<P>
   We had seen them, too. And we wanted to go. But feeling a little
long in the tooth _ and wide in the midsection _ for the wanton
world of, say, Hedonism, we opted instead for the
family-togetherness vibe of Boscobel Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The SuperClubs-owned, 207-room resort claims good credentials.
It's included in ``100 Best All-Inclusive Resorts of the World''
(Globe Pequot, $16.95) and ``Best Places to Stay _ Caribbean''
(Houghton Mifflin, $18). Family Travel Forum, an online publication
(www.familytravelforum.com), named it the Best Beach Resort in its
Top Getaways for Families listing.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the guarantees. We were pleased to discover that
the resort has a No Hurricane Guarantee, which means that if a
hurricane strikes, you will be reimbursed for the disrupted night
and given a voucher for the same number of nights to be used during
a future stay. And the Jamaica Sunshine Guarantee provides that on
any day the sun does not make at least a brief appearance, you get
a voucher equal to the value of another day's stay.
</P>
<P>
   Sounded like a winner _ but you really never know until you
experience a place.
</P>
<P>
   So here we are, months later, in this tropical garden spot where
the virgin strawberry daiquiris flow (along with headier
concoctions), a big fuzzy brown bear mascot in swim trunks strolls
the sands, and the buffet boasts everything from macaroni and
cheese to curry goat.
</P>
<P>
   While the kids paint T-shirts, scramble off on a treasure hunt
or play arcade games, we adults settle under beach umbrellas with a
good book or relax beside the adult pool with a frosty beverage.
Although the children's program is always an option, family
activities such as pool olympics or sandcastle-building contests
are scheduled throughout the day. Every evening, there's Family
Showtime, with entertainment that ranges from steel band music to
an islands-flavored floor show.
</P>
<P>
   And most of us are happily snoozing in our beds before the
stroke of midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, this used to be one of Hugh Hefner's Playboy
resorts back in the swinging '60s before it reopened as a family
resort in 1987. The only bunnies here now are the ones in the
hutches at the petting zoo.
</P>
<P>
   We weren't the only ones caught up in the laid-back allure of
this tropical playground.
</P>
<P>
   Like our family, the Haushers from Appleton, Wis., visited in
early fall and ``absolutely loved it,'' says mom Jennifer Hausher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls (Elizabeth, 8, and Emily, 6) really had fun making
new friends, getting their hair braided, having strawberry
daiquiris whenever they wanted, and hanging out at the pool to
their hearts' content. In their words, this place is `better than
Disneyland.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Gould, a British Airways flight attendant from Newcastle,
England, found ``a lot for the kids to do,'' too, including ski
lessons and rides on a boat-towed, giant banana float.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been to Jolly Harbor in Antigua, and the quality of
the food is much better here and they have premium (liquor)
brands,'' adds Gould, vacationing with her husband, Peter, and
children, Becky, 13, and James, 12.
</P>
<P>
   I watched the Greenaway family from Petawawa, Ontario, take a
spin on the banana and caught up with the mom and dad _ Irene and
Drew _ at the adult pool bar later in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Irene and Shelby, 7, and Tal, 10, were
rendezvousing with Drew, a Canadian Forces captain running training
sessions at Camp Newcastle in the Blue Mountains, home to the
Jamaica Defence Force. ``From talking to all the locals and
officers who came before me,'' Drew says, ``Boscobel Beach is best
for families.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the most part, he agrees. But he finds the shabby life
preservers at the water sports shed in need of replacing. (He's
right.) And he isn't comfortable with the access afforded the
surfboard entrepreneurs who paddle up to (and sometimes inside) the
roped-off beach area to hawk carvings, trinkets and conch shells.
</P>
<P>
   These guys do add local color. I make the acquaintance of Smoky
Joe, a one-man tourism board who sells ratty-looking conch shells
and rattles off his services. ``I can take you snorkeling or
fishing _ what you want to do. I show you my country, and you tell
me about your country.''
</P>
<P>
   I decline the side trips, but agree to buy a shell for $12 _ he
originally asks $20 _ after he scrapes off sediment and deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why you want me to take all the nature off,'' he
chides me. ``You want it to be pretty. But this is nature!''
</P>
<P>
   Other vacationers wade out to cut deals with Smoky Joe's
competitors. There's Spice Man and George, who carve animals from
local wood, and Mike, whose conch shells have all the ``nature''
scraped off and shine pearly pink.
</P>
<P>
   Later that afternoon, there is trouble in paradise. During a
beach volleyball game, my husband and daughter witness an offshore
altercation provoked by a local who apparently has a score to
settle with George.
</P>
<P>
   Security officers _ who are stationed throughout the resort and
provide a certain peace of mind _ get medical attention for George,
who reportedly was stabbed. The offender flees.
</P>
<P>
   Management assures me this is an isolated incident. No guests
are harmed, and technically speaking it took place off property _
as resorts don't ``own'' water rights.
</P>
<P>
   So much for local color. It makes me think that Drew Greenaway
is probably right.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn and Ken Snider _ American-born pastors of New
Celebration Church in Mandeville, Jamaica, for the past 14 years _
actually chose Boscobel for a family getaway because of the tight
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``In August we were staying in St. Mary's (parish), and we were
robbed,'' says Kathryn. ``In Jamaica you have to b aware.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she concludes that ``Jamaica is a great place for any
family to visit. It's close enough you can get here in a day, and
it's really a different culture.''
</P>
<P>
   We agreed, which is why we thought the T-shirt our daughter
selected at the Montego Bay airport was just perfect. It read:
``One Problem _ Leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   PACKAGES, INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   When you sign up for an Air Jamaica package, you'll be booked
aboard Air Jamaica on a flight leaving at 7 a.m., meaning you could
be on the beach by noon. Air Jamaica's ``Sale of the Century''
winter deals for travel between Dec. 17 and Feb. 17 begin at $659
for two nights and $1,499 for six nights. Air-only is $291 round
trip from Atlanta to Montego Bay through Feb. 17. Call Air Jamaica
at 1-800-568-3247, check the Web at www.airjamaica.com or contact a
travel agent. To reach SuperClubs, call 1-800-467-8737 or visit the
Web site at www.superclubs.com.
</P>
<P>
   For information on family vacations in Jamaica, call the
Jamaican Tourist Board in Miami at 305-665-0557 or visit the
colorful, well-organized Web site jamaicatravel.com
</P>
<P>
   UPCOMING EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Air Jamaica Jazz and Blues Festival: The fourth annual music
fest, to be held at James Bond Beach in Oracabessa and the Jamaica
Grande Hotel in Ocho Rios Jan. 20-23, will feature Kenny G, Al
Jarreau, Mary J. Blige, Dr. John, Gladys Knight, Kool &AMP; the Gang
and Grover Washington Jr. The event will include a Caribbean Street
Fete featuring music and dancing on James Avenue in Ocho Rios and a
Sunday morning gospel-style Jazz Brunch by the Sea. Special
four-night festival ticket packages are $160 and $185. Call Air
Jamaica at 1-800-568-3247 for information on flights and
accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bob Marley All-Star Tribute: TNT's ``One Love: Bob Marley All
Star Tribute'' concert will be taped at Oracabessa Bay on Dec. 4.
Scheduled artists include Rita and Ziggy Marley and the Melody
Makers, Erykah Badu, Sheryl Crow, Lauryn Hill, Queen Latifah, Sarah
McLachlan, Busta Rhymes, Jimmy Cliff and Seal. Air Jamaica is
offering packages starting at $429 ($569 all-inclusive) per person
double occupancy for three nights beginning Dec. 3.1-800-568-3247.
</P>
<P>
   BEST OF BOSCOBEL
</P>
<P>
   Here are four reasons why we'd come back to Boscobel Beach
resort:
</P>
<P>
   1. The staff is fabulous: I've never encountered such a smiling
bunch so eager to please. Observes Jennifer Hausher of Appleton,
Wis.: ``The folks at Boscobel seem to work very hard to make sure
everyone's stay was very pleasant and were always asking if they
could help us, if they could get something for us. The housekeeping
staff worked very hard every day making sure our room was clean, as
well as the hallways.''
</P>
<P>
   2. The entertainment crew is tireless: ``We couldn't believe how
hard the entertainment crew worked,'' Hausher adds. Whether hosting
a water polo and reggae party at the family pool before lunch or a
festive Jamaican stage show with conga-line dancing at the Terrace
after dinner, Bashful Brian, Awesome Audene, Ravishing Rachel, D.J.
Tony and Powerful Patrick keep moving like Energizer bunnies with
fresh batteries. They will not allow anybody to have a bad time.
</P>
<P>
   3. The children's programs are way cool: The four children's
clubhouses include Tiny Town for little ones 4 and under, Bears'
Bungalow for ages 4-7, Boscobel Bunch for ages 8-12 and Jump Up
Club for ages 13-17. Activities planned from 9 a.m. until 10 p.m.
might include arts and crafts, bicycle rides, beach games, a
glass-bottom boat trip, snorkeling, tennis, movies and theme
parties _ depending on the age group. Kids can eat together at the
Barbecue Park or the Terraces, where a special kids area offers
fare such as macaroni and cheese, hot dogs, burgers and fries.
Also, there's a petting zoo where children are introduced to goats,
pigs, ducks and rabbits.
</P>
<P>
   4. The adults-only areas provide welcome respite from the small
set: OK, we love our kids, but it's nice having time to ourselves.
We can escape to the adult pool and bar while our offspring are
being taken good care of. And we find blessed air conditioning at
the piano bar and the Italian-style restaurant Allegro. Many of the
resort's public areas are open to the breezes _ even the Pavilion
restaurant, which is the resort's only other table-service
restaurant. (The Terraces features buffets at breakfast, lunch and
dinner, and the Beach Grill is a short-order walk-up.) The disco,
the Escape Hatch, seems to be geared to a younger adult crowd _ it
doesn't get cooking until 10 p.m., and we were all played out by
then.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constiution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
