<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4462 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-JAMAICA21-COX     11-18 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-JAMAICA21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life at an all-inclusive jamaican resort presents `no problem'
when the gang's all here
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 21.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORACABESSA, Jamaica
</P>
<P>
   o way am I going to rip through the blue Caribbean hanging on
for dear life astride a big inflated yellow banana.
</P>
<P>
   Ensconced in a chaise lounge on the sands of Boscobel Beach, I
watch for two days with guarded curiosity as the whimsical craft
peels offshore again and again, towed behind a ski boat that churns
through the surf with an insouciant vro-o-o-om.
</P>
<P>
   It looks reckless _ yet, um, sorta fun. But the sign at the
resort's water sports area clearly warns: The banana boat is likely
to tip over. That's enough for me. There could be sharks out there.
I'm no fool.
</P>
<P>
   But the fearless keep queuing up. All ages. All sizes. And so at
last I find myself straddling the floating fruit with my
11-year-old daughter and Christopher Lindo of Kingston, also 11, in
front of me. I can't believe I'm doing this. I'm too old for such
nonsense. Oops, too late to bail. The boat lurches and Christopher
cries, ``Ohhhhh, we're all going to di-i-i-i-eeeeeee!''
</P>
<P>
   But we don't. We don't even fall off. We r-- de this bucking
banana like a bunch of Caribbean cowpokes. We holler, laugh and
wave to sunbathers on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   I tame the wild banana, and, as they say here: Everyting's cook
and curry.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the sort of family-fun-in-the-sun we'd come to
Jamaica for. Another round of those yummy (alcohol-free) frozen
strawberry daiquiris, please _ and a Red Stripe on draft for dad.
</P>
<P>
   Boscobel Beach, a lushly landscaped resort on a private bay 10
miles east of Ocho Rios, is one of SuperClubs' all-inclusive
properties, including the adults-only Grand Lido, Hedonism (I, II
and, since September, III) and Breezes. It's the only one that
permits children under 16.
</P>
<P>
   Boscobel isn't just kid-friendly _ it's kid-indulgent with
almost nonstop activities for tots to teens, supervised by
counselors who seem devoted to showing kids a terrific time.
</P>
<P>
   While Boscobel boasts adults-only areas (a private pool and bar
and the Italian restaurant Allegro), the resort is obviously
designed with families in mind _ no nude beaches, no drunken
revelries, no all-night debauchery (only at the rather laid-back
piano bar are drinks served as late as 2 a.m.). The Sunday night
beach party is about as wild as it gets. Moms, dads and kids vie
for prizes in heated three-legged races and egg-in-spoon relays in
the sugary sand, running to a reggae beat. Kids score Boscobel logo
merchandise; adult winners get bottles of Appleton rum.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the de rigueur hair braiding _ which can run as much
as $60 for a full head of cornrows and plaits if you aren't savvy
at bargaining _ and perhaps a splurge at the gift shop, crafts
market or massage salon, you won't need to worry about spending
money.
</P>
<P>
   All-inclusive means just that: Your up-front payment covers
accommodations, all meals, snacks, beverages (alcoholic, too),
entertainment, water sports (sailing, skiing, windsurfing,
snorkeling and scuba diving) and a children's program that keeps
kids busy from 9 a.m. until 10 p.m. Gratuities are included.
</P>
<P>
   Early this fall, our family of three paid $1,762 for a
three-night Air Jamaica Vacations package that included round-trip
airfare from Atlanta to Montego Bay and airport transfers. Children
under 14 visit the resort for free; we paid only $174 for our
daughter's airfare. We traveled in the low season; prices rise
during the winter months, but deals always seem to be available.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of going the all-inclusive route _ especially on a
short vacation _ is that you see little of the country outside the
resort. We were tempted to at least sign up for a tour to Dunn's
River Falls and some shopping in nearby Ocho Rios. But with only
two full days and two half days at Boscobel, we felt we needed the
time to fully explore the possibilities under our noses.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, our van driver on the two-hour jaunt from Sangster
International Airport in Montego Bay to Boscobel provided a running
commentary in lilting patois. And the view from the van windows
provided a vivid, if fleeting, slice of day-to-day Jamaica life.
</P>
<P>
   As we sped down a narrow highway along the northern coast,
chickens flapped to get out of the way, little girls in green
jumpers ambled home from school and tethered goats grazed lazily
just yards from the highway. While some roadside entrepreneurs
hawked their wares from open-air huts, others stood precariously
close to the asphalt with strings of fresh-caught fish or bravely
thrust out hands full of guineps, which resemble large scuppernongs
but are in the lychee nut family.
</P>
<P>
   Our driver pulled off the road at a rest stop where we bought
spicy meat-filled patties, jerk chicken and Red Stripes. We caught
glimpses of sights such as the 1796 Anglican church in Falmouth and
the place where Columbus landed in 1494. And along the way we
picked up some Jamaica-speak: Call Ocho Rios ``Ochi,'' Montego Bay
``Mo'Bay'' and casually toss out those all-purpose replies ``No
problem'' and ``Yah, mon.''
</P>
<P>
   We arrived at the gates of Boscobel shortly after 1 p.m. An
eager young man whisked away our bags and showed us to our junior
suite with an incredible view of the jewel-like water that changes
from blue zircon near the beach to deep sapphire further out at
sea.
</P>
<P>
   Would we be needing anything else, the smiling bellhop inquired.
Well, perhaps he could ...
</P>
<P>
   But before we could finish our request, we heard the two words
that would become our mantra in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
