<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4465 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-UCLA-LADN     11-18 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FANTASY BOWL, USC TAILBACKS TOUGH TO BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marcus Allen. Mike Garrett. Anthony Davis. Ricky
Bell. Jon Arnett. Morley Drury. Cotton Warburton.
</P>
<P>
   Football fans from the 1920s to the 1980s recognize these
household names as among the greatest backs in USC history, or in
some cases, in the history of college football.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know how strong an all-time USC team's backfield
might be, consider that this would be our bench in Part II of the
Daily News' mythical matchup between USC's and UCLA's greatest
players.
</P>
<P>
   We wouldn't hesitate to use any of those players against an
all-time UCLA defense, but first the Bruins would get to look at
Heisman Trophy winners O.J. Simpson and Charles White.
</P>
<P>
   It would be fascinating to ponder how a game like this might
unfold. Would the Trojans try to play power football, hoping they
could manhandle UCLA defensive linemen Cliff Frazier, Fred McNeill
and Jack Ellena?
</P>
<P>
   Would an offensive line featuring Outland Trophy winner Ron
Yary, Lombardi Trophy winner Brad Budde, NFL Hall of Famers Ron Mix
and Anthony Munoz and All-American Tony Boselli even care who
played on the defensive line?
</P>
<P>
   How big a hole would Simpson have on student body right?
</P>
<P>
   It might be a classic battle of strength against speed. UCLA
linebackers Jerry Robinson and Carnell Lake would certainly be
swift enough to cause headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Are you worried about USC having a playmaker? Simpson's 64-yard
touchdown run against UCLA in 1967 is perhaps the most-recalled
play in the 68-year history of the rivalry, and gave the Trojans a
dramatic 21-20 victory en route to the national championship. And
the only above-mentioned lineman he had on that team was Yary.
</P>
<P>
   White went 4-0 against the Bruins from 1976-79, so let's assume
he'd be able to make a few plays too.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Pat Haden was 3-0 in the crosstown rivalry, with the
closest margin of victory 10 points. And who was better in a clutch
situation? Remember his two-point conversion to Shelton Diggs in
the 1975 Rose Bowl that gave the Trojans an 18-17 victory over Ohio
State?
</P>
<P>
   Simpson and White would certainly never get tired, with two
Heisman winners (Allen, Garrett) itching to play on the sidelines
along with the other top backs mentioned above. There are still
fans from the 1950s who believe Arnett's runs were the most
exciting in Trojans history while Drury was USC's first 1,000-yard
runner in 1927, a feat that wasn't repeated until Garrett did it 38
years later.
</P>
<P>
   But this USC team can do a lot more than run. Haden threw 26
touchdown passes in his two years as a starter, and he would only
have Keyshawn Johnson and Lynn Swann as his wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   A better question might be who would cover tight end Charles
Young, an All-American who led the 1972 national championship team
in receptions before enjoying a 13-year career in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Young was as good a tight end as there was in college
football,'' said former USC coach John McKay, who coached Young and
Swann together in 1971 and '72. ``Swann, our flanker, and Young
could catch anything. I wasn't worried.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as the running game would dominate this matchup, a more
interesting dilemma would be how Keyshawn Johnson and Swann would
be covered by cornerbacks Carlton Gray and Jim Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Johnnie Morton would come in as a third receiver, to
recreate his last-minute touchdown reception in the Trojans' 45-42
victory over UCLA in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: This game would feature top-notch talent on both
sides of the ball. Something no one is saying about this Saturday's
game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
