<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4466 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-SAFETY-HNS &LR;      11-18 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY WOVEN INTO TEXAS A&AMP;M BONFIRE TRADITION, FORMER STUDENTS SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Safety is as much an ingredient of the Texas A&AMP;M bonfire as the
thousands of logs that fuel it, former students said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And it is as woven into the tradition as ``red pots'' and crew
chiefs and University of Texas outhouses.
</P>
<P>
   There are strict rules about how the bonfire is constructed,
about who does what jobs and about the safety equipment used for
tree-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Work crews are overseen by a hierarchy of supervisors and
managers. There are limits on how high and how wide it can be
built. Training classes are conducted covering each phase of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the way it works is you have overkill when it comes
to safety,'' said James Fuqua, a ranch worker in the North Texas
city of Quanah and a former ``red pot,'' or senior bonfire
supervisor, in the early 1980s. ``Our main job as red pots was to
be the safety guys and make sure that no one got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   At least nine students were killed and nearly 30 others injured
early Thursday when a 40-foot-high stack of logs collapsed on the
College Station campus.
</P>
<P>
   Fuqua said that the ultimate authorities on the bonfire site are
the senior red pots, so named because of the red hard hats they
wear. Under them are junior red pots, picked by the seniors as
apprentices in the art of bonfire building.
</P>
<P>
   Below them in the hierarchy are ``brown pots,'' who are
responsible for the equipment, ``yellow pots,'' who are leaders
from the dormitories, and crew chiefs, who supervise each work
crew.
</P>
<P>
   The student body makes up the bulk of the work crews and are
assigned tasks according to experience level and seniority at the
school.
</P>
<P>
   The most inexperienced crews on the site, usually freshmen, are
fitted with white tape on their ankles to signify ``that they need
to be watched out for,'' said Fuqua, and that they are not
permitted on the stack.
</P>
<P>
   Fuqua said only red pots are allowed to work on the three top
stacks of the bonfire, anywhere from 30 to 50 feet above the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets pretty dang touchy up there sometimes,'' Fuqua said.
</P>
<P>
   The most important part of the bonfire is the center pole
constructed of two long telephone poles spliced together end to
end. This pole is posted in the ground to a depth of about 15 feet
and held in place with four guy wires.
</P>
<P>
   Logs are then placed in concentric circles, from smallest to
largest, around the center pole until the diameter of the bonfire
is about 45 feet. The logs are tied together with three pieces of
wire each.
</P>
<P>
   The next layer of logs is then similarly arranged on top of the
first and so on, until the entire structure is about 55 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Wolfskill, a commodities broker in New York who was a red
pot in 1974-75, said that safety has always been the prime concern
of any crews building the bonfire. Because it is a student-run
event, he said, safety has to be a priority, or the university
administration would intervene.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped the university wouldn't end the tradition,
although university officials weren't discussing that Thursday.
Instead they kept focus on rescuing the injured and recovering
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, the only deaths associated with bonfire
construction were recorded in 1955, when a student was hit by a
swerving car, and in 1981 when someone was crushed by a tractor
hauling wood.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1935, when students dismantled an irate farmer's barn for
use in the fire, &UR;  &LR; the annual bonfire was an ad hoc affair, not
sanctioned by the university. The first all-log fire was burned in
1943 and the first fire using a center pole occurred in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, the bonfire reached its record height of 109 feet 10
inches, but because of concerns about violating a College Station
safety ordinance, the university limited it to height of the
structure to 55 feet in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonfire has evolved over time,'' Fuqua said. ``In the
beginning they were little more than trash fires, but over the
years it developed into a highly organized, tightly controlled
event in which relatively few people have been hurt. Of course,
there are injuries, people cutting themselves and falling, but most
of the time the reason has been stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad deal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
