<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-WEB-EXECS-ROUNDTABLE-     11-18 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-EXECS-ROUNDTABLE-ART-5TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE PIONEERS: THE BUZZ NEVER STOPS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of bios
and company descriptions is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: Questions may be italicized) 
(af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Speed. Sleep. Greed. Recruiting. Role models like
Thomas Edison and Ayn Rand. Losing money, yet turning away capital.
New-found wealth and an ensuing change in lifestyle _ or not.
</P>
<P>
   Those were some of the topics on the table when four chief
executives from dot.com companies _ Candice Carpenter of iVillage,
a women's Web site; Fernando J. Espuelas of StarMedia Network, a
Spanish- and Portuguese-language service; Kevin O'Connor of
DoubleClick, an online advertising network, and Stephan J. Paternot
of Theglobe.com, a shopping, news and business information site _
gathered late one afternoon early this month at The New York Times
for a wide-ranging discussion about managing in the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   These pioneers from Silicon Alley, an area in the Flatiron
district of Manhattan that is populated by many fledgling Internet
companies, were joined in the two-hour discussion by Saul Hansell,
Patrick J. Lyons and Judith H. Dobrzynski of The Times.
</P>
<P>
   As founders of young companies, each executive had experienced
the adrenaline highs and the growing pains that accompany the
transformation of an idea into a business and then into a publicly
traded company. They don't worry about nonexistent earnings in a
topsy-turvy environment where not producing a profit is, for the
moment, a virtue. For them, the bigger pressure is to build
organizations _ fast _ before opportunities slip away.
</P>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from the conversation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the difference between running the kind of company you
run and running a big company? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER Speed. Leading in conditions in which speed is a very
big factor. It puts a lot of additional pressure on all the
systems. And you have a lot of very young people, and you're
teaching them to be managers at a very accelerated pace without a
lot of formal programs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT Tying into that is just the idea of keeping your
entrepreneurial spirit. Things are shifting fast enough that you
need to be able to jump into any new idea, shift your company into
it and move at light speed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS I would say the absence of a road map. Not that any
business is particularly easy, but when there's nothing that you
can follow except your instincts and the little bit of data you're
able to gather in this context of a lot of speed, I think there's a
lot of intuition that goes into these kinds of very fast-moving
environments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR In large corporations, you need to spend a lot of time
quantifying what the market's going to look like and how you're
going to go about it and what the expenses are going to be.
</P>
<P>
   And here it's very much speed, it's intuition, it's trying to
figure out, ``Is this a big market or a small market?'' If it's a
big market, you go after it. You spend a tremendous amount of money
and you go after it quickly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the first thing that's sacrificed in the name of
speed? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR Facts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER Sleep. We're trying to really come up with graded
solutions to burnout caused by exhaustion. We have people who have
been at this for four years in our company and we have to figure
out a way to get them to learn how to completely refresh themselves
in short increments of time.
</P>
<P>
   I've stood at the elevator with people going on vacation and
actually taken the laptop and the cell phone out of their hands and
said, ``Great, now you can actually have a vacation.'' The only way
to truly regenerate yourself enough to be truly creative and
inventive again is to be unwired at times in the year and to be in
the other part of the world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do any of you have programs for dealing with burnout? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT Sometimes it's frequent rotation of some of your stars.
You'll often find that in your company you have a few stars, and if
you leave them in the same position too long they'll burn out. And,
quite frankly, you don't want to lose them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER
</P>
<P>
   We're starting a sabbatical program. It's for people who've been
there three years who would love to be there 20. We're giving them
a month to go and just do whatever they want. Sleep probably will
be at the top of most people's list. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS Are you going to take it yourself? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER Yeah, I am. I have to, otherwise no one else will take
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR We have a very strong policy that people can move to
wherever they want to move. Any job in the company's open. So we
try to force rotation, because doing the same thing, day in and day
out, tends to cause burnout.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consciously Reaching Out &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Tell us a little bit more about how you're managing growth so
far. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS I travel all the time. And I try to talk to as many
people as possible. We do monthly all-hands meetings and we
actually Web-cast them simultaneously and have people call in and
try to have an ongoing dialogue. And now we're doing things which I
never thought we'd ever do. We're going to create an employee
newsletter. We're doing a lot of things that I used to scoff at
when I worked at other companies.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What I've also found is that things I said two years ago are now
on a plaque, and that people are still acting the same way: ``But
Fernando said that.'' Yeah, but that was two years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is communication a common problem? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT Absolutely. We've seen ourselves have to increase the
rate of communication dramatically. When we started four or five
years ago, it was a group of 20 to 25 people. My partner (Todd
Krizelman, co-chief executive) and I could just make decisions very
quickly, hoping everybody can keep up. But eventually it starts to
hurt you more when you get to 200, and people in departments don't
understand what's going on. And we've had to deal with a lot of
organizational changes over the last year, but everybody
understands why we're doing stuff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR We start off with a week of training. It's a week of
indoctrination for every employee _ whether you answer the
telephone in the German office or you're a vice president, it
doesn't matter. You sit, you learn what we do, why we do it, what's
the core culture of the company, so everybody's got a good, firm
foundation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do managers who have worked at large companies fare in
your kinds of companies? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR On average, they've fared pretty well. You've got to
pre-screen them very carefully. You tend to get people who expect
to have two assistants. But our first test is, we make them take a
pay cut. If they won't take a massive pay cut, you've pretty much
got them pegged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do they have options, though, on the other end? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR Absolutely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER The structure that I've seen be the most successful is
a solid infrastructure of senior managers from big companies, very
seasoned, very good at creating structure. That gives you room to
promote people with less management experience, and have someone to
go to when wisdom and time around the track is the issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mountains of Resumes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How hard is it to find employees? Are strangers handing you
resumes as soon as they find out who you are? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR I probably get 10 resums myself a day. We probably get,
as a company, 100 resums a day. There's a lot of talent that wants
to get in, that absolutely wants to get into the dot-com company.
To get great, smart people is always tough. But it's relatively
easy for a dot-com company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS We have two realities. One is in the U.S., which
mirrors that. But in Latin America, it's totally different: There's
no such thing as us. There's a lot of big companies that are owned
by families, so the best you can hope for is to work for so and so,
as opposed to being one of the owners of the company. So in Latin
America we're able to really tap into really great people who don't
have an equivalent to go to. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT Even though we get a hundred resumes a day, we're at a
point where we're trying to find the perfect person to fit this
type of software development. It's easier for us to find people in
marketing and sales, because New York has a lot more of these
people and they're easy to train.
</P>
<P>
   But finding the right technical person, whether it's for
infrastructure or for software, we still find it tough. These
people can command huge salaries from the banks. And finding a
seasoned database manager, for instance, can mean that you have to
pay huge cash, because some of these people want the options and
they want the cash, and they're not going to leave their cushy job
at Goldman Sachs unless you throw it all at them. The fact is, if
you're a well-known dot-com company, it helps immensely over the
unknown dot-com companies and over a lot of the other companies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How to Set Priorities &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you find that your thinking about the way you run your
company changes over time? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS For the last two years, I've been thinking about, well,
what happens in 10 years and what happens in 20 years? Which is
kind of a ridiculous thing to think about on the Internet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR Making that transition from a total entrepreneurial
world with no rules or anything to where you've got to have
professionalization, you've got to have systems; you've got to have
order. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT You have to learn to delegate. Todd and I were
completely attached to the product, had to test everything
ourselves. We were the chief QA (quality assurance) guys.
Eventually, you have to stop that. As much as I still use the
product now, when I have to use it, I want to be able to rely on 50
people who think about this more than I do and who know it better
than I do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR On the flip side, I still spend half my time with new
products _ because that is the entrepreneurial side and new
products are the key to rejuvenating the company, growing the
company. We set out to create a big company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Did you, from the beginning, do something differently than
other start-ups might have done, because you were planning for
growth? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR Definitely. I was fortunate because I started my first
company right out of college. So I went through the ``how you could
have done things differently and better?'' We tried to avoid all
the mistakes. I was building the human infrastructure, getting the
people who could build their own business and leverage. When I look
at DoubleClick, we're actually a collection of about 50 companies:
People who were running their own thing, whether it's their own
country, and there were 22 countries, or we have a bunch of
business units with people running their own businesses. The thing
we most tend to look for in people is intelligence and _ I call it
_ athleticism: people who love to compete, don't like to lose. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS I don't think anybody stumbles onto a big company. You
have to visualize where you're going. You don't know the path
necessarily, but there's a goal. There's something I always think
about and try to get people to think about. I'm not a martial-arts
guy, but when you break a board with your hand, what they teach you
is that if you were able to project the energy, not on the surface
of the board, but behind the board, you will break it. And you can
break three boards, then four boards. But if you aim it for the
surface, you will break your hand. And that's a little bit of what
you dream about. You have to make choices accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   When we were looking for venture funding, and we were out of our
money and we got offered by not-so-great VCs (venture capital
firms) who wanted not-so-great terms, we knew we'd never go there.
So we held out. And we got good funding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER I can think of a number of examples where we turned
down advertisers, we turned down money, because to do (otherwise)
would create a precedent which would limit us later. And as a very
tiny company, it's very scary to do or have to do it. And once you
do it, it inspires everybody. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of Churchill, and Branson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Other chief executives want to be Jack Welch of General
Electric. Is there any model you think about? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS I spent a lot of time learning how Winston Churchill
ran the Second World War. I bring that up as a metaphor _ not
having information, not having clarity, the stakes being very high.
Of course, the stakes he had to deal with were somewhat higher than
what we have to do. But that was part of the encouragement _, to
think that something so important could be managed, and all the
mistakes that were made and the chaos of the moment. And the other
thing, which he said, which I love as a philosophy, is: You don't
have to get it right all the time. You just have to get it right 51
percent of the time, and that will carry you through. And that's a
very, very liberating philosophy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER I admire two people. Steve Ross, who turned a funeral
parlor into one of the great media empires in the world (Time
Warner). He did it by empowering people tremendously. And he was a
bit of a cowboy, but that's the only way you get from a funeral
parlor to one of the largest media companies in the world. When you
were in the room with him, you would want to just get up and run
and help him to fulfill this vision.
</P>
<P>
   And then in the dot-com world, I personally admire Tim Koogle
(chief executive of Yahoo) so much. I think Yahoo has an elegance
in the way they do things. They never sacrifice. They're the only
portal that never charged money for carriage. And they did it
because they only want to have the very best content. They want to
invite the best people in. Everything they've done has been for
long-term greatness.
</P>
<P>
   There's all these fancy dot-com buildings down in Silicon
Valley. And you go to Yahoo and it's so very understated. We send
our architects out there to visit it because, we said, this is the
model. And the employees love it because they really thought about
how the employees could have a great day there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT Todd and I have the same idol: Richard Branson (founder
of the Virgin Group) _ just his philosophy of wanting to be a
successful businessman and having fun while doing it. And he's one
of those guys that's really built up one of the best-recognized
brands in the world. And after reading his book, ``Losing My
Virginity,'' you can see how he's had a lot of similar experiences
to what Todd and I had. Seeing how he started from some
inexperienced young guy and turned it into some major media empire.
And seeing how this man embodies the brand, Virgin, is extremely
inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   Todd and I have always had a philosophy since we started, that
we're only doing this as long as we have fun. The day that you're
just doing it for the money, that's the day we get out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR Mine's more historical. Edison was a horrible CEO but a
hell of an innovator. He pretty much innovated the 21st century.
And then Ayn Rand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER Yeah. Champion of capitalism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR Her philosophy of capitalism and the individual is just
how we pretty much run the company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think Koogle is great. I think Steve Case (chairman of America
Online) is amazing. How many times did people write Case off? And
he's always come back. Gates (Bill Gates of Microsoft) is an
incredible entrepreneur that everyone really respects _ an
entrepreneur who was successful in transitioning from an
entrepreneur to building a phenomenal company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you imagine out a couple of years? If you have a
10,000-person organization, is it going to be like every other
10,000-person organization?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR There's nothing wrong with big companies. We all want
to become one. And we all want to create a company that stands the
test of time. Look at the great companies: General Electric _ what
they do is something to be idolized. Disney _ they keep innovating.
IBM _ we all want to be like that. But we all want to stay away
from the bureaucracy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS I'm sure that some Internet companies will become
stodgy old media companies in the next five years. The challenge is
how do you maintain that freshness and how do you organize yourself
and how do you develop a culture that it doesn't matter whether
you're 500 or 5,000 or 50,000 people. At Microsoft, they have
30,000, 40,000 employees. They move fast. They have that drive.
That's cultural. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Price of Profits &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How long do you think you can exist without producing
profit? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR It's clear what the market's telling us. They want to
give us a lot of money, so we take it and we invest. Why? We look
back, and what was the biggest mistake that we made? We should have
invested even more money. We should have lost more money. Why?
Because this is the biggest thing that's ever hit. Market share is
everything.
</P>
<P>
   But it depends on what stage the company is in. People are going
to start expecting profits from us in the next one to two years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT The reason we all lost money and all went crazy for
this is because we realized how big it could be. And it's worth
losing the money for the sake of becoming that much bigger down the
long road. And I think that investors traditionally, by default,
will say ``yes, we'd prefer a profitable company,'' but not if they
know it's at the expense of getting that company to be way bigger a
little bit further down the road. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS Things have changed. In '96 when we started our
company, nobody knew if anybody could make a profit on the Net. And
now we look and we see that there are certain models, in our case
the advertising model, and the e-commerce models, actually can be
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest risk is that we under-invest, as Kevin said, because
this won't come again. And if we don't own that waterfront before
everyone else, somebody else will. We don't want to be in a
situation next year having to buy someone for a billion bucks that
we could have invested $25 million to build or buy them when
they're little.
</P>
<P>
   We have invested over the last two years much more in building
our brand than the advertising revenue available in the whole of
Latin America. Now we're either very stupid or clever and I'd like
to think that we're clever, because it means that we are now
capturing more than our fair share of that revenue opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How much longer will it be before people begin to say ``wait
a minute''? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER Off the Internet, media companies take five to seven
years to become profitable. Everybody knows that in the media
business. AOL took eight years, because they were early. Let's say
Yahoo took four and a half. So that kind of defines it.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what's interesting is that many of the investors came
out of technology. They don't have models of the dynamics of a
media company. They're applying a different model and then
wondering, ``Gee, this doesn't look like anything I've seen,'' but
it's not like the world has never seen it before. You can look at
media models and see exactly where we all are on the curve, because
it's a business where you do spend a lot up front to build brand,
to build advertising-revenue generation capability, and then your
revenue starts scaling past it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR It is starting to happen. The scary thing that's
happened is what's coming out public today are companies that have
no revenue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do you pay your employees? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS We pay good salaries, but fair salaries within the norm
for that kind of job in other industries. And then we try to get
people to really think about the stock being their major
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does everybody have stock? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS Yeah, after I believe it's six months _ after your
first review _ everyone gets stock options. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT Same policy exactly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. At a couple of your companies, the stock price today is a
quarter of where it once was. Does that linger as a question in the
hallways? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT You've got to have open communication with your people.
You've got to tell them not to look at your day-to-day stock price,
but at the same time they deserve to have an explanation and
understanding of where things are going in the long run. Give them
enough vision so that it's their decision: ``Well, I don't care
what the stock's at today, I think that we had a great internal
story, and a year from now I think things could be way better; I'm
going to stick around.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER At that time of the IPO, we pulled out the stock
charts of five companies and we said, ``Well, here's what you're in
for.'' The pattern was so ridiculously consistent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Risk vs. Executive Reward &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Many big-company chief executives think you're overpaid. The
whole world thinks they're overpaid. Are you overpaid and are they
overpaid? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR Am I working a million times, or whatever it may be,
smarter than someone else? No. Am I overpaid? No. It is what it
is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS We win when the stockholder wins and not otherwise,
which is, I think, a perfect alignment of value.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT If those traditional media types all want to complain
about it, they can always start their own Internet companies and
take a chance, and I think they'll realize what the risk-reward
ratio is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER It is a little bit like the lottery, because the
person brought in to run eBay hit the lottery. She, Meg Whitman, is
great, but she would be the first to say she got really lucky. The
risk of walking away from what's known and guaranteed and starting
over in one room that you're sharing with eight people, in
retrospect, looks like no big deal. But when you do it, you're
taking a big risk. Our culture happens to reward that behavior,
which is one reason it's a great country.
</P>
<P>
   My old media colleagues say, you know, ``damn, this is really
annoying that you guys went and did this,'' but there's something
in you that allows you to go take that risk. It wasn't guaranteed.
In the end, it could have been worth absolutely zero. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you worry that the Internet economy isn't a fair economy,
that you have to be lucky to get rich in it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR No, I think the market's very discriminating, and
customers are very discriminating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT In many senses, it's this wealth creation _ even though
sometimes I don't like the fact that a lot of people are jumping
into this industry to make a buck _ that is driving every single
business out there to want to give it a chance. No one disputes
that the Internet, in some way _ business to business, business to
consumer _ is improving the lives of consumers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wealth, but No Time &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you tell people who want to be entrepreneurs about
your lives and the impact that sudden wealth has had on your
lifestyle? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR I tell everyone just to pursue what you love. If you
pursue what you love, you're either going to put in the effort, and
you become the best at it, and then you're going to create a
successful company, and lots of money, and do well and have fun, or
you're going to die poor and happy because you pursued what you
love. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS I was just meeting with entrepreneurs talking about
this in Argentina and saying: Forget the money. You probably won't
go public. You probably won't be able to raise money. You're
probably going to die as a company, so you have to focus on the
fundamentals. What is it that you're going to do that's going to
change the world? And if you pick something that changes the world
really well and you do it very well, then you'll make money off of
that. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER You have to have leisure time to change your
lifestyle, and no one has leisure time yet, so I don't see people
rushing out and capitalizing on the money to change the way they
live. Everyone's too busy building a franchise right now.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this is going to create huge shifts in wealth. And I
think it's going to open up charitable giving in a wave that we
haven't seen for 50 years that's going to change this country
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   I did go out and buy a few Versace gowns. It was really
therapeutic. And I've just bought a little fur jacket, and all of
that's really fun, but at the end of the day, that all takes time,
and I basically have to go back to work and keep building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have time to follow politics? What do you want from
Washington? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR I think the Internet is changing the world like no
other system _ in such a short period of time _ that it's causing
industries to become entrenched in wanting to limit the Internet.
People want to stick their hands on the Internet through
regulations, so I think we're all finding ourselves spending a lot
more time educating governments and senators and Congress people to
make sure that they understand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT A coalition has been formed _ Netcoalition.com _ that
is specifically for the purpose of having someone there, including
the CEOs of those member companies, going to Washington and
speaking with senators, just educating them, so that eventually,
when they do make a policy decision they haven't made it completely
out of thin air. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER We're involved in politics on the consumer side. We
have each of the presidential candidates coming in to do a town
meeting in which the questions are not created by the people of
iVillage but are filtered up through the membership. It's just
having this fabulous rejuvenating impact on democracy that we
haven't even seen the beginning of yet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR Platform for libertarianism worldwide, you're going to
see it worldwide. That's my theory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Change the World &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there a difference in culture between now and the 1980s?
Are we just a ``greed-is-good.com'' culture or is anything
different motivating people now? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS At least in the first couple of waves of the Internet,
you'll find a lot of people who think they're actors in a play to
change the world, which is very different than money for money's
sake.
</P>
<P>
   We're not investing in glamour and luxury; we're investing in
our product and our people and basic business stuff. So I think the
culture is very different.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT If you look at the movie ``Wall Street'' as the
quintessential example of that, nothing really new was being
created. We're in positions here where I think the reason there is
wealth is because we're doing something completely different than
playing with money. We are literally shaping, in some way, the way
people are going to live and the way businesses are going to run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER I was talking to someone about this whole thing, about
why this thing grabs hold of you. And then you feel like you don't
have it; it has you. For some reason, some number of people have
been tapped on the shoulder, like `you're going to be part of this
thing that is going to be born.' There is nothing that's going to
stop this particular transformation.
</P>
<P>
   It is great sometimes. Other times, it's just so consuming that
you wish you could just dial down and have 60 percent of the
experience. But that's not available. You're either in, tapped, put
to work, on the road crew, or probably you're not in. There is no
kind of convenient, ``this really works for my life.'' And I think
that's probably when any big transformation happens _ it just sort
of puts people to work in the service of itself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Kevin is burning to say something. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR It's something I probably shouldn't say, because it's
contrarian. I think that without question there's a real temptation
for some really bad things to happen. And you start to see signals
of it. We had the highest turnover in our Silicon Valley office.
</P>
<P>
   I'll talk to an employee who's leaving the company and saying:
``Love the company, love the compensation, love DoubleClick, love
everything, but I'm going to go and really throw my hat in the ring
with a hot new start-up over here. The guy next door made $20
million. I've got to make my $20 million or I'm a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   So you start to see greed. Money creates greed, and greed
creates corruption. And you're going to see more and more of this.
You're going to see bad companies. Wherever there's an incredible,
immense amount of money, there's going to be bad people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER As long as the pie keeps rapidly expanding,
everybody's going to be really good friends and get along really
well. When it starts really getting to be a battle for market
share, it'll be a different story. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No Fun in the Fishbowl &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you all really hate about being a chief executive?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS Having to be ``on'' all the time. Everyone you meet
sees you through that optic. So much so that now, unless it's a
business context, I never say what I do. I always work for ``a
Latin American company.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATERNOT That's exactly what I do as well. A nameless company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change I saw to the negative is going from a private
company to a public one. All of a sudden you have to be that much
more careful with the random people that you meet, because
sometimes you'll start off in a perfectly casual conversation and
before you know it, you realize that person's just wanting to know
where your stock's going next week. That can get annoying.
</P>
<P>
   It's constantly feeling like sometimes you're being taken
advantage of by people who do know who you are, and you just want
to be anonymous. You don't want to necessarily be a public profile
24 hours a day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there anything else you dislike? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARPENTER Travel. Today, being a CEO means an enormous amount of
travel. Often, you go somewhere and you talk for an hour and it's
critical. You have to do it, but you think, ``God, this whole thing
took me 12 hours and it was an hour of something that actually
happened.'' We can be more and more productive on planes with
computers, but travel takes a huge personal toll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS I arrived this morning (in Miami) at 5 from Buenos
Aires, had a press conference at 8:30, gave a speech at 9:30 and
got on a plane at 11 (to come to New York).
</P>
<P>
   Something I don't think is at all a positive is that the CEO
figure has become a bit of a starlet. Literally, there's probably
30 people or more in our company who could have done that speech
today, and done it much better than I, since I was half dazed
anyway. But people want to meet you, and that makes a difference.
Sometimes it is a bit overwhelming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR To me, it's just family. You just don't get to see
them. Wife can understand, but two kids, two young kids, they have
a tough time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will you still be the chief executive of DoubleClick when
you're 60? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR The board willing. Hopefully, I'll drop dead behind my
desk of old age and the board doesn't shoot me. So far they like
me, though. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You envision that kind of career? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR Yeah, if the board thinks I'm the best person for the
job, then, yeah, I'd love to keep it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How about the rest of the panel? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPUELAS Sixty's a long way away. I love what I do. I can't
imagine doing anything else, but I've also seen people who've been
at the same job for 20 years, and it's not pretty. I'd like to also
think that I'm imminently replaceable and that within the 700
people we have in our team are at least 100 that could have my job.
I like to think that anybody can actually replace me and that that
should be everyone's desire at our company, that they should want
my job and that they should work for it and get it.
</P>
</TEXT>
