<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURSUIT OF STOCK WEALTH BRINGS A WORLD OF SWINDLERS
</P>
<P>
   Along with the greatest bull market in American history comes a
world of low-priced stocks and high-priced dreams, of grimy offices
and sham companies, of swindlers who bilk Americans out of roughly
$2 billion a year, securities regulators say. The problem is so
severe that regulators and prosecutors have made it one of their
chief goals to crack down on what they used to dismiss as
``penny-stock fraud.'' It was in this world that Albert Alain
Chalem and Maier Lehmann lived _ and died. The men, who were
promoting stocks over the Internet together, were both shot in the
head on Oct. 25 and left to die on the marble floor in the $1.1
million home in Colts Neck, N.J., where Chalem lived.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are examining whether there is a link between the
deaths of the two stock promoters and an account one of them may
have had at Harbor Securities, a small stock trading firm that
closed this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL TECHNOLOGY SEEPS INTO FILMS
</P>
<P>
   Mike Figgis, the director of ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' is seeking
to exploit the digital technologies that are beginning to seep into
the Hollywood mainstream. His latest film, ``Time Code 2000,'' is
being shot in real time with four digital cameras as one continuous
take. When it appears in theaters, he said, the images from all
four cameras will be shown simultaneously, either in horizontal
strips with four images shown left to right or stacked two atop
two, allowing audience members to edit the film in their heads as
they try to follow the plot. Once inside the walls of major
studios, many think, digital movie making will have a great effect
on how movies are made and how people view them.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING AGREES TO SETTLE BIAS CASE
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has agreed to pay at least $4.5 million to women and
minority employees who the Government says are paid less than their
white male counterparts, according to people involved in the
settlement, the largest ever under a Labor Department affirmative
action compliance program.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P 500 AND NASDAQ HIT RECORDS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rallied, led by computer-related companies, after
Hewlett-Packard sold shares in its measurement instruments unit.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 14.23 points, or 1
percent, to 1,424.94, a record. The Nasdaq composite index climbed
77.72 points, or 2.38 percent, to 3,347.11, also a record. The Dow
Jones industrial average climbed 152.61 points, or 1.4 percent, to
11,035.70.
</P>
<P>
   4 NATIONS BACK CASPIAN PIPELINE
</P>
<P>
   Four nations in the Caspian Sea region _ Georgia, Azerbaijan,
Kazakhstan and Turkey _ took a step toward embracing one of
President Clinton's cherished foreign policy projects, a pipeline
that would assure Western control over the region's potentially
vast oil and natural gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF HEWLETT INCREASE 21%
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Hewlett-Packard jumped nearly 21 percent, one day
after the company posted stronger-than-expected quarterly earnings,
set an aggressive sales goal for next year and began spinning off
its test and measurement business. Hewlett-Packard closed at
$94.3125, up $16.3125. Shares in Agilent Technologies, the test
business, were up $12.75, at $42.75, in their first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE DEFICIT IS SEEN STABILIZING
</P>
<P>
   The nation's trade deficit appears to be stabilizing as foreign
economic growth picks up and the American demand for imports slows,
Commerce Department figures showed. While the gap widened in
September, to $24.4 billion, analysts said it would have narrowed
had it not been for surging oil prices and an off month for
aircraft delivery.
</P>
<P>
   28 REGAL HOTELS ARE SOLD IN U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium &AMP; Copthorne, a London real estate company, has agreed
to buy the 28 Regal hotels in the United States for about $253
million plus the assumption of $387 million in debt from Regal
Hotels International of Hong Kong. The hotels include the Regal
U.N. Plaza in Manhattan, the Regal Biltmore in Los Angeles, the
Regal Bostonian in Boston and the Regal McCormick Ranch in
Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
</TEXT>
