<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PREVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT IS CHOICE FOR TOP HONORS IN WOMEN'S BASKETBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Except for one charity doubleheader last Sunday and the first
two rounds of the Preseason National Invitation Tournament Monday
and Wednesday, the women's college season will begin in earnest
Friday night. But a few games already played have hinted that the
women's game, which boomed in the 1990s, will be forever different.
</P>
<P>
   The best teams figure to be such old reliables as Connecticut,
Tennessee, Louisiana Tech, Rutgers, Georgia and UCLA. But they will
be joined by a dozen or so others that may be ready to drag some of
the marquee teams down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee had upset the U.S. national team the week before,
after the national team had routed UCLA and Stanford by at least 50
points each. That hardly impressed Louisiana Tech, which outhustled
Tennessee and won, 69-64.
</P>
<P>
   While Pat Summitt, the Tennessee coach, was publicly critical of
her players, she also realized that the loss could provide them
with a wake-up call. She played down the victory over the national
team because those pro stars had spent all night flying to
Knoxville, Tenn., and were flat. Against Louisiana Tech, her team,
which started three juniors, a sophomore and a freshman, lacked
leadership and played as if it expected to win simply because it
was Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more people accountable on both ends of the court,''
she said. ``The junior class has to grab this team and take
responsibility for leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The best of those juniors, and the most outspoken, is the
all-American Tamika Catchings. Summitt expects her to take over the
team the way Chamique Holdsclaw did before she graduated to the
Women's National Basketball Association last summer. Catchings is
willing to assume the burden, but on her terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year,'' she said, ``it was Chamique and the Lady Vols. I
don't want it to be like that. When we make it to the national
championship, I want it to be the Lady Vols, not Catchings and the
Lady Vols or Semeka Randall and the Lady Vols. We don't want that
individual stuff. We want it to be a team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss by Rutgers in that Knoxville doubleheader was a concern
because the North Carolina State Wolfpack was barely a top-20 team,
yet it humbled Rutgers, 68-55. Rutgers is a running team, but most
of its players seemed baffled when North Carolina State outran and
outhustled them.
</P>
<P>
   This should have been a wake-up call for Rutgers, too, and for
all the other good teams that may have forgotten why they became
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of good teams out there,'' said Gail
Goestenkoers, the Duke coach. ``Last year, the fact we saw new
faces in the Final Four gave more teams hope they could be there.
That's half the battle _ believing you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Final Four teams in the National Collegiate
Athletic Association's 64-team tournament were Purdue, Duke,
Louisiana Tech and Georgia. Purdue beat Duke for the championship.
Georgia and Louisiana Tech are strong again, but in an example of
how much depth has come to the sport, Purdue and Duke face a
struggle just to make this season's top 20.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue lost its excellent guard combination of Stephanie
White-McCarty and Ukari Figgs to graduation. Tiffany Johnson, who
would have started this season at guard, was killed in an auto
accident. Coach Carolyn Peck left for the pros. Graduation took
three Duke starters, including 6-foot-6-inch Michelle Van Gorp.
Tennessee graduated Chamique Holdsclaw, maybe the best female
college player ever, and point guard Kellie Jolly, the glue of
Tennessee's champion teams.
</P>
<P>
   While Tennessee and Rutgers lost Sunday and Georgia beat
Alabama-Birmingham by only a point Monday night in the Preseason
NIT, Connecticut has been awaiting its opener Sunday at Iowa. Coach
Geno Auriemma said he felt good about his team, which is ranked No.
1 in the two major preseason polls. Auriemma was especially pleased
with the return of the 5-9 point guard, Sue Bird, who missed most
of last season after reconstructive knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Bird is one of three sophomores who will start. The two others
will come from Tamika Williams, Swin Cash and Asjha Jones, all 6
feet 2 inches, all pitiless on the boards and capable of scoring
spurts. Williams, Cash and Jones are so athletic that three taller
centers _ 6-5 Paige Sauer, 6-5 Kelly Schumacher and a 6-6 transfer,
Christine Rigby _ will struggle for playing time.
</P>
<P>
   The other starters are juniors _ 6-2 Svetlana Abrosimova, an
all-American from Russia, and 6-0 Shea Ralph, healthy again after
three knee operations. The only freshman on the team is Kennitra
Johnson, a 5-7 point guard who seems sure to get major playing
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potentially,'' Auriemma said, ``we can be very good, as good
as any team I've had at Connecticut, but we're still a young team.
Svet and Shea are the two keys. Sue Bird is about two months away
from being all the way back. Our style is predicated on the
pressure we put on people, and last year we never fully recovered
from the injuries to Sue and so many others.''
</P>
<P>
   That UConn team was upset by Iowa State in the regional
semifinals. This year, UConn expects to play in the Final Four
March 31 and April 2 in the First Union Center in Philadelphia. As
Abrosimova said, ``We're going to be really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma said he welcomed the rise of Rutgers, Notre Dame and
Boston College in their Big East Conference, which UConn has
dominated for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always difficult when we were the only big team in the
conference,'' Auriemma said, ``because if we lost a league game it
was on `the CBS Evening News.' You would never imagine this 10
years ago. It's something we always hoped would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For Marsha Sharp, the Texas Tech coach, the increase in national
contenders has been a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago,'' she said, ``there was never a chance
probably for someone that wasn't in the Top 25 to beat someone who
was in the top five. Now it happens all the time. I think that says
a lot about the growth of the game and how it's changed. I think
it's a great statement for the sport and for universities who have
made that commitment to build strong women's basketball programs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Frank Litsky thinks these are the 16 teams most likely to reach
the regional rounds of the NCAA women's basketball tournament and
provide the lineup for the Final Four in Philadelphia. (Last
season's records in parentheses.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAST TEAM STANDING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT (29-5)
</P>
<P>
   Graduation took only one starter (Amy Duran), and the two
remaining seniors have become backups. So this team is young yet
experienced, and it plays defense with a morale-breaking fury.
Svetlana Abrosimova, the 6-foot-2-inch, 19-year-old junior from
Russia, and the 6-0 Shea Ralph are fiery with the ball. Sue Bird,
her surgically repaired knee almost sound again, returns at point
guard; it's not her natural position, but that does not matter with
this uptempo offense. ``If Sue has a great year,'' Coach Geno
Auriemma said, ``we have a chance to be a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THREE MORE FOR THE FINAL FOUR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE (31-3)
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols have won three of the last four national titles.
Although Chamique Holdsclaw is gone, this team could repeat behind
three gifted juniors _ Tamika Catchings (6-1), Semeka Randall
(5-10) and Kristen (Ace) Clement (5-11) _ but the operative word
must be ``we.'' Coach Pat Summitt knows she has work to do because
Clement, the point guard, sometimes does not spot an open teammate,
and those teammates sometimes forget there is a point guard.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA TECH (30-3)
</P>
<P>
   Year in and year out, Coach Leon Barmore replaces graduation
losses with guards who can fly and post players with muscle. He
lost three starters from last season's Final Four team, but the 5-8
Betty Lennox has joined the super-quick, 5-5 Tamicha Jackson in the
backcourt and Shaka Massey (6-3) is punishing under both boards.
The Lady Techsters are fast and deep.
</P>
<P>
   RUTGERS (29-6)
</P>
<P>
   A quick, athletic team that seems ready to challenge for the
national title. At 5-6, Tasha Pointer is a mercuric point guard,
and the 5-10 Shawnetta Stewart is a gunner, but more physical play
underneath would help. ``With nine juniors and seniors,'' Coach C.
Vivian Stringer said, ``we have depth, maturity and experience. I
think we'll do well. I'm an eternal optimist.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOUR THAT COULD KNOCK ON THE DOOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA (27-7)
</P>
<P>
   Despite three losses to Tennessee, the Bulldogs reached the
Final Four last season. Four starters return, including the
high-energy backcourt of the Miller twins _ Kelly (18.5 points a
game) and Coco (18.4). Tawana McDonald and the newcomer Shala
Crawford, both 6-4, provide power under the boards.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA STATE (25-8)
</P>
<P>
   Everyone returns to the team that knocked Connecticut out of the
last NCAA tournament. Four players, led by the 5-8 Stacy Frese,
averaged in double figures. The goal is the Final Four because, as
Coach Bill Fennelly said, ``If you don't believe it and don't think
about it, why do you come out and practice?''
</P>
<P>
   NOTRE DAME (26-5)
</P>
<P>
   Sheila McMillen, a 3-point gunner, is gone, but the 6-5 Ruth
Riley, a big scorer in the low post, returns. ``We're not going to
rely on Ruth to carry us all season,'' Coach Muffet McGraw said.
``I've got six people who can score a lot. This is the most
athletic team we've had. We're going to be very good.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA (26-8)
</P>
<P>
   All the starters return, including Maylana Martin (6-3), a
preseason all-American, but Martin (back), the 5-9 Erica Gomez
(shoulder) and the 5-7 LaCresha Flannigan (knee) are recovering
from surgery. Although this scoring powerhouse averaged 85.2 points
a game last season, it tends to get careless on defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EIGHT THAT COULD HANG AROUND LATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA STATE (17-12)
</P>
<P>
   In its season-opening upset of Rutgers, the Wolfpack showed how
energetic it could be. The 5-10 Tynesha Lewis is a smooth off
guard, the 5-7 point guard Terah James and the 6-3 forward Kaayla
Chones hardly play like freshmen and the 6-6 Summer Erb is so big
that opponents must alter offenses and defenses.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA (28-8)
</P>
<P>
   There are no seniors but there are three top-rate juniors _
Nikki Teasley (6-0), the point guard; Juana Brown (5-11), the off
guard, and LaQuanda Barksdale (5-11), the rebounder. Size is
desperately needed under the boards, and the Tar Heels hope that
LaShonda Allen, a 6-5 sophomore, can provide it.
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS (20-9)
</P>
<P>
   More consistency would have helped last season. Only Alicia
Sheeler is gone from that team, so this edition has experience and
depth. Susan Blauser, a 6-2 forward who averaged 17.2 points a
game, will get help from the 6-1 Tauja Catchings (sister of
Tennessee's Tamika) and Allison Curtin (5-9).
</P>
<P>
   PENN STATE (22-8)
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions live on 3-point shooting, and they may go far
if they learn to play tough against the bad teams as well as the
good. Their five top scorers return, led by the 6-3 center Andrea
Garner (14.4 points a game), the 5-11 off guard Lisa Seepherd
(14.1) and the 5-7 point guard Helen Darling (12.4).
</P>
<P>
   AUBURN (20-9)
</P>
<P>
   There is great potential here. Everyone returns from last
season, notably center Conswella Sparrow (6-2) and forward Tasha
Hamilton (5-10). Sparrow averaged 14.4 points a game on 61.4
percent shooting, Hamilton 14.6 on 56.3 percent. Rebounding is
excellent, but 3-point shooting (29.3 percent) not so good.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA STATE (22-8)
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those Southeastern Conference powerhouses that
loses its share of league games, but beats almost everyone else.
The four returning starters include Katrina Hibbert, a 5-11
Australian wing player, and Detrina White, a 5-11 center who has
trouble guarding bigger opponents in the post.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-SANTA BARBARA (26-4)
</P>
<P>
   A superstrong team from the supersoft Big West Conference; once
the conference season starts it is seldom tested. Everyone returns,
and still there are only three seniors. Watch for Erin Buescher, a
6-3 junior guard who last season averaged 19.9 points and 47.3
percent 3-point shooting.
</P>
<P>
   OLD DOMINION (28-4)
</P>
<P>
   An uphill battle awaits because Mery Andrade, the best player
and best defender, is gone, along with the other 3-point shooters.
The burden falls on Lucienne Berthieu, a 6-2 junior forward-center
from France. The well of foreign talent has dried up, so the Final
Four seems just a dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
