<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-FOREIGN-POLICY-A     11-18 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FOREIGN-POLICY-ART-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BRUSHING UP ON FOREIGN POLICY FOR A WORLD STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT21 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By FRANK BRUNI and ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Sunday it was just a conference call, and it
lasted little more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But for more than two hours on Monday afternoon, and then again
Monday night, and then again Tuesday afternoon, several of George
W. Bush's leading foreign policy advisers and top aides sat with
him in the yellow-walled parlor and blue-walled dining room of the
governor's mansion in Austin, Texas, and trotted the globe: Russia,
China, North Korea, Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Their principal mission was to put the finishing touches on a
foreign policy speech that Bush is scheduled to give on Friday. But
there was another, equally important goal: the education of Bush on
the subject _ international affairs _ that has caused him the most
trouble in his presidential campaign so far.
</P>
<P>
   And there was awareness, among advisers inside and outside the
gilded chambers, that the scrutiny given to Bush's words on this
topic would only intensify in the coming days and weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to have a live, hour-long interview on ``Meet
the Press,'' his first appearance on a Sunday morning talk show
this campaign. Then, between Dec. 2 and 13, he will participate in
three televised debates with his rivals for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will almost certainly be challenged to demonstrate the kind
of international fluency that eluded him during an unanticipated
grilling about foreign leaders by a television reporter two weeks
ago. These events will provide a fuller, fairer test of just how
well he has been preparing.
</P>
<P>
   The way that Bush handles them, several advisers acknowledged,
could be critical for the continued success of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always felt there would be a moment when people would start
looking at us differently,'' said one adviser. ``That moment's
come, and we've got to rise to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The adviser conceded that even though the televised pop quiz was
almost universally dismissed as inappropriate, ``people viewed that
episode as potentially illuminating. We know that it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite that assertion and all of Bush's preparation, the
Texas governor still seems a bit shaky on foreign soil.
</P>
<P>
   During a telephone interview with an Associated Press reporter
on Tuesday, Bush made a reference to the Russian military attacking
women and children in Chechnya, the breakaway republic. When the
writer asked if the attacks were still occurring, Bush could be
heard asking someone near him if he was correct in his belief that
they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Condi Rice is shaking her head in agreement,'' Bush then
answered, referring to his chief foreign policy adviser,
Condoleezza Rice.
</P>
<P>
   For several days now, in television interviews, telephone calls
with reporters and comments on the campaign trail in Iowa, Bush has
been conducting what seems to be a nonstop rehearsal for the speech
he will deliver Friday in Simi Valley, Calif., and for his
television appearance on Sunday. Advisers say he recognizes the
interview as an essential rite of political passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has said privately to people, `I've got to take some
questions given to me by people who are pretty good at it and get
dirtied up a bit,''' one adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   In his previews of the speech, Bush has vowed to be a fierce
advocate for what he calls a new internationalism, with the United
States playing an active role in promoting peace. He has said he
will strongly support free trade, especially with China. He has
said that international aid should be withdrawn if Russia persists
in its aggression against Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   In Davenport, Iowa, on Wednesday, Bush acknowledged that voters
may have questions about his readiness for the global stage, but
said, ``I think the American people have questions about every
person running for president in terms of foreign policy, and they
should.''
</P>
<P>
   His advisers, he said, have helped him translate his bedrock
beliefs about the U.S. role in the world into specific policies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he added, ``They help me understand the nuance _ a
word I'm learning. In Texas politics, we don't spend much time on
nuance. But there's nuance in foreign policy. I'm beginning to
learn that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's education began early this year with a stream of visits
to the governor's mansion by Ms. Rice and other experts, including
George Shultz, President Reagan's secretary of state, and two
people who served under President Bush _ Paul D. Wolfowitz, a
senior defense official and Robert Zoellick, an undersecretary of
state.
</P>
<P>
   These experts and Bush's aides quibbled with the frequent
characterization of these sessions as tutorials, saying that the
discussions have been more free-wheeling than that, with Bush doing
as much talking as listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not a blank slate at all,'' said Dov Zakheim, who was a
senior official in the Department of Defense under President
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   These advisers added that what Bush lacked in detailed
knowledge, he made up for in curiosity. Richard L. Armitage, who
was a senior official in the Pentagon under President Bush, turned
to a sports metaphor to make the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``In basketball,'' Armitage said, ``you can't coach height. In
foreign and defense policy, you can't coach liking it. And he likes
it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush has demonstrated a particular fondness for asking his
advisers hypothetical questions about possible developments in the
world's hot spots. Several advisers said he seemed to prefer
discussions to in-depth reading, although he has been known to
needle advisers when something they say diverges from something
they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   His demeanor is focused, but the atmosphere is relaxed. If a
meeting begins at the end of one of Bush's runs, he may show up in
sweaty workout clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush hit the campaign trail and began taking unscripted
questions from reporters, these advisers and Bush's policy
director, Josh Bolten, have frequently provided him with written
information about current events. The material, sometimes in
question-and-answer form, supplements Bush's own reading of daily
newspapers and magazines, advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rice, a specialist who once worked with the National
Security Council, said that in addition to visiting Bush in Austin
about once a week, she calls or sends him electronic mail every few
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to say, `Here are some breaking issues that you may want
to pay attention to,''' she explained. ``I consider it my job to
sort, and to say, `Gee, Chechnya has reached the point where we
have to think a little more about it.' It's partly for the long
haul, but it's also, frankly, because he may be asked about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After a newspaper columnist, writing about the pop quiz,
suggested 10 more relevant foreign policy questions that Bush
should be asked, Ms. Rice and other advisers pulled together
background information on each one and provided it to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   What Bush's aides and advisers have not done is riddle him with
the kinds of simple facts that they say have nothing to do with his
ability to make proper decisions about foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thinks it's important for him to memorize names in
order to deflect criticism,'' Ms. Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Other advisers said that Bush has also been encouraged, in
answering questions, to stick to the broad themes and priorities
that he is trying to articulate.
</P>
<P>
   That is Bush's sensibility, anyway, advisers said. ``Like
Reagan, he's got a predisposition for certain broad ideas,'' said
Richard Perle, an assistant secretary of defense under President
Reagan. But, Perle added, ``I think he's intellectually more
curious than Reagan was.''
</P>
<P>
   Other advisers also noted Bush's inquisitiveness. ``Some people
can ask you the first question, but I was more impressed when he
asked a follow-up and another and another,'' said Shultz.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has convictions and he's testing them,'' Shultz said.
``He's honing his views.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
