<HEADER>
A4484 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ART-2T     11-18 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES A COMPROMISE BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd Take is scheduled to move by 10 p.m.m ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo _ NYT11 _ Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ United by a desire to proclaim victory and leave
town, Republicans and Democrats in the House joined on Thursday
night to pass the final budget bill of the year, seven weeks after
the fiscal year began.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted, 296-135, for a package of five spending bills
containing $385 billion, sending the measure to the Senate. An
avalanche of oratory from three Senate Democrats seeking benefits
for their states blocked the bill's path and briefly threatened a
government shutdown, a threat that evaporated when the Senate
extended the budget deadline until Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties claimed political victory in nearly identical
language after the House vote, in which 170 Republicans were joined
by 125 Democrats and one independent in supporting the bill.
</P>
<P>
   After seven months of haggling over the year's 13 spending
bills, and after 10 days of intense negotiations between the White
House and the Republican leaders in Congress, both sides said the
result represented the essence of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called it ``a hard-won victory for the
American people.'' His chief of staff, John Podesta, simply said,
``We're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   And House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois said that Congress
had ``basically turned the corner on how this town does business''
by limiting spending in a booming economy, allowing the government
to pay down a small part of its $3.6 trillion debt instead.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans fought for and won a $17 billion spending
increase for the Pentagon, along with more money for politically
popular health research and education. They said they kept their
promise to refrain from using excess contributions to Social
Security to pay for the spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats and the White House were able to assert that they
had won the funds for hiring more primary school teachers and local
police officers, underwriting Middle East peace agreements and
finally paying some of the $1 billion withheld by Congress in dues
the United States owes the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed on providing $12.8 billion over five years to
teaching hospitals, nursing homes and other health care providers
who were suffering financially from cuts in Medicare imposed by
Congress in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The 84 Republicans voting no were protesting spending increases
won by the White House for programs like foreign aid and
environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
   The 51 Democrats who voted no, a quarter of their party in the
House, split with their president over the compromises the White
House made in its final budget negotiations with the Republicans.
Some rebelled over restrictions Republicans sought on aid to
international family planning groups in exchange for freeing up the
back dues owed the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed to a ban on using such aid to promote abortions
to free nearly $1 billion that the United States owes the United
Nations. He can waive the restrictions, but then $12.5 million in
federal grants to women's health groups would be shifted to a
children's fund.
</P>
<P>
   Angry at this tradeoff, 19 female House Democrats demanded that
the White House make amends. Steve Ricchetti, a deputy White House
chief of staff, told them on Thursday that the administration would
ask Congress next year for more than $500 million in federal grants
for the groups.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats protested what they called bookkeeping tricks in
the budget that allowed the Republicans to claim that they had
protected Social Security surpluses. The Congressional Budget
Office says the bills dip into the retirement reserves for at least
$17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The final budget deal, agreed to early Thursday morning,
included some of this sort of sleight-of-hand, such as delaying the
last payday of next September for Pentagon personnel and some
civilian government employees so it falls in the next fiscal year.
That saves no money, but eliminates expenditures in the 2000 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These accounting gimmicks may appear to be funny,'' said Rep.
David Obey of Wisconsin, the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee. ``But they're corrosive of democracy and
of our role in it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
