<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SIGNS OF MECHANICAL FAILURE FROM EGYPTAIR RECORDER DATA, SAY
OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With AIRCRASH-EGYPT) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A re-examination of information from the flight
data recorder on EgyptAir Flight 990, from the time of takeoff to
just before the aircraft plunged toward the sea, has uncovered no
sign of a mechanical malfunction, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was ``rock steady,'' said one aviation expert involved
in the case, who, like others, expressed doubt that anything could
have been mechanically wrong with the plane, a 10-year-old Boeing
767, without an indication of some kind on the flight data
recorder, which keeps track of 155 categories of information,
involving dozens of aircraft systems.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of even a hint of an equipment breakdown was the
strongest piece of evidence, according to both aviation
investigators and law enforcement officials, that someone at the
controls of the aircraft may have been responsible for the crash,
deliberately forcing the jet into a steep dive. The crash in the
early morning hours of Oct. 31 killed 217 people, including 106
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   A g official involved in the case said that while the Egyptians
continued to believe that the plane's dive and remarks on the
cockpit voice recorder could be the crew's a rational response to
some mechanical problem with the plane, they had not thus far
proposed a theory of what that problem might have been.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said that a relief pilot whom they
identified as Gameel el-Batouty, was in control of the Boeing 767
as the catastrophic events began to unfold about a half-hour into
the New York to Cairo flight. They said that a cryptic remark he
made that may have been a prayer made them suspect that he
deliberately crashed the plane.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the chairman of the National Transportation Safety
Board, the agency that took over the investigation when Egypt
delegated its responsibility for the inquiry to the United States,
said that the main focus of his agency was to decide whether the
crash has been properly investigated as an accident, or whether it
was a crime and thus the province of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from Cairo arrived in Washington about 1 p.m.
Thursday. But with the contents of the tape now a delicate
diplomatic issue, the NTSB, which is leading the inquiry, made no
official statement and would not even say who the new Egyptian
experts were. A spokesman said he believed there were ``four or
five of them.''
</P>
<P>
   One investigator contrasted the lack of any hint of trouble on
EgyptAir 990 with Swissair Flight 111 disaster, another recent
crash at sea of a big passenger jet with a modern flight data
recorder. In that case, he said, problems were evident from
information picked up on the flight data recorder on the MD-11 long
before the crew radioed for help. The plane crashed off Halifax,
Nova Scotia, on Sept. 2, 1998, killing 229 people.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Justice Department official said Thursday that a
decision about whether to transfer the case to the FBI from
aviation safety officials would probably be made in a few days. The
decision is significant because it would, in effect, declare that
authorities suspect the crash was caused by a criminal act, not a
mechanical malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department official, Eric Holder, , said that while
U.S. officials would coordinate with Egyptian officials, U.S.
authorities would reach their own independent judgments about the
crash. ``We need to have some further discussions with them before
any decisions are ultimately made,'' said Holder, the deputy
attorney general. ``But I would not say anything is contingent upon
the approval of the Egyptian government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
