r a BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX     11-18 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL DRAGGING DEATH DEFENDANT GETS LIFE TERM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Shawn Allen Berry, a 24-year-old cinema manager
and bull rider who said he counted African-Americans among his
friends, on Thursday became the third white man to be convicted of
capital murder in the gruesome dragging death of a disabled black
man.
</P>
<P>
   But Berry was spared the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   An all-white jury, which deliberated about 10 hours over two
days to reach a verdict, took 75 minutes to sentence Berry to life
in prison, meaning he has no chance for parole until he's 64.
</P>
<P>
   The other men convicted in the killing of James Byrd Jr. _
avowed white supremacists John William King Jr., 25, and Lawrence
Russell Brewer Jr., 32 _ were sentenced to death earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got better than Byrd! Rot in hell!'' Ethel Parks of Jasper
shouted as Berry was led in a bulletproof vest to a car that would
take him to prison in Huntsville. At the wheel was Curtis Frame,
the lead investigator at the crime scene after Byrd's decapitated
remains were found dumped at a black church five miles outside this
East Texas town.
</P>
<P>
   Berry stared straight ahead and made no response. In the
courtroom, he turned to his fiancee Christy Marcontell after
hearing the sentence, kissed her full on her lips as she copiously
wept and then let himself be escorted out by sheriff's deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors issued a joint statement saying the verdict was reached
unanimously after ``long hours of painful and prayerful
deliberations.'' In a questionnaire returned to Judge Joe Bob
Golden, they indicated that they did not think that Berry would be
a threat to society when he's eligible for release in 40 years _ a
necessary element to reaching a death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sympathize with his family,'' said Clara Taylor, a sister of
the victim. ``We also lost someone. But their pain was was caused
by what Shawn did.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury was swayed by ``emotionalism'' in the punishment phase,
she said. ``I'm glad it's over, and I accept their verdict. But I
think they shared equally in the crime and should have received the
same sentence,'' Taylor said of Berry.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the third trial could not come too soon for this
timber industry community of 7,100 _ 45 percent black, 55 percent
white _ where life has been unsettled since Byrd's remains were
found on June 7, 1998. There was an evident pride among residents,
black and white, that justice prevailed with all-white jurors in a
racially charged case, one that attracted international notoriety
and revived memories of Old South white-on-black violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that we can start healing,'' said John Matthews, a
white real estate agent whose office is directly across the street
from the century-old courthouse. ``And it establishes that hate
crimes won't be tolerated in Jasper. We've set a precedent for all
East Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry's attorney, Joseph Columbus ``Lum'' Hawthorn of Beaumont,
expressed disappointment with the verdict but said he was happy
that his client did not get the death penalty. Berry will likely
appeal, Hawthorn said, citing Golden's rejection of the last-minute
motion for a change of venue and what Hawthorn said were mistakes
by the judge in jury selection.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen defense witnesses, including
African-Americans, testified that Berry was not a hate-filled
person. District Attorney Guy James Gray several times told the
jury that he did not consider the defendant a racist, instead
arguing that he participated in the torture slaying for the sheer
fun of it. Then Gray produced footprint evidence that, he
contended, showed that only Berry could have driven the pickup when
Byrd was being dragged.
</P>
<P>
   In the punishment phase, Berry cried and asked to be excused
after he listened to a friend describe him as a loving father to a
2-year-old named Montana and as a man who would not be dangerous in
the future. The session briefly adjourned; when it resumed, Berry
returned to his seat between his lawyer and sobbing fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   But at no time did Berry express remorse for Byrd's murder, a
point that the prosecution repeatedly stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Berry was asked on the stand on Thursday if he was remorseful.
At first, instead of answering the question directly, he referred
to a psychiatrist's testimony that a defendant who denies
culpability rarely expresses remorse.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, Berry finally said, ``I feel very sorry for what
happened to Mr. Byrd, and I've said so from Day 1. I wanted to
speak to the Byrd family but couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   To show that Berry did not represent a continuing threat, Berry
testified that he had a black cellmate and was given trusty status
in Jasper County Jail after his arrest as a capital murder suspect.
He was allowed to walk freely to a jail area that leads outside and
even once informed jailers the door was unlocked, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Hardy, an assistant district attorney who is a former karate
champion, thundered the jury in his raspy, high-pitched voice:
``Shawn Allen Berry chose to move in with Bill King. Shawn Berry
chose to pick up Mr. Byrd, chose to take him to a remote area,
chose to chain him like an animal to the back of a pickup and drag
him three miles. He chose to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Byrd did not choose to be left decapitated in front of a
church.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
