r a BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-HISTO     11-18 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-HISTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONFIRE IS THE GRANDADDY OF A&AMP;M TRADITIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE COCHRAN 
and KRISTIN N. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not ``a bonfire'' or ``the bonfire.'' It's Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   It dates to 1909, making it a Texas A&AMP;M tradition older than the
rousing Midnight Yell Practice. Older even that the first official
A&AMP;M mascot, the beloved collie Reveille I.
</P>
<P>
   The autumn blaze symbolizes what half a dozen Aggies described
Thursday as Texas A&AMP;M's ``burning desire to beat the hell out of
t.u.,'' known outside College Station as the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For Aggies, Bonfire is so much more than a football rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Schellenbach Bogle, A&AMP;M Class of '81, stood close to the
fire during her college days and remembers the flames and the
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat is intense,'' the Fort Worth free-lance writer
recalled. ``And it's an emotional thing, I guess because it's the
spirit of something that binds living and dead people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an emotional brotherhood and sisterhood there that
links you with everybody who was ever there and who will ever be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillard Stone felt that spirit. ``It is not an event,'' said the
former Texas A&AMP;M Corps of Cadets deputy commander, now a Fort Worth
financial analyst. ``It's an experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Hub Baker's father felt it. So did Hub, a second generation
Aggie and the general manager of Cowtown Coliseum in Fort Worth.
And now Hub's daughter, a senior speech and communications major,
also feels the spirit.
</P>
<P>
   But for only the second time in 90 years, there will be no
Bonfire this year. The first time was in November 1963, after
President John F. Kennedy was slain on the streets of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   And now, another tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   As 60 to 70 students worked atop the pile early Thursday
preparing the framework for the Thanksgiving blaze, the 40-foot
tower of logs collapsed with a sickening roar, crushing some
students to death and injuring others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like pickup sticks. These logs are all intertwined,''
Bart Humphreys, a College Station Fire Department spokesman, told
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Kristi Holban, alumni relations director at Texas Christian
University in Fort Worth, said A&AMP;M students and alumni ``are
probably stronger in tradition than any school I've seen
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Holban said that dedication to school spirit may stem at least
partly from A&AMP;M's fierce rivalry with UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, their ring is a big deal. When an Aggie sees
another person with a ring on, they will cross the room to
introduce themselves,'' Holban said. ``They are just a strong,
well-connected alumni group.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandra Pate of Fort Worth, who attended A&AMP;M during the
mid-1970s, says the school's strong traditions are linked to its
military roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any of these military schools. Their traditions are
kind of set in stone,'' she said. ``Down there, there's not a patch
of ground that's not sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Obdyke, Class of '67 and president of the Capital City A&AMP;M
Club in Austin, was a freshman in 1963 when Kennedy was shot. He
said he hopes this year's tragedy does not mean the end of Bonfire
because the project has such a unifying effect on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his Bonfire days, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We all participated in some way. The most experienced groups
did the stacking on campus, because it was recognized that it was
hard work and dangerous. The juniors and seniors did the cutting of
the tree with axes or chain saws, and the underclassman carried
those logs out of the woods to the trucks that transported them to
campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety has always been a concern. This is just a tragic
accident...''
</P>
<P>
   Concern over the tradition was mixed with profound grief
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a horrible, horrible thing for all these kids and
their families, and the whole community,'' said Fort Worth attorney
James Creel, a trustee of the A&AMP;M Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even know what caused it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the tragedy renewed a debate over the future of
Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bonfire is not worth one Aggie's life,'' said Lee Bradley,
Class of '61 and director of the Fort Worth Water Department. ``But
it's not a tradition we would like to see go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who once stacked logs for the fire, says he has two
daughters who have worked on the annual project.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling was really for the loss of the kids and their
parents,'' he pointed out. ``I realize it could happen anywhere;
people have car wrecks and die...
</P>
<P>
   ``But you just hate to have it associated with one of the good
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Haltom City lawyer Bill Ray, Class of '81, worked on the bonfire
for five years, helping guard it on occasion and sometimes
struggling to the top to tie logs. The project begins as early as
September, and some say it requires 125,000 hours of student labor.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry traces its roots back nearly a century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when it got started, people who went to A&AMP;M were ranchers
and farmers, the cowboys, because it was cheap,'' Ray said. The
University of Texas ``was looked on more as the upper crust.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hub Baker: ``Every Aggie is heartbroken over this tragedy,
because they all relate to the bonfire. My dad was an Aggie, and
the great stories he told about the camaraderie and the spirit and
the kinship among the students, all these guys working together to
put up that great bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tradition of Bonfire needs to stay at A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   A night or two before the annual UT game, the Aggie Corps of
Cadets traditionally stands at attention as the Fightin' Aggie Band
plays ``The Spirit of Aggieland'' and flames and sparks light up
the darkened sky.
</P>
<P>
   The crowning touch is an orange outhouse perched atop the pile
of logs, placed there by a crane. Constructed and painted by band
members, the outhouse is decorated with signs identifying it as
``t.u. frat house'' and ``Austin City Limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such lightheartedness, Abilene author Glenn Dromgoole, a
former editor of the campus newspaper and the Bryan-College Station
Eagle, says he was concerned for years about the potential for
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid it would start from the bonfire and catch some
houses on fire,'' he said. ``But I never thought, never dreamed,
something like this would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
