<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4491 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-APPELFELD19-COX     11-18 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-APPELFELD19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Conversion': Loss of identity has meaning for Jews
 &HT;    By Joel Engelhardt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEVASSERET ZION, Israel _ Aharon Appelfeld _ round-faced,
balding and professorial _ sits in his pleasant apartment in the
suburban hills outside Jerusalem, and explains in the way of a
grandfather why he writes haunting tales of Jews spurning their
religion in the years before the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his well-regarded novels, ``The Conversion,'' most of
the Jews in an Austrian town have converted to Christianity,
leaving only a small circle of merchants to adhere to the old ways.
Even those who convert will die, however, since the Nazis are still
to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book is about escaping Judaism and how you cannot escape
it,'' Appelfeld says, choosing his words carefully. ``And this is a
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Appelfeld knows tragedy well. As an 8-year-old, he witnessed his
mother's murder during the Holocaust and spent time in a
concentration camp. But his novels aren't full of black-booted
Gestapo. They are set in idyllic European cities and villages long
before or after the threat of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a disintegrated society,'' he says of his
characters. ``They have lost their Jewishness. It has just
evaporated and the young people don't know why they are Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Serious questions hang heavily, like dirty laundry, in the
novels of Appelfeld, 67, whom Newsweek has called a writer worthy
of Nobel Prize consideration:
</P>
<P>
   Can the Holocaust happen in America? Can Jews just decide to
stop being Jews? Is the greatest threat to the Jewish people the
Jewish people themselves?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Conversion,'' in which an adult Jew joins most of his
generation in converting to Christianity but is destroyed by his
lost identity, takes place in turn-of-the-century Europe but, on a
larger level, could be America today. Appelfeld sees in America a
Jewish culture disappearing through its own misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Jews do not face the threat of European Jews. There's
been too much intermarriage. But the threat is that the culture
will disappear _ not totally, but it will shrink. You can see it in
every community,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Conversion'' and ``The Retreat,'' the story of Jews who
remove themselves to a mountain resort to learn to act like
Gentiles, capture that shrinkage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy of the Holocaust is that it came in a moment when
Jewishness was no more dear to Jews,'' Appelfeld says. ``Up to the
end of the 19th century, most (Jews) were ready to sacrifice
themselves for their Jewishness. Then suddenly, the Jew doesn't
want to be a Jew. The community doesn't have meaning. He wants to
be an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 40-plus books, of which 13 have been translated from
Hebrew to English, he writes about the periods before, during and
after the war, a time he calls ``100 years of Jewish loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions he asks mirror the questions the author wrestled
with as he came to grips with a childhood torn by Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   He was the child of urban Jews who forgot they were Jews. They
did not master the prayers or attend services on holy days.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nazis came to Czernovitz, Appelfeld's home city in what
is now part of the Ukraine, they did not take his family's failure
to observe the Sabbath into account. They killed Appelfeld's mother
and sent the 8-year-old boy and his father to separate
concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   He escaped. He survived by denying his identity, first alone,
living in the Ukrainian woods, and then marching through Europe as
a kitchen boy with the Russian army. He snuck into Palestine after
the war, fought for Israel's independence, and found himself in a
new land, with a new language and, by the age of 18, still no
identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came with a lot of terrible experience of the camp and the
ghetto and I wanted to understand what happened to me because I was
too young during the Holocaust,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He attended Hebrew University and only in his early 20s began to
wonder about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disoriented. Not born here. No parents. It was only late
that I began to ask, `Who am I? Where are my parents?'
</P>
<P>
   ``These existential questions became the drive of my writing.''
</P>
<P>
   He began publishing his novels in the early 1960s but his work
was not translated to English until 1980 with ``Badenheim 1939,''
the story of what happens to people when their summer resort is
converted to a prison ghetto under the efficient watch of a
faceless bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Appelfeld creates an absorbing world of idiosyncratic,
self-absorbed types, but draws his characters through
understatement. His writing is clear. His ideas are wrapped in
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rule is always less is more,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He writes at home, at a desk in his basement study, for five to
six hours a day. ``If you can sit everyday five to six hours in
front of a blank page, you are a writer,'' he says. ``It's a lot of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiles when told his Spartan style reveals a debt to
Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to say something, say it. If you don't, don't say
it. And it should be understandable. Every sentence should be
understandable. Writing is not fog. It should be transparent.''
</P>
<P>
   He will retire next year after 25 years as professor of Jewish
literature at Ben Gurion University, a 90-minute bus ride from his
home.
</P>
<P>
   He is working on a new novel, as yet untitled, and he won't
reveal its plot. But it is sure to raise questions.
</P>
<P>
   Appelfeld won't go as far as to say the Holocaust could happen
again, in America. But his novels won't let readers forget that it
happened once, and the victims living their lives didn't see the
signs, didn't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Staff researcher Dorothy Shea contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
