<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-STORM19-COX     11-18 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-STORM19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powerful vision force behind `Issac's Storm'
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ This book goes on the shelf alongside
``The Perfect Storm,'' each as powerful as the storms described on
their pages, each an outstanding example of the rather odd modern
publishing phenomenon _ the nonfiction weather disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The true power and terrible beauty of ``The Perfect Storm'' was
contained in its human drama: men against nature, against God even,
the story of hubris and folly and technology, all humbled before
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, with ``Isaac's Storm,'' the story of Isaac Cline, a
weatherman stationed in Galveston, Texas, in September 1900. That
was the month and year the deadliest hurricane in history scrubbed
Galveston and 6,000 of its residents from the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas few of us will ever find ourselves aboard a Gloucester
fishing boat north of Nova Scotia, as in ``The Perfect Storm,''
many of us live in hurricane alley. Even as the monster Floyd
approached in September, even as TV forecasters spoke in terms of
Category 4, we lacked a true sense of the power of these storms.
Few have lived through a big storm. Even Andrew was a tight little
fury, localized.
</P>
<P>
   The TV-news video camera can do its job well both before and
after a storm. But action shots of bending palm trees in the
gathering storm do not convey the fury of sustained winds of 150
mph, with gusts up to 200. Conditions during a storm of such
hideous magnitude are so dangerous there can be no action shots.
Only word-of-mouth recollections and reflections, survivors' tales
in the hands of a masterful writer can convey the terror.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what Erik Larson does in ``Isaac's Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm hit Galveston during the afternoon of Saturday, Sept.
8, 1900. But it might as well have been midnight; Galveston was
caught sleeping. What followed was an event that had been waiting
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The new National Weather Service, of which Isaac Cline was a
charter member, had grown out of the U.S. Army Signal Corps. In
1882, somebody had decided that knowing the weather would be of
military value. Isaac Cline signed on. By 1900, the country was
full of itself, full of faith in science and technology. There was
even blindly optimistic talk of changing the weather, harnessing
nature.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, Galveston had grown to a city of more than
30,000, occupying a barrier island between the Gulf of Mexico and
Galveston Bay. Galveston's highest point was just 9 feet above sea
level. But optimism reigned supreme when it came to tides and
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Even in 1899, when a northeast storm blew the water out of
Galveston Bay, no one deduced that southeast winds could blow the
Gulf of Mexico into the bay, over the city. All was right on the
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sept. 8, 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the storm had been forwarded to Galveston by Cuban
weather-watchers. But, in tune with the times, U.S. weather
forecasters dismissed the Cuban warnings, not because of any
perceived fault in data but because the warning had come from Cuba,
which was thought a lesser place where lesser minds dwelled. The
shallow pride of manifest destiny had a hand in Galveston's death.
</P>
<P>
   As the waves increased, so, too, did Isaac Cline's concern.
While tourists and children played in the Gulf surf, Cline began
warning anyone who would listen. At first, few did. Barometers were
scarce, understanding of the instruments scarcer still. The water
rose. The wind rose.
</P>
<P>
   Larson has scoured old first-person accounts, telegrams,
testimony before Washington committees. He doesn't have to
embellish recollections with speculations on what people might have
been thinking. The facts speak _ scream _ for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Galveston had built strong houses, capable of
withstanding hurricane winds. But when rising waters floated these
houses from their foundations, they made terrible boats. The
recollections of families who spent the night of Sept. 8 lashed to
their beds and chimneys as their homes crashed down around them are
as terrifying as anything in print.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes, chapter by chapter, hour by hour. Death by
death. Ninety orphans died when nuns tethered them together in
lifelines. The lines became tangled, the children drowned.
Eighty-five passengers on a train elected to stay aboard as the
water rose. They thought nothing could blow a locomotive over. They
were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   And Isaac Cline, along with his brother and children and wife,
suffered their own form of divine punishment. Even those who were
spared were not spared. The book's section on the cleanup, the
burning of bodies, the smell of death, should be read while wearing
a surgical mask and gloves. Photos of the destruction exist, but
Eric Larson makes a word worth a thousand pictures.
</P>
<P>
   This is a book every Floridian should own. Keep it wrapped in
plastic, because if a hurricane of Floyd's ferocity ever hits, it
might be all that remains.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
