<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-WEASEL19-COX     11-18 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WEASEL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another fast-paced, bluntly told killer thriller
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In his latest assault on the forests of
America, James Patterson attempts to channel Hannibal Lecter. With
Geoffrey Shafer, a minor British diplomat/spy posted in Washington,
D.C., Patterson creates yet another audacious evil genius who gets
away with things that might not be so easily replicated in life as
they are on the page.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Harris is a baroque, rather entertaining stylist,
whereas Patterson is a straight-ahead crafter of basic declarative
sentences. This is not in itself a major problem; that comes with
Patterson's concept for Shafer. In a word, he's too obvious _ not
the suave, controlling psychopath that is Lecter, but an erratic,
sweaty, fullbore loon zoned out of his skull on all manner of
mood-altering drugs courtesy of his shrink, with whom he's having a
thankfully undramatized S&AMP;M relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Shafer is entirely too ragged to successfully navigate home and
career while maintaining a burgeoning career as a serial killer
spawned by a computer game. Also, Shafer's modus operandi is
borderline comic _ he dresses up in blackface and goes out in his
gypsy cab to murder people _ a homicidal Al Jolson.
</P>
<P>
   The accoutrements of Patterson's plot are modern, but actually
it's a variation on the old Richard Connell short story ``The Most
Dangerous Game,'' in which a big-game hunter goes daffy and decides
to hunt the biggest game of all _ man.
</P>
<P>
   Across the aisle from Shafer is Patterson's Good Cop, Alex
Cross, who is, not to mince words, a little dull. Without Morgan
Freeman to shade him in, there's nothing particularly interesting
about him. He's just a good, honest, hard-working cop, without any
leaps of deductive brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson keeps the pot boiling not by introducing plot twists
from left field but by doing double reverses with his already
established characters.
</P>
<P>
   His storytelling is blunt, at times reminiscent of the lurid
thrills of Sax Rohmer and Mickey Spillane _ as much typographical
as linguistic: ``An agent at the FBI had investigated the e-mail
address and found that it didn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   And he tends to tell us things rather than show them, as in this
brief recapitulation of Cross talking about his murdered wife:
``We'd been married four years and had two small children. The case
has never been solved and that's what still tortures me. Maybe
that's what drives me to solve every case I can, no matter the
odds.''
</P>
<P>
   A less courageous writer, having killed off Cross' wife in a
previous book, might want to lay off putting his fiancee in peril _
really, what are the odds? _ but Patterson boldly plows ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the basic storytelling function, the key to
Patterson's success is pace _ one damn thing or another is always
happening, in a nonstop succession of very short chapters (``Pop
Goes the Weasel'' has 123 of them).
</P>
<P>
   Although Patterson's books are, on the surface, pitch-perfect
beach reads, he has successfully managed to transcend that category
and become a brand-name writer, hence the fall publication date,
suitable for gift-giving ... assuming, of course, that your idea of
a gift involves multiple murders via throat-slitting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
