<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-AID-1STLD     11-18 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-AID-1STLD-WRITETHRU-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CHECHEN WAR IN BACKGROUND, U.S. DELIBERATES CURBING AID TO
RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs to delete `Jr.' after George W. Bush in 8th graf; no other
changes) 
(With EUROPE-TALKS) 
(js) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration is quietly reassessing
whether to slow two major loan programs to Moscow as the war in
Chechnya accelerates and the two leading candidates for the
Republican presidential nomination call for a cutoff of aid to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In public, White House officials have said that they continue to
favor modest economic support for the Yeltsin government and that
termination of the aid could further destabilize Russia before two
major elections there. Sandy Berger, the national security adviser,
reiterated that position on Monday when he told reporters that
despite the Russian military offensive in Chechnya, it would not
``make sense for us to affect'' a forthcoming loan from the
International Monetary Fund, ``assuming the economic and
transparency criteria are met.''
</P>
<P>
   But within the administration, divisions on the question are
growing; advocates of both views say there is a movement to go slow
on two major loans _ one from the International Monetary Fund and
another from the Export-Import Bank of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a debate brewing in our government over
engagement versus disengagement for a year now,'' one senior
administration official said Thursday. ``But in recent weeks it has
gotten much more intense, and there are some strong voices for
disengagement.''
</P>
<P>
   The first issue is whether the United States should allow the
International Monetary Fund to release a long-delayed payment of
$640 million to keep Russia from defaulting on past monetary fund
loans. The money, part of a $4.5 billion program, would actually
never enter Russia; it would simply be transferred from one IMF
account to another.
</P>
<P>
   But its delivery would take economic pressure off Russia's
central bank, which officials in several departments of the
administration fear could send a political message that Moscow will
not have to pay a price for its continued military action in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say that they are making the decision
on the merits, and are ignoring the political impact on Vice
President Al Gore, who played a major role in the development of
the administration's economic support program for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's staff appears increasingly worried about his
vulnerability on the issues, especially because Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, the Republican front-runner, has said he will call for a
complete cutoff of the aid to Russia in a foreign policy speech he
is expected to deliver on Friday. And Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
Bush's leading challenger for the nomination, has already opposed
the loan while the war in Chechnya continues.
</P>
<P>
   An even bigger issue is the Export-Import Bank loan, a half a
billion dollars for the export of U.S.-made oil equipment to
Russia. Unlike the monetary fund loan, this money would come
directly from an agency of the U.S. government. Again, it would not
go directly to Moscow but rather to U.S. companies supplying
Russian oil companies with equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it would constitute the first resumption of direct
U.S. aid to Moscow in more than a year, and officials say the
semi-independent Export-Import Bank has come under pressure from
the administration to put the loan on ``administrative hold,''
perhaps for a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   In both instances the administration is making the case that, at
the moment, the loans should be slowed for economic reasons that
have nothing to do with Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   That enables it to avoid the question of whether it should seek
to cut off the money as an act of political protest over the
Chechen military campaign, as it did to Indonesia during the
violence in East Timor earlier this year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the case of the monetary fund loan, lengthy negotiations with
Russia have yet to resolve some issues of ``transparency'' _ public
explanations of how Russia is spending money and regulating its
banks. The fund is insisting, for example, that Russia commit to a
public audit of Sberbank, a major bank owned by the government, and
make a series of amendments to its bankruptcy laws, among other
demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time Russia has not met the economic criteria,'' said
one senior administration official deeply involved in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But asked whether Russia's behavior in Chechnya would be
considered in coming weeks, the official added, ``These things are
always complex and there is a desire to maintain flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two Export-Import Bank loans pending, both of which
have received preliminary approval from the bank's board of
directors and were referred to Congress for a 30-day review period,
now complete. The board is now free to approve the loans whenever
it feels ready. But that moment still seems weeks or months away,
and could be longer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the deals involves $203 million in financing for the sale
of equipment and services by ABB Lummus Global Inc., a Bloomfield,
N.J., company, to update the Ryazan Oil Refinery near Moscow. The
second is $292 million in financing for exports by Halliburton Co.,
of Dallas, to rehabilitate the Samotlar oil field.
</P>
<P>
   The loans were controversial before the Chechen fighting because
the Russian company that will benefit, Tyumen Oil Co., is a player
in a complex takeover effort that involved the bankruptcy of
another oil company. The European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development, 10 percent controlled by the U.S. government, is a
major creditor of the bankrupt company.
</P>
<P>
   The European Bank has been involved in a long-running dispute
involving Tyumen. The case has already been in the Russian courts,
and it has involved charges that the bankruptcy was manipulated by
Russian oligarchs. Because of the on-going dispute, some
administration officials have argued against aiding Tyumen.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
