Project Vantage, basis for the new Aston Martin DB7 Vantage - a
svelte coupe ($140,000) or convertible ($150,000) with undeniably
firm muscle tone, thanks to a mighty 6-liter V12 engine that pumps
out 420 horsepower. The DB7's six-cylinder engine - adapted from a
Jaguar design - is still available, but Aston Martin's future
revolves around the new V12 and its future derivatives. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ASTON-MARTIN-1, 11-18 -- A
DB7 Vantage Volante. Inset, Bob Dover, Aston Martin's chairman.
Ford's strategy is to turn Aston Martin into a globally recognized
British alternative to Ferrari. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 21
-- BIZ-MICROSOFT-TV, 11-18 -- Using the Microsoft WebTV remote
control, Tim Tainter clicks on answers on his TV screen to play
``Jeopardy'' against other home players. Analysts say
point-and-click simplicity explains how interactive television,
after a history of spectacular flops, may finally be poised to take
off in prime time. (Marissa Roth/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BLOOMINGTON, Minn. -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
NOV. 21 --BIZ-FOR-ME, 11-18 -- Sharon and Don Storholm have
developed a thriving business with the Executive Auto Desk,
designed to eliminate chaotic conditions for people who work in
their cars. ``I never wanted to be an inventor,'' says Mr.
Storholm. ``This one is the first and the last.'' (Steve Woit/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 11-18 --
Frances Conroy, left, Patrick Stewart and Meg Gibson in Arthur
Miller's ``Ride Down Mount Morgan'' in 1998 at the Public Theater.
Stewart says his return to Broadway is a testament to his
inordinate love for the play and its central character, Lyman Felt.
``Arthur has created a wonderful and complex leading character,''
he says. ``It's musical and emotional and expressive, and very,
very funny.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PORTLAND, Ore. -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV.
21 -- EARTHQUAKE-RISK, 11-18 -- Charles Geoffroy, the retired
advertising and retailing executive, lived in a seven-bedroom house
on a hillside for years without earthquake insurance. But he and
his wife, Alida, added quake insurance when they moved into a
condominium on the edge of the Willamette River in Oregon. (Shane
Young/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- LIVING-WAGE-LAWS, 11-18
-- Madeline Janis-Aparicio, director of the Los Angeles Living Wage
Coalition, cites the failure of Washington to raise the national
minimum wage to keep pace with the needs of the working poor. The
coalition, an amalgam of community groups, churches and unions, is
out to redress the balance. ``We need to build union agreements
that have community support and will last,'' she says. (Kim
Kulish/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) TANGIERS, Morocco -- Nov. 18, 1999 -OBIT-BOWLES-2, 11-18
-- Paul Bowles in his Tangier's apartment in March, 1998. Bowles,
the American author of ``The Sheltering Sky'' who was known for
taking in literary and artistic figures at his adopted home of
Tangiers, died Thursday. He was 88. (Rikard Westman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1999 - OBIT-BOWLES-B&AMP;W, 11-18 --
Paul Bowles at the Mayfair Hotel in New York in 1995. on Sept. 17,
1995. Bowles, the American author of ``The Sheltering Sky'' who was
known for taking in literary and artistic figures at his adopted
home of Tangiers, died Thursday. He was 88. (David Corio/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 18, 1999 - SPEND-CONGRESS, 11-18 --
Members of the staff of Democratic Senators review the federal
appropriations bill in Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle's office
on Thursday. The White House and Republican leaders in Congress,
grappling for political advantage, agreed in principle to an
across-the-board spending cut of about $1.3 billion, and met this
afternoon to seal a final budget deal. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- Nov. 17, 1999 -- AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS, 11-17 --
Edward Lu, 3, takes a liking to the new Lexus IS due out in July
2000. Other attendees at the New England International Auto Show
study some of its more practical features. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Nov. 17, 1999 --
BIOTECH-CHALLENGE-BOS, 11-17 -- Dr. Richard F. Selden, the founder
and president of Transkaryotic Therapies, watches as Douglas Treco,
senior vice president of research and development, studies a
speciem in a microscope. ``We started as a gene-therapy company and
knew it would take as much as 15 years to get a product to market,
so we knew we needed other products to provide us with revenue, and
our EPO will be our first,'' says Selden. EPO is an anti-anemia
drug, erythropoietin, which is expected to generate $1.8 billion in
sales this year. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 21 --
PRICE-THEATER, 11-18 -- From left, Bob Dishy, Jeffrey DeMunn,
Harris Yulin and Lizbeth Mackay in ``The Price'' at the Royale
Theater. ``Though I saw the original production of Arthur Miller's
'The Price' with Pat Hingle and Arthur Kennedy as the brothers, I
have no memory of being as moved and as peculiarly cheered by it as
I was by the current production,'' writes Vincent Canby. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 21 --
TOGETHER-THEATER, 11-18 -- Carol Burnett and Ruthie Henshall
rehearsing ``Putting It Together,'' a collection of songs from
various Sondheim shows staged as a fugue of relationships. The new
production opens Sunday night on Broadway. ``It's not a walk in the
park,'' says Ms. Burnett. ``But Sondheim never is. The music is
hard to learn and attention must be paid to his lyrics. He's always
surprising you.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- Nov. 17, 1999 -- BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS, 11-17
-- Cleveland Cavaliers Shawn Kept leans out as Paul Pierce of the
Boston Celtics looks to pass to an open teammate. The 6-foot-7-inch
guard, who is just 23, helped the Celtics beat the Cavs, 114-103.
He finished with 30 points, 11 rebounds, 4 assists, 4 steals and 7
turnovers. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 21 --
HOFFMAN-FILMS, 11-18 -- Philip Seymour Hoffman on Gansevoort Street
in Manhattan, near his home. Standout work in films such as
``Boogie Nights'' and ``Happiness'' has placed Hoffman on the
precipice of stardom. But the 32-year-old actor seems hesitant to
embrace the possibility of becoming the next big thing. ``I don't
want to assume anything,'' he says. ``I don't even want to assume
that people will like what I've done.'' (Jack Manning/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- KATE-THEATER-REVIEW, 11-18
-- Brushing up their Shakespeare: From left, Michael Berresse,
Marin Mazzie, Brian Stokes Mitchell and Amy Spanger in the revival
of the Cole Porter musical ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' which opened last
night at the Martin Beck Theater. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1999 - GULBENKIAN-COLLECTION, 11-18
-- Rene Lalique's ``Serpents Brooch,'' which will be on display at
the Metropolitan Museum of Art as part of an exhibit from the
collection of Calouste Gulbenkian. The exhibit will contain
extraordinary examples of Islamic and Turkish textiles and
ceramics, 18th-century silver, European painting and Lalique's Art
Nouveau jewelry of Lalique. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 18, 1999 - ADV. FOR SUN, NOV. 21 --
GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN-COX, 11-18 -- John Koskinen, chairman of the
President's Council on Y2K. Koskinen's consuming mission is to
educate every American about Y2K, the software flaw that exists
because many older computer programs and chips recognize only the
last two digits of the year. When 2000 arrives, those computers may
misinterpret ``00'' as 1900 and cause equipment malfunctions. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1999 - FOOD-MINIMAL-COX, 11-18 --
With only a week left until T-Day, you're cutting it close if
you're still thinking of preparing a full-fledged,
made-from-scratch feast. By combining recipes with just a few
ingredients, you can orchestrate a wonderful meal with elegance and
ease. And at holidays especially, it keeps you from getting
overwhelmed. (William Berry/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
