<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 11/18/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 18, 1999 - CONGRESS-PORK, 11-18 --
Sen. Ted Stevens, chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee,
center, puts his arm around Pete Domenici, the Senate Budget
Committee chairman, while talking to reporters about the
negotiations over the federal budget on Tuesday. Bolstered by a fat
economy and nifty surpluses, this year's federal budget promises to
set new records in Congress when it comes to using taxpayer money
for things like tracking volcanic ash in Alaska, counting walruses,
fixing YMCA swimming pools and studying wood. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) CHICAGO -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- SCI-BIOTECH-FDA, 11-18 --
Dr. Phillip Michaels, left, talks with other panelists before a
public meeting organized by the Food and Drug Administration on
Thursday. The FDA, while maintaining that its policy regarding
bioengineered foods is safe, opened the first of three public
meetings today and was greeted with both heated criticism and
staunch support of genetically engineered products. (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) ANDERSON TOWNSHIP, Ohio -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., NOV. 21 -- INVEST-WITH-FOLKER, 11-18 -- Steven E. Folker
seeks to invest his fund in large-capitalization, high-quality
growth companies. ``We want companies that historically have been
able to consistently grow their earnings at above-average rates,''
says Folker, shown having a quick dinner with his wife, Jennifer.
(Mark Lyons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) EAST SELKIRK, Manitoba -- Nov. 18, 1999 --
CANADA-WOMEN-PAY, 11-18 -- Bev Austen will benefit from a sweeping
pay equity settlement with the Canadian government. ``This is a big
win for us,'' says the 51-year-old immigration clerk of what may be
the largest such settlement in North American history, wherein
Canada's government agreed late last month to pay about $2.3
billion to 230,000 past and present federal workers, overwhelmingly
women. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 21 --
WEB-EXECS-ROUNDTABLE, 11-18 -- From left, Kevin O'Connor of
DoubleClick, an online advertising network; Fernando J. Espuelas of
StarMedia Network, a Spanish- and Portuguese-language service;
Candice Carpenter of iVillage, a women's Web site; and Stephan J.
Paternot of Theglobe.com, a shopping, news and business information
site. They gathered earlier this month at The New York Times for a
wide-ranging discussion about managing in the Internet age.
(Richard Perry/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) COLLEGE STATION, Texas -- Nov. 18, 1999 --
SUB-BONFIRE-COLLAPSE-2, 11-18 -- Rescue workers search for victims
after a pyramid of logs collapsed Thursday killing at least nine
students. The 40-foot tower erected for Texas A&AMP;M's traditional
football bonfire came roaring down early Thursday, crushing the
students to death and injuring 28 others. (David Kennedy/Austin
American Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) COLLEGE STATION, Texas -- Nov. 18, 1999 --
SUB-BONFIRE-COLLAPSE-1, 11-18 -- Rescue workers and students
console each Thursday in front of a pyramid of logs which collapsed
killing at least nine students. The 40-foot tower of logs erected
for Texas A&AMP;M's traditional football bonfire came roaring down
early Thursday, crushing the students to death and injuring 28
others. (David Kennedy/Austin American Statesman) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) HOTENSLEBEN, Germany -- Nov. 18, 1999 --
GERMANY-RECONCILE-2-B&AMP;W, 11-18 -- The Jaeckels ran a store in
Hotensleben, until they were deported to Auschwitz, where they were
killed. Reinhold Jaeckel - in his mother's arms, his father at far
left, in a 1908 photo - filed a claim for family property in 1990,
after the fall of the Berlin Wall made possible a search for truth
and reconciliation. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) JERUSALEM -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- GERMANY-RECONCILE-1, 11-18
-- Joram Jaeckel, 53, places a stone on the newly erected tombstone
of his father's grave. Jaeckel's grandparents, owners of a textile
store in the Hotensleben, Germany, were banished from history
between 1945 and 1989.(Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- SATELLITE-TV,
11-18 -- Paul Falla, who installs satellite dishes for Planet TV,
adjusts a customer's dish in this 1998 file photo. Bowing to an
objection by Senator Phil Gram, R-Texas, the House passed a
hard-fought bill that gives satellite television companies the
right to air local television channels, assuring that cable
companies will soon have a dose of competition. (Richard L.
Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) HOLLYWOOD -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- DIGITAL-FILM-2, 11-18 --
Saffron Burrows as Miss Julie and Peter Mullan as Jean in Mike
Figgis' 1999 film ``Miss Julie.'' Figgis, a British director best
known for the Oscar-winning ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' is at the very
least extraordinarily ambitious, some might say audacious, about
exploiting the digital technologies that are beginning to seep into
the Hollywood mainstream. (MGM/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) HOLLYWOOD -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- DIGITAL-FILM, 11-18 --
Film director Mike Figgis on the set of a feature length movie he
is shooting with hand-held video cameras in real time without cuts.
Figgis, a British director best known for the Oscar-winning
``Leaving Las Vegas,'' is at the very least extraordinarily
ambitious, some might say audacious, about exploiting the digital
technologies that are beginning to seep into the Hollywood
mainstream. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- KOHL-PROFILE, 11-18 -
Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wisc., during an interview on Thursday. Kohl is
objecting to a dairy provision in the final spending bill of the
year. Kohl says that under pressure from lawmakers from the East,
congressional leaders stuck a section in the final spending bill
that would prevent the Agriculture Department from putting a new
milk pricing system into effect and allow New England states to
maintain a cartel that keeps the price of milk there artificially
high keeping out milk from other states. This works to the
disadvantage of dairy farmers in Wisconsin. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) COLTS NECK, N.J. -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- BROKER-DEATHS,
11-18 - Members of a police forensics team arrives with
investigative equipment to the home of Albert Alain Chalem where he
and his business partner were found shot to death last month.
According to police Chalem and his partner Maier Lehmann were
involved in a business that promoted stocks over the Internet.
(Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) ATLANTA -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- BUSH-FOREIGN-POLICY, 11-18
-- Gov. George Bush of Texas during a campaign appearance in
August. His staff's principle mission these last few days has been
to prepare the finishing touches on a foreign policy speech that
Bush is scheduled to give on Friday. But an equally important goal
is the ongoing education of Bush on international affairs; a
subject which has given him the most trouble in his campaign for
the Republican presidential nomination. (Rick McKay/Cox News
Service)
