park,'' says Ms. Burnett. ``But Sondheim never is. The music is
hard to learn and attention must be paid to his lyrics. He's always
surprising you.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- Nov. 17, 1999 -- BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS, 11-17
-- Cleveland Cavaliers Shawn Kept leans out as Paul Pierce of the
Boston Celtics looks to pass to an open teammate. The 6-foot-7-inch
guard, who is just 23, helped the Celtics beat the Cavs, 114-103.
He finished with 30 points, 11 rebounds, 4 assists, 4 steals and 7
turnovers. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 21 --
HOFFMAN-FILMS, 11-18 -- Philip Seymour Hoffman on Gansevoort Street
in Manhattan, near his home. Standout work in films such as
``Boogie Nights'' and ``Happiness'' has placed Hoffman on the
precipice of stardom. But the 32-year-old actor seems hesitant to
embrace the possibility of becoming the next big thing. ``I don't
want to assume anything,'' he says. ``I don't even want to assume
that people will like what I've done.'' (Jack Manning/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1999 -- KATE-THEATER-REVIEW, 11-18
-- Brushing up their Shakespeare: From left, Michael Berresse,
Marin Mazzie, Brian Stokes Mitchell and Amy Spanger in the revival
of the Cole Porter musical ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' which opened last
night at the Martin Beck Theater. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1999 - GULBENKIAN-COLLECTION, 11-18
-- Rene Lalique's ``Serpents Brooch,'' which will be on display at
the Metropolitan Museum of Art as part of an exhibit from the
collection of Calouste Gulbenkian. The exhibit will contain
extraordinary examples of Islamic and Turkish textiles and
ceramics, 18th-century silver, European painting and Lalique's Art
Nouveau jewelry of Lalique. (Metropolitan Museum of Art/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 18, 1999 - ADV. FOR SUN, NOV. 21 --
GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN-COX, 11-18 -- John Koskinen, chairman of the
President's Council on Y2K. Koskinen's consuming mission is to
educate every American about Y2K, the software flaw that exists
because many older computer programs and chips recognize only the
last two digits of the year. When 2000 arrives, those computers may
misinterpret ``00'' as 1900 and cause equipment malfunctions. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1999 - FOOD-MINIMAL-COX, 11-18 --
With only a week left until T-Day, you're cutting it close if
you're still thinking of preparing a full-fledged,
made-from-scratch feast. By combining recipes with just a few
ingredients, you can orchestrate a wonderful meal with elegance and
ease. And at holidays especially, it keeps you from getting
overwhelmed. (William Berry/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
