<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4501 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PUC-PUC_SFCHRON &LR;      11-18 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pac Bell to Raise Home Rate on Information Calls  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Pacific Bell can almost double the cost of calling 411 from a
residential phone, state regulators voted yesterday.
<P>
   Despite receiving 42,000 messages from citizens mostly opposed
to the rate increase, the state Public Utilities Commission allowed
Pac Bell to raise the charge for local directory assistance from 25
cents to 46 cents per call. The board voted down a compromise plan
to allow a charge of 35 cents per call.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell also will slice the number of free 411 calls for
residential customers from five to three per month and eliminate
the two free 411 calls per month given to business customers.
</P>
<P>
   And the cost of checking to see whether a line is busy will jump
from 50 cents to $1.20, while the charge for interrupting a call in
an emergency will rise from $1 to $1.25.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell plans to put the new rates into effect in two to four
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates said they would appeal the PUC decision,
which they said would put an extra $100 million in annual revenues
into Pac Bell's coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sellout to Pac Bell,'' said Thomas J. Long, an attorney
for The Utility Reform Network, a San Francisco ratepayer advocacy
group. ``They're putting $100 million on the backs of captive
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   And Commissioner Joel Hyatt, who voted against the proposal,
called the increase ``outrageous,'' saying directory assistance is
a vital service for millions of Californians, especially with the
proliferation of new area codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're about to do is absolutely, intolerably
unacceptable,'' said Hyatt when it became clear the commission
would vote 3-to-2 in favor of the 411 increase, the first in 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Directory assistance is part of basic local telephone
service,'' he said. ``I believe millions of Californians rely on
directory assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote capped a heated debate that began in May 1998 when Pac
Bell asked to raise the directory assistance rate to 50 cents
immediately and by as much as $1.10 per call as needed. The company
also asked permission to charge $2 for each busy-line verification
call and $4 for each emergency interruption.
</P>
<P>
   The phone company said it was just trying to recoup the money it
loses providing those services. Including labor and equipment
costs, directory assistance costs Pac Bell an average of 48 cents
per call, said spokesman John Britton.
</P>
<P>
   TURN disputed Pac Bell's estimate, saying its analysis showed
that the company was spending just 25 cents for each 411 call.
</P>
<P>
   And Commissioner Henry Duque said a PUC analysis found that Pac
Bell was spending 39 cents per call.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Hot Topic
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been a hot-button topic for California consumers.
Duque noted the PUC has received 42,000 calls and letters ``and few
of them said, `Please raise our rates and prices.'''
</P>
<P>
   In August, a state administrative law judge recommended capping
411 rates at 50 cents per call, which consumer advocates complained
was still too high.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC approved a compromise offered by Duque to allow a
21-cent per call increase, which would still make directory
assistance in California the third lowest of any state in the
country. &UR;  &LR; Long-distance companies such as MCI and Sprint charge
about $1 for each local directory assistance call.
</P>
<P>
   Duque defended the application to raise rates as necessary to
maintain the quality of directory assistance service and to help
ensure that he 1,800 jobs of operators, who handle 411 calls in
California, are not shipped to other states or handed over to
machines.
</P>
<P>
   According to Duque, about 80 percent of customers make three or
fewer 411 calls per month, so they would not be affected by the
rate change.
</P>
<P>
   ``No price lower than 46 cents is reasonable,'' Duque said.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Carl Wood offered an alternative that would have
capped the charge at 35 cents per 411 call and kept the number of
free calls at five per month for residential customers.
</P>
<P>
   Wood argued that the PUC was acting under the assumption that
411 callers were mostly ``lazy yuppies who don't want to go to the
phone book to look up a number.''
</P>
<P>
   The PUC had no firm demographic information available, but Wood
said there was enough anecdotal evidence that 411 callers are
mostly people with limited English reading skills or those who have
are visually impaired.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, ``with the proliferation of new area codes, more
and more customers are going to find it necessary to access this
service.''
</P>
<P>
   The final vote pitted the three commission members _ Duque,
Josiah Neeper and Richard Bilas _ appointed by former Gov. Pete
Wilson against the two new members appointed by Gov. Gray Davis _
Hyatt and Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Hyatt also joined a 4-to-1 vote against Wood's compromise,
saying that alternative did not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   The final outcome did please seven directory assistance
operators in the audience representing their union, the
Communication Workers of America, even though there were still no
job guarantees in the PUC decision or their own collective
bargaining agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to allow us to do better in our jobs as well as
keep us in California,'' said Jeff Downey, a 14-year veteran 411
operator.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC vote does not affect directory assistance calls from pay
phones. Those rates are regulated by the Federal Communications
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
