<HEADER>
A4502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      11-18 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: MITTERRAND DOCTOR DISHONORED
</P>
<P>
   The personal doctor of former President Francois Mitterrand has
been stripped of two of France's highest honors, the Legion of
Honor and the National Merit Order, for revealing in a book that
Mitterrand had hidden his cancer from the public for years before
he died in 1996. Dr. Claude Gubler, 65, had already lost his
medical license for writing the book, which was quickly taken off
the shelves for violating the medical oath of secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: TRACING NAZI ROOTS
</P>
<P>
   Germans born under the Nazi breeding program to create a master
race will now be able to see their files and trace their roots.
Under the project, women deemed to fit the ideals of the German
race were mated with selected men. The babies were then given to
adoptive parents or sent to orphanages if they did not meet the
racist criteria. The records of some 1,000 children in Berlin
archives could help them identify their parents.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: SLAVE LABOR WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Germany warned against putting more pressure on German companies
to raise their share of compensation to Nazi-era forced laborers
after a $4.3 billion offer was rejected by American negotiators.
Otto Lambsdorff, the government's top negotiator, said the latest
bid could not be improved.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: `RED KEN' TO RUN
</P>
<P>
   Ken Livingstone, who as leader of the Greater London Council in
the 1980s was known as ``Red Ken'' for his left-wing policies,
emerged as a viable candidate in the London mayoral race when the
Labor Party added him to its three-person short list. Livingstone
will compete with the former actress and transport secretary,
Glenda Jackson, and Frank Dobson, the former health secretary, for
the chance to run against the Conservatives' candidate, the
novelist and politician Jeffrey Archer.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: NEW UNIVERSITY CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   Health Minister Juan Ramon de la Fuente resigned to become
rector of the National Autonomous University. The previous rector,
Francisco Barnes, resigned after failing to resolve a student
strike, provoked by a modest tuition increase, which since April
has paralyzed the university, Latin America's largest institution
of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: SPACE ACCORD
</P>
<P>
   In a major advance for Brazil's space program, Ukraine and
Brazil have signed an accord that calls for Ukraine to begin
launching commercial satellites from equatorial Maranhao State by
2001. Ukrainian authorities plan to put up as many as 12 rockets a
year over the 10-year period of the agreement from the launching
pad Brazil has been using for its own satellite program and other
clients.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: TOUGH GUN LAW
</P>
<P>
   Striving to send a strong message to violent criminals,
President Thabo Mbeki's cabinet approved strict gun-control
legislation. The legislation, which must be approved by Parliament,
would allow the government to declare some people unfit to carry
firearms, require gun owners to reapply for licenses at least every
five years and create gun-free zones, including bars and
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: `OIL FOR FOOD' PROGRAM
</P>
<P>
   Unable to agree on a resolution continuing the Iraqi ``oil for
food'' program in its present form for another six months, the
United Nations Security Council is likely to roll over the existing
resolution for two weeks, diplomats said. Council members say the
program may be dealt with at the same time that the full council
debate begins on setting up a new arms inspection system in coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: U.S. ATTACKS
</P>
<P>
   An American Navy FA-18 from the aircraft carrier John F. Kennedy
attacked a radar site in southern Iraq. Officials said the strike,
near Basra, was a response to Iraq's violation of the ``no flight''
zone the day before, when three fighter jets darted into the zone
and quickly left.
</P>
</TEXT>
