<SLUG> BC-AGILENT-AGILENT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Spin-Off Gives HP, Dow a Jolt  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hewlett-Packard shareholders enjoyed a $13.6 billion bonanza
yesterday, thanks to an unexpectedly favorable earnings report and
the rousingly successful initial public offering of the company's
Agilent subsidiary.
<P>
   The Palo Alto computer-maker, with more than 1 billion shares
outstanding, soared $13.31 to $94.31 in New York Stock Exchange
trading _ its highest close in more than seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   HP's performance sparked a strong surge in the overall market,
with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index climbing 14.23 to a record
1,424.94 and the Nasdaq composite index also hitting a new record _
up 77.72 at 3,347.11
</P>
<P>
   A component of the Dow Jones industrial average, HP
single-handedly accounted for 84 points of yesterday's 152.61-point
gain in that widely followed blue-chip indicator, which closed at
11,035.70. The Dow now stands less than 300 points below its
all-time  &LR; high of 11,326.04, set on August 25.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $8 billion of the $13.6 billion leap in HP's market value
was attributable to the spin-off of 72 million shares _ or 16
percent _ of Agilent, an operationally independent subsidiary, also
based in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   The shares were sold to the public yesterday at $30 and soared
to $42.75 by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   HP, which still owns 380 million shares, gained $4.8 billion
from that increase, plus $3 billion from a 36 percent eleventh-hour
boost in the IPO price, which originally had been pegged at $22.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a second spin-off of the remaining 380 million
shares in about six months, with HP shareholders getting all of
them in proportion to their HP holdings. At that point, Agilent
will be entirely independent of HP.
</P>
<P>
   If the present share ratios persist, HP shareholders will
receive 37 Agilent shares _ current value, $1,581.75 _ for every
100 HP shares (current value, $9,431.25) they own.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent is made up of HP's old-line instrument business _
testing and measuring devices used in the semiconductor, health
care and telecommunications industries, among others. HP spun it
off in hopes of focusing investor attention on its supposedly
sexier businesses: computers, printers and the like.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday, at least, the Agilent tail wagged the HP dog.
Experts say the company will benefit from the strong
telecommunications market, a recovery in the chip market, and
improvements in the economy of Asia, where it does substantial
business.
</P>
<P>
   John B. Jones, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney in San
Francisco, said it is fairly common for companies to spin off only
a small minority interest in a subsidiary at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``You create an independent entity, give them the opportunity to
leverage an independent business focus, then the shareholders of
the originating company get the benefit,'' Jones observed.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, after the stock market closed, HP announced
earnings per share of 75 cents, excluding special charges, for the
fiscal fourth quarter ended last month. It beat analyst estimates
by 2 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   That helped give the stock its big jolt yesterday, as did
comments by Carleton S. Fiorina, HP's president and chief
executive, who said the company's goal in the current fiscal year
is to raise revenues and earnings by 12 to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
