r f BC-Y2K-Y2K_SFCHRON &LR;      11-18 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-Y2K </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Banks Ready to Roll Into the New Year  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Banks have readied their computers for the year 2000 and should
cruise into the new year with few problems, a top federal regulator
said in San Francisco yesterday.
<P>
   At a briefing for The Chronicle, Donna Tanoue, chairman of the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., noted that regulators had examined
all 10,300 of the nation's banks and thrifts at least twice and
found only five that had not adequately prepared their computers
for the date change.
</P>
<P>
   Those cases mainly involve documentation issues rather than
hardware or software problems, she added. None of the five
institutions operate in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're increasingly confident that it's going to be business as
usual'' after January 1, Tanoue said.
</P>
<P>
   The five institutions whose Y2K preparations regulators rate as
less than satisfactory are a sharp improvement from 16 months ago,
when 774 banks and thrifts had such ratings, Tanoue said.
</P>
<P>
   Banks, along with airlines and electrical utilities, have been
widely viewed as among the institutions most vulnerable to the year
2000 problem, which arises because many old computer programs use
two digits to indicate years.
</P>
<P>
   Such programs cannot distinguish between the years 2000 and
1900. Unless they are updated, date-sensitive financial records
could be thrown into chaos next year. Alarmists predict that ATMs
will stop working, account information will be lost and payment
posting will be garbled.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have given top priority to ensuring that financial
institutions update their computers. Under the supervision of state
and federal agencies, banks and thrifts have spent billions of
dollars rewriting software and testing systems.
</P>
<P>
   While those efforts have reassured regulators, large segments of
the public have been wary.
</P>
<P>
   Officials still predict a surge in demand for currency as
consumers and businesses hoard cash to protect themselves against
breakdowns in the banking system. The Federal Reserve has stocked
$200 billion in currency in its vaults _ about $50 billion more
than usual _ to meet demand for cash, said Robert Parry, chief
executive of the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco, who
accompanied Tanoue.
</P>
<P>
   The FDIC released results of a Gallup survey conducted in
October and November that showed some waning of public worry.
</P>
<P>
   Nine out of 10 ten  &LR; people responding said they were either very
confident or somewhat confident that their financial institutions
were prepared for 2000. That compared with 76 percent of
respondents in a March survey who said they were confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not as concerned as they used to be,'' Tanoue said.
</P>
<P>
   While the FDIC chief predicts business as usual for bank
customers come January 1, it won't be that way for bank regulators.
The FDIC and other bank regulatory agencies plan to keep their
offices open throughout the New Year weekend, as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be here in case people have concerns,'' Tanoue
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
