<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-MVP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ DIPLOMATIC IN HIS MVP SHUTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite having more first-place votes than the winner,
Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez was more diplomatic Thursday about
losing the American League's Most Valuable Player Award to Texas
Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez than the sports minister of his
native Dominican Republic, Juan Marichal.
</P>
<P>
   Marichal, the Hall of Fame pitcher who briefly played for the
Red Sox at the end of his career, called it an ``injustice.'' He
was not alone in that sentiment, as Red Sox fans throughout New
England reacted negatively to the news that Martinez, who earlier
in the week won the American League's Cy Young Award as the
league's outstanding pitcher, fell 13 points shy of adding the MVP
award to his trophy case.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the MVP to the fans of Boston,'' said Red Sox general
manager Dan Duquette, offering his condolences in a media
conference call to the Sox ace who fell short in his bid to become
the first starting pitcher to be named MVP since Roger Clemens won
the award for Boston in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez, left completely off two ballots cast by the 28
voting members of the Baseball Writers Assn. of America when two
fourth-place votes could have made him the winner, did not begrudge
Rodriguez, the first catcher to win the award since the Yankees'
Thurman Munson in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the pile was good enough to be MVP,'' said
Martinez, alluding to a crowded field that included at least eight
legitimate candidates, including teammate Nomar Garciaparra, who
finished seventh in the balloting after a second-place finish in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hold it against anybody,'' Martinez said. ``If they
don't want to vote for me, there's nothing I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   George King of the New York Post and La Velle Neal of the
Minneapolis Star-Tribune did not list Martinez among the 10 players
for whom they were allowed to vote. Fourteen points were awarded
for a first-place vote, 9 for a second, 8 for a third, etc.
</P>
<P>
   King, who covers the New York Yankees for the Post, was on
vacation and unavailable for comment. Neal, who covers the
Minnesota Twins for the Star-Tribune, was inundated with calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I'm not a pitcher-for-MVP guy,'' Neal said, echoing
a view expressed by numerous baseball people _ including Red Sox
manager Jimy Williams earlier this season _ that pitchers who
perform just once every five days do not deserve the same
consideration as everyday players. ``I believe whoever wins that
award should be on the field every day, helping his team win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he had a tremendous season. I know he may be an
exception. But there were other good players on that team. You may
have the best shortstop out there in Garciaparra. Jimy Williams did
a marvelous job running that team. It wasn't just Pedro alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for field players. That's just my belief and I'm
sticking with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez became the seventh AL catcher to win the award, the
first since the Yankees' Thurman Munson in 1976. He hit 35 home
runs, a record for American League catchers, and his batting
average of .332 was the highest by an AL catcher since the Yankees'
Bill Dickey hit .362 in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez last week also won his eighth Gold Glove for defensive
excellence, a total eclipsed among catchers only by Hall of Famer
Johnny Bench, who has 10. He threw out 39 of 72 base-runners
attempting to steal, a 54 percent success rate that was the highest
of any catcher this decade.
</P>
<P>
   But curiously, the two beat reporters assigned to the Rangers
who cast votes for MVP rated Rodriguez's teammate, designated
hitter Rafael Palmeiro, higher than they did Rodriguez. Evan Grant
of the Dallas Morning News voted Palmeiro first, followed by
Martinez. He had Rodriguez ranked sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Paul of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram also voted Palmeiro
first, with Martinez fourth and Rodriguez fifth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
