<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTSCRUSHED-CHAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS REMEMBER A BRILLIANT STUDENT AND FAITHFUL FRIEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT FRAZIER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KELLER, Texas _ The news of his death blared across Keller High
School's loudspeakers, followed by a moment of silence.
</P>
<P>
   Then came tears for a brilliant teen-ager who had earned
numerous awards _ including the honored title of friend.
</P>
<P>
   Chad A. Powell, 19 _ Eagle Scout, track team member, tutor,
guitar player, National Merit Scholar and 1999 Keller High School
valedictorian _ was among the students who died when a log stack
collapsed Thursday at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been going in between absolute rage and bawling,'' said
former classmate and neighbor Ruth Huston, now an 18-year-old
freshman at Columbia College in South Carolina. ``Whenever anyone
felt bad, he'd start singing a weird song or quoting the Simpsons
or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, every student, neighbor and teacher mourning his loss
spoke of Powell's achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was president of Keller High School's National Honor
Society and a stand-out member of its state academic decathlon
team, winning four gold and four silver individual awards in
regional and state competitions. He was one of 11 Texas students on
the Fina all-state academic athletic team.
</P>
<P>
   He was voted Keller High School's ``most likely to succeed,''
and classmates expected his success to be stunning. Powell hoped to
own start his own company specializing in the design of operating
systems for computers. Those who knew him believed he was most
likely to put Microsoft mogul Bill Gates out of a job, as Powell
sometimes jested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except with him, you got the feeling that he could do it,''
Keller track coach David Park said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing seemed out of his reach, because of his ability and
determination, others said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked hard and gave everything he had. If he did it, he
was putting everything into it,'' track coach David Coker said.
``He wasn't a naturally gifted athlete, but he made himself an
athlete through determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell was more valued, though, as a friend who was always
upbeat and willing to help others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a brother to everybody,'' said Juan Tatum, Keller High
School junior.
</P>
<P>
   Keller High Principal Randy Baker agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a loss not only for Keller High School, but the
entire district and community,'' he said. ``He was a true leader.
He was a friend, both to the students here, the faculty and
administration. He was a great kid to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell taught everywhere he went, and not only by example. In
study hall, any student could call on him for assistance,
regardless of their age or the subject, teachers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very sweet, intelligent, wise beyond his years. He had
a very quick wit,'' district spokeswoman Julie Zwahr said.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's helpfulness reached even into Keller school district's
central office. He started helping program computers in the Keller
central administration in seventh grade. Over the years, he also
helped set up the district's cable TV programming and its Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything Chad did, it was done not only with excellence but
with integrity and character. He was just a real outstanding kid,''
said J.D. Tomlin, student minister at First Baptist Church of
Keller, where Powell was a member.
</P>
<P>
   During his junior high and early high school years, Powell was
involved with the church's youth ministry programs and participated
in community outreach events, Tomlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad was a superfriendly guy,'' Tomlin said. ``He was
brilliant, but very humble about it. He loved education and
learning, but he also loved people. He was very relational and had
many friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Students filed out of Keller High on Thursday were subdued with
emotion and tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the most unselfish people I've ever met,'' said
Daniel Pessing, a Keller High School senior and fellow track team
member. ``He's worked so hard his whole life, and he had so much
ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The school canceled extra-curricular activities Thursday night.
Friay, the district's emergency team will take over some school
duties, allowing teachers, staff and counselors to spend time with
Powell's family or grieving students.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's mother works as an assistant in the school district's
personnel office. His older brother, Jeremy, graduated from Keller
High and now attends Texas Tech. His younger brother, Josh, is a
senior at Keller High.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some teachers that are just distraught,'' Cocker said.
``There are some freshman on the track team that knew him for just
one season who are distraught. Tomorrow will be a long day.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker read a statement from Powell's parents Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He died giving of himself just as he lived _ giving of
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   A video of his valedictory address was a poignant reminder
Thursday. Draped in his blue graduation gown and sporting academic
medals, Powell spoke of saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say goodbye,'' he said. ``Goodbye teachers, who
helped to get us here today. Goodbye friends, who must go their
separate way. And goodby to the life we have known. To move on is
the price we must pay.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorial fund will be established in his name, school
officials said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff writers Jennifer Radcliffe and Tara Dooley contributed to
this report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
