<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CLINTON-SIGNATURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE E-MAIL AGE, A PRESIDENT'S SIGNATURE IS STILL A MUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SPEND-CONGRESS.) 
(th) 
 By DAVID STOUT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In this age of computer simulation and instant
global communication, some things must be done the old-fashioned
way. Getting the president's signature on a piece of paper is one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   So when Congress passes continuing resolutions to keep the
government running until a budget is approved, someone has to take
that resolution in hand and give it to President Clinton for his
signature. With the president in Turkey, some people have had to do
a lot of flying this week.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress passed a continuing resolution on Wednesday to
keep several major departments going, a member of the White House
legislative affairs office boarded a plane that departed from
Washington around 9 that night. The trip to Turkey would normally
take about 10 hours, according to Jake Siewert, the deputy White
House press secretary, but difficulties with connecting flights
made this one a bit longer.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. The resolution was signed by Clinton shortly before
5 p.m. Washington time, with a good seven hours to spare before the
resolution expired.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, John Podesta, the White House chief of staff,
was to fly to meet Clinton and get his signature on a continuing
resolution passed Thursday that is good until early December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crisis averted,'' Siewert said, pointing out that all kinds of
diplomatic documents and other important papers are flown thousands
of miles, even in the computer age.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not know why the president's actual signature is
required on a continuing resolution, except that the law providing
for such things has been on the books longer than computers have
been on desktops.
</P>
<P>
   And is there ever a worry that a pouch with a vital piece of
paper might be lost on the way, leading to a government shutdown?
``We give them to responsible adults,'' Siewert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
