<HEADER>
A4523 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-18 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHERS VS. EVERYDAY PLAYERS? NO COMPARISON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now if they would only listen to me . . .
</P>
<P>
   . . . we wouldn't have this problem.
</P>
<P>
   Was Pedro Martinez the best performer in all of baseball this
year? Double duh. Was he the Most Valuable Player? I say no.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is very simple. Pitchers shouldn't even be
eligible for the Most Valuable Player award, not as it's presently
constituted. Ever hear of rendering to Caesar the things that are
Caesar's, and God the things that are God's? That's very sound
Biblical advice that applies very nicely to this baseball issue. An
everyday player cannot be properly and accurately and precisely
compared to a pitcher. So why bother trying?
</P>
<P>
   The Cy Young Award was created in 1956 to reward the man
designated as baseball's best pitcher. Why? There are only two
possible reasons. One is that people felt pitchers were not being
properly rewarded by the MVP process. The second is that people
felt it was an impossibility to weigh the contributions of an
everyday player vs. a pitcher. Can you think of any other reason?
</P>
<P>
   At that juncture, each league had produced four starting
pitching MVPs (reliever Jim Konstanty won the National League award
in 1950) in the official Baseball Writers Association of America
balloting, which began in 1931 with the selections of Frankie
Frisch in the National League and Lefty Grove _ yes, a pitcher _ in
the American. That very first Cy Young year, Don Newcombe (27-7,
3.06, five shutouts) also won the MVP. Sandy Koufax ('63) and Bob
Gibson ('68) in the National League, as well as Denny McLain ('68),
Vida Blue ('71), and Roger Clemens ('86) in the American, were all
starters, like Newcombe, who also won the MVP.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, but if voters wanted to be consistent, how do they
explain missing the most obvious pitching MVP of all-time? They
gave Steve Carlton the Cy Young Award in 1972 for winning 27 games
with a 1.97 ERA, 310 strikeouts, and eight shutouts. If you think
pitchers should be eligible for MVP, Player of the Year, or
anything you'd like to call the top performer, how did he not get
the MVP for winning 27 times on a team that only won 59 games?
That's not Most Valuable. That's MOST VALUABLE!!!!
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the winner was Johnny Bench, who had 40-125 power totals
while being the best defensive catcher in baseball. Oops, almost
forgot. The Reds won the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Bench was a very worthy choice, and that, plus the Phillies'
last-place standing _ was Carlton supposed to pitch all 162 games?
_ made the difference. I guess. We'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that nobody on this earth can make a
compelling, definitive case for a pitcher, be he a starter or a
closer, as opposed to a man who is in the lineup every day. If
someone would like to re-word the award to ``Outstanding
Performer,'' as opposed to the newbulous ``Most Valuable,'' there
would be no problem. If we could do it retroactively, Carlton would
get his 1972 award and Pedro would have his prize today. Nobody in
baseball was more dazzling than Pedro _ when he performed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a common sense issue. You are trying to compare a man who
is out there every fifth day with someone who is out there every
day. It's a ridiculous premise.
</P>
<P>
   The great example was 1978, when voters were asked to decide
between Jim Rice and Ron Guidry. This was like being a farmer
having the greatest crop of apples he's ever produced (46 homers,
139 RBIs, 406 total bases, etc.), as well as the greatest crop of
oranges he's ever produced (25-3, 1.74 ERA, nine shutouts). Both
crops were flawless. How to decide?
</P>
<P>
   This is far different than trying to make decisions involving a
position player vs. a position player and a pitcher vs. a pitcher.
This is nothing less than an existential question. Better the ghost
of Jean Paul Sartre decide than a member of the BBWAA.
</P>
<P>
   But pitchers are eligible till further notice, so what to do?.
Well, I say the first look must always be at worthy position
players. If none stand out, then look at pitchers. I'm sorry, but
pitchers should only win the award in a position player vacuum.
When Bobby Shantz won the AL MVP in 1952 by going 24-7 for a
fourth-place Philadelphia A's team, he benefitted from the fact
that no position player had a killer year. That's just one example.
When Denny McLain (31-6) and Bob Gibson (1.12, 13 shutouts) each
won in 1968, it was the nadir of 20th-century offense. As Reggie
Smith once said, Carl Yastrzemski ``saved the American League from
the embarrassment of not having a .300 hitter (Yaz hit .301).'' In
such a clear vacuum it may have been acceptable to select a
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   No such vacuum exists today. To the contrary, this may have been
the deepest crop of worthy MVP candidates ever. Finishing sixth
this year was an honor. With so many legitimate position player
candidates, there really was no need to tap a pitcher, even one who
had as spectacular a season as Pedro's.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to George King of the New York Post and LaVelle
Neal of the Minneapolis Star-Tribune, the two gentlemen who left
Pedro off their MVP ballots entirely. They could only have done
this because they, like me, are philosophically opposed to a
pitcher winning the award (I give each the benefit of the doubt on
the sheer stupidity charge). But they are not operating in a
vacuum. They know very well that pitchers are eligible, and that
Pedro had a monumental year. Under the current rules of the game,
nothing justifies their actions. They may not like the rules, but
rules are rules. If they felt strongly about it, they should not
have voted at all. They knew what was at stake; they had to put
Pedro in there somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Again, no one should be forced to make this decision.
Unfortunately, people do. In the complete absence of any
competition, I would vote for a pitcher having a year like Pedro's.
But this year? Absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   I would have voted this way: 1. Pudge Rodriguez, 2. Manny
Ramirez, 3. Derek Jeter, 4. Roberto Alomar, 5. Pedro, 6. Rafael
Palmeiro, 7. Nomar Garciaparra, 8. Bernie Williams, 9. Shawn Green,
10. Junior Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   If Messrs. King and Neal had voted my way, Pedro still would
have finished second. That's fine with me. He should be very
satisfied with his Cy Young. The right man won the MVP.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
