<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-SANDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIDS EXPECTED SOON FOR LOCKHEED'S N.H. UNIT, SANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin Corp. is preparing to entertain bids for its
Sanders military electronics division, based in Nashua, N.H., and
for more than 30 years one of the Granite State's largest
employers.
</P>
<P>
   Some state officials worry a sale of Sanders could mean layoffs
among its 4,000 employees in New Hampshire and Massachusetts, but
Sanders president Walter P. Havenstein prefers to put a happy face
on the company's future.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is profitable, he says, with annual sales approaching $1
billion, and it would make sense for a buyer to keep it intact and
to continue its operational autonomy. ``We're committed to making
Sanders work, and to work here in New Hampshire,'' Havenstein said
in an interview this week.
</P>
<P>
   Havenstein said he could only guess who might bid. But a person
familiar with the process said other aerospace companies, including
L-3 Communications Holdings Inc., Northrop Grumman Corp., General
Dynamics Corp., and British Aerospace, have expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
   No deal is expected for at least several months. Northrop and
General Dynamics declined to comment and L-3 Communications did not
respond to inquries. British Aerospace spokesman Phil Sousey
confirmed the company is mulling a purchase, adding that ``BA has
an interest in all goings-on in the aerospace industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Another option is a management buyout, but Havenstein said it is
too soon for him to discuss whether he might want to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the future, Sanders would come with a built-in major
customer _ Lockheed Martin, which through its other divisions buys
30 percent of Sanders' output of antimissile devices, microchips,
and other defense-related electronics. Other defense contractors
account for most of the rest of Sanders' sales.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders might do even better out from under the parent's wing,
Havenstein said, by attracting more Lockheed Martin rivals as
customers. ``People who would normally consider Sanders . . .. as a
captured unit of Lockheed Martin might be more likely to look at us
as a merchant supplier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin's possible sale of the Sanders division is yet
another piece of the massive retrenchment among defense contractors
following a decade of industry consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Havenstein, who joined Sanders nine months ago, already had a
working knowledge of the company in his previous job as head of a
Raytheon Co. unit in Falls Church, Va. As often happens in the
shrinking defense industry, Raytheon and Sanders were sometimes
rivals for work and, at other times, partners.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is Lockheed Martin's largest operating subsidiary in New
England, with primary facilities in Nashua, Hudson, and Merrimack,
N.H. About 1,500 of Sanders' employees are engineers and another
1,000 are in manufacturing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin also owns an infrared imaging unit with 400
employees in Lexington, Mass., and has about 1,900 employees at
smaller units throughout New England.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, at the height of the Reagan administration
defense build-up, Sanders had 9,100 employees. But even at less
than half that size it remains one of New Hampshire's largest
employers, and a cornerstone of the state's high-technology
industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin says Sanders is one of several aerospace
electronics units, including Fairchild Systems in New York, that it
might prefer to sell as a bundle. The decision to evaluate these
companies for sale was announced in September, following poor
performance reviews by the Pentagon, and a string of disappointing
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin share prices aredown more than 60 percent from
a late-1998 high of 55, closing Thursday on the New York Stock
Exchange at 20 5/8, up 1 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   The Sanders division, once known as Sanders Associates, was
founded in Waltham, Mass. in 1951 by a group of 11 former Raytheon
Co. employees led by Royden C. Sanders. It moved to Nashua the next
year, and through following decades became known for production of
``countermeasure'' devices used to fool enemy missiles, either by
jamming their radio frequencies or by firing flares to confuse
heat-seeking sensors.
</P>
<P>
   The founder left in 1975 after pressing unsuccessfully to enter
computer production; he now owns design firms in Wilton and
Merrimack, N.H. Lockheed Corp. bought Sanders in 1986 for $1.2
billion, keeping its name and giving it relative autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to antimissile devices, Sanders makes computer chips
known as monolithic microwave integrated circuits, used in guidance
systems for missiles and satellites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
