<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: COMBAT ON SPENDING ENDS IN A DRAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SPEND-CONGRESS) 
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For all of the partisanship and intense wrangling
of the past 10 days, the budget agreement between President Clinton
and the Republican-run Congress ended up being most remarkable for
its moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the temptations posed by an era of federal surpluses,
the package approved by the House on Thursday night contains no
expansive new spending programs, such as President Clinton's
proposal for a new Medicare prescription drug benefit. Nor does it
include the $792 billion tax cut over 10 years that the Republicans
tried to push through, only to be stopped by Clinton's veto.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over spending for the 2000 fiscal year showed that
both an impeached president and House Republicans, reduced to a
razor-thin majority, proved remarkably resilient. The outcome came
about because each side, in effect, fought the other to a draw. As
a result, both sides could take credit on Thursday for a spending
agreement that will take another step toward paying down the
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   And the most far-reaching effect of this year's budget struggle
may well be a consensus that has emerged through two years of
political combat that Social Security payroll taxes should no
longer be used to pay for other government programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first used the ``save Social Security first'' refrain in
1998 to stop Republican tax cuts. But this year, with the size of
the surpluses growing almost monthly, Clinton softened his stance
to allow for new spending. He said that 63 percent of the total
budget surplus over 15 years should be used for Social Security
with the rest going to other programs.
</P>
<P>
   That was when the Republicans decided to trump Clinton and call
for the entire Social Security reserve to be protected. Many
Republicans said this week that their pledge had created a powerful
new political weapon to contain federal spending in a time of
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing was when it was obvious that we stopped the raid
on Social Security, we set a parameter that was impenetrable,''
said Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the idea of leaving Social Security revenue untouched
has now become so widely embraced that some version of it is
recited by presidential candidates across the political spectrum _
from Gov. George W. Bush of Texas to former Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said, ``I think its going to be very
difficult for either party to go back at any time in the future and
acknowledge that they are using the Social Security trust funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately this idea could come back to haunt the Republicans as
much as the Democrats _ constraining tax cutting as well as
spending. ``We checkmated each other,'' said a senior Democratic
staff member. ``We said `save the surplus to stop tax cuts.' They
used it to stop spending programs. So it came out as a draw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican focus on Social Security, which has long been an
issue that Democrats wielded against Republicans _ was part of a
fundamental shift in tactics by the brash conservatives who swept
to control of Congress in 1994 on a pledge to reduce the scope of
government. It came in fits and starts across the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans began the year pledging fiscal restraint but
then blew past the spending limits set in the 1997 balanced budget
law by more than $30 billion. They approved a $792 billion tax cut,
but failed to generate much public enthusiasm for it.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of fighting after Clinton vetoed the tax cut,
Republican leaders made a pragmatic decision to adjust to the
limits of divided government and to the mood of an electorate that
is no longer dominated by the angry and economically pressed voters
who swept them into office.
</P>
<P>
   They borrowed, and sightly retooled, historical Democratic
campaign themes. They promoted education spending. They put more
money into the military and certain health programs than even
Clinton had asked for. They struck compromise after compromise with
the president, thus moving more in line with a time when their
preferred presidential candidate is running as a ``compassionate
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've kept the bulls-eye off our forehead, unlike the last
four years,'' said Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   And oddly enough, after years of cacophony, the Republicans
found a unifying theme in Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily, Republicans pledge to keep the money brought in
from the Social Security payroll tax from being used to pay for
other government programs _ even though Democrats wield studies
from the nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office that the
Republican spending bills are full of gimmicks and actually risk
eating into the Social Security reserve by $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The theme helped Republican leaders rally the party's moderates
who want to pay down the national debt and its conservatives who
believe that the refrain has created a powerful new political
firewall that will prevent both parties from increasing the size of
government now that deficits are no longer forcing reductions in
spending. Of the projected $3 trillion surplus across the next
decade, $2 trillion of the money would be in Social Security
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a moment that's dripping with irony,'' said Marshall
Wittmann, director of congressional relations for the conservative
research group, the Heritage Foundation. ``We've reached the fourth
year of the Republican revolution and they are laying their
political future on defending the cornerstone of the welfare
state.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If you ask Republicans what time it is, they say
`save Social Security.' If you ask what the weather is they say,
`save Social Security.' It's a kind of unity they haven't had since
they took over.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Republicans can really benefit politically from the
Social Security issue in next year's elections is another question.
Among the public at large, polls show voters still trust Democrats
far more than Republicans when it comes to issues relating to the
retirement fund.
</P>
<P>
   Irritated by Republican commercials accusing Democrats of
wanting to raid Social Security, House Democrats on Thursday
continued to showcase all the accounting gimmicks the Republicans
used to hide the true levels of spending they approved.
</P>
<P>
   Still each side could point to victories. Clinton received money
to pay for his signature programs to hire 100,000 more teachers and
50,000 more community police officers. He secured money to pay the
country's back dues to the United Nations and finance the Wye River
Mideast peace accord. And the White House fought off provisions on
mining and oil drilling that it had opposed as threats to the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans got a foothold for their efforts to loosen federal
restrictions on how education money can be used. They put in place
language to limit federal financing of groups that promote abortion
rights overseas. They prevailed in increasing military spending
even more than Clinton wanted. And they won a largely symbolic
across-the- board spending cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were a football game, the score would be pretty close
to a tie,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas. ``This is a deal where
no one got a scalp, but everyone came back from the hunt with
something to brag about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
