<SLUG> BC-BKC-CBS-MADNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S MADNESS: CBS PAYS $6.2B FOR NCAA EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS locked up March Madness for the next 11 years by spending an
astounding $6.2 billion for the television rights to the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, announced Thursday night after CBS, Fox, and ESPN had
made presentations to the NCAA, comes on the heels of the equally
staggering $2.4 billion NASCAR package with NBC, Fox, and TBS.
</P>
<P>
   The three-week tournament represents one of most expensive
packages in sports television. The $17.6 billion, eight-year NFL
deal is still the gold standard. The NBA's $2.64 billion, four-year
deal with NBC and TNT is in its second year, while Major League
Baseball is in its last year of a $1.7 billion, five-year deal with
Fox, NBC, and ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   The skyrocketing deals are fueled in part by advertisers'
willingness to reach the all-important male demographic between the
ages of 18 and 34 as well the networks' need to have a
cross-promotional platform to market its other prime-time
programming.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other network, CBS knows what it's like not to
have such a vehicle, a painful lesson learned in 1993 when it lost
the NFL to the then-upstart Fox network for what was then
considered an astronomical $1.56 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first blush, what seems to be an obnoxious amount of money
might make sense if you peel back all the layers of the
agreement,'' said David Carter, a sports business analyst at the
University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   In this particular case, CBS receives all of the television
rights, including over-the-air broadcasting, cable television,
satellite, digital and home video and Internet rights. CBS also
acquires all rights to related electronic commerce and various NCAA
Web sites. The deal begins in 2003 after CBS existing contract
expires. The new deal more than doubles the networks $1.73 billion
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The is the first sports deal in history to extend beyond our
traditional platforms into the world of new media,'' said Leslie
Moonves, president and CEO of CBS television.
</P>
<P>
   Long plagued by an aging viewership, CBS has transformed itself
into a younger, hipper network. Its merger with Viacom, for
instance, enables CBS to promote its sports programming on VH-1,
Nickelodeon, MTV, and other Viacom networks.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said the NCAA is potentially troubling, largely because
it calls into question the precarious balance between education and
big-time sports. ``The ethical implications are extraordinary,''
Carter said. ``Its more than just the money. Because of the NCAA
revenue-sharing process, you might see conference shakeouts where
schools jockey to get a bigger piece of the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA opened negotiations early and ended CBS's exclusive
bargaining period in August. The network has broadcast the event
since 1982, when it acquired the tournament from NBC. It added the
early rounds, which had been broadcast by ESPN, in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ABC-ESPN issued a tersely worded statement. ``The ABC-ESPN bid
offered the best opportunity for exposure and growth for the NCAA
men's basketball tournament,'' said ESPN spokesman Josh Krulewitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``With over 2,300 college basketball games, the woemn's
championship tournament, 277 other NCAA competitions and nearly 100
college football, ESPN remains the home of college sports.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
