<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-MVP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' RODRIGUEZ IS AL MVP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ Ivan Rodriguez has long been considered the best
catcher in the American League. Now he's considered the best
player, period.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rodriguez earned that honor Thursday when he was named the
American League's Most Valuable Player, narrowly winning the award
over Boston Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means a lot to me,'' Rodriguez said. ``It's a great
honor. The awards every player wants to win is Most Valuable Player
and a World Series. Now I've got the MVP award, the next one I want
to have is the World Series ring. But this is a great feeling. I
still don't believe it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   With Juan Gonzalez winning in 1996 and 1998, the Rangers have
taken home the award three of the past four years. Jeff Burroughs
also won it while playing for the Rangers in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty exciting for the franchise, winning three of the
last four years,'' general manager Doug Melvin said. ``I think
Pudge will look at this as an incentive to win another one. This
puts him further on the path to the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez received 252 points, edging Martinez by 13 points
among the 28 ballots cast. Rodriguez received seven first-place
votes, and Martinez received eight. But Martinez was hurt by being
left off two ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed at all,'' Martinez said in a conference
call with Boston reporters. ``Everybody that was in that pile was
good enough to be MVP, so I don't have anything against anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28 voters, two baseball writers from each of the 14 American
League markets, list 10 players. First place is worth 14 points,
second place is worth nine and then 8-7-6-5-4-3-2-1 in descending
order. Balloting is conducted by the Baseball Writers Association
of America.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Indians second baseman Roberto Alomar and outfielder
Manny Ramirez tied for third place with 226 points and Rangers
designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro was fifth with 193 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously disappointed, but I'm happy for Pudge,''
Palmeiro said. ``He had a tremendous year. He deserves it as much
as anybody else who could have won it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is the ninth catcher in major-league history to win
the award and the first since Thurman Munson won with the New York
Yankees in 1976. It's the fourth time since the award was started
in 1931 that a player won the MVP award despite not receiving the
most first-place votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys I was competing against all had a great year,''
Rodriguez said. ``They all had dream seasons. But that's baseball.
I felt I had a good season, I felt I had a good shot at the MVP,
and it came true.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez receives a $250,000 bonus for winning the award.
Palmeiro will receive a $100,000 bonus for finishing fifth. The
Rangers' standard policy is to give a $250,000 bonus for winning,
$100,000 for finishing second through fifth and $50,000 for
finishing sixth through 10th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for Raffy,'' Rodriguez said. ``He
deserved to win the award, too. He had an incredible season.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro said: ``It's never been a goal of mine, but, since I
came this close, this is the kind of thing that will motivate me
even more. I think it will motivate Pudge, too. This puts him in an
elite class, and he's going to work even harder to stay in that
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was rewarded for having one of the greatest seasons
ever by a catcher. He hit .332, the highest batting average by an
American League catcher since 1936, when Hall of Fame player Bill
Dickey hit .362 for the New York Yankees. His 35 home runs are the
most by an American League catcher, and his 116 runs scored match
the second most by a major-league catcher. His 113 runs batted in
are the second most by an AL catcher since 1957, and he is the
first major-league catcher to hit at least 20 home runs and steal
20 bases in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also stood out defensively by throwing out a
career-high 54.2 percent of base runners attempting to steal,
leading the American League for the fifth consecutive year. He also
had only one passed ball and won his eighth consecutive Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think the production he gives the Rangers in all
aspects of the game can't be matched by any of those other
candidates,'' said ``St. Paul Pioneer Press''' Scott Miller, who
voted Rodriguez first.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro hit .324 with 47 home runs and 148 RBI. But a knee
injury forced him to spend most of the season as the Rangers'
designated hitter, and that hurt him with some voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, people arguing that based on pure numbers that it
should be Raffy, didn't sell with me because he's a DH,'' said
``The Tampa Tribune'''s Joe Henderson, who voted for Roberto Alomar
and listed Rodriguez third. ``He put up some unbelievable numbers,
and maybe Texas wouldn't have been as good without him. But he's a
part-time player; the same with Martinez.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Palmeiro: ``There's nothing I can do about that. We played
with Lee Stevens at first base, and we were successful with that.
You can't go back and change it. It was the best way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Pudge had a great year. He deserves to win the award.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
