<HEADLINE>
USC BASKETBALL TEAM TO RELY ON SIX KEY VETERANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC basketball coach Henry Bibby was asked to
evaluate his incoming players this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I have to?'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   That about sums up the Trojans this season, a team that will
rely on six players for almost everything. But Bibby is so pleased
with his six veterans that he has little doubt USC will improve on
last year's 15-13 record and NIT appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are shooting for the NCAA Tournament, and it should
be an attainable goal if two or three of those new players Bibby
didn't want to talk about contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be better than last year,'' Bibby said. ``It'll be
something different this season. You won't see 15 or 16 changes in
the starting lineup. Six or seven guys will play the majority of
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby has spent most of the previous three seasons shuttling
players in and out of games, but said mass substitutions are no
longer going to be a problem this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's team was tough to coach. I couldn't pick a lineup
because no one guy stood out,'' Bibby said. ``Last year, we had
guys that thought they should have been playing. Last year, we had
guys that thought they could coach the team.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Bibby couldn't substitute if he wanted to. USC will
rely on six players: Center Brian Scalabrine; forwards Sam Clancy,
David Bluthenthal and Jarvis Turner; and guards Brandon Granville
and Jeff Trepagnier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have six guys that can do almost anything,'' Scalabrine
said.
</P>
<P>
   This six-pack gives USC a talented core group, and unlike last
season there should be relative harmony within the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was so different, with players being mad,''
Scalabrine said. ``This year, there's no gripes about playing time.
Everyone gets along with each other. It's a pretty mature group of
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be easy keeping everyone happy, because the top six
players should all get plenty of scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You figure there's 60 or 70 shots in a game, so every player
should get about 10 shots,'' Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby is counting on maturity to help the Trojans avoid a
midseason lull, when they lost 10 of 13 games. Their fortunes
turned in February, when they upset No. 4-ranked Stanford 86-82 in
Maples Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think top three in the Pac-10 is realistic for us,''
Granville said.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for optimism lie in the relaxed nature surrounding
the program. No one is looking over his shoulder about playing
time, and Bibby is running more complex practices because most of
the players are accustomed to his system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, it's kind of laid-back,'' Turner said. ``He gives
us more leeway because everyone's more mature.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the players themselves. The 6-foot-9 Scalabrine
is one of the top players in the Pacific-10 Conference after
averaging 14.6 points and 6.4 rebounds last season. This year, he
will become a 3-point threat and try to improve his rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Brian Scalabrine has to step up his rebounding,''
Bibby said. ``He hasn't been a good rebounder because we depended
on him for so many things. This year has to complete the cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Clancy (6-7) could make the greatest impact, appearing
stronger and more dominating in USC's two exhibition games. He'll
be the muscle inside, along with Scalabrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam's range has improved dramatically,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are also expecting 6-7 sophomore Bluthenthal to
become an outside shooting threat, and Bibby has handed him the
starting small forward spot.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, a senior, will be the sixth man and relieve all three
frontcourt players. He could even play some emergency point guard,
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could play four positions or maybe five,'' Bibby said. ``A
lot of people think I am crazy for saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting guards are Granville, who averaged nearly 28
minutes as a true freshman, and Trepagnier, a budding star in the
conference with a reputation for thunderous dunks.
</P>
<P>
   If Trepagnier can develop an outside shot, the Trojans could
make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working on it every morning, that's how much I want to
prove it to people that I can shoot,'' Trepagnier said.
</P>
<P>
   So what about those newcomers that Bibby refused to talk about?
Well, actually, he opened up slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five young players making the jump to major college
basketball, they're making it slow,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   Junior-college transfer Rashad Jones will have to play because
he is the backup point guard. The Trojans hope he can play about 10
minutes a game without hurting the team. The other contributor
should be 6-11 center Konstantinos (Kostas) Charissis, from Athens,
Greece. He's been raw in the exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rashad Jones and Kostas, those two right there, are not very
consistent right now,'' Scalabrine said. ``Kostas can give us five
minutes and bang.''
</P>
<P>
   The other possible reserve who might play is freshman shooting
guard Malachi Thurston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really shoots the basketball, he can come in and give us a
breather,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   The tallest Trojan _ 7-3 freshman Luke Minor _ will redshirt
while freshman guard Nate Hair is just starting to practice again
after suffering a stress fracture in his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about us rebounding the basketball. I'm
concerned about good defense at times,'' Bibby said. ``Can we hold
people to 65 points a game? That's something we have as a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through the war with young, unproven players. This
year, they know what's in front of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
