<HEADER>
A4543 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-WOMEN-PAY-ART-     11-18 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-WOMEN-PAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EQUITY CASE IN CANADA AS REDRESS FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT32 was sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST SELKIRK, Manitoba _ As an afternoon autumn light slanted
across a gray tableau of railroad tracks and power plant
smokestacks, a new joy infused a weather-worn trailer planted here
on the edge of a potato patch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big win for us,'' said Bev Austen, a 51-year-old
government filing clerk who has not seen a lot of big wins since
her husband died from metal poisoning 23 years ago, leaving her
with two small children to raise.
</P>
<P>
   In what may be the largest pay equity settlement in North
American history, Canada's government agreed late in October to pay
about $2.3 billion to 230,000 past and present federal workers,
overwhelmingly women. It will pay them back salaries, with
interest, to conform with a concept enshrined two decades ago in
Canada's Human Rights Act: ``equal pay for work of equal value.''
</P>
<P>
   Drafters of the law argued that women routinely end up working
in ``female ghettos'' _ as clerks, librarians, nurses, secretaries
and telephone operators. These jobs often pay less than ``male''
jobs that involve comparable education, responsibility, mental
demands and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Using these four criteria, committees made up of workers and
management devised a numerically based system for rating and
comparing ``male'' and ``female'' jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They compared us to painters, and most of us disagreed with
that,'' said Ms. Austen, who has been a clerk here for Canada's
immigration service for the last decade. She noted that the
government requirement for a painter is a 10th-grade education,
while clerks generally have high school diplomas, plus training in
accounting and word processing. ``Then we discovered that painters
made a lot more than clerks.''
</P>
<P>
   Paired by numerical scores, ``female'' jobs routinely won less
pay than ``male'' jobs. A chief librarian made $35,050, while a
dairy herd improvement manager made $38,766. A computer operations
supervisor made $20,193, while a forestry project supervisor made
$26,947. A typist made $10,531, while a sailor made $14,097.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison formulas _ the whole concept of equal pay for
work of equal value _ has been bitterly criticized by free-market
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come up with some concept, where a bunch of bureaucrats
arbitrarily decide, based on some abstract theory, that one job of
one kind that women dominate is somehow the same as another
completely different job that men dominate _ it's unworkable,''
said Monte Solberg, a member of parliament from the Reform Party,
the official opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Men who work in predominantly ``female'' job categories will
also receive checks as part of the effort to equalize pay scales.
With the pay dispute dating to 1984, most beneficiaries of the
settlement have retired or moved on to jobs in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``That they toiled at wages that were openly advertised and, in
fact, which often surpassed comparable pay in the private sector,
matters not a whit,'' complained Giles Gherson, political editor of
The National Post, a newspaper that has become the standard-bearer
of Canada's tax-cutting movement.
</P>
<P>
   The payment, critics argue, will delay moves to cut taxes here.
Canada already has the highest personal income tax burden among the
Group of Seven industrialized nations. After tax cuts go into
effect in Germany and Japan next year, Canada will have the highest
corporate tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   Countering arguments that the payment will eat up Canada's
budget surplus, Daryl Bean, president of the federal civil service
union, estimated that over 40 percent of the $2.3 billion would be
returned to the government in the form of income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the white trailer, which she shares with her 23-year-old
daughter, Jacqueline, an artist, and her 25-year-old son, Michael,
a bartender, Ms. Austen estimates that she will get about $15,000,
with the first checks arriving next spring. ``This is so late,''
she said. ``This would have really helped when the kids were little
and we really needed the money.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
