<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: U.S. BISHOPS ARE NOT NO EASY TO LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BISHOPS-REACT) 
(lh) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When it comes to many economic and social issues,
the nation's Roman Catholic bishops can put all but the most
liberal Democrats in the shade.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, for example, the bishops issued a statement calling
for an end to capital punishment, not least because it ``is often
applied unfairly and in racially biased ways.'' In September, they
joined other religious groups in a document that called access to
housing ``a sacred right'' and urged the government to do more to
help the poor find permanent shelter.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent annual meetings, the bishops have often taken
conservative positions in internal church issues, underlining their
gradual shift toward the right in the 1990s, a result of two
decades of appointments by Pope John Paul II. On Wednesday, for
example, the bishops voted to adopt a statement of new standards
for Catholic universities that would require theologians to be
certified by a bishop to show they were teaching ``authentic
Catholic doctrine.''
</P>
<P>
   And in 1998, on the issue of abortion, which the bishops see as
a human rights issue, they pledged themselves to challenge
politicians, particularly Catholic politicians, who support
abortion rights to undergo ``a change of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   What explains the apparent difference in directions, some
prelates and authorities on the church say, is that the bishops
tend to be more conservative on the internal church issues, and
those have come to dominate meetings of the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, by contrast, the bishops' conferences were
preoccupied by debate on sweeping pastoral statements about wealth
and poverty in America and the nation's role in preserving world
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s, we were dealing with a lot of big, spectacular
issues,'' said Bishop Robert N. Lynch of St. Petersburg, Fla., in a
news conference after the bishops' meeting ended Thursday. In the
'90s, he said, ``it seems to be a lot of internal issues.''
</P>
<P>
   And on those issues, the bishops have felt pressure from the
Vatican to follow its direction. Three years ago, for example, Rome
sent back to the bishops for revision an earlier version of the
higher education document, which is titled, ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae,''
a Latin phrase meaning ``From the Heart of the Church.'' The
Vatican asked for a more legalistic approach to the relationship
between the church and the university classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting all kinds of instructions from the Vatican,''
said the Rev. Thomas J. Reese, editor of the Jesuit magazine
America. ``And they're fairly deferential to the Vatican.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, church authorities in Rome ordered an
American priest and nun to end their longtime ministry to gay and
lesbian Catholics and their families. Despite hopes expressed by
some of the ministry's supporters, the bishops made no move to
question the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The shift toward the right is more apparent because the
conference lacks a consensus-building figure, who could unite
conservatives and moderates among the bishops, as it had in
Cardinal Joseph Bernardin, the Chicago archbishop who died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal John O'Connor, who as archbishop of New York occupies
the nation's most prominent and influential see, did not attend the
bishops' meeting this week. But his presence was felt in two
letters he sent, both of which were read aloud. One expressed his
support for the document on higher education.
</P>
<P>
   The other bade an apparent farewell to his fellow prelates. In
that one, he said it would be ``the height of presumption'' for him
to expect that Pope John Paul II would allow him to remain in
office much beyond his 80th birthday, next Jan. 15. Who might
succeed him has been a matter of growing, if often private,
speculation, including at the bishops' meeting.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But as a body at least, the bishops will probably continue to
defy easy labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Reese said that looking beyond their opposition to abortion, and
their support of state aid to parochial schools, the prelates still
stand ``to the left'' on many issues. As examples, he cited the
bishops' support for the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which was
defeated recently in the Senate, and their concern for the rights
and well-being of undocumented workers.
</P>
<P>
   The conference's president, Bishop Joseph A. Fiorenza, head of
the Diocese of Galveston-Houston, said the bishops were not
``pulling back in any way'' from addressing issues outside the
church. ``I think you will see us addressing more things like
assisted suicide, capital punishment, sanctions against Iraq and
Cuba,'' Fiorenza said. ``We will respond to those issues out of
what we believe, out of our faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
