<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VODAFONE WILL SWEETEN BID FOR MANNESMANN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL and ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Directors of Vodafone Airtouch PLC, the world's leading
wireless telephone carrier, decided Thursday night to sweeten their
all-stock bid for Mannesmann AG, Germany's engineering and
telecommunications giant _ raising it as high as $125.3 billion,
according to executives close to the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   While Mannesmann had previously said it was worth even more,
Vodafone will put its new offer _ nearly 18 percent higher than a
$106.4 billion bid Mannesmann rebuffed last Sunday _ to a meeting
on Friday of the German company's supervisory board.
</P>
<P>
   The Vodafone board's decision came as Mannesmann suffered a
legal setback in its struggle against the British company. Its
lawsuit seeking to disqualify Vodafone's investment banker,
Goldman, Sachs, was thrown out by a London judge, who harshly
chastised Mannesmann for bringing it.
</P>
<P>
   If Vodafone's sweetened takeover offer to Mannesmann is
rejected, executives close to Vodafone said, the British company
could opt to make a hostile bid _ the largest ever _ challenging a
battery of German legislation and corporate bylaws intended to
prevent such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   A Vodafone takeover of Mannesmann would create a company with
near-dominance of Europe's principal wireless markets and a network
that stretches from the United States to Africa, Asia and the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's top executives began intense consultations with the
company's investors on Tuesday to sound them out about the level of
a bid they were prepared to back without diluting their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the discussions held Thursday night said
Vodafone's directors had agreed to offer as much as 240 euros, or
$247.20, a share. That would value the German company, whose chief
executive, Klaus Esser, is fiercely committed to independence, as
high as $125.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Such an offer would surpass the $115 billion acquisition of
Sprint by MCI Worldcom announced last month and the $82.4 billion
hostile bid that Pfizer Inc. made two weeks ago for a
pharmaceutical rival, Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   If completed, it would be the largest takeover outside the
banking industry, where deals are valued in deposits or assets, and
can run in the hundreds of billions of dollars or higher.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the board meeting, Vodafone shares rose 6.5
pence Thursday, or 2.3 percent, to 2.835 pounds ($4.58). Mannesmann
shares rose 10.85 euros, or 5.5 percent, to 207.50 euros ($213.56).
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the increasingly sour relationship between the two
companies, Mannesmann took out full-page advertisements Thursday in
leading European newspapers, arguing that its combination of
wireless, fixed-line and data operations offered far greater
prospects for growth than Vodafone's single-minded commitment to
wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   But a moment of drama in the battle took place Thursday in
Britain's High Court, where a judge dismissed the move by
Mannesmann to prevent Goldman from advising Vodafone in its
acquisition plans.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Judge Gavin Lightman both set important precedents
for the legal defenses available to targets like Mannesmann and
also handed the German company a harsh rebuke, questioning its
probity on the eve of a board meeting that could determine the
company's future.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann sought the injunction Monday barring Goldman from its
advisory role with Vodafone, arguing that the Wall Street
investment bank faced a conflict of interest because it had access
to confidential information from previous work for Mannesmann. It
also said that Goldman had promised Mannesmann that it would not
represent Vodafone in a hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   Lightman ruled Thursday, however, that Mannesmann's case was so
flawed that ``this application is completely hopeless and must be
dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It should never have been brought,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Mannesmann's legal moves represented ``totally
disgraceful and unacceptable conduct,'' the judge said. He was
referring to an affidavit sworn by a Mannesmann executive asserting
that he had been present at a meeting where Goldman reassured the
German company that it would not advise Vodafone in a hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   That affidavit was presented to Lightman on Monday and, as a
result, Goldman, Sachs volunteered to suspend its advisory role
with Vodafone. Subsequently, however, Goldman challenged the
affidavit, and the Mannesmann executive, identified as Kurt
Kinzius, then withdrew it and all the main assertions he had made
in it. The judge said the affidavit ``contained totally false
evidence.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mannesmann's conduct, Lightman said in his 10-page ruling,
``calls for severe criticism'' because it offered ``false and
misleading evidence.'' A further ground for censure, the judge
said, was ``blowing away the froth _ the total lack of any
substance in Mannesmann's claim.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All these considerations,'' he went on, ``raise serious
questions as to the good faith of the claim in the first place and
whether it was indeed, as suggested by Goldman, Sachs, merely a
sporting exercise designed to rule out of play Vodafone's first
choice of advisers in the hostilities to come and pre-empt a bid by
Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is to be noted that the other leading firms are already
retained by Mannesmann. It is to be hoped that there will be no
repetition of this unseemly exercise in other cases.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the investment bank said the ruling ``confirms
that Goldman Sachs acted entirely properly in its efforts on behalf
of Vodafone Airtouch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We take our obligations to our clients very seriously,'' the
statement said, ``including safeguarding confidential information
and carefully vetting any potential conflict of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann's chief executive, Esser, said only, ``We believe we
were justified in seeking to protect the interests of Mannesmann,
and we are disappointed in the decision of the court.''
</P>
<P>
   During the hearings, Mannesmann's lawyer, Stanley Burton, had
told the court: ``This case is a battle in a war being fought on a
wider front.'' But Goldman's lawyers sought to depict the ruling as
defining an area where, in the words of its lawyer, Lord Peter
Goldsmith, ``this sort of serious application is not to be used as
another weapon in the armory'' of a takeover defense.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gillers, a professor of legal ethics at New York
University, said that while the judge's opinion was a powerful
rebuke, it did not necessarily have implications beyond the
Mannesmann-Vodafone struggle because ``it turns on what is found to
be a fabrication.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the problem of the boy who cries wolf,'' he said.
``Mannesmann is going to meet a skeptical bench if it ever returns
with a similar claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers who discussed the implications of the case
seemed divided on its impact. Some said the ruling provided what
one called a ``seminal judgment'' because it offered corporate
advisers one more layer of protection against clients' conflict of
interest claims.
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers, indeed, said the ruling might encourage
aggressive investment banks to decide to loosen their
conflict-of-interest policies, making it harder to compete for
business in an industry where firms fight aggressively for
blue-chip clients.
</P>
<P>
   But others said the case had created a backlash against
investment banks. Several bankers said they had received calls from
clients earlier this week requesting clarification of their firms'
conflict-of-interest policy, and in some cases asking for
confidential client lists and assurances similar to those
Mannesmann had requested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
