<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY SENTENCES THIRD KILLER IN JASPER CASE TO LIFE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By PATTY REINERT 
and RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Shawn Berry, who invited a drunken, disabled
black man into his pickup with two Klansmen and drove him into the
woods to be chained and dragged to death, was convicted of capital
murder Thursday, but the jury spared his life.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, 24, expressed little remorse and blamed his co-defendants
for the torture and murder of James Byrd Jr., whose mangled,
decapitated corpse was dumped outside a black cemetery in the East
Texas woods. The June 7, 1998, killing was the most heinous racial
crime in recent Texas history and prompted armed black activists
and the Ku Klux Klan to march on this Piney Woods town of 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have voted for the death penalty,'' said Jasper County
District Attorney Guy James Gray. ``But a life sentence is
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry's co-defendants, Bill King, 25, and Russell Brewer Jr.,
32, were convicted earlier this year and sentenced to death by
injection.
</P>
<P>
   In Berry's case, the all-white jury deliberated 10 1/2 hours
over two days before convicting him Thursday morning. In the
afternoon, they took little more than an hour to give him a life
prison sentence. He will serve at least 40 years before becoming
eligible for parole at age 64.
</P>
<P>
   Berry showed no emotion as State District Judge Joe Bob Golden
announced that the jury did not believe he poses a future threat of
violence, which would have been required for them to give him the
death penalty. He kissed and hugged his sobbing girlfriend,
Christie Marcontell, before sheriff's deputies escorted him from
the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Byrd family also cried as the verdict sunk in and
the weight of three grueling trials began to lift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can accept life,'' Byrd's sister, Clara Taylor of Houston,
said outside the Jasper County Courthouse. ``The jurors were
honest, capable people with a difficult decision to make. What was
most important to us was that he be convicted of capital murder so
that we could have justice for our brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said it was stressful to watch as Marcontell, Berry's
brother, Louis, and several friends pleaded for his life, but she
said it was only natural that they would do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I sat there and listened to them, I thought how James must
have pleaded with Shawn Berry for his life out there, and as his
family, we wish that we had also been there to plead for his
life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's family members said they believe all three men were
equally responsible for the murder, and while Berry was the only
one who was not a known white supremacist, evidence in his
seven-day trial indicated that he was the driver of the truck and
that it was his logging chain that was used to drag the 49-year-old
Byrd more than three miles.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny specks of Byrd's blood were found on the shoes of all three
killers, but Berry's jeans and shirt also were stained with his
victim's blood, which prosecutors contended was a sign he may have
played a bigger role in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   However, Berry did not have the racist tattoos and violent
rhetoric of his two co-defendants, and about 20 people testified as
character witnesses for him, including two blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Byrd's sisters waited outside on the courthouse lawn and
watched as Berry, amid tight security, was led to a car to be taken
to the state prison system's diagnostic unit in Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   As one of Berry's friends yelled, ``We love you, Shawn,''
another woman, Ethel Parks, taunted, ``At least you got better than
Byrd.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks, an African-American, followed Berry to the car, shouting,
``One more thing, Shawn: Rot in hell, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors read a brief statement to the media before leaving the
courtroom, saying they had reached their unanimous verdicts after
``long hours of painful and prayerful deliberations.'' They refused
to answer any questions.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's defense attorney, Joseph C. ``Lum'' Hawthorn, said he
was disappointed in the conviction, but happy that jurors had opted
for a life sentence. He described his client as relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who had taken the stand Thursday to ask the jury for his
life, at first remained defiant and refused to take any
responsibility for his crime. He told of his love for Marcontell
and for their 2-year-old son, Montana.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, however, Assistant U.S. Attorney Brit
Featherston, who assisted the local D.A., grilled him. If he were
such a good family man, Featherston asked, why was he partying with
King and Brewer the night of Byrd's murder, cruising Jasper looking
for women. Why hadn't he married Marcontell, Featherston asked,
instead of abusing her and then appearing on national television
and coming into court wearing a fake wedding ring?
</P>
<P>
   Featherston also confronted Berry with his lies to police and
with the physical evidence against him. However, Berry stuck to his
most recent story, that he had innocently offered Byrd a ride home,
and that he tried to defend him once he realized King and Brewer
intended to kill him. He backed off, he said, when they threatened
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Featherston said, ``Let's go on to another lie then.
When you picked up James Byrd Jr. and Bill King told you, `Let's go
kick (him),' and then Mr. Byrd asked you, `Man, where are we
going?' what do you tell him was going to happen?'' Featherston
shouted. ``What happened was you stopped and killed James Byrd Jr.,
didn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was that I stopped, and Bill King and Russell
Brewer killed James Byrd Jr.,'' Berry replied, adding that despite
the jury's guilty verdict, his involvement in the murder had not
been proved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you look at this jury and look at the Byrd family and
explain why you have no remorse over this crime?'' Featherston
demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very sorry for what happened to Mr. Byrd and I've said
that from day one,'' Berry said. ``And I would do anything in the
world if I could do it over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that include going home and going to sleep after dragging
James Byrd down the road?'' Featherston asked. ``In 40 years, if
this jury spares your life and you get out of prison, do you think
a black man would feel safe walking down Martin Luther King?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Berry answered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another of Byrd's sisters, Mylinda Washington, said that even
after sitting through three trials, the family is still haunted by
questions about what happened the night her brother was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll ever know what role each of these men
played, but I know all three participated,'' she said, ``because I
don't believe my brother would just sit there and let himself be
beaten and chained like that. The autopsy results show he was
fighting, and I know my brother said something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to know what he said.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, the Byrd family plans to visit James Byrd
Jr.'s grave a few blocks from the courthouse. They will lay flowers
and a banner that says, ``Justice for James. Rest in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
