<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4555 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-     11-18 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES A COMPROMISE BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for rewriting throughout) 
 (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT11 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ United by a desire to proclaim victory and leave
town, Republicans and Democrats in the House joined on Thursday
night to pass the final budget bill, seven weeks after the fiscal
year began.
</P>
<P>
   Congress then voted to keep the government running for two more
weeks while the Senate finished its work.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted, 296-135, for a package of five spending bills
containing $385 billion, sending the measure to the Senate. There,
an avalanche of oratory from three Senate Democrats seeking
benefits for their states blocked the bill's path and briefly
threatened a government shutdown, a threat that evaporated when the
Senate extended the budget deadline until Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the House passed a new continuing resolution, the
Senate did the same. A short time later, the White House chief of
staff, John Podesta, carrying the continuing resolution, left for
Athens so President Clinton could sign it.
</P>
<P>
   After the earlier House vote on the omnibus spending bill, in
which 170 Republicans were joined by 125 Democrats and one
independent in supporting the bill, both parties claimed political
victory in nearly identical language.
</P>
<P>
   After seven months of haggling over 13 spending bills, and after
10 days of negotiations between the White House and the Republican
leaders in Congress, both sides said the result represented the
essence of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called it ``a hard-won victory for the American
people.'' Podesta, simply said, ``We're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   And the speaker of the House, Dennis Hastert of Illinois, said
Congress had ``basically turned the corner on how this town does
business'' by limiting spending in a booming economy, allowing the
government to pay down part of its $3.6 trillion debt.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans won a $17 billion spending increase for the
Pentagon, along with more money for politically popular health
research and education. They said they kept their promise to
refrain from using excess contributions to Social Security to pay
for the spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats and the White House were able to assert that they
had won the money for hiring more primary school teachers and
police officers, underwriting Middle East peace agreements and
finally paying $351 million of $926 million withheld by Congress in
dues the United States owes the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed to provide $12.8 billion over five years to
teaching hospitals, nursing homes and other health care providers
who were suffering financially from cuts in Medicare imposed by
Congress in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The 84 Republicans voting no were protesting spending increases
won by the White House for programs like foreign aid and
environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
   The 51 Democrats who voted no, a quarter of their party in the
House, split with the president over the compromises the White
House made in its final negotiations with the Republicans. Some
rebelled over restrictions Republicans sought on aid to
international family planning groups in exchange for freeing up the
back dues owed the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed to a ban on using such aid to promote abortions
to free nearly $1 billion that the United States owes the United
Nations. He can waive the restrictions, but then $12.5 million in
federal grants to women's health groups would be shifted to a
children's fund.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Angry at this trade-off, 19 House Democrats who are women
demanded that the White House make amends. Steve Ricchetti, a
deputy White House chief of staff, told them on Thursday that the
administration would ask Congress next year for more than $500
million in grants for the groups.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats protested what they called bookkeeping tricks
that allowed Republicans to claim that they had protected Social
Security surpluses. The Congressional Budget Office says the bills
dip at least $17 billion into the retirement reserves.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The final deal, agreed to early Thursday morning, included some
of this sort of sleight of hand, such as delaying the last payday
of next September for Pentagon personnel and some civilian
government employees so it falls in the next fiscal year. That
saves no money, but eliminates expenditures in the 2000 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``These accounting gimmicks may appear to be funny,'' said Rep.
David Obey of Wisconsin, the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee. ``But they're corrosive of democracy and
of our role in it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was not ready to pass the bill. with three Democratic
senators threatening to hold it hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., threatened to hold back the continuing
resolution over a law, stripped from the final spending package,
which would have required satellite television companies to carry
local stations in rural regions. When the Senate majority leader,
Trent Lott of Mississippi, promised him the Senate would take up
such a measure by April, he relented.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., rose. He had threatened to block
any bill _ including a continuing resolution and the final budget
package _ over language in the spending bills that he said favored
dairy farmers in the East and hurt his state's milk producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the options we have is to vote against a continuing
resolution which would in effect shut down the government at
midnight, which is something I have considered,'' he said. ``It's
not a step that I'm going to take.''
</P>
<P>
   The maneuvering was necessary because Congress was operating
under a 24-hour continuing resolution, its sixth of the year, which
kept the agencies covered by the spending bills running without a
real budget. But the instant passage of a continuing keeping the
agencies going until Dec. 2 alleviated that problem.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will soon take up the final budget package, that
includes five separate bills in one:
</P>
<P>
   _ A $315 billion measure for the Departments of Health and Human
Services, Labor and Education. Of that sum, $229 billion is for
mandatory programs that Congress must finance, like Medicare and
Medicaid. The rest, $86 billion, is for programs like medical
research, special education and job training.
</P>
<P>
   _ A $39 billion measure for the Commerce, Justice and State
Departments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two $15 billion bills, one for the Interior Department, one
for foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   _ A $429 million bill for the District of Columbia. Added to the
bill was a $576 million emergency measure for the flood victims of
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the continuing resolution does not mean that the battles in
the Senate are over. Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia, dean of
Senate Democrats, took the floor on Thursday night with a
three-page amendment in hand, seeking to protect his state's coal
miners from a court ruling ordering them to stop dumping debris
from mountainside strip mines into valley streams. He sought to
attach it to any legislation he could, including one of three
continuing resolutions then being considered. The White House had
threatened to veto any bill containing an earlier version of his
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate met into the night it had not adopt his amendment
so far, but Byrd seemed certain to continue his efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
