<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4562 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-DISNEY-BOXOFFICE-LADN     11-18 0325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-BOXOFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERSEAS BOX OFFICE RECEIPTS TOP $1 BILLION, CLOSE IN ON RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dave McNary 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK -- With more than six weeks left in 1999, Walt Disney
Co.'s international box office receipts have topped $1 billion for
the fifth consecutive year, extending its industry record.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Buena Vista International operation crossed the
milestone Sunday, giving it a shot at topping its all-time mark of
$1.25 billion in 1997. 20th Century Fox posted the best-ever mark
last year with $1.95 billion, mostly due to ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bug's Life'' made the biggest contribution of 39 films with
$160.7 million overseas, followed by ``Enemy of the State'' with
$114.1 million, ``Runaway Bride'' with $110 million, ``Tarzan''
with $100 million, ``Armageddon'' with $82.9 million and ``The
Sixth Sense'' with $75 million. ``Tarzan,'' Disney's eighth
consecutive animated movie to top $100 million overseas, and
``Sense'' are still playing in major markets.
</P>
<P>
   Still due to contribute this year are ``Toy Story 2'' and Arnold
Schwarzenegger's ``End of Days.'' ``Runaway Bride'' was handled
domestically by Paramount and ``End of Days'' will be released in
the United States by Universal.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which also hit $1 billion overseas in 1997, is the only
other studio to achieve back-to-back years at the 10-figure mark.
Sony hit $1.25 billion in 1997 and Warner Bros. reached $1.07
billion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Disney is also within $25 million of going past $1 billion
domestically this year for the fifth time in six years while Warner
is $85 million away and Universal needs $150 million more.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic box office is 8 percent ahead of last year and
should finish around $7.5 billion. The National Association of
Theater Owners issued a forecast this week that 1999 admissions
will hit 1.6 billion, up from 1.48 billion last year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
