<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEWLETT-AGILENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFIT NEWS AND SPINOFF SEND HEWLETT SHARES UP SHARPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares of Hewlett-Packard jumped 17 percent
Thursday, one day after the company posted stronger-than-expected
quarterly earnings, set an aggressive sales goal for next year and
began spinning off its test and measurement business.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard shares closed at $94.3125, up $13.3125, on the
New York Stock Exchange. Shares in Agilent, the test and
measurement business that Hewlett-Packard is spinning off, were up
$12.50, at $42.50, in their first day of trading, also on the Big
Board.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard sold 72 million Agilent shares at $30 each on
Wednesday in the largest initial stock sale by a Silicon Valley
company and the ninth largest by a U.S. company this decade. The
sale represented a 15 percent stake and was $1 billion larger than
originally expected. Hewlett-Packard plans to distribute the
remaining shares to its shareholders next year.
</P>
<P>
   Of 21 analysts reporting to First Call/Thomson Financial, seven
raised their recommendations on Hewlett-Packard shares Thursday,
with four going to strong buy. The consensus estimate for the first
quarter of fiscal 2000 jumped to 78 cents from 73 cents, with the
full-year estimate moving to $3.37 from $3.27.
</P>
<P>
   After warning last month of an earnings shortfall,
Hewlett-Packard reported results on Wednesday that beat analysts'
revised estimates by 2 cents, not including charges related to the
spinoff of Agilent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Carleton S. Fiorina, who joined Hewlett-Packard in
July as president and chief executive, said in a conference call
with securities analysts that she was setting a goal for fiscal
year 2000 of 12 percent to 15 percent growth in sales and profit.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they liked what they heard on the call, referring
not only to Ms. Fiorina's ambitious goals, but to
stronger-than-expected sales of printers and high-end servers.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's PC business was strong and would have been
stronger had it not been constrained by component shortages caused
by the earthquake in Taiwan. Furthermore, she told the analysts,
the Hewlett operation was profitable, unlike some other
large-volume makers of personal computers. Storage systems also
have room for sales growth, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like this organization is clearly not broken,'' said
John B. Jones Jr., an analyst with Solomon Smith Barney. ``It's not
firing on all its cylinders yet, but Fiorina is aggressively
focusing them on segments of the market that can produce as much as
15 percent growth, or even higher, as they kick in,'' he said.
``Looking at the growth rate at other PC companies, or Sun
Microsystems, you can make the case that if she really fixes it,
there's a lot more upside here than 15 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most analysts, Jones could not comment on Agilent because
of his firm's involvement in the offering, but he said its success
probably helped increase investor confidence in Hewlett-Packard as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of confusion about how to value the Agilent
part,'' he said. ``It wasn't included in anyone's numbers and
people were trying to figure out how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Conigliaro, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs, said the
shares were due for a recovery after being overly beaten down in
response to the earlier warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What ended up happening is they did beat a number that had
been talked down,'' she said. ``But the stock had cratered, and
there were a lot of money managers who were underweighted on
Hewlett-Packard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4573 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-BUDGET-SPENDING-HNS &LR;      11-18 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES $385 BILLION SPENDING PACKAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House gave its overwhelming approval Thursday
to a final $385 billion spending package for the 2000 fiscal year,
ending nearly seven weeks of contentious negotiations with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But a dispute over dairy price controls, coal mine waste dumping
regulations and rural loan guarantees for satellite television
ventures threatened to hold up passage in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators were so angry over not getting their loan, dairy
and mining concerns addressed in the final bill that they sought to
block consideration of a temporary spending measure that would keep
government offices open until the Senate holds its final vote on
the budget and adjourns.
</P>
<P>
   But after some last-minute deal-making promising that their
concerns would be addressed in future legislation, the lawmakers
dropped their objections and the Senate joined the House in
approving a seventh stopgap measure to keep the government
operating through Dec. 2, if necessary. The last temporary spending
extension, known as a continuing resolution, was to expire at
midnight Thursday, and another extension was necessary to continue
funding seven government departments.
</P>
<P>
   The deal cleared the way for the Senate to take up the budget
package containing the last five of the 13 annual government
appropriations measures, and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., said he was hopeful a final vote would be held Saturday or
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., said he was prepared to
filibuster the final bill unless federal dairy price controls
favoring eastern and southern producers are changed.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote earlier of 296-135 in favor of the package came
after Clinton and Republican leaders signed off on the final
details of how to pay for increased spending in some programs
without tapping the Social Security Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Democratic and Republican leaders all hailed the final
bill as a winner for the country and for their own political
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget is a victory, and a hard-won victory, for the
American people,'' Clinton told reporters in Turkey, where he was
meeting with European leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing ... is that we didn't dip into the
Social Security trust fund,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill. ``It changed the way that this town does business and it
probably will put an indelible mark on how this country will see
its fiscal and financial future.''
</P>
<P>
   Even House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., offered limited
praise for the bill. He had indicated only a few days ago that he
might not support it. But he ended up encouraging his Democratic
colleagues to vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This package has a lot of good in it, it has a lot of bad in
it. But on balance it has more to recommend it than not,'' Gephardt
said.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote brought an end to months of intense political
wrangling over what to do with the first budget surplus in 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Congress, with Clinton's blessing, cobbled together
a $1.8 trillion budget for fiscal 2000 that includes about $610
billion in discretionary spending beyond the federally mandated
allocations for Social Security, welfare and other benefit
programs. The discretionary spending, including money Clinton
wanted for hiring new teachers and police officers, supporting the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, and paying U.S. dues owed to the
United Nations, came in at about $30 billion more than the spending
limits Congress and the president set in 1997 for the 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that $30 billion was added by Republicans before they
even entered negotiations with Clinton early last month, hoping to
shut off further demands from the president for additional money.
But during the negotiations, they ended up giving him nearly $6
billion in additional funding, although they forced him to accept
several creative ways of paying for it to avoid siphoning off the
money from Social Security funds.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most controversial cost-saving measures was an 0.38
percent across-the-board cut in federal spending, which will save
$1.3 billion. But in agreeing to the cut, which he had vowed to
fight only two weeks ago, Clinton won the right to implement it in
a way that is not expected to hurt important programs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton also agreed with Republicans to delay a
military pay day scheduled for Sept. 30 next year until Oct. 1, the
start of the 2001 fiscal year. That maneuver is expected to save
$3.5 billion by moving the payout, which includes a raise for
military and some civil service personnel, into the next fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   And in an effort to find more cash to pay for Year 2000
programs, Clinton also agreed to expediting the transfer of $3.7
billion from Federal Reserve private accounts to the U.S. treasury.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to increased spending for some of his favored
programs, Clinton also prevailed in having a number of
anti-regulatory provisions removed from the bill that he believed
would have been harmful to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was an amendment that would have allowed West
Virginia coal mining operations to continue razing moutaintops and
dumping the wastes into nearby streams and valleys in violation of
court rulings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans got a lot out of the negotiations as well,
including a provision limiting the amount of money the
administration can give to international organizations that perform
or promote abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Although mostly symbolic, the provision will limit the amount of
money available to those organizations to $15 million from a pool
of about $385 million dedicated to foreign family assistance
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also succeeded in winning more flexibility for
the states in using federal education money for teacher training
and other needs.
</P>
<P>
   But they boasted primarily of fulfilling their pledge not use
Social Security surpluses to fund government programs. However, in
order to make that claim the Republicans employed a number of
accounting techniques in order not to count about $17 billion that
will be spent in 2000 as part of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office says the money will actually
come from the retirement fund unless a revised analysis of federal
revenues scheduled for January shows a government surplus coming in
from non-Social Security sources.
</P>
<P>
   Although the budget package drew strong bipartisan support in
the House, some members complained about the creative accounting
they said was designed to ``cover up'' the Social Security
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill is replete with gimmicks. It contains $17 billion in
Social Security spending that simply won't be counted,'' said Rep.
David Obey, D-Wis., who voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Other members who ended up opposing it complained before the
vote that they had simply not had time to read through the
2,000-page bill, which wasn't written up and distributed to members
until midday Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget contains who knows what,'' said Rep. Sheila
Jackson Lee of Texas, who voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows what is in it and what is out of it,'' she added,
holding up a copy that had some provisions blacked out and others
handwritten into the margins.
</P>
<P>
   Other members opposed the bill on grounds that it resembled, as
one lawmaker put it, ``a huge Christmas tree filled with ``big ugly
ornaments'' for special interests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
