<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4574 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-WEEKEND     11-18 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-WEEKEND-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LUBBOCK _ The groundwork has been laid for a huge weekend of
sports, perhaps one of the biggest in the history of Texas Tech
University.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the competition will take place with a cloud over the new
basketball arena and the football program.
</P>
<P>
   The United Spirit Arena opens tonight when the Red Raiders host
Indiana and coach Bob Knight in a nationally televised (ESPN)
basketball game. The Lady Raiders, two-time defending Big 12
champions, follow Saturday night with the Four in the Fall Classic
doubleheader featuring UCLA, LSU and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But the $62 million arena comes with a price tag some have said
drained much-needed funds from the university's academic programs.
</P>
<P>
   The football team closes out the 1999 regular season Saturday
afternoon _ Parents Day _ against Oklahoma with a faint chance of
qualifying for a seventh consecutive trip to a bowl. And Wednesday,
Tech chancellor John T. Montford announced SBC Communications Inc.,
the parent company of Southwestern Bell, had donated $20 million
for the renovation of Jones Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the Thursday editions of the Lubbock Avalanche-Journal
sports section bore a blaring headline that indicated Tech athletic
administrators, according to unnamed sources, have been talking, or
intend to begin talks, with a Clemson assistant coach about
replacing football coach Spike Dykes, 61.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing so far has dampened the spirits of Tech athletic
director Gerald Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, this is the biggest weekend we've ever
had,'' he said. ``That arena opening up, that's something we've
been looking forward to for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sold out for Indiana; the football game, we're expecting
over 40 (thousand); we've got a chance to set an all-time
attendance record, average per game. We've got a lot of out-of-town
people coming in for the arena, the football game, and the Lady
Raiders the next night.''
</P>
<P>
   While not a sellout, Myers said he anticipates the new
15,000-seat arena will be full when Marsha Sharp leads the Lady
Raiders onto the floor for the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a big weekend for Texas Tech athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that varsity basketball at Tech would move out of
ancient, leaky, drafty Memorial Coliseum into a new arena have
circulated for almost as long as James Dickey has coached the
Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's real excited,'' said Dickey, entering his 10th
season. ``We really felt like we needed a new facility. The
Coliseum has been good to the university, but it was time after
about 40 years (to move). We're real proud of the United Spirit
Arena; it's a special place. And we're hoping to create a lot of
great excitement and memories in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But certainly, Indiana is a tough home opener.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hoosiers are 3-0 all-time against the Raiders. And Knight is
the winningest active NCAA Division I coach with 743 victories.
</P>
<P>
   But the basketball assignment is no tougher than that facing
Dykes and the Red Raiders in the regular-season finale. The
Oklahoma Sooners and passing sensation Josh Heupel bring a 6-3
record (4-2 in the Big 12) into Jones Stadium on Saturday. Oklahoma
averages 37 points per game and, on the strength of Heupel, is
ranked among the nation's top 10 in passing.
</P>
<P>
   But it might not be the Sooners or their quarterback that is the
biggest hurdle for the Raiders. The last three weeks have been
filled with rumors that Dykes would resign or be asked to leave at
season's end.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche-Journal reported a school had contacted Clemson
officials for permission to talk with offensive coordinator Rich
Rodriguez about a head coaching job. According to the
Avalanche-Journal's sources, the school was Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, formerly offensive coordinator at Tulane, has
declined to talk about job possibilities until after the Tigers'
season finale at South Carolina on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, citing school practice that was reiterated by Montford,
wouldn't confirm or deny contact with Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to say the same thing that I told (the
Avalanche-Journal),'' Myers said. ``We're going to address all of
these things at the end (of the season). We're not going to address
any rumors or any speculation or anything. That's basically what
the administration, the board, everybody else (has said) when all
these things started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll address it when the season's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers said Thursday's report disturbed Dykes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it made him feel too good,'' he said. ``He's
trying to finish up the season. It's definitely a distraction to
the players. Nobody's said anything to the players. I think it's a
distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What good does it do? I guess you create some interest. But
you've got a coach who's trying to finish up a season, has a chance
to qualify for a bowl. You don't have to talk to (the players)
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers also shot down speculation that cost overruns of a
reported $10 million on the new arena had forced the athletic
department to siphon funds from other areas of the university
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' he said. ``It's not anything I know about.
None of those funds, as far as I know, and I pretty well know,
affected any academic buildings or anything else. That's absolutely
wrong. We're responsible for paying the bonds on the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers said it is illegal for state funds not allocated for
athletic expenditure to be taken from another area of the
university's operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't spend (state) money on athletic facilities,''
Myers said. ``We have to generate our own from the private sector,
ticket sales, marketing, TV, radio, conference revenues. You just
can't do it. You can't use state funds to build athletic
facilities. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what Dykes chooses to do remains the subject for
speculation. A decision will be made, Dykes said, after he conducts
a personal evaluation and the athletic administration conducts a
routine postseason re-evaluation of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what happens, if he wants to step down or
whatever happens, I'd like for him to feel good about it, and to
treat him right,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior quarterback Rob Peters said he's disappointed the
injury-plagued Raiders (5-5, 4-3) haven't fared better. But he's
more upset over the way the football world in West Texas has
treated Dykes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that's happened to him. Coach Dykes has done a
great job here,'' said Peters, who will sit out Saturday's game
because of a concussion. ``I don't think people really realize what
he's done for this program. He's taken us to another level where
we're competitive every year. We've got a chance to win every year,
every game. We didn't have that before he got here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that people are kind of wishing him out. And I
think once he's gone, people will realize how much they would like
to have him back.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
