<SLUG> BC-TRADE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRADE GAP APPEARS TO BE STABILIZING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trade deficit appears to be stabilizing as foreign economic
growth picks up and the voracious American demand for imported
goods and services slows, Commerce Department figures showed
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While the gap by which imports outpace exports widened in
September, to $24.4 billion, the third biggest on record, analysts
said it would have narrowed for the second consecutive month had it
not been for the surging price of imported oil and an off month for
exports of aircraft, which tend to occur in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really seen some improvement'' since the deficit peaked
at $24.9 billion in July, said Robert D. Hormats, vice chairman of
Goldman, Sachs International and a former trade official in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He added that while the jump in oil prices would tend to mask
this trend in coming months, the United States was well positioned
to supply high-technology products to developing and newly
industrialized countries that are increasingly able to afford them.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the deficit with China in September inched up
to $6.9 billion from $6.87 billion. This provides ammunition to
those in Congress who oppose the agreement reached Monday under
which China is to lower barriers to American exports in return for
support of its application for membership in the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters, including Hormats, counter that such large
imbalances show how important it is that Chinese markets be opened
and that China be admitted to the world trade group, which sets the
rules for international trade.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the amount of what the United States bought from
China was 6.3 times what it sold to China, up from 5.9 times in
September 1998. Exports to China edged up just $100 million, to
$1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deficit with Japan climbed to $6.6 billion in
September from $6.4 billion, with American purchases 2.5 times its
sales compared with 2.1 times in the month a year earlier. Exports
were virtually unchanged at $4.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Noland, senior fellow at the Institute for International
Economics in Washington, said the deficit with Japan, whose economy
is still weak, would most likely expand in coming months until
higher prices slow Japanese exports.
</P>
<P>
   But he called trade adjustment elsewhere in Asia on track.
``Those economies are pulling out of their recessions,'' Noland
said, referring particularly to Hong Kong, Korea, Singapore and
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, American exports amounted to $81.7 billion in
September, $700 million less than the record set in August. The
biggest factor was a $900 million decline in capital goods, which
the Commerce Department said consisted primarily of civilian
aircraft. By contrast, agricultural sales, which have been
depressed, rebounded to the highest level in almost two years, and
consumer goods also sold better in world markets.
</P>
<P>
   Imports edged up to a record $106.1 billion, $700 million more
than in August, despite a $400 million decline in foreign motor
vehicles and parts. This is in sharp contrast to the first nine
months of the year, when automotive imports surged 22.5 percent,
compared with figures in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Swamping this was a huge rise in the nation's bill for imported
oil, a $6.8 billion jump reflecting higher volume as well as higher
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's deficit with the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries jumped to a record $3 billion in September from
$2.7 billion in August.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent stabilization, the American trade deficit so
far this year totals $191.6 billion, or 58 percent more than the
deficit in the period a year earlier. It is on a path to reach $255
billion.
</P>
<P>
   While this is already a record number of dollars, the deficit in
the past has represented a larger share of the American economy, a
more accurate measure of its importance. In 1987, the last time the
trade deficit set a record before this summer, it accounted for 3.3
percent of gross domestic product; it now represents 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's report also showed that the deficit with Western
Europe shrank to $3.5 billion from $4.4 billion, while that with
Canada fell to $2.9 billion from $3.3 billion. The deficit with
Mexico was unchanged at $2.2 billion. Unlike the aggregate figures,
comparisons with individual countries are not adjusted for
recurring seasonal variations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
