<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WARY OF USC'S SPEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sure, USC has a propensity for penalties,
squandering second-half leads and faltering in the face of its
crosstown rival.
</P>
<P>
   But the Trojans also have the great equalizer _ speed _ and
nothing scares UCLA's beleaguered secondary more than the prospect
of receivers R. Jay Soward and Kareem Kelly turning 10-yard passes
into 70-yard touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at their receivers' ability to make big plays with
the run and catch,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said. ``Speed will be
very important to the game, and they have a lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have not seen speed like they'll see Saturday. Ohio
State isn't as fast as USC. Neither is Oregon State or Oregon or
Arizona. One stumble, one missed tackle could mean a USC touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really fast, and that's something that has given us
trouble,'' Bruins safety Joey Strycula said.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way the Bruins can simulate USC's speed in practice,
but there are two ways to neutralize it:
</P>
<P>
   _Pressure quarterback John Fox. The more time he has, the more
time Kelly, Soward and Windrell Hayes have to run past the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blitz every down,'' UCLA defensive coordinator Bob
Field said. ``But if the quarterback's got all day, and he's got
fast receivers, that's a bad combination.''
</P>
<P>
   _Play conservatively. The Bruins probably will play a few steps
off the receivers and force USC to move the ball 5 yards at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be smart,'' Strycula said. ``We can't bite on the
hitch routes. We can't let them beat us deep.''
</P>
<P>
   How they stand: Safety Lovell Houston, who has started the last
three games, won't play because of a concussion suffered against
Washington. Sophomore Julius Williams, a converted cornerback, will
replace him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting ready as best I can so that hopefully I can step
in for Lovell,'' Williams said. ``I know the defense, but I'm
concentrating on understanding the offensive situations a little
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve safety Jason Stephens is questionable because of a
strained groin. If he can't play, struggling senior Eric Whitfield
will relieve Williams. Freshman Audie Attar, who's improving
rapidly but has little experience, is Strycula's backup at strong
safety. Junior Jason Zdenek has been pulled off the scout team in
case the Bruins need a fifth safety.
</P>
<P>
   Missing man: He has not played a game all season, and his name
is rarely mentioned on Spaulding Field. But chances are the Bruins
will miss suspended cornerback Marques Anderson on Saturday like
they have not missed him this year.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has a load of talent; he's fast, strong and physical.
And the two best games he's ever played are against USC. In 1997,
after Soward burned Jason Bell for an 80-yard touchdown on the
opening series, Anderson contained Soward the rest of the game.
Last year, Anderson had five tackles and forced two fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marques always got up for playing the tough games and the best
receivers,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: As for the key to victory, Toledo said: ``We need
to sustain some drives and score some points, and we have to keep
from giving up big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks it will be a high-scoring game, Toledo added:
``No. It better not be, because we can't score much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
