<SLUG> BC-TEN-CHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS DOESN'T LET NET OR OPPONENT GET IN HER WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Call it youthful exuberance, gamesmanship or a dollop
of showboating custom made for Madison Square Garden and its
partisan crowd: Venus Williams, turbo-charged at finding herself
three points from her first Chase Championships semifinal, indulged
a whim and leapfrogged over the net Thursday night as she and her
cowed opponent, Barbara Schett, switched sides for the first and
last time in their lopsided second-set tie breaker.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-seeded Schett took the conventional path around the
net. But Williams, in lift-off mode this week for her Chase debut,
took a more direct route. After she hurdled the net, she won the
next three points of the tie breaker, converting her first match
point by provoking a backhand return into the net from Schett, and
raised her arms to applaud the crowd, herself and her 6-4, 7-6
(7-2) victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like going around,'' Williams said of her flight
over the net. ``It seemed like such a long way to walk around, so I
was going to jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Schett, unable to beat the third-ranked American in all four of
their confrontations, chose not to find Williams' nimble maneuver
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe she tried to impress me or something; I don't know,''
Schett said. ``But it's entertaining for the people. It's good. If
I would be as tall as her, I probably could do it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Schett's mood was less than downcast after the loss, thanks to
some imminent vacation plans. Her season over, she intended to be
on Friday morning's first flight to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   As a favorite sparring partner of Steffi Graf during her final
year on the circuit, Schett was accustomed to dealing with baseline
power, but that did not give her the ability to consistently
counteract Williams' arsenal in this 1-hour-20-minute quarterfinal.
Her return was the shot that lost her the match, and not just at
match point: she earned only one break point against Williams'
serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's serving very well; it's very fast and I can't really
read it,'' Schett said. ``I had big troubles with her first serve.
Even her second serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams broke for a 4-3 edge in the first set and converted it
with a service winner. In the second, Schett kept up with her until
the tie breaker, then faltered.
</P>
<P>
   Schett opened the tie breaker by double-faulting and buried a
backhand in the net to set Williams up for her leap over the net at
4-2. The winner said she missed getting to prowl the city shopping
scene with her fourth-seeded sister, Serena, who withdrew Monday
with a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a rivalry,'' Williams said, as she cradled her
other best friend, her miniature Yorkshire terrier, Pete. But she
did not go so far as to wish her little sister back into this
event. ``It's good for everyone, I guess. They don't have to worry
about fighting against Serena. And I don't have to worry about
fighting against Serena.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's tough. Little sisters are mean,'' she said, paraphrasing
the post-match comment she had made to her sister just after having
been dethroned by her last month in Munich at the Grand Slam Cup
final.
</P>
<P>
   Williams indicated that, sister or no sister, she intended to
acquit herself impressively at this final tournament on the 1999
calendar, an event where she might rise to a career-best second in
the world if she can subdue its defending champion, top-ranked
Martina Hingis, in the semifinals and go on to claim the title.
Thursday night, Hingis encountered minimal resistance from
fifth-seeded Mary Pierce, and advanced, 6-1, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier this year, in the middle of the year, I was suffering
from not being able to win my tough matches, which is not like
me,'' said Williams, who is 5-8 against Hingis, but victorious in
their last two matches. ``So now I'm doing better with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
