<HEADLINE>
STUDENT'S FRANTIC CALL: `WE DON'T KNOW WHERE JOHN IS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM KIMBERLY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Eric Etheridge and John Comstock were
buddies from the Dallas suburb of Richardson, freshmen residents of
the same Aggie dorm and now co-workers on the growing Aggie
Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, they were assigned the grueling
midnight-to-6 a.m. shift, but they had grades to keep.
</P>
<P>
   Etheridge, 18, wanted to get some sleep before a test that
morning, and Comstock, 19, needed to study. They looked around to
see if they could sneak past the upperclassmen who were forever on
their case as they sat perched high in swings unloading logs that
were handed to them.
</P>
<P>
   About 2:30 a.m., Etheridge got down from the swing where he had
been handing logs over to workers on the stack. Comstock was still
up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and noticed it was leaning a lot. That's probably
when it started,'' Etheridge said. ``It just started to shift, then
there was a crash and then it fell.''
</P>
<P>
   The brightly lit site was suddenly dark. The light poles to
which guy wires were attached had been pulled by the toppling
stack.
</P>
<P>
   In the darkness, there were screams and cries.
</P>
<P>
   The senior members began to organize the students by dorms and
took a head count. At head count for Moses Hall, which had 19
residents at the site, Comstock was missing. He was trapped under
the logs.
</P>
<P>
   Etheridge went back to his dorm along with other students and
called his mother: ``We don't know where John is.''
</P>
<P>
   Etheridge's mom called Comstock's mother, Dixie Edwards in
Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards turned on the TV, and watched. ``I lost it, I thought he
was dead. I really thought he was dead,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She called other mothers of classmates. At 7 a.m. she got a call
from Comstock's minister with Central Baptist Church. At 9 a.m. she
watched the rescue of a student, who had been administered
intravenous fluids even as he lay beneath the logs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew it was him,'' she said. ``I didn't recognize him.
They had him all blanketed, but a mother knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening Comstock, a former soccer player for Dallas'
elite Jesuit High School, was at College Station Medical Center. He
had a broken arm and two broken legs, Etheridge said, and doctors
were trying to save his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
