<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4588 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-ALMVP-HNS &LR;      11-18 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALMVP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ARLINGTON _ A string of Gold Gloves speaks to sustained excellence.
A reputation for embarrassing even the best of baserunners precedes
him as well.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even so, Thursday was special. At the end of his finest season,
Texas Rangers catcher Ivan ``Pudge'' Rodriguez could add one more
distinction to his glittering list of accomplishments _ that of
being honored as the 1999 American League Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the award players dream of always,'' Rodriguez said at
a late-afternoon news conference at the Ballpark in Arlington. ``It
finally came true.''
</P>
<P>
   Not by much. In balloting by the Baseball Writers' Association
of America, Rodriguez actually drew fewer first-place votes (8-7)
than runner-up Pedro Martinez, the brilliant Boston Red Sox pitcher
who already had picked up the AL Cy Young Award after finishing
23-4 with a 2.07 ERA and 313 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, however, finished with 252 total points to 239 for
Martinez, in part because two of the 28 voters _ George King of the
New York Post and La Velle Neal of the Minneapolis Star Tribune _
refused to list Martinez among their top 10.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was the closest since 1996, when then-Ranger Juan
Gonzalez won the first of his two MVP awards in a 290-287 decision
over Seattle's Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Counting Gonzalez's 1998 MVP, this makes three times in the past
four seasons that a Ranger has won the AL MVP _ despite the fact
that the club has lost its last nine postseason games and has never
advanced beyond the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rodriguez enjoyed his best season, hitting .332 with 35
homers and 113 RBIs. That was the highest average for an AL catcher
since the Yankees' Bill Dickey hit .362 in 1936, and Rodriguez
became the first AL catcher to hit .300 and surpass 100 in both
runs scored (115) and RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   He threw out 39 of 72 would-be base stealers (54 percent), a
success rate that led all major-league catchers for the fifth
straight year. With 25 steals, he also became the first catcher
with more than 20 homers and more than 20 steals in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've recognized that he's been the best catcher in baseball
in all the previous awards that he's won,'' Rangers general manager
Doug Melvin said. ``This kind of tops it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who earned a $250,000 bonus for winning the award as
part of his contract, credited Rangers hitting coach Rudy Jaramillo
with helping produce his best offensive season, and cited work with
a personal trainer as a major factor in avoiding the second-half
burnout that had been a problem in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Puerto Rico native also grudgingly admitted that skipping
winter ball may have aided his stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``In September, I always got a little bit tired,'' he said.
``This year, it was exactly the opposite. I felt stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's Manny Ramirez and Roberto Alomar tied for third
place with four first-place votes and 226 points each. Rangers
designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro was next with four firsts and 193
total points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raffy's like my brother,'' Rodriguez said. ``He deserved the
MVP also. The way he played with a sore knee the whole year was
really something.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter was sixth, followed by Red Sox
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who just completed the second year of a five-year,
$42 million contract with the Rangers, expressed hope that he would
finish his career with the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be here until I hang up my glove and say I don't
want to play no more,'' he said. ``This organization is special,
especially for the Latin players.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Gonzalez, no longer is around after being dealt to
the Detroit Tigers in a multi-player deal as the Rangers determined
they would not be willing to meet his salary demands when he
becomes a free agent after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Among the day's highlights for Rodriguez was a congratulatory
call from his old teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Any messages?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got two; I've got one,'' Rodriguez said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to enjoy this one for a little while now, and who
knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
