<SLUG> BC-RITE-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RITE AID ANNOUNCES INQUIRY BY THE SEC INTO ACCOUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rite Aid Corp., the troubled drugstore chain, said Thursday that
the Securities and Exchange Commission had started a formal
investigation into its accounting practices and that its former
auditors resigned last week because they said they could no longer
believe management.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released after the close of the stock market
Thursday, Rite Aid, which is based in Camp Hill, Pa., said it
intended to cooperate fully with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the resignation by the company's accounting firm,
KPMG International, and of the SEC investigation were laid out in a
Form 8-K filing with the SEC. Such filings are used to report
important events or corporate changes.
</P>
<P>
   Securities analysts said the disclosures came as no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already been so surprised by the things going on there
that nothing is really shocking any more,'' said Mark Husson, an
analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid's accounting problems stem from a three-year
acquisition binge that effectively doubled the size of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The full extent of the difficulties became apparent only
gradually.
</P>
<P>
   The company's results have fallen far short of Wall Street's
expectations, its results for the last three years are being
restated and its chief executive, the architect of its expansion,
has resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, the company warned analysts that it would fall far
short of quarterly earnings estimates, and then reported numbers
that were even weaker than it had led Wall Street to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Leonard I. Green, a Los Angeles investment banker who
is also a big Rite Aid shareholder, was named chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Rite Aid's stock price has plummeted since its
problems began to emerge. The stock, which in the last year has
traded as high as $51.125, closed Thursday on the New York Stock
Exchange at $6.875, down 25 cents. The company is in the midst of a
search for a new permanent chief executive and chief financial
officer, posts it hopes to fill by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Finding capable candidates is proving difficult, Husson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the most attractive place to work right now,'' he
said. ``The new chief executive has a huge job in terms of
remotivating and regrouping a band of rather shell-shocked
troops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
