<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHECHNYA AND THE WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Nov. 19:
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin of Russia growled this week at Western
leaders meeting in Turkey that they had no right to criticize his
nation's war against ``bandits and killers'' in Chechnya. On this
point, the Russian president is simply wrong. Yeltsin and his
allies in Moscow need to listen to warnings by those leaders who
tried during the European security conference in Istanbul to
explain that using bombs and tanks would not work, militarily or
diplomatically, to oust Chechen terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac of France, for example, said this war
to combat terrorism was ``a tragic error'' that was taking too many
innocent lives in the breakaway republic. President Clinton, who
had compared the earlier Chechen war, from 1994 to '96, to
America's Civil War, this time tried another tack.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reminded Yeltsin about the beneficial side of meddling
by outsiders. He noted that the West had rallied to Yeltsin in
August 1991 as hard-liners tried to take over the government and
the Yeltsin forces were in the streets of Moscow. ``If they had put
you in jail instead of electing you president,'' Clinton told the
Russian leader, ``I would hope that every leader of every country
around this table would have stood up for you and for freedom in
Russia and not said, `Well, that is an internal Russian affair that
we cannot be part of.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was the tougher words of the Europeans, the more
understanding tone of Clinton or other unrevealed factors in the
Istanbul meeting, the Russians did agree to allow the chairman of
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe to visit
Chechnya and help seek a political resolution to the conflict.
That, at least, is good news. It means that the leaders meeting in
Turkey will have both a political and humanitarian role in the
region. But Chechnya is still a raw battlefield that Russian
leaders are using to rally political support at home even as
criticism mounts abroad.
</P>
<P>
   While Russia's need to pursue terrorism is understandable,
Yeltsin and his government should take note of Gov. George W. Bush
and those in the Clinton administration who want to take a harsher
line against Russia. Bush has suggested cutting off aid until
Russia stops killing Chechen civilians. Such threats, aimed more at
the American voters than at the international arena, sound better
on the campaign trail than they would as policy. Aid to Russia is
in America's own interest _ not only to provide help in dismantling
Russia's nuclear weapons but also to foster economic and civic
stability in an emerging democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, however, must realize that good will in the West
and especially in America is in their interest as well. The stream
of refugees from Chechnya and the bombings in downtown Grozny are
images the American people care about. In the long run, these
cruelties add to American doubts, not simply about Chechnya but
about the willingness of Russia's leaders to move away from the
brutal methods of the past.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
