<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-RAP-SONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT ON SONG, `ROSA PARKS,' IS REJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (th) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ Many of the lyrics in the song ``Rosa Parks''
by Outkast, a rap group, are not words generally associated with
Mrs. Parks.
</P>
<P>
   In the song named after the woman whose refusal to move to the
back of a bus in 1955 gave birth to the civil rights movement,
expletives and racial epithets are mixed with occasional sexual
references. Mrs. Parks is never mentioned, although the refrain is,
``Ah ha, hush that fuss/Everybody move to the back of the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday a federal judge rejected a lawsuit by Mrs. Parks
against the rap group and its producers. Mrs. Parks had contended
that the group had defamed her and had violated her ``right of
publicity,'' which is the right of individuals to withhold their
endorsement of commercial products unless they are compensated to
their satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Barbara K. Hackett of the U.S. District Court for the
Eastern District of Michigan ruled that the song was ``an
expressive work'' and protected by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The judge wrote that the song was at least partly about Mrs.
Parks and was not being used simply in a marketing or advertising
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the necessary linkage between title and content is
easily satisfied here, plaintiff would be hard-pressed to
demonstrate that defendants' use of her name as the title to their
song is `simply a disguised commercial advertisement' to sell a
product, especially considering the song has received widespread
acclaim and was nominated for a Grammy Award,'' the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The group did not ask Mrs. Parks' permission to use her name for
the song, which is on an album, Aquemini, that has sold 2.5 million
copies.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Beck of Atlanta, who defended Outkast, said the group
had meant to honor Mrs. Parks by naming the song after her. The
group told Rolling Stone magazine earlier this year that the
references to going to the back of the bus were intended to tell
other rap groups that Outkast had arrived on the music scene, and
did not allude directly to Mrs. Parks.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Mrs. Parks, Gregory J. Reed of Detroit, said that
he would appeal the decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2251EST &QL; 
