<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE LAST CLINTON BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Nov. 19:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's ambitious domestic agenda, presented last
January at the height of the impeachment struggle, always faced an
uphill struggle in getting approved by a Republican Congress. The
Republican counter-demand for a $792 billion tax cut was similarly
destined to be blocked by Clinton's veto. After a year of
posturing, the budget for this year that is finally getting enacted
this week _ the last of Clinton's presidency _ is striking for its
stringency. There are modest spending increases in some of the
president's priority areas like education, but over all the
Republican approach of spending restraint has shaped this budget.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his presidency with a $290 billion deficit and is
ending it with a surplus of more than $100 billion, a remarkable
achievement. This page, along with many people in Congress, would
prefer that during one of the longest periods of prosperity in
history the nation spend additional funds to expand health care,
clean up the environment, extend educational opportunities and face
up to other unmet needs. But as a practical matter, given
Republican control on Capitol Hill, any bold steps in these areas
would almost certainly have been enacted this year as part of a
messy compromise, with unnecessary tax cuts, military spending and
pork-barrel programs tacked on _ all of it using the hard-won
surpluses lying ahead. The new budget is surely better than such an
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The budget is an important marker for the vast political changes
of the last few years. When the era of budget surpluses began
dawning, Clinton challenged Congress to ``save Social Security
first.'' He insisted on deferring outsized tax cuts and spending
programs until steps were taken to assure that the Social Security
obligations could be met in the next century, when the baby-boom
generation starts to retire. Republicans, laboring to overcome the
public's longtime distrust of their intentions in this area,
responded by trying to outdo Clinton to ``save'' the retirement
system. They insisted this year on an end to the decades-long
practice of tapping Social Security tax revenues for regular
programs. They have largely won this argument, but the result is
that very little money is left over for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Within these restraints, Clinton scored well on a series of
skirmishes with Congress in the last several weeks. He has won
significant funding increases for teachers, police officers,
teaching hospitals, school programs in distressed areas, a ``new
markets'' initiative to encourage investment in poor communities
and a new drive to buy up undeveloped land. The deal that sealed a
budget agreement was the White House's willingness to adopt a
minuscule across-the-board budget cut, proclaiming that it is more
selective and less across-the-board than Republicans say.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is restrained fiscally, the budget leaves room for
more serious arguing about priorities in the next year, with
presidential candidates joining the fray. Republicans will continue
to argue that voters would prefer tax cuts above all else.
Democrats on the campaign trail and in Congress need to make the
case for using swelling revenues in future budgets to deal more
ambitiously with health care, schools and unmet social needs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
