<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4608 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-ASBESTOS-GRACE-SPI &LR;      11-18 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-GRACE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
W.R. GRACE STARTED IN THE BAT GUANO BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. had a not-so-fragrant beginning in 1854.
William R. Grace, who had fled the Irish potato famine to Peru,
chartered ships to trade bat guano and bird droppings.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, he moved his headquarters to New York and
set up a worldwide network trading fabric, fertilizer, machinery
and other products.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of World War II, William Grace's grandson, Peter,
took over control of the company and ran it for almost a half
century, until 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company's focus remained on chemicals and
packaging, Peter Grace diversified Grace into everything from
sporting goods to tacos.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1995, Grace divested many of its larger businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Securities and Exchange Commission sued Grace for
manipulating earnings in one of its divisions. To settle the suit,
Grace set up a $1 million financial education fund.
</P>
<P>
   Grace has gone through elaborate reorganization in the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers handling the asbestos suits against Grace say the
shuffling was done to conceal assets and cloud the corporate lines
of responsibility. Grace denies the charges and calls the moves
``solid business decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it has downsized, Grace's sales are still about $1.4
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   But like other giant companies that sold asbestos products
during the heyday of the flameproof fiber, Grace is still plagued
by lawsuits filed by people allegedly harmed or killed by the
fibers in the insulation, garden products and other applications it
sold.
</P>
<P>
   More than 250,000 asbestos-related suits have been filed against
Grace.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of them except the 187 involving the miners and the
families from Libby, are personal injury suits dealing with the
hazards of asbestos products, said Jay Hughes, Grace's top
litigation counsel.
</P>
<P>
   About 150,000 suits have been settled or dismissed. An estimated
102,000 cases remain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spotlight was thrown on one of Grace's darkest moments when
the movie ``A Civil Action'' was released in January.
</P>
<P>
   John Travolta and Robert Duvall dramatized the book of the same
name written by Jonathan Harr. The book told the story of families
living in the old New England mill town of Woburn on the outskirts
of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Five Woburn children and one adult died of acute lymphocytic
leukemia from exposure to chemicals in their drinking water. Others
were sickened. Grace and another company were found by the
Environmental Protection Agency to be responsible for dumping the
toxic chemicals that poisoned two of Woburn's wells.
</P>
<P>
   Grace paid $8 million to eight families in return for the
withdrawal of lawsuits they had filed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Grace was indicted by the Department of Justice on two
counts of lying to the EPA in 1982 about the amount of hazardous
chemicals it used at its Woburn plant. In 1988, Grace pled guilty
to one count and was fined the maximum _ $10,000. Today, the
penalty for that charge is $500,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0535 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4705 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-TRAGEDY-HNS &LR;      11-18 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-TRAGEDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY AMID TRADITION: AT LEAST 9 DEAD, 28 INJURED AT TEXAS A&AMP;M 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
and ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ A 40-foot tower of logs, carefully
assembled by students to be set ablaze in Texas A&AMP;M University's
most beloved tradition, tumbled to the ground in an instant early
Thursday, crushing at least nine people to death.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight students were injured when the structure on a
corner of the university campus collapsed about 2:45 a.m. CST. An
estimated 50 to 70 students were working on top of the pyramidlike
stack of logs at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden ... the center pole snapped, and everything
went with it,'' said Nathan Knowles, a freshman from Alba, who
jumped 25 feet from the perch where he was wiring logs to the stack
as it buckled under him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took five seconds, if that much, for the whole thing to
come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials identified the dead as Christopher Breen of Austin, a
1997 graduate; Jeremy Frampton, a senior psychology major from
Turlock, Calif.; Jamie Hand, a freshman environmental design major
from Henderson and the only female casualty; Christopher Lee Heard,
a freshman pre-engineering major from Houston; Lucas Kimmel, a
freshman biomedical science major from Corpus Christi; Bryan
McClain, freshman agriculture major, San Antonio; Chad Powell,
sophomore computer engineering major, Keller; Jerry Self, sophomore
engineering technology major, Arlington; and Nathan Scott West, a
sophomore oceanography major, Bellaire.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the nine confirmed dead, at least two students _
one male and one female _ were known to be buried Thursday night
under the mound of timber that was to have become fuel for A&AMP;M's
annual bonfire. Rescuers continued to carefully remove logs to try
to reach these victims, but hopes that they might be found alive
was dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good, but there's always hope,'' university
spokeswoman Cindy Lawson said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day two students were rescued, including one who
was administered intravenous fluids as he lay beneath the logs with
two broken legs and other injuries.
</P>
<P>
   At least five of the nine confirmed dead were members of A&AMP;M's
1,962-member Corps of Cadets.
</P>
<P>
   University officials and police had not determined what caused
the bonfire to collapse, but witnesses said it happened quickly,
and then chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Harris, 19, a freshman from Longview, said he saw stunned
students turning to assist their injured colleagues as emergency
medical crews began arriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just crazy. It was chaos. Everyone was running around.
There were people lying around everywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he clung to a log as the stack fell. He did not
remember hearing anything but the voice of a fellow Corps of Cadets
member, Jody Jacobs, yelling at everyone to ride the stack to the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the tragedy, a pervasive sense of gloom
descended on the campus, and silence replaced the pre-bonfire
excitement and banter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still hasn't sunk in yet,'' said Harris. ``I still find
myself talking about getting things for the bonfire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggie Bonfire, a 90-year-old tradition on campus, was being
built in anticipation of A&AMP;M's football game with its arch-rival,
the University of Texas, on Nov. 26. The stack of logs would have
been lit Thanksgiving night.
</P>
<P>
   For several days, students _ elaborately trained _ had been
working in shifts around the clock to assemble the structure.
University officials said the bonfire had reached a height of about
40 feet. When completed, it would have been 55 feet tall and
included 6,000 to 7,000 logs from trees in the area felled by
students.
</P>
<P>
   This year's bonfire, however, is canceled. And the future of the
event seems uncertain, although many students and alumni said they
believed the tradition should be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   No full-time university staff members were on site at the time
of the bonfire collapse, although Thompson had checked on the
construction at 10:30 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Aggie Bonfire is a student-run organization,'' said
Rusty Thompson, faculty adviser to the operation. ``And these
students who work on the bonfire are adults.''
</P>
<P>
   He said licensed crane operators were at the site at all times
during construction. The rescue efforts were tedious and
meticulous, as crane operators carefully picked logs off one by
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical that the dismantling of this stack be in an
orderly fashion,'' said Bart Humphreys, spokesman for the College
Station Fire Department, which was heading up the rescue operation.
``It's like Pick-up Sticks. These logs are all intertwined. We can
work on one side of an area, but once these logs become interlaced
we have to work from a different angle in order to get deeper in a
certain spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials had used sensitive listening devices, such as the type
used to find earthquake victims, trying to locate students. By late
afternoon, a golden retriever from the Austin Police Department was
brought in to help search for more victims.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen said notes and phone calls of
condolences had been pouring into the school from all over the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great tragedy,'' Bowen said. ``Everybody is just
broken-hearted about what has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers from Houston, San Antonio and Austin were sent
Thursday afternoon to help relieve crews that had been working in
60- to 90-minute shifts since before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said engineering faculty members and other experts are
examining the logs as they are picked off the pile, hoping to be
able to determine what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Early speculation about the cause of the tragedy focused on a
possible break of the center pole, a key design feature. Several
witnesses reported having heard the pole snap, but Thompson said
this had not been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The center pole is actually two poles that are spliced and
bolted together and then wrapped with 660 feet of steel cables.
While there were visible breaks in the center pole, Thompson said
it is too early to determine if that was the cause of the collapse
or if they broke after the logs started tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
