<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COACHES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT, TOLEDO AREN'T EXACTLY BUDDIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just because UCLA coach Bob Toledo and USC coach
Paul Hackett are rivals, it doesn't mean they can't like each
other.
</P>
<P>
   It just so happens they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett speculated recently that maybe his getting hired at USC
might be something Toledo resents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bob and I both grew up with USC as the football school
in this city,'' Hackett said. ``Did he have a choice when he came
back (to UCLA)? He was out of work. He was fired at Texas A&AMP;M. Is
that a lot of choice?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked when he closed USC practice on Wednesday if he was copying
Toledo's tradition of closing Bruins practices the week of the big
game, Hackett answered:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to keep up with Bob, that's been one of my real focuses
of my whole career, to keep up with Bob,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Toldeo has been able to hold his own in this verbal warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Asked last year if UCLA's season was a disappointment because it
lost its final two games, including the Rose Bowl, Toledo fired
back, ``It's not like we got embarrassed by a 6-5 team or
anything,'' an obvious reference to USC's loss to Texas Christian
in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett wasted little time responding: ``You know what's
interesting about Bob? He keeps looking over here. I'm not looking
over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even someone as smooth and diplomatic as former USC coach John
Robinson, who hired both coaches as assistants in the 1970s,
couldn't deny the animosity the two have for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be something to it,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   So how would Robinson describe the relationship? ``I think it's
passable.''
</P>
<P>
   Quizzed directly about their relationship, both coaches offer
near-identical responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not that close. We're not bosom buddies,'' Toledo said.
``It's not like I get on the phone and call him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a bosom-buddy relationship,'' Hackett said. ``We
don't go out of our way to see each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The public saw first-hand the strained atmosphere between the
coaches following UCLA's 34-17 victory last season. Hackett was
incensed afterward because Bruins quarterback Cade McNown faked a
pitch in the final 30 seconds and reversed field for a 23-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what that last play of the game was about,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Did Hackett think it was uncalled for? ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, Hackett is bothered about the incident. ``Was he
thinking, `Let's just rub it in?' It's unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   From whence does the animosity spring? One need only look at
their resumes. Both grew up in the Bay Area and played quarterback
for their high school teams. Toledo starred for Lincoln High in San
Jose, while Hackett led Miramonte High in Orinda, outside Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   A year apart in age, they became rival college quarterbacks
playing in the Far Western Conference _ Toledo for San Francisco
State, Hackett for UC Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But things didn't really get rocky until 1976, when both were
hired by Robinson as assistants at USC.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably only natural they became rivals. Hackett was
unyielding, arrogant and on his way toward becoming known as a
quarterback expert. He also held the job Toledo really wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo coached the secondary, a frustrated offensive specialist
coming to USC just to get his foot in the door at a major college.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hackett denies being aware of any jealousy from Toledo,
but his answer has an edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have come about from his side, but, hey, I had the
job,'' Hackett said. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, too, denies having a problem with Hackett, but he
acknowledges he will never ignore him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respond to comments. I try to use everything ' Toledo
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
