<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDENTITY OF BRICK-ATTACK SUSPECT STILL UNKNOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUAN FORERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Detectives searching for the man who smashed a
27-year-old midtown Manhattan office worker with a brick took to
the subways and knocked on doors on Manhattan's East Side Thursday
in an intensive effort to find anyone who could identify the
assailant.
</P>
<P>
   Using 60 detectives and dozens of patrol officers, the police
focused on the area stretching from the East 30s to the East 70s,
paying particular attention to one location: Madison Avenue and
East 75th Street. It is at the spot that investigators now believe
the attacker found the brick used in the attack, removing it from
the base of a tree, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After being shown sketches of the attacker, some people in the
area told the police they believed they had at one time seen the
assailant.
</P>
<P>
   But no one was able to give the police a full name or lead
detectives to where the man could be found, police officials said.
As a result, investigators were having a hard time narrowing their
search.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Nicole Barrett, who was struck from behind on
Tuesday afternoon for no apparent reason as she prepared to cross
Madison Avenue at 42nd Street, has once again reminded the city
that despite the drop in crime over the last few years, random
violence can easily shatter the perception that the city is safe.
As a result, the police force has devoted extraordinary resources
to finding the attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett, who last year moved with a friend from Texas to New
York, was transferred Thursday from the surgical recovery room at
Bellevue Hospital Center to the neurosurgical intensive care unit,
where she remained in critical but stable condition, said Lorinda
Klein, a hospital spokeswoman. After the attack, Ms. Barrett
underwent two operations to relieve the pressure on her brain
caused by a skull fracture she suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's still critical but improving. She's not out of the woods
yet; she's unconscious but she's not in a coma,'' said Ms. Klein,
attributing the assessment to Dr. Patrick Kelly, the chairman of
the Neurosurgery Department at Bellevue. ``We're cautiously
optimistic that things will work out and she'll continue to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett's parents, Sharon and Arlen Barrett, who on
Wednesday flew to New York from their home in Athens, Texas, and
were taken to the hospital by city officials, remained there
throughout the day. Ms. Klein said the couple were overwhelmed by
the outpouring of support from New Yorkers, several of whom had
sent flowers and called in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our family has deep faith that Nikki will make it through,''
the family said in a statement released by the hospital. ``God will
see our family through this. We appreciate your prayers and good
wishes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
