<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW STONEMAN CAN FOCUS ON FINLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Now that he has a manager in place, Anaheim
Angels general manager Bill Stoneman can focus on re-signing
pitcher Chuck Finley.
</P>
<P>
   But will he?
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman would like to hire a scouting director as soon as
possible and wants to delve into discussions with other teams about
possible trades. As for Finley, Stoneman had a 10-minute telephone
conversation with him Wednesday, just before Finley left on a trip
to talk with representatives of the Seattle Mariners and Arizona
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to Chuck I still want to meet face to face,'' Stoneman
said. ``I have to determine what Chuck Finley really wants. Does he
want to go to a club that's been a proven contender in recent years
so he can get that ring he doesn't have? Or is it important for him
to be an Angel the rest of his career and form part of the winning
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who turns 37 this month, will command as much as $9
million per season for as many as three seasons in the free agent
market, something the Angels seem unwilling to match.
</P>
<P>
   ``If another club comes along and makes an offer to him that
blows him away that we can't match, we won't,'' Stoneman said. ``We
won't go beyond our means to retain him. Are we interested in
having him back? Sure, we want him back. But you have to live
within your means. We're not going to design our payroll around
what a player wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, though, has said that money isn't the most important
aspect of a contract to him. And in fact, in past years he has
taken less from the Angels than he could have gotten on the free
agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Finley or no Finley, Stoneman says his primary focus is on
obtaining starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already got a couple of old guys in (Tim) Belcher and
(Ken) Hill, and we've got a few young guys (Jarrod Washburn, Ramon
Ortiz and Brian Cooper),'' Stoneman said. ``We'd like to get some
guys that fall in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Never say never: Toward the end of the 1999 season, Angels
president Tony Tavares said he wouldn't hesitate to trade all 25
players if it were possible. Wednesday, he was asked if Mo Vaughn,
who just completed the first year of a six-year, $80-million
contract, is untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never say never to anybody'' Tavares said. ``If Wayne
Gretzky can be traded, anybody can. Who knows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
