A4744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-PCB-NYT &LR;      11-18 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PCB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 EDITORIAL: A NEW FRONT IN THE PCB WAR  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Nov. 19:
</P>
<P>
   New York's attorney general, Eliot Spitzer, who has been suing
big corporations right and left recently, has now charged General
Electric with impeding navigation along a stretch of the Hudson
River and thus preventing the river from reaching its full
potential as a commercial and recreational waterway. The suit
represents a novel attempt to speed a resolution of the 25-year
controversy over PCB contamination in the Hudson River. If
successful, the suit may also establish a precedent for claims
against other companies whose activities can be shown to have
restricted economic development along New York's waterways.
</P>
<P>
   But the furor surrounding Spitzer's announcement inflates its
immediate importance. The real battle is still the struggle between
the company and the federal Environmental Protection Agency, which
will decide late next year whether to require GE to undertake an
expensive dredging operation to rid several contaminated ``hot
spots'' in the river of PCBs. GE has never denied responsibility
for the chemicals, which were discharged from two now-defunct
plants north of Albany years ago. The EPA regards PCBs _
polychlorinated biphenyls _ as a health risk to wildlife and to
people who regularly eat fish caught in the upper Hudson. PCBs are
also among the biggest remaining obstacles to the ecological
recovery of the river.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's suit does not address environmental or health risks.
Instead it argues that the costs associated with removing and
storing toxic sediments are so high that the state has been unable
to dredge an important navigable waterway that stretches from Lake
Champlain to Waterford, about 30 miles south of the old GE plants.
As a result, Spitzer asserts, economic activity has suffered. His
suit seeks to force GE to pay the extra costs of dredging the PCBs,
a sum that could be at least $10 million. At his news conference,
Spitzer openly invited other communities up and down the Hudson to
bring similar actions if his strategy turns out to be successful.
His hope is to achieve what one of his associates called a
``critical mass'' of lawsuits that will force GE to undertake
widespread dredging, whatever the outcome of the EPA investigation.
</P>
<P>
   GE, which called the suit absurd, was not alone in questioning
Spitzer's approach. To begin with, there was much confusion over
whether the channel actually needed dredging, with the New York
State Canal Corp. saying no and several local officials saying yes.
The Canal Corp., a division of the state Thruway Authority,
controls 524 miles of canals. It would presumably have to put up
part of the money if a judge rules in favor of dredging the
channel.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John Cahill, Gov. George Pataki's environmental
chief, warned that the depositions and other requirements
associated with the suit would siphon valuable resources from the
environmental agency's study and from a state investigation. The
Pataki camp, unduly sensitive to any challenge to the governor's
claim to be the state's top environmentalist, is clearly annoyed by
Spitzer's intervention. Compared with the EPA's investigation of
health and ecological damage along the entire river, Spitzer's suit
seems too narrow to get the job done. But the war to rid the Hudson
of PCBs is an important one, and Spitzer has every right to join
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0545 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
