<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-MALINO-NYT &LR;      11-18 0216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MALINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 JOHN G. MALINO, 60; EXECUTIVE AT LOEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John G. Malino, an executive with Loews Corp. in New
York who oversaw all its real estate activities, died Sunday at a
hospital in Manhattan. He was 60.
</P>
<P>
   He died of complications from heart surgery performed last
month, said Candace Leeds, a spokeswoman for Loews.
</P>
<P>
   Malino, who lived in Woodmere, N.Y., worked at Loews for 35
years, starting in the real estate department of Loews Theaters in
1964.
</P>
<P>
   He was named vice president of real estate for the entire
corporation in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1994, Malino was honored by the Real Estate Board of
New York for ``the most ingenious deal of the year'' _ securing the
Ed Sullivan Theater in Manhattan for the ``Late Night With David
Letterman'' show on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Malino had worked with CBS real estate executives to help
relocate the show and to buy and renovate the theater, at 1697
Broadway and 53rd Street, and some adjoining office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   John Gray Malino was born on Oct. 15, 1939, in Brooklyn and
graduated from New York University.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Phyllis; four daughters, Joanne
Ruggiero, Debbie Ackerman, Linda Malino and Dana Rich, all of
Manhattan, and two grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
