<SLUG> BC-REGAL-HOTELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON COMPANY TO BUY REGAL HOTELS IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A London real estate company has agreed to buy the 28 Regal
hotels in the United States for about $253 million plus the
assumption of $387 million in debt from Regal Hotels International
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The hotels include the Regal U.N. Plaza in Manhattan, the Regal
Biltmore in Los Angeles, the Regal Bostonian in Boston and the
Regal McCormick Ranch in Scottsdale, Ariz. Regal is a unit of
Paliburg Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The real estate company, Millennium &AMP; Copthorne, which is traded
on the London stock exchange, is 52.4 percent owned by CDL Hotels
International, which is headquartered in Singapore and listed on
the Hong Kong exchange. CDL is a unit of the Hong Leong Group.
</P>
<P>
   Kwek Leng Beng, the chairman of both CDL and Millennium &AMP;
Copthorne, said, ``The Regal purchase enables the group to acquire
in a single stroke a substantial presence in the world's largest
hotel market, thereby fulfilling our publicly stated ambition of
becoming a truly global hotel operator.''
</P>
<P>
   Millennium and Copthorne already owns 42 percent of the Plaza
and has interests in the Millennium Broadway and the Millennium
Hilton, all in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Other hotels in its latest acquisition are located in Chicago,
Minneapolis and St. Louis, among other major business centers. All
of those hotels, which eventually will be renamed Millennium, are
upscale properties with conference rooms, fitness clubs, swimming
pools and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   An additional eight hotels in the package announced Thursday are
full service hotels operating under such brand names as Comfort
Inn, Clarion and Four Points. The remaining eight properties are
limited service hotels. David Cook, the finance director of
Millennium &AMP; Copthorne, said in a telephone interview that the
company would assess the performance and standards of each hotel
and would probably sell some of them.
</P>
<P>
   In the year ended Dec. 31, 1998, Regal hotels in the United
States had after-tax profit of $22.5 million on revenue of $265.9
million. Millennium &AMP; Copthorne's profit in 1998 _ a year in which
it owned only 24 hotels _ was $98.2 million on revenues of $360.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Including the pending Regal acquisition, Millennium &AMP; Copthorne
will have spent more than $1 billion in less than a year to acquire
hotels, more than doubling their number to 117 and doubling the
number of rooms to 30,571. Among its acquisition were 43 hotels in
Asia and the Pacific, acquired from its parent company, CDL.
Earlier this month it acquired the 673-room Seoul Hilton Hotel for
$228.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we knew if we wanted to be a truly global player,'' Cook
said, ``we would have to play in the biggest market in the world,
and the biggest market is the USA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
