<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVENPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 LANOUE DAVENPORT, 77, EXPERT IN EARLY MUSIC AND INSTRUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LaNoue Davenport, a pioneering figure in the revival of early
music and period instruments and a former leader of the acclaimed
ensemble New York Pro Musica and the American Recorder Society,
died on Nov. 4 at Good Samaritan Hospital in Suffern, N.Y. He was
77 and had been suffering from emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   Little in Davenport's youth suggested that he would one day be
involved with medieval and Renaissance music. Born in Dallas on
Jan. 26, 1922, Davenport began his musical career playing the
trumpet in small jazz bands. He earned a double scholarship in
basketball and music to Texas Christian University. Later he
enlisted in the Navy, serving in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   During these years he was recruited to play the trumpet in
Claude Thornhill's band, which toured from ship to ship
entertaining crew members. After the war he moved to New York,
where his elder brother, Pembroke, a director of musicals (``Kiss
Me, Kate'') helped him get work in Broadway pit bands.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, Davenport enrolled in the New York College of Music,
where he became a protege of the German composer and musicologist
Erich Katz, who introduced him to early music. In 1953 he began
playing with the newly formed New York Pro Musica, directed by Noah
Greenberg. He assumed the directorship after Greenberg's death in
1966, though in 1970, he formed his own ensemble, Music for a
While, taking some Pro Musica players with him.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's association with the American Recorder Society began
in the late 1940s. He edited the society's newsletter during the
1950s and became its first national president in 1960.
Concurrently, in 1957, he founded and directed the Manhattan
Recorder Consort.
</P>
<P>
   Atypically for champions of early music on period instruments,
Davenport encouraged his musicians to include contemporary works on
programs. Under his leadership, concerts by the Manhattan Recorder
Consort often included music by Hindemith, Britten and other
20th-century composers along with medieval and Renaissance works.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He served on the faculty of Sarah Lawrence College and was also
a noted arranger and editor of early music.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is survived by his wife, the soprano Sheila
Schonbrun-Davenport of Stony Point, N.Y.; their two sons, Stefan
and Chester; two sons from his first marriage, Darius and Mark; and
six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
