r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      11-18 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN ON STUMP MISSES SENATE VOTES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain wasn't there when the Senate voted on raising
the minimum wage and cutting business taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't around to vote on an African and Carribean trade
package, or to weigh in on the use of leg traps in wildlife
refuges, or restricting credit-card ownership by people under 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator missed votes on whether to condemn President
Clinton for granting clemency to Puerto Rico nationalists, or to
symbolically endorse the ``Roe vs. Wade'' decision legalizing
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigns hard for the GOP presidential nomination, McCain
is missing votes more frequently than anyone in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He is proving the adage that you can't be two places at once.
Quite often, he's opting to be in New Hampshire, South Carolina and
other key primary states instead of on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has a history and tradition of solid attendance, and
McCain, until this year, was no exception. In 1998, senators
participated in an average of 97.4 percent of 314 recorded votes,
and McCain came in at 94 percent, according to ``Congressional
Quarterly.'' Sixteen senators didn't miss a single vote last year.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this year is different for McCain, who has emerged as
the leading alternative to GOP presidential front-runner George W.
Bush. From July 1 to Oct. 1, a particularly busy campaign period,
McCain missed 41 of 108 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever possible, he tries to make it back for the major
legislative votes, but unfortunately that's not always feasible,
given the hectic travel schedule and demands of a presidential
candidate,'' McCain spokeswoman Nancy Ives said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain missed the opening of his South Carolina campaign
headquarters so he could be in Washington to vote on a GOP tax
bill, Ives said. He also was absent from several town meetings in
New Hampshire so he could vote on a partial-birth abortion ban, and
his wife, Cindy, hosted the meetings in his place.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is doubtless receiving few accommodations from Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, the key player in the scheduling of
important votes. Lott and McCain have disagreed for years over
McCain's legislation to reform the campaign-finance system, and the
battle seemed to turn personal this past year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the absences, McCain, chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee, has shepherded through legislation encouraging
businesses to correct Y2K problems and helped negotiate an
agreement for a TV ratings system, his staff said. He pushed for
congressional approval for an environmental and habitat restoration
project along the Salt River.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who lacks Bush's large campaign bankroll, is often away
because he is relying on campaigning and television appearances to
compensate for the Texas governor's huge money advantage.
</P>
<P>
   This year, McCain has appeared more frequently than any of his
colleagues on the Sunday news shows, so far with 24 appearances,
according to ``Roll Call,'' the Capitol Hill newspaper. He has
undertaken two national book tours to promote his bestseller,
``Faith of My Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether McCain will come under criticism
for his Senate absences, or whether voters will be understanding.
</P>
<P>
   He is not up for Senate re-election until 2004. His 1998
campaign opponent, Democrat Ed Ranger, unsuccessfully sought to use
McCain's presidential ambitions against him, suggesting he would
abandon voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what he's doing? He's running for president,'' Ranger
said last October, a few months before McCain announced formation
of a presidential exploratory committee. ``He's going to roll all
that money into a presidential fund the day after the election.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain easily defeated Ranger in the election. McCain did
eventually transfer $1.9 million in leftover contributions from his
Senate campaign into his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the votes McCain missed were not close enough, at
least in the final tally, for McCain's absence to have made an
appreciable difference.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of the votes he missed were on lightweight issues.
</P>
<P>
   In the minimum-wage debate, for example, the Senate voted on
Nov. 9 for a package of business tax cuts, and raised the hourly
wage by $1 to $6.15. The vote was 54-44.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier the same day, the Senate rejected, by a vote of 50-48,
an alternative Democratic plan that would have raised the minimum
wage more swiftly than the GOP intended.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., was steaming mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how members who voted for their own pay increase
but against our minimum-wage proposal will be able to face their
constituents and explain their actions,'' Kennedy said, according
to the ``Washington Post''.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, there was a different sort of problem. He has to
explain not how he voted on the minimum-wage bill, but rather why
he didn't vote on it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
