<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STINK-BOMB-CHARGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER N.Y. CITY OFFICIAL CHARGED WITH SETTING OFF STINK BOMBS IN
PLANES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former New York City health official was charged on
Thursday in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn with assaulting and
intimidating Trans World Airlines crew members last year after
detonating stink bombs on a flight taking off in New York and one
departing from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The former official, Victor E. Botnick, 45, set off a stink bomb
under his seat on TWA Flight 925 during takeoff from Charles De
Gaulle Airport on Aug. 1, 1998, according to court papers. The
searing fumes made crew members and passengers teary-eyed, forcing
the plane to return to the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days later, court papers said, Botnick set off another
stink bomb as TWA Flight 924 took off from Kennedy International
Airport. This time, two crew members checked beneath Botnick's seat
and found glass shards and a wet area reeking of burning rubber,
according to the papers.
</P>
<P>
   The court papers said that Botnick, a frequent flyer on TWA, had
become angry after the airline inadvertently canceled his family's
reservations on a flight to Israel to celebrate his son's Bar
Mitzvah in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Botnick, a resident of Yonkers, N.Y., was released yesterday on
$150,000 bond. Federal Magistrate Roanne L. Mann instructed Botnick
to stay away from airports and airplanes unless he received
specific approval from the court.
</P>
<P>
   Botnick, who was accompanied by his wife, Lee, glared at
reporters as he left the courtroom and said ``no comment'' to
questions. When a reporter tried to follow him, he turned around
and said ``Did you understand? No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 80s, Botnick served as a special assistant and confidante
to Mayor Edward I. Koch. He resigned as the head of the municipal
hospital system in 1986 after admitting that he had falsely claimed
to be a college graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Gina L. Mendola, Botnick's lawyer, said the charges against him
were ``trumped up'' to support a separate federal investigation in
New Jersey. ``There is not a great deal of evidence against my
client,'' she said in court, but declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia M. Monaco, the assisant U.S. attorney who is handling
the case against Botnick in Brooklyn, confirmed that he was being
investigated by the U.S. attorney's office in New Jersey on a
separate matter, but denied that there was any connection. Michael
Drewniak, a spokesman for the attorney's office in New Jersey, said
there were no charges against Botnick at this time, but declined to
comment further.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's hearing, Ms. Monaco requested that Botnick, who is
unemployed, undergo a psychiatric evaluation. The court denied the
request after Botnick's lawyer objected, but ordered him to
continue psychiatric counseling with his own doctor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
