r e BC-TV-WEEKEND-REVIEW-SFC     11-18 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC'S `Y2K' A REAL DISASTER FOR VIEWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Reviews of CBS' ``Sarah, Plain and Tall: Winter's End,'' 
 HBO's ``RKO 281'' and PBS' ``Shooting the Past'' follow. Check 
 local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ken Olin should be enjoying his fourth season as the star of
``EZ Streets,'' but instead he's made a garbage movie for NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, airing Sunday, is ``Y2K,'' a typically artless
disaster movie in which the villain is the Y2K computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   Olin is a government computer expert and rugged action hero who
is shocked, appalled and yet strangely laid-back when all hell
breaks loose on New Year's Eve 1999.
</P>
<P>
   An F-18 crashes in the Marshall Islands, bodies pile up at a
Swedish nuclear power plant, the Champs-Elysees and Times Square go
dark, computer-controlled cell doors swing open at maximum-security
prisons, an airliner is in trouble over Washington, D.C., and it's
minutes to meltdown at a nuclear plant near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I suspect, it's tough logging onto AOL.
</P>
<P>
   So the producers and writers have assembled their inventory of
everything that can go wrong, Y2K-wise, and made it all go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Not that NBC would want to alarm anybody. ``This program does
not suggest or imply that any of these events could actually
happen,'' says a cautionary warning at the movie's start.
</P>
<P>
   Given the level of believability on TV shows today, the warning
should be superimposed over most shows.
</P>
<P>
   But only a perfect imbecile would get revved over a movie this
horridly unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, in one moment Olin is at Dulles airport in Washington
to save the airliner. It's several minutes past midnight, Eastern
time. A scene later, he's in Tacoma, Wash., before midnight Pacific
time.
</P>
<P>
   I figure he's had 2 1/2 hours, tops, to fly 2,400 miles, east to
west, with or without in-flight beverage service.
</P>
<P>
   Possible? Yeah, but a viewer might expect some rudimentary
explanation. There is none. Did you know that TV movies in the
1990s are written by monkeys? Is that a secret?
</P>
<P>
   The final words spoken in this predictable sweeps month
monstrosity: ``I think something's wrong in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh really.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   While NBC implies and suggests Mach speed, CBS slows time for
Sunday's Hallmark Hall of Fame presentation of ``Sarah, Plain and
Tall: Winter's End.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the third installment in the popular ``Sarah'' saga,
stretching back to the original TV movie in 1991. Glenn Close is
back as the mail-order bride of a taciturn Kansas farmer
(Christopher Walken).
</P>
<P>
   By ``Winter's End,'' she's his longtime wife. It's March 1918.
The Great War drums on in Europe, and the influenza epidemic rages
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Enter a stranger (Jack Palance) who claims to be Walken's
long-lost father. And, in fact, is. The dramatic conflict is that
Walken despises him because the father walked out on his family
when Walken was a child.
</P>
<P>
   The movie belongs to Palance. The big galoot is bent, scrawny,
white-maned and craggy-faced, but he remains a formidable screen
presence. In a deftly turned performance, he's a man willing to own
up to his flawed past, but unwilling to sacrifice his pride.
</P>
<P>
   This movie might even give Palance a chance to do for the Emmys
what he did for the Oscars in 1993, though one-armed push-ups might
be out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winter's End'' is the kind of low-key, wholesome entertainment
that clicks best with the approach of the holidays. It won't
challenge the brain. But it'll warm the cockles. It might even cock
the warmles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   HBO's ``RKO 281,'' showing Saturday, is a pretty picture with a
splendid cast and not a lot to say. Still, it's entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on a 1996 PBS documentary about the battle
over ``Citizen Kane,'' and the HBO title refers to the production
number of ``Citizen Kane'' at the RKO studio.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's based on a documentary, the first significant scene
in the movie is a fabrication. It places Orson Welles (Liev
Schreiber) at a San Simeon dinner party in 1940. A little verbal
joust with his host, William Randolph Hearst (James Cromwell),
leads to ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perfectly suicidal,'' Welles' friend and future ``Citizen
Kane'' collaborator Herman Mankiewicz (John Malkovich) says of the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll scorch the earth,'' Welles tells him. ``We'll astonish
them all.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie also features Melanie Griffith as Hearst's mistress,
Marion Davies; Brenda Blethyn as Hearst gossip columnist Louella
Parsons; and Roy Scheider as RKO studio head George Schaefer.
</P>
<P>
   ``RKO 281'' was filmed, of all places, in London. Studio sets
and London locales, including the Victoria and Albert Museum, were
used to re-create the Hearst castle at San Simeon. Really, there
aren't many locales in the film, but the San Simeon knock-off is
sumptuous.
</P>
<P>
   The cast and visual treats keep ``RKO 281'' interesting, so much
so that viewers might not even notice the absence of a point of
view.
</P>
<P>
   Welles is bratty; Hearst is arrogant, though with a tender side
toward Davies. We knew that, and the movie amounts to an
eye-catching but ultimately dry retelling of a familiar story.
</P>
<P>
   And where did ``Rosebud'' come from? The story has been around a
long time, and ``RKO 281'' seizes on it. It was rumored to be
Hearst's pet name for his favorite part of Davies' anatomy. Hearing
that it'll turn up in ``Citizen Kane'' is what really burns
Hearst's toast in this film.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooting the Past,'' written and directed by British dramatist
Stephen Poliakoff, posts a wonderful first installment on ``Mobil
Masterpiece Theatre'' Sunday on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   The last half, a week later, droops narratively and strains
credibility. But ``Shooting the Past'' is a divertingly offbeat
little story about a clash between settled values and modern life.
</P>
<P>
   It takes place at a quiet photo archive in London, where an
oddball staff preserves a mammoth collection of 10 million
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble ensues when an American entrepreneur (Liam Cunningham)
buys the building to convert it into a business college. Most of
the photos will have to be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The staff, headed by a thoroughly civil manager (Lindsay Duncan)
and an eccentric genius of a curator (Timothy Spall), has one week
to thwart the plan or find a new home for all those photographs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a delicious story with all sorts of symbolic ramifications.
And Spall (``Secrets and Lies'') drips with conspirational sabotage
as he takes viewers into his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But there are drawbacks. Poliakoff takes liberties in resolving
his story, and there's a piece of sore-thumb casting. Cunningham is
a British actor hog-tied by an American accent, or approximation of
one.
</P>
<P>
   Watching him try to inhabit the ill-fitting role is, by itself,
sardonically entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
