<SLUG> BC-SPEND-POUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERSONAL TOUCH IN BUDGET FIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
   (With SPEND-CONGRESS) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In this age of computer simulation and instant
global communication, some things must still be done the
old-fashioned way. Getting the president's signature on a piece of
paper is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   So when Congress passes resolutions to continue government
operations until a budget is approved, someone has to take those
resolutions in hand and give them to President Clinton for signing.
With the president in Turkey, some people have had to do a lot of
flying this week.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress passed a continuing resolution on Wednesday to
keep several major departments going, a member of the White House
legislative affairs office boarded a plane that departed from
Washington around 9 that night.
</P>
<P>
   The flight was delayed, but the resolution was signed by Clinton
just before midnight on Thursday night in Turkey, or shortly before
5 p.m. Washington time, with seven hours to spare before the
resolution expired.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the White House chief of staff, John Podesta,
was to fly to Greece, where the president will be on Friday, to get
his signature on a continuing resolution passed on Thursday and
good until early December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
