<DOCNO> NYT19991118.0561 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-18 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4775 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE19-COX     11-18 1723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Makings of bonfire tumble down on Texas A&AMP;M students, killing 9
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Caleb Hill was on the stack when it all
came down and with it, possibly, an end to the most venerated
tradition at the core of Texas A&AMP;M University: the ceremonial,
Texas-sized bonfire built and set ablaze before the big game
against the University of Texas every year.
</P>
<P>
   Nine students died, 28 were injured, three critically, after the
unfinished 40-foot pyramid of post oak and cedar elm collapsed here
about 2:30 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two more people remained buried in the pile late Thursday as a
large crowd, a mix of the mournful and the curious, turned out to
watch on a windy, dusty night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know whether they are dead or alive,'' said Cindy
Lawson, A&AMP;M's executive director of university relations. ``It's
going to be a long night, guys. They're trying to be very careful
for people who are inside the stack. They have not been able to
communicate with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The collapse recast an exuberant school activity bursting with
anticipation and intrastate gridiron rivalry as an unfathomable
tragedy that leaves a pair of looming questions the community was
too stunned to even contemplate answering: How could it have
happened, and is this how the bonfire ends?
</P>
<P>
   There will be none this year, only the second time since 1909 _
the other being 1963, following the assassination of John F.
Kennedy in Dallas. Traditionally, scores of students work
throughout the fall on the project, cutting and loading logs,
installing the center pole, constructing the cakelike stack slowly
before ``Push'' (when the effort becomes out of necessity a
24-hour-a-day affair), followed by the installation of an outhouse
at the top, and finally, after a season of waiting, the lighting of
the fire. Much of this proceeds with the knack for exaggerated
ceremony and esprit-building for which Aggies are both admired and
made the butt of jokes.
</P>
<P>
   News of the accident shot through one of the nation's most
obsessively in-touch alumni networks at Internet speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tentacles of Texas A&AMP;M go into practically every
community,'' said Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, a 1972 A&AMP;M graduate and a
yell leader and bonfire stack leader in his senior year. ``There is
a lot of grieving in Texas today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, a Yale undergrad, became emotional during a
CNN interview, saying, ``It's sad, it's tough.'' The presidential
library and museum of Bush's father, George Bush, is on the A&AMP;M
campus.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, blood-donors, many of them in Aggie colors, descended
on the Blood and Tissue Center of Central Texas in triple the
number on a typical Thursday. And More than 300 people gathered for
a vigil on the south steps of the Capitol on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   At the scene, witnesses described the normal work proceeding
apace, then, in the blink of an eye, bedlam as tons of logs _ the
finished structure, at a planned 55 feet, would have weighed at
least 5.4 million pounds, or 2,700 tons _ collapsed on the working
students.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was atop the lowest level, tethered by ropes to the center
pole when the stack fell. His job had been to straddle a new log
and to guide it into place as a pulley lifted it up. Then he would
wire the log with baling wire at the top to keep it in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just wired the log,'' Hill said. ``Twenty seconds later,
I heard a large, thundering crack.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked up and saw that the center pole to which he was he was
tethered was leaning away from him. The force of the quaking stack
jerked him up towards the top. He was slammed into the pile,
cracking a wrist and breaking his nose. Students _ about 70 of them
at the time, either on the stack or the perimeter _ scrambled or
jumped. Typically, the only nonstudents working on the site are
crane operators from local construction companies that donate both
machinery and manpower.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after rescue workers arrived, so did hundreds of
students.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn, the first 25 injured students had been carried to
hospitals. Four were already confirmed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Then began the delicate and exhaustive search through the pile.
Using three cranes, emergency crews gingerly removed the logs one
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like pick-up sticks,'' said Bart Humphreys, with College
Station Fire/EMS. ``All of the logs are intertwined.''
</P>
<P>
   At mid-morning, the scene was uncommonly quiet as mute students
gathered outside the yellow crime-scene tape. Some wept. Some
prayed. Some whispered to one another. Some called family and
friends on cell phones. Others sat alone, away from the
destruction, just waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 9 a.m. two students, still alive, were removed
from the rubble and taken to the hospital. It had taken workers
four hours to reach them.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour later, workers began using sonar equipment
used in earthquakes to locate people in the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson implored onlookers to be still to avoid disrupting the
motion detectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you care about these kids, stop walking,'' Lawson shouted.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 minutes, the only noise was the whir of television truck
engines, helicopters overhead and the wind flapping the crime-scene
tape.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference minutes later, Lawson choked a little as
she declared: ``Yeah, there are some sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   She said authorities had heard moaning and tapping but they
couldn't discern if it was one person or two. At the time, five
remained unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   As the logs were peeled off the pile, somber squads of helmeted
bonfire builders carried them away.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the builders who survived stayed for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get them to go home, get something to eat and
rest,'' said A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen.
</P>
<P>
   An exhausted student, head on helmet, slept in the fetal
position as reporters and on-lookers walked around him.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the university began its official investigation into
what caused the accident, independent theories were advanced
throughout the day. Hill believes the structure's center pole
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Thompson, the faculty bonfire adviser since 1990, said
there are two visible cracks but no evidence yet that the center
pole snapped first, turning a carefully constructed pile into
deadly debris. He said everything appeared fine when he last
inspected the stack about 10:30 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras on two campus buildings were Webcasting the
construction, university officials said, but one of the pair broke
about two weeks ago and it was unclear if the second recorded the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The local religious community responded with no fewer than three
prayer services Thursday, while area hospitals treated young people
who ought to have been the picture of physical well-being. Bryan
and College Station's two hospitals worked on the wounded. Bruised,
dust-covered students waited in hospital lobbies with anxious
parents, awaiting treatment and news.
</P>
<P>
   A large knot jutting rudely from the side of her head,
20-year-old Lauren Scanlan sat outside the St. Joseph Regional
Health Center struggling to remember what happened in the moments
before the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a swing on the first stack and I realized the logs
were swaying and I thought just one log was out of place. I looked
up and more were moving, and I thought it would stop but it
didn't,'' said Scanlan, a sophomore who suffered a broken nose and
several large cuts and scrapes on her face and arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking I needed to push my swing away from the
stack but I don't know if I did. The next thing I knew I couldn't
see. One of my contacts had fallen out and I was bleeding. I was
stumbling around and one of my friends grabbed me and walked me
out. Other than that, I don't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, freshman Rachael Hines, 18, was wiring logs at ground
level when the stack gave way. The logs tumbled away from where she
was working. ``The logs started to move so I looked up to my rig
man to tell him to stop the logs from moving and then I realized it
wasn't just my logs moving. Then, we heard a loud crack and it fell
right in front of me,'' Hines said. ``I took off running around to
the right side because my whole dorm was on the side that it fell
on. One of them (a fellow dorm resident) was walking around and one
was unconscious on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of Hines' friends was still unaccounted for as of noon.
</P>
<P>
   The two hospitals in the Bryan-College Station area went on
alert about a half hour after the crash. By early morning, the
hospitals had received more than two dozen students.
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire tradition goes back 90 years, although the school
didn't officially sanction it until 1935 _ and only then the
university jumped in because enthusiastic students used an
unfortunate farmer's log barn for materials. Over the years, the
structure was built higher, reaching 109 feet in 1969. The size was
limited to 55 feet high and 45 feet wide. According to ``A
Centennial History of Texas A&AMP;M'' by Henry Dethloff, the bonfire
``symbolizes every Aggie's desire to beat the hell out of Texas on
Thanksgiving Day.''
</P>
<P>
   The only incident that hinted at Thursday's accident was in
1994, when the structure collapsed on one side. No one was hurt,
and university officials determined that the ground, sodden and
unstable from rain, was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   But after the stack claimed nine lives, including one student
who turned 19 only this week, some here openly question the price
of the school's resolute adherence to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Robert ``Woody'' Peel, a junior who was working on the bonfire,
has had enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the outside looking in, it's one of those hard things to
explain. It's an Aggie thing,'' Peel said. ``But if it costs lives,
I'm not going to be for it unless they find a way to make it 100
times safer. It's too dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the site Thursday afternoon after being patched up, Hill
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is a tragedy that no amount of foresight could
have prevented,'' Hill said. ``Bonfires unite Aggies young and old.
It's a tradition that should not stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Laylan Copelin, Jason Spencer, Brad Reagan and
Sharon Jayson contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
