u f BC-UPS-SUIT19-COX     11-18 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-SUIT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS charged with insurance fraud
 &HT;    By Rob Modic
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ United Parcel Service customers who bought
insurance for packages for the past 16 years filed a class-action
lawsuit Thursday seeking $42 billion from the country's largest
shipping company.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in Montgomery County Common Pleas Court,
claims the Atlanta-based company fraudulently collected fees to pay
insurance for packages with values of more than $100 when the
company was self-insured and that the money collected as insurance
payments was directed to an offshore business owned by UPS
stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   UPS, registered as a corporation in Ohio and New York, acted
illegally as an unlicensed insurance company, according to the
lawsuit, which seeks to invoke Ohio's Corrupt Activities Act and
its triple-damage penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit stems from documents obtained from a federal
government victory against UPS in U.S. Tax Court on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   UPS recently took a $1.44 billion charge in the second quarter
and made a $1.3 billion payment to the government to stop interest
penalties while it considers an appeal of the tax case, said Norman
Black, UPS national spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A Tax Court judge found that UPS must pay taxes on money sent to
a Bermuda-based corporation that was set up as an insurance
company.
</P>
<P>
   Black, who said he had not seen the local lawsuit, countered
that UPS had used Pittsburgh-based insurance company National Union
Fire Insurance Co. to write the insurance for its packages.
</P>
<P>
   National Union Fire Insurance, a co-defendant in the lawsuit,
used Overseas Partners, Ltd., in Bermuda to reinsure what it had
written. OPL is owned by holders of private UPS stock but it is not
a UPS subsidiary, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we followed every state regulation and rule
interpretation and application at the time we were exiting the
insurance business (in 1983),'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Tax Court ruling that found the procedure to
be a ``sham,'' since Oct. 1, UPS has been using a subsidiary,
licensed to write insurance in all 50 states, to write its
insurance on packages it ships.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit details how UPS operated the alleged scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS, in concert with the other defendants herein, instituted a
practice whereby UPS charged . . . a fee which it promised to use
to purchase shippers' property insurance to cover the declared
value over $100 of parcels, but UPS did not remit the fee to an
insurance company for the purchase of insurance,'' the lawsuit
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead . . . the fees paid for insurance premiums . . . were
deposited into UPS accounts and the profits were shared with and/or
invested in an enterprise directed and controlled by UPS and the
other defendants,'' the lawsuit shows.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also shows that the defendants were motivated by an
intent to deprive the shippers of money, and tried to hide the
proceeds by transferring those proceeds out of the United States to
avoid paying taxes.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Swaim, a Dayton attorney who is one of six Dayton and
Louisville, Ky., attorneys who filed the lawsuit, declined comment
on the allegations in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also cites statements provided in the Tax Court case
that show that in 1984, UPS billed its customers $99.8 million for
insurance and paid out claims of about $22 million.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks ``in excess of $14 billion'' in compensatory
damages, but it does not spell out specifically how that amount was
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs include Robert and Melinda Allen and Video Aire
International, all of Fort Worth, Texas; Keilson-Dayton Co., and
Gregg T. Wellinghoff, all of Dayton; Francis A. Bonanno, Inc., and
James G. Bonanno, of Springboro; OH/Penn Inc., and Nicholas J.
Siroki, Springboro.
</P>
<P>
   Also listed as plaintiffs are Randd &AMP; Associates Printing &AMP;
Promotions Inc., and Richard H. Dobson Jr., of Moraine; Marsha J.
Copher; Peterson Electric Supply Co., Louisville, Ky.; Falls City
Electric Supply Inc., of Jeffersonville, Ind.; and J.W. Russell
Electric Co., of Louisville Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Other defendants include American International Group, of New
York; AIG Risk Management Inc., of New York; Frank B. Hall
Insurance Brokers of Paramus, N.J.; Prometheus Funding Corp., of
New York and Aon Group Ltd., of Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
